DeLay criticizes reform of campaign financing By LETITIA STEIN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Only weeks after President Clinton signed into law
the first campaign finance legislation to clear Congress in over a
decade, Rep. Tom DeLay returned to the stump Thursday to challenge
the reform movement.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing the conservative side of the hotly-debated issue, DeLay,
R-Texas, called on policy makers to eliminate caps on campaign
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay, the House Republican Whip, also accused journalists of
aligning with liberals to support reform while the media industry
has profited from political advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The innocuously labeled `campaign finance reform' movement is
perhaps the most worrisome and disingenuous special interest of
them all,'' DeLay said during a campaign finance forum at the Cato
Institute, a Washington think tank that promotes free markets and
limited government.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we know today as campaign finance reform is simply an
effort to have the government regulate and ration political
discourse in America,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign finance reform movement received a boost this year
when Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., made the issue a cornerstone of his
unsuccessful presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, in its first action to tighten campaign finance laws
since the post-Watergate reforms, last month closed a tax code
loophole that allowed some groups _ so-called 527s _ to fund
political activities with unlimited and unregulated donations.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which went into effect July 1, requires these
organizations to publicly disclose donor lists and political
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's attack on the movement Thursday underscores the uphill
battle reformers face in their effort to enact laws to dampen the
influence of money in government and politics.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman also warned that the limited legislation
recently approved would not pass constitutional muster in an
inevitable court challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Issue advocacy is a freedom that we have to protect at all
costs because it is in the Constitution _ not only the right to
free speech, but the right to assemble and to petition your
government,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the debate, legal experts have long claimed
that DeLay's First Amendment concerns are unsubstantiated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Constitution does not say, and has never said, that a
legislature can impose no regulations on the flow of money into
politics,'' said E. Joshua Rosenkranz, president of the Brennan
Center for Justice at the New York University School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court has made clear over the course of 200 years
that all of the seemingly absolute terms of the Constitution are
always subject to balancing when the government has a very
important interest at stake,'' Rosenkranz said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers at the Brennan Center have worked with lawmakers to
ensure the disclosure bill and other proposals do not cross the
line between the regulation of campaign activities and restrictions
on speech, Rosenkranz said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
