 MISSION-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
NASA weighs expense, risk of Mars mission By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   As NASA races to revamp its failed Mars exploration program,
scientists are torn over how aggressively the agency should proceed
with a risky and expensive robotic mission that could hasten the
search for life on the Red Planet.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, more than 200 experts wrapped up three days of
NASA-sponsored debate at the Lunar and Planetary Institute in
Houston over how the agency should reshape its Mars exploration
strategy in response to a pair of mission failures last year.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators blamed the losses of the Mars Climate Orbiter and
the Mars Polar Lander on NASA mismanagement and underfunding.
</P>
<P>
   With the advice of scientists and engineers, NASA expects to
unveil a new 20-year exploration strategy for Mars by December, one
that could be funded at about $400 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the discussion at the gathering focused on how much of a
priority NASA should assign a robotic mission that would attempt to
collect small samples of Martian rock and soil.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers would examine the soil and rock for signs of
biological activity. Scientists have yet to prove the existence of
even primitive life beyond the Earth, though neighboring Mars is a
leading candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't overestimate the value it will have,'' said Mike Duke,
a Lunar and Planetary Institute scientist who told colleagues the
Martian dirt would reveal clues about the origin of the planet, its
climate and mineralogy as well as the presence of life. ``It would
be a tremendous leap forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But the cost of the mission, estimated at from $1 billion to $2
billion, could prove even more devastating if it was attempted too
soon and failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been searching for a low-cost Mars sample return mission
for years,'' said Donna Shirley, a former Mars mission manager at
NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory. ``I'd like to discourage any
magical thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA lacks the technology to land a probe at the precise site it
would like to collect a sample, Shirley cautioned. The cost of
launching all of the equipment required for the complicated mission
also will drive up the cost, she argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our challenge is not to launch something before it's ready,''
said Scott Hubbard, who recently took over as NASA's
Washington-based Mars program manager.
</P>
<P>
   However, he noted that obtaining fragments of Mars with robots
is in NASA's plans.
</P>
<P>
   At the Houston conference, several scientists offered less
costly and risky alternatives for first collecting samples from
Mars' small moons, Deimos and Phobos.
</P>
<P>
   One scientists proposed launching spacecraft that could skim
close to the surface of the moons while firing projectiles. The
impacts of the projectiles would kick up dust that could be
collected during the fly-by and returned to Earth for study.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's record of Mars exploration has been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, NASA lost communication with its Mars Polar
Lander as the spacecraft began a high speed descent toward a
landing at the planet's south pole. Though they could not prove
conclusively how it was lost, investigators uncovered an overlooked
computer software error that would have caused braking rockets to
shut off while it was still airborne.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, NASA lost communication with its Mars Climate
Orbiter as the orbiting weather satellite was steering into orbit
around the Red Planet. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
