 TALKS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Mideast summit not dead yet By GREG McDONALD 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright sought
Thursday to revive the Camp David summit in President Clinton's
absence, but there were still signs the Israelis and Palestinians
were balking at making peace despite a last-minute decision to
continue talks.
</P>
<P>
   Albright took control of the talks, which had all but collapsed
late Wednesday night, after Clinton left for Japan to keep his
commitment to attend the so-called Group of Eight economic summit.
He plans to rejoin the talks Sunday if the Israeli and Palestinian
delegations are still at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Albright spent the day shuttling back and forth between Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in
hopes of narrowing the differences between the two. Clinton was
unable to resolve the differences during nine intense days of
pressuring both leaders to end the bitter half-century dispute
between their peoples.
</P>
<P>
   Albright ``will continue to try to close the gaps and move
forward on the issues so that when the president returns he can
assess the status of our efforts,'' said State Department spokesman
Richard Boucher.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's here to carry the ball forward. The determination is
there; the effort certainly is not slacking in any way,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were no plans for Barak and Arafat, who have not
met face-to-face since Saturday, to hold a trilateral session with
Albright. And Israeli and Palestinian sources said the two were
still far apart on the issues, especially over how to divide up
Jerusalem in order to make room for a Palestinian state capital.
</P>
<P>
   However, the fact that the two leaders were still at Camp David
_ after a day spent Wednesday preparing to leave the presidential
retreat and accusing each other of negotiating in bad faith _ was
no small accomplishment, said one Israeli official.
</P>
<P>
   ``That they are still here is an indication that neither one of
them is willing to give up just yet on this opportunity. They have
to reach a settlement of all the problems that have divided us,''
said the official.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a chance this will end in success.''
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joe Lockhart had declared the summit
over shortly before 11 p.m. CDT Wednesday, issuing a statement
saying the parties had failed to reach an agreement. Both the
Israeli and Palestinian delegations and press contingencies had
already been ordered to pack and check out of their hotels before
the statement was released, and motorcades were waiting at Camp
David to take the leaders back to Washington so they could fly
home.
</P>
<P>
   But as newspapers across the country were hitting the streets
with headlines screaming that the Middle East peace talks had
failed, Clinton emerged shortly before midnight Wednesday from
seclusion of the presidential retreat near Thurmont, Md. to
announce that Barak and Arafat had a change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   Failure, the weary-looking president said, had suddenly _ even
miraculously _ been replaced by hope once again that a deal might
be possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The short answer to why we're still here after everybody
thought we were through is that nobody wanted to give up. After all
these years, as hard as these issues are, they don't want to give
up. And I didn't think we should give up, and so we're still
plugging away,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left shortly after that to attend the economic summit,
saying he would return to Camp David on Sunday to ``assess'' where
the negotiations stand.
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing for reporters Thursday, Boucher denied that the
failure announcement had been staged by the White House in order to
pressure the two leaders into staying for further discussions.
</P>
<P>
   He said a consensus to continue the talks emerged among the
leaders in discussions they were having to wrap things up after
Lockhart issued his statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that process the leaders got a sense with each other that
it was, in fact, not the best thing to do to conclude, but rather
it was better to stay and keep working on this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The way events unfolded Wednesday, it appeared that neither
Arafat nor Barak wanted to be the first to walk out of the summit,
even though they spent most of the day accusing each other of
negotiating in bad faith and threatening to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian sources said Thursday that the two sides
still have not been able to agree on the final boundaries of a
Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza Strip or the fate of
more than three million Palestinian refugees who have been driven
from their homes since Israel was established in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   But the main stumbling block, they said, remains the competing
claims to Jerusalem, which both sides regard as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Wednesday offered a number of proposals aimed at
resolving that issue, including shared sovereignty of the old
walled city of East Jerusalem. But that offer has apparently been
rejected by the Palestinians who are insisting that Israel, which
captured and annexed East Jerusalem in the 1967 war, return it all
to their control. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
