 HEAR-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Power conservation leaves inmates without air By JAMES KIMBERLY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ During the hottest hours of at least two days during
this heat wave, inmates and guards at a Houston-area prison
sweltered without the benefit of air conditioning or fans so that
the prison system could conserve electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Texas prison cell blocks are not air-conditioned. Consequently,
inmates and correctional officers rely on electric fans for relief
from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   But the fans were not available at the Darrington Unit
medium-security prison in Rosharon last Thursday and Friday
afternoons because the Texas Department of Criminal Justice was
trying to conserve power. More than 1,600 men are incarcerated at
Darrington, and they are overseen by nearly 400 correctional
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of a contract signed this year with Reliant
Energy HL&AMP;P, the Texas Department of Criminal Justice can earn
credits for every kilowatt-hour it conserves when demand for
electricity is greatest.
</P>
<P>
   The prison system is one of 40 commercial customers that Reliant
Energy can call and ask to reduce the amount of electricity being
used. When the commercial customers conserve electricity, more
power is available for homes and other customers, said Reliant
spokeswoman Leticia Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for electricity usually peaks around 4 p.m., Lowe said.
Customers are asked to cut back on their power consumption for only
three hours at a time, Lowe said, and the contract limits to 15 the
number of times Reliant can ask a commercial customer to reduce
usage in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   But those three hours can be tough to take, said a correctional
officer at the Darrington Unit. If the temperature outside is
higher than 100 degrees, the temperature inside the prison is
significantly higher, particularly on the third floor, said the
officer, who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   High temperatures in the Houston area have been at or above 100
degrees for more than a week. When the effects of humidity are
factored in, it feels even hotter. So far, eight deaths in Houston
have been attributed to the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inmates are pretty upset about it,'' the prison guard
said. ``It's just as bad for the officers as it is for the
inmates.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Reliant asked its commercial customers to conserve electricity
July 13, July 14 and Monday. The temperature in Houston on those
days ranged from 99 to 102 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first year that the prison system contracted with
Reliant Energy to conserve power. Last year, the prison system cut
similar agreements with power companies that serve prisons in
Abilene, Beeville and &UR;  &LR; Kenedy.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements earned the prison system $96,000 worth of credits
toward their electric bills last year, said department spokesman
Glen Castlebury. By adding 12 Houston area prisons to the program,
the prison system hopes to earn $200,000 worth of electric bill
credits. The money not spent on electricity will be used to improve
auxiliary power systems at the prisons, Castlebury said.
</P>
<P>
   Darrington was the only prison in the Houston area to have a
problem, Castlebury said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 11 successes last week and one failure,'' Castlebury
said.
</P>
<P>
   The other Houston area prisons saved power by using diesel
generators. An electrical problem prevented Darrington from doing
the same, Castlebury said. Security was not breached since locks on
gates and cell doors can be operated manually, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance crews thought they fixed the electrical problem, so
Darrington tried again on Friday to run on generator power. Once
again, the prison found itself in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Castlebury said Darrington will not participate in the energy
conservation program again until the electrical glitch is fixed.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of fans might have been uncomfortable but probably did
not pose a significant health risk to inmates, said Dr. David
Persse, Houston's director of Emergency Medical Services.
</P>
<P>
   If the air the fans is circulating is hotter than the normal
body temperature of 98.6 degrees, then fans may actually do more
harm than good, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about fans is, ironically, if you are in a hot room,
they can actually make it worse. That's the way a convection oven
works,'' he said. ``It's not having air conditioning that is the
bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
