<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 SUMMIT-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Clinton hit by protests in Okinawa By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKINAWA, Japan _ As the leaders of the world's largest
industrialized nations gathered here for their annual summit,
President Clinton arrived today on an island gripped by mass
demonstrations against the presence of the U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried hard to understand the concerns of the public
here,'' said Clinton, who was met on the island with calls to
consolidate the military presence here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do what we can to reduce our footprint on this
island.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came to this southern Japanese island, site of the last
major battle between the United States and Japan during World War
II and still home to 26,000 U.S. troops, to confer with Russian
President Vladimir Putin and leaders of six other industrialized
nations.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, an estimated 20,000 protesters formed a human
chain to block the entrance to the Kadena Air Base, one of 15 U.S.
facilities located on the small island. Police security remained
very tight on the island today in the wake of the protests.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the local population and the U.S. troops
stationed here are often strained. But tensions have been running
high in recent weeks, following the arrest earlier this month of a
drunk, 19-year-old Marine who allegedly entered an Okinawan home
and fondled a 14-year-old girl in her bed. That incident rekindled
memories of the rape of a 12-year-old girl by three U.S. servicemen
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take seriously our responsibility to be good neighbors, and
it is unacceptable to the United States when we do not meet that
responsibility,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In a ceremony summit organizers are hoping will help defuse the
tensions, President Clinton visited the Cornerstone of Peace, a
memorial dedicated to the more than 234,000 who died during the
bloody battle of Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   A third of the Okinawan population died in the 83-day battle 55
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asia is largely at peace today because our alliance gives
people throughout this region confidence that the peace will be
defended and preserved, that no more such monuments need ever be
built,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks were not the only gesture designed to help
quell the uproar. U.S. military officials have banned drinking on
eight Marine bases during the summit, which continues through
Sunday, and restricted Marines and sailors to base between midnight
and 7:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Later today, Clinton will gather with the other leaders of the
Group of Eight _ the United States, Japan, Britain, Germany,
France, Italy, Canada and Russia _ in his last economic summit as
president. Clinton is the first president to visit Okinawa since
President Eisenhower in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders will discuss a host of social and economic issues,
ranging from the spread of AIDS to efforts to alleviate world
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   One major issue on the leaders' agenda is the so-called
``digital divide,'' the gulf between the industrialized nations and
the developed world in terms of their access to computer
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Clinton will meet with Putin, who comes to Japan armed
with new warnings of a Russian-Sino response to any development of
a proposed U.S. missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   The system would be designed to intercept missiles fired at the
United States or U.S. troops. Proponents argue the technology being
contemplated would not provide protection against the massive
arsenal of Russia but could guard against a launch by a state such
as North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   A $100 million flight test of the system failed earlier this
month, and Clinton has not yet decided whether to move forward with
actual development.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, however, insist development of the proposed system
would represent a violation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese have been even more adamant in opposition. Before
traveling here to Okinawa, Putin met with Chinese President Jiang
Zemin to discuss the U.S. missile defense system. Putin and Zemin
then issued a joint statement condemning the proposal, warning it
could ``pose the most grave, adverse consequences'' and trigger a
new arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Putin also visited North Korea this week, the first-ever visit
by a Russian leader, and proposed the missile shield be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   G-8 members France and Germany already have criticized the
defense system as a potential threat to global disarmament. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
