<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8456 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOREINTEXAS-HNS &LR;      07-21 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 IN TEXAS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Gore rushes to Texas to rip Bush By PATTY REINERT 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Vice President Al Gore brought his criticism of
presidential rival George W. Bush's state budget to the governor's
back yard Thursday, as the two fought for the last word on Bush's
fiscal prowess and priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of Texas pride and Bush's popularity in the state even
as he bashed the governor's policies, Gore accused Bush of letting
Texans down by putting tax cuts for the wealthy ahead of health
insurance for poor children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wonderful state, but I think it should be a state
where it's just as easy to raise a child as it is to set up an oil
rig,'' Gore told families and state lawmakers gathered at the Seven
Oaks Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Texas, as anybody who's been here knows, work
just as hard or harder than anybody else,'' he added. ``The
question is, is the Bush government here working just as hard for
them and helping to ensure that they succeed?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush shot back quickly from 80 miles up the interstate in
Austin, accusing the vice president of trying to mislead Texans
about their state budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Texas budget is balanced and in the black. We have a
surplus of $1.4 billion in the bank,'' Bush said at the Governor's
Mansion. ``For Vice President Gore to claim otherwise for his own
political purposes is a travesty _ he should be ashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican state Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander also stepped
into the budget fray Thursday, officially confirming that state
government will have a surplus of $1.4 billion by Aug. 31, the
halfway point of the state's 2000-2001 budget period.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Chronicle reported earlier this month that
legislators likely will need to tap the surplus to cover unexpected
expenses totaling about $610 million in some state programs.
Rylander noted that the surplus would be more than enough to cover
the overruns.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and some other Democrats have attempted to tie the budget
shortages to a tax cut the governor pushed, and the vice president
scuttled a planned campaign stop in Iowa Thursday to fly to Texas
in hopes of capitalizing on the uproar.
</P>
<P>
   In his San Antonio appearance, Gore was joined by state Sens.
Mario Gallegos, D-Galena Park, and Frank Madla, D-San Antonio, and
state Reps. Carlos Uresti, D-San Antonio, and Ruth Jones McClendon,
D-San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Also with him were several mothers who had tried to maneuver the
state's cumbersome process for signing children up for health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Texas began 1999 with a record surplus of $6.4 billion, which
legislators used that year to raise teacher pay and increase
spending on other education and health programs. They also used
$1.7 billion of the surplus for the tax cut that Bush proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Bush squandered the 1999 surplus on $1.7 billion in
tax cuts for the wealthy, including $45 million for oil companies,
while neglecting health care and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that Governor Bush is a popular and well-liked
governor here, and I want to give him some credit on that score. I
think he has a warm and engaging personality,'' Gore said. ``But
you know, the presidency is more than just a popularity contest. It
involves whether or not you're willing to fight for what's right,
whether or not you're willing to spend some popularity to do
difficult, hard things.''
</P>
<P>
   While governors in other states have used the nation's economic
boom to address the needs of everyday people, Gore said, Bush's
priority was helping the wealthy. The same would be true, he said,
if Bush were elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that Texas ranks last in the United States in the
percentage of people with health insurance; that the state is
second-worst in the country, behind Arizona, in providing health
coverage for children; and that last year, about one-fourth of
Texas children lacked insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by state lawmakers who fought last year to expand
health coverage for children under the Children's Health Insurance
Program, or CHIP, Gore said Bush had fought the improvements and
his administration has delayed enrolling children who qualify. The
program provides health insurance for children who don't qualify
for Medicaid but can't afford private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the state could lose $449 million in federal funding
for CHIP because it got a late start in enrolling children. In
addition, participants in Thursday's event criticized the state's
system as being nearly impossible to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supporters greeted Gore's San Antonio motorcade, waving
signs with such slogans as ``Viva Bush'' and ``Gore can't handle
the truth about Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Rob Junell, D-San Angelo, chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee and a Bush supporter, defended the state's
budget and the CHIP program that lawmakers established last year
for low-income children. The Legislature appropriated $179 million
for the program over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Junell told reporters in a conference call arranged by the Bush
campaign that Texas got a late start on CHIP because the
Legislature wasn't in session when the federal government issued
regulations for the program.
</P>
<P>
   Junell said the Legislature thoroughly debated budget priorities
during the 1999 session. And he noted that most legislators _
including some Democrats now criticizing Bush _ voted for the
budget and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer added that money from the state's
surplus had been used for $3,000 raises for teachers statewide and
to eliminate the sales tax on over-the-counter medicines, in
addition to the tax cuts Gore cites.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster his criticism of state finances and policies, Gore
appeared with Carrie De la Fuente, a single mother of four, who
said she tried repeatedly to sign her children up for CHIP, but
sometimes had to take hours off work, waiting for delayed
appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd say, `No, you need more documents,' so then I'd have to
get another appointment to go back with more documents,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said it wasn't unfair to speculate that the delays were
``intended to limit the number of people who participate'' in the
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are now 16,000 children in Texas eligible for health
insurance who don't have it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to assign Governor Bush responsibility for all
the problems that exist,'' he said. ``I do think it's fair though
to ask what he has done to try to solve them. He fought against
those in the Legislature who tried to remove the obstacles, and I
think that's an important indicator of the priorities he wants to
establish.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed expanding CHIP to nearly 1 million uninsured
children, and allowing poor families who still don't qualify to buy
into the program at rates that are less expensive than private
insurance. His plan would cost $146 billion over 10 years. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
