<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACK GOING TO THE MAT TO IMPROVE ITS APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ No one is saying so directly, but if you
listen to the conversations around the U.S. Olympic Trials, there
is a distinct feeling that someday the hammer contestants will be
throwing at each other.
</P>
<P>
   Or that sprinters will be wired for the sound of their pre-race
woofings.
</P>
<P>
   Or pole vaulters must clear an electrified, sparking crossbar
(style points for scissoring the bar).
</P>
<P>
   It is the charge of Craig Masback, CEO of USA Track &AMP; Field, to
get his sport off its lips and into the American sports
consciousness. While he made none of the above suggestions, he all
but acknowledged that it is a pro rasslin' world, and the rest of
us are merely ring-card girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to structure the rules of the sport to make it as
entertaining as possible,'' Masback said Thursday after his ``state
of the sport'' speech. ``We need to look at the field events to max
out the entertainment value.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, ``our natural analogy (to rasslin') would be our
throwers.''
</P>
<P>
   So, C.J. ``The People'' Hunter, Lance ``Let's Break a'' Deal and
John ``No One Meana'' Godina, pack up your implements with your
face paint.
</P>
<P>
   By 2004, it won't be the Olympic Trials. It will be Five-Ring
Smackdown.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I exaggerate. But not much.
</P>
<P>
   The major buzz at the Trials, which wrap up Sunday with the main
event in the 200 meters between 400-meter champion Michael Johnson
and 100-meter champion Maurice Greene, has been the trash-talking
between the principals. Johnson, track's most prominent male figure
and a heretofore reticent orator, has been poor-mouthing Greene
with almost as much acid as Greene has tongue-lashed him. It's all
junior-league Vince McMahon, but hey, McMahon had to start
somewhere too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy it; I like it,'' said Masback, a former Olympic
distance runner. ``I know that the public reaction will be nothing
but good for the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a true burlesque impresario.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the official track uniforms debuting in Sydney
were unveiled (by Nike, official owners of USA Track and Field) and
were just about one tattoo short of turnbuckle-worthy.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a mean-looking black with a Spiderman pattern, the unis
were festooned with some vaguely fascistic symbols _ an ominous
``USA'' upon a winged shield, coupled with a red star that would do
proud any remaining Soviet communists.
</P>
<P>
   However dubious the look, the stylings could probably get
somebody elected governor in Minnesota. That's the sort of
gratification track is after.
</P>
<P>
   Masback acknowledged that when he took over track's top business
position three years ago the critics said the sport was
``bankrupt'' in America and ``lacking confidence in its place in
the world of sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of that was true, and has been so for years _ at least
since the cashiering of the old Soviet Union. The Evil Empire
provided the United States one of the great rivalries in all of
sports. America used to care a whole lot more about the Olympics
when beating the commies meant something, however symbolic and
artificial.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is no archenemy, only gentle-looking Kenyan runners
and Chinese divers.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The rivalry) doesn't exist anymore, and that hurts,'' Masback
acknowledged. He attempted to talk up some meets with other
nations, but it isn't the same.
</P>
<P>
   Track, whose history of high drama and unforgettable moments is
arguably unsurpassed in all of sport, has yet to win over the
saturated American fan. Almost everyone involved has made numerous
suggestions, and for the last 30 years, almost none have been taken
up.
</P>
<P>
   Masback put on the predictable spin, saying his little industry
was ``good and getting better'' and asserting, accurately, that the
enthusiasm, crowds and organization Sacramento has provided
``exceeded all expectations'' and are ``the best trials ever.''
Unfortunately, a good fortnight does not a success make.
</P>
<P>
   Masback cited the NBC ratings for the opening weekend (4.0) as
the best for a TV sports event in the period, and he said the
seasonal ratings for its Golden Spike track circuit exceeded those
of the National Hockey League, Major League Soccer and the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, those sports are also in desperate search for
footing among fans and advertisers, and none have track's heritage
or its participation levels in junior high and high school.
</P>
<P>
   Masback is persuaded that the world's No. 1 track team will have
such a strong showing in Sydney that it will propel the sport
beyond the every-four-years fringe and into the American
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   But since the mainstream is filled with chairs broken over the
backs of the entertainers, Masback is making plans to take the
hammer throwers aside to ask them if they can sharpen their
short-range aim.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
