<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8460 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-21 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS TRIP ON STAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Call off the morticians. Cancel the burial.
The Athletics are very much alive.
</P>
<P>
   And the American League West race is still that _ a competition.
Seattle holds most of the cards, but Oakland still has an ace or
two up its sleeve _ not to mention a wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's Matt Stairs broke up Aaron Sele's bid for a no-hitter
in the seventh inning Thursday, then put the Mariners away with a
two-run homer in the eighth, highlighting Oakland's 5-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Stairs said it was as important a victory as the A's have had
all year, because the Mariners could have started to put the A's
away if they'd won. Seattle has a four-game lead over Oakland; if
the Mariners had won, the lead would have been six.
</P>
<P>
   ``At six games, the season's not going to be over, but they're
going to be extremely difficult to catch,'' Stairs said in
appreciation of the 55-39 record the Mariners have built up 94
games into the season. ``At six games, maybe we'd have to start
thinking about the wild card.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at four games, it's going to be tough to catch the
Mariners, because they're solid in so many ways. After losing (6-3
on Wednesday night), winning today was huge for us. Absolutely
huge.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no need to feel too sorry for Seattle. True, the
Mariners lost despite a terrific outing by Sele. But the Mariners
survived a harrowing, injury-plagued eight-game road trip to finish
with a 4-4 record.
</P>
<P>
   And their four-game lead in the West is one game better than
when they left town, despite shortstop Alex Rodriguez missing the
entire trip and designated hitter Edgar Martinez not starting five
of the eight games because the DH is not used in National League
ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to play all that time minus A-Rod, and then we didn't
have Edgar available,'' catcher Joe Oliver said. ``A 4-4 record is
a good trip for us, especially going into National League parks
(for six games). That was as good a road trip as we could have
hoped for.''
</P>
<P>
   Backed by more sizzling defensive work from the Seattle infield,
Sele almost made the trip better than the Mariners could have hoped
for. He battled control troubles to take a 1-0 lead into the
seventh inning. A one-out walk to Ben Grieve was followed by a
looping single to left by Stairs that broke up the no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was saying in the sixth inning that the best thing we had
going for us was the fact that Sele had a no-hitter going,'' A's
general manager Billy Beane said. ``In that situation, they're
going to go with him until he gives up a hit, and not go with the
matchups they might go with otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's what happened. Sele hit Jeremy Giambi, then caught
too much of the plate, enabling A's shortstop Miguel Tejada to
crack a two-run double. The lead was 3-1 later in the inning on a
Terrence Long single off Jose Paniagua, and Jose Mesa allowed a
two-run bomb in the eighth to Stairs before the Mariners came up
one run short with a three-run rally in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   While Sele put up zeroes, A's starter Gil Heredia came up with a
few of his own. Mariners shortstop Carlos Guillen stunned Heredia
with a solo homer in the third, but he pitched out of two-men-on
jams later in that inning as well as in the second and sixth
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners racked up hits _ they finished with nine _ but they
weren't leading to any runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got our hits,'' Oliver said. ``But we didn't get them in
spots where we could have driven in some runs. But give us credit.
Even after they took the big lead, we came back. We went down
fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   That fact wasn't lost on the A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't over when we got up 5-1,'' manager Art Howe said.
``You don't get to be four games in front this deep into the season
by giving up. They came back hard. We were just able to hold them
off. It was a big win for us.''
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to winning four of the trip's first seven games, it
was a not-so-big loss for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a long stretch for us,'' Sele said. ``It's not
just that we've been on the road for eight games. If you go back to
before the break, we've played 18 of the last 21 on the road going
back to the series in Texas (which started June 30).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tough schedule. We've done well. And it's going to be
a lot of fun to go home. If you are able to go .500 on the road and
win at home, you'll find yourselves quite a few games over .500.''
</P>
<P>
   To be exact, 16 games over.
</P>
<P>
   So by the end of the afternoon, as they packed up in the bowels
of the Oakland Coliseum, the Mariners were thinking more of what's
to come and less of what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it would have been nice to get this one,'' manager Lou
Piniella said. ``But 4-4 is acceptable. It really is. We went on
the road playing short and we went 4-4. That's good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners now look at a season-high 13-game homestand at
Safeco Field, where they are an AL-best 30-13 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder Stairs said catching the Mariners wasn't going to
be easy.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
