<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8461 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     07-21 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BIGGER DIVISION GAP, M'S NEED MORE POP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Aaron Sele could at least console himself with
a reassuring mantra.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going home. We're happy about that,'' the right-hander
said Thursday after a 5-4 loss to the A's at the Coliseum ended a
long and winding stretch for the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing 18 out of 21 on the road is worse than playing 21
straight,'' said Sele, who had the added bonus of a cross-country
trip to the All-Star Game in Atlanta, making the first half of July
a frequent flyer's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Mariners are heading home, where they have built the
bulk of their winning record at Safeco, their field of dreams.
</P>
<P>
   (begin italics) Pitching and defense. Pitching and defense. (end
italics)
</P>
<P>
   That is the other popular Mariner mantra. So far, it has served
the AL West leaders well.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the Mariners punctuated that point. In a 6-3
victory, they all but performed a clinic in the two categories that
make them frontrunners in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Moyer was outstanding, while Mark McLemore and David Bell
led a stellar defensive effort that magnified the defensive foibles
of the A's, the worst defensive team in baseball with 91 errors.
</P>
<P>
   But the follow-up was not exactly what the Mariners needed _ a
sleeping giant waking up on their watch.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Stairs, his softball-player physique contributing to his
.215 batting average, looped a single into short right field in the
seventh inning, opening the door for the A's.
</P>
<P>
   With one swing of the bat, Sele's no-hitter was undone.
</P>
<P>
   So was Sele, who had walked Ben Grieve before facing Stairs. He
hit Jeremy Giambi to load the bases, then gave up a two-run double
to Miguel Tejada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't making good pitches,'' Sele said. ``I was behind in
the count from the start, and if you get behind, you're going to
get hurt. I was fortunate to keep the game close, but then I let a
situation get out of hand in the seventh.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, with Jose Mesa on the mound, Stairs clocked a
two-run homer. The A's may be rediscovering their ``Bash Brothers''
persona.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the best scenario for the Mariners, whose superior
pitching and defense should have produced a wider gap atop the
division.
</P>
<P>
   Sele, now 11-5, having lost his past two starts, has enjoyed
magnificent run support this season. He was among the league
leaders, averaging 7.32 runs per start.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, though, the A's asserted their strength _ and perhaps
their biggest advantage over the Mariners _ when Stairs resurrected
his home-run power.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone was wondering whether the current Mariners _ albeit
without the injured Alex Rodriguez _ need to make improvements to
their lineup, Thursday's game was a wake-up call.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners managed nine hits, three in a three-run ninth. But
it wasn't about what the Mariners did or didn't do.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it was how the A's, with two homers Wednesday night and
a big one Thursday, have the kind of lineup that can strike hard
and quick.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, Mariners general manager Pat Gillick has held so many
meetings, he should consider renting Camp David. For weeks, the
Mariners have been talking like they're eager to find that extra
pop for their lineup.
</P>
<P>
   When Lou Piniella said Ken Caminiti would be a good fit, Gillick
had that deal in the works, derailed by the Astros placing the
power-hitting third baseman on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, as names like Johnny Damon and Jason Kendall have
been floated, and as B.J. Surhoff remains the coveted hitter who
doesn't want to come to Seattle, the Mariners have quietly and
professionally held their division lead.
</P>
<P>
   With Rodriguez saying he hopes to return Monday against the A's
after sitting out three games against the Rangers, the Mariners'
potent 3-4-5 punch will be back in order.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Mariners to extend their three- and four-game leads,
there must be more bang.
</P>
<P>
   The players aren't worried about upsetting chemistry or making
way for a new personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to be loaded. Too much is not a bad thing.
Better to be prepared. You never know,'' McLemore said.
</P>
<P>
   The second baseman said he wouldn't be surprised if the deal the
Mariners finally make is not just for a role player, but a star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't put anything past Pat. George Steinbrenner is one
who'll go out and do what needs to done. Pat's another one,''
McLemore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Gillick, Piniella, vice president of baseball
administration Lee Pelekoudas and player development director Roger
Jongewaard) are smart enough to know who's going to be the right
fit. They're the ones who put this thing together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard people talking about how Rickey (Henderson) wasn't
going to be a good fit, and look at him. He can still beat you.
When I heard he was going to be released in New York, I knew he was
going to come here. I wanted him to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners return home for a 13-game stretch against some of
the best teams in the American League with plenty to be happy
about, except that they aren't quite as deep and dangerous as they
could be.
</P>
<P>
   The A's are far from the perfect model to emulate when it comes
to building a contending ballclub. But a Matt Stairs homer every
once in a while shows what a little extra pop can accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
