<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8462 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-VEEPSTAKES-CAMPAIGN-S     07-21 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEEPSTAKES-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURE THING ABOUT THE CANDIDATES' VEEP CHOICES: THEY'RE WHITE 
 MALES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Take a look at who's on top of George W. Bush and
Al Gore's list of potential running mates.
</P>
<P>
   They are Baby Boomers and war veterans. They are big state
governors and small state senators. And they are all white men.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush prepares to announce his running mate and Gore narrows
his list, the women and minorities once touted as promising
possibilities have all but faded from contention.
</P>
<P>
   California Sen. Dianne Feinstein, once seen as Gore's most
logical choice, has been eclipsed by a number of her male
colleagues. Secretary of Energy Bill Richardson, a Latino, has seen
his negatives increase with the price of gasoline. Former Cabinet
Secretary Elizabeth Dole impressed no one with her aborted run for
president. And Gen. Colin Powell has flatly ruled out accepting an
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers blame the expected absence of such candidates on
the limited number of women and minorities in prominent positions
and the peculiarities of the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein's prospects would skyrocket if California were seen as
a swing state, as would Dole's if Bush were far behind among female
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it serves as a reminder that 80 years after women gained the
right to vote, and 40 years after minorities were guaranteed access
to polls, both groups have a ways to go before becoming fixtures at
the uppermost echelon of American politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The glass ceiling is chipped. It's not yet shattered,''
Feinstein said in a just-published book called ``Nine and
Counting,'' co-written by the nine female senators.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore have not publicly discussed their lists. It is
impossible to know with certainty who is being considered. But all
of the speculation _ based on face-to-face meetings, requests from
campaign officials for background information and chatter on the
campaign buses _ is focused on a dwindling list of about a dozen
white men.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the idle springtime talk of Maryland Lt. Gov. Kathleen
Townsend Kennedy, Oklahoma Rep. J.C. Watts, or New Jersey Sen.
Christine Todd Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   As decision time approaches, the hottest rumor on the Republican
side involves Bush's vanquished primary season rival, Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, who once said of Bush that ``if he's a reformer,
I'm an astronaut.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of insisting he would not consider the vice
presidency, McCain reportedly told Republican officials this week
he might take the number two slot if it is offered.
</P>
<P>
   Other top GOP prospects include Senator Chuck Hagel of Nebraska,
Govs. Frank Keating of Oklahoma, Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania George
Pataki of New York and former Defense Secretary Richard Cheney, the
man who is heading up Bush's search for a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will make up my mind soon,'' Bush told reporters earlier
this week. An announcement is expected as early as Monday, a week
before the start of the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, insider scuttlebutt is focused on House
Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., who is seen as someone who
might immediately bridge the Democrat's split on labor and trade
issues. Sens. John Kerry of Massachusetts, Evan Bayh of Indiana,
Bob Graham of Florida and Joe Lieberman of Connecticut are also
considered top prospects, as is former Sen. George Mitchell of
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Most say the lack of women and minorities is simply a numbers
game. The entire top tier of vice presidential candidates come from
the ranks of senators and governors. There are just nine female
senators out of 100 (and Texas Republican Kay Bailey Hutchison is
constitutionally barred from joining fellow Texan Bush on the
ticket.) Just three of the nation's 50 governors are women.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are more stark for minorities. Outside of Hawaii,
the only minority senator is Native American Ben Nighthorse
Campbell, whose ponytail and love of Harleys makes his selection
highly unlikely. There are currently no African American senators
or governors.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Wilson was a city council member in Des Moines, Iowa, when
Geraldine Ferraro was named to the 1984 Democratic ticket, and she
remembers thinking that women would be seriously considered on
every ticket thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as president of the White House Project, Wilson works
toward changing public attitudes in order to return women to the
national ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time since Geraldine Ferraro was selected
that women are actually, seriously being discussed,'' Wilson said.
``It's taken us a long time to get to that place.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and other observers believe that were it not for a few
twists of the 2000 campaign, a woman might well have been named
vice president. But since white men still occupy well over 80
percent of the seats in Congress and in state houses, they say it
is no surprise that Bush and Gore appear to have turned to them
during a close election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't enough women yet who are credible, who have the
national national stature to be seen as a seen as something more
than filling a slot,'' said Eleanor Clift, a contributing editor
for Newsweek magazine who recently co-authored a book titled
``Madam President: Shattering the Last Glass Ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's lead in the polls has led many advisers to counsel him to
pick a safe, conventional choice. And his strength among women in
the polls, a group that normally heavily favors Democrats has
further reduced the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the gender gap has vanished has taken away the
incentive,'' Clift said.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, the ranks of nationally known women is thin, and they
do not come from the Midwest states where the election is likely to
be won.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein has long dismissed the likelihood of her selection,
insisting that she is focused on winning re-election to the Senate.
Most strategists believe California is safely Democratic without
Feinstein, and that her addition to the ticket could lead to an
uncomfortable focus on her husband's business dealings with China _
even though he pledged three years ago to donate any profits from
such investments to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe Feinstein is simply too independent to play to role
of a loyal No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure she has the requisite number of subservient genes
required for vice president,'' Clift said.
</P>
<P>
   Seated in the vice president's private Capitol Hill office a few
steps from the Senate chamber, California Sen. Barbara Boxer said
she has no doubt a woman will occupy a national office in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women didn't get the vote until 1920,'' said Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a function of their experience. Right now, you don't have
too many who fit the bill. It's not a matter of if. It's a matter
of when.''
</P>
<P>
   The apparent exclusion of women and minorities from the A list
was evident in recent feature story in the New York Times Sunday
Magazine, which detailed Gore's selection process and included tiny
mug shots of 10 top contenders stripped across the top.
</P>
<P>
   They were all white men.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is this?'' Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-San Francisco, said in
response to the photos, blaming the media more than Gore's campaign
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Democratic Party in the 20th century, and a woman
couldn't make a list of 10?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
