r a BC-INS-CITIZENSHIP-SFCHR     07-21 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INS-CITIZENSHIP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT RULES INS CAN'T REVOKE CITIZENSHIP
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a decision protecting thousands of
naturalized citizens, a federal appeals court ruled Thursday that
the U.S. Justice Department cannot skirt the court system and
revoke citizenship on its own.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Court of Appeals in San Francisco said the Immigration
and Naturalization Service did not have the authority in 1997 to
implement new procedures to strip individuals of citizenship in
closed-door administrative hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The decision directly affects 2,692 naturalized citizens across
the nation who received notices in 1997 or 1998 informing them of
the INS's intention to begin procedures to revoke their
citizenship. The INS claimed they had failed to disclose criminal
backgrounds. A federal judge in Seattle issued a preliminary
injunction in 1998 barring the agency from continuing the practice.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, the Court of Appeals in San Francisco ruled
in a 2-1 decision that the INS had the power to revoke citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   But in a decision Thursday by an 11-judge panel, the same court
ruled that Congress had given only the judiciary that authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizenship in the United States of America is among our most
valuable rights,'' wrote Judge Andrew Kleinfeld of Alaska in the
court's opinion. ``For the Attorney General to gain the terrible
power to take citizenship away without going to court, she needs
Congress to say so.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has provided only one way to revoke the citizenship of
naturalized citizens, Kleinfeld said, and that is for a federal
prosecutor to file a petition in court. ``There is no statutory
warrant of a second way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The court rejected the Justice Department's argument that
because it had the right to grant citizenship it also had the power
to take it away. The court called the argument ``weak.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no general principle that what one can do, one can
undo,'' Kleinfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan S. Franklin, the Washington, D.C., lawyer representing
the nationwide class of citizens challenging the INS, said the
decision gives all naturalized citizens the protection of a
neutral, independent judge.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that under administrative procedures, the INS official
who issues the notice alerting people to the fact they might be
ineligible for citizenship is the same person who makes the final
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased that the court has unanimously confirmed that
the INS cannot take away the precious right of United States
citizenship without first proving it in a court of law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Franklin, the citizens who received notices
included a woman in Los Angeles held by police for growing a
marijuana plant. It turned out to be a house plant, and the woman,
who was originally from Mexico and had lived in the United States
for most of her life, was released by police.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, Franklin said, a man in New York faced loss of
citizenship after he was arrested. Though his arrest was nullified
by a judge, the INS notified him that the agency was initiating
procedures to revoke his citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokeswoman Carole Florman said that the
government lawyers had not had a chance to review the decision but
would take ``appropriate action following our review.''
</P>
<P>
   The INS adopted the rules in 1996 in the wake of criticism by
Republicans of Citizenship USA, a campaign launched by the Clinton
administration that allowed 180,000 immigrants to become citizens
before the November election without having to go through a
criminal background check.
</P>
<P>
   The INS responded by conducting an unprecedented review of more
than 1 million people granted citizenship between August 1995 and
September 1996. The study found 6,300 people lied or failed to
inform the INS about prior arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,600 people received notices that the INS was taking steps
to revoke their citizenship, but the agency acknowledged that only
369 of those people had committed crimes that would make them
ineligible for citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   The INS ultimately revoked the citizenship of 16 people before
the judge in Seattle issued the injunction blocking the process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
