<HEADER>
A8466 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-DELEGATION-ABORTION-S     07-21 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELEGATION-ABORTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIFORNIA GOP PICKS PRO-CHOICE ADVOCATE FOR PLATFORM PANEL  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The California delegation to the Republican National Convention
has chosen a pro-choice advocate as a representative on the GOP
platform committee _ and she will push for a ``more moderate''
party position on abortion, state leaders said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Parsky, who heads Texas Gov. George W. Bush's campaign in
California and chairs the 374-member state delegation, told
reporters Thursday that Toni Casey, the vice-mayor of Los Altos
Hills, has been appointed to the key subcommittee, which deals with
family issues within the GOP platform.
</P>
<P>
   He pledged she will be ``a good advocate'' for a viewpoint that
clearly differs from the official party position on the volatile
issue of abortion.
</P>
<P>
   With a little over a week to go before the Republican National
Convention opens in Philadelphia, the announcement was part of an
effort by state GOP leaders to underscore Bush's efforts to enlarge
the party's ``big tent.''
</P>
<P>
   The current GOP platform condemns abortion _ and makes no
exceptions for rape, incest or the life or health of the mother.
Bush has said he will not contest that language and believes the
GOP ``ought to maintain its pro-life tenor.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey, a strong Bush supporter, said Thursday that she will tell
GOP convention delegates that the issue has no place at all in the
GOP platform. ``The better solution is to recognize that this issue
has differing opinions on this side, and each side has respect for
the other,'' she said. ``This ... is a privacy and moral issue and
should be taken out of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The former biotech lobbyist said she is receiving 50 cards and
letters a day from pro-choice Republicans supporting her presence.
That's a far cry from the 1996 GOP national convention in San
Diego, where abortion proved a bitterly divisive issue _ and former
California Gov. Pete Wilson was lambasted by hard-liners for
unsuccessfully attempting to get his party to reconsider its tough
anti-abortion stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very incredible opportunity ... of having a full place
at the table,'' said Casey, who credited Bush's own campaign, as
well as the state GOP, for the change. But Casey added that
pro-choice Republicans are ``clearly unified in supporting George
W. Bush, and we will come out of the convention ... to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsky, in a conference call to reporters, also touted the
California GOP delegation as reflective of California's diversity,
saying it represented ``a different kind of convention for a
different type of Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   But Parsky ran into trouble when he acknowledged that the GOP
has made no real measure of how diverse his delegation is, either
ethnically or in sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Parsky said Republicans ``don't operate (delegation selection)
with any quota system,'' and while there's no data to prove it, he
has ``high confidence'' that the party's representatives will
represent fresh voices at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic campaign adviser Bob Mulholland immediately
called the GOP's efforts to tout diversity ``a carnival shell
game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush Jr.'s already caved in to Jerry Falwell and Bob Jones''
on the issue of abortion. Their platform says they believe that
abortion should not be a private matter _ it should be a crime,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he ridiculed the GOP's attempt to portray its ``handpicked''
delegation as diverse. ``Maybe to a billionaire, this crowd looks
diverse,'' said Mulholland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0015 </DOCNO>
