<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BE SURE TO BRAKE FOR GARTER SNAKE  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Deep thoughts, cheap shots and bon motz ...
</P>
<P>
   -- In Los Angeles, they're rounding up stray dogs and gassing
them, as part of city beautification for the Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   To survive, a dog must blend in. So please give generously to my
campaign to buy straw boaters for L.A.'s stray dogs.
</P>
<P>
   -- At the Buchanan Grill in the Marina, Mike Fogarty nods toward
a row of serious regulars on stools near the window and says,
``I've seen younger faces on stamps and money.''
</P>
<P>
   -- That Disneylandesque cultural thing proposed for Pier 45,
Steven Cannata says one thrill ride should be a United Airlines
fantasy flight simulator that takes off and lands on time.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ernest Isaacs points out that in the recent news story about
the dangers of cell-phoning drivers, the crash investigator's name
is Frances Bents.
</P>
<P>
   -- And when Diane Egelston wrote a complaint letter to
Washington Mutual Bank, she got a reply thanking her for her
concern about the rest rooms, even though that wasn't her
complaint. The letter was signed by Quality Service Management guy
Sebastian Bologna.
</P>
<P>
   -- Up in Napa Valley, Maxine Carlin was watching the notices
scroll on the community-access TV station and was struck by an ad
for the Upper Valley Spa (cq)  &LR; and Neuter Network.
</P>
<P>
   -- If it's dangerous to do cell-phoning, e-mailing and
TV-watching while driving, how about big insurance and registration
discounts for drivers of low-tech or no-tech cars? Take a yearly
polygraph test, get big savings.
</P>
<P>
   -- Cuffs Corbett goes into a flower shop on 18th St., in the
heart of the Castro, asks for a boutonniere. Two French guys are
working. ``A boutonniere? I don't know what that is, do you?''
``Yes, I think so, but I don't know how to make one.'' Mama mia.
</P>
<P>
   -- Someone named Pogonup was watching TV when her Seti screen _
a Web site that allows your computer to search for extraterrestrial
intelligence _ went into some kind of strange hyperspeed.
</P>
<P>
   She asks, ``Now that the aliens have contacted me, what do I do
next?''
</P>
<P>
   Direct them to the Upper Valley Spa and Neuter Network.
</P>
<P>
   -- At Carmel's Homescapes store, Daryl Glen reports, they sell
Demeter ``Pick Me Up'' Cologne in ``Funeral Home'' scent. A hint of
pine box?
</P>
<P>
   -- Construction on the BART extension came to a screeching halt
when a truck ran over a garter snake. Kevin O'Brien notes that they
saved 60 or more of the snakes, squashed one, and yet work halts.
``If I were a truck driver, I'd keep a few of the snakes in a cage
in the cab. If I accidentally squished a snake on the road, I'd
whip out a spare and tell the biologists or whoever checks that I
revived it.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Garter snake gets squished, it's Shutdown City. Pedestrian
gets squished, nothing stops. Maybe that's because garter snakes
are endangered.
</P>
<P>
   -- O'Brien's scheme reminds me: How come baseball players never
try the Old Hidden-Ball Trick any more?
</P>
<P>
   -- Disneyland: Lynn Downey and Tom Puthoff are in line for the
Matterhorn. As one sled chugs up the big first hill, they notice
that one rider is chatting on a cell phone. Then they get into
their bobsled and it stops dead halfway up the big incline. Lynn
says, ``Do you suppose Disneyland will now tell people to turn off
their cell phones when they get on rides, like they do in
airplanes?''
</P>
<P>
   -- Ballyard wildlife: Jon Carroll spied barn swallows living in
the eaves of the grandstands, and they dip and dart over the crowd,
adding to the ambiance.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Abney spotted a pair of bats, the winged kind, swooping
over McCovey Cove, and he wonders, ``If you are bitten by a bat at
a Giants' game, at the next full moon will you turn into a Dodger
fan?''
</P>
<P>
   -- Sure it's nutty, but common sense ain't working: Susan
Seitz-West suggests that the city issue each pedestrian a
garter-snake costume.
</P>
<P>
   -- Two mystery candidates are about to officially jump into the
S.F. Supervisor Sweepstakes in Districts 5 and 6. Both are
famous-name, old-S.F.-liberal pols who can't be counted on to kiss
The Machine's rear. So they won't get Willie's blessing, but they
could stir stuff up.
</P>
<P>
   -- Anthony Flores was watching ``The Love Bug,'' filmed in '69
in the Bay Area, and got misty eyed at the scene where the car
rally goes through Chinese Camp in gold country, and you see a
station selling gas for 40 cents.
</P>
<P>
   -- Lead story in last Sunday's Fresno Bee travel section:
``Oakland? OK!'' Way to go, Oakland. But the headline should have
been: ``There's there there!''
</P>
<P>
   -- Tom Torlakson, an Assemblyman from Antioch, had his identity
stolen a couple of years ago by a meth-cooking con man. So
Torlakson held a town hall meeting last Wednesday to discuss
identity theft. But how do we know that was really him?
</P>
<P>
   -- Census worker Bill Warner, plastic ID card on a chain around
his neck, is standing on a SoMa street corner. A homeless guy is
checking him out and Bill braces for some kind of harangue about
government workers.
</P>
<P>
   Guy says, ``Nice tie.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The Golden Dragon Massage Parlor, on Mason in the 'Loin, now
has an ATM machine. No, I don't know if this is a spa and neuter
place.
</P>
<P>
   -- My favorite in-house memo title, on a note about possible
computer problems, and I save it to read on hot days: ``What to do
if your Coyote freezes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
