<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8469 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DEPLOY-DNC &LR; - &UR; LADN     07-21 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEPLOY-DNC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LIMIT PROPOSED FOR PROTESTERS
</HEADLINE>
 - LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ To satisfy a federal judge, Los Angeles police
proposed Thursday allowing Democratic National Convention
protesters within 100 yards of the Staples Center, but vowed to
``not surrender our city.''
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Bernard C. Parks, speaking before two City Council
committees, said the new plan would protect life and property --
but involve substantially more officers and boost the cost of
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not surrender our city,'' Parks said. ``Our duty lies
first with protecting the city, securing the convention and
allowing demonstrators to have their say -- not the other way
around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will require us to have more officers on duty at Staples
Center and there will be higher costs,'' Parks told members of the
Budget and Finance and Ad Hoc Committee on the Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The new proposal will be submitted to U.S. District Court Judge
Gary Feess, whose ruling released Thursday says the original plan
would violate protester rights to free speech by restricting them
to a yards from the Staples Center, across Olympic Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Protecting the safety of all people present in the Staples
Center area during the convention is undoubtedly a significant
government interest,'' Feess wrote. He added, however, that the
``government cannot infringe on First Amendment rights on the mere
speculation that violence may occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Several council members voiced concern that the new plan would
leave police unable to protect other areas of the city, including
the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have spoken to Valley commanders and others and they tell me
about how thin they are in the ranks,'' said Councilman Joel Wachs.
</P>
<P>
   Police plans would allow for coverage, Parks said, even if the
city goes to full mobilization, with officers assigned to 12-hour
shifts, which effectively doubles the size of the force.
</P>
<P>
   Although expensive -- such a plan costs $1.5 million a day --
Parks said it is a way to ensure police coverage across the city.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Tokaji, the American Civil Liberties Union staff attorney
who challenged the city's original plan, questioned whether the new
plan goes far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cases cited by the judge said that 75 yards away is too
far,'' Tokaji said. ``We will look at whatever they submit, but on
the surface that doesn't sound acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Without providing specific numbers or the cost, Cmdr. Tom
Lorenzen said the new plan might involve several hundred more
officers ``I can tell you from our experience in this city that
even with a fence, it is unstable and insecure. Without a fence, it
would be completely out of control. And if the demonstrators
attempt to breach the fence, it will mean we need even more
officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Alex Padilla said he was disturbed by the timing of
the discussions -- much of which had been heard before and was
assuming a worst-case scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making assumptions based on demonstrations that may or
may not happen, on violence that may or may not happen,'' Padilla
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the various official protest groups have adopted a
pledge of nonviolence, Parks said the same oath was made last year
in Seattle before the World Trade Organization meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to be like the Seattle police chief and stand
up before the cameras and say they lied to me,'' Parks said. ``We
have to prepare for any eventuality.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
