<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACHILLES' TENDON SIDELINES ANDERSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Center fielder Garret Anderson, after
suffering a couple of brain cramps in the past week, has come down
with what the Angels hope will be a less-lingering malady: a
strained Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was a late scratch from Thursday's lineup because of
the sore left heel. He suffered the injury while running during
Wednesday night's 3-2 loss to Texas but was penciled in the
designated hitter's spot on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It added injury to insult for Anderson, who twice in the past
week has failed to back up right fielders on balls that got away
from them.
</P>
<P>
   MERCKER UPDATE: Kent Mercker threw batting practice, the latest
step in his recovery from a cerebral hemorrhage on May 12. Mercker
reported no problems and is slated to throw a simulated game on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia said that a return by Mercker in 10
days is unrealistic, but if all goes well, the long man/spot
starter would likely be back before Sept. 1, when rosters are
expanded to 40 players. The plan is for Mercker to throw a couple
of simulated games before beginning rehab assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Mike Fyhrie has been outstanding in Mercker's role
(a 1.37 ERA over his last 26 innings), Scioscia said he won't have
a problem finding a spot for the left-hander. The Angels have only
one left-hander in the bullpen, Mike Holtz. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
