<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8474 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-HMOS-BENEFITS &LR; - &UR; LADN     07-21 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMOS-BENEFITS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMOS TO COVER ACUPUNCTURE VISITS
</HEADLINE>
 - LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ First it was banning smoking in restaurants and
bars. Later it was Tae Bo and drinking shots of wheat grass. Now
health-conscious Californians want their health plans to offer
herbal supplements and acupuncture along with regular doctor
visits.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate their 2 &UR;  &LR; million California members, Woodland
Hills-based Health Net announced Thursday that it will begin
offering HMO-style coverage of acupuncture service and herbal
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   For a small fee -- no more than $15 -- a Health Net member will
be able to visit an acupuncturist to relieve, well, all the things
acupuncturists relieve. That same Health Net member will be able to
buy supplements for a similarly low co-payment.
</P>
<P>
   Other HMOs have offered limited coverage of acupuncture and
herbal supplements, but Health Net's is believed to be the most
comprehensive to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done our research, which shows there is a demand for
these services,'' said Lisa Kalustian, associate vice president of
communications and public relations at Health Net.
</P>
<P>
   There's also medical proof. Kalustian said the National
Institutes of Health has concluded that acupuncture has been proved
to be an effective therapy for a variety of conditions, including
lower back pain and chemotherapy-induced nausea and vomiting.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to offering discount programs for complementary
therapies, as some other health maintenance organizations do,
Health Net's acupuncture and herbal supplements coverage allows
members with HMO benefits to self-refer to an acupuncture provider
for up to a $15 co-payment, depending on the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Diamond, senior media manager with the American
Association of Health Plans in Washington, said more and more
health plans nationwide are offering some acupuncture benefits but
not to the extent of Health Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``It varies from plan to plan greatly still,'' Diamond said.
``Employees who want these benefits should ask their health plans
or their employer to see if they will purchase them.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamond said if there are enough employees who are willing to
pay for an herbal supplements plan, the HMO will provide coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers need to remember that a lot of alternative
treatments are very costly, so it's hard to afford them out of
pocket,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of these plans to the employer vary, Kalustian said,
from about 80 cents per member per month up to about $2.50 per
person per month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price depends on whether it's just chiropractic care or
combined with acupuncture and herbal,'' Kalustian said.
</P>
<P>
   At Blue Shield of California, members have access to
chiropractic and acupuncture benefits depending on their plan, said
company spokeswoman Michelle Naiditch.
</P>
<P>
   For 1.2 million Californians with PPO coverage, acupuncture and
chiropractic is automatically part of their benefits package, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   For HMO plans, it's offered if the employer chooses to purchase
the optional acupuncture rider, while Medicare members are offered
the plan in a ``complementary benefit'' package for $25 per month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers have expressed a strong interest in mind, body and
health,'' Naiditch said. ``Our benefits and the discounts available
respond to those consumers with the assurance Blue Shield standards
for quality are being met.''
</P>
<P>
   Health Net's acupuncture and herbal supplement benefits will be
offered as an optional feature to employer groups beginning Aug. 1
with initial effective dates a month later.
</P>
<P>
   The new benefits are available to employers offering Health Net
commercial or Medicare HMO benefits, she said. The network of
acupuncture providers is maintained by American Specialty Health
Plan.
</P>
<P>
   Health Net is a subsidiary of Foundation Health Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
