<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BOS </SLUG>
  
 RED SOX SPLIT WITH ORIOLES; SCHOUREK DONE?
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Pete Schourek was as tough a lefty as there was in
the National League in the mid-1990s, even though Red Sox Nation
barely caught a glimpse of that incarnation. And he'll always own a
small but notable niche in Red Sox annals as the guy who was given
the ball instead of Pedro Martinez one October, with a playoff
series hanging in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   But Schourek, who would sooner stop breathing than pitching, may
have reached the stage in his career where he is more useful in a
pre-med class at Tufts, where students could examine his ravaged
left arm, than back on the mound for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The longest day of the season for the Red Sox _ a day-night
doubleheader split against the Baltimore Orioles that saw the Sox
take the first game, 11-7, and lose the second, 9-4, with a
suspended Carl Everett (he was hit with a 10-game ban for last
Saturday's confrontation with umpire Ronald Kulpa) still in uniform
pending his appeal _ may have more lasting ramifications for
Schourek.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5-inch Virginian is 30, but his left arm might as
well be as old as that of another gallant Sox lefty, Mel Parnell,
who is 78. Schourek lasted seven outs in Thursday night's loss and
was charged with five runs on five hits and two walks.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, as the Sox wearily prepared for a postmidnight
flight home, Schourek admitted his arm was hamburger. In addition
to having bone chips in his elbow, which he hoped he could grin and
bear until winter, he also has stiffness in his shoulder. He
suspects, after talking with team doctor Bill Morgan, that he has
some fraying in his rotator cuff and a bone spur in the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think anyone will sign me after five surgeries?''
Schourek said as he contemplated his baseball mortality. ``I can't
beat myself up about it.''
</P>
<P>
   With Schourek sporting a record of 2-9, an ERA of 5.05, and a
bum arm, and a country boy named Paxton Crawford, who already has
won in the big leagues and three days ago threw a no-hitter at
Pawtucket, waiting in the wings, Schourek's days in the rotation
appear to be numbered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see me making my next start for sure,'' Schourek said.
``After that, I don't know. I'm scheduled for an MRI in the next
couple of days, and we'll see how that plays out.''
</P>
<P>
   The suspicion is that it will play out just as unhappily as
Thursday night's game, when John Wasdin, who warmed up in the first
inning of both ends of the twinbill, finally got the call in the
third inning with the Sox still ahead, 3-2, but two Orioles on base
and a 2-and-0 count on Charles Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin walked Johnson, a base on balls that was charged to
Schourek. That loaded the bases, which for Wasdin is about as safe
as setting his pants on fire. Four times this season, he has
pitched with the bases full, and 10 of the 12 runners have scored,
including three Thursday night all coming home courtesy of Mark
Lewis's double into the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the third time we'd gotten Wasdin up,'' Williams said.
``We didn't have a lot of bullets out there. It didn't work, but it
was the right time to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez, the Game 1 starter, survived a stormy
introduction Thursday afternoon, giving up a first-inning grand
slam to Will (the Infrequent Thrill) Clark, who would later homer
off Wasdin in Game 2. Mike Bordick added a final two-run shot off
Bryce Florie in the seventh to put to rest any thoughts of a Sox
sweep.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't an idle notion. The Sox had beaten the O's 10
straight in Camden Yards, smacking 17 hits in the opener to rescue
Martinez, who allowed just one more run in his five innings of
work. Hours after baseball disciplinarian Frank Robinson called
Everett to tell him about his upcoming 10-game vacation, the Sox
center fielder hit a two-run home run with his first swing since
getting the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a distraction to me,'' Everett had said before the
game. ``It's all behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though Everett would go on to whiff four times for only
the third time in his career, it was smooth sailing for the Sox in
Game 1 once they got past Clark's first slam in nine years. Troy
O'Leary was on base five times with a walk and four hits, driving
in three runs. Nomar Garciaparra singled, doubled, and tripled,
raising his average to .403. (He proved mortal in Game 2, going 0
for 5 to bring his average down to .396.) Jason Varitek, who came
into the game in a 1-for-18 spin, doubled, homered, and singled.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got big hits all day,'' said Orioles manager Mike
Hargrove. ``They have a track record of getting big hits and
driving in big runs and that's what we saw.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what Hargrove and the Orioles saw in Game 2, when
the Sox had just four hits off a wild Scott Erickson (six walks in
5 1/3 innings) and three relievers.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles, meanwhile, had 14 hits and seven walks against
Boston moundsmen Schourek, Waz, and Florie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to sit down,'' Williams said as he popped up from his
chair after Game 2, which lasted 3 hours 14 minutes, two minutes
longer than the matinee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got beat. We've been here a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long enough for the immortal Izzy Alcantara to see action,
though. He was the only Sox position player not to take the field
in the doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   For Schourek, the leaving may be the hardest part. He graduated
from George C. Marshall High School in 1987, the same year he
pitched his first game of pro ball. It was only a year later, in
1988, when he had his first operation on his left elbow, and missed
the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, he was in the big leagues. The guy has made a
career out of making comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid has got a heart as big as this building,'' Williams
said. ``He wants to pitch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
