<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-EVERETTSUSPENDED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAGUE GIVES EVERETT 10 GAMES FOR OUTBURST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Minutes after being informed Thursday morning that
he had been suspended for 10 games and fined (an amount not made
public) by Major League Baseball for twice making contact with
plate umpire Ronald Kulpa last Saturday, Red Sox center fielder
Carl Everett filed an appeal through the Major League Players
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lenaghan, assistant general counsel for the players
union, said he filed the appeal after speaking with Everett in the
visitors' clubhouse, about an hour before the penalty was announced
by Frank Robinson, vice president of on-field operations for Major
League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal allows Everett to continue playing until a hearing is
held. The hearing will be conducted by Paul Beeston, baseball's
chief operating officer. No date has been set for the hearing, and
while Beeston has attempted to hear appeals more quickly than
league presidents did in the past, it took him nearly six weeks to
make a ruling on the multiple appeals filed after the Dodgers'
brawl with spectators May 16 at Chicago's Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   It also was three weeks before Beeston conducted his hearing on
the Tigers-White Sox brawls April 22, for which Dean Palmer of the
Tigers was suspended eight games for charging the mound, then
coming out of the clubhouse for a second brawl after already having
been ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to need time to prepare,'' Lenaghan said. ``This
is not your garden-variety case.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10-game suspension assessed Everett is the stiffest penalty
given a player by Robinson, who is in his first year of
administering discipline. It also is the longest given a player for
an on-field incident since Bill Madlock, who was playing for
Pittsburgh, shoved his glove in the face of umpire Jerry Crawford
in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The statement from the commissioner's office read, ``Boston Red
Sox outfielder Carl Everett has been suspended for 10 games and
fined an undisclosed amount for excessive arguing, using foul
language, and making contact with an umpire on two occasions during
the Mets-Red Sox game at Fenway Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett hit a home run in his first at-bat after being informed
of his suspension, then struck out a season-high four times in the
Red Sox' 11-7 win over the Orioles in Game 1 of a day-night
doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a reaction,'' Everett said before the first game,
breaking his silence on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Everett was asked about comments by Larry Reynolds, his agent,
that a closer viewing of videotapes of the incident showed he had
not head-butted Kulpa, who is in his first season in the big
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing is that the majority of the media tried to
make a guy (into) a monster,'' Everett said. ``Everybody is quick
to judge. I fault the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he regretted any of his actions, Everett said, ``You're
asking a question I really don't have an answer for, because that
answer can be fabricated. There's no need to answer that.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate reaction from the executive board of the
World Umpires Association, the umpires' new union that is in a
critical stage of its negotiations with Major League Baseball on a
new collective bargaining agreement. Karen Brinkman, administrative
assistant for the WUA, said early Thursday night the union may have
a statement forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox spokesman Kevin Shea said general manager Dan Duquette,
who was not with the team, would not comment on the suspension. Red
Sox manager Jimy Williams was asked if he found the penalty
excessive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not for me to decide,'' Williams said. ``Everybody has a
job, just like you have with that pen right now. Frank Robinson
certainly has a tough job, but somebody has to make a decision. He
accepted the responsibility of taking that job, so he's handled it
the best he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett acknowledged he had spoken with Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him, that's all I can do,'' Everett said. ``He
called me. I talked to him. I told him my side. That's all I can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the severity of the suspension, Everett mentioned
how he had spoken out against Pedro Martinez's five-game suspension
for hitting Cleveland's Roberto Alomar with a pitch April 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've defended Pedro before, and what I stated with Pedro I
pretty much still feel the same,'' he said. ``Certain situations
are going be treated differently, so really I don't have an opinion
on every situation that goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The media) tried to make me out to be a monster, that's the
whole thing. That's purely it. If you listen to everything someone
said, it's their own opinion instead of what you actually see.
That's what they want everyone else to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he saw, Everett said, ``I would say I didn't do the
things people said I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he found unfair about the suspension that led
him to appeal, Everett said, ``I'm not gonna . . . That's . . . I
can't really state that here because there's no merit here. Where I
state that is when I go for my appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reporter mentioned to Everett that several of his
teammates had explained Everett's actions as the result of a
competitor being ``juiced.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There again, I mean I can say some things that could rattle
some feathers but I'd rather keep that to myself until I appeal my
case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked if he blamed Kulpa, who twice drew a line in the
dirt near home plate after Mets catcher Mike Piazza complained that
Everett was standing too close to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to judge another person,'' he said. ``I would
not go out of my way to just make myself look better. Let
everything stand as it is right now. At a later date, I can
elaborate.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he felt he owed an apology to his teammates, he
said: ``That's just something between me and my teammates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
