<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA COLUMN: WHAT'S FOX UP TO?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the surface, the latest strategic move by the folk at Fox
Sports doesn't make sense.
</P>
<P>
   The network that hired Keith Olbermann away from MSNBC and
installed him as the fulcrum of its Fox Sports News show, since
refurbished as the National Sports Report (NSR), is leaving that
show to host a weekly show on Sunday entitled ``The Keith Olbermann
Evening News.''
</P>
<P>
   Olbermann still will host the baseball pregame show on Fox and
have an expanded role in the network's postseason coverage, but his
days as co-host on the NSR are numbered. The new show is set to
debut on Aug. 6, and it will replace the NSR on Sunday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Fox President David Hill, who has been the nursemaid for
virtually every sports product at Fox, said that Olbermann has met
the goal of establishing the NSR as a competitor to ESPN's
SportsCenter, and that the plan was always to create him some new
challenges. Olbermann will also be executive producer of his show,
meaning no one will be around telling him what he can and can't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``In TV, you've got to be a shark,'' said Hill. ``When Keith
first came here, the news show was a mess, and he's corrected that.
This is something brand new, an attempt to redefine what networks
give viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One phrase I want to keep clear of with this show is `the
thinking man's show,' because I thing that would be wrong. But we
are trying to create something that's new.''
</P>
<P>
   Olbermann describes the new show as a hybrid. It will look like
a normal highlights show for 15 to 30 minutes, then move to
analysis, a live interview with a newsmaker and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have a smorgasbord quality,'' said Olbermann. ``It's
like a Sunday newspaper. The Sunday paper is always bigger and has
many more things in it than any other days. The threshold will be
finding enough compelling stories to make it a solid hour of
wall-to-wall information.''
</P>
<P>
   Olbermann's job history is dotted with disagreements with
management, most notably his acrimonious departure from ESPN. Most
often, he has complained at management attempts to dumb-down its
sports product (i.e., Fox's sappy Regional Sports Report).
</P>
<P>
   So the question had to be asked: Was there a conflict between
Olbermann and NSR execs, especially since the recent changes that
saw less time for Olbermann commentaries and more time for
analysts?
</P>
<P>
   No, says Hill and Olbermann. But Hill admits the NSR needed to
change directions to adapt to a new environment that includes the
Internet. The emphasis on analysts early and often was a response
to Fox surveys that show 42 percent of all NSR viewers know the
result of the games that interest them before tuning in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't terribly happy with the original NSR and its former
role as Fox Sports News,'' Hill said. ``Our ratings were such that
I once asked if it wouldn't be cheaper to fly all the viewers in
and put them in a studio?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're using the same philosophy we took when we created the
NFL pregame show: Report the facts and wrap them in analysis. The
great joy of sports is anticipation what happened, what does it
mean, and what's going to happen next.''
</P>
<P>
   This policy is OK when the analysts are the fearless Kevin
Kennedy (baseball) and energetic Marques Johnson (basketball), but
bad when the analyst is the somnolent Phil Esposito (hockey). Those
shows work best, too, when the anchors are also strong
personalities, like Olbermann.
</P>
<P>
   Hill prefers to flip direction. Rather than focus on what the
NSR is losing, he's looking forward to Olbermann's new show and the
way it hopefully will fit with other aggressive, content-heavy Fox
shows, like ``The Last Word'' with Jim Rome and ``Goin' Deep'' with
Chris Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a greedy programmer,'' said Hill. ``The more strong
programs I have the better.''
</P>
<P>
   And the decision does come at a time when the networks are all
flexing their often ignored and undernourished journalist muscles.
ESPN recently added a weekly edition of ``Outside the Lines'' and
HBO will debut a show hosted by Bob Costas after the baseball
season as a companion to ``Real Sports with Bryant Gumbel.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be wonderful if all of these shows thrived, but
hard-hitting sports shows are a pretty low priority for sports
fans. Howard Cosell's ``Sports Beat'' show on ABC back in the '70s
was a Nielsen failure. Ratings aren't nearly as important in cable,
but it isn't cheap to front shows with hosts like Olbermann, Costas
and Gumbel.
</P>
<P>
   At least in Olbermann's case, he answers to himself. As he joked
Thursday, ``the key to this show is the opportunity to be executive
producer. which may allow me to submit my own resignation to
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   THIRD AND LONG: Fox Sports will double its number of Hall of
Fame broadcasters next weekend when ex-Raider Howie Long is
inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The analyst on the Fox NFL pregame show says his broadcast
experience helped put his playing career in better perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt Millen said this when I went to work for Fox, and I now
know what he meant,'' said Long. ``I didn't have any perspective of
my own career until I had the opportunity to talk with coaches and
players, especially young players coming up now, who thought a
great deal of how I played the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had tremendous respect for the privilege to play in
the NFL, and when you're playing, you don't think of yourself in
those terms. That was a benefit of my TV work I didn't really
expect.''
</P>
<P>
   DOG DAYS OF SUMMER: Coming to the ESPN and ESPN2 airwaves
beginning July 27 will be 17 hours of ``The Great Outdoor Games,''
an X Games spin-off the cable owns and hopes to develop into solid
alternative programming each summer.
</P>
<P>
   There will be 21 events in four categories that fall way outside
of the usual sports panorama fishing, timber events, target sports,
and sporting dogs. Other than the old ``American Sportsman'' series
hosted by Curt Gowdy or ESPN coverage of the occasional Lumberjack
Games, these sports haven't been graced by many cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The fishing events include bass fishing, fly-fishing and casting
competition, and there will be shotgun, rifle and archery events in
the target section. The timber events include the always popular
Hot Saw and Two-Board Jigger, and the dogs will compete in Big Air
and Fly Ball competition.
</P>
<P>
   Big Air is essentially the doggy long jump. Technology has also
gone to the dogs with the first use of the Dog Cam worn by some
competitors. ESPN is taking this event seriously. The host is NFL
reporter Mark Malone, and ABC's Jack Arute, ESPN NHL analyst Bill
Clement and ESPN college football voice Ron Franklin are also
members of the cast.
</P>
<P>
   Says Arute about the assignment: ``Dogs almost always are
accommodating even after a bitter defeat, and you rarely need to
watch out for inappropriate language.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Baywatch'' actress Kelly Packard will also do photo essays
during the coverage. Of herself, one might hope.
</P>
<P>
   AND NOW THE NEWS: It didn't take deposed Monday Night Football
announcer Boomer Esiason to find work. Westwood One/CBS Radio named
him an analyst on their Monday night radio broadcasts, joining
Howard David and analyst Matt Millen. Esiason has been co-host of a
football show on CBS Radio for more than a year. ... Tennis
Nielsens got a bump thanks to the American success of Pete Sampras
and Venus Williams at Wimbledon. Turner (TNT) averaged a 1.1 for
its 66 hours of daytime coverage, which works out to 868,000 homes
per broadcast. That was double what HBO averaged and also higher
than TNT's usual daytime average. NBC's ratings were also up over
last year. ... The newly aggressive U.S. Tennis Assn. has expanded
its media presence with a new series on CBS, ``Topspin,'' that airs
the next four Saturdays (11 a.m. this week). ... Monday's edition
of ``Real Sports'' on HBO (10 p.m.) includes a piece on gay
athletes. ... Sunday's ``Page One'' on CNN/SI (9:30 a.m., 4:30
p.m., 7:30 p.m.) focuses on sports parent rage. ... ESPN Classic
covers baseball's Hall of Fame induction ceremonies Sunday at 1:30
p.m. ... ESPN will go live with about ten minutes of Tour de France
coverage Sunday morning if Lance Armstrong is in a position to win
the race. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
