<HEADER>
A8486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CUBA-U.S.-1STLD-WRITE     07-21 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES EASING OF EMBARGO ON CUBAN TRADE AND TRAVEL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)  By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House of Representatives on Thursday night
approved measures to bar the Treasury Department from enforcing
restrictions on travel to Cuba as well as on the sale of food and
medicines to the island.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the 38-year-old American trade embargo on Cuba hailed
the votes as a major first step in the House toward clearing the
way to commercial ties and even American tourism.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 232-186, lawmakers ordered that the Treasury
Department's Office of Foreign Assets Control, the chief bureau for
enforcing sanctions against Cuba, be prohibited from spending
federal funds to restrict Americans from traveling there or
engaging in the sale of food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty Republicans voted in favor of the amendment on travel,
which was added to the bill to finance the Treasury Department and
Postal Service by Rep. Mark Sanford, R-S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford expressed elation at the vote, which he said was a sign
that lawmakers are increasingly prepared to engage the government
of Cuba, just as they have sought to end the isolation of
governments such as China and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford said the vote would help correct ``an incredible
inconsistency'' in American foreign policy, and marked a victory
for Americans who claim a constitutional right to travel to nations
whose governments are at odds with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Sanford said, American travel will advance the cause
of democratic reforms in Cuba more surely than efforts to isolate
the Cuban people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This marks the beginning of the an end for an outdated policy
toward Cuba,'' he said. ``We've tried 40 years of isolation. It has
not worked. The will of the house is that we take this incremental
step.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of sanctions against Cuba noted that it still remains
illegal for Americans to travel there as tourists, even if the
Treasury Department becomes unable to enforce the law.
</P>
<P>
   There is no companion measure on travel currently before the
Senate, the critics noted, and the overall bill faces a
presidential veto on unrelated matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has little practical effect, because the law hasn't
changed,'' said Rep. Robert Menendez, a New Jersey Democrat who is
one of three Cuban-American members of Congress. ``What you've done
in this act is to create lawlessness.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the vote on travel to Cuba has particular resonance.
Until the 1959 triumph of the revolution, Cuba was the leading
American tourism destination in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the government of Fidel Castro has built up
tourism, adding European-financed hotels in Havana and at the
popular beach resort of Varadero.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, a Cuban-American Republican from
Florida, charged that the measure would provide revenues to ``the
worst violator of human rights in all of the Western Hemisphere.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration since last year has greatly broadened
the categories of Americans allowed to travel to the island,
allowing more than 200 universities to license student travelers.
Such people-to-people contacts, American officials say, will
enhance the prospects for a peaceful political transition to
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   About 135,000 Americans visited Cuba last year on
government-approved trips. Another 22,000 traveled illegally
through third countries such as the Bahamas or Mexico, according to
Treasury Department estimates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 0200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
