<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK-TRIALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S LONG JUMP REACHING NEW HEIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 c.2000 San Bernardino Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Trash talk? Oodles. Upsets, breakthroughs, clutch
performances? Plenty of each.
</P>
<P>
   What the 2000 U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials lacks as it
enters its final three days is a world record, and it doesn't
appear the sport's superstars are going to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the women's pole vaulters.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone is going to make this the 14th U.S. trials out of the
past 17 with at least one world record, the practitioners of the
newest Olympic track-and-field event are most likely to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 16 feet could happen,'' said Stacy Dragila, holder of
the two-month-old world women's vault record of 15 feet, 1 inches.
``I mean, on a good day I could pull it out. It wouldn't be that
big a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Female vaulters are making such dramatic strides, a Beamonesque
trashing of the record is not out of the realm of the possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've started out with this sport being nothing and we've had
to bring it to something,'' said Kellie Suttle, who has a best
vault of 14-10.
</P>
<P>
   Dragila is the Michael Johnson of the sport; even before the
women's vault is contested in the Sydney Games, she already has a
widely seen television commercial. Dragila, 29, vaults to the show
tune ``I Enjoy Being a Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   She is additionally famous for roping goats as a young rodeo
performer in her rural Northern California home, and a bit infamous
for posing nude in a for-charity calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Vaulting remains something of a novelty for women, and its top
performers are pioneers as well as sort of sorority sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Said Suttle: ``I remember in the '95 nationals, people were
going, `What the hell is going on here? Girls with sticks!'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, now look at us. Our event's in the limelight and we have
to do everything we can to keep it there.''
</P>
<P>
   Women vaulters are known for showmanship, playing both to crowds
and cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not just wave a hand at the crowd, or shake our legs
around and look all mean and stuff,'' Suttle said. ``Let's get the
crowd involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of Olympics berths might begin to break up That Old
Gang of Theirs, but for now the vaulters remain close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost too close,'' Dragila conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Vaulters are known to help each other with information about
wind and the runway. Said Suttle: ``We've got this awesome thing in
common.''
</P>
<P>
   Dragila is the favorite to win gold at Sydney, but she is well
aware that American-record holder Jeff Hartwig didn't survive
qualifying here last weekend; he no-heighted and went home.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying in the women's vault is today; the finals are Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Final qualifying in the men's javelin and steeplechase was
contested late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In prelims on Thursday, Day 5 of the trials:
</P>
<P>
   -- Through four events, pre-meet favorite Chris Huffins led the
decathlon with 3,685 points, 100 more than rising star Tom Pappas.
Defending Olympic gold medalist Dan O'Brien withdrew from the event
with a foot injury.
</P>
<P>
   -- Johnny Gray's attempt to make a fifth Olympic team ended in
the 800-meter prelims, where he faded to last in his heat. Gray,
40, holds the 15-year-old American record of 1:42.60. Bryan
Woodward of Long Beach had the No.3 time.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Clark Family put three runners into the final of the
women's 800. Hazel Clark and sister Joetta Clark-Diggs had the top
times, and sister-in-law Jearl Miles-Clark posted the No.6 time.
``I'm really glad our team advanced,'' Hazel Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Connie Price-Smith, winner of 21 national championships, led
the women's shot put with a mark of 57-4, nearly 7 feet short of
her lifetime best.
</P>
<P>
   -- Eric Thomas, who just missed the 1996 Olympic team, had the
best time in the men's 400-meter hurdles preliminaries, at 49.25
seconds. Atlanta Olympics gold medalist Derrick Adkins had the
ninth-best time at 49.84.
</P>
<P>
   -- Lance Deal, silver medalist in 1996, led hammer prelims with
a throw of 245 feet, 11 inches. ``My daughter said to me, `Just
pretend it's the Olympics,''' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
