<HEADLINE>
SECOND-HALF SURGE LIFTS SPARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Sparks couldn't play any better than
they have against teams from the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Though trailing the New York Liberty at the half, the Sparks
came back for an 82-66 victory at the Forum, their eighth win in
eight games against a team from the East.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks shot 61 percent from the field and snapped New York's
six-game winning streak in front of 7,269.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks quickly got back on track after a losing an 11-point
lead and trailing at halftime 40-39. Los Angeles took a 61-47 lead,
outscoring New York 22-5 to start the second half.
</P>
<P>
   New York, which shot 47 percent in the first half, was held to
26 percent in the second half for 35 percent overall. They made
only two field goals during the Sparks early run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great defense,'' said Sparks coach Michael Cooper. ``I thought
we were able to sustain it longer than they had in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cooper had to remind the Sparks about how champions are
expected to play at the half, guard Tamecka Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talked a little bit about that killer instinct that
champions have,'' Dixon said. ``We picked it up on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks outrebounded the Liberty 39-23, which accounted for
several of the fastbreak points (22) the Sparks accumulated. Center
Lisa Leslie had a game-high 21 points and 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks shot 68 percent in the second half, finishing the
game making 34 of 56 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie was 8 of 11 from the field, and forward DeLisha Milton
had 17 points on 7 of 12 shooting. Guards Ukari Figgs was 5 of 5
from the field, finishing with 10 points, and Dixon was 6 of 7 for
12 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've been struggling as a team on the year shooting
and tonight we just came out and shot,'' Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks scored the first six points and stretched their lead
to 10 points when Milton scored to make it 25-15.
</P>
<P>
   Center Clarisse Machanguana gave the Sparks good production off
the bench, coming in to score five points to keep the home team
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But after that it was all Liberty, which quickly turned around
the game with a 16-5 run. Tamicka Whitmore and Teresa Weatherspoon
scored 11 of the points. After Whitmore's free throw, Weatherspoon
scored a 3-pointer and cut the lead to five with a pair of free
throws. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 0214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
