<HEADER>
A8515 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-OY-VEY-HILLARY!-ECONO     07-21 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OY-VEY-HILLARY!-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OY VEY! IS HILLARY CLINTON REALLY ANTI-SEMITIC?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 750-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Big Apple's media are easily bored, and the
Senate race between Rick Lazio and Hillary Rodham Clinton was in
danger of being written off as the mother of all snores.
</P>
<P>
   Recent claims in a book about Rudolph Giuliani _ vexed love
life, father in the Mafia, etc. _ only reminded journalists what
fun they would have had if the mayor had not dropped out of the
race.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with relish that they seized on reports that Hillary
had called somebody a ``(expletive) Jew bastard.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that she said it in 1974, if she said it at all? A
new book about the Clintons, ``State of a Union,'' describes Mrs.
Clinton hurling this abuse at Paul Fray, then manager of President
Bill Clinton's unsuccessful campaign for a seat in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Fray is a Baptist who claims only a Jewish great-grandmother,
and has often provided reporters with embarrassing details about
the Clintons. The First Lady denied this particular accusation
emphatically at a tearful press conference. (Needless to say, she
is scheduled to appear at a synagogue this weekend.)
</P>
<P>
   Not entirely helpfully, just as Mrs. Clinton was saying that she
did not even remember the argument with Fray, her husband took time
out from trying to negotiate a Middle East peace deal to say that
she ``never said it,'' though ``she might have called him a
bastard.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to accuse the Republicans of character assassination.
This allowed his wife's Republican opponent, Lazio, to remind
voters of the Clintons' tendency to shift blame swiftly to others.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can Mrs. Clinton have been wholly pleased by some other
attempts to defend her. A former
presidential-adviser-turned-troublemaker, Dick Morris, who is
Jewish, said that Mrs. Clinton is not anti-Semitic, though she
would keep serving him pork whenever he turned up for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times suggested that racist obscenities were
unlikely to have been uttered by ``one of the most politically
correct people on the planet,'' even if she has a foul temper.
</P>
<P>
   At least Giuliani was unequivocally nice, saying ``I'm willing
to accept her at her word.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Paul's Road-to-Damascus moment had nothing on Rudy's. Mrs.
Clinton's desire to disown this ancient profanity is
understandable. In New York's 1998 Senate race, Alfonse D'Amato's
chances of re-election were dealt a mortal blow when he called his
Jewish opponent, Chuck Schumer, a ``putz-head.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Yiddish scholars said this was a serious penis-based
obscenity, and not, as D'Amato claimed, the innocent twin of
schmuck.
</P>
<P>
   Before he used the word, polls showed D'Amato winning more than
a third of New York's 1.2 million Jewish votes; in the end, he took
only a fifth, which may have caused his narrow loss.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Jews have long tended to support Democrats. However,
even before the recent controversy, polls showed Hillary winning
only 54 percent of the Jewish votes to Lazio's 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many Jews have long regarded Mrs. Clinton as weak on Israel, and
thoroughly dislike her public embrace of Palestinians and her calls
for the establishment of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has worked for compensation for victims of the Holocaust,
and several prominent and wealthy New York Jews, who supported
Schumer in 1998, have publicly backed him.
</P>
<P>
   The current controversy is also playing to the perception of
many voters (Jewish or not) that Mrs. Clinton says one thing in
public _ usually a platitude _ while holding very different, even
vitriolic, views in private.
</P>
<P>
   The real Mrs. Clinton has been so well hidden from the voters
that it is easy for them to speculate that she may do all manner of
nasty things.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not everything is going against Mrs. Clinton in a race
that is still too close to call. She has been cleared, albeit
halfheartedly, of having played an inappropriate part in the
Travelgate affair.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's failure to march alongside Hillary and Rudy in the
gay-pride parade may have cost him some homosexual votes, despite
his claim that only previous engagements kept him away.
</P>
<P>
   And there remains the awkward possibility that he will be
prosecuted for insider dealing by the Securities and Exchange
Commission, over his purchase in 1997 of options on shares in Quick
&AMP; Reilly, a brokerage, shortly before it was acquired by Fleet
Financial at a big premium.
</P>
<P>
   The voters might be prepared to forgive him; but, if the SEC
were to charge him, could he stay in the race? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
