r k BC-CALIF-HOUSING-SQUEEZE     07-21 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-HOUSING-SQUEEZE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S NEW GOLD RUSH: HOUSING  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: California and Western-State Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The good life isn't what it used to be. Silicon
Valley headhunters report that executives from New York think twice
about multimillion-dollar offers when they compare the tiny place
they might afford in the Bay Area with the pile they live in in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Although America remains, on average, a cheap place to live by
European standards, it has pockets where the dynamism of the
economy has fuelled not only tremendous growth in wealth, but also
steep inflation in the cost of living.
</P>
<P>
   The sharpest price rises have come in the heartland of the new
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The average monthly rent for a one-bedroom apartment in Palo
Alto, in the heart of Silicon Valley, is $1,900, and prices in some
complexes have jumped from $1,550 at the beginning of the year to
$2,200 in June.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Sunnyvale, rents have climbed 25 percent since
the beginning of the year, and the vacancy rate has dropped to a
negligible 0.03 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Buying is just as daunting: the median house price in San
Francisco's Bay Area is $370,000, compared with $135,000 for the
country at large.
</P>
<P>
   For the well-off, this provides a chance either to moan or
gloat, depending on when they bought their house. They are unlikely
to be shut out altogether; they simply pay more or live in a
smaller space. The less well-off end up being displaced.
</P>
<P>
   The exodus of working-class residents is creating both
commercial problems and political strife. Nurses at Stanford's
hospital were followed by those at ten other Bay Area hospitals
when they went on strike last month to demand wages that would
allow them to live closer to where they worked, rather than
enduring a commute of several hours.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter of the positions in the Los Altos police force are
empty because officers, unable to live near the town, have
resigned, and the force expects to be down to half-strength by the
autumn.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure extends to the vacation resorts where the new
wealth goes to play. Median house prices around Lake Tahoe, a ski
area on the eastern border of California, have risen 60 percent in
the past year.
</P>
<P>
   The chambermaids and ski-lift attendants are being priced out.
In Truckee, the small main town of the resort, the Safeway
supermarket has resorted to advertising on television to attract
staff.
</P>
<P>
   One river-raft tour organizer has prepared for the summer season
by importing 12 assistants from eastern Europe and housing them in
tents.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the pressure is cyclical; the Bay Area has seen housing
bubbles before, and this one too will eventually burst. But the new
economy has permanently changed some patterns of life.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Kotkin of Pepperdine University in Los Angeles, author of a
forthcoming book on the geography of the information age, sees the
favorite cities of the Internet economy, such as San Francisco and
Seattle, as boutiques for the young, single and rich.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, for example, has the lowest density of children of any
city in America. Just 10.8 percent of its residents are aged
between five and 17.
</P>
<P>
   The cultural and ethnic mix that used to characterize inner
cities is increasingly found in suburbs. Yet even boutiques _ or
the mountain resorts that Kotkin calls ``Valhallas'' _ need a
mixture of people in order to function, including manual laborers,
police, nurses and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the cry in America's rental hot-zones for more
``affordable housing'': subsidized accommodation reserved for those
who work nearby and cannot afford the market rates.
</P>
<P>
   In California's budget, passed this month, $570 million has been
allocated just for this. In Aspen, a particularly chic resort town
in Colorado where the median price of a house is now over $2
million, ``affordable housing'' is needed even for people who
would, in most places, be the prosperous upper-middle class.
</P>
<P>
   To live in America's most sought-after enclaves, you need not
only to find your own house; you also need to help provide one for
your poor local lawyer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
