r k BC-BANKROLLING-PEACE-ECO     07-21 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKROLLING-PEACE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL AMERICA BANKROLL A CAMP DAVID DEAL?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 550-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A ghost at Camp David has been America's Congress.
This week, as musing turned to the monetary rewards for peace, the
speaker of the House of Representatives, Dennis Hastert, wrote to
President Bill Clinton, tartly reminding him that Congress is the
sole authority for spending money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to be kept fully apprised of all aspects of the
negotiations prior to entering into any commitments,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch McConnell, the head of the Senate subcommittee that would
have to propose any aid package that formed part of a peace deal,
says, ``The chances of the Congress approving (the money) this year
are pretty slim, probably even nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   His opposite number in the House, Sonny Callahan, worries that
``a lame-duck president looking for a legacy might be willing to
write a blank check to get an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   America bankrolled the first Camp David agreement, between
Israel and Egypt in 1978. If there should be a second deal, might
Congress scupper it? The possibility seems real.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has come under unprecedented attack in Congress lately,
meaning that bipartisan backing for a deal signed by the Israeli
government can no longer be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few weeks, congressmen of both parties have
criticized Israel for its proposed sale of an airborne radar system
to China, and have been only partly mollified by the deal's
cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, when the Israelis suggested that a peace deal
with Syria might cost America around $17 billion, largely for
splendid new military equipment to offset the loss of security once
Israel had withdrawn from the Golan Heights, congressmen were
openly unsympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   But that sum pales into insignificance compared with the alleged
costs of any likely Palestinian deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians are said to have claimed that it will take
something like $40 billion to resettle or compensate the refugees
who were evicted in 1948 from what is now Israel, plus other forms
of compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is also claiming vast amounts of money, partly to rehouse
those of its settlers who will have to leave the West Bank, partly
to buy yet more splendid military equipment to offset the loss of
security from handing over control of the Jordan Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The grand total may be $70 billion or even more, of which
America's share could be in the order of $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers at this stage are plucked from the sky. But given
that this is an election year in America, the potential for
grandstanding is endless. Campaigning politicians are bound to say
that this is money for a Clinton legacy, and that it would be far
better spent on health care.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, the chances are that if the negotiators were to
reach a deal that was accepted in Israel and Palestine, Congress
would approve it.
</P>
<P>
   Congressmen are being disingenuous in claiming to be out of the
loop. Although the negotiations are secret, both the National
Security Council and Israel's ambassador have been busy briefing
congressmen, to prepare the ground should there be a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Clinton will be out of office by the time any bill is
presented to Congress _ which should mean a Congress less strongly
influenced by anti-Clintonian sentiments. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
