<HEADLINE>
ETHERTON GROWS UP IN ANGELS' WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Keep the ball down, change speeds and throw
strikes, and it doesn't matter if you're pitching in Little League
or the major leagues, you'll get hitters out.
</P>
<P>
   It's a formula that Seth Etherton is using well in his brief
big-league career.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie right-hander from USC isn't blessed with an
overpowering fastball or a knee-buckling curve, but he displayed
once again the qualities of a polished pitcher Thursday night in a
6-1 win over Texas before 23,150 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Spiezio, filling in at the designated hitter spot for late
scratch Garret Anderson, hit a home run and Darin Erstad had two
hits _ padding his major league-leading total to 157, scored a run
and drove in another as the Angels won for the ninth time in 12
games.
</P>
<P>
   But the star of the night was Etherton (5-1), who won his fifth
consecutive start and lowered his ERA to 3.97 with the best and
longest performance of his nearly two-month long major-league
career.
</P>
<P>
   He scattered six hits (all but one were singles), struck out two
and his only two walks came in the eighth inning when he was
clearly tiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's ready for the challenge of the big leagues,'' said
manager Mike Scioscia, who briefly sent Etherton back to Triple-A
Edmonton last month when the Angels had a glut of starting
pitchers. ``He makes a bigger footprint each time out there. I
don't think he's going anywhere. ... This guy's for real.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was equally appreciative, rewarding Etherton with a
standing ovation when he was lifted with one out in the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy who just over two years ago was pitching USC
to the College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Etherton, who has walked only 17 in his eight starts, made
pitching look simple. He threw strikes (72 of his 109 pitches were
strikes), kept the Rangers off balance with his change of speeds
and relied on his defense, which turned two double plays behind him
and three for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been a power pitcher,'' said Etherton, who attended
Dana Hills High in Dana Point and was the Angels' first-round draft
pick in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at USC, I struck out a lot of guys but it was with
off-speed pitches and locating my fastball. Nothing changes here.
Moving the ball around is the key to the game. I know I'm not going
to blow people away. I understand my limits.''
</P>
<P>
   A sign of how well Etherton pitched was when he twice had Rafael
Palmeiro, one of the game's premier hitters, well out in front of
pitches that he hit for fly balls.
</P>
<P>
   The key, said catcher Bengie Molina, was Etherton's ability to
locate his 88 mph fastball early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was his day,'' Molina said. ``By the start of the second
inning I could tell he was on. He needed to throw his fastball
early in the count and work ahead and that's what he did.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
