<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Some surprising words from my wedding day that I'll never forget
</P>
<P>
   By Phil Latham
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ It has been 20 years ago now, but I remember
it with the clarity that you remember important moments in your
life: Your wedding, the birth of your children, the death of a
loved one.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was almost my wedding moment, just about an hour
before the service, in fact. I was well past nervous and into numb
when my father walked into the small room where the groomsmen were
properly making every joke they could about me.
</P>
<P>
   When he asked them to leave, nervous came back. Quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Because I knew that my father had not come into the room for
some teary-eyed, mushy moment. My father couldn't conjure up much
emotion for the movie ``Ol' Yeller'', which can make most
red-blooded American males bawl in their boots. No, this was not
going to be that kind of special moment.
</P>
<P>
   The horrible thought crossed my mind that maybe he was going to
try to give me some advice, the possible range and breadth of which
gave me the shivers.
</P>
<P>
   But I was wrong about that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Though we were alone in the room _ the other guys fled like rats
when he told them to leave _ he came up close to me. His eyes got
narrow and his voice got low and gruff. The last time I had seen
him act like this was the last time I got a whipping _ at 12 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell you something, boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever he used the word ``boy'' it generally meant he was
angry at me. What could have made him so upset on my wedding day?
After all, he was in a position to never have to support me in any
way again.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a few minutes you're going to be married. I'm warning you
about something.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused for effect, though he really didn't have to do so. We
could have been standing in the middle ring of a three-ring circus
and my attention would have been focused on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ever, ever hit your wife, if you ever lay the first
hand on her, get ready. You don't have to worry about her family
coming after you. No. Because I'll be here first. I'm going to whip
you like a man, whip you so that you'll beg me to stop, but I'm not
going to stop. Do you understand?''
</P>
<P>
   I understood.
</P>
<P>
   Now I know that some of you will think that threats of violence
aren't proper. I agree with you But, since my father had never
committed violence on me before, it was clear to me even then that
this was no threat.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, my father was telling me, in his own gruff way, that
violence against women was completely unacceptable and that it was
one thing that could make him turn against me.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, my father being the wild man that he was, I could
never be completely sure, could I? And I never was, either.
</P>
<P>
   I can't help but wonder what a different kind of world we might
live in if all fathers pulled their sons aside on their wedding day
and told them a similar straight-forward message.
</P>
<P>
   I have never once contemplated violence of any sort against my
wife, but had that ever happened in my marriage, I know that my
father's words would be ringing in my ears before I could have
landed the blow.
</P>
<P>
   Words alone aren't enough to stop family violence, no matter who
they come from. But don't think that the right words from the right
people don't have an impact.
</P>
<P>
   It was 20 years ago that I heard those words and I won't ever
forget them. In fact, it is quite likely that someday, I'll be
repeating them myself.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (Texas) News
Messenger. His email is platham(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
