<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another swing at ba$eball
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTEVILLE, Ga. _ We took our granddaughter and her friend
Caroline to the ballpark the night before the All-Star game. More
accurately, they took us. It was our first trip to Turner Field.
Naturally, they had been before.
</P>
<P>
   I spent the evening thinking about my first boss in The Atlanta
Journal sports department, the redoubtable Col. Ed Danforth. Col.
Danforth leaned heavily to horse racing and football. Although his
readers would never have suspected, he didn't much care for
baseball. But there wasn't much else going on in an Atlanta summer
at mid-century, and being the newspaper's sports editor, he had to
put in regular appearences at the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1954 he was recovering from a heart attack. As
the junior member of the firm, my job was to accompany him to Ponce
de Leon Park when the Atlanta Crackers (if you don't know, don't
ask) were in town. There were no elevators. I carried his heavy
Royal typewriter to the press box and made the trip down on the
field to solicit starting lineups from the managers.
</P>
<P>
   One hot July evening, with the score tied in the bottom of the
ninth and every prospect of extra innings, the colonel turned to me
and confided in a gravelly whisper. ``Young man,'' he said, ``you
won't have to do this when you are my age. Professional baseball is
a game for seventh-graders played by grown men. It'll be gone
before the century is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching Sammy Sosa slam batting practice lobs into the outer
reaches of a cheering mob, I wondered what Mr. Danforth would
think. Was he right or wrong in 1954? Baseball surely survives, but
it isn't a game he would recognize.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, there's the price of a ticket. On Monday night it
cost $75 to sit in deep left field and watch what amounted to
batting practice. Fortunately, the company my working wife is
associated with sponsored the Home Run Derby and gave away tickets.
Otherwise, the tab for the four of us would have been $300.
</P>
<P>
   We also were invited to the company picnic in one of the
pavilions. Based on figures posted at concession stands, I'd
estimate the fried chicken, pasta, salad, hot dogs, hamburgers,
cookies, cake and refreshments we consumed at the picnic would have
totaled around $1,000 if we had been paying. Parking was only $10.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball survives in 2000, but a night at the park is for Bill
Gates. My guess is several million dollars changed hands on enough
beer to float the Queen Mary and tacos sufficient to fill a freight
train stretching from here to Birmingham, not to mention peanuts
and Cracker Jacks at $3.75 a pop. Despite a blessed pregame
downpour, I personally required three bottles of water at $3 each
to survive the heat.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I had attended a baseball game I was one of a
throng of 6,000 in the late Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium. Baseball
was looking very much like the moribund sport it was accused of
being before it went head over heels into show business.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching the entrance to Turner Field, I decided to impress
the girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you realize?'' I asked, ``that I stood on this very spot
watching Mayor Ivan Allen drive a bulldozer to break ground for
Atlanta Stadium?''
</P>
<P>
   They must have been impressed, so much so that they were at loss
for words. They didn't answer. They just rolled their eyes. For
them Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium is as deep in the past as Ponce
de Leon Park. Or Spiller. (If you don't know, don't ask.)
</P>
<P>
   What I didn't expect was all the stuff outside the stadium, and
in the concourses. The only way I can describe Turner Field and
environs is to suggest a cross between the midway of the old
Southeastern Fair in Atlanta, Disney World, and vendors' row at the
Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima.
</P>
<P>
   Since we were only going to see batting practice, I assumed the
stands would be half-empty. They were full. That was a surprise,
although it should not have been. If no All-Stars had showed up,
fans would come just for the hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   Well aware of the game's commercialization, I was still shocked
to see the extent. Turner Field has more advertisements than the
Sunday paper. A billboard the size of a boxcar exhorted fans to
play the Big Game for $34 million. When the Crackers played in
Ponce de Leon, gambling, now encouraged by lawmakers, was against
the law. Cops made periodic sweeps through the left-field bleachers
to nab two-bit hustlers enticing fans to wager 25 and 50 cents on
fly balls.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what I'd tell Mr. Danforth if I could get a message
through. So much has changed. I kept asking myself how Country
Brown (if you don't know, don't ask) would look laying down a drag
bunt in a ballet suit. I'm not a pervert, but I wish I could have
visited the All-Star locker rooms, just to see how they squeeze
into those tight pants.
</P>
<P>
   To contact Jim Minter, write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, 692 N. Glynn St., Suite A, Fayetteville, GA
30214.
</P>
</TEXT>
