<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shrinking interest in national election reflects rise in apathy
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Politics is important because it determines who gets what.
</P>
<P>
   Dwindling voter interest in the upcoming presidential election
indicates that a lot of people are not going to get what they want.
</P>
<P>
   Americans who drop out of the political process can't complain
when they see politicians doling out their tax dollars to the
people who took an active part in politics.
</P>
<P>
   At this point back in the 1992 presidential campaign, 63 percent
of American voters said they had thought about the upcoming
election. Four years later, only 55 percent of voters said they had
thought about the 1996 presidential election. This year, only 46
percent of voters have thought about the coming presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
   This drop-off in interest about the presidential election
corresponds to a similar nosedive in interest in politics.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Pew Research Center for the People and the
Press, voter interest in politics dropped from 55 percent in 1992
to 42 percent in 1996 and to a low of 38 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   These dismal figures indicate that voter turnout for the
November election will hit a new low. This means those Americans
who remain active in politics will have proportionally more clout
when it comes time to decide who gets what.
</P>
<P>
   There are no guarantees, of course, that Americans who follow
campaign issues, remain active in politics and vote in every
election will get what they want.
</P>
<P>
   It comes close to a guarantee, however, that Americans who do
not participate in the political process, which is called
representative democracy, are more unlikely to get what they want
out of government.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that younger Americans, according to the Pew
report, are more cynical and disconnected from politics than even
in the recent past. This means young people are disenfranchising
themselves from decisions that will determine their future.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that loss of interest in politics is most
pronounced among well-educated young Americans. The Pew study found
that in June 1992, 68 percent of 18-34 year-old college graduates
said they had given a lot of thought to that year's election. That
number dropped to 39 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   Older Americans have a higher interest in politics. They also
vote in greater numbers. Life has taught them that politics is
important. As a result, they are more likely to get what they want.
</P>
<P>
   This year's presidential campaign has both major parties falling
all over themselves boosting Social Security and Medicare. They
also are squabbling over which party has the better prescription
drug plan. This phenomenon will really hit home when the Baby
Boomers retire.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew study found that one reason so many more Americans have
lost interest in this year's campaign is because they believe that
who is elected president is not as important as it once was.
</P>
<P>
   They also are more satisfied with this year's candidates than
the candidates in the previous two presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   Why Americans think the presidency doesn't matter as much as it
used to is beyond me.
</P>
<P>
   It also doesn't make any sense that satisfaction with this
year's presidential candidates is up when the Pew study found that
the public has little know- ledge about where the candidates stand
on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   When asked which candidate has proposed building a missile
defense system and reducing the number of U.S. nuclear weapons,
even if Russia refuses to do the same, only 18 percent correctly
identified Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Rolling Stones recognized that you can't always get
what you want. But if you try sometime, you just might find that
you get what you need.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is the Senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
