<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wheaton grateful for peace
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, OHIO _ One of Dr. Sherry Wheaton's favorite quotes comes
from Morris West's The Shoes of the Fisherman. ``Reach out for the
risk of living with both arms. One has to embrace the world like a
lover. One has to accept pain as a condition of existence.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one thing to quote those words in speeches, or to share
them with the families of the Alzheimer's patients she works with
as medical director of SeniorCare at Miami Valley Hospital. After
suffering serious injuries from an attack by a German shepherd,
Wheaton is learning more about what it means to live them.
</P>
<P>
   Best known locally as a medical reporter for Channel 7, Wheaton
isn't sure when she will return to her work at the station. Because
of nerve damage, her face is partially paralyzed. She can't smile.
``This is not a face that can go on television,'' Wheaton says,
recovering at her home following the July 8 attack.
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton and her husband, Terry, had arrived only the night
before for a weekend visit with Terry's daughter, Becky, and her
husband in Tucson, Ariz. Saturday morning, Wheaton and Becky were
the early risers.
</P>
<P>
   For most of her life, Wheaton had been afraid of dogs. But a
woebegone stray she picked up at Fifth and Main _ ``just a
skeleton, really'' _ changed all that. Zoe is now a member of the
family, with a beautiful golden coat and incorrigibly wagging tail.
</P>
<P>
   So Wheaton didn't think twice about getting on the floor, nose
to muzzle, with the feistier of the couple's two German shepherds,
Ulk. The dog had greeted the couple the night before by growling
and baring his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd better be on your good behavior,'' Wheaton cooed,
``because Terry's afraid of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton never saw the dog lunge. ``I was looking at Becky, and I
saw it happen through her eyes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the nerve damage, she didn't feel any pain. She
immediately went into cool, collected doctor mode, telling everyone
else what to do. ``It's ironic that, after spending my career
trying to undo all that, and open up, I was the one in control,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her face was black and blue, her eyes swollen shut. She
underwent emergency plastic surgery the same day, and, less than
two weeks later, the angry scar on her right cheek has healed
considerably. The nerve damage also is expected to heal eventually.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the woman who dispenses lessons about health
and lifestyle has absorbed some lessons of her own. Sad as she is
that Ulk must be put to sleep, Wheaton said ``the biggest message
from this is that everything can be a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   A gift?
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton explained that she can't remember the last time she had
two uninterrupted weeks to read, to meditate, to bask in the
comfort of friends. ``How most of us live our lives, we're always
racing, racing, racing. I do it, too. This is giving me time to do
my own inner journey.''
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part has been all the people who are calling, asking
what they can do. ``It's easy to be a giver; it's hard to be a
receiver,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wheaton will return to work at SeniorCare as soon as she can.
Although she has received nothing but support from Channel 7, she
has put her career there temporarily on hold.
</P>
<P>
   She said it's part of the journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all searching for the meaning of life _ and the meaning
of life is in living it. That means the painful times must be
embraced and nurtured and loved, just like the good times.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
