<HEADER>
A8609 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD22-COX     07-21 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spalting maple considered beautiful by many
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some interesting questions about wood and wood finishes today.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, a gentleman reports that he ``recently came
across some spalted maple boards about 10 inches wide. Finishing?
Anything I should be aware of? Any thoughts on staining? Lacquer?
Polyurethane? Gluing up? Joints?''
</P>
<P>
   Spalting, for those unfamiliar with the term, refers to the fine
dark lines, like ink drawings, that appear on wood as insect
activity and decay begins. It can happen on any wood, but obviously
is more pronounced on light woods such as maple, beech and birch.
</P>
<P>
   Many woodworkers, and I am among them, consider it the most
beautiful wood in the world. However, the boards must be moved into
a dry place and the decay arrested before it has gone far enough to
weaken the wood. If there are places on it mushy to the touch, they
will have to be cut away or the board discarded.
</P>
<P>
   The very idea of staining such wood is outrageous. Don't even
think of it.
</P>
<P>
   Lacquer, I think, would be out of place on such an earthy wood,
and it's impractical anyway unless you have a spray setup and
experience using it. Forget polyurethane. I'd use my standard
oil-varnish mix.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming sound boards, glue-up is unexceptional and any
appropriate joints may be employed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm making a swing for outdoors out of cedar. I'm thinking for
the main spans to use a 2x6 to support the swing on each side. The
span of the 2x6 would be 65 inches with 4x4s on each end. How much
weight could I expect the 2x6 to support? Should I go with a 2x8,
or double up the 2x6? I'm hoping to support 400 pounds, given two
adults.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll assume here that he's making a porch swing, and using
western red cedar.
</P>
<P>
   Having assumed that, I'd suggest that he forget the cedar and
use something with good strength _ almost anything is stronger than
cedar. I wouldn't expect a cedar 2x6 to support 200 pounds, let
alone 400. A 2x8 wouldn't support any more weight, since the
strength is in the thickness and not the width.
</P>
<P>
   There are other problems, too. Cedar weathers well in terms of
appearance, but not to the touch. Exposed to the elements to any
degree at all, it gets rough and splintery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am making some wooden blocks for my 5-month-old and was
wondering what finish to use. They will probably spend most of the
time in his mouth, so I want to get something real safe. Any
ideas?''
</P>
<P>
   When my granddaughters were small, I was turning wood
semi-professionally. I finished things I made for them with
Behlen's Salad Bowl Oil. I don't know how much they chewed on it,
but they never blamed it for sickening them.
</P>
<P>
   Another fellow recommended using pure walnut oil, available at
some groceries. ``It polymerizes to a nice finish and is completely
safe as it is an edible oil,'' he reports. Some turners I know use
mineral oil as a finish, but it doesn't come to much in my opinion.
It never really dries, and tends to get dirty rather easily.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
