A8632 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     07-21 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Friday, July 21, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Saturday and
Sunday. If you have questions, please call Eric Rosenberg at
202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   POWER-SHIP (San Francisco) _ As a PG&AMP;E barge slated for a
floating San Francisco Bay power plant sails through the Panama
Canal, Bay Area residents stood on the steps of City Hall and vowed
to stop it ``on land and on sea.'' By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-INSIDER (Albany, N.Y.) _ What author Ted Conover endured
to get the inside story about working as a state correction officer
in notorious Sing Sing was only the beginning. ``Newjack: Guarding
Sing Sing'' (Random House, $24.95), Conover's grim account of nine
months working as a rookie New York correction officer, is creating
controversy in criminal-justice circles. By PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   THE-PILL (Undated) _ Long before ``the pill'' came to mean birth
control, young women who had premarital sex faced a set of
potential social consequences beyond the pregnancy itself. Unwed,
pregnant women sometimes disappeared, to return and resume life
after delivering their babies in charitable homes. Infants were
represented as premature, born once couples were safely married.
Contraceptives and abortions were covertly sought. By MICHAEL
LOPEZ. (For release Sunday, July 23.)
</P>
<P>
   OLD-HOUSES (Undated) _ Authors will often write about fond
memories of the houses where they grew up. But Richard Hampton
Jenrette chronicles the history of six remarkable houses in
``Adventures with Old Houses'' (Wyrick &AMP; Co., $60). The author
writes in detail about the properties that he has preserved for
generations to come. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS. (For release
Sunday, July 23.)
</P>
<P>
   DAY-BED (Undated) _ As the forerunner to the sofa and the chaise
lounge, the day bed served as a place for quiet relaxation and
contemplative meditation. The day bed is a long seat with a
stationary or adjustable end that can be lowered to form a bed. By
FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS. (For release Sunday, July 23.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHASE-EXEC (San Francisco) _ David A. Coulter, who emerged this
week with a top job at Chase Manhattan Bank nearly two years after
being ousted as chairman and chief executive of San Francisco-based
Bank of America, isn't interested in looking back. Coulter, 52,
made that clear Thursday in his first interview with The Examiner
since BofA was purchased by Charlotte, N.C.-based NationsBank in
September 1998. By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CREOLE-TRAIL (Lake Charles, La.) _ The Creole Nature Trail,
which loops through Calcasieu and Cameron parishes of southwest
Louisiana, is more Nature than Creole. The natural world laps at
the roadside from marshes, canals, beaches, lakes, piney woods and
prairies. Their mysteries and subtleties can be gleaned at three
public wildlife refuges and a bird-and-butterfly sanctuary. By
MARTY RACINE.
</P>
<P>
   With: CREOLE-TRAIL-INFO
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Houston) _ Maite Costa-Medic and Jean-Michel
Poupart are in love. In love with each other. And in love with the
world. Many of us share their dream: Pack up one morning, leave all
our worries behind and take off together to explore the unknown, to
immerse ourselves in new cultures and new adventures, to savor
every precious second until our last penny is exhausted. Yes, many
of us dream. But for Maite and Jean-Michel, fantasy became reality.
By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   ORIENTALISM-EXHIBIT (Williamstown, Mass.) _ The Sterling and
Francine Clark Art Institute is showing an ambitious history of
Orientalism in America, from 1870, when it gained popular currency,
to just before World War II. Orientalism, the notion of an
``Orient'' replete with sultans and dancing girls, camel drivers
and bazaars, is a concoction of myth and cliche that has served a
range of nationalist, capitalist and chauvinist purposes through
the years. By TIMOTHY CAHILL. (For release Sunday, July 23.)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-EMMYS (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Thomas O'Neil, a journalist who
wrote a book chronicling the history of the Emmys, is a raving
zealot when it comes to the television awards. So it's no wonder
that O'Neil's head comes close to exploding whenever he thinks
about the upcoming change in voting procedures. He predicts a
calamity on par with Pompeii. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-LOSER (Undated) _ Appropriating another defeatist
term of endearment from the mouths of America's young, ``Clueless''
writer-director Amy Heckerling returns with ``Loser.'' It's a
nonevent, though. The knowing bite is gone. She seems merely bitter
now, casting about for unmitigated warmth and hating herself for
it, and punishing us in the process. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BENEATH (Undated) _ I was calloused and skeptical
enough to know going in that ``What Lies Beneath'' would be
hell-bent on eliciting screams from anyone who watched. I knew this
from the preview, which I had seen eight or nine times (I do not
exaggerate) and which promised a film about an unreasonably
gorgeous yuppie couple. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-POKMON (Undated) _ Will children abandon their
dog-eared copies of ``Harry Potter and The Goblet of Fire'' for
``Pokmon the Movie 2000?'' Wait until kids get a load of ``P2K,''
with its jacked-up self-consciousness and attempt to give kids the
summer-movie fix they may have missed with ``Chicken Run'' (though
I don't see how). By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS-DEFENSE (Stockton, Calif.) _ For years, the
stereotypical San Francisco 49ers offensive lineman was a
lightweight. Bobb McKittrick, the longtime offensive line coach who
died of cancer earlier this year, favored undersized, overachieving
players. His blocking schemes were based on quickness. That's
beginning to change. By BRUCE ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ What an embarrassment it is to be
a liberal sometimes. Not only do you have to spend your time
worrying about endangered bugs, genetically altered cornflakes and
cops playing kick the can with carjackers, but you have to listen
to some odd ideas and the most unnatural language. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   TEENS-WORK (Berkeley, Calif.) _ Freed from the classroom, record
numbers of teenagers are blowing off the old American tradition of
taking a menial summer job. Indulgent, affluent parents are backing
their kids' choices to be summertime sloths. By NORMA J. SHATTUCK.
</P>
</TEXT>
