<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, July 22 and Sunday, July 23
, 2000 are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   EDMONSON-COLUMN _ The Internet might be the greatest
communication advance since the invention of the printing press. It
could also be the unrivaled champion at spreading misinformation.
The most recent highly visible instance involves a group that
gathered about 200 years before e-mail: the signers of the
Declaration of Independence. A number of recent columns _ including
one by Ann Landers that ran July 4 _ recount what supposedly
happened to some of these men. The pieces are riddled with errors,
exaggerations and misinterpretations. (Edmonson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ According to the Pew Research Center for the
People and the Press, voter interest in politics dropped from 55
percent in 1992 to 42 percent in 1996 and to a low of 38 percent
this year. These dismal figures indicate that voter turnout for the
November election will hit a new low. This means those Americans
who remain active in politics will have proportionally more clout
when it comes time to decide who gets what. Nethaway, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ I can't help but wonder what a different kind of
world we might live in if all fathers pulled their sons aside on
their wedding day and told them this similar straight-forward
message. (Latham, Marshall News-Messenger) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ Baseball survives in 2000, but a night at the
park is for Bill Gates. My guess is several million dollars changed
hands on enough beer to float the Queen Mary and tacos sufficient
to fill a freight train stretching from here to Birmingham, not to
mention peanuts and Cracker Jacks at $3.75 a pop. (Minter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVEDMCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ One of
Dr. Sherry Wheaton's favorite quotes comes from Morris West's The
Shoes of the Fisherman. ``Reach out for the risk of living with
both arms. One has to embrace the world like a lover. One has to
accept pain as a condition of existence.'' After suffering serious
injuries from an attack by a German shepherd, Wheaton is learning
more about what it means to live them. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ In case you were wondering, all that fuss in
Washington over fixing the so-called ``marriage penalty'' _ some
couples pay more together than they would filing individually _
isn't about the marriage penalty at all. It's about snookering
Democrats. Hey, this is an election year, folks. (Tom Teepen is
national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Kenny went out and bought his eight-year-old
grandson a baseball glove the other day. And now it was time to
break it in, which puzzled the child because most kids today just
take their glove off the store shelf and go straight to the field
-- which is why the ball bounces out of the glove so often.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ Since the era of Huntley and Brinkley in the NBC
skybooth, wraparound convention coverage has been relegated to the
all-news cable channels. To bear witness as the Republicans perform
next week in Philadelphia, CNN alone plans to send more8 a.m. to 10
p.m. Monday-Friday, and 1-10 p.m. on weekends and holidays.
</P>
