   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet HEALTHY LIVING page for the current
week. This layout is now available.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET HEALTHY LIVING 0718 -- In medical terms, osteoporosis is
the disease resulting from reduced bone density that leads to
increased susceptibility of fractures. Family history is the
biggest risk factor, and the biggest predictor of osteoporosis,
experts say. But new screening and drugs can now prevent the
disease, even in women who have inherited ``bad bones.'' (Guthrie,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PLUS: Summertime play can pose threat to children's teeth.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AND: Health &AMP; Media notes (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMOTIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-BMW3231 _ A review of the BMW 323i station wagon.
(DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ Spalting, for those unfamiliar with the term,
refers to the fine dark lines, like ink drawings, that appear on
wood as insect activity and decay begins. It can happen on any
wood, but obviously is more pronounced on light woods such as
maple, beech and birch. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   RELIGIONRELIGION-FRIENDSHIP _ ATLANTA _ Kay DeLaFosse and Pat
Cronic have been friends for four decades. They often meet at
church, attend mass and have lunch together. Like many other close
friends, DeLaFosse and Cronic have created a bond that helps them
deal with the problems of life. There's something spiritual in
their connection, something they and others have trouble putting
into words. We explore the importance of friendship, talk with
therapiests, academics and just plain folks. (Rakoczy, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   TVTOUR-HOLLOWAY _ LOS ANGELES_ Diane Holloway column from the
fall TV tour: Michael Richards. Former ``Seinfeld'' star has a new
series coming this fall and its production history has been a
troubled one, with script rewrites, episodes reshot, etc.
(Holloway, Austin American-Statesman). 18-22.
</P>
<P>
   UNLESS OTHERWISE NOTED, THE FOLLOWING STORIES ARE EMBARGOED FOR
SUNDAY, JULY 23, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY _Sydney _ In going from Georgia to Australia, then, the
Olympics have gone from one British penal experiment to another.
This odd kinship of outcasts dawned on me as I was sitting at a
cafe beside Sydney Cove, the aquamarine inlet that sets off the
heart of the city like a jade pendant. Ferry boats were churning
through the whitecaps of crisscrossing wakes. On one side of the
cove, the Opera House roof loomed like the upturned prows of a
dozen giant rowboats. On the other side, blue Australian flags
streamed in the breeze atop the long steel arch of the Harbour
Bridge. It's hard to imagine now, but this postcard spot was where
the First Fleet landed in 1788 with a thousand convicts and
sailors. Ten thousand miles from home, they struggled and almost
starved yet somehow managed to transform their bitter exile into a
city and nation that will soon command the world's attention.
(Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY-DO _Quick ideas for things to do in Sydney, from touring
the Opera House to petting a kangaroo at the Taronga Zoo.
(Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY-LINGO _ A bludger is a deadbeat. A tall poppy is a
selfish cad. These and other delights of the colorful Australian
brand of English known as Strine are defined in our glossary.
(Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   FAT-SOUTHERNERS _We know that America overall has a weight
problem - by some measures, 50 percent of the population is at
least somewhat overweight. But what's the Southern piece of that
pie? According to a new AJC poll, Southerners are more likely than
people elsewhere in the US to admit to being ``moderately or
seriously'' overweight - even though they set the bar for what
constitutes ``overweight'' higher than residents of other states
do, and given even more latitude to men than they do to women. At
the same time, though, Southerners are more willing to blame their
own bad habits for their weight problems. Includes interviews with
poll respondents and Southern sociologists. With charts, possible
photos. (McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ENHANCER _ The Theater 2000 is a device that promises to
``enhance'' the performance of your home sound system by ``allowing
listeners to hear music or sound effects as if they were literally
in the middle of a live recording or concert hall.'' And while it's
hard to describe exactly what the unit is doing, it actually does
seem to give music a more full-bodied, three-dimensional feel.
(Cummings, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   CAR-TECH _Video games, DVD players and even the PC are moving
out of the home and onto the road, which has made owning a simple
CD or cassette player for your set of wheels last century's news.
Luxuries usually strewn about the family room are becoming popular
gadgets in cars and in roomy SUVs. Ever since Oldsmobile introduced
a videocassette player for its minivans in 1998, car-stereo
enthusiasts have been adding more dazzle to audio systems with the
addition of video. And the automotive world is jumping the
bandwagon; every major manufacturer now offers video in the car.
(Dayton Daily News) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the
current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 0718 -- Camera walks focus on capturing Yosemite
National Park's staggering vistas that inspired the monumental
images created by America's greatest nature photographer. (Meyers,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: The art of taking good vacation pictures (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AND: Travel Briefs (N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET LIFESTYLES _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet Lifestyles page for
the current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET LIFESTYLES 0720 -- Costumed crime fighters, who have
thrived for years in comic books, need a hero themselves. Comic
book sales have steadily declined as computer games and the
Internet draw potential readers away. Some comic publishers hope
that same technology can rescue them. Artists are turning from
pencils to pixels as their companies explore online comics,
Internet animation and other computer-based graphic technologies to
reach new readers. (Fernandez, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes 2-column color photo of comic books and a 3-column color
photo of a Web site of hero Spiderman.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: COMICS ON THE SILVER SCREEN -- Comic books may not be
highly profitable in themselves, but as properties for other media,
they are priceless. (Fernandez, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WHO ARE THE X-MEN -- a primer to the characters in
``X-Men,'' which comes to theaters on July 14. (Cumming, Dayton
Daily News) Art includes a 3-column color illustration of an
``X-Men'' character.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet Books page for the
current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0718 -- A suburban Atlanta housewife has become the
favorite reviewer for the Amazon.com Web site. She reads books as
regularly as most people brush their teeth, one in the morning and
one at night, and for the past five years she has written more than
500 reviews for Amazon.com. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PLUS: Reviews of Joanna Trollope's ``Marrying the Mistress'' and
Martin Amis' ``Experience''
</P>
<P>
   AND: List of best sellers from the New York Times
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ On Larry McMurtry's new book of essays,
``Roads.'' (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FILMS _Critical picks for the upcoming Pan African Film
Festival, which is part of the National Black Arts Festival. At
least two of the 30 films to be shown at the High Museum's Rich
Auditorium _ Mozambique's ``Comedia Infantil'' and Senegal's ``La
Petite Veneuse de Soleil'' _ are delicate tales of children and
testaments to the human spirit. (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   NBAF _Curtain-raiser for the National Blacks Arts Festival,
which is centering its events around the Atlanta University Center.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HEURING _ interview with Lori Heuring, an actress/model from
Austin who gets a big break in ``The In Crowd,'' which opened
Friday. (Barchas, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
