<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8659 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-G8-CLINTON-0722-COX     07-21 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G8-CLINTON-0722-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    G8 LEADERS CRITICIZED AT SUMMIT OVER DEBT RELIEF; CLINTON, PUTIN
TALK MISSILE DEFENSE
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAGO, Japan _ Amid criticisms that the leaders of the world's
seven richest nations have done little to meet their commitments to
reduce the debt of poor nations, the leaders pledged Friday to work
harder to fulfill their goals.
</P>
<P>
   However, critics said the countries _ the United States, Canada,
France, Italy, Germany, Britain and Japan _ are still moving too
slowly in meeting their promise from last year's summit in Cologne
to cancel up to $100 billion of debt owed by 40 of the world's
poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaders at Cologne made a big political statement last
year saying they'd cancel $100 billion in debt,'' said Marlene
Barrett, a spokesperson for Jubilee 2000, an organization
campaigning for debt cancellation for poor countries. ``They simply
failed to get that through.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first day of the three-day summit in this seaside resort
town on the island of Okinawa, President Clinton also held a side
meeting with Russia's president Vladimir Putin, who joined the
other nations for a working dinner later Friday _ to make it a full
Group of Eight summit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's meeting with Putin, coming just six weeks after his
trip to Moscow in June, centered largely on security issues and
Putin's trip to North Korea this week, in which he announced that
Pyongyang had offered to give up its missile program if other
nations would provide it with rockets to launch satellites into
space.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's missile program is the prime motivation for a U.S.
national missile defense which is vigorously opposed by Russia and
China. France and Germany also have opposed the defense system.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder told reporters,
``I'm skeptical about it.'' He stressed that America can do what it
sees in its national interest, but said it should discuss the issue
with NATO and Russia. Chirac said he feared creation of a missile
shield could start another arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said he will decide this summer whether to go ahead
with the missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House official said Clinton discussed North
Korea's offer with Putin but added the United States still needs
further clarification.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not entirely clear what's in (North Korean leader) Kim
Jong Il's mind with regard to this possible trade-off,'' said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``A very dangerous
idea would be the international community would provide actual
launch capability to North Korea, that is to say rockets launched
from North Korean territory.''
</P>
<P>
   However, if Kim envisions launching North Korean satellites on
foreign soil, ``it's something we'd be prepared to pursue,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the United States and Russia issued a joint
statement saying they are dedicated to finding new ways to
cooperate on controlling the spread of missiles.
</P>
<P>
   They also had a lengthy discussion on the Middle East peace
talks going on at Camp David. The White House official said Putin
offered his assistance but would not give details of the
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The G8 discussion of debt relief came one day after a meeting in
Tokyo in which leaders of several developing countries stated their
frustration with the slow pace of debt relief by the world's
richest nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of (the G8 leaders) referenced the meeting that had taken
place yesterday . . . and which gave greater impetus to the need to
get the Cologne debt commitments implemented,'' said Lael Brainard,
deputy national economic advisor.
</P>
<P>
   So far, nine countries have qualified for the debt relief
initiative and a few have had their debt repayments reduced, but
none have had their debts canceled, Barrett said. Another 11
countries may qualify by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Jubilee 2000, a coalition of faith-based groups, labor unions,
women's groups _ and a few rock stars _ has been active since 1996
and has collected 19 million signatures in 120 countries. It
believes that 52 poor countries should qualify for debt
cancellation totalling $354 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're spending more on paying back their debt than on
healthcare and education,'' said Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   A statement released by G8 leaders Friday _ not including Russia
_ expressed concern that many of the poor nations are at war or
have military conflicts which prevent them from qualifying for debt
relief. They agreed to do more to help those countries qualify, but
Brainard said there was no discussion of relaxing the terms of debt
relief.
</P>
<P>
   Jubilee 2000 would like to see an independent process for
determining which countries qualify for debt relief, rather than
having the lender decide what loans to forgive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the creditor is the judge, jury and prosecutor all at
once,'' Barrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton landed in Okinawa Friday morning and headed straight to
a peace memorial in an effort to placate criticism from another
corner _ local Okinawans unhappy with the large U.S. military
presence.
</P>
<P>
   Okinawa hosts about 26,000 American military personnel, more
than half of the American forces in Japan, even though it comprises
less than 1 percent of Japan's land mass. An estimated 27,000
people turned out Thursday to form a human chain around Kadena
Airbase in a show of protest.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged to continue efforts to ``reduce our footprint on
this island,'' but some Okinawans were disappointed that he neither
said anything specific about base reduction nor apologized for an
incident earlier this month in which a drunken U.S. marine
allegedly entered a local house and molested a sleeping 14-year-old
girl.
</P>
<P>
   A few small, scattered groups of anti-base protesters appeared
at various summit venues and along the main road.
</P>
<P>
   The Okinawa summit is Clinton's eighth and last G8 summit. He
joined the group as the new kid on the block and leaves as the
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.g8kyushu-okinawa.go.jp
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
