<P>
   WANDERLUST-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Writing about walking, it
turns out, is almost as plentiful as writing about writing, yet
much of it, as Rebecca Solnit points out in her subtle and
suggestive history, ``Wanderlust: A History of Walking,'' is
``episodic'' with ``no overarching plot.'' By Edward Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   SEX-SURVEYS (Undated) _ Sex surveyors are bedeviled scientists.
People lie about sex. Those who don't lie often say inaccurate
things. And most sex researchers aren't exactly neutral. Sex
surveys give ``a hardened imitation of reality,'' says John H.
Gagnon, an emeritus professor of sociology at SUNY Stonybrook. We
get certain answers because we ask certain questions. And we ask
certain questions because of fear. By Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   (Will be filed in category `a')
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-LIBEL-LAW (Undated) _ In the United States, with its
ironclad belief in the right to free speech, libel plaintiffs need
to prove not only that the speech in question is false, but also
that it was published with a reckless disregard for the truth. In
England, the burden is in exactly the other direction: the
offending speech is presumed to be false, and it is up to
defendants to prove that it is in fact true. That tends to have a
dampening effect on what newspapers print and what publishers
include in books, especially when the material is likely to offend
someone who is powerful, rich or particularly litigious. By Sarah
Lyall.
</P>
