<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWLS SETTLE IN AND THE GARDEN BLOSSOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ We named the
first owl after my husband's late father. We call him Owlvin, for
Alvin. Now he's joined by another we call Owloise, after Eloise, my
late mother-in-law. I know their namesakes would approve. Maybe
they've come back to watch over.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Living in a place that is fast running out of wild things, we
feel charmed that these snowy creatures with caramel streaks
deigned to move into our oak tree.
</P>
<P>
   These are barn owls, endangered in some parts of the country but
still common in California even as their habitats lose ground.
</P>
<P>
   We're lucky. Friends lost the owls, red-tailed hawks and
butterflies drawn to their neighborhood by a nearby stand of
eucalyptus trees that were knocked down in favor of a subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   Bird rescuer Diane Hichwa who lives on Sonoma Mountain says barn
owls are losing their haunts as barns, old buildings and water
towers are torn down. But she said we should also feel special to
be chosen. Owls are finicky.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, it's probably not our charming selves that they're
drawn too, but the potential for good eats. Given a barn owl's
diet, which is mostly rodents, we offer a regular ``smorgy'' of
burrowing critters who have had their way with our field and
gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Some owls can eat five gophers a day. I don't know if ours are
actually dining on gophers or just scaring the heck out of them but
we have more dahlias and zinnias left standing this summer than
ever before.
</P>
<P>
   We're on different shifts, the owls and us. They're just getting
off work when we're getting up. We pass around 6 a.m. most
mornings. Whoever goes to the kitchen to start the coffee now must
make an owl report.
</P>
<P>
   They are usually there, standing in the door of their owl box,
not moving, just staring our way with those big ET eyes. They look
like two stuffed animals.
</P>
<P>
   We wave. We take photos. We talk to them. They probably think
we're loons.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually we'll even adjust to their scream, which sounds like
Martha from ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf'' is on the loose.
</P>
<P>
   People say you get used to the screech of a barn owl just like
you get used to the smell of a skunk as a part of rural ambience.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Bentley with the Audubon Society thinks owls had a lot to
do with making people believe in ghosts. She says that long ago
when churches were next to graveyards, owls lived in the cozy
quarters of church spires and preyed on the mice that flourished in
the cemetery grass. Someone walking through a graveyard at night
would suddenly have ``this great white thing silently swooping down
toward them,'' says Martha. ``And then it would let out the most
horrible sound. It's no wonder people started telling ghost
stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Owlvin and Owloise also came to us because of the wooden owl box
which we built and hoisted high up into an oak tree two years ago.
It was vacant for so long we started making jokes about our folly,
saying it was a dog house blown up into the trees by the last
tornado.
</P>
<P>
   We think Owlvin must have cruised by a few times, like you do
when you're thinking about a new house, not wanting to appear too
eager. Single at first, he joined up with a partner. Although we
haven't seen any babies we think we've heard some little owl
squeaks, which would be nice, seeing as how we already think of it
as the family tree.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
