<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRANAGH MOVIE A LOST LABOR FOR MIRAMAX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are going to fail, fail spectacularly. And in this, the
recent Miramax movie release, ``Love's Labour's Lost'' has
succeeded magnificently. According to last Sunday's Parade
magazine, ``Lost'' was playing in 14 American theaters and had
grossed barely $100,000. Miramax says the gross is $299,000; the
trade magazine Variety reports $190,000. Whatever. For Hollywood,
the number is minuscule. After the movie opened in mid-June, it
didn't even appear on the Hollywood Reporter's list of 50
top-grossing movies in the country, which included two Imax movies
that show only in special facilities, and nWaves's obscure 1999
release ``Alien Adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   How could this possibly happen? Admittedly, ``Lost,'' which
combines an exuberant Shakespeare comedy with venerable Broadway
show tunes, was a hard concept to sell. The reviews were all over
the map: Jay Carr sort of liked it; Entertainment Weekly gave it a
C+ ; Jeffrey Gantz of the Boston Phoenix awarded it five stars on a
scale of one to four. I enjoyed it. It's hard to make a
16th-century play fun, but director Kenneth Branagh _ with assists
from William Shakespeare, George Gershwin, and Cole Porter _ did
just that.
</P>
<P>
   The word among exhibitors is that, faced with conflicting
reviews, Miramax decided not to support the movie. The company's
Dimension Films division has been making untold millions with the
flashy, cashy, trashy ``Scream'' series and this summer's monster
hit, ``Scary Movie,'' so the Bard is taking a back seat. Miramax
spokeswoman Elizabeth Clark rejects this argument, saying ``we did
what we normally do'', e.g. interviews and TV appearances by
Branagh and costar Alicia Silverstone, to promote ``Lost.'' ``Not
every film is measured by its success at the box office,'' Clark
says. ``It's still something we're glad we made.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Commonwealth, you can find ``Lost'' at the West Newton
Cinema, and it will be arriving shortly at theaters in Dennis and
Williamstown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Look eastward, Angel
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I have only two questions about Hell's Angels founder Sonny
Barger's new autobiography, which is selling well enough to have
appeared on several national bestseller lists. 1: Why isn't his
fabulously successful, motorycle-borne book promotion tour coming
to New England? 2: In his book, which I will surely read someday,
does Barger narrate one of the seminal moments in modern American
literature, meaning his brutal, nonfatal stomping of gonzo
journalist Hunter S. Thompson?
</P>
<P>
   The answers to these questions are: no and no.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Green, chief publicist for Barger's publisher, William
Morrow &AMP; Co., explains that Sonny's bike tour, on which he is
accompanied by a flight of 50 or more fellow Angels, has more or
less stuck to Route 66. At some bike stores _ not bookstores, bike
stores _ Barger has sold up to 600 copies of ``Hell's Angel.'' But
we have plenty of subliterate thugs who ride choppers here _ why
not bring him up to Laconia, N.H., for the big fall ride around
Lake Winnipesaukee? It's not excluded, Green told me, adding that
``Sonny has already done an event in the East, in South Dakota.''
(!) And although he does write about dealing LSD in San Francisco
in the 1960s, he doesn't include the Thompson stomping in his
memoir. For that, you'll have to read Thompson's own ``Hell's
Angels,'' which is still in print.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Random notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Angry, unpredictable, and smart are three traits I admire in a
journalist, and Debra Dickerson has all three. I remember reading
Debra's columns in a Harvard Law School student newspaper, where
she honed an edgy, take-no-prisoners style. Her forthcoming memoir,
``An American Story,'' just received a coveted starred review in
Publisher's Weekly, and in an accompanying interview, Debra
promises to bring her book tour to the inner-city neighborhoods
familiar to her from childhood: ``I'll go out into the 'hood as
well,'' she told PW. ``I'm not Clarence Thomas. I love my people.''
. . . Alex Beam culture hero Christine Lavin forwards the Web
address for the Alanis Morissette Random Lyric Generator
(http://www.brunching.com/toys/toy-alanislyrics.html), which will
allow you to compose million-selling songs with requisite teen
angst. No software yet to reproduce Christine's eloquent wit. . . .
This is a very beautiful book: ``A Place of Beauty: The Artists &AMP;
Gardens of the Cornish Colony,'' by Alma Gilbert and Judith
Tankard, published by Ten Speed Press. It's a combination history
and coffee-table portrait of the Cornish, N.H., artists colony,
storied hangout of painter Maxfield Parrish, sculptor Augustus
Saint-Gaudens, Isadora Duncan, Maxwell Perkins, and Winston
Churchill. No, not that Winston Churchill . . .
</P>
<P>
   Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
