<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WHAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHAT LIES BENEATH' REALLY NOT SO FRIGHTENING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
WHAT LIES BENEATH 
Directed by: Robert Zemeckis 
Screenplay by: Clark Gregg 
Starring: Michelle Pfeiffer, Harrison Ford, Katharine Towne,
Mirando Otto, James Remar, Victoria Bisdewell, Diana Scarwid, Amber
Valletta, Joe Morton, Micole Mercurio 
Running time: 130 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (terror/violence, sensuality and brief language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Certainly, there should be room for an adult version of ``I Know
What You Did Last Summer.'' But ``What Lies Beneath'' isn't it.
Essentially, it's claptrap, but Harrison Ford and Michelle Pfeiffer
don't take naturally to claptrap and director Robert Zemeckis stubs
his toe on it, too, especially in the end. It's meant to be a
scarefest in which Pfeiffer sees dead people, specifically a dead
woman her husband had been sleeping with. ``What Lies Beneath'' is
the kind of movie in which sins not only come home to roost but
move in under the floorboards and start doing poltergeist stuff.
Meanwhile, Pfeiffer's spooked wife starts doing a Hitchcock number
out of ``Rear Window,'' spying on the guy next door after his wife
mysteriously disappears. But clearly, that's not all there is to
it.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, her character, a classical musician who gave up her
career in deference to that of her high-powered geneticist husband,
played by Ford, is sitting on unarticulated anger, or at least
resentment. One look at their perfect world, a handsome lakeside
house in Vermont, complete with garden, and you know it can't be
the Eden it seems. Ford and Pfeiffer make this clear in their first
bedroom scene. She looks sexy in her nightie, sexy enough to
convince her workaholic husband to detach himself from his laptop
and attach himself to her instead. But she's clearly tense and he's
prickly.
</P>
<P>
   These two are not at ease with each other. Matters aren't helped
when she turns to him, frightened after doors start opening and
closing, appliances go on and off, and noises are heard, and his
response is to bundle her off to a shrink. There's such a repressed
quality in their outwardly perfect lifestyle that a long, sustained
scream seems a valid reaction, quite apart from any poltergeists.
So far, so good with the film, which is a bit poky but of sleek
enough workmanship to keep you watching. It's interesting, too, to
discover that the word ``lies'' means as much as the word
``beneath'' in the title, as ugly things start coming to light and
the hitherto passive wife begins to think about maybe reclaiming
her life.
</P>
<P>
   The question becomes one of who's lying to whom as Pfeiffer's
increasingly confused character, ironically named Claire,
intensifies her snooping on her neighbor and also begins to examine
a few of the objects in her own house with new eyes. As Claire
begins fraying, so does her husband, Norman. His good-guy patience
evaporates and he blows up at Claire, accusing her of trying to
sabotage a paper he's preparing to deliver at an important
conference. It's about as genuinely primal as the film gets.
There's something mechanical and calculated about the way it layers
its revelations and metaphors. You receive them as information
transmitted to your data bank, not as creepy-crawly stuff making
the hairs on the back of your neck tingle.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Pfeiffer deliver craftsmanlike work, but the film
steadily unravels as Zemeckis tries to ratchet up the suspense. He
borrows from a couple of other Hitchcock films (the score also owes
much to Bernard Herrmann's music for ``Psycho''), and, apparently
sensing a shortfall in the scariness department, steers the film
into jack-in-the-box territory, hoping to yank thrills from the
sudden appearance of one character or another. But as this one or
that one _ at one point, even the couple's dog _ pops into the
frame, it becomes glumly undeniable that they're all flogging a
dead horse. At one point, in what becomes an interminable ending,
Claire accusingly screams at Norman, ``There's a presence in our
house!'' The trouble is that the presence isn't Hitchcock's. It's
more like William Castle's _ except that Castle (``The Tingler,
``House on Haunted Hill'') was much more at ease with shameless
exploitation and did it a lot better than ``What Lies Beneath.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
