<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY HARRIS BACK IN THE RUNNING WITH THE PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL SMITH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Patriots have been searching for him for
three years now.
</P>
<P>
   He is a comparable replacement for Curtis Martin. The Patriots
thought they had him when Robert Edwards ran for more than 1,000
yards as a rookie in 1998. But an injury left his career in
jeapordy, so the search continued.
</P>
<P>
   It brought the Patriots to Kevin Faulk in the '99 NFL Draft. He
hasn't turned out to be an every-down back, though he has become
their best kick returner. So the Patriots turned to veteran Terry
Allen, who rushed for 896 yards last season. It was his only in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to this year's edition of the annual running
back challenge. All the Patriots want is for someone to give
respectability to their running game, thereby taking some of the
pressure off Drew Bledsoe. They drafted J.R. Redmond out of Arizona
State, thinking he could come in and possibly be ``the guy.'' The
problem is, he hasn't come in yet.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before they drafted Redmond, however, the Patriots
signed former Bear and Packer Raymont Harris. All he has done in
the first four days of training camp is put distance between
himself and Redmond in the race for the starting job. He has had
what coach Bill Belichick calls ``a good, solid, consistent camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris has had his share of setbacks in his five-year career.
They've made him hungry. It's still early, but you can tell by the
way Harris is running in training camp that he wants the job search
to end with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of those kinds of guys that has a chip on his shoulder
when it comes to football,'' Harris said Thursday after the team's
morning workout. ``I see the type of things that they say about me,
being over the hill and slow and injury-prone and things like that.
I'm a competitor. I don't want my game to be viewed that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely taking this as a challenge, and I'm going to
prove a lot of people wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the skepticism comes from the fact that Harris was out
of football all of last year. Since being drafted out of Ohio State
in the first round by Chicago in 1994, he has played in all 16
regular-season games only once in his career.
</P>
<P>
   A broken collarbone kept him out of all but one game in 1995. A
year later, a knee injury forced him to miss four contests. After a
breakout 1997 season with the Bears, Harris signed a free-agent
deal with Green Bay, for whom he was supposed to be a steady
complement to Dorsey Levens. But he missed half the '98 season with
a stress fracture in his left leg and torn ligaments in his ankle.
The Packers released him, and he spent 1999 watching the NFL on
television, as several tryouts couldn't land him a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was really trying at times,'' said Harris, who
rushed for 1,033 yards in 1997 despite playing in only 13 games.
``I would catch myself analyzing and critiquing games. Watching
other running backs do their thing, and watching my friends go out
there and rooting for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just really tough. It was like having something taken
away from you in a way. And it was out of my control. And I usually
have control of things in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Harris appears to be in control of who will line up
behind Bledsoe. If he continues to impress while Redmond continues
to hold out, it will be very difficult for the rookie, who is
coming off groin surgery, to beat out the veteran for the starting
spot.
</P>
<P>
   For Harris, New England presented a good opportunity to start
over. He knew the Patriots needed a running back, and also knew
that he'd have a chance to play for a winning team. And it didn't
hurt that his former teammate in Chicago, fullback Tony Carter, was
also in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the team was very solid and had a chance to make some
definite waves in the league this year,'' said Harris. ``We've got
a new coaching staff, everyone's going to be starting new, and I've
got a chance to revive my career.''
</P>
<P>
   From what he's seen in training camp, Harris believes the
Patriots have what it takes to win it all. ``There's a lot of
talent here,'' he said. ``There are some guys here that are three
years removed from the Super Bowl. So the talent is definitely
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 29, comes from a great running back tradition at Ohio
State, which has featured the likes of Archie Griffin, Keith Byars,
Robert Smith, and Harris's teammate with the Buckeyes, Eddie George
of the Titans. Harris hopes that, like Smith and George, he can
become one of the league's elite backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all like great friends,'' said Harris, who started his
pro career as a fullback but moved to tailback in the fourth game
of the '97 season. ``I've learned a lot from them, and I'd like to
believe that I taught them some things here and there. They believe
in me. They know what kind of person I am on the field and off the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   The league saw a glimpse of what Harris could do with the
football while he was in Chicago. Now he's out to prove that he
hasn't lost it. One thing's for sure, he said: He's going to give
it his all whether he's the man or just one of a committee of
running backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always considered myself the kind of person that would do
anything that the team needed me to do,'' said Harris. ``If I keep
working hard, this injury stuff right here, statistically, it just
can't happen too many more times. I know things are going to work
out well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
