<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-EARLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVE EARLE EXPLOITING HIS SECOND CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the casual observer, Steve Earle looks like a garden-variety
overachiever. He's just hit the road for a tour in support of his
fine new CD, ``Transcendental Blues'' _ the country music
renegade's fifth album in five years. He's finishing up a
collection of short stories, ``Doghouse Roses,'' scheduled for
spring release by Houghton Mifflin. He's producing an album for
Canadian singer-songwriter Ron Sexsmith, contributing to the
soundtrack for a film about Abbie Hoffman, and writing his first
play, about executed murderer Karla Faye Tucker. (In his spare
time, Earle is an outspoken activist for eradicating the death
penalty, eliminating land mines, and boosting welfare.) He commutes
from Nashville to Chicago to teach a songwriting class three nights
a week. As a really cool spiritual exercise, Earle is writing a
haiku a day for a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to wake up in the morning to a $500-a-day
habit,'' he says, by way of explanation. Far from a stress-addicted
Type A personality, Earle fills his days and nights with the
gregariousness of someone who not so long ago filled his time with
far less constructive pursuits _ namely smoking crack and downing
Dilaudid, a synthetic form of heroin.
</P>
<P>
   For the better part of 20 years, Earle was a raging drug addict.
That he managed to carve out a career as Nashville's best-loved
rebel, marry and divorce six times, father two children, and stay
alive is miraculous. A large portion of credit goes to Earle's
mentors: the late Townes Van Zandt and Guy Clark, a pair of
songwriters well-versed in both and self-destruction and
redemption.
</P>
<P>
   The last five years mark an incredible creative run for Earle, a
true chameleon of a songwriter. ``Transcendental Blues'' is his
most inward-facing and ambitious album to date, a sea change from
last year's ``The Mountain'' _ a collaboration with bluegrass star
Del McCoury. It's an earthy, trippy, scorched cross-pollination of
folk, pop, rockabilly, Celtic, and country music. It includes some
of Earle's usual in-your-face narratives, but also more personal
reflections, and he lets the battle scars show.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Transcendental Blues,' the song, is pretty ambiguous for
me,'' Earle says, on the phone from E-Squared, his Nashville-based
record label. ``It's about the idea of change, and that change for
me is not elective. It's necessary for my survival. If I don't
continue to change, I'll die. I feel like a completely different
person than the person who made `Guitar Town' and `Copperhead Road'
(two albums Earle made in the '80s). Not that I'm ashamed of those
records. I just have a hard time recognizing the person who made
those records as me.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, after failing to appear in court for sentencing on a
prior heroin charge, Earle was incarcerated and then sent to a drug
treatment facility because ``they didn't want me dying in their
jail.'' That's where Earle finally kicked drugs. Make no mistake,
though. There were none of the usual epiphanies or revelations
involved in Earle's recovery. He didn't turn to religion or the 12
Steps. He had, Earle says, no desire to stop using. ``I had no
intention of ever getting clean. I knew I was an addict, knew I was
dying, and didn't think I could kick it. Where did I get the
strength? I got locked up.''
</P>
<P>
   Earle feels, understandably, like a man who's been given a
second chance. ``It almost feels like a second life, a second
career,'' says Earle. ``I've figured out what I missed, and I'm
living it now. I probably am doing more than I ever have. But for
the first time in five years I don't have a single song written for
another record. I have a life now. I do other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those other things are setting up house with the woman he
loves _ who has wisely, Earle concedes, decided against marrying
him _ and finding his voice as a writer of prose and poetry. He's
four months into his commitment to write 365 haikus in as many
days, a project inspired by ``just sort of wanting to learn
something about it.'' Those may sound like the words of a
dilettante; in Earle's case, they're the words of a man making up
for lost time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got an eighth-grade education,'' Earle says. ``I never
took English lit. The way I know about poetry is I read ``The
Electric Kool-Aid Acid Test'' and then backtracked to Kerouac, and
Kerouac and (Gary) Snyder were two of the earliest people to write
haiku in English. It's a great literary exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Earle is as uninterested in the mainstream country music scene,
or Nashville's star-making machinery for that matter, as he ever
was. His label is an imprint of Artemis Records, run by respected
industry veteran Danny Goldberg, and distributed by RED, a large
independent distributor. Earle has total creative control, and all
that freedom suits him fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised by Townes and Guy, so at a very early age I met
people who weren't doing it for the money. I got lucky when, at a
certain point in time, mainstream music became interested in what I
was doing. I call it the Great Credibility Scare of the Mid-'80s.
But the last decade has been a supernova period for country, and
music that's left of center really gets obscured. I do what I do,
and I'm pretty comfortable with it. And I'll never get a lecture
from Danny Goldberg about how many records I'd sell if I'd tone
down the death penalty stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Earle has no regrets about the past. His one lingering
resentment, he says, is how his kids _ now 13 and 18 _ were treated
at school because of what parents and teachers read about him in
the papers. Likewise, he acknowledges a single thread of goodness
that's come from surviving two decades of self-abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have sort of a spiritual center now that I didn't have
before,'' says Earle. ``But my spirituality is real retarded. It
basically consists of `I believe there is a God, and it ain't me.'
It's simple, but it works.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
