A8692 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-CHUCK-BOS &LR;      07-21 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CHUCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHUCK &AMP; BUCK' IS SURPRISINGLY FRESH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
CHUCK &AMP; BUCK 
Directed by: Miguel Arteta 
Screenplay by: Mike White 
Starring: White, Chris Weitz, Lupe Ontiveros, Beth Colt, Paul
Weitz, Maya Rudolph, Mary Wigmore, Paul Sand, Gino Buccola 
Running time: 95 minutes 
Rated: R (sexuality and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And now for something a little different. We are talking about
``Chuck &AMP; Buck,'' a film more loaded with originality and mercy
than any film so far this year. The Playskool resonance in its
title is deliberate. Buck, the film's geeky protagonist, is a case
of arrested development, a 27-year-old man emotionally stalled
somewhere in preadolescence. He's fixated on his boyhood pal,
Chuck, who has, shall we say, moved on while Buck has simply sat at
home replaying and replaying his childhood. When Buck's mom dies,
aided by a heavy cigarette habit, he registers no emotion. He just
moves on to Los Angeles, where he has quite a bit of emotion
invested because that's where Chuck lives. Buck can't wait to get
there and rekindle what he remembers as Chuck's affections.
</P>
<P>
   But while Buck has remained pretty much unchanged except
chronologically, Chuck has become a hard-driving music biz agent
with a smart girlfriend he's about to marry. He greets Buck's
arrival with muted enthusiasm, then makes it pretty obvious that
he'd just as soon avoid Buck. The latter's feelings are hurt, but
this only causes him to intensify his efforts to connect. While
Chuck displays increasing discomfort, Chuck's girlfriend is more
polite and humane, inviting Buck to several of their parties, where
it becomes apparent that Buck doesn't fit into Chuck's new circle.
Increasingly desperate, Buck takes most of his inheritance, rents a
theater across the street from Chuck's office, and pays for a
staging of a psychodrama he wrote, called ``Hank &AMP; Frank.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Buck's thinly veiled view of his obsession with Chuck, and
long before it receives its one and only performance, you know that
something's got to give. Among the things that veer into
invigorating territory are the respective trajectories of each
character. Just when you think you know where they're headed, and
you think you have a read on them, you're pleasantly surprised to
discover that Mike White's screenplay is a step ahead of you,
dancing beyond your expectations for the characters. As White,
director Miguel Arteta, and the actors ratchet up the tension, you
know that something gruesome or something transformative is going
to happen, and you're irretrievably hooked. To not stick around and
see how it all goes down becomes unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Spike Jonzes' screenplay for ``Being John Malkovich''
have we encountered a piece of writing for the screen that contains
the unpredictable zigs and zags of White's script. White is best
known as a writer for ``Dawson's Creek'' and ``Freaks and Geeks.''
His performance here as his own malfunctioning creation opens new
frontiers in geek chic. A large part of the considerable impact of
``Chuck &AMP; Buck'' also stems from the actors' spot-on success at
subverting our expectations. Just as dramatically potent as White's
Buck are the Weitz brothers, Chris and Paul (they made ``American
Pie''), as, respectively, Chuck, with his progressively
disintegrating cool, and a marginally functional actor named Sam,
cast by Buck to play the Chuck surrogate in his play.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, White and Arteta also make sure the women's roles
are no less faceted and engaging in unexpected ways. Beth Colt is
an important part of the film's success as the fiancee who reveals
unforeseen dimension as her patience is tested. Lupe Ontiveros, as
the savvy and pragmatic stage manager who uses Buck's vanity
project as an opening to show what she can do as a director, could
herself be the subject of a film. Director Arteta, meanwhile, more
than fulfills the promise of his 1997 debut, ``Star Maps.'' ``Chuck
&AMP; Buck'' is a screenful of freshly conceived, serendipitously
dimensioned characters going we know not where as they play out
their agendas. It's all we ask of a film but almost never get, as
it first makes us squirm, then makes us cheer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
