<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CONVSERVATISM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIVELY LOOK AT `COMPASSIONATE CONSERVATISM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
Compassionate Conservatism: What It Is, What It Does, and How It
Can Transform America 
By Marvin Olasky. Free Press. 272 pp. $24. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush knew Marvin Olasky as a dreamy-eyed intellectual.
Marvin Olasky knew George W. Bush as the owner of the Texas Rangers
baseball club. In the early 1990s, the two men were brought
together. They did not talk about the infield fly rule.
</P>
<P>
   Olasky is the high priest of ``compassionate conservatism,''
which, depending upon your point of view, is either the visionary
philosophy or the deft slogan behind Governor Bush's presidential
campaign. And now, smack in the middle of the 2000 presidential
race, Olasky has produced a brisk little guide to the guiding
philosophy of the Republican candidate for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Olasky is a professor of journalism at the University of Texas
at Austin and the editor of World, a weekly Christian news
magazine. He is also a onetime fledgling reporter at the Boston
Globe. Today he is the chairman of the Bush campaign's policy
subcommittee on religion. He continues to be a prodigious author
and pamphleteer.
</P>
<P>
   His latest work is not quite a manifesto, not quite a treatise,
not quite a tour of how (and where) compassionate conservatism
works. It is, instead, a combination of all three _ readable,
approachable, and provocative.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, it is an attack on the welfare state that was
constructed by one Texan, President Lyndon B. Johnson, and that
faces a new threat from another Texan, Bush. Olasky doesn't bury
his critique; here it is, right on the fourth page of his book:
</P>
<P>
   ``The major flaw of the modern welfare state is not that it is
extravagant, but that it is too stingy. It gives the needy bread
and tells them to be content with that alone. It gives the rest of
us the opportunity to be stingy also, and to salve our consciences
even as we scrimp on what many of the destitute need most _ love,
time, and a challenge to be `little lower than the angels' rather
than one thumb up from the monkeys.''
</P>
<P>
   Two major principles undergird the idea of compassionate
conservatism. The first is a form of federalism, one that prefers
private and individual assistance to government aid and that
accepts government intervention only at the closest possible level,
preferably not from Washington. The other principle is a belief
that religious organizations (the phrase you will encounter in the
news columns is ``faith-based institutions'') ought to be empowered
to reassume the positions of respect and power they had a century
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to look within the family first; if the family
cannot help, maybe an individual or group within the neighborhood
can; if not, then organizations outside the neighborhood but within
the community should be called on,'' Olasky writes. ``If it is
necessary to turn to government, compassionate conservatives
typically look first to municipal, then to county, then to state,
and only then to federal offices.''
</P>
<P>
   But Olasky argues that religious organizations, which minister
to spiritual needs that often are greater than people's material
needs, are best suited to assume the role of helping the poor, the
sick, and the disabled. And he contends that churches, synagogues,
and mosques engaged in social-welfare undertakings ought to be
eligible for some government assistance.
</P>
<P>
   He believes that religious organizations have special insights
and special success in these endeavors. He argues, moreover, that
resistance to providing funding to religious groups for such work
grows out of a belief that religious institutions should be
isolated completely from public money.
</P>
<P>
   Olasky points out that taxpayers have subsidized religious
institutions for years; after all, contributions to religious
groups, which constitute about half of all charitible giving from
individuals, are tax deductible, which makes such contributions a
government subsidy. Religious groups, moreover, usually don't pay
sales or property taxes, another public subsidy. ``Each level of
government has seen merit in such arrangements,'' he writes, ``and
the tax-exempt status of religious organizations has rarely caused
conflicts or jeopardized their liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the spine of the book. Much of the volume is a
travelogue, with Olasky and his son journeying around the nation _
through Texas, to the Mid Atlantic, to the Midwest _ examining the
successes of social welfare programs based on these ideas. The
examples are compelling.
</P>
<P>
   But the most provocative element of the book is Olasky's
interpretation of what the constitutional scholars call the
``establishment clause'' of the Bill of Rights: ``Congress shall
make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting
the free exercise thereof.''
</P>
<P>
   Olasky argues that the primary goal of that sentence is to
provide freedom for religion, not freedom from religion. Of all the
debates of this presidential year, that may be the one most worth
having _ and the one least likely to occur.
</P>
<P>
   The volume includes a brief forward by Governor Bush and the
text of a Bush speech praising compassionate conservatism in
action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
