<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAMPTON COMES ALIVE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So what if Peter Frampton isn't in a position to charge the high
ticket prices that some of his boomer-rock peers have demanded in
recent years. Frampton still doesn't like it _ and he's not about
to withhold his criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It blows my mind. I don't agree with it,'' says Frampton.
``It's called raping the public.''
</P>
<P>
   If only more artists, managers, and conglomerates (namely SFX)
had the same thought, right?
</P>
<P>
   Frampton is keeping his prices very reasonable by rock-veteran
standards. He headlines the South Shore Music Circus in Cohasset,
just outside of Boston, Wednesday at prices of $34 and $26 _ a
fraction of the $250 gouging to see the recently scuttled Diana
Ross and the Supremes tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a disgusting price for a fake show,'' Frampton says,
aware that Ross was the only original Supreme on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Frampton is feeling feisty these days _ and for good reason. His
career is starting to surge again. He just released a new album,
``Live in Detroit,'' a surprisingly powerful effort that is also
out on DVD. He has a new ``Behind the Music'' episode on VH1 airing
next month. He has the ``Peter Frampton Anthology'' due next month
as well, featuring classic Frampton tracks, plus songs from his
previous bands, Humble Pie and the Herd. He also recorded two songs
for the upcoming Disney album ``Tigger Mania.'' And he has an
acting role in Cameron Crowe's long-awaited film, ``Almost Famous''
(due in theaters Sept. 16). It's a loose history of '70s rock in
which Frampton plays Humble Pie's road manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a pivotal scene where there's a table full of famous
road managers playing cards,'' Frampton says with a laugh. He also
served as ``authenticity adviser'' on the film, consulting on
hairstyles and fashions of the '70s, and helping direct the live
footage of the fictional concert band, Stillwater.
</P>
<P>
   Frampton's chief claim to fame was the 1976 album ``Frampton
Comes Alive,'' which sold 16 million copies and is still the
best-selling live album of all time. If anyone knows the '70s era,
it's Frampton, who first got to know film director Cameron Crowe
when Crowe, then known as a rock journalist, wrote the liner notes
to the live album.
</P>
<P>
   Frampton has had pronounced highs and lows ever since, enduring
record label hassles as well as stints playing for David Bowie (his
``Glass Spiders'' tour) and Ringo Starr's All-Starr Band. This year
he was asked again to be on Starr's tour, but declined because he
was too busy with his own projects. (He was replaced by guitarist
Dave Edmunds on Starr's tour.)
</P>
<P>
   He's been encouraged not just by baby boomers who are back
checking out his shows, but by a younger audience just getting
turned on to him through classic-rock stations and, yes, through
the albums of their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there were young crowds last year, but this year
they're even younger,'' says Frampton. ``You've got 16- and
17-year-olds in front singing the words even to the obscure songs
on `Frampton Comes Alive.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Frampton, who now lives in Nashville (where he just joined the
Foo Fighters onstage to perform ``Show Me the Way''), is also
particularly excited about his ``Behind the Music'' special on Aug.
6. VH1 staffers conducted 12 hours of interviews with him and
chatted with his parents in England and with former Rolling Stones
bassist Bill Wyman, one of his oldest friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill was actually the first person to manage me and produce
me,'' says Frampton. ``I was in a band at age 14 called the
Preachers. The drummer was Tony Chapman, the original drummer of
the Stones before Charlie Watts. He was best friends with Bill
Wyman and he brought Bill down. Bill is very loyal. He had said to
Tony, `You get a band together and I'll produce it.' And I've been
friends with Bill ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Based on a captivating debut CD, ``Words for Living,'' not to
mention buzz that's building with each publication cycle,
anticipation was high for P. J. Olsson's set at Karma Wednesday
night. His blend of folk-rock with electronic beats and samples is
reminiscent of Beck and Beth Orton, and Olsson swings from ballads
to soundscapes to industrial-strength rockers with zonked-out grace
on record; unfortunately, the charm of his studio project was
pretty much erased by unbearably loud sound and a troubled mix.
</P>
<P>
   Words matter for a singer-songwriter, and Olsson's were largely
inaudible, with or without the groovy filters and distorters he
made generous use of. Keyboards, bass, and guitars blurred into an
indistinguishable wash, depriving these intelligent songs of all
the sonic and literary nuance that made them interesting in the
first place. It's a critical moment in Olsson's career, and a good
time to reassess his live show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
