<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-NSYNC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HARD WORK OF BEING TEEN IDOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teen idols are often called ``overnight sensations.'' True or
not, it's just the way the public perceives these unusual
creatures, who pop up on MTV as if they were hatched yesterday,
even though they might have toiled for years.
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync has heard the phrase, but will tell you strongly it does
not apply to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody hears about the work that we've been putting in the
last five to six years. Everybody just hears about the last year
and a half,'' singer Chris Kirkpatrick says of the Orlando-based
superstars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody hears about us singing at high schools for years, or
doing the national anthem at Orlando Magic games, or at baseball
games in the area,'' Kirkpatrick adds during a telephone press
conference before the current tour began in early May. ``We have
worked hard.''
</P>
<P>
   And the group is still working hard. Sure, they're being paid a
king's ransom for their work now _ that happens when you sell a
record 2.4 million copies of your new album in the first week, as
occurred in April _ but the long hours have only intensified.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the downside of being in 'N Sync, Kirkpatrick says,
``We don't get much time to rest. Just when you think you're
getting a day off, you don't. We never get days off. In the last
five years, we've maybe had one week off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We enjoy doing the tours, but if you have a day off, a charity
will want you to come by and say hi to some kids. Or you do your
own charity event,'' he says. ``But that is stuff you really enjoy
doing. And, mainly, we're doing what we love, so I'm not knocking
it. If you have to do it every day, then so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start out, you always have to prove yourself,'' adds
'N Sync singer JC Chasez. ``But now people are enjoying the music.
Now it's all about being creative and finding new ways to introduce
it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The way that 'N Sync is introducing it this summer is through
the massive ``No Strings Attached'' stadium tour (also the name of
their album), which uses otherworldly props, smoke bombs, hydraulic
lifts, lasers, and other goodies to create a kind of Broadway
theater for young fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concentrating on an interactive experience this time,''
says Chasez. ``This show is like 'N Sync interactive. There's some
really cool stuff that the crowd gets involved with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a special feeling to feel that you're part of the
show,'' he adds. ``When I go to a show, I always love it when
somebody stares at me or points at me. It's like, `Dude! Mick
Jagger just pointed at me!' So we're trying to make that happen a
lot in the show.''
</P>
<P>
   The group rehearsed hard for this tour _ from 6 to 12 hours a
day _ and the results were evident at the opening date in Biloxi,
Miss. on May 9. The concert was devoid of typical opening-night
glitches, as Chasez and Kirkpatrick, along with fellow members
Justin Timberlake, Lance Bass, and Joey Fatone Jr. put on a
jubilant show with enough special effects to keep the fans gasping
throughout.
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync members dance so feverishly that they seem like a blur
at times. It has gotten to the point where Chasez even admits,
``Most likely we'll be doing a little less dancing on our next
tour. And hopefully we will have grown musically by then. We want
to do this for a long time. We'll be doing more writing and
producing, and as far as the shows are concerned, they will be less
dance-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be too old to dance this much!'' Kirkpatrick says.
``It's killing me.''
</P>
<P>
   Being teen idols, 'N Sync exists in a brutally competitive field
where people wonder aloud if the group is better than the
Backstreet Boys, better than Britney Spears, better than 98
Degrees, and better than all the rest. But 'N Sync doesn't
encourage such talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, other people make a much bigger deal of it than we
do,'' says Chasez. ``It's not something we're concentrating on. We
just do what we do, day in and day out, which is what we've done
from the beginning. We don't worry about comparisons. I mean, look
at baseball players. They don't go to bed thinking, `I hate those
other guys.' They just want to get up to bat for themselves, which
is the way it works for us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they're also aware that they have an image to uphold
as idols. ``When we get onstage, we don't run out there and
(swear),'' says Kirkpatrick. ``Or say, `This is the time we take
off our shirts, or this is when we moon the crowd and try to get
arrested.' We don't do that. We know we have an image to uphold _
and we try to uphold it to the best of our abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, they're also keeping an eye on Sisqo, their
somewhat risque opening act whose big hit this year was the
suggestive ``Thong Song.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make the show more exciting,'' Kirkpatrick says
of Sisqo. ``But I think he also realizes that his crowd is not 100
percent our crowd, and our crowd is not 100 percent his crowd. He's
a professional. He understands we have an image to uphold.''
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync, which has also taken control of its business affairs
(each member takes turns monitoring their business managers, for
instance), is now starting to think of long-term plans. At the head
of the list is making a ``high-school-style'' movie musical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not pretending to be great actors. We just want to do
something fun,'' says Kirkpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, now that they've made it to the big time, they're
getting a firsthand taste of what being a teen idol is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're stuck in hotels eating a lot of hotel food,'' says
Kirkpatrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get to walk around much,'' adds Chasez. ``We go to
malls occasionally, but they can get hectic if people recognize us.
Yeah, for the most part, we're stuck in hotels.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8705 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-LOSER-BOS &LR;      07-21 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LOSER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTCASTS ARE LIKEABLE IN ENDEARING `LOSER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
LOSER 
Written and directed by: Amy Heckerling 
Starring: Jason Biggs, Mena Suvari, Zak Orth, Tom Sadoski, Jimmi
Simpson, Greg Kinnear, Dan Aykroyd 
Running time: 98 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jason Biggs and Mena Suvari starred in ``American Pie'' last
year, although not together. And Biggs was nowhere near ``American
Beauty'' as Suvari became the rose-petal-bedecked object of Kevin
Spacey's sexual fantasies. Amy Heckerling's ``Loser'' plays A-list
matchmaker, bringing them together as two college students at a
thinly-veiled NYU. Biggs's dorky Paul and Suvari's smart, sensitive
Dora are such sweet, caring, trusting people that you hope they'll
get together, if only because the rest of New York will chew them
up and spit them out if they're left on their own. ``Loser''
doesn't quite rank with the films that bracket Heckerling's pop
culture high priestess status _ ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High''
and ``Clueless.'' But it's enjoyable enough, even if it's not as
original as the year's best romantic comedies: ``High Fidelity,''
``Wonder Boys,'' and the imminent ``The Tao of Steve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Loser'' has a foreordained quality. You spend a lot of time
imagining you can hear the pieces falling into place as Biggs's
upstate rube is shredded by his three rich, callous party-animal
roommates and Suvari's gifted but financially struggling coed
allows herself to be steamrolled by Greg Kinnear's smug,
self-infatuated prof, whose exploitation of Dora is by no means
limited to the sexual variety. He's even worse when she dares to
have a thought of her own and his fascist control freak side shifts
into overdrive. It's a tribute to Kinnear's innate likability that
he raises a character who could otherwise have been the film's most
two-dimensional to the level of the barely tolerable. The
manipulations of Heckerling's script are never what you wouldn't
call deeply concealed, especially when it comes to Paul's three
snaky roommates who kick him out.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they're through with him just yet. When they discover
that the university has found him a live-in job at an animal
hospital, they reopen their acquaintanceship with him, figuring
they can use the space on weekends for parties they hope will end
in date rape with the help of drugs slipped into the punch bowl. Of
course, Paul and Dora have begun to edge together, accelerated by
the chance to ooh and aah over kittens and puppies, but Paul's
three nemeses and Kinnear's slick but callow prof aren't through
with them. As the party animals, Zak Orth, Jimmi Simpson, and Tom
Sadoski are lively presences, with Sadoski hinting that he might be
the next James Spader and all three knowing just where to go with
the amusingly nasty dialogue Heckerling gives them. When Paul
enters their shared quarters wearing what is to become his
trademark fur-lined cap, one cracks: ``Did the producers of `Fargo'
have a garage sale?''
</P>
<P>
   At more than a few points, Heckerling the writer allows herself
a few easy outs. Heckerling the director usually knows how to
finesse her way around the the obviousness of her screenplay's
manipulations. Once Paul exchanges the figurative animal house for
the much more restful, healthful literal one, the script
occasionally OD's on warm, cuddly stuff. But the forces of
mendacity lined up against the couple are never more than
caricature-deep. The young lovers-to-be aren't so much menaced by
the prof and the bonehead roommates as by their own innocence.
Suvari and Biggs are pretty and sympatico, too, with Suvari the
more convincingly vulnerable one. Only once does Heckerling the
director err in her handling of them. At the end, when they move in
for the big clinch, we see them in profile and the characters'
innocence drops away, to be replaced by what clearly are the power
auras of two young stars moving up the A-list. ``Loser'' will help
them ascend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
