<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8707 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-HALL-FISK-2TAKES-     07-21 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HALL-FISK-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIDE OF NEW ENGLAND ABOUT TO ENTER HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ After all is said and done, the Red Sox are
still his team.
</P>
<P>
   Proof of that will come Sunday when Carlton Fisk, regarded as
one of the most durable catchers in major league history, takes his
place in the Baseball Hall of Fame along with four others. On
Sunday, Fisk will become perhaps New England's most famous baseball
player.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Vermont and raised in New Hampshire, ``Pudge'' Fisk
spent his first 12 years in the majors with the Red Sox. After a
contract squabble, Fisk moved on to the Chicago White Sox in 1981,
where he proudly wore socks of a different color. But when he
looked back, Fisk found many of the same fans who supported him at
Fenway had stuck with him during his years in Chicago. He will also
have a great following Sunday, when record crowds are expected in
Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk may not know it yet, but he's going to be swamped by fans
from Boston, Chicago, and many other cities as well. An entire
generation of baseball fans has grown up watching reruns of Game 6
of the 1975 World Series. At least two million fans will swear they
were in Fenway that night and followed him through his dance up the
first-base line, and his home run trot around the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Was it nice, Pudge?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he will answer. ``I hit that ball good. All I wanted
was for the ball to stay fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Why a Red Sox cap?
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to wear a Red Sox cap in the Hall of Fame was
never a difficult one. New England is still where my roots are. And
I'm a New England person even though I don't live there. I always
wanted to be a member of the Boston Red Sox. I've retired, but I'm
still working for them. I'd like to do more.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Long before the Hall of Fame trumpets sounded, there were
stories about Fisk and his rise from a small town where his
graduating class at Charleton High consisted of 42 students.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, the Red Sox hired Jack Burns, a former major leaguer
with St. Louis and a scout with a good track record. Wilbur Wood of
Belmont and Bill Monboquette of Medford were said to be two he
recruited. But as Ray Fitzgerald, the late Globe columnist put it,
this is about one who almost got away.
</P>
<P>
   Burns had heard about a rangy 18-year-old catcher from New
Hampshire. He went to see Carlton Fisk play American Legion ball.
Burns found a game in Keene, N.H., and quickly formed this opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell the truth,'' he said, ``Fisk didn't look that good as
a catcher. He had a good swing and a strong arm, but he had a lot
of passed balls.''
</P>
<P>
   But Burns began to change his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an awful lot I did like about him, so I kept going
back. I saw Fisk play 16 times. They showed me a rock that Fisk had
hit beyond left field where the ball must have been hit 450 feet.
Anybody who can hit a ball that far, I surmised, deserved a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles were the first to give it to him, selecting him in
the 36th round of the June 1965 draft. But Fisk, who had decided to
go to college, was not eligible. The Sox made sure they would get
him the next time around.
</P>
<P>
   When it was learned that Fisk was not returning for his
sophomore year at the University of New Hampshire, Burns wrote the
office of the baseball commissioner to confirm that Fisk would be
in the June 1967 draft. The Sox took him as their first-round pick,
the fourth selection overall. The Orioles drafted infielder Brent
Nicoloff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even today, some still doubt Fisk's Hall of Fame credentials.
Fisk didn't catch a game as a professional until 1968. Not
including 14 games in the majors, Fisk played in just 346 games in
four seasons prior to his arrival to stay in the majors in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   However, Fisk rose to stardom quicker than any would have
imagined. After a year in the service, Fisk joined the Red Sox
after catching stints at Greenville (S.C.), Waterloo (Iowa),
Pittsfield, Pawtucket, and Louisville. He wasn't considered a great
hitter, for power or average, but he was a take-charge player and
the Sox needed that type of catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the 1972 season, veteran Duane Josephson, who appeared
in 26 major league games, lost the No. 1 job and never got it back.
Another veteran, Bob Montgomery, replaced Josephson briefly but
played in only 24 games. Fisk played in 131 regular-season games
that year and was selected to the All-Star Game by Orioles manager
Earl Weaver, who didn't care in the least that Fisk was not on
several ballots. It was that kind of year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he was brash guy,'' said former Red Sox teammate
Reggie Smith recently. ``But I have to say he was also very good. I
never anticipated that he would last as long as he did as a
catcher. He wound up having a wonderful career.''
</P>
<P>
   Said former Red Sox radio voice Ned Martin: ``He was always on
top of the pitcher and the game. He was a fierce competitor even
with his teammates. He caught every popup. He and George Scott
wanted every ball.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fisk could not be expected to keep up the pace of his rookie
season. He played in 135 games in 1973, batting .246. But he was
troubled by injuries the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, the Cincinnati Reds won the World Series in seven
games, but after 25 years, people are still talking about what Fisk
accomplished in Game 6. After Boston tied the game in the eighth
inning on a home run by Bernie Carbo, Fisk hit the winning homer in
the 12th inning down the line in left for a 7-6 victory in what is
considered one of the greatest games in Series history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The celebration of that moment has made me realize how popular
baseball is and how it affects people's lives,'' said Fisk.``People
reflect on moments in baseball they can attach to things in their
own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's grown men acting like kids with sticks and
balls and gloves and relating it to something deep and meaningful.
It's still the greatest moment in my career. We were still alive in
the Series that proved out to be my only chance to win a ring. For
a little hometown boy from New Hampshire to go out on his own with
no path to follow and have this kind of success is outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the 1975 Series, the power-laden Red Sox were expected
to end the championship drought that had lasted since 1918. Fisk,
29 at the time, made a contractual commitment to Boston for three
years. With other veterans like Fred Lynn, Jim Rice, Dennis
Eckerley, Rick Burleson, and Fisk as a nucleus, Boston was able
average 91 victories over a five-year period.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox failed to win the title and suffered through a
one-game playoff loss to the Yankees in 1978. Somehow, Fisk got the
blame for the failure to win a World Series. But the fact is, they
would have never have come so close without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my teacher most of the time,'' former Sox reliever Bob
Stanley said. ``In fact, when he left, I sort of went downhill.
Pudge was a great catcher. He used to yell at me a lot, something
my wife didn't like. One day she asked why he did that? He yelled
back, `Because sometimes he's stupid.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing you appreciated about Pudge was his strength was
handling pitchers and always keeping their minds focused on the
game. He taught me what I know.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The injuries
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the five years that followed that historic World Series, Fisk
batted .255, .315, .284, .279, and .289. He was now 34 and a
spirited veteran. By most estimates, injuries caused him to miss
the equivalent of six years of work, but he always found a way to
get back into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (injuries) started in Boston,'' said Fisk. ``I know I had
a couple of injuries that should have dictated I never play again.
I had my knee blown out at the plate and reconstructed. I hurt my
hand three times; a couple of groin injuries. I missed a lot of
prime time because of rehab.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I hurried back because I always felt that I had more to
contribute to a game than just catching a ball and throwing it back
to a pitcher. I always felt we needed direction, not so much
control. The idea was to provide positive direction and assurance
that what we were doing was the right way to win the game.'' It was
a way that I knew would work.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
