<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8708 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-HALL-FISK-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     07-21 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HALL-FISK-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 COOPERSTOWN, N.Y.: ... would work.''  
 
The insult 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christmas came early for Fisk in 1980. On Dec. 20, he was a
member of the Red Sox awaiting a contract offer in the mail for
$210,000 for the 1981 season. When it didn't arrive until a few
days later, Fisk discovered he had stumbled into the rare air of
free agency with no compensation. Less than two months later, Fisk
signed a contract with the White Sox, with whom he spent the next
11 1/2 seasons before retiring.
</P>
<P>
   On advice from his attorneys, Red Sox general manager Haywood
Sullivan mailed the renewal agreement past the Dec. 20 deadline
deliberately, and Boston paid the price. Fisk appealed the
tardiness to an arbritator, won his case and signed with the
Chicago White Sox in a deal that was said to earn him $3.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox at first blamed the Post Office, but the fans saw
through that. What was particularly disturbing was a claim by the
34-year-old Fisk that he had been told in 1976 that he could
renegotiate his contract if other salaries went up. Sullivan denied
such a commitment ever existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was crushed when the Red Sox did what they did to me in in
1980,'' said Fisk in a recent Globe interview. ``I didn't want to
go. But once I talked to the Red Sox, I found I had no other
choice. It was like a slap in the face, and I wished at the time I
had some explanation for it. I grew up in that organization, and to
me it was a second family. Then you're told you're not wanted. It
was bewildering.''
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't have been. The $1 million-plus days were just
around the corner and it was well known that Sullivan was a
hard-liner who would rather reshape the club than pay high
salaries. Rice and Eckersley were exceptions. Fisk was not.
Sullivan was clearly unable to deal with the modern agents and
maintain a small-market salary base. (The club had been purchased
by the Yawkey Foundation a few years earlier for $15 million). But
the fans loved Fisk and his absence left a large hole in Red Sox
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to wonder why they cheered so loud,'' said Fisk. ``Then
one day I realized they were yelling for me not against me.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rice: ``We knew his longevity would get him into the Hall
of Fame. But he had some great numbers to go along with that, which
put him on a par with all the great catchers, past and present.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fisk's Chicago days produced better numbers than he had in
Boston. Wearing No. 72, the reverse of the No. 27 he wore for
Boston, Fisk played with a fire that couldn't be dimmed,
particularly on his visits to Fenway. Fisk tortured his old team,
hitting .310 in 105 games. He had 116 base hits, including 27 home
runs and 67 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   But Fisk didn't play Boston every day. Much of his time in
Chicago was spent in run-ins with media and management. There were
many misunderstandings that left hard feelings on both sides. White
Sox owner Jerry Reinsdorf and Fisk were hardly friends down the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox reached the postseason once during Fisk's years in
Chicago. After winning 99 games and taking the AL West by 20 games
in 1983, they lost to Baltimore in four games. In 1986, the same
team finished 20 games behind, manager Tony LaRussa was off to
Oakland, and Fisk would begin to absorb some of the blame for the
team's slide. He found himself being assigned to DH and outfield
duties more and more. Chicago had three more losing seasons,
followed by winning seasons in 1991, 1992, and 1993. But the last
season, involved a travesty almost as bad as the one Fisk
experienced in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk needed to catch just 79 games to reach Bob Boone's modern
record, but he was getting fewer and fewer chances. And Fisk was
still smarting from a pay cut. The 1993 team was talented, and it
took some effort to put Fisk behind the plate. Once the record fell
at 2,226, Fisk's career was all but over.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever goodwill Fisk felt disappeared in the playoffs when he
was not allowed into the clubhouse as a visitor and got a police
escort out.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Fisk's name appeared on the Hall of Fame
ballot, and he will be entering with Tony Perez, a former Red Sox
teammate who played for the Reds in that 1975 Series, and Sparky
Anderson, who managed Cincinnati in '75.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, it wasn't hard to choose,'' said Fisk of his preference
of Red Sox over White Sox as he enters the Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Would Fisk have been better off had he stayed in Boston?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I would have played with the same reckless
abandon as I did,'' he said. ``But I do think I was a better player
in Chicago. Maybe older and wiser. Certainly more mature. But
because of that moment in 1975 and wearing a Boston uniform many
don't even realize I played for Chicago or how well I did there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured Fisk will get a warm welcome whenever he shows up
in the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're aware of the past,'' said Red Sox general manager Dan
Duquette. ``Others like me and John Harrington have worked hard to
see he is made to feel welcome in Boston, and he has been for
several years. He works for us as a coach in the spring. Perhaps we
can find an opportunity to do more. We enjoy having Pudge and his
family around.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service and Internet material ws used to prepare this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
