<HEADLINE>
CROSSING THE OCEAN STILL A CRUCIAL TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you think of the great American companies from the old
economy _ Gillette, Coke, McDonald's _ they all had one thing in
common: They made the leap from national leaders to world leaders.
By becoming dominant international players they were able to keep
growing long after their domestic markets were saturated, and they
were able to achieve a scale and a stock market value that
otherwise would have been impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But what about in the new economy? Which companies will be
global giants, and which will run into trouble when they try to
cross the ocean?
</P>
<P>
   The question comes to mind because a least a few of the hottest
American firms are getting a somewhat cool reception overseas.
</P>
<P>
   America Online is one. AOL has more Internet subscribers than
anyone else in this country, but according to a recent account in
The Wall Street Journal, AOL's track record around the globe is not
as impressive. AOL trails local competitors in Brazil, Canada,
France, and Germany, and ranks 10th among Internet service
providers in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``At every port overseas, AOL has run into home-grown
competitors backed by well-financed phone companies or media groups
with strong local content,'' wrote the Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm also has had trouble exporting its success. The San
Diego company has a cell-phone technology that it hoped would
become a world standard, much the way Windows has become the global
operating system for personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past two months, South Korea said it might abandon
the Qualcomm system in favor of a competing European one. And
China, which already uses the European technology, said it was
sticking with that system for now. Qualcomm stock has dropped 60
percent since the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast those stories with the experience of EMC. The Hopkinton
data storage company reported terrific earnings this week, paced by
huge sales gains all over the world. EMC is the top storage company
here, in Europe, and in Asia, except for Japan. ``In Japan, the
local companies always have a hometown advantage,'' said Mark
Fredrickson, an EMC spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   What's the lesson here? Money managers and analysts say there is
no one simple way to predict who will win abroad. But as a general
rule, the purer technology companies, those selling software or
hardware, should have an easier time than those selling content,
they say. And companies selling to corporate customers should have
an easier time than those selling to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are selling equipment, the differences among countries
aren't as pronounced,'' said Rob Joseph, an analyst with State
Street Research. Put another way, there is no such thing as a
French router or a German computer server.
</P>
<P>
   In many categories _ EMC in storage, Sun Microsystems in
servers, Cisco Systems in routers _ American companies already
dominate the international arena.
</P>
<P>
   On the content side, where companies like AOL, Yahoo, Amazon and
eBay play, the challenges are steeper. ``These are businesses that
can more easily be duplicated,'' said Mark Klee, co-manager of the
John Hancock Technology Fund. ``They are also businesses that have
some local character.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL has already encountered plenty of local competitors who got
there first with a comparable service. Internet retailers like
Amazon can easily be cloned. On the auction side, eBay has to deal
with language differences, plus different rules and regulations for
auctions in each country.
</P>
<P>
   The barriers can be overcome. Analysts point to Yahoo, the
popular portal, as an example of a content company that has
prospered overseas. According to Media Metrix, Yahoo ranks first in
Internet traffic in Japan and England and second in both France and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo got out there before the others,'' said Barry Parr, an
analyst with Interational Data Corp., a research firm. ``They also
decided from the beginning that international was going to be a big
part of their strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors looking for historical parallels might think of MTV,
an American business that has succeeded overseas by creating a
customized, localized product in markets all over the world. It can
be done. It just isn't easy to do.
</P>
<P>
   We don't pretend to know who is going to make it and who isn't
in the competition for the world. But we do know one thing: The
answer matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are looking at valuation,'' said Klee, ``you need to
know how big the available market is. By asking who is going to be
a player just in this country and who is going to be a player
worlwide you are barking up the right tree.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
