<HEADER>
A8711 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-WOMEN-BOS &LR;      07-21 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALLON'S SIDE TRIP PUTS HER IN THE FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GURNEE, Ill. _ She may be the most famous athletic daughter to
come out of Natick, Mass., but after Thursday, Meg Mallon may be
the US Women's Open's most infamous woman. And the impish Mallon
could care less.
</P>
<P>
   Mallon took the opening-round lead in the 55th Women's Open with
a solid 4-under-par 68 Thursday at the Merit Club, giving her a
one-stroke lead over two Australians, Karrie Webb and Shani Waugh.
But it is how Mallon approached her round _ especially the 14th
hole _ that created a buzz throughout the course, among the
golfers, the caddies, and the United States Golf Association.
</P>
<P>
   She started the week hitting it ``sideways in practice,'' as
Mallon described her wayward ways, but Thursday, on the 14th tee,
Mallon more or less hit the ball sideways again. But this time she
did it on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Mallon chose to play the 14th hole (par 4, 406 yards) by hitting
her ball down the parallel 13th fairway, which is separated from
the 14th by a large pond. And when her ball landed on the wrong
fairway, recalled Mallon of the merry scene, ``all the USGA ladies
got on their little speakers and said, `We've got a situation
here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A situation?
</P>
<P>
   A situation.
</P>
<P>
   For sure. Mallon's drive flew right over the head of Laura
Davies and shocked a threesome of former Open champions, Davies,
Annika Sorenstam, and Se Ri Pak, all blissfully playing what they
thought was their hole, the 13th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it right over Laura Davies's head,'' said Mallon, ``and
it certainly shocked them when I did that. They weren't quite sure
what I was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mallon was. She had played a practice round earlier in the
week with Pat Hurst and decided the best way to approach the 14th
green was down the 13th fairway. Ah, but with the advice and
consent first of Mallon's caddie, John Killeen. ``He's the star in
this,'' said Mallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hit it in the water (on the 14th, in practice), I had
hit it in the bunker, so I decided that going over the 13th
(fairway) was the better option,'' said Mallon. But when Mallon
tried the indirect route in practice, Hurst said to her, ``Meg,
what are you doing?''
</P>
<P>
   But Mallon went ahead Thursday anyway, sent ``all those USGA
ladies'' scurrying ``to their little speakers,'' and parred the
hole. ``So I don't know what the USGA is going to do now,'' said
Mallon. ``I don't know if they're going to put a tree up there or a
row of (portable toilets).''
</P>
<P>
   As word spread and golfer after golfer asked witnesses exactly
which path Mallon had chosen to take, the USGA also was all ears.
The USGA placed the 14th tee to force golfers to carry the water
from the tee.
</P>
<P>
   Kendra Graham, the USGA's director of Rules and Championships,
said she ``was as surprised as many of you were to hear how Meg
played 14. I guess creativity is the hallmark of US Open champions.
I think it's ingenious. I mean, it just shows there are many ways
to skin the cat.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham was asked if the USGA had any plans to follow its
precedent from the men's 1979 US Open at Inverness when Lon Hinkle
took an unorthodox route with his tee shot. The USGA then planted a
tree, forever known as the ``Lon Hinkle tree,'' to block Hinkle's
route.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham said she believes the USGA will do nothing. ``I will
give you my personal opinion, and my personal opinion would be that
we would do nothing,'' said Graham. ``That's because I think Meg
took some chances by playing the hole that way.'' (Mallon's drive
had to go over a tree to reach the wrong fairway.)
</P>
<P>
   The 68 by Mallon, the 1991 Open champion, was scored in the
relatively quiet morning breezes, which freshened considerably in
the afternoon. Webb, who has been frustrated in four Open attempts,
was able to fashion her 69 despite the breezes and despite having
to wade into a pond on the par-3 seventh to try her unorthodox
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Webb had to take off her right shoe and sock, plant that foot in
the water and mud, choke up on her club, and swat her ball from the
edge of the water. Her magnificent shot landed 8 feet from the pin
and, after wiping off the mud that was nearly up to her knee, she
sank the putt for par.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back home in Australia, I have a place where we go fishing and
I have to walk through mud like that,'' said Webb. ``So it felt
like I was back home fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Also one stroke behind Mallon is Webb's fellow Australian,
Waugh, who is appearing in her second Open. And Waugh said she
learned much from her first Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up in Australia, we didn't really know about the US
Open,'' said Waugh. ``I believe Jan Stephenson (an Australian) won
it a few years ago and I have to admit my ignorance, but I didn't
even know. But I've learned something about this tournament is
different; you see how excited the players are about the Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Two strokes behind Mallon are Juli Inkster, the defending
champion, and Kellee Booth. Seven players finished at 71, three
strokes behind the leader, including Betsy King, Kelli Kuehne, and
Beth Daniel. All told, 12 players broke par and 10 others are even.
</P>
<P>
   Among local golfers, Carri Wood of Hyannis, Mass., ``was
thrilled and excited'' about her 1-over 73, which tied her for 14th
place. ``I had gone to bed (Wednesday) night hoping for maybe a
75,'' said Wood, a former Massachusetts Amateur champion who
carried her own bag in an Open qualifier that earned her a spot
here.
</P>
<P>
   Wood's score might have been better except her 3-footer for
birdie on the par-5 18th lipped out in the growing darkness and
drizzle. ``It hit a spike mark,'' said Wood, ``but I'll take 1
over. I'm very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   On the disappointing side, Sorenstam, a tourney favorite, shot a
1-over 73. ``It's only Thursday,'' said the Swede. ``There are
three more days of golf. I had a few chances out there with my
putter that I should have made, but other than that I am happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallon's 68 was her lowest opening-round score. And also her
most interesting, especially now that ``my little secret'' on how
to play the 14th hole is out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be interesting to see what happens now,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
