<P>
   TAX STRATEGIES AND DIVORCE, by Tracy Byrnes
</P>
<P>
   The tax implications of divorce spawn loads of issues, including
how to handle alimony payments and what to do with the house.
</P>
<P>
   Alimony payments are deductible to the payer. Child-support
payments are not. Some people paying child support may try to
disguise it as alimony. But if that ``alimony'' ends on a child's
milestone, i.e., his 18th birthday or the day he goes off to
college, the Internal Revenue Service will know that you have been
camouflaging your child support. You will then be required to pay
tax on all that previously deductible money.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of playing games with the IRS to mitigate your tax hit,
consider a divorce settlement trust, also known as an alimony
trust.
</P>
<P>
   Slugged THESTREETCOM-ALIMONY-TRUST-NYTSF
</P>
