<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers)  
 NOTHING IS CERTAIN EXCEPT DEATH, TAXES AND CONGRESSIONAL RACES  
 By CARL HULSE  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   WASHINGTON _ In a new twist on the
old saw, the 2000 congressional campaign is shaping up as a debate
over sickness and taxes.
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Democratic leaders try to position their party as the
champion of Medicare drug coverage, Republicans _ with the help of
some Southern Democrats _ are countering with a string of tax cut
proposals they think will resonate with voters of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just plain wrong for death and marriage to trigger
increased taxes,'' declared Sen. William Roth, the Delaware
Republican who chairs the Finance Committee, after the House and
Senate cut estate taxes and eased the penalty on married couples
who pay more together than they would if they filed separately.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP believes it has backed Democrats into a corner, putting
them in the difficult position of defending higher levies on
families trying to hang on to their inheritance and hard-working
two-income couples.
</P>
<P>
   Many moderate and conservative Southern Democrats are just as
enthusiastic about the tax cuts; a substantial number of the 51
House Democrats who backed the marriage-penalty measure hailed from
the region and five of nine Democratic senators who backed the GOP
on estate taxes were Southerners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fundamental question of fairness,'' said Rep. Mike
McIntyre, D-N.C., about the marriage penalty bill. ``We want to do
everything we can to make sure we are honoring society's most basic
institution. This is one family-friendly way Congress can help
married couples.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bud Cramer, D-Ala., agreed. ``Marriage is not an excuse for
raising more tax revenue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats contend the tax cuts are too expensive and will
benefit mainly the wealthy when most Americans would prefer that
surplus dollars be used to pay down the national debt. Critics tied
the GOP proposals to the Democrat's key issue, saying the money
going for the tax cuts is being siphoned away from a possible
Medicare drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican leadership says, no, we can afford these tax
cuts for the wealthiest 2 percent of families, but we cannot afford
that expensive old Democratic prescription Medicare program that is
going to help seniors not have to choose between eating properly or
taking their medicine properly,'' said Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   DELICATE POSITIONING
</P>
<P>
   It is always a touchy matter when the death of a prominent
politician creates a strategic opening. Potential candidates have
to be sensitive to the community grieving a lost leader while
laying the groundwork in cases where time is of the essence.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty was never more clear than with the passing
Tuesday of Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga. With Democratic Gov. Roy
Barnes expected to quickly name someone to serve a brief four
months before a November special election, those interested in the
post had to quickly make their intentions known but be as
respectful as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Lewis, the Democratic civil rights hero, was among the
first to go public, saying he would gladly accept a Senate
appointment though he noted he was still coming to grips with the
loss of Coverdell. Popular former Gov. Zell Miller, a favorite of
state Democrats, took the route of avoiding quick comment while
others expressed surprise at their names even figuring in the
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's death presents Democrats with a unexpected
opportunity to gain a Senate seat, but they must tread carefully.
An attempt to install a Democrat in a vacant Texas Senate seat in
1993 backfired badly when Election Day rolled around.
</P>
<P>
   SWEET SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   Even Mr. Reform himself isn't strong enough to defeat the sugar
lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, the Arizona Republican who is arguably the
nation's most electrifying political personality at the moment,
tried a new tack in aiming to kill sugar price supports. He
proposed eliminating federal salaries for Agriculture Department
workers who administer the sugar program, effectively scuttling it.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate sugar backers defeated his provision by a wide 65-32
vote, reinforcing recent House action maintaining the controversial
program. Sugar producers were happy about escaping yet another
legislative assault and blamed large sugar users such as candy and
food makers for the persistent attacks.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THOSE PRIORITIES STRAIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Republican insiders are packing for Philadelphia and the
whirlwind of parties, rallies, parades and other glitzy affairs
that will swirl through the Republican National Convention
beginning July 31. But the Alabama delegation obviously knows the
bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   The packed day-by-day calendar of events issued by the state
party carries only one entry for Aug. 4, the day following the
convention: ``Begin campaigning for George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1433EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
