<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDMONSON-COLUMN22-COX     07-21 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDMONSON-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web makes it easy for errors to be perpetuated
 &HT;    By George Edmonson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet might be the greatest communication advance since
the invention of the printing press. It could also be the unrivaled
champion at spreading misinformation.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent highly visible instance involves a group that
gathered about 200 years before e-mail: the signers of the
Declaration of Independence. Several recent columns _ including one
by Ann Landers that ran July 4 in the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
_ recount what supposedly happened to some of these men. Many of
the pieces are riddled with errors, exaggerations and
misinterpretations.
</P>
<P>
   Fact-checking isn't really my intent here. Numerous writers,
many on the Internet, have pointed out mistakes in the material. If
you go to the Web site below, I'll guide you from ajc.com to Web
sites with more information.
</P>
<P>
   I'm also not bashing the Internet. It can be a marvelous tool.
And, in truth, electronic communication isn't a requirement for the
distribution of erroneous material. The scurrilous and widely
disseminated ``Protocols of the Learned Elders of Zion,'' for
instance, managed to promote hatred around the world almost 100
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet does make it easy for errors to be promulgated
and perpetuated. Landers' Wednesday column brought another example.
A reader's letter reprinted something she said she had ``found ...
on the Internet.'' It attributed a ``bill of no rights'' to
Mitchell Kaye, a Republican state representative from Marietta, Ga.
Kaye, incorrectly referred to by Landers as a congressman, didn't
write it. Kaye and the author said they believe the attribution
mistake began some years ago when Kaye forwarded it in an e-mail,
and a recipient thought Kaye had composed it.
</P>
<P>
   What I want to do is raise a red flag, for you as readers and
for us as journalists.
</P>
<P>
   There are two lines that I think every reporter has heard at one
time or another:
</P>
<P>
   ``If your mother says she loves you, check it out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When in doubt, leave it out.''
</P>
<P>
   We forget these at our peril.
</P>
<P>
   Picking material up from the Internet and printing it without
checking is like playing Russian roulette with five loaded
chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is very conducive to the spread of folklore,''
said Timothy Noah, a writer for the Web magazine Slate and author
of several columns on the Declaration mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it gets on the Internet ... there's no stopping it,''
said Lewis Napper, who actually wrote the ``bill of no rights.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of examples I've seen more than once are Adolf Hitler's
supposed remarks on the success of Nazi gun control and the U.S.
government's alleged 26,911-word regulations on the sale of cabbage
(that one's been printed in the Journal-Constitution at least twice
in recent years _ in syndicated writer Donald Lambro's column and
in Q&AMP;A on the News).
</P>
<P>
   Although a Web site traces the stories about the signers of the
Declaration back at least as far as a 1954 Collier's article, it
seems to have been the Internet that provided a boost. Reading
through several of the variations brings to mind the children's
game of telephone, where a tale twists and turns from beginning to
end.
</P>
<P>
   Researcher Richard Hallman helped me look into some of the
statements. I also talked with historians _ what you as a reader
should reasonably expect from anyone planning to publish it.
</P>
<P>
   At the Jamestown-Yorktown Foundation, historian Edward Ayers
noted that scholars can get a reading on the credentials of a book
by noting the publisher, the author's background, legitimate
reviews, the footnotes and sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no filter out there on the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But what draws so many people to what could be called ``junk
history''?
</P>
<P>
   ``People,'' Ayers said, ``like to go for simple ... things that
are easily understood.''
</P>
<P>
   He may be right. But I think that if we get it right, we would,
more often than not, prove the cliche to be true: Truth is stranger
than fiction.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, it's the only thing that belongs in the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   For related Web sites, see www.ajc.com/insideajc
</P>
<P>
   George Edmonson is Public Editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. His e-mail address is gedmonson(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
