<SLUG> BC-OLDERAMERICANS-ACT22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE PANEL APPROVES NEW VERSION OF OLDER AMERICANS ACT
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Senate committee Friday unanimously re-authorized
the Older Americans Act, a program that has provided the elderly
with home and community-based services since 1965.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new bill represents a modernized and streamlined Older
Americans Act, but it also maintains the very programs that have
made the act so important,'' said the bill's co-sponsor, Sen. Mike
DeWine, R-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's new provisions include the National Family Caregiver
Support Program, which will send money to the states to help local
agencies provide information to families about care options, help
set up support groups, provide counseling and respite care to
families caring for older relatives.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes the Nutrition Services Incentives Program,
which will make it easier for some elderly to qualify for
federally-subsidized meals.
</P>
<P>
   First authorized in 1965, the Older Americans Act has provided
such services as home-delivered meals, in-home care, respite care,
and ombudsman programs to the elderly so they can live with
independence and dignity, said the committee's chairman, Jim
Jeffords, R-Vt.
</P>
<P>
   The program has been amended several times since its
introduction in 1965, and the current bill will reauthorize the act
for five years. The bill also authorizes a White House conference
on aging in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1972 we created an elderly national nutrition program, in
1978 we established a separate title in the act for Native
Americans, and in 1987 we established programs to prevent abuse,
neglect, and exploitation of the elderly,'' Jeffords said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we have taken one more step to recognize the needs of
family caregivers because they deserve a helping hand with their
tireless efforts and sacrifices in caring for their parents and
grandparents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Donna E. Shalala, secretary for the Department of Health and
Human Services, said the department is grateful that the bill
included the caregiver support program, which she said ``will help
thousands of family members who are struggling to care for their
older loved ones who are ill or have disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Senate Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions Committee:
www.senate.gov/(tilde)labor
</P>
<P>
   Department of Health and Human Services: www.dhhs.gov
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's email is rodell(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
