<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8843 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-21 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     YOUNG COUPLE CAPITALIZE ON A FRENCH CONNECTION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;     By HARRY SHATTUCK  
 &HT;    
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Maite Costa-Medic is 27, Jean-Michel Poupart 29. And
in Maite's words, ``We are in love.''
</P>
<P>
   In love with each other. And in love with the world.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us share their dream: Pack up one morning, leave all our
worries behind and take off together to explore the unknown, to
immerse ourselves in new cultures and new adventures, to savor
every precious second until our last penny is exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, many of us dream. But for Maite and Jean-Michel, fantasy
became reality.
</P>
<P>
   The young couple's odyssey began last year in Nice, France,
their hometown, where Maite, who has a college degree in foreign
studies, entered a contest sponsored by a government agency. The
objective: Devise a project that promotes tourism in France and
educates residents _ especially children _ about life-styles in
other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Maite's proposal: Visit each of Nice's designated ``sister
cities,'' live with local families and report home through daily
e-mails to elementary schools along with periodic journals,
photographs and follow-up presentations.
</P>
<P>
   Her vision represented well the goals of the sister-cities
program _ an international exchange of people, ideas and cultures
in hopes that these relationships lessen the chance of world
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Maite won first prize. But the challenge was only beginning.
Nice has 26 sister cities, including Houston and Miami, and the
cash award would go only so far. She had to solicit sponsors and
make all arrangements to fit a limited budget.
</P>
<P>
   And it only made sense for Jean-Michel to accompany her. With an
undergraduate degree in journalism and experience as a special
envoy in South Africa, Mexico and the United States, he was
well-equipped to chronicle their adventures. Graduate degrees in
political science and law were assets, and the two spoke five
languages between them.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there was that not-so-insignificant matter of love.
</P>
<P>
   So last Oct. 15, they departed Nice. When they paused in Houston
in late June, Maite and Jean-Michel still were two weeks from
returning home _ and then only for an interlude. During their
travels they stayed one month each in China, Japan, Thailand and
Australia; three weeks in the Philippines, New Zealand and Brazil;
and two weeks in New Caledonia.
</P>
<P>
   They'd spend a week to 10 days in a sister city, then venture to
other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   They had no money for fancy hotels. ``But the families we stayed
with in our sister cities treated us like special guests,'' Maite
said. ``In Japan, we stayed with families the whole month.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Brazil, we lived for one week in an orphanage. It was a
wonderful experience: We speak French and the children speak
Portuguese, but we were able to communicate and share good times.''
</P>
<P>
   As for getting around, Jean-Michel said, ``We walk a lot. And we
ride buses. In the Philippines, we couldn't find room inside, so we
rode on the roof of the bus. We had to lie down when we passed
beneath trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of their favorite experiences were unplanned.
</P>
<P>
   ``One morning in China, we met a man on the street,'' Maite
said, ``and he said, `Would you mind if I spent a day with you and
just practiced my English?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And in New Caledonia, we went to see tortoises, and a man
said, `Have you ever seen sharks?' Before we knew what happened, we
were swimming with the sharks.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bangkok, Maite said, ``We went to the zoo, and after eating a
lot of unusual food on our trip, we were so pleased to see what
looked like French bread for sale. So we bought what we thought was
a brioche and started eating it. Everyone kept staring at us, and
we couldn't understand why. Afterward, we found out that the bread
was only to feed the animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tasted good, though.''
</P>
<P>
   The only real mishap occurred in Brisbane, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a bag stolen,'' Maite said. ``All our pictures were
inside. It was sad. But we've been quite lucky. Before we left, ]gy
</P>
</TEXT>
