<HEADER>
A8848 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-GRAHAMVP-NAT     07-21 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-GRAHAMVP-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        GRAHAM: VEEP SHOULD BE ACTIVIST
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Anand Giridharadas  
 &HT;    c. 2000 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (July 21) - If Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., eventually
lands the job of vice president, this much is clear: the veteran
lawmaker will be no potted plant.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Graham refuses to wade into mounting media
speculation that he might soon become Vice President Al Gore's
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   But in a brief interview on Capitol Hill today, Graham said he
views the vice presidency as a platform for action. The office has
evolved in the last 50 years, he said, leaving the veep not so much
a patient understudy as an architect of his own political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``The office has undergone significant change in the last
half-century,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Vice President Harry Truman took the White House reins upon
Franklin D. Roosevelt's death, he was famously unaware of his
surroundings, Graham noted. An aide is said to have told Truman to
snap out of his daze and act presidential.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Graham said, the vice president has increasingly
taken on more responsibilities - and also grown more privvy to all
the information, intelligence and strategizing floating around the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The modern vice presidency is characterized by access,
openness and respect,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   He said admiringly that Gore had taken the level of awareness
and action to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice President Gore pushed it forward by being given a series
of specific responsibilities,'' he said, pointing to Gore's role in
U.S.-Russian relations, government reinvention and technology
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he painted a picture of the vice president as an
informed activist with his own set of duties, Graham declined to
offer any insight into his own priorities, if chosen, or to
speculate about his chances.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about a New York Times report yesterday that
President Clinton has been plugging Graham for veep among close
friends, the senator only said it was ``flattering.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't answer that,'' he said repeatedly, when the
questions got more personal.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
