<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8849 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-CREOLE-TRAIL-INFO-HNS     07-21 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREOLE-TRAIL-INFO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;     NAVIGATING THE CREOLE NATURE TRAIL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;     By MARTY RACINE  
 &HT;    
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you go: Creole Nature Trail National Scenic Byway
</P>
<P>
   Getting around: Driving the Creole Nature Trail's loop from
Sulphur, take Louisiana 27 south (Exit 20 off I-10) to Holly Beach,
then east to Creole, then north toward Lake Charles. An alternate
approach to Lake Charles is via Louisiana highways 384 and 385.
Eastern and western spurs jut from the loop along Louisiana 82.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: The Sabine National Wildlife Refuge visitor center
is located south of Sulphur along Louisiana 27, which passes
through 10 miles of the refuge's eastern edge. The visitor center
is open 7 a.m.-4 p.m. weekdays and noon-4 p.m. weekends. A
11/2-mile walking trail is about four miles south of the visitor
center and also along the scenic byway. Alligators often are
sighted in the area, especially during warmer months. Call
337-762-3816 for information; inquire about usage fees.
</P>
<P>
   The 84,000-acre Rockefeller State Wildlife Refuge is located at
the eastern terminus of the trail. The East End Boat Launch is
accessible for fishing and boating from sunrise to sunset between
March 1 and Dec.
</P>
<P>
   1; a fishing or hunting license or a ``Wild Louisiana'' stamp
(available for $5 at convenience stores) is required. Call
337-538-2276.
</P>
<P>
   The 9,621-acre Cameron Prairie National Wildlife Refuge is
located along Louisiana 27 between Holmwood and Creole. The visitor
center is open 7:30 a.m.-4 p.m. Mondays-Fridays and 10 a.m.-4 p.m.
Saturdays. Call 337-598-2216; inquire about usage fees.
</P>
<P>
   Although not directly on the Creole Nature Trail loop, the
35,000-acre Lacassine National Wildlife Refuge - at the edge of
Grand Lake and about 15 miles from the Gulf of Mexico - makes an
easy side trip. The dominant feature is Lacassine Pool, created by
enclosing a 16,000-acre marsh with a low levee. Up to 800,000 ducks
and geese have been observed here. The refuge office, at the end of
Highway 3056, is open 7 a.m.-3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   daily; some portions of the refuge are open from one hour before
sunrise to one hour after sunset. Call 337-774-5926.
</P>
<P>
   The Holleyman, Sheely and Henshaw Bird Sanctuaries are located
near the western terminus of the nature trail along Louisiana 82.
They are open daily. More than 2 billion birds use these
sanctuaries each year; for human visitors, much of the area is
accessible only by boat. A ``Wild Louisiana'' stamp is required to
bird-watch, bike, picnic or camp.
</P>
<P>
   The Imperial Calcasieu Museum, on the scenic byway at 204 W.
Sallier in Lake Charles, occupies the homesite of Charles Sallier,
an early settler for whom Lake Charles is named. Exhibits include
original Audubon bird and animal prints, an early-1900s barber shop
and an antique apothecary collection. Hours are noon-5 p.m.
Tuesdays-Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $1; 50 cents for children. Call 337-439-3797.
</P>
<P>
   The Brimstone Historical Society Museum, located at Frasch Park
in Sulphur, commemorates the American sulfur industry. Hours are
9:30 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Fridays. Call 337-527-7142.
</P>
<P>
   Additional resources: The Southwest Louisiana Lake Charles
Convention and Visitors Bureau can provide information not only on
the Creole Nature Trail but on other area attractions (including
casinos, lodging and dining). Call 800-456-7952 or 337-436-9588.
Access www.visitlakecharles.org on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For comprehensive information about the Creole Nature Trail on
the Internet, access www.byways.org and search by state. This site
also contains details about other scenic routes nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   For tourism information about all of Louisiana, call
800-633-6970 or access on the Web www.louisianatravel.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8852 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-CREOLE-TRAIL-3TAKES-H     07-21 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREOLE-TRAIL-3TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     CREOLE TRAIL OFFERS SAMPLING OF CULTURE, NATURE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (With: CREOLE-TRAIL-SIDE)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;     By MARTY RACINE  
 &HT;    
 &HT;     c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE CHARLES, La. _ The Creole Nature Trail, which loops through
Calcasieu and Cameron parishes of southwest Louisiana, is more
Nature than Creole. For culture, the first designated National
Scenic Byway on the Gulf Coast is a sampler.
</P>
<P>
   The region is part Cajun, but not the heart of Acadiana. It is
Creole, but not the cradle of zydeco. It's the Old South, yet not
plantation country.
</P>
<P>
   The natural world laps at the roadside from marshes, canals,
beaches, lakes, piney woods and prairies. Their mysteries and
subtleties can be gleaned at three public wildlife refuges and a
bird-and-butterfly sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of the Nature Trail is a 100-mile U-shaped loop that
begins in Sulphur and ends in Lake Charles. Eastern and western
spurs that jut from the southern corners near the Gulf of Mexico
increase the trail's length to 180 miles, but some travelers may
find them to be too out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Those accustomed to panoramic horizons can breeze the 100-mile
loop in mere hours. Other than the wildlife centers, there are no
official rest stations or learning centers to distract you. Only a
handful of small towns beg your pause. You can drive the route
visiting two refuges in a not-so-hectic day trip.
</P>
<P>
   By slowing down, however, you begin to absorb the rhythms of
this watery tableau. Take three days, and fleeting impressions will
spin into focus, clarifying a land and its people.
</P>
<P>
   WEST LOOP: ``They won't bother you. He's just swimming around.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading south from Sulphur on Louisiana 27, the coastal prairie
frays into the marshland at the Cameron Parish line. Sunlight
shatters and refracts on backwaters sunk into the horizon. Leon
Redbone is drawling Up the Lazy River on the car radio.
</P>
<P>
   This is the outback; elevation: pretty darn low.
</P>
<P>
   In the roadside canal, or ``road ditch,'' Hilton and Mabel Boyer
(Boy-AY) of Lafayette are crabbing the afternoon away. Using fresh
shrimp as bait, they've almost filled a bucket with blue crabs.
</P>
<P>
   In season the Boyers also catch catfish, gar, flounder, speckled
trout and reds in these waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you what, we do like fish,'' Hilton says. ``Seafood is
healthy for a person.''
</P>
<P>
   One weekend an alligator jumped on this bank and snacked
impolitely on the Boyers' nice picnic basket of chicken legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opened its mouth that big,'' Mabel says, eyes wide, arms
spread. ``Big one like this, you think it never come on the ground,
but they can do it fast and catch a bite. Ooh-wee.''
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, by Second Bayou Bridge, Moses Taylor of Lake
Charles points out a gator lurking near the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't bother you,'' he says casually, as if it were a
common yard lizard. ``He's just swimming around.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is here to catch shrimp. He uses a cast (or throw) net
legally not exceeding 6 feet. When tossed, it opens like a
parachute.
</P>
<P>
   The legal limit is 5 gallons, or 25 pounds, and in the
capricious cycle of shrimping, this is a good year, he says. ``They
runnin' good.''
</P>
<P>
   Over a drought-stricken region where even the water is thirsty,
the air grows dense and scuds over the lowlands in ragged, metallic
clouds. Now it's rising, releasing a warm, healing rain. Shrimpers
scattered along the canal are too preoccupied to pay heed.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is the Sabine National Wildlife Refuge, established in
1937 to preserve a stretch of coastal wetlands for wintering and
migrating waterfowl from the Mississippi and Central flyways. This
marshland is huge, linking Calcasieu Lake on the east with Sabine
Lake at the Texas border.
</P>
<P>
   Marshland is formed by impenetrable clay soils that keep water
from draining. In a setting where changes in elevation are measured
in inches, a marsh is slightly lower than the surrounding prairie.
A 1.5-mile walkway penetrates the marsh, but in warm weather beware
of mosquitoes and dive-bombing deerflies. Wear long sleeves and
pants or slather on the people's choice: Avon Skin So Soft.
</P>
<P>
   The reward is in seeing turtles, rabbits, muskrat, nutria,
raccoons and, in season, any of 250 species of birds. And leash
your dog, for gators love a picnic.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH LOOP: ``You put a little roux in there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ooh wee, they had a racket last week,'' Mabel Hilton had said
of Holly Beach on Memorial Day weekend. ``All day. All night. They
play that boom-boom music, the kids, they had big stereos in the
back of their trucks. Those windows were shaking, hmmm, hmmm.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this weekend should be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   On a hung-over Sunday morning the kids are already blasting
boom-boom music, firing up barbecue grills and drinking beer.
</P>
<P>
   Bumper sticker: ``Work is for people who can't fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Holly Beach is a salty, unincorporated enclave of weathered
shacks, rusted trailers and crooked cabins on a milelong grid of
narrow streets.
</P>
<P>
   The speed limit is 15 mph, like driving in a permanent school
zone. Like being in your own movie. This is the edge of America and
thus it feels; Key West should be so rustic.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's patrols are visible, but the ambience is basically
self-regulated, the locals say, by a simple code: Don't act stupid.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
