<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8856 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-CREOLE-TRAIL-1STADD-H     07-21 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREOLE-TRAIL-1STADD-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; LAKE CHARLES, La.: x x x act stupid. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And no glass on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Decorum is ensured by the stability of old-line families, many
of them Cajun.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come here with families to relax, let their kids swim,
catch crabs,'' says Elrick Taylor, who owns the Holly Beach Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Elrick and his wife, Betty, hail from near Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born a Cajun; I'm gonna die a Cajun,'' he says. ``I'm
proud of it.
</P>
<P>
   We enjoy living. If you don't stop and smell the roses, what's
it worth to you? I hope one day I get rich, but if I don't I know
I've lived a good life.''
</P>
<P>
   When they were raising five children, Holly Beach was the only
vacation the Taylors could afford. Then they dreamed: Let's buy a
business and not leave. Ten years ago Elrick kissed his insurance
career goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Summer is the busy season. Winter brings oil workers.
Regardless, Holly Beach is hardly the Cajun Riviera, as it so
claimed before an annual festival of that name went broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like it did 40, 50 years ago,'' Taylor says.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor leans back in the morning shade; Cajun tunes squawk on
with fiddle and accordion over the speaker. Not much to do; no
one's checking in at this point. In the afternoon he'll follow the
shadows across the street to Edward and Linda Hebert's fixit
garage, where they'll chat up fishing and such and pass comment on
the flesh-baring, lobster-red beach crowd lugging 12-packs out of
the T&AMP;T Market.
</P>
<P>
   The Heberts (AY-bears) met long ago at a dance at the Four
Corner Bar, now closed. He fished for a living and paved county
roads with oyster shells. Then they opened a gas station. Today
they'll sell you a part or fix a flat. Mostly, they sit.
</P>
<P>
   Their sons are commercial fishermen, but a ban on gill netting,
supported by sportsmen claiming overfished waters, has hurt, Taylor
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame what they done to the fisherman. They don't
realize how many lives they're affecting. You used to be able to
catch thousands of pounds of flounder, sell that for $2 a pound.
You could make some money.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heberts fish for food, and Linda's ``gar balls,'' fashioned
from the maligned garfish, are legendary around here. This, she
says, is the secret:``You take your fish, and you grind it up. I
use boiled potatoes; some people use bread. They have to be real
potatoes, not that instant kind.
</P>
<P>
   You mix that up in there with that fish with all your
seasonings, onions, bell peppers, celery, salt and pepper. You mix
it up real good, and you form yourself a little patty, like a
meatball, and you mash it flat, not too flat, about that thick, and
fry it in hot grease.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, ``You make a tomato gravy. You smother your tomatoes down,
and you put a little roux in there to thicken your gravy, with your
onions and parsley and green onions and celery and bell peppers.
And then you mix that with your seasoning, and then you drop your
little patties of fish in there, and you put that on rice.''
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon the barbecues are snuffed and the Sunday exodus
is on.
</P>
<P>
   Several blocks from the carefree, sunshiny beach is the Daiquiri
Days' Bar &AMP; Grill, a Confederate emblem in front. Inside it is
dark, and two men sit over beers. Tom is 47, Herman 51. They are
angry. Politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers. Blacks. Taxes. Government.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daddy told me when I was a young kid that in my lifetime
I'll see another Civil War,'' Herman says. ``I believe it's headed
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we're gonna have a revolution,'' Tom replies. ``It's
comin'.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It better hurry up and happen, I'm getting a little older all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Late afternoon, only ghosts and oldtimers remain in Holly Beach.
In shadow's length the Gulf looks muddy - swollen with silt, locals
claim, by dredging 10 miles up the coast by the Army Corps of
Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   No one here is very proud of that water.
</P>
<P>
   Pyramids of slimy seaweed raked from the surf line the beach
like rusted sculptures. A lone vehicle trolls for parties past,
leaving tread marks in the sand. Empty beer cans glint off the
crimson sunset. A soft breeze skates in off the sea. A black alley
cat pads under the vapor lights of Porpoise Avenue, poking for
skeletons from the deep.
</P>
<P>
   Another sundown, another weekend gone.
</P>
<P>
   EASTERN SPUR:``We're destroying what was an abundant way of
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The air smells like boiled cabbage on the approach to the
Cameron Ferry that crosses the Calcasieu Ship Channel. Dark columns
discharge from the Omega Protein plant.
</P>
<P>
   Sign at the ferry landing: ``Trucks hauling flammables must
cross separately.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many outsiders speak fondly of industrial Cameron, but there
are reasons to stop. Fresh- and saltwater fishing abound, and
deep-sea charters may be arranged. The Cameron courthouse dates
from 1937, and its walls whisper of the time in 1957 when it
sheltered hundreds from Audrey, the last direct hurricane.
Historical homes grace some neighborhoods, and on Monkey Island,
the dead from both sides lay buried as a result of an 1864 Civil
War naval battle.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve miles east you can veer left to Lake Charles or head
straight out a lonely spur to the Vermilion Parish line. Straddling
a chenier plain, a sandy, tree-covered ridge paralleling the coast,
Louisiana 82 ducks under moss-covered trees toward the Rockefeller
State Wildlife Refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Sabine and Cameron Prairie refuges, Rockefeller is a
``scientific site.'' A small visitor center at the refuge office is
open year-round, and a boat launch is open March 1-Dec. 1 for
fishing, crabbing and alligator sightings.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby Grand Chenier is basically a grocery, and inside you
might come across lifelong resident Teddy Broussard.
</P>
<P>
   Broussard, 53, is not overly optimistic about southern Cameron
Parish.
</P>
<P>
   The economy is stagnant, still top-heavy in oil and fishing. The
freshwater marshes are messed up, contaminated, he asserts, by Lake
Charles processing and chemical plants and by saltwater flowing
inland from the ship channel. Salt kills plants, eroding the soil
and transforming fertile marshes into open water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a lot of silting problems, a lot of salinity,
things that normally would be as God created it and would take care
of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   But the environment can't repair itself, he says, due to
over-engineering. Ship channels, dredging, weirs, levees and
impoundments have remade the coastline in the government's image.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ...... MORE)
</P>
