<HEADER>
A8860 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-CREOLE-TRAIL-2NDADD-H     07-21 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREOLE-TRAIL-2NDADD-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; LAKE CHARLES, La.: x x x government's image. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Agencies like your FEMA, your Corps of Engineers, you don't
have much use of your land no more. You would think it's more or
less communistic.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of people here who cannot afford to comply with
such stringent rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will give up, sell the property to the government.
We'll end up being a federal sanctuary.''
</P>
<P>
   Broussard shakes his head at the memory of open trapping,
hunting and fishing, of unlimited access to resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're slowly destroying what was an abundant way of life. If
something isn't done in the very near future we're gonna lose what
we got.''
</P>
<P>
   EAST LOOP: ``Them mosquitoes eat you alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Northbound on Louisiana 27 from Creole, the Intracoastal
Waterway Bridge has a bird's-eye view of marshland lapping the
prairie, as if the waterway divided a neighborhood in half.
</P>
<P>
   Just beyond the bridge is Cameron Prairie National Wildlife
Refuge, a birder's paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Waterfowl and raptors migrate from the north to spend the winter
here.
</P>
<P>
   In May, roseate spoonbills and egrets begin nesting. Tropical
birds arrive for the summer from the Caribbean. Shorebirds are
abundant on the mud flats in late summer, and in the fall
blue-winged teal populations are peaking.
</P>
<P>
   A footbridge over a moat near the visitor center offers, in
season, an opportunity to see gators. Not exactly in the wild, but
a gator's a gator. Inside the center are displays detailing the
region's ecology and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Toward Lake Charles it's cattle and rice country, though sugar
cane, called the ``lazy man's crop'' because it can't be rotated,
has moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar is cheap. Doesn't make a man money.
</P>
<P>
   It is Saturday morning at the Holmwood Grocery _ the sign says
``Beer, Boudin and Cold Worms'' - and in front a young lady is
tending the register. The men are around the corner, in the back
where the bar happens to be, discussing the day's fishing
expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam got him a case of beer. Barry got a case of beer. Shep got
a case of beer. Let's see, Aaron got a case; Barry's girlfriend got
a 12-pack; and Billy Joe got half a keg of beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody hoots.
</P>
<P>
   The grocery has been in the Natali family for two generations.
In segregation days the barroom was divided in half by a wall.
Blacks used the other side, says Entienne ``Jackie'' Lognion, 66.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could only see 'em through that mirror (over the backbar).
You wanted to talk to one of the blacks, you had to talk through
the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all friendly. We'd buy liquor and go sit outside and
drink with 'em. It's hard to hate somebody you work side by side
all day long with. He's human. Got a heart just like us. You needed
help, shoot, about six of 'em would give you a hand. Best people in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the bar Steve Natali, groggy from allergy medication,
rests his head on the counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the hives,'' he manages. Tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah right, tomatoes, somebody retorts. ``It's the fish. He ate
40 pieces of fish last night. No wonder you breakin' out.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he did cook four batches, Natali acknowledges. ``Everybody
was outside; all of a sudden, just out of the blue, boy, the
mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Them mosquitoes were so little you couldn't see 'em on your leg.
Eat you alive. I tell you what, I'm fryin' a lot of them with my
french fries.''
</P>
<P>
   Get some Cajuns in a bar and soon enough they're talking food.
They'll rhapsodize over butter pickles like they were communion
wafers. Bologna? Filet mignon. ``He starts slicing that bologna;
you get them big onions, goes to slicing them onions ... that man
was happy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lemme tell ya,'' the fellow in the corner says, ``there's two
things he likes _ watermelon and boiled crabs. I say `likes,' but
he'll whip your butt for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Already in May the gardens are producing. Lognion shows off a
cucumber the size of a football.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a squash,'' one of the men says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a squash; that's a cucumber. Cross my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Piggly Wiggly's got boudin,'' someone announces.
</P>
<P>
   Lognion turns to a visitor. ``They make (boudin) all over around
here.
</P>
<P>
   But order it spicy. Down here in southern Louisiana, if it ain't
spicy, people don't mess with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Natali, back among the living, is talking mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love mushrooms in my gumbo. Take some of those portobello
mushrooms, slice a big ol' bunch of 'em, put 'em in with a little
butter. Smother 'em. Unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to pick them pink ones,'' Lognion advises.
``You get a high. You won't remember nothin'. But them kids, after
a rain, they go to the piney woods and get 'em for dope, boil 'em,
drink that juice, put your lights out. One kid died from it; that
fad there kinda changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lognion's father farmed rice, and during the Depression the
grain kept his family alive. Jackie eats it almost every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get some gravy, you know, gosh darn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't eat rice,'' the man seated beside him confesses. ``I
hauled so much rice, I'm mad at it. You don't need rice to eat
gumbo.''
</P>
<P>
   Say what? Did I hear you straight? Jackie wants to know. ``Me, I
got to have rice in that gumbo ...''
</P>
</TEXT>
