<SLUG> BC-TEENS-JOBS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENS WITHOUT SUMMER JOBS ARE MISSING OUT ON LESSONS OF LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NORMA J. SHATTUCK  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Freed from the classroom, record numbers of
teenagers are blowing off the old American tradition of taking a
menial summer job.
</P>
<P>
   A Georgetown University junior was quoted in an Associated Press
article as saying: ``I know it sounds arrogant, but my time is
worth more than $8 or $10 an hour . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Indulgent, affluent parents are backing their kids' choices to
be summertime sloths. Other teenagers may deign to take jobs, the
AP article said. But ``not in low-paid and mind-numbing wage
slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   In my late teens and early 20s, I too felt deserving of
dignified, rarified summer employment. Still, I found myself
punching time clocks as a low-paid serf yearning to breathe free
from the ``mind-numbing'' toil at which privileged kids now sneer.
</P>
<P>
   My unhappily employed status stemmed from having admirable
parents. They had prevailed by sweat and strong wills over the
starkness of the Depression and the stresses and dislocations of
World War II. Their four-letter word of choice was w-o-r-k.
</P>
<P>
   My string of jobs had one common factor: a high DQ (Dreariness
Quotient). One was a clerical stint in the stuffy attic of a
neighborhood pharmacy. Fellow toilers in what I saw as a distinctly
Dickensian setting were two aged women _ the firm's bookkeeper and
her assistant, who chain-smoked and rasped out frequent bulletins
on her iffy state of health.
</P>
<P>
   The bookkeeper _ when taking a break from pounding a formidable
looking business machine called a comptometer _ sometimes recounted
anecdotes about her days as a flapper. During her flaming youth,
she confided, she'd been ``a dancin' fool!''
</P>
<P>
   If I closed my eyes, I could imagine Bob Cratchit hovering
nearby, nodding merrily.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, I'd taken this attic serf position (and a cut in pay) to
escape the multiple miseries of two previous summers working the
swing shift at a fruit cannery. It was a noisy, ear-offending place
where overhead tracks moved lines of clinking, rattling cans to be
filled with peaches, pears or fruit cocktail.
</P>
<P>
   I proved poorly qualified. Sorting fruit at a conveyor belt made
me nauseated (a form of motion sickness) while my brief stint
overseeing the bubblings and burpings of an enormous tomato paste
pot left me as red-splattered as a casualty carted into an
emergency room. I had, oddly, never been told what to do if the vat
threatened to erupt.
</P>
<P>
   A less stressful assignment _ to the maraschino cherry position
of the fruit-cocktail line _ proved to mesh perfectly with my skill
level.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside pear, peach, and seedless grapes serfs, I
settled into the routine of measuring out exactly 24 neon-bright
cherries and tossing them into half-gallon cans. We prayed for
equipment failure, because that allowed us _ mainly students and
purse-poor young teachers _ to talk without screaming and to share
common feelings of summer forlornness.
</P>
<P>
   Following long, tedious weeks at such jobs (it helped to think
of them as equivalent to Dickens' blacking factory ordeal) another
trial awaited. Tan-challenged and bereft of vacation chatter, I
returned to a campus that seemed awash in toasty-brown goddesses.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, my self-esteem suffered until I adopted a
psychological strategy. I'd imagine some glossy sorority girl as
the babbling wreck she'd have been after a swing-shift of watching
tomato paste boil.
</P>
<P>
   The AP article suggests that summer job shirkers may be `` . . .
missing out on what some consider a hallowed American coming-of-age
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it never occurred to me at the time, I know today that my
humble toil taught me lessons in, well, knowing how humble I truly
was.
</P>
<P>
   At every job site, others had skills and know-how that told me I
wasn't such a whiz once I left the classroom. What better lesson
could we wish for the legions of over-indulged youth in Year 2000?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Norma J. Shattuck is a San Francisco Bay area writer and
editor.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
