</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOICESTREAM-DEUTSCHE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG TYCOON SPINS LITTLE-KNOWN TELECOM VENTURES INTO GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Hong Kong, Germany, Britain, Wash.)  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ For years, Li Ka-shing has foraged in the darker
corners of the telecommunications industry: a paging service in
Australia, an upstart mobile-phone operation in Britain, a
little-known provider of personal communications services in
Bellevue, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Now that last company, VoiceStream Wireless, is weighing a $53
billion takeover bid from Deutsche Telekom. And Li, a Hong Kong
multibillionaire for whom the phrase Midas-touch seems almost
inadequate, may have found gold in another dark corner.
</P>
<P>
   If Deutsche Telekom acquires VoiceStream for the price being
floated _ a very big if _ the 23 percent stake owned by Li's
company, Hutchison Whampoa Ltd., would be worth nearly $12 billion.
That is 10 times the $1.2 billion Hutchison has invested in
VoiceStream since late-1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely amazing,'' said Sanjeet Devgan, the head of
Hong Kong research at Prudential-Bache Securities. ``But this
management team has done it time and again.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Li reaped a $22 billion profit when Hutchison
sold its British mobile-phone company, Orange, to Mannesmann of
Germany _ then watched as Britain's Vodafone AirTouch waged and won
history's largest takeover battle for Mannesmann.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts criticized Li for the Orange and VoiceStream
investments, saying the price of entry was high and the technology
unproven. But in both cases, Li correctly foretold the market.
Hutchison wound up owning assets the titans of the
telecommunications industry felt they could not live without.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're comfortable taking calculated risks in industries they
understand,'' said Tim Dattels, the head of investment banking in
Asia for Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., who has advised Li on several deals.
``They make very quick decisions, and they're not sentimental about
selling assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike AT&AMP;T, Vodafone or Deutsche Telekom, Hutchison does not
aspire to build a global telecommunications empire. It is driven to
wring the highest returns from its investments in the least amount
of time. If Deutsche Telekom were to buy out Hutchison's stake in
VoiceStream, analysts said Li would happily forsake the U.S. market
after less than three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their strategy is to buy early, build the network to a certain
extent and, when the market values are peaking, sell out,'' Devgan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts cautioned that Deutsche Telekom's bid for VoiceStream
could founder for several reasons, not least cold feet on the part
of the German company's board. But if the deal unravels, the giant
Japanese mobile phone operator, NTT DoCoMo, is said to be
contemplating an offer.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As in the Mannesmann-Vodafone battle, Li's hand will weigh
heavily on the scales. In addition to its 23 percent stake,
Hutchison has five directors on VoiceStream's board.
</P>
<P>
   Devgan calculated that Deutsche Telekom's offer would value
VoiceStream at more than $15,000 per subscriber. That compares with
the $10,000 per subscriber that Hutchison got for Orange. And it is
more than double the per-subscriber valuations of most publicly
traded mobile phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Li, 71, emigrated to Hong Kong from neighboring Guangdong
Province in the 1950s and got his start selling plastic flowers. Li
soon graduated to property development, and in 1980, he made a run
at Hutchison Whampoa. It was a milestone: Li was the first Chinese
businessman to control one of the great colonial hongs, or trading
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Li did not change the wheeler-dealer culture of Hutchison _ only
its scale and geography. Where once Hutchison ran docks and ships
in this former British colony, it now runs ports in the Panama
Canal, an oil company in Canada and mobile-phone networks in Europe
and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Hutchison paid $6.7 billion for a license to offer
next-generation cellular services in Britain. Analysts shook their
heads at the lofty price-tag. But a few months later, the company
recouped more than half its investment by selling a 35 percent
stake in its European mobile venture for $3.15 billion to NTT
DoCoMo and Royal KPN, the Dutch mobile phone operator.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison's goal of offering Europe-wide mobile service will not
be cheap. The European subsidiary, Hutchison 3G, must obtain
licenses in Germany, France and Belgium, in addition to building
the network. Analysts estimate that Hutchison's share of the costs
could reach $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may lead to their downfall, because they are getting
carried away bidding for 3G licenses in Europe,'' said one analyst,
who, like most here, requested anonymity when commenting on
Hutchison.
</P>
<P>
   Li's recent European deal bore another hallmark of his operating
style: the use of partners to spread risk and provide an exit
strategy. In the case of VoiceStream Wireless, people who know Li
said he was attracted by the company's founder and chief executive,
John Stanton.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Stanton, who helped start McCaw Cellular, built VoiceStream by
stitching together wireless licenses and buying his two principal
rivals, Aerial and Omnipoint. It was a hard slog; cellular stocks,
particularly those of personal communications services companies,
were languishing.
</P>
<P>
   One day two years ago, Stanton traveled to Calgary, Alberta, to
meet with Li's chief deputy, Canning Fok, and discuss Hutchison's
investment in VoiceStream. People who recall the meeting said
VoiceStream's stock hit an all-time low that day. But Fok was
undeterred. Hutchison had invested millions of dollars, and endured
heavy losses, before Orange turned a corner in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Today, VoiceStream is an alluring prospect to globally minded
telephone companies like Deutsche Telekom. It is one of the few
independent cellular operators in the United States. And its
digital network uses GSM technology, which is compatible with the
network operated by Deutsche Telekom in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, another German company needed a similar wireless
asset to fulfill its ambitions. That company, Mannesmann, paid Li
$14 billion for Hutchison's controlling stake in Orange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
