<HEADER>
A8869 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-21 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE ARE TOUGH TIMES TO BE A LIBERAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What an embarrassment it is to be a liberal
sometimes. Not only do you have to spend your time worrying about
endangered bugs, genetically altered cornflakes and cops playing
kick the can with carjackers, but you have to listen to some odd
ideas and the most unnatural language.
</P>
<P>
   Homicides are up 29 percent this year so far in Jerry Brown's
fair city of Oakland. A police spokesman was quoted as saying of
the increase, ``It's not gang-related, it's not dope-related. We
still have some narcotics-involved homicides, but the majority has
to do with just plain anger management.''
</P>
<P>
   Murder as bad anger management. That's like describing the
failure of a $100 million anti-missile system as a ``glitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland police gave some examples of badly managed anger. In one
case, a 75-year-old man shot his wife to death during an argument
in their home, and in another case a man shot another man dead
because he spilled beer on his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Blow someone to kingdom come because his Budweiser dampened your
loafers? I'd say that's worthy of a lifetime scholarship to the
graduate school of anger management at Folsom U.
</P>
<P>
   Please bring closure to the field of anger management. And all
you cops, please peer-counsel fellow officers so they'll stop
talking like that, and just kick the bejeezus out of us instead.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then, as a liberal, you have to believe in the most curious
solution to gun violence: When guns are locked up, you won't have
to lock up criminals.
</P>
<P>
   On July 29, cops and volunteers will go through East Oakland
knocking on doors (gingerly, I hope) and offering tips on anger
management and peer counseling, as well as giving away gun locks in
hopes that the five seconds it takes to unlock the gun will be
enough time to cool off and say, ``So what's a little beer on my
shoes?''
</P>
<P>
   Is the kind of person who might shoot someone over spilled beer
going to put a lock on his gun in the first place? I'd say this is
a case of poor brain management on the part of the Oakland P.D.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, for the days when liberals didn't have to believe in stuff
like this, and liberals like Harry Truman gave people hell instead
of managing it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As good liberals we're never supposed to manage our anger toward
tobacco companies. We're supposed to cheer when a Florida jury pins
$145 billion in damages on cigarette makers to punish them for
marketing a defective product.
</P>
<P>
   What's defective about it? Cigarettes do exactly what they're
supposed to do: give people a good smoke, a bit of relaxation, a
cool image in some circles and a hell of an addiction.
</P>
<P>
   We all know that's what they're designed to do, and they do it
very well.
</P>
<P>
   You might as well call lawyers defective because they earn
millions of dollars convincing jurors that the big bad tobacco
companies made smokers ignore all those surgeon general's warnings
and poison themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Well, bad example. Lawyers are a defective product. The Florida
tobacco verdict will be under appeal longer than any kid now taking
up cigarettes will live.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the tobacco companies have a history of lying,
manipulation and fooling young people into doing things that are
bad for their health. But so has the U.S. government, whenever it
has decided to commit troops to dubious interventions.
</P>
<P>
   You can't even get the government to pay money to those who
fought good fights they didn't choose, like veterans of Bataan. But
the government and trial lawyers are happy to give millions to
those who voluntarily took up a habit they knew wasn't good for
them.
</P>
<P>
   Risk and reward are a little out of whack, especially since
lawyers get an inordinate amount of the action from class-action
suits.
</P>
<P>
   Liberalism is dead in legislatures, but lives in perverse form
in the law. It has nothing to do with freedom or the autonomy of
the individual, unless that individual is a lawyer out to make big
bucks from a big business.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What happens if I get colon cancer from eating meat? Should I
sue Iowa Beef? What happens if I get cirrhosis of the liver from
drinking beer? (Instead of getting shot for spilling it on the
wrong guy's footwear.) Should I sue Anheuser-Busch?
</P>
<P>
   What happens if I suffer second-hand SUV poisoning by rolling
over my other car in the driveway? Should I sue Land Rover?
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, beef, beer and big vehicles will be banned by the
righteous, but go ahead and enjoy them, even though you know
they're hazardous to the health. But for now the answer to all of
the above questions is to get on the phone to a lawyer, because
individuals apparently are not responsible for their own choices
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   And if the phone is a cell phone that causes brain cancer, make
another call to another lawyer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
