<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTN: Style and Leisure Editors: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, July 23, and thereafter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX-ABSTINENCE (Undated) _ In a culture saturated with sexual
messages, where consenting adults seem to hop into bed at the bat
of a feathery eyelash, a small minority are willfully dropping out
of the game. Calling themselves ``born-again virgins,'' they
embrace abstinence not so much on moral or religious grounds, but
to cleanse themselves and reassert self-control. By Ruth La Ferla.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   KINA-PROFILE (New York) _ The hot new pop star Kina has the
boundless, often angry energy of a young Tina Turner, and the same
never-ending legs, planted wide in a prizefighter's stance. She
wears her hair in a blond-dyed, Afro and wears like skintight red
leather pants and stiletto heels. A gut-bucket soul singer with the
attitude and style of a rock star, she is the latest of a recent
wave of African-American women to break from the rigid formula of
contemporary R&AMP;B. By Douglas Century. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-ROMANCES (Undated) _ Yes, I have had seductive e-mail
relationships with men. But I never got in over my head until I
started e-mailing old boyfriends. Suddenly, I had Internet
relationships with two men simultaneously, both of them former
lovers I found on the Web. With one, I was like a frisky Doris Day.
With the other, I was Catherine Deneuve. With both of them, I was
in trouble. By Linda Lee.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-FLATTERY (Undated) _ A look at the pervasiveness of
flattery in the fashion business _ it is coin of the realm _ and
its remarkable, necessary plasticity. ``The E mores of the fashion
industry were taken from 18th-century Versailles,'' Simon Doonan
was saying. ``It's a structure that's complicated by the fact that
everyone in it is terrified of losing advertising _ the sword of
Damocles. So fragility and fear are driving this need, these
conventions.'' By Penelope Green.
</P>
<P>
   ESZTERHAS-RHAPSODY (New York) _ George W. was getting into full
stride and pulling some pretty decent laughs. Bill Clinton was
making some comic headway explaining the cosmic unfairness of the
whole Monica thing. (``A little reward. Just a little reward. A
piece of angel food cake to recharge my batteries.'') Monica told
all, once again, to Linda Tripp. And Joe Eszterhas, sitting front
row center at the Douglas Fairbanks Theater, listening to the words
of his ``American Rhapsody'' wash over him, expertly delivered by
seven actors, looked like a happy man. By William Grimes.
</P>
