<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-LIBEL-LAW-2TA     07-21 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-LIBEL-LAW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBEL SUITS FLOURISH IS PLAINTIFF-FRIENDLY BRITAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Ideas)  
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When she first heard about it, Deborah Lipstadt believed that
David Irving's threatened libel suit would be little more than a
fleeting inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `This is a classic nuisance suit,''' said Lipstadt,
the author of ``Denying the Holocaust,'' which portrays Irving as a
Holocaust denier who manipulates history to further his own agenda.
``I thought there would be a few lawyers' letters, and then it
would go away.''
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't go away. Five years later, Lipstadt, a professor
of Modern Jewish and Holocaust Studies at Emory University in
Atlanta, won a drawn-out court case along with her publisher,
Penguin Books, but only after spending more than $3 million and
enlisting a formidable army of experts who had to prove that what
she had said about Irving was true. The victory left Lipstadt with
an unusually personal understanding of the vagaries of English
libel law.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, with its ironclad belief in the First
Amendment right to free speech, libel plaintiffs like Irving need
to prove not only that the speech in question is false, but also
that it was published with a reckless disregard for the truth. In
England, the burden is in the other direction: The offending speech
is presumed to be false, and it is up to defendants like Lipstadt
to prove that it is in fact true.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound reasonable, but it can be prohibitively
difficult, said Helena Peacock, the legal director of Penguin Books
in Britain. ``Quite often, things are true, but it's very hard to
provide evidence in court that shows they're true,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the British system tends to have a dampening effect
on what newspapers print and what publishers include in books,
especially when the material is likely to offend someone who is
powerful, rich or particularly litigious. ``A lot of journalists
feel very strongly that the libel laws support the very people they
are traditionally supposed to call to account _ those in
authority,'' said Bob Jones, an emeritus fellow in journalism at
City University in London. ``In a profit-oriented, highly
competitive media industry, managements are not too keen on taking
risks when it comes to powerful people, because they know how
expensive it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the difference in laws is that England
has never held free speech in as high esteem, as the United States
has; English courts have tended to regard it as subordinate to
things like reputation, for instance. ``It's all connected with the
English culture of deference,'' said Eric Barendt, a professor of
media law at University College London.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, because of its plaintiff-friendly libel laws, London
is not-so-affectionately known among lawyers as ``a town called
Sue.'' ``We're becoming the libel capital of the world,'' said Mark
Stephens, a lawyer specializing in free speech cases here. ``The
U.K. is probably the best plaintiff jurisdiction anywhere, and as a
consequence we get increasingly sophisticated plaintiffs looking at
which country is best to sue in and being increasingly attracted to
the U.K.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent ruling by the House of Lords, which serves as England's
court of last resort, has not helped. The case concerned the effort
of a high-profile Russian politician and businessman, Boris
Berezovsky, to bring a libel suit against Forbes, the American
magazine, in England. A 1996 Forbes article said that Berezovsky
was followed by ``a trail of corpses, uncollectible debts and
competitors terrified for their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Forbes argued that since the case involved a Russian
citizen and an American publication with a circulation in England
of less than 2,000, it had nothing to do with England. When a
lower-court judge agreed, Berezovosky appealed to the House of
Lords and won.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes plans to bring up the matter with the European Court of
Human Rights in Strasbourg, France, whose decisions can overrule
even those of the House of Lords. But if the case ends up going to
trial, Forbes will be put in a highly awkward position.
</P>
<P>
   ``One will have to ship a sizable number of members of the
Russian underworld here to testify,'' said David Hooper, a lawyer
on Forbes' English legal team. ``The whole thing is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   When they do find themselves sued in English courts, American
publications tend not to fare well. In a recent case, The New York
Times and The International Herald Tribune lost a libel suit
brought by Marco Pierre White, a celebrity chef in London, who said
that a generally favorable Times article from 1998, reprinted in
The Tribune, libeled him when it said he had had a
``well-publicized bout with drugs and alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   The Times drew this inference from White's autobiography, in
which he referred to having embarked on a ``big bender,'' only
reforming his ``decadent'' ways because ``eventually I couldn't
stand watching another person getting drunk or someone else
injecting smack into his veins.'' Had the case been heard in
America, The Times would have argued that its characterization was
an honest interpretation of what White himself had said and did not
show a reckless disregard for the truth. But in England, the jury
took a dim view of the American free-speech tradition. It found for
White and ordered the papers to pay him some $125,000 in damages,
as well as his legal costs, which are likely to be several hundred
thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, when American courts have occasion to
consider England's libel laws, they are hard-pressed to contain
their dislike for a system so antithetical to their own. This was
made abundantly clear in 1996, when _ asked to enforce an English
libel judgment because the defendant had moved to Maryland _ the
Maryland Court of Appeals, the state's highest court, refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``The signing of the Declaration of Independence, the adoption
of state constitutions and the later ratification of the First
Amendment signaled a major departure from English law and policy
concerning free speech and freedom of the press,'' the court said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The concern for American newspapers and magazines, lawyers say,
is that the recent Berezovsky ruling, as well as the growing
availability of American publications on the Internet, will make
them increasingly vulnerable to plaintiffs seeking to take their
grievances to English courts. ``In the Internet age,'' said Patrick
J. Carome, a specialist in defamation law in Washington, ``there is
a worry that we're going to see more and more situations where
foreign defendants are being hauled into court in countries like
England.''
</P>
<P>
   Why does England persist in holding on to its libel laws? They
certainly have few champions among newspapers in Britain. But
because of the news media's almost universal unpopularity among
lawmakers (who know only too well what it feels like to be on the
wrong side of a tabloid article), Parliamentary efforts to amend
the system have generally failed.
</P>
<P>
   There are some good aspects to the laws, argues David Price, a
defamation lawyer in England: ``I would defend them on the basis
that whether something is true or false is a useful piece of
information. A trial on whether a public figure has or has not been
guilty of wrongdoing is a much more useful exercise than one on
whether a newspaper believed he was guilty of wrongdoing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Lipstadt believes that fighting Irving in court, as
unpleasant as it was, had an unforseen benefit: ``In the U.S., this
would have been thrown out of court, but if it had been thrown out,
Irving would have been able to say that he never got his day in
court. I thought, `This British law is making me jump through
hoops.' But he was the one who was stripped naked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
