<SLUG> BC-PROVIDENCE-REVIVAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEEKEND EXCURSION: URBAN NOCTURNE BY FIRELIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  Paula Deitz is the editor of The Hudson Review. 
 By PAULA DEITZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ Last New Year's Eve the unexpected happened.
Cities everywhere planned pyrotechnic and other elaborate public
displays to celebrate the millennium individually, but what evolved
was a confluence of ancient rituals linked across time zones as the
new year repeatedly unfolded out of darkness on television screens
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   From the first torches lighted on South Pacific islands to fire
dances in the Judean Hills in Israel and flames on the Thames in
London, a global community of viewers was mesmerized not by
technological razzmatazz but by age-old ceremonies featuring the
primal elements of fire and water.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most evocative of these quasi-primitive rites anywhere
was an artist's installation called ``WaterFire Providence.'' But
when throngs promenaded along the banks of a cove in the
Woonasquatucket River on that memorable evening to view the
braziers of burning logs reflected in the dark waters, they had
more to celebrate than the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few years before, the city had regained its rivers by
rescuing the Providence River from under generations of road
decking and relocating its confluence with the Moshassuck and
Woonasquatucket, which flow into it at a strategic juncture near a
new inner harbor at the cove called Waterplace Park.
</P>
<P>
   In place of polluted waters and a dead ``downcity,'' as the
business district is called, Providence has become more like those
vibrant European cities with rivers running through them and
picturesque bridges joining the two banks. Suddenly buildings that
were previously on back streets, like the cluster that forms the
Rhode Island School of Design, found themselves looking out on
riverside greenswards.
</P>
<P>
   Three major department stores have appeared as part of the new
downtown Providence Place Mall designed by Friedrich St. Florian,
an architecture professor at the school, with a view of Waterplace
Park through a three-story-high Winter Garden. (The railroad tracks
that divided the city have also been permanently detoured to a new
station, with the old Union Station as the centerpiece of another
attractive development.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, as families escape to Cape Cod and other New England
vacation spots, it has become de rigueur to stop in Providence on
the way for a summer weekend featuring as its centerpiece one of
the many Saturday night reprises of WaterFire, with its haunting
musical accompaniment, along with dinner at a riverside cafe with a
view of the fires or a quick turn at an instant outdoor ballroom on
a nearby plaza.
</P>
<P>
   During the day, tree-lined Benefit Street on College Hill near
Brown University is still one of the most beautiful historic
districts in the country, with its four centuries' worth of major
domestic architecture: colorful clapboard Colonial houses along
with Federal, Greek Revival and Victorian mansions.
</P>
<P>
   And the RISD Museum (pronounced RIZ-dee) never ceases to amaze
with its exotic exhibitions plumbed from the depths of a collection
that represents its well-traveled donors.
</P>
<P>
   Voices in the Fire
</P>
<P>
   When William D. Warner, a local architect and planner,
masterminded the uncovering and rerouting of the rivers, he also
designed the 12 new bridges, including five for pedestrians only,
that appear to have been there for eons, so well does each blend
with the period of its neighboring buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The iron arch of one brick bridge echoes the main gates of Brown
University just up the hill and serves as a kind of processional
entry to its academic halls. Painted tiles inlaid into bridge walls
recount with maps and images the history of the adjacent areas for
a self-guided tour along the river walks, which themselves feature
linked bollards and piers as true remnants of river life.
</P>
<P>
   When the work was completed, Warner left protruding in the
middle of the Providence River a series of granite piers that had
supported decking over one section of the river. ``I thought these
would make appropriate bases for sculpture designed by students at
RISD,'' he said. Little did he know of the glorious future in store
for these stolid cubes as torchbearers.
</P>
<P>
   Their presence eventually fired the imagination of the artist
Barnaby Evans, a 1975 graduate of Brown, who created WaterFire in
the small cove up the river as a public artwork that would, in his
words, ``invite people back to celebrate the city as the core of
civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he originally intended WaterFire as a one-time
happening on First Night 1995, after the following performance, in
1996, Joan Slafsky, a prominent arts supporter who was among those
encouraging him to produce it regularly, spearheaded the fund
raising that established WaterFire as integral to Providence's
community and cultural life.
</P>
<P>
   Evans likens WaterFire to his Southwestern childhood experience
of sitting around a campfire in the desert with his family at
twilight. As the evening wore on, he would listen to the intimate
murmur of voices in the fire glow that dwindled to embers under a
vault of stars.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense WaterFire recreates this campfire mode for the
thousands who gather along the river walks, as they did on a recent
midsummer Saturday night, to participate in this theatrically timed
event. The braziers are lighted during the last glimmer of daylight
on designated evenings and burn until 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The artist envisions this glittering stream of firelight on
water as a kind of preverbal experience that appeals on many
different levels to children and art historians alike. Everyone
merges individual memories with the visual reality of the 97 metal
braziers that illuminate the central spine of the rivers. Set 20 to
35 feet apart, the braziers are neatly stacked with fragrant pine
and cedar logs from storm-felled trees that could no longer be
salvaged.
</P>
<P>
   For one visitor they recalled the moment at an outdoor Noh
performance in Japan when the Buddhist priests ignited braziers to
light the stage at cherry blossom time. The magical simplicity and
beauty of the crackling fires reflected in the water belie the
complex preparations that make WaterFire possible and add to its
charmed and quiet atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Music of the Night
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Evans and his staff, 140 volunteers are on board
for the occasion, most of them silently plying the quiet waters in
flat-bottom barks heaped with wood to stoke the pyres. (With a nod
to fire mythology, the boats are appropriately named Prometheus,
Daedalus, Icarus and Athena.)
</P>
<P>
   Dressed entirely in black like the Japanese Bunraku puppeteers
who disappear onstage behind their colorful puppets, the volunteers
are instructed how to place each log in turn with the simple
gesture of an outstretched arm as the boats glide stealthily by the
blazing braziers.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally a Venetian gondola traversing the waters is
silhouetted against the firelight. Waves of people jamming the
river walks briefly vanish into dark passageways under bridges
illuminated by candle-lighted chandeliers. Others crowd riverside
restaurants for a close-up view. In brief, the bateaux-mouches that
brighten the Seine at night in Paris don't have a patch on the
communal ceremony that is WaterFire.
</P>
<P>
   Further aural enchantment is provided by taped music that
resonates across the waters, with different selections made by
Evans for each performance and listed in the evening's program. To
reflect the varied cultures represented by the spirit of WaterFire,
he combines Buddhist chants with Armenian folk songs and
compositions by the contemporary Estonian composer Arvo Part with
Maria Callas singing an aria from ``La Wally'' by Catalani.
</P>
<P>
   There was a moment after midnight when Luciano Pavarotti boomed
``Nessun dorma'' from Puccini's ``Turandot,'' and everyone appeared
to stand stock still at Waterplace Park to listen and gaze at the
panorama of firelight against the glittering lights of Providence's
new skyline.
</P>
<P>
   Never was a city better named to reflect cultural and artistic
freedom than at that moment, which also reflected Roger Williams'
original vision when he founded the city for religious freedom in
1636.
</P>
<P>
   As a way of drawing the crowds into the adjoining side streets
and plaza, Evans also invented the outdoor Sovereign Plaza Ballroom
for WaterFire nights. Red drapes were hung behind an arcaded
building facade, the decorative stone Turk's head above was
lighted, and a glamorous instant ballroom was created with a
polished black octagonal dance floor over the cobblestone street.
</P>
<P>
   With lessons given before sundown, couples danced the night away
by tangoing to live music on one WaterFire night. Other WaterFire
performances will also feature dancing this summer, from swing and
salsa to waltzes and fox trots. No one goes home unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   Night life in Providence is complemented by a rich cultural
program of daytime events before the David Hykes' ``Hallelujah''
signals the lighting of the first torch of WaterFire at sunset. In
addition to its excellent permanent collection of arts and
artifacts, the RISD Museum has two summer exhibitions on the
subject of traveling.
</P>
<P>
   The first, ``The Far Traveler,'' follows the history of travel
in the 19th and 20th centuries through fashions specific to modes
of travel (automobile, railway, steamship and airplane) along with
the decorative and functional objects (portable desks and wardrobe
trunks) that were necessary conveniences. By combining these
displays with paintings and prints, the show represents the depth
of the museum's stores.
</P>
<P>
   Wanderlust and Mansions
</P>
<P>
   Last year the museum was offered a collection of clothes
selected for Virginia Hardesty Moss by Glamour magazine when her
essay won the magazine's prize trip to Paris and London in 1948.
This donation sparked the exhibition, which evokes a long era when
travel dress _ from early motoring coats and veils (1905 and 1906)
to a Vera Maxwell Ultrasuede suit (1974) _ was considered stylish
as well as practical.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing nowadays among the jeans-clad populace can touch Moss'
red flared coat and leopard-skin beret in a wardrobe that also
included a ``big occasion'' dress with a velveteen jacket that one
could walk away in today. Evidently she had a wonderful time, and
``Madame Schiaparelli even gave her a blouse in Paris,'' said
Madelyn Shaw, the curator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tokaido: The Lure of the Open Road in 19th-Century Japan''
equally inspires wanderlust through Abby Aldrich Rockefeller's
suite of Hiroshige prints following the Eastern Sea Route between
Edo (now Tokyo) and Kyoto.
</P>
<P>
   By studying the prints in sequence, the viewer gets into the
spirit of the trip, which proceeds past tea stands and inns and
sometimes across fields under a full moon or over bridges where
feudal lords are given the right of way. In another example of
RISD's strengths, a circa 1900 fragment of tie-dyed cloth in indigo
on view in the gallery nearly matches those displayed in stores in
a print of Narumi, where travelers bought the famous local products
as souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from the museum are two historic mansions that
demonstrate the great wealth and enterprise of early Providence
citizens. The interior of the 1865 palazzo-style Governor Henry
Lippitt House on Hope Street is one of the best examples of local
workmanship, both in the Herter-style decorative woodwork and in
the faux-wood and hand-stenciled finishes on walls and ceilings
executed by church decorators.
</P>
<P>
   On a weekend afternoon, it was the scene of a private summer
wedding that gave the house a certain elegant panache of reality
that it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   The 1786 late-Georgian house on Power Street built by John
Brown, a great China Trade merchant from the family that eventually
financed Brown University, possesses one of those wonders of
Providence furniture design, a rare nine-shell, blocked-front
bookcase and desk, as well as many treasures from Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Equally historic is the carriage house across the street where
Providence's longtime mayor, Vincent A. Cianci Jr., lives
surrounded by massive plantations of red impatiens that harmonize
with the brick surrounds. Cianci is the enlightened spirit and
dynamic force behind Providence's revival. When he dined with
friends at the riverside Cafe Nuovo during the last WaterFire, he
said it was gratifying to be mayor and see the rivers reborn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with America is that we do not appreciate our
cities enough,'' he said, criticizing suburban sprawl. His next
project? ``I am going to run I-95 out of town, so that we can heal
and rebuild our neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   There's more to come in Providence.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of summer attractions, along with travel
information.
</P>
<P>
   WATERFIRE PROVIDENCE begins on the Providence River at the
Corliss Street bridge next to Memorial Park and continues to
Waterplace Park and the Francis Street bridge on the
Woonasquatucket River and the Park Row bridge on the Moshassuck
River. WaterFire is scheduled for July 27, 8:09 p.m.; Aug. 5, 7:58
p.m.; Aug. 12, 7:52 p.m.; Aug. 24, 7:36 p.m.; Sept. 2, 7:17 p.m.;
Sept. 13, 6:53 p.m.; Sept. 23, 6:42 p.m.; Oct. 13, 6:06 p.m., and
Oct. 28, 5:26 p.m. Information: (401) 272-3111.
</P>
<P>
   SOVEREIGN PLAZA BALLROOM. Dancing takes place at the circle on
Westminster Street in front of Sovereign Bank New England, which
sponsors the event. It is scheduled for Aug. 5, West Coast swing
and nightclub two-step, lesson at 7 p.m. and open dancing from 8 to
midnight; Aug. 12, Latin salsa, lesson at 7 p.m., open dancing from
8 to midnight; Sept. 2, fox trot and waltz, lesson at 6:30 p.m.,
open dancing from 7:30 to midnight. Information: (401) 272-3111.
</P>
<P>
   RHODE ISLAND SCHOOL OF DESIGN MUSEUM, 224 Benefit St., (401)
454-6500. ``The Far Traveler'' and ``Tokaido: The Lure of the Open
Road in 19th-Century Japan,'' through Sept. 10. Hours: Tuesdays
through Sundays, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.; third Thursday of month until 9
p.m. Admission: adults, $5; seniors, $4; children 5 to 18, $1;
college students with valid ID, $2; free from 5 to 9 p.m. on third
Thursday and all day the last Saturday of each month.
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNOR HENRY LIPPITT HOUSE MUSEUM, 199 Hope St., (401)
453-0688. Tours by appointment only. Admission: adults, $5;
students and seniors, $4.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN BROWN HOUSE MUSEUM, Rhode Island Historical Society, 52
Power St., (401) 331-8575. Hours: Tuesdays through Saturdays, 10
a.m. to 5 p.m., Sundays, noon to 4 p.m. Admission: adults, $6;
seniors and college students, $4.50; children 7 to 17, $3. Summer
band concerts on the lawn, Thursdays at 6:30 p.m. through Aug. 24.
Admission: adults, $5; children 12 and under free with an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   THE WESTIN PROVIDENCE, 1 West Exchange St., (401) 598-8000.
Within walking distance of Waterplace Park and Providence Place
Mall. Double and single rooms, from $169 to $329.
</P>
<P>
   THE OLD COURT BED AND BREAKFAST, 144 Benefit St., (401)
751-2002. Built in 1863 in the Italianate style as a rectory.
Double and single occupancy, $145 weekdays and $165 weekends,
including breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   CADY HOUSE BED AND BREAKFAST, 127 Power St., (401) 273-5398. A
Victorian house only a short walk from the John Brown House. Double
and single occupancy, $90 and $80 respectively, including
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   Providence is filled with excellent restaurants. On WaterFire
nights those in the vicinity of the rivers set up tables along the
river walks or in nearby streets and plazas, adding to the festive
air of the event. A few are listed below.
</P>
<P>
   CAFE NUOVO, 1 Citizens Plaza, (401) 421-2525. A fusion of
American and Mediterranean cuisine. Entrees from $18.95 to $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   BELLA VISTA, 1 American Expressway (in Waterplace Park), (401)
272-1040. Northern Italian specialties. Entrees from $15.95 to
$42.95.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RIVERS, 7 Steeple St., (401) 751-0350. An American bistro
featuring local organic produce and seafood. Entrees from $12 to
$23.
</P>
<P>
   XO CAFE, 125 North Main St., (401) 273-9090. Pleasant, funky
decor and multicultural cuisine. Entrees from $18 to $25.
</P>
<P>
   NEATH'S, 262 South Water St., (401) 751-3700. A combination of
French and Asian cuisine. Entrees from $17 to $25.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   BY AIR: American Airlines offers flights from La Guardia and
John F. Kennedy International airports; US Airways flies from La
Guardia. A round-trip ticket from New York on American Airlines
bought 21 days in advance is $149; with no advance purchase, $332.
A round-trip ticket on U.S. Airways bought 21 days in advance is
$129; with no advance purchase, $424. Information: American
Airlines, (800) 433-7300; US Airways, (800) 428-4322.
</P>
<P>
   BY RAIL: Amtrak offers service to Providence seven times daily
from Pennsylvania Station in New York. The trip lasts about four
and a half hours, or about three and a half hours on the new Acela
Regional trains. Round-trip coach fare is $88; $83 for the elderly
and $64 for children under 15. Round-trip first-class fare is $128;
$115 for the elderly and $71 for children under 15.
</P>
<P>
   BY BUS: Greyhound Bus Lines offers service to Providence from
the Port Authority Bus Terminal in New York. The trip takes four
and a half to five and a half hours. Round-trip fare is $43; $41
for the elderly; $21.50 for children under 11.
</P>
<P>
   BY CAR: From New York City, take Interstate 95 north directly
into Providence.
</P>
