<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    AL GORE'S VEEP QUIZ _ PLUS A FREE CRIB SHEET
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's see if you're smarter than the presumptive Democratic
presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Put on some earth-tone casual wear and take this simple quiz.
</P>
<P>
   1.Does Al Gore need to do something to shake up the race? Yes.
No.
</P>
<P>
   2.Should this be a stunt, something ``cute''? Yes. No.
</P>
<P>
   3.Should this stunt involve the vice presidential selection and
its announcement? Yes. No.
</P>
<P>
   4.Will the electorate be entitled to gag if Al Gore tries this?
Yes. No.
</P>
<P>
   5.Will any of this have the slightest effect on the presidential
race? Yes. No.
</P>
<P>
   See, wasn't that easier than the draw-me cowboy for a mail-order
art course?
</P>
<P>
   But for the half-fast or folks who've spent the last few months
on Uranus, here's the crib sheet.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 is something of a trick question. Gore's need to shake up
the race depends on whether you believe his protestations that the
current national polling means ``next to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The quicker Gore does the attempted shaking up, the clearer it
will be that he's just as worried as most Democrats about George W.
Bush's lead in about nine out of 10 polls over the last three
months.
</P>
<P>
   The slower Gore takes it, the more faith he has in his claim
that the issues _ education, Social Security, Medicare, patients'
rights, drugs costs, gasoline prices _ are on his side and that
voters will come around once they start focusing on the election.
</P>
<P>
   But this wasn't a discussion question, now, was it?
</P>
<P>
   Of course Gore needs to shake up the race. But he had better be
careful how he does it. And that means the answer to Nos. 2 and 3
is not only no, but hell no.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is worried that Bush, already marginally ahead, will get a
traditional bounce from the Republican National Convention and pull
farther in front. That means the vice president would just have
more ground to make up around the Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   So there are now reports Gore will attempt to short-circuit the
Bush bump by announcing his own choice for vice president within
hours of the close of the Republican show in Philadelphia and be
out on the stump with his running mate that weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Voters know a gimmick when they see one _ artifice masquerading
as substance. (Review videotape of Michael Dukakis in the tank.)
</P>
<P>
   And if there is one thing that Al Gore does not need, it's to
look more calculatedly programmed.
</P>
<P>
   With a quick announcement of a running mate, Gore would also be
giving up an opportunity to review the initial public reaction to
Bush's convention performance and that of the GOP vice presidential
nominee. That won't be clear until early the next week.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine that any of the Democratic vice
presidential prospects would be so stunning that the public
reaction (especially on a midsummer weekend) would be profitably
astonishing for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   One has trouble imagining a scenario in which the public
response is: ``Oh, thank God, Al has chosen (John Kerry, Bob
Graham, Evan Bayh, Joe Lieberman, etc.) and rushed to tell us about
it.'' It's not that any of them are seriously problematic, it's
just that none is a silver bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Two asterisks:
</P>
<P>
   (1) This dullsville angle was pointed up by the brief frisson
that ran through the chattering classes with the idea that Gore,
improbably, might select House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt.
It's not that Gephardt is Mr. Scintillating, it's just that he
would have been a more interesting choice than the remaining White
Boys.
</P>
<P>
   (2) Having two weeks ago questioned whether George W. Bush had
the courage to take the somewhat pro-choice Tom Ridge as a running
mate, I'll raise the same issue for Gore regarding Bayh, whose less
than perfect abortion-rights voting record has sent several
feminist arrows his way.
</P>
<P>
   Enough of this digression. The answer to No. 4 is yes, the
electorate would be entitled to gag if Gore tries to be too tricky
with his veep selection or timing of the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to No. 5. Here the key word is ``slightest.''
Only if the race comes down to the 1 or 2 percentage point range
are the vice presidential candidates likely to make much of a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Barring some political cataclysm, it will be Bush plus X vs.
Gore plus Y. And in this equation, both X and Y almost certainly
equal zero.
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
