<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV23-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIND CHIMES NEED FLEXIBLE CORDS TO SOUND IN THE WIND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July   23, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I replaced the cords on my wind chimes because they had
rotted, using nylon fishing line. Now the tubes don't move or sound
in the wind. What did I do wrong?
</P>
<P>
   SUSAN McANDREW, Carlisle, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think the nylon fishing line will work because it is
not flexible enough. I think a thin cotton or polyester cord would
be more flexible. Also, check out similar chimes to see if you can
determine what the cords are made of. Or, ask a wind chime dealer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I decided to replace the carpet on my hardwood stairs, I
found the steps to be in good shape except for a few spots where
the tack board splintered the wood. I'd like the nice-looking
treads to show on each side of the new carpet, so I plan to
refinish them.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of wood filler should I use, and should I apply it
before I apply the oil-based polyurethane varnish, or before
sanding?
</P>
<P>
   MRS. R.H. MAYER, Metairie, La.
</P>
<P>
   A. For the holes in the treads, use a wood filler. Wood filler
is what wood fillers are called. Use a latex-based filler in a
plastic bucket. It's a neutral color, good for most floors. Apply
the filler directly into the holes. If the varnish is dark, you can
buy a dark filler to match; it comes in all colors. Then you can
sand the treads lightly, and apply two coats of oil-based varnish.
</P>
<P>
   The following does not apply to your situation because your
treads are varnished. If you run into a situation where you must
fill holes on an unvarnished surface, here is how to do it with
perfect results:
</P>
<P>
   Sand the surface smooth, wipe with paint thinner, then apply the
varnish, at least one coat. Let dry, then fill the holes. The
reason you apply the filler over one coat of varnish is to prevent
the filler from smearing the wood. Sanding the stain from a filler
smear is impossible. After the filler sets overnight, you can apply
a second and possibly third coat of varnish.
</P>
<P>
   If you stain the tread, the procedure is the same. After
varnishing the stained wood, apply a filler of the same or similar
color as the stain. And, if the filler is a bit darker than the
finish, that is OK, because dark marks show up less than light
ones.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a 9- by 12-foot rug on my wall-to-wall carpeting. It
looks great but insists on curling on one side. It is hazardous and
annoying. I have tried laying patio brick on the curl. That works
for a time, but after a while, the curl returns. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   CURLING, JUST CURLING, San Leandro, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is some hope. Rug and carpet stores and dealers carry
special mesh pads to keep throw rugs from throwing, and to keep
corners and edges down. One is called Blue Miracle (the mesh is
coated with vinyl).
</P>
<P>
   If pads don't work, try this for the curls: double-faced carpet
tape.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My ranch house has a one-foot projection over the foundation,
about 16 feet long. The windows are triple-glazed, but the ceiling
of the projection is not insulated. Warm air in the house hits the
cool ceiling, and I get a lot of moisture and mold on the ceiling.
The house is 46 years old. How can I insulate that ceiling?
</P>
<P>
   RAYMOND BARRETT, Braintree, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Insulation is the only thing that will prevent mold from
growing. Mold grows on damp surfaces. The surface gets damp because
water vapor condenses on it. Warming up that ceiling will help
prevent anything from condensing on it. You can't get to the space
above the ceiling of the projection, either from below or through
the attic. So, the ultimate is to cut.
</P>
<P>
   I said that insulation is the only thing that will prevent mold
from growing. That is only half true. Another way to stop the mold
is by ventilating, to reduce or eliminate the water vapor. That is
not practicable.
</P>
<P>
   Cut out the ceiling and put in rigid insulation. I think four
inches will do; that much Styrofoam will give an R value of 20;
that much High R Sheathing (a modified urethane foam) board will
give an R value of 28. Put in six inches if you like, and rebuild
the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Another, easier way is to glue 2-inch-thick rigid insulation
(one of the above) on the ceiling, border it with decorative wood
trim and glue or nail a new ceiling on the insulation, driving
nails through the insulation. It will not give you as high an R
value, but it will be enough to stop the condensation.
</P>
<P>
   You can do this if it does not bring the ceiling down enough to
cover the window.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The metal soap holder in my bathroom looks pretty good until
it turns green. I use bleach to get rid of it, and it is fine for a
while, but it always comes back. It is silverish in color. How can
I keep that green away?
</P>
<P>
   MARY ANN FITZGERALD, Milton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If the green goes away with a bleach solution, it may be
algae, and there is little you can do except continue with the
bleach treatment. I can't imagine that it comes back so quickly and
frequently.
</P>
<P>
   But it might also be corrosion of brass or copper, which creates
a green or greenish-blue color. Since it looks silverish, it may be
chrome plated, but there might be copper or brass exposed to cause
the greening.
</P>
<P>
   The solution: Keep washing off the green or get a new, ceramic
soap holder.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
