<HEADLINE>
SIGN OF THE TIMES: CLINTON PRESS AIDES SEEKING JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HELEN THOMAS  
 c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With time running out on the Clinton
administration, staffers in the White House press office are
looking to their futures.
</P>
<P>
   Press secretary Joe Lockhart has passed the word that he does
not expect to remain on the job beyond early fall. His likely
successor is deputy press secretary Jake Siewert, who pinch-hits
for Lockhart on many occasions in his absence. Lockhart has been
job hunting on the West Coast, but with his expertise in politics,
he is likely to get offers in the Washington area.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy press secretary Jennifer Palmieri is leaving her White
House post at the end of the month to start a new gun-control
advocacy group in Washington. Press assistant Julia Payne has moved
over to Vice President Al Gore's staff.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's aide de camp Chris Engskov has joined a
venture capital group in Seattle. He was the ``Man Friday'' for the
president, always at his side and ready to do whatever needs to be
done. He's the guy who puts Clinton's speech text on the podium
right before a speech.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, who took over the post from McCurry in the aftermath
of the impeachment ordeal, learned the ropes rapidly and fell
quickly in step with President Clinton. He is a straight shooter
and has the respect of the press corps.
</P>
<P>
   New York has become the hunting ground for some of the White
House job seekers. With their credentials and insider knowledge
they are bound to land on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As far as reporters are concerned the second Camp David has been
deja vu all over again, although press secretary Joe Lockhart
insists otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart warned reporters against drawing ``too many parallels''
with the first Camp David summit in 1978 when Egyptian President
Anwar Sadat and Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin negotiated
for 13 days before achieving a breakthrough settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not 1978,'' Lockhart warned.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there are some similarities such as the news
blackout. Lockhart behaves just like then-White House Press
Secretary Jody Powell did in 1978. Both gave ``news briefings''
about the Camp David meetings but there was no news in those
briefings.
</P>
<P>
   The tidbits at both summits dealt with the menu at the Camp
David meals, what the negotiators were wearing and a few words
about the general mood.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters learned that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak was
given the ``Dogwood'' cottage and Palestinian Yasser Arafat was
assigned to the ``Birch'' cabin. In 1978, Egyptian President Sadat
occupied ``Dogwood'' and Begin was in ``Birch.''
</P>
<P>
   Camp David, near Thurmont, Md., was created during World War II
as a retreat for President Franklin D. Roosevelt near Washington.
He dubbed it Shangri La.
</P>
<P>
   The barbed wire encampment guarded by Marines in camouflaged
fatigues has always been no-man's land for reporters and a haven
for presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the grounds are 20 cabins _ most of them built in the
Nixon era _ including Aspen Lodge, a spacious hideaway for
presidents, nestled in the woods on a mountaintop.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton spoke at the recent ceremony on Capitol Hill
when the legendary Father Theodore Hesburgh, president of the
University of Notre Dame for 35 years, was presented the
Congressional Gold Medal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton recalled that Hesburgh's first job at Notre Dame was as
chaplain for the married veterans who had enrolled under the GI
Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   The pregnant wife of one of the veterans was rushed to the
delivery room and the baby, taken by a Caesarean section, had a
heartbeat but no breath. The medical team could not induce the
infant to breathe. But the instant Hesburgh baptized it with cold
water, the baby began to cry loudly, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career, some members of the clergy criticized
Hesburgh for his focus on academic improvement. His retort: ``Piety
is no substitute for competent scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   Once at Notre Dame, a young Jewish student from Boston left
campus two weeks into the semester because two freshmen hurt him
deeply with anti-Semitic slurs. The freshmen were sent to Hesburgh,
who told them to go to Boston and try to persuade the young man to
return to Notre Dame. If they failed this mission, he said, don't
bother to come back to the university. Clinton said all three came
back and they all graduated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that is leadership,'' the president added.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Liz Carpenter, Lady Bird Johnson's press secretary, spoke in
Dallas July 12 to commemorate the 35th anniversary of the signing
of the Medicare bill. She recalled that President Lyndon Johnson
went to President Harry Truman's home in Independence, Mo., to sign
the landmark bill because Truman had first proposed the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   She said that Johnson began his remarks with the statement that
``The people of the United States loved and voted for Harry Truman,
not because he gave them hell, but because he gave them hope.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Helen Thomas can be contacted at 202-298-6920 or via email:
helent &LR; hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
