<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8909 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-NASCAR-TIRES-NYTR     07-21 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-TIRES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR DRIVERS FEEL TIRE PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett has struggled a little, Jeff Gordon has struggled a
lot, and many other top NASCAR drivers are somewhere in between as
Winston Cup racing continues through one of its most unusual
seasons in years.
</P>
<P>
   The season's first 13 races saw 12 different winners, including
two rookies. No truly dominant car, or group of cars. Drivers who
almost never run up front were suddenly doing well.
</P>
<P>
   Why? To sum it up in one word: tires.
</P>
<P>
   At the race track, tires are perhaps the most critical element
in setting up a car to run fast. The chassis is adjusted to work
with the tires. Each track is different, and over the years, the
elite teams compile extensive notes on what works best for each
race.
</P>
<P>
   So, while the tires and cars themselves change, there has always
been a base line to work from, a place to start.
</P>
<P>
   No more.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a change in the tire,'' explained Jarrett, the
defending Winston Cup champion. ``There has been a total
reconfiguration of the tire and it's totally different.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear decided to make changes after tire failures caused a
number of serious accidents during the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was wrong with the tire Goodyear produced, but it had a
stiff sidewall, which made the cars hard to turn. To compensate,
the teams ran with low air pressure and a lot of camber in the
front tires.
</P>
<P>
   On a passenger car, the tires are straight up and down because
the car runs on flat roads. But to make race cars faster through
the corners, teams tilt the top of the right tire front-in and the
top of the left front-out so that as much tread as possible grips
the banking. Excessive camber, as this is called, combined with low
air pressure, causes severe wear on the inside sidewall of the
right front as it goes through the turns, which can cause the tire
to fail.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent that, Goodyear came out with a new generation of
tires this year with a softer sidewall. That meant the teams
couldn't tilt the right front-in as much, because it would roll
over on the sidewall, and it also meant they had to use higher air
pressure to keep the tire up.
</P>
<P>
   The new tire made the cars easier to turn, but it made
everyone's notes obsolete because the tire's characteristics were
almost the opposite of what the teams had worked with before.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, the amount of flex in the sidewall, or tire
spring rate, varied from one set of tires to the next. Teams would
get their cars set up to work with a certain stiffness in the tire,
then suddenly find the car was handling totally differently because
a new set of tires was either stiffer or more flexible than the set
before.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all this, most teams were reluctant to make major
changes at first, going with what had worked in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys were putting a lot of camber in to make sure the car
would turn, and that was blowing the right front,'' said Larry
McReynolds, who is the crew chief for Mike Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was making Goodyear look bad and it wasn't their fault.
So they came up with a new tire with a softer sidewall,''
McReynolds said. ``The car turns better now, but our notes are
worthless. We had to go 180 degrees the other direction.''
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds said the new tires helped Matt Kenseth and Dale
Earnhardt Jr., two rookies with rookie teams. ``They didn't have
any notes, and they just did what the tire wanted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During the first half of the season, Earnhardt Jr. won two races
plus The Winston and Kenseth won once, a success rate unheard of in
Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   It appears, however, that the elite teams are starting to regain
their advantage as the season moves along. For example, Tony
Stewart has won three of the last six races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're getting better, and I think there are five or
six teams out there, if somebody hits on the combination, they
could break away,'' said Robbie Loomis, Gordon's crew chief.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
