s f BC-INVEST-Q&AMP;A-BRONSON-$A     07-21 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-Q&AMP;A-BRONSON-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWAITING PEARLS FROM THE IPO PIPELINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nasdaq seems to have gotten beyond its valuation problem,
sort of. Earnings from most technology companies remain strong. And
the market for initial public offerings, many of them technology
issues, is showing signs of cranking up again after a sharp
slowdown this spring.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 104 new issues were priced in the second quarter,
according to Thompson Financial Securities Data. That was down from
141 in the first quarter and 166 in the fourth quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But the figures are relative: In the first quarter of 1999, when
the stock market was booming, only 73 new issues were priced.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a lot in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   IPOfinancial.com, publisher of a twice-a-month newsletter, is
tracking more than 300 companies that are waiting to come to
market. More than two-thirds of those got in line before May 1 and
are awaiting improved conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Bronson, a senior analyst for IPO Monitor, a research firm,
and a Silicon Valley venture capitalist, took some time last week
to talk about the new-issue market. Following are excerpts from the
conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Q. The stock market appears to have stabilized, and the deal
flow has picked up a bit over the last few weeks. Is the new issue
market ready to fly again?
</P>
<P>
   A. It seems like we have washed a lot of the speculative nature
out of the market, but there is a long list of issues that have
been pulled, and those issues haven't come back. We are in the
summer doldrums. I suspect there are many significant IPOs related
to the Internet and telecommunications that are holding back to the
fall in anticipation of a more robust market. Those companies that
have been in registration that have postponed their deals or cut
back on their size are smart. You want to come out in the most
stable Wall Street environment that you can. How your stock does
when it goes public colors a company's capability for the following
six months to a year.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Did the meltdown in the Nasdaq make investors more selective
about new issues?
</P>
<P>
   A. In the past couple of years, we have seen companies go out
and be very successful as story stocks, companies with some
revenues but no real prospects for earnings in the near term. You
are not going to see as many of them. In order to garner strong
interest in the public market, companies that go public over the
next few quarters will be able to promote the fact that they will
have earnings in the near term.
</P>
<P>
   Q. The drop-off in initial public offerings has been sharp, but
the decline in secondary sales of stock has been even more
pronounced. Are some companies not going to be able to tap the
market?
</P>
<P>
   A. I am not aware of anyone giving up on a secondary offering.
But you will see a lot of consolidation, with companies that are in
vertical spaces buddying up. There is just not enough consumer
support to sustain all of them. And this is healthy, because only
the strongest survive ... Now is a great opportunity for companies
to just buy.
</P>
<P>
   Q. A lot of the Internet mania seems to have evaporated. Does
that reflect changing attitudes about the commercial potential of
the World Wide Web?
</P>
<P>
   A. Marketing on the Net will always be a wonderful tool, but it
is doubtful it will supplant or cut into sales traffic. At the end
of the day, companies will discover that the Internet is a good way
to cut the cost of doing business as opposed to augmenting
revenues. That is why it is a very exciting time to be part of the
infrastructure build-out for the Internet and related platforms.
There is all sorts of activity in what is now the second chapter of
building the next level of Internet infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Aside from infrastructure companies, what sorts of companies
will likely be well received by investors in coming months?
</P>
<P>
   A. Biotechnology is very much coming into its own now. Companies
have been doing research to the point where they now have something
to sell in the marketplace. This is different from the biotech wave
in the early 1990s, when there was a ground swell of enthusiasm
that faded because there were no real products. Now we have
companies with real products that are based on biotechnological
innovations. And those companies will probably come to market.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Last year, tons of money was invested by venture capitalists.
Have those flows slowed?
</P>
<P>
   A. There doesn't seem to be any less interest in investing money
privately to help build out this second wave of infrastructure,
much less vertical market companies. Everyone continues to be very
enthusiastic about the potential. When that potential is realized
in terms of companies producing net profit remains to be seen. And
the IPO event is simply the last step in the venture capital cycle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
