<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8911 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CYC-LANCE-INC22-COX     07-21 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-LANCE-INC22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armstrong to become tour de force
 &HT;    By Sheryll Poe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe they should call it the Tour de Cash. Should 28-year-old
Lance Armstrong win his second Tour de France Sunday, he will
become an even more powerful marketing machine.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of seeing a yellow racing jersey, some companies are
seeing gold.
</P>
<P>
   This time last year, Armstrong was making $500,000 with
endorsements from the U.S. Postal Service team and $30,000 per
speaking engagement. Now he commands $100,000 per speech and an
estimated $5 million per year in endorsements, some through the
year 2004. Analysts can only debate how much he would be worth with
a second Tour de France victory.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his endorsement deals, Armstrong has another year
on his $2 million-a-year contract with the U.S. Postal Service
team.
</P>
<P>
   His total income of about $7 million this year is roughly the
same salary as Dallas Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a very hot name in sports over the past year, and
this will continue to keep him on the hot list for another year,''
said sports marketer Bob Williams of Chicago-based Burns Sports
Celebrity Service Inc., who ranks Armstrong with former Denver
Broncos quarterback John Elway and Washington Redskins cornerback
Deion Sanders in public speaking fees. ``There aren't many athletes
that can charge six figures for a speech. For appearances, he's at
the top of the list,''
</P>
<P>
   But it might be too soon to start comparing him to fellow Nike
spokesmen Michael Jordan or Tiger Woods, Burns said. ``Jordan and
Woods don't even do appearances and if they did, no one could
afford what they (would) charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Schinman, the president of New York-based entertainment
consulting company Platinum Rye Entertainment, who represents
Charles Schwab and the New York Stock Exchange, agrees. ``He's not
even close to being the next Tiger Woods. It's comparing apples and
oranges,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the remaining 129 from the original 190 Tour competitors,
no one comes close to attracting Armstrong's level of the media
attention. In France, he is known as ``Lance Inc.'' Teammate Cedric
Vasseur said traveling with Armstrong is like ``traveling with a
rock star.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong products have been good for Austin retailers, who are
seeing $58 official cycling jerseys fly off the shelves _ mostly to
fellow cyclists. Sun &AMP; Ski Sports Expo stocks the official team
jerseys, matching socks, hats and yellow T-shirts with sponsor
logos. ``Lance has been beneficial to cycling overall,'' said
general manager Jeremy Trudeau. ``It's not really about the sales,
but about broadening a lot of people's expectancy of the biking
industry. He's opening a lot of eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   That level of adulation comes as a surprise to Schinman at
Platinum Rye. ``Find anyone who can name a cyclist besides Greg
LeMond or Lance Armstrong. He's a B-level marketer, recognized in
his sport, but below the Jack Nicholas', Mark McGuire's, Ken
Griffey's or Kobe Bryant's.''
</P>
<P>
   The week after his 1999 victory, Armstrong appeared in a ``Just
Do It'' commercial by Nike, one of his longtime apparel and
equipment sponsors. Nike took out a double-page ad in Paris' daily
newspaper L'Equipe this week featuring Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is certainly one of our top overall athletes,'' said
spokesman Scott MacEachern. ``He's really proven himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike will continue to use Armstrong in its retail advertising
campaign, MacEachern said, adding that the cyclist is as marketable
as Woods, Marion Jones, Maurice Greene and Jordan. Nike spent about
$10 million on its Armstrong campaign during the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Williams believes the nature, as well as the price of
Armstrong's future public appearances will change. With potential
offers of more money, Armstrong might choose to do more television
and print jobs. ``He can do those in one day, and they can use it
for the entire year, and spend more time training or with his
family,'' he said. ``I think he'll start charging more for his
television commercials, and he might increase his appearance
fees.''
</P>
<P>
   Schinman remained skeptical. ``He's not going to take a product
over the top,'' he said. ``Even if he won five Tour de Frances in a
row, he still wouldn't be in the upper echelon of spokespeople.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schinman said Armstrong might have more pull in Europe,
where cycling is a more visible sport, and with companies
interested in promoting cycling gear. But, he said, ``if you pulled
100 people aside and asked them if they even knew the Tour de
France were going on right now, most of them wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen companies, from the U.S. Postal Service to local
e-tailer bike.com, are paying Armstrong a minimum of $500,000
annually for endorsements and at least $250,000 to use the
cyclist's name or image in their commercial pitches.
</P>
<P>
   To earn his $5 million in endorsements, Armstrong has been
featured in eight national television commercials since August,
including three with Nike, as well as pictured on two Wheaties
boxes. He also has deals with American General Insurance, AIM
Mutual Funds, Bristol-Myers Squibb and Bridge Information Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts believe Armstrong has the potential to add even
more corporate clients. ``I wouldn't market him aggressively, maybe
the top companies with each industry,'' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Bike.com hopes to continue its two-year contract with Armstrong
at the end of this year, but remains cautious in the face of higher
prices. ``Lance has a reputation of being loyal to the people who
believe in him,'' said chief executive Bill Hayden. ``We don't know
what his needs are, but we'll try to understand and meet his
requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong also received a $400,000 book contract last year for
his autobiography ``It's Not About the Bike,'' which hit the
shelves in May. Two major studios are negotiating for film rights.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service team also has benefited from Armstrong's
presence. The team increased from 16 to 19 riders and has gained 22
sponsors paying a minimum of six figures to have their logos worn
on the team uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service certainly won't make the same mistake
Armstrong's former biggest sponsor made. In 1996, Cofidis, a French
revolving credit company, cancelled a $2.5 million contract to have
Armstrong on its racing team after it was discovered that he had
testicular cancer that had spread to his brain and lungs.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving chemotherapy, brain surgery and surgery to
remove his testicle, Armstrong made a comeback in 1997. In
co-operation with the Lance Armstrong Foundation, sponsor
Bristol-Myers Squibb to developed Cycle of Hope, a major cancer
education campaign. Since 1997, the Lance Armstrong Foundation has
raised $10 million to fight cancer, with approximately $600,000 of
that coming from Armstrong's pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1625EDT &QL; 
