<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8920 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-TV-EMMYS-HNS &LR;      07-21 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-EMMYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR CRITICIZES NEW VOTING METHOD FOR EMMY AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Thomas O'Neil, a journalist who wrote a book
chronicling the history of the Emmys, is a raving zealot when it
comes to the television awards. So it's no wonder that O'Neil's
head comes close to exploding whenever he thinks about the upcoming
change in voting procedures. He predicts a calamity on par with
Pompeii.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the greatest tragedies in show-biz history is about to
take place,'' said the author of ``The Emmys,'' first published in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the Emmys _ where no one, including critics, is ever left
entirely happy. The Emmy nominations were announced Thursday
morning, and while my skull is in no danger of flying apart, there
are certainly some areas that leave me with a headache.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the list: Where is ``Malcolm in the Middle?''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the first-year Fox comedy netted five nominations,
including an obviously deserving bid for Jane Kaczmarek for her
role as the terrorizing/terrorized mom Lois. But the rookie show
failed to get a nomination for best comedy. Wrong, wrong, wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The five nominees: ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' (CBS),
``Frasier'' (NBC),``Friends'' (NBC), ``Sex and the City'' (HBO) and
``Will &AMP; Grace'' (NBC)are all great, but ``Malcolm'' was simply the
funniest show on television this past season.
</P>
<P>
   Also not nominated was Kaczmarek's husband, Bradley Whitford of
NBC's ``The West Wing.'' (Another husband-and-wife team was
nominated: Michael J. Fox as best comedy actor for ``Spin City'' on
ABC and Tracy Pollan as best guest actress in a drama for NBC's
``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit.'')
</P>
<P>
   But the White House drama's first season earned 18 nominations,
tying HBO's ``The Sopranos'' for most of any show this year. Both
are nominated for best drama along with last year's undeserving
winner, ``The Practice,'' ``Law &AMP; Order'' and the over-the-hill
``ER.'' A very early prediction: Look for the mob show to win as a
payback for last year's snub.
</P>
<P>
   The Emmy Awards will air on Sunday, Sept. 10, on ABC. Garry
Shandling will host.
</P>
<P>
   Other first-glance observations:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' (WB) earned a nomination for best
writing in a drama. That show deserves some recognition from the
academy; it's much, much more than some brat show.
</P>
<P>
   _ The wonderful ABC television movie ``Annie'' received 12
nominations, but none for Alicia Morton in the title role. She's
the best Annie I've ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Star Trek Voyager'' (UPN) received more nominations (seven)
than the great-but-grim HBO miniseries ``The Corner'' (four), which
received the same number of nods as the eminently forgettable ABC
musical ``Geppetto.'' A quirk of numbers, yes, but yeeeecccch. The
fact that Khandi Alexander is not nominated is so mystifying that
I'm torn between amusement and fury; young Sean Nelson also
deserved a nomination.
</P>
<P>
   _ NBC had the most nominations of any network with 97, followed
by HBO with 86, ABC with 64 and CBS trailing far behind with 41.
Fox had 26 bids, while the WB and UPN combined had the same number
of bids as PBS by itself (12).
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil is outraged about a decision by the Academy of Television
Arts &AMP; Sciences to change the way voting is done. Instead of
bringing voters into a Los Angeles hotel for a 48-hour viewing
binge of all the nominees' submissions, this year's episodes will
be sent to voters' homes.
</P>
<P>
   The danger, O'Neil said, is that voters, once subject to strict
monitoring rules, might not even watch the tapes, and instead vote
for shows based on reputation or the influence of friends.
</P>
<P>
   The old system ``guarantees every single nominee that their work
will be seen by every single voter,'' O'Neil said. ``It is all
being destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   The author said the Academy changes were a result of the
organization getting hammered by critics after ``The Practice''
beat out ``The Sopranos'' for best drama last year. Critics' picks
can differ from Emmy voting: Writers often base their opinions on a
season of work rather than individual episodes. O'Neil fears the
new policy will decrease the chances for a deserving upset winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you realize from now on we will have a popularity
contest?'' he said. ``There is nothing less at stake here than the
next `Hill Street Blues' or the next `Cheers.'
</P>
<P>
   Nonsense, say advocates of the change, noting that the old
system often limited the pool of voters to those able to make an
extensive time commitment (read: retirees). Academy officials said
the tapes will be watched at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the members of the Television Academy take the
Emmys quite seriously,'' Chairman Meryl Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil's predictions of disaster may be hyperbole, but the
academy is certainly put on notice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
