<SLUG> BC-ART-EXHIBITS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT COVERS THREE CENTURIES LIGHTLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)   By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the New York art scene simmers down for the summer,
Connecticut museums offer a kaleidoscope of exhibitions that range
from American impressionism of the 19th century to video imagery
for the 21st, with Connecticut itself or art produced there as a
prime subject.
</P>
<P>
   You can see riches from London and local sources in New Haven
and Greenwich, visit a sprightly Calder display in Hartford,
explore the art of the video screen in Ridgefield, and in New
Britain follow part of the American Impressionist Art Trail, which
winds through the state.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, for the most part you're in green country, where
outdoor pleasures complement the art inside. Here is a rundown of
some art shows that give added dimension to Connecticut as a summer
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth Athenaeum
</P>
<P>
   Of Calder shows there is no end. But just when you think you've
seen enough of the wizard's work for a while, along comes another
irresistible opportunity. Such is the case with ``Calder in
Connecticut,'' at the Wadsworth Athenaeum in Hartford, a banquet of
more than 150 objects, including letters, photos and sketches.
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania-born Calder (1898-1973) established a home and
studio in Roxbury in 1933. What's different about this show is that
all of it is drawn from Connecticut sources. Eric M. Zafran, its
curator, suggests that Connecticut influenced the style and content
of Calder's work in many ways, from the rolling terrain of its
hills to the flora, fauna and climate there.
</P>
<P>
   The artists, collectors and friends with whom Calder surrounded
himself in this rural retreat of New York culturati also helped
stimulate and shape his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Works on view range from the monster orange stabile
``Stegosaurus'' (1973), 50 feet high and weighing 40 tons, a
permanent installation on the Athenaeum's grounds, to his first
wood sculpture, the small ``Very Flat Cat'' of 1926, a reclining
feline made from an old oak post found on a visit to a friend in
the hamlet of Sherman.
</P>
<P>
   Paintings, drawings, rug designs, jewelry, toys and personal
mementos _ many of them gifts bestowed by the artist _ augment the
fancy-free mobiles and stabiles in which the show abounds.
</P>
<P>
   Calder's connection with the Wadsworth was for life. His work
first appeared there in a 1935 show at the invitation of the
museum's dynamic director, Chick Austin. Of the three entries in
that show, ``Little Blue Panel'' (1935), an electrified mobile in
which a spindle and two balls rotate at different rates, was bought
by the Athenaeum for $75. One of the first Calders to enter a
museum collection, it is in the current show, still doing its
little act in an overall brilliant presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Yale University Art Gallery
</P>
<P>
   An important artist from Calder's era was Philip Guston
(1913-1980), whose work shares the spotlight with two other
exhibitions at the bustling Yale University Art Gallery in New
Haven. In 1967 Guston made a shocking transition from his
established mode of lyrical abstract expressionism to figurative
painting of a cartoony, often bizarre nature that made some critics
gag. But Guston, ``tired of all that purity,'' wanted to try his
hand at what he called storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   This small but stimulating show explores the four-year period of
his transition, focusing on an ``alphabet'' of individual images he
developed for his new work: Klan-like hoods, bricks, cups, clocks,
picture frames, an easel and so forth, each painted on a small
panel. The crudity of the images is offset by lush painting and a
robust color sense.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the full-scale canvases that Guston worked his alphabet
into are on view, like ``Riding Around'' (1969), in which three
Klannishly robed figures with big cigars tour the city in a
menacing black open jalopy. Some of his earlier abstract
expressionist works from the '60s are also displayed. Altogether
the show gives an illuminating glimpse of the work of an artist
courageous enough to make a drastic change.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way spiritually from Guston to Gothic Revival, but
physically, just a step. The first-floor galleries also house
``Modern Gothic: The Revival of Medieval Art,'' an exploration of
Gothic Revival architecture in the United States and Britain from
1830 to 1875.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 objects _ paintings, sculptures, architectural
drawings and models, along with furniture and decorative objects _
are on display, including the work of American talents including
Alexander Jackson Davis and Richard Upjohn, and the British
architects A.W.N. Pugin and Sir Charles Barry.
</P>
<P>
   Gothic Revival came about from the yearnings of some scholars,
artists and clergymen for the purity of pre-Renaissance days. The
show focuses on the style as it was used in houses, churches, civic
buildings and universities (including, of course, Yale), and on the
patrons who commissioned it and the reasons they did so.
</P>
<P>
   Anglophilia, the novels of Sir Walter Scott and the appeal of
picturesque ruins were some factors that influenced Americans, as
seen in a rendering of Lyndhurst, the medieval-looking stronghold
in Tarrytown, N.Y., originally designed by Davis in 1838 for a Gen.
Paulding and redone by him around 1865 for George Merritt, a
wealthy New York businessman.
</P>
<P>
   A useful feature is that the exhibition catalog is a guide to
Gothic Revival architecture still standing in the Northeast,
combining architects' drawings with modern photographs and even
providing itineraries. So even after it closes, this show goes on.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
