u i BC-IRELAND-SCANDAL-HAUGH     07-21 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-SCANDAL-HAUGHEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS GRILL EX-IRISH PRIME MINISTER IN CORRUPTION PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ The official interrogation and humiliation of Ireland's
former prime minister, Charles J. Haughey, began in earnest Friday
as lawyers began grilling him on accusations of soliciting some $12
million in bribes, gifts and kickbacks.
</P>
<P>
   As he arrived at Dublin Castle, where the nation's most
far-reaching investigation into corruption is being held, Haughey
was showered with abuse by about two dozen demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   They threw pennies at him, shouting that the coins were
``legitimate campaign contributions'' compared to the millions
Haughey is alleged to have solicited from businessmen, mostly
property devleopers, from 1979 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haughey! Haughey! Haughey! Jail! Jail! Jail!'' they chanted.
</P>
<P>
   Haughey accumulated a fortune during his three terms as prime
minister. He lives in a $30 million, 300-acre estate lined with
fine art, some of it given to him by businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   Haughey ignored the taunts, but once inside the ornate Georges
Hall where Justice Michael Moriarty is presiding over the tribunal
probing widespread influence-peddling, his humiliation continued.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's session resembled the first round of a boxing match, as
Haughey and his interrogators took a measure of each other. As he
did in 1997, when he admitted he took $2 million from supermarket
magnate Ben Dunne, Haughey Friday claimed his financial matters had
been handled by his close friend, Des Traynor, who has since died.
</P>
<P>
   But tribunal counsel John Coughlan made it clear that he intends
to prove that Traynor is nothing more than a conveniently dead
scapegoat and that Haughey ran his own finances. Backing his
claims, Coughlan produced a series of embarrassing memos from
Allied Irish Bank, which spent most of 1974 trying to force Haughey
to pay some $350,000 in debts.
</P>
<P>
   Haughey sat impassively as Coughlan read the memos aloud. In
one, a banker complained that Haughey had a ``proclivity toward
making arbitrary, unauthorized'' withdrawals. Another concluded
that Haughey's ``living expenses are huge and totally unrelated to
his ... salary.''
</P>
<P>
   Still another said, ``Mr. Haughey is quite irresponsible in
money matters. He cannot be trusted.'' Long before he settled his
debts, Haughey was Ireland's finance minister.
</P>
<P>
   One plaintive memo from an exasperated banker who had tried to
get Haughey to pay his debts seemed to encapsulate the allegations
against Ireland's most charismatic, controversial leader of the
last century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Haughey,'' the banker wrote, ``has abused our confidence and
trust.''
</P>
<P>
   As Coughlan read the embarrassing memos, Haughey momentarily
glanced at the ceiling, where three elaborate crystal chandeliers
hang, and then to the lime green walls adorned with chiarascuro
paintings, the sort of artwork that Haughey filled his mansion with
and is accused of buying with money shaken down from people wanting
to do business in Ireland during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Haughey acknowledged to Coughlan that he was financially
overextended in 1974. At the time, Haughey had been banished to the
backbenches of his Fianna Fail party as punishment after being
narrowly acquitted of criminal charges that he had supplied weapons
to the Irish Republican Army after civil unrest broke out in
Northern Ireland in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was borrowing from Peter to pay Paul,'' Haughey said.
</P>
<P>
   So far has Haughey's esteem fallen that an Irish journalist
sitting in the press gallery remarked in a stage whisper, ``Sure,
Charlie, but what did you get from the other 10 apostles?'' Several
people snickered at the remark.
</P>
<P>
   Tribunal lawyers plan to grill him on how he allegedly pocketed
most of the $300,000 he raised for the liver transplant of his
close friend and deputy prime minister Brian Lenihan, who has since
died.
</P>
<P>
   Tribunal lawyers also want to ask Haughey how he suddenly paid
off the Allied Irish Bank in 1979, just before becoming prime
minister. By that time, his debt had grown to more than $1.5
million but he abruptly settled it after being a deadbeat for five
years. A developer claims he gave Haughey nearly half of the money
needed to settle the debt, but tribunal lawyers will be pressing
Haughey to name the other contributors.
</P>
<P>
   If Haughey refuses to name those who gave him money, the
tribunal lawyers say they will try to make him pay the cost of the
investigation, which so far is about $10 million. That will make
little dent in Haughey's estimated $150 million war chest.
</P>
<P>
   As he left the witness stand Friday, Haughey paused to sign an
autograph for Pat Cahill, a teacher. Haughey probably assumed that
Cahill was a fan, but Cahill later revealed himself to be anything
but.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very angry with Mr. Haughey,'' said Cahill, who asked for
the autograph as a souvenir rather than out of admiration.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks Haughey should be jailed, as do about two-thirds of
Irish people, according to recent polls. Cahill, 55, said his two
daughters had to move to Boston to find work as waitresses at Irish
pubs in the city's Dorchester section, while he and other Irish
workers were told by Haughey to tighten their belts in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like so many other young Irish people, my daughters had to go
abroad to find work. They had to live in Savin Hill (part of
Boston) instead of at home, and I was unable to get a pay rise
while Charlie Haughey and his cronies were getting rich. It isn't
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Haughey is nearly 75 and undergoing treatment for
prostate cancer, Moriarty said he would limit Haughey's testimony
to two hours a day. The tribunal will break for the summer next
Friday, meaning that Haughey will return to the stand in Septem
ber, and could remain there through much of the early fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8924 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-EXHIBITS-2NDTAKE-     07-21 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-EXHIBITS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: goes on.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Britain Museum
</P>
<P>
   The New Britain Museum of American Art is a prime stop on the
so-called Impressionist Art Trail, a group of Connecticut museums
with significant collections of American impressionist art. So it
is altogether fitting that the museum has mounted what it calls the
first major treatment of Connecticut impressionists in several
decades, with no fewer than half the 70 paintings in this mixed bag
of a show drawn from its permanent collection.
</P>
<P>
   Before the turn of the century, the shoreline art colonies in
Connecticut _ Cos Cob, Lyme and Mystic among them _ were a hotbed
of artists influenced by the French movement.
</P>
<P>
   Those who either lived in Connecticut or spent extensive periods
there included Childe Hassam, Julian Alden Weir, John Twachtman,
Theodore Robinson and Willard Metcalf, but there were plenty of
lesser-knowns as well as later also-rans who produced weak American
translations of the work of their French predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with this show is that it includes too many of the
latter, with the time line going all the way to the 1950s, well
past the golden age of American impressionism.
</P>
<P>
   Hassam, whose work looms large here, is best represented by a
big oil, ``On the Way to the Grand Prix'' (1887), a Paris scene of
horse-drawn carriages carrying fashionable revelers. A couple of
black-and-white etchings and lithographs uphold his reputation as a
printmaker. Weir, whose work is the subject of a comprehensive show
at the Bruce Museum, shines with ``Windham From Mullins Hill''
(circa 1895), a lyrical rural landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights include ``Noank, Conn.'' (1905) by Walter
Griffin, a peaceful late afternoon scene on the water in pale blue
light, and two lovely floral still lifes (circa 1885) by a
little-known artist, Charles Ethan Porter, inspired by the French
painter Henri Fantin-Latour.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Moment's Rest'' (undated), a poignant but light and airy
rendition of a mother watching her sleeping child, is the work of
another artist whose name rings few bells today, Louis Paul Dessar.
Although a bit late in the game, Ernest Lawson's large ``Spring
Tapestry'' (1930), a thawing landscape seen through a screen of
bare trees, makes a good impression.
</P>
<P>
   In short, this overly ambitious anthology offers the good, bad
and indifferent. A little editing would have helped.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Museum
</P>
<P>
   Another stop on the Connecticut Impressionist Art Trail, the
lively Bruce Museum, has zeroed in on the work of Julian Alden Weir
(1852-1919), whose Weir Farm _ his home and studio straddling
Ridgefield and Wilton _ is now a National Historic Site. ``A
Connecticut Place: Weir Farm, an American Painter's Rural Retreat''
displays more than 70 paintings, some by prominent artists who
visited him there, among them Hassam, Twachtman, John Singer
Sargent and Albert Pinkham Ryder.
</P>
<P>
   Weir, who began as an academic painter and whose impressionist
phase lasted only a decade, starting about 1890, is also
represented with some of his friends in the ``Connecticut
Impressionists'' show at the New Britain Museum. He acquired the
farm in 1882, and it became not only a beloved refuge from city
life but also the subject of more than 250 of his paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Outstanding among those shown at the Bruce in Greenwich are
``Lengthening Shadows'' (1887), a view along a winding path framed
by young trees to a sunny hilltop; ``Landscape: Branchville, the
Palace Car'' (early 1890s), a softly lighted springtime reverie
that includes a small shack on runners, known as the Palace Car,
that was drawn by oxen to different painting sites; and the
strongly brushed ``High Pasture'' (1899-1902), a gentle, summery
impression of rolling land, trees and shadows that tilts toward
abstraction.
</P>
<P>
   In his painting Weir never strayed far from the figure, and a
few figure and portrait subjects are also shown here, but the focus
of the show is rightly on landscape.
</P>
<P>
   In a nearby gallery ``Earth's Elusive Shores: The Art of Mapping
After 1500'' provides a fascinating look at how mapmaking evolved
after Gutenberg's invention of movable type, the voyages of
Columbus and other Europeans and the translation of Ptolemy's
second-century ``Geographia'' from Greek into Latin.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly 50 maps on view from the 16th and 17th centuries
range from crude, ill-informed endeavors to models of accuracy for
their day. They include treasures like Heinrich Buenting's
cloverleaf world map of 1581 with Jerusalem as its center, and
``Atlas of the Whole World'' (1570) by Abraham Ortelius, famed for
its beauty and fidelity to known fact.
</P>
<P>
   Aldrich Museum
</P>
<P>
   Eleven artists, some well known, some not, present videotapes
and mixed-media installations in this live-wire (to use an
old-brain term) show, meant to explore how the wily video medium
can affect the viewer's sense of time. ``Speed of Vision'' is the
Aldrich's first full video show, and to put the concept across, the
Ridgefield museum has divided itself into three ``time zones'':
slow motion, real time and hyperspeed. Hold on to your hat.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely on the slow-motion side is Nam June Paik's ``Buddha
Watching TV'' (1974-2000), a rare event in this artist's manic
work. A Buddha head, half buried in dirt, is in front of a
television monitor on which a similar Buddha head appears. The two
eye each other motionlessly, presumably until the end of time.
</P>
<P>
   Hovering on the very edge of hyper is Charles Atlas' ``Martha,
Martha, Martha, Martha, Martha,'' a tribute to the choreographer
Martha Graham. In it shots of Graham and dance images from every
source you can think of, including a series of nightclub events
previously devised by Atlas (even Martha Stewart appears,
presumably because of her name), are made into a five-monitor
collage that beguilingly blitzes the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   The better attractions also include Annika Eriksson's deadpan
``Connecticut Firefighters Pipes and Drums,'' a tape of a community
marching band in full regalia performing with military precision,
projected at movie-screen size in the same gallery where it was
shot, and Matthew McCaslin's ``Bloomer,'' a 12-monitor speeded-up
spectacular in which flowers appear as buds that, in split seconds,
miraculously burst into bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be passed up either are Jonas Akerlund's ``Ray of
Light,'' in which, to music by Madonna, the passage of a frenetic
24-hour urban day is compressed into five minutes of fly-by
imagery, and Doug Aitken's powerful ``Diamond Sea (Linear
Version),'' a rhythmic photographic essay on the desert, coast and
well-guarded diamond mines of Namibia.
</P>
<P>
   Give it real time; by and large ``Speed of Vision'' is more
rewarding than not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
