<HEADER>
A8925 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-REITS-$ADV23-N     07-21 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-REITS-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CAN REITs BECOME A TECHNOLOGY PLAY?  
 (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By SANA SIWOLOP  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Real estate investment trusts have played yin of late to the
technology sector's yang.
</P>
<P>
   When the technology-laden Nasdaq composite index has risen,
shares of REITs have generally fallen, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts and money managers suggest that investors look
to certain REITs as technology plays in and of themselves. They
point to the growing number of REITs that are either actively
investing in technology to improve their businesses, or that cater
to the real estate needs of e-commerce companies, which often
require huge distribution facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts recommend that investors also keep tabs on those
REITs that are busy rolling out new high-speed, high-bandwidth
telecommunications and Internet services for their tenants. These
companies, they say, are poised to benefit from the federal REIT
Modernization Act of 1999, which, when it takes effect in January,
will allow REITs to widely offer nontraditional services like
landscaping, parcel delivery, concierge services and
telecommunications _ to their own tenants as well as to other
parties.
</P>
<P>
   REITs are now allowed to generate only 5 percent of revenue from
such ancillary services. The new law is ``probably the biggest
development in the REIT industry since 1986, when REITs were
permitted to both own and manage real estate,'' said Anthony R.
Davis, an analyst at UBS Warburg Dillon Read.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some experts say investors may be getting carried away if
they think that the REIT sector will furnish the world's next Cisco
Systems. Arthur J. Hurley, portfolio manager for the SSGA/Tuckerman
Active REIT fund, said technology, at least in the near term, would
benefit REITs mostly by allowing them to operate more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley pointed to AvalonBay Communities of Alexandria, Va., an
apartment REIT that is already using an Internet-based system for
leasing and managing its properties. ``It's not too early to look
for technology plays in this industry, but it's too early to look
for revenue streams,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, as REITs keep focusing on owning or managing real
estate, Davis said, only 4 to 5 cents a share in funds from
operations typically come from ancillary services.
</P>
<P>
   But that's for now. He said income from ancillary services would
grow at least 20 to 40 percent annually over the next four to five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Jay P. Leupp, a managing director at FleetBoston Robertson
Stephens, said the industry's overall technology investments might
account for 10 to 20 percent of its revenue by the end of 2002.
While bullish on the technological promise of REITs, Leupp urged
investors to scrutinize the managers of REITs that are moving into
new service areas.
</P>
<P>
   Davis agreed. ``The mistake that some REITs will make is to go
too fast and too much, and lose sight of their core businesses, so
it all boils down to management, '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the industrial real estate market, Leupp says two early
leaders are ProLogis Trust of Aurora, Colo., and AMB Property of
San Francisco, which is already building large distribution
facilities for electronic commerce companies like the Webvan Group,
the online grocer. As for office REITs, he says he thinks the
leader in that market is Equity Office Properties Trust of Chicago,
which is aggressively rolling out high-tech telecommunication
services to its office tenants. Leupp also likes Spieker Properties
of Menlo Park, Calif., which owns and manages both office and
industrial space.
</P>
<P>
   Among shopping-center REITs, Leupp likes Pan Pacific Retail
Properties, an operator of strip centers that is based in Vista,
Calif. He says it has invested in a service that lets shoppers do
online comparison-shopping among tenants of the company's shopping
centers.
</P>
<P>
   Both Leupp and Davis say the Simon Property Group of
Indianapolis is the technology leader among REITs that are focused
on malls. They cite the 50 percent stake that Simon holds in
MerchantWired, a high-speed communications network that will
provide retailers with services like the ability to authorize a
credit card purchase in less than two seconds.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
