A8926 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-JOEMURRAY-SUBCOLUMN22     07-21 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-SUBCOLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: CORRECTED NAME OF ``THE ANDY GRIFFITH SHOW'' IN SIX GRAF.
CHANGED 'his'' TO ``her'' IN THIRD FROM LAST GRAF.
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Here's a tip: Appreciate a good
waitress
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I love good waitresses. If I had my way, along
with Mother's Day and Secretary's Day, there would be a special day
to honor good waitresses everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Sad to say, not all waitresses everywhere are good. Here's a
couple of waitress stories, one good and one bad.
</P>
<P>
   Story No. 1:
</P>
<P>
   An older fellow, obviously a cafe regular, had been kidding with
the waitress, no youngster herself, since he sat down at his booth.
</P>
<P>
   Not only were they on a first-name basis, it seemed that they
were also neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've noticed you had a lot of company visiting this week,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Lordy, yes,'' she sighed. ``Too much, if you want to know
the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   She was sort of an Aunt Bea type from the old TV series ``The
Andy Griffith Show,'' and worked her tables quickly and
efficiently, bustling from one to another with a friendly word for
each customer.
</P>
<P>
   But anybody can make a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lookee here,'' the older fellow said, raising his voice to
reach her several tables away. ``I ain't got no spoon. I ain't got
no ice water. I ain't got no _ ``
</P>
<P>
   At which point she broke into song:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahhhhhhhhhhh ain't got nobody,'' she warbled, ``and nobody
cares for me!''
</P>
<P>
   Smiling grandly, she added, ``Do you remember that old song?''
</P>
<P>
   By the time she returned with a spoon and a glass of ice water,
he was still laughing, and so was most everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   Good waitress!
</P>
<P>
   Story No. 2:
</P>
<P>
   A man came into a cafe at noontime, sat down on a counter stool
and, holding the menu in one hand and massaging his swollen jaw
with the other, considered the choices.
</P>
<P>
   The waitress, a younger, no-nonsense type, had her pencil poised
to take his order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just come from the dentist,'' he said, wincing as he
spoke. ``I'm not sure I can manage to chew much of anything, but
maybe an egg sandwich would be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   She shook her head and frowned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We serve egg sandwiches only at breakfast,'' she said, her
lips pursed. ``You'll have to select something from the lunch
menu.''
</P>
<P>
   The customer made a groaning noise. At the same time, so did the
man sitting on the stool next to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, come on,'' the other fellow said to waitress. ``He's just
had his teeth worked on. He doesn't have any other choice. Surely,
it can't be that much trouble to fix him an egg sandwich.''
</P>
<P>
   The waitress paused, thought for a half-moment, but then shook
her head again.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we're using the grill for hamburgers and -- ``
</P>
<P>
   ``And you can use the grill for eggs, too,'' he said, his voice
a bit stern, his glare a bit demanding. ``Just this once, all
right?''
</P>
<P>
   Without a word to either of them, she whirled around and stomped
off toward the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``One ... egg ... sandwich,'' she all but yelled.
</P>
<P>
   The man with the sore mouth turned to his benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' he said, nodding. ``Thank you very much!''
</P>
<P>
   And he got his egg sandwich, ate it, paid his bill and left,
never knowing that the man next to him just happened to be the cafe
owner.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't have known, either, that the particular waitress _
who couldn't be agreeable even with her boss, much less the
customers _ would soon be looking for a new job.
</P>
<P>
   Bad waitress. Good story.
</P>
<P>
   (P.S. Observe Good Waitress Day every day. Tip generously.)
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
