<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TOUR-TEACHERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELLEY GOES BACK TO SCHOOL WITH NEW FOX TEACHER DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ He has done lawyers on ``L.A. Law,'' ``The
Practice'' and ``Ally McBeal.'' He's done doctors on ``Chicago
Hope.'' He's even done small-town folk on ``Picket Fences.''
</P>
<P>
   But David E. Kelley says he has been wanting to do a series
about teachers for a long time, and, like an assignment for extra
credit, he just never got around to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blessing of a series being successful, like `The Practice'
and `Ally McBeal,' is also a curse that you've got to wait before
you get to the next one,'' the prolific writer/producer said. ``So
this has been gestating with me for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Ally McBeal'' and ``The Practice'' are still going
strong on Fox and ABC, respectively, on Oct. 23 Kelley will give
birth to Fox's ``Boston Public,'' another ensemble drama about
imperfect people trying to do the right thing, usually for the
right reasons, sometimes for the wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley, who grew up in the Boston suburbs and went to law school
at Boston University, says teachers are his heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that teachers are the most powerful people in
the world and the least recognized,'' he said. `I've just always
admired the commitment that teachers have, how they stay committed
in the face of a world that is so often without immediate reward.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley, whose portrayal of heightened reality usually gets him
in hot water with the particular group he is depicting, will no
doubt hear from educators who don't appreciate some of the antics
of his characters on ``Boston Public,'' but he is steadfastly
unapologetic in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you knew the stories that I'm already getting from teachers
_ `You wouldn't believe what's happened to me' or `You wouldn't
believe what's happened in our school' _ a lot of those things I
won't dare tell in the first few episodes because you'll think it
couldn't be true,'' Kelley said. ``But those things are happening,
and maybe one of the reasons they continue to happen is that there
is an ignorance out there that these kinds of things don't go on.''
</P>
<P>
   When last we saw special agents Mulder and Scully, the former
appeared to be taking a trip on an alien spaceship, and the latter
revealed she was in a family way.
</P>
<P>
   Can it be? Mulder gonzo? Scully prego?
</P>
<P>
   Chris Carter, the man with all the answers when it comes to
``The X-Files,'' says we'd better believe it. 'Course, this is the
same guy who once said the series would end after seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepares for an eighth, Carter told TV critics this week
that David Duchovny will appear in 11 of the 20 episodes this
season and that Robert Patrick (``Terminator 2'') will come aboard
to play special agent John Doggett.
</P>
<P>
   Doggett will be the new man in Scully's life, but not her
partner in any sense. Carter describes Doggett as a ``knee-jerk
skeptic,'' a by-the-book FBI veteran who is as much an insider as
Mulder is an outsider. (And for all you baseball fans, the name
Doggett was inspired by Jerry Doggett, former broadcast partner of
L.A. Dodgers play-by-play man Vin Scully, the inspiration for
Gillian Anderson's Dana Scully.)
</P>
<P>
   Carter is aware that Duchovny's occasional appearances on the
show and Patrick's addition to the cast may eliminate the sexual
tension between Mulder and Scully that has always given ``The
X-Files'' its special cachet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's afraid of change,'' he admitted. ``Everyone says,
`That's what made the show work, and that's what's great about the
show.' That's true, David and Gillian are the reason for the show's
great success. But that doesn't mean you can't threaten the
paradigm, you can't threaten the model, you can't threaten the
relationship. I think, dramatically, you'd better do that every
once in a while, or else you're going to have a very stale show.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's season premiere is scheduled Nov. 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
