<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8932 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-CUSTOMER-SERVICE-     07-21 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CUSTOMER-SERVICE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: he asked. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a result, turnover on customer service desks runs as high as
100 percent per year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One author has even suggested that dissatisfaction has to do
with customers' experiences with good service. Dr. Leonard Berry, a
professor of marketing at Texas A&AMP;M University and author of
``Discovering the Soul of Service'' (Free Press, 1999), agreed that
service was not good. ``I give service in America a C minus,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, Berry added, people's expectations for
service are rising. ``We want better service even though we think
we'll get worse service,'' he said. ``And part of the reason is
because we have experienced excellent service enough to know that
it's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the explanation, there seems to be no dispute about the
reality of the decline. Complaints to the Better Business Bureau
have risen sharply in recent years, said Ron Berry (no relation to
Leonard Berry), senior vice president of the Council of Better
Business Bureaus in Arlington, Va. Even so, Berry added, only a
small percentage of disgruntled customers actually file formal
complaints to bureaus.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Barany, an educational consultant in New York, is a
conspicuous exception. In March, she bought a Sony VAIO notebook
computer at Data Vision, a computer retailer in Manhattan, but she
was unable to get the computer to work properly. After several
rounds of phone calls and repeated trips to the store, she sent off
a raft of letters and copies to the Better Business Bureau, Sony,
The New York Times, Data Vision and American Express, whose card
she used to pay for the machine.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, last month, Data Vision allowed Barany to exchange her
computer for a less expensive IBM Thinkpad. The difference in price
was issued as a store credit.
</P>
<P>
   But Barany is unhappy with the store credit. She wants a refund.
</P>
<P>
   Every dispute has at least two sides. Jim Garson, a vice
president of Data Vision, said that there was nothing wrong with
Barany's laptop and that all it needed was a software patch for the
internal modem. He said that he had offered to install the software
for her but that she had declined. By allowing her to trade for the
newer computer, he said, he took a loss on the old one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take back a notebook three months later, especially
when there's nothing wrong with it,'' he said. ``How much more
customer service can you give?''
</P>
<P>
   Garson said many of the complaints against his store were
unfounded. One customer called Garson to say she had bought an
Olympus camera a year ago and seldom used it, so she wanted to
return it, he said. ``I said: `Ma'am, there's nothing I can do. Try
to sell it on eBay.''' She complained to the Better Business
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Some consumers do not feel satisfied unless they make themselves
heard. Julie Kennedy, a corporate lawyer in San Francisco, is a
customer service maven if ever there was one.
</P>
<P>
   On the phone, she always presses ``0'' immediately to reach a
human. She shops only in stores that will give refunds, and she has
no qualms about firing off a letter if she is dissatisfied. ``I
think there's a social contract that goes beyond courtesy,''
Kennedy said. ``You pay someone money and you expect to be valued.
It ticks me off when I find people so oblivious to that
principle.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy also makes a point of sending a letter when she
stumbles upon excellent service.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Kennedy called United Airlines to reserve a
flight to Ireland, using her free miles. Dodging the thicket of
blackout dates made the task look formidable until she found an
agent as interested in making the trip work as she was.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying everything,'' she said. ``I was on the phone
with him for over two hours. He tried every date, every time, and I
got to use my free tickets.'' She sent a letter of praise to the
airline.
</P>
<P>
   Another consumer who keeps careful watch over the service he
gets is Jim Hobby. He has a professional interest in the subject as
well: he is vice president of customer client care at Gateway and
has spent 25 years in the customer service business, including time
at American Express and Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids call me the client from hell,'' he said. ``They say
when they're out with me and I get this look, they run, because
they know someone is going to get my lecture on what customer
service should be.''
</P>
<P>
   What customer service should be, he said, is a collection of
thoughtfully placed ``pleases'' and ``thank yous,'' combined with
careful listening. These are known as soft skills. ``It's showing
that you care and you want to work with the customer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Service via live chat is growing in popularity, Hobby said, and
so is the use of e-mail for such interactions. Gateway has also
simplified its automated phone system in response to what Hobby
described as a great deal of customer frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Complaining is getting easier in some places. Many companies
that emphasize customer service, like American Express, now let
customers dispute charges on line.
</P>
<P>
   The Better Business Bureau has seen a rise in the number of
online complaints it gets. And a growing number of sites dedicated
to filing gripes are cropping up online.
</P>
<P>
   One such site, called uGetHeard.com, allows consumers to send
both gripes and praise. Complaints are followed by efforts by
uGetHeard.com to resolve the disputes. The average resolution is
small _ around $50 _ but the gratification for the customer is
beyond measure, said Michael Chen, the site's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Chen said he was inspired to set up the site after a
particularly unpleasant experience he had last spring at a private
mailing center in the San Francisco Bay Area, where he went to mail
a package. After paying, he grew nervous when he saw that no one
was wrapping the package, so he decided to do it himself.
</P>
<P>
   But when an employee demanded that he pay for the sealing tape
he was using, he protested. After a while the manager emerged from
the back. ``She said: `You're really irritating. We're too busy to
deal with you,''' Chen recalled. ``I've never been spoken to like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   That was all the impetus he needed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
