<SLUG> BC-NET-CONVENTIONS-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET WILL PICK UP WHERE TV LEAVES OFF AT POLITICAL
CONVENTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Friday, July 21, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 Editors: Material at bottom is suitable for graphics box 
 By J. SCOTT ORR  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Political junkies, fear not: The Internet has got your fix.
</P>
<P>
   As the television networks retreat from coverage of the
Democratic and Republican national conventions this summer, dozens
of Internet sites are poised to take up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   From the skyboxes to the convention floor, keynote speeches to
behind-the- scenes chatter, online journalists will be converging
on the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia and the
Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles in heretofore
unimagined numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1996, there were two of us covering the conventions for
online magazines. This time there will be hundreds, maybe
thousands,'' said Jacob Weisberg, chief political correspondent for
the online magazine Slate.
</P>
<P>
   While the networks turn up their noses at gavel-to-gavel
coverage of the conventions, Web operations like America Online,
Voter.com, Pseudo.com, C-SPAN.com, FedNet.com and many more will be
beaming live coverage of the quadrennial political gab-fests to
desktops around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the television networks scale back their coverage of the
political conventions, we are stepping up ... convention
programming,'' said Kathleen deLaski, director of political
programming at America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Both conventions have designated special areas for online media
for the first time: Internet Alley for the Republicans and Internet
Avenue for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Keenan, deputy director of the Senate Press Gallery, said
the gallery issued convention credentials for more than 70 online
organizations and that doesn't count those that applied through the
Radio and TV Gallery and the Periodicals Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has definitely been a dramatic increase. Last time we
had only one online news service apply and it went out of business
before the conventions began,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the lack of any real political drama, all of the major
networks are planning to scale back coverage of the conventions.
ABC is opting to air exhibition NFL football games on the opening
nights of both conventions. Wider coverage is planned on cable
stations C-SPAN, CNN, Fox News Channel and MSNBC. The Republican
convention begins on July 31 and the Democratic one on Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``First off, the networks are not going to be providing much
coverage,'' said Michael Bustamante of Voter.com. ``Secondly, with
the Internet, individuals have the ability to get the information
they want when they want it. If it's 1 in the morning and they're
just getting home, they can look at what's going on and everything
they missed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is fast becoming the medium of choice for political
junkies, according to a survey done for American University's
Center for Congressional and Presidential Studies.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 1,005 people taken last March found that 19 percent
said the Internet is a ``very important'' source of political news,
while another 32 percent said it is ``somewhat important.''
Eighteen percent said it was ``not very important'' and 21 percent
said it was ``not important at all.''
</P>
<P>
   What that means for Internet news and entertainment sites is
that a sector of the public is hungry for the kind of
around-the-clock political coverage only the Web can provide.
</P>
<P>
   The online news operations see the conventions as an opportunity
to demonstrate the advantages of a medium that is not reliant on
ratings like the networks and not tied to deadlines and delivery
restraints like newspapers and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Some predict that the around-the-clock coverage capabilities of
the Internet could lead to changes in the conventions themselves,
which have been tailored over the years to meet the needs of the
prime-time media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a problem for us that the conventions are still revolving
around the broadcast media, so all the major events are happening
in the evening. Things might be different next time around once it
becomes clear that daytime events will be covered,'' said Keith
Carney of FedNet, which will be providing live video feed from the
conventions to Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   David Bohrman, CEO of Pseudo.com, said he expects the Internet
to have the same kind of effect on the conventions that television
did when it was first used at the 1948 Republican convention, also
held in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty years ago, TV technology changed politics by ushering in
the era of the sound bite. This year, (Internet) technology will
open up the process again,'' Bohrman said. Pseudo.com will
broadcast live video from skyboxes at both conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Pseudo and the television networks in the skyboxes is
America Online, the nation's largest Internet service provider with
22 million subscribers. AOL plans live gavel-to-gavel coverage of
the events and ``24-hour access to newsmakers and events.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the explosive growth in use of the Internet since the
1996 convention, technological advances also are contributing to
the massive increase in online coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Most important is the increase in bandwidth that speeds the flow
of data between computers and allows video signals to travel the
Internet. The technology is far from perfect, though, and the video
images most people will see will be no bigger than a playing card.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology wasn't there in '96,'' said FedNet's Carney.
``There was audio technology, but there was not sufficient video
technology during the last election. That's where the real change
will be seen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most innovative new technologies to be offered for
the conventions come from Congressional Quarterly, which will be
feeding hourly reports to hundred of reporters and others via
wireless Motorola two-way e-mail devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition to get information out has never been this
intense,'' said David Rapp of Congressional Quarterly. ``It's a
whole new world in the political news business.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of the Internet sites that will be offering
coverage of the Republican National Convention, July 31-Aug. 3, and
the Democratic National Convention, Aug. 14-17.
</P>
<P>
   American Online keyword: Election 2000
</P>
<P>
   C-SPAN: www.cspan.org
</P>
<P>
   FedNet: www.fednet.net
</P>
<P>
   Pseudo.com: www.pseudopolitics.com
</P>
<P>
   Salon: www.salon.com
</P>
<P>
   Slate: slate.msn.com
</P>
<P>
   Voter.com: www.voter.com
</P>
</TEXT>
