<HEADER>
A8943 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-FOSSIL-SALE-NEWHOUSE &LR;      07-21 1623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSSIL-SALE-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUCTION OF FOSSIL SETS OFF ARGUMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Friday, July 21, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: 2 photos, of Siefker (NNS1) and fossil (NNS2). 
 By MARY KATE FRANK And MARK MUELLER  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In August 1960, three teen-age boys with a passion for old bones
made the discovery of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Siefker, Michael Bandrowski and Joseph Geiler,
dust-covered fossil hunters who regularly plumbed the earth for
ancient secrets, knew there was something important about the
winged reptile they found embedded in the rock of a North Bergen
quarry.
</P>
<P>
   They were right.
</P>
<P>
   Little bigger than a dragonfly, Icarosaurus siefkeri, as the 200
million-year-old relic would later be called, took the scientific
world by storm, showing that vertebrates glided through the air far
earlier than previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, the once-famous fossil is again grabbing
attention.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 27, Siefker, who maintains possession of the prehistoric
prize that bears his name, will put it on the auction block for a
minimum bid of $250,000. The Los Angeles auction house handling the
deal suspects the fossil could fetch much more.
</P>
<P>
   But the sale, which Siefker contends is necessary to help pay
medical bills he incurred after suffering a debilitating stroke, is
tinged with controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Some paleontologists call the idea of an auction an appalling
intrusion of modern commercialism into a scholarly field that
traditionally shuns such acts.
</P>
<P>
   And Siefker's old digging partners were unaware the fossil even
had been removed from the American Museum of Natural History in New
York, its resting place for three decades before Siefker demanded
its return in 1989. Geiler and Bandrowski said this week they had
no idea Siefker was planning to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Both dispute that Siefker, 56, unearthed the fossil on that
overcast afternoon in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found it,'' Bandrowski, 55, of Cliffside Park, N.J., said
this week when alerted to the auction. He declined further comment.
It was unclear whether he plans to seek a portion of the fossil's
sale price.
</P>
<P>
   Geiler, also 55 and now living in Cambridge, Ohio, backs up
Bandrowski's account. Moreover, as Geiler remembers it, Siefker
wasn't even there when he and Bandrowski struck archaeological
gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went home with Michael,'' Geiler said. ``Some time later,
Mike showed it to Al, and immediately Al wanted to bargain for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Geiler said Siefker, then 16, made Bandrowski an offer for the
fossil that he couldn't refuse: a telescope and $30. Today Siefker,
who lives in North Bergen, says he doesn't remember the trade,
though in a 1989 newspaper story about the fossil he acknowledged
the deal. But he insists he helped unearth the fossil. ``It was
like seeing the Grand Canyon for the first time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Geiler, for his part, said he isn't particularly troubled by the
auction. ``At this point, science has already studied it,'' he
said. If the money from the Icarosaurus will help Siefker's health,
then the sale ``is not the end of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   To this day, the find, the only complete imprint of the
Icarosaurus siefkeri, remains a significant one.
</P>
<P>
   The creature lived an estimated 200 million years ago, in the
late Triassic period, predating dinosaurs and Archaeopteryx,
evolution's first true bird, by 50 million years. Resembling a
large dragonfly, the Icarosaurus measured 7 inches long and
stretched 10 inches from wingtip to wingtip.
</P>
<P>
   At the time it was found, the Icarosaurus became the oldest
airborne vertebrate known to scientists. Its discovery was a
monumental event that shed new light on prehistoric times.
</P>
<P>
   Unveiling the fossil with great fanfare at the American Museum
of Natural History in New York in 1961, Edwin H. Colbert, then the
museum's chairman, said the discovery upended science's known
timetable on animals' first airborne efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It proves that vertebrates attempted flight some 10 million
years earlier than anyone suspected,'' Colbert said.
</P>
<P>
   The shape of the fossil's delicate webbed wings and its
elongated ribs indicated the creature couldn't actually fly,
Colbert said. Instead, the Icarosaurus siefkeri glided from tree to
tree, in the manner of a flying squirrel.
</P>
<P>
   Avid amateur fossil hunters who hoped at the time to become
paleontologists, Siefker, Geiler and Bandrowski prowled North
Bergen's Granton Quarry at every opportunity, collecting dozens of
fish fossils dating back hundreds of millions of years.
</P>
<P>
   Over long hours, they patiently chipped at pieces of soft black
shale, gingerly sifted through dirt and carefully studied what
others might regard as mere rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Geiler called the discovery of the Icarosaurus ``pure, dumb
luck.'' He remembers spending hours helping Bandrowski extricate
the bones as the sky grew dark and a soft drizzle began to fall.
The two boys were 15 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that Mike was very excited that he might've found
something that was extremely different,'' Geiler said. ``That was
probably the reason why we stayed longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Siefker soon became the bones' caretaker. Museum officials later
named the creature after him, a customary honor bestowed on fossil
finders.
</P>
<P>
   For three months, Siefker kept the Icarosaurus in the bedroom of
his West New York home. Using needles, he cleaned the specimen
carefully ``every night till I got tired.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a feeling it was very important,'' he said. ``I was very
careful with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But during one of the nightly cleanings, Siefker punched a hole
in the creature's left arm bone. Worried, he told his science
teacher about the mishap and was advised to take the fossil to the
American Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, Siefker turned over his prized relic to the museum
for ``safekeeping,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, he said, gave him a receipt stating that the fossil
was on loan for study purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The museum spent months cleaning and studying the fossil before
putting it on display in April of 1961.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   All three boys, hailed as heroes by the national media, were
present at the exhibit's unveiling. Time magazine noted their
achievement on April 14, 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Siefker's fame, however fleeting, lasted slightly longer than
the exposure enjoyed by his teen-age buddies. At one point, he
appeared on the popular television game show ``To Tell the Truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Smitten with science more than ever, the three friends worked
together after school in the museum's vertebrate paleontology
laboratory, cleaning specimens and preparing them for study.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the creature -- previously unnamed -- was designated the
``Icarosaurus siefkeri.'' The museum's action irritated Siefker,
who claimed scientists promised him he could choose the moniker.
Siefker's choice: ``Siefkerosaurus.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 30 years, Siefker was content to leave the fossil
with the museum. That changed in 1989, when Siefker, with no income
at the time, decided to sell the piece.
</P>
<P>
   When the museum balked, Siefker sued the revered institution for
$60 million. The museum relented.
</P>
<P>
   With the Icarosaurus back in his possession, Siefker shopped it
around, seeking $5 million, said David Herskowitz, a natural
history specialist for California-based Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield,
which is handling next month's auction.
</P>
<P>
   Informing Siefker the price was too high, the auction house
declined to sell the fossil, Herskowitz said, adding that Siefker
also pitched the petrified remains to museums. There were no
takers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Siefker was dealing with the effects of a
stroke he suffered within a year of reclaiming the fossil.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, mounting medical bills persuaded him to lower his
selling price.
</P>
<P>
   When the auction takes place next month in Los Angeles, it will
be simulcast in the agency's San Francisco office and carried live
over the Internet, Herskowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's priceless,'' he said of the fossil. He added that he has
received more catalog requests for the Icarosaurus sale than for
any other natural history auction.
</P>
<P>
   While the auction house expects bidding to reach $350,000,
Herskowitz said he wouldn't be surprised if dinosaur fever drives
the price considerably higher.
</P>
<P>
   But if Herskowitz and Siefker are optimistic about the prospects
of a bidding war, some paleontologists are hoping the auction is a
bust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good fossils ought to be in museums where they get proper care
and attention,'' said Colbert, the former chairman at the American
Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   Now 95 and working as a research assistant at the Museum of
Northern Arizona in Flagstaff, Colbert said the chance that the
fossil could end up with a private owner is reason enough not to
auction it off at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``In private collections, they usually suffer damage or are
lost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Icarosaurus fossil, Colbert added, is particularly
vulnerable because of its delicate, hollow bones.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary Kate Frank and Mark Mueller are staff writers for The
Star-Ledger of Newark, N.J. Staff writer John Yocca contributed to
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
