<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ The Israeli peace delegation's
mood shifted toward the hopeful Friday as officials outside the
secluded Camp David revealed that Prime Minister Ehud Barak, two
days after summoning his plane to leave and then sending it back to
the hangar, believed the chances for the peace summit meeting's
success had improved considerably. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   G8-CLINTON (Naha, Japan) _ Russian President Vladimir Putin
continued to make the case against a national missile shield being
proposed by the United States in a meeting with President Clinton
Friday night, but Clinton, despite a failed test earlier this
month, refused to back down from the controversial defense program.
By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-LIBEL-LAW (Undated) _ In the United States, with its
ironclad belief in the right to free speech, libel plaintiffs need
to prove not only that the speech in question is false, but also
that it was published with a reckless disregard for the truth. In
England, the burden is in the other direction: The offending speech
is presumed to be false, and it is up to defendants to prove that
it is in fact true. That tends to have a dampening effect on what
newspapers print and what publishers include in books, especially
when the material is likely to offend someone who is powerful, rich
or particularly litigious. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
