<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOARD-DIRECTORS-$ADV23-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO YOU WANT TO BECOME A CORPORATE DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corporate boards aren't what they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   The average length of tenure is dropping and turnover is rising.
More seats are going to outside directors. Chief executives are
joining fewer boards, the better to focus attention on the ones
they choose.
</P>
<P>
   This evolution, over the last decade, has made boards better at
dispensing tough, objective advice, say corporate governance
experts, and may even be playing a role in American companies'
current run of success.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes also mean that there are many more opportunities
than before to become a director for the first time _ if you can
catch the eye of a recruiter or a nominating committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, boards mainly found new members through their
existing members,'' said Peter D. Crist, the vice chairman of
Korn/Ferry International, the executive search firm, who spends
about half his time filling directorships. ``We've tended to move
away from that model, although it certainly still occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the competition is tough. The valuable career-building
experience of serving on a board, not to mention the prestige,
stock options and other perquisites that come with a director's
seat, attract many more interested people than there are openings.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say executives can take a number of specific steps to
improve their chances. Some are obvious _ like adding overseas
experience or a successfully executed Internet strategy to a
curriculum vitae. Others are more subtle.
</P>
<P>
   Following are some strategies that management experts suggest
for getting your name among the most promising candidates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SET THE STAGE _ Most companies, and virtually all large ones,
want their directors to have experience running something big _ a
company, a division, a business unit _ of their own. Executives do
not usually reach this level, generally executive vice president or
chief financial officer, until their 40s or later. But recruiters
say up-and-comers in their 30s can take steps now to help
themselves in the future.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Ilene S. Gordon, then in her late 30s, was a
rising executive in Chicago. She had put in some time at Boston
Consulting Group, but most of her experience was in the packaging
industry. ``I wanted to get on a board to be exposed to broader
issues,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   So she did what she could to get noticed. She joined the
Economic Club of Chicago and volunteered for the membership
committee, allowing her to meet many local executives. She also
signed up with two networking groups for women and, later, became a
director of a hospital in Evanston, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Gordon serves on two corporate boards _ at A.J. Gallagher
and United Stationers _ and has completed terms at three others.
</P>
<P>
   Executives recruiters say her approach _ working hard to meet
people outside her company and joining the board of a nonprofit
organization _ are among the most effective strategies for aspiring
directors.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit groups are often eager for advice, and may be more
willing than a corporation to name a younger manager who is
enthusiastic about the group's mission. A stint on a nonprofit's
board yields a sense of how boards function in general and a chance
to meet other director-level executives.
</P>
<P>
   PUT YOUR NETWORK TO WORK _ The chief executive of almost every
big company in the country receives stacks of board invitations but
turns most of them down. But a growing number of bosses take
advantage of the requests to refer their lieutenants for board
seats.
</P>
<P>
   Some are even more proactive. John Hawkins, a recruiter at
Russell Reynolds, a search firm, says he has received calls in
recent months from three chairmen, asking him to meet with
high-ranking executives at their companies and size them up for
directorships.
</P>
<P>
   More than friendship is involved: the chairmen hope that their
proteges will learn from executives at other companies and become
stronger potential chief executives, Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   The message for aspiring board members is clear: If the chance
presents itself, tell your boss that you think that joining an
outside board could make you more effective at your own job. Few
bosses are likely to be put off by this, because most were once in
the same position. ``I felt it was important, to prepare myself to
be CEO, to have the experience of being on an outside board,'' said
Sidney Taurel, the chief executive of Eli Lilly, who is now on the
boards of ITT and McGraw-Hill.
</P>
<P>
   It also makes sense to let an executive recruiter know about
your interest. But an unsolicited letter is not usually the most
effective strategy, recruiters say. ``I get letters every day, and
I read them,'' Crist said. ``But clearly, as you can imagine, if
someone is introduced to me by a friend or someone I respect, I'm
going to pay attention to that,'' more closely than an
over-the-transom note from a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Osar was the treasurer of Tenneco in 1997 when, during a
performance review, the chief financial officer told her that
joining a board would be an important way to broaden her
experience, she said. Osar then called a recruiter she knew and
expressed her interest. The recruiter set up a breakfast for her in
New York with a colleague of his who specializes in board searches
_ Hawkins. Within a year, Hawkins had connected her with Allergan,
the pharmaceuticals company, which made her a director. Osar is now
the chief financial officer of Westvaco, a packaging company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   SEE FIRSTHAND, AND BE SEEN _ One of the best ways for executives
to learn how boards work _ and, in turn, to become attractive
candidates _ is to get in front of the board at their own
companies, recruiters say.
</P>
<P>
   ``CEOs want to know that whoever's coming on their board
understands the dynamic,'' said Andrea Reynolds, a managing
director at Russell Reynolds. That means leaping at any assignment
that might result in a presentation to directors.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, the experience may lead to an invitation to
join another board _ on which one of your own company's directors
already serves. At the least, the experience adds an important
credential to a dossier, recruiters said.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing beats actually serving on a board, and management
experts say small companies can provide the ideal initial
directorship for many executives. ``At some point, you have to do
your starter-upper board,'' Crist said.
</P>
<P>
   Such a board, he said, lets a new director have an immediate
effect by providing a perspective not previously represented.
</P>
<P>
   KNOW WHAT YOU WANT _ Once elected to a first board, an executive
should forswear other board assignments for a few years, recruiters
said.
</P>
<P>
   Being a productive director typically requires more than 150
hours a year, on top of one's day job. New directors should devote
their energy exclusively to the first company that trusts them with
a director's chair (unless lightning strikes and Ford or Coca-Cola
calls).
</P>
<P>
   When Judith A. Sprieser became the chief financial officer of
Sara Lee six years ago, she was already on the board of a much
smaller manufacturing company. Her promotion led to a flood of new
board offers, she said, but she turned them down, choosing to focus
on her new job and to wait for an invitation from a company that
was similar in size.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard, because there were a lot of very, very
interesting companies,'' said Sprieser, who last week became the
chief executive of Transora.com, a business-to-business exchange
for the food industry. But the forbearance paid off last year, she
said, when she received an offer to serve on the board of Allstate
_ which brings in more revenue than Sara Lee and is also based in
Chicago, minimizing the travel time away from her family.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T LOSE SIGHT OF THE BASICS _ Executives can increase their
odds of board selection in many ways, but recruiters say the most
important is also the most obvious: ``The best way to get on a
board is to do your job,'' said Ted Jadick, a managing partner in
the board practice of Heidrick &AMP; Struggles in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Crist added: ``Just do exactly what you're paid to do
exceedingly well. You will be found. I guarantee it.''
</P>
<P>
   A sense of serenity can help, too. The selection process for
almost any board is complex and carefully calibrated, having as
much to do with the group's current makeup as with the credentials
of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the keys here is, be patient,'' Hawkins said. An
executive may rise to president or chief financial officer of his
company, he added, but his selection to an outside board ``may not
happen even in the first year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very quirky,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1702EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
