<SLUG> BC-McCAIN-VEEP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN STIRS SPECULATION AS BUSH'S VEEP  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 By STEWART M. POWELL   
 c.2000 Hearst Newspapers    WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
the feisty maverick who galvanized independent voters with a
populist crusade that won seven presidential primaries, stirred
speculation Friday that he would be willing to join the Republican
ticket as George W. Bush's vice presidential running mate. McCain
and his allies repeatedly declined to rule out the possibility that
the three-term senator would accept an invitation from Bush to join
the GOP ticket. McCain coyly insisted Friday that ``nothing has
changed'' since he told a news conference in Pittsburgh in May _
following a private post-primary reconciliation summit with Bush _
that he did not want to be considered as Bush's running mate. ``But
if Gov. Bush called, I'd certainly like to talk to him about the
weather and how things are going and how good a campaign he's
running,'' McCain added.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A McCain associate who is close to the three-term senator
elaborated, saying that even though McCain did not wish to be
considered for the No. 2 post and ``would prefer that Gov. Bush not
offer him the job, if he did, he would serve.''
</P>
<P>
   The associate added, speaking on condition of anonymity: ``If
Sen. McCain is asked by Gov. Bush to serve his country, he would _
he can't say `no' to that.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain indicated that he didn't think he was on Bush's short
list of running mates, telling CNN that he had ``not been vetted or
asked for my tax returns or anything like that. I do not believe
that I'm in the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain associate raised the possibility that McCain and Bush
might get together following their attendance at the Atlanta
funeral of the late Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what happens,'' the associate said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But Nancy Ives, who serves as McCain's Senate press secretary,
said that the senator had ``no plans'' to meet privately with Bush
before flying home to Arizona for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, engulfed by mounting speculation over his choice for a
vice presidential running mate, began a weekend of planned
seclusion at his sprawling ranch in Crawford, Texas on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to make up my mind over the weekend,'' Bush said,
adding: ``The days of speculation are over.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about McCain, Bush did not repeat his usual response that
McCain had asked not to be considered and that Bush was taking him
at his word.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's a good man. He's a friend of mine,'' Bush said, adding:
``He'll be a loyal soldier for my candidacy. He is a man of duty
and he loves his country.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain still captivates many Republican leaders and independent
voters. The latest Fox News survey completed July 13 found that 23
percent of 900 registered voters surveyed believed that McCain
``should be the Republican vice presidential nominee.'' McCain
outpaced every other likely vice presidential prospect by a
three-fold margin with the exception of former Republican Cabinet
officer Elizabeth Dole. Twenty two percent of those surveyed said
Dole should be the GOP running mate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's political fortunes also were buoyed by a letter
circulated by House Republicans urging Bush to choose the former
Navy pilot and Vietnam prisoner of war to help Republicans retain
control the House.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va., chairman of the House Republican campaign
committee, urged the Bush campaign to choose McCain in a telephone
call earlier this week to Dick Cheney, the former defense secretary
and ex-White House chief of staff who is vetting prospective
running mates for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has campaigned for the re-election of 13 House members
and three senators since abandoning his own presidential candidacy
after setbacks in the March 7 Super Tuesday primaries. McCain has
been asked to appear on behalf of more than 100 other House members
or House candidates by election day, said Todd Harris, spokesman
for McCain's political action committee, Straight Talk America.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation about McCain was triggered by an Associated
Press dispatch late Thursday that cited four independent sources
who recounted comments made by McCain to Pennsylvania Gov. Tom
Ridge in a private telephone call last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know me, Tommy. If the governor asked, you know I would
serve. I would prefer not to, but I'll serve,'' McCain told Ridge,
according the sources quoted by AP.
</P>
<P>
   McCain did not deny the quotation in subsequent comments to
reporters late Thursday and Friday. McCain only dubbed the
conversation with Ridge ``private'' and insisted that he did ``not
tell'' Ridge that he was ``interested'' in serving as Bush's
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's comments _ and the absence of a denial _ cracked open a
door that McCain had closed following the former rivals' meeting in
Pittsburgh on May 9. At that time, McCain firmly rejected in
advance any invitation to join Bush's ticket as the vice
presidential running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked that I not be considered for vice president of the
United States,'' McCain told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Bush quickly replied: ``I take him for his word.''
</P>
<P>
   William Schneider, a political scientist with the American
Enterprise Institute in Washington, D.C., said McCain's readiness
to stoke speculation about partnering with Bush sowed ``trouble''
for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is supposed to be Bush's moment when he makes up his mind
_ and McCain is saying, `If he really begs me I'd be willing to
consider it,'' Schneider said. ``Does Gov. Bush really need to be
overshadowed by his vice president?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
