<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8949 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-ABORTION-$ADV23-H     07-21 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ABORTION-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOP PRO-CHOICE FORCES FACE UPHILL CLIMB AT PLATFORM MEETINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 23   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They know they face virtually insurmountable odds,
but pro-choice Republicans are running a stealthy campaign to
moderate the Republican Party's strong anti-abortion platform
plank.
</P>
<P>
   Their first target is the 107-member GOP platform committee,
which will meet in Philadelphia Friday and Saturday, just before
Monday's opening of the Republican national convention.
</P>
<P>
   The abortion rights advocates say that if they cannot persuade
the committee, they will switch to an alternate strategy: They will
seek to win over the majority of delegates from each of at least
six states.
</P>
<P>
   If they succeed, then under the party's parliamentary rules, the
2,066 convention delegates will have to vote on the platform plank
by plank. That would force a debate on the abortion issue, and, the
pro-choicers hope, give them a chance to soften or even eliminate
the plank. If they do not succeed, the platform will be voted on in
its entirety early in the convention, and the plank will remain.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Stone, who heads Republicans for Choice, a political action
committee that raises money for pro-choice Republican candidates,
recognizes the odds against opening the issue to floor debate.
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive nominee, and Republican
elders want seriously to head off an abortion firestorm before a
national TV audience because it would crack the image of party
unity they hope to generate at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening it up would be Bush's worst nightmare,'' Stone said in
an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign staff appears unperturbed by the pro-choice
effort.
</P>
<P>
   `` You're going to see a more unified Republican Party than
you've seen in years,'' said one Bush senior adviser, who asked not
to be named. ``We expect a relatively smooth convention. There's no
concern on abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made his position clear. To appease the Christian right
and other conservatives opposed to abortion, the governor, who once
favored exceptions to the ban, has said he wants no changes in the
GOP's 1996 abortion plank.
</P>
<P>
   The plank does not mention any exceptions _ such as in cases of
rape, incest or where the woman's life is at stake _ in its
opposition to the procedure. It says, ``The unborn child has a
fundamental individual right to life which cannot be infringed. We
support a human life amendment to the Constitution and we endorse
legislation to make clear that the Fourteenth Amendment's
protections apply to unborn children.'' Ray Sullivan, a Bush
campaign spokesman, said campaign aides are not quizzing platform
committee delegates about their views on abortion. But he said,
``We do have policy staff working with the platform committee to
help minimize any inconsistencies and encourage compatibility
between the Bush campaign and the Republican platform.''
</P>
<P>
   The pro-choice side insists that eliminating or softening the
plank is the only way to reach out to moderate women voters. ``If
you want to reach out to women, you have to talk about choice,''
said Susan Cullman, co-chair of the Republican Pro-Choice
Coalition. Without the anti-abortion plank, ``we might lose some
extremists on one side, but we'll gain people who stay home or
register as Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro-choice Republicans are under no illusions about the
difficulty of getting the party to change direction on abortion,
Cullman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still outnumbered at this convention,'' she said. ``But
there are more people this time who support us than in 1996 or
1992. Our hour is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone pointed to a poll her organization commissioned earlier
this year showing that while 54 percent of the Republican
respondents described themselves as pro-life, 69 percent strongly
agree that government should not be involved in making a decision
on whether to have an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   If recent history is a precedent, the pro-choice advocates'
chances of success appear dim. In 1996, the platform committee
embarrassed presidential candidate Bob Dole when it rebuffed his
attempt to add a ``tolerance provision'' to the abortion plank. The
provision said the party tolerates differing views on the procedure
and that some Republicans favor abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   While Dole opposed abortion, he favored the rape, incest and
life-of-the-mother exceptions to any ban. That put him at variance
with the party's abortion plank.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Washington-based American Conservative Union
released a survey of 393 of the GOP convention's 2,066 delegates,
showing that 57 percent of respondents favored banning abortion
with exceptions in cases of rape, incest and danger to the woman's
health. Eighteen percent favored a total ban on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
