<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-VIDEO-FESTIVAL-3TAKES     07-21 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-FESTIVAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO AS ART IN A WORLD ON TAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The word NUMBER in parentheses has been used instead of the
symbol, which is nontransmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The chorus of an old John Prine song asks, ``Wouldn't
we be in good shape/if our lives were on videotape?''
</P>
<P>
   We shouldn't have to wait much longer for an answer, since it
often seems these days that no aspect of our private and communal
lives is shielded from the patient, prying lens of the video camera
_ though the tape itself, in the digital era, may soon be obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   From amateur pornography to security surveillance loops, from
home movies of weddings, childbirths and family reunions to C-Span
and ``Big Brother,'' video records and shapes what we know of
reality. It takes our confessions, tells our secrets and presents
our public rituals of shame and celebration. So what kind of shape
are we in anyway?
</P>
<P>
   One place to look for an answer might be at the New York Video
Festival, which opened Friday and runs through Thursday at the
Walter Reade Theater at Lincoln Center. The ubiquity of the medium
makes this year's festival, part of Lincoln Center Festival 2000,
especially interesting. It also may present the programmers, the
audience and the video artists whose work is being shown with a
newly acute challenge.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes video as an art form _ which often presents
apparently undigested slices of quotidian experience in grueling
real time _ from video as a tool for making family albums or
catching shoplifters, which does the same thing?
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, what separates video from the movies? Recent
films like ``Chuck and Buck,'' ``Time Code'' and ``Thirteen''
exploit the rough textures and bumpy rhythms of video to create
effects of unnerving intimacy similar to those found in many of the
festival's offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The awarding of this year's Palme d'Or at Cannes to Lars von
Trier's ``Dancer in the Dark'' raised the possibility that digital
video might come to the rescue of auteur cinema, but von Trier's
work also decisively blurs the distinctions between cinema and its
protean stepchild.
</P>
<P>
   Which is, all in all, a good thing, or at least an interesting
development. What's the difference between a video and a movie?
What separates reality from artifice? As it happens, the festival's
first offering, Trent Harris' ``Beaver Trilogy'' (showing
Saturday), is a work that raises these questions, and a number of
others including ``What in the world was that?''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else it is, ``Beaver Trilogy'' is a rivetingly strange,
multilayered inquiry into celebrity, obsession and serendipity. It
begins in 1980, with a parking-lot encounter between Harris and
Larry Huff, a voluble young man whose consuming ambition is to be
``on the tube, the set, television.''
</P>
<P>
   He introduces himself as an impressionist _ ``the Rich Little of
Beaver,'' the small Utah town that gives the film its name _ but
his enthusiasm seems to exceed his talent. Though Huff does a
little John Wayne and an almost passable Sylvester Stallone, his
real passion is for Olivia Newton-John, whom he impersonates,
resplendent in blond chicken-wing wig, at a local talent show that
he organizes for Harris' benefit.
</P>
<P>
   By itself ``The Beaver Kid'' _ which ends with Huff's heartfelt
performance of Barry Manilow's ``New York State of Mind'' (an
encore after his signature piece, the Newton-John ballad ``Please
Don't Keep Me Waiting'') _ would be an appealing curiosity, a
window into a half-forgotten moment in American popular culture and
a premonition of the current obsession with gender-bending
performance.
</P>
<P>
   But Harris followed his initial cinema verite oddity with two
remakes, the first starring an as yet unknown Sean Penn, the second
featuring the madcap emoting of Crispin Glover.
</P>
<P>
   Each installment makes explicit some of the buried themes of the
original _ the exploitive relationship between filmmaker and
subject, the thin line between glory and humiliation, and the
tension between conformity and self-expression in small-town
America.
</P>
<P>
   The second part is an almost verbatim re-enactment of the first.
The third, ``The Orkly Kid'' _ edited like a made-for-television
movie and boasting a full battery of credits _ makes Huff's story
into a tongue-in-cheek morality play about daring to be different
and following your dreams, however ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   But not even Glover's uninhibited performance can match the
uncanny sincerity of the real-life Huff, who comes from somewhere
beyond any filmmaker's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   What place is that? ``The Beaver Trilogy'' makes several
references to ``Real People,'' a long-forgotten forerunner of the
current flood of reality programming. And scattered through the
festival's diverse thematic programs are a number of arresting,
horrifying and sometimes boring real people, including some of the
artists themselves, presented amid the background noise and surface
clutter of their very real lives.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday afternoon and again on Monday evening you can take
an invigorating tour through several states of misery and squalor
in ``All Too Human,'' described as ``Three Chronicles of Abject
Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   These videos are queasily fascinating and morally troubling.
Richard Billingham, known for his unflattering photographs of his
working-class parents in northern England, brings us into their
midst in ``Fishtank,'' which observes his father's drunkenness and
his mother's needy melancholy, as well as their pet goldfish.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Loss Prevention,'' Jeanne C. Finley describes her elderly
mother's arrest for shoplifting and reflects on her own unhappy
childhood as the daughter of a kleptomaniac. The program's capper,
``If Only I,'' consists of Donigan Cumming's grueling, captivating
interviews with a woman named Colleen, whose biography moves from
childhood sexual abuse to alcoholism, institutionalization and a
failed suicide attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Only I'' is the emotional equivalent of a snuff film. It's
clearly meant to disturb, but it crosses an ethical line that other
pieces, including ``The Beaver Trilogy,'' attempt both to demarcate
and to skirt. The video not only records Colleen's abjection but
also participates in it. That she may be too far gone to care or to
protect herself hardly excuses the invasion of her privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in the age of celebrity _ the age of ``Survivor,''
cyberspying, and eager auto-surveillance _ the concept of privacy
may be obsolete. In any case, not all the violations of it recorded
at the festival are so grim, so emotionally charged, or so morally
questionable. Which brings me to George Kuchar, an experimental
Super 8 maven of the 1960s (``Hold Me While I'm Naked,''
``Corruption of the Damned'') turned indefatigable video diarist.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's program includes a selection of recent work
from Kuchar's extensive catalog _ visits to friends and neighbors,
travels here and there, all featuring his walrus-mustached visage
and his variously solicitous and sarcastic commentary. This
program, at which Kuchar will appear in person, is an antipasto for
the feast of episodic eccentricity that is ``Secrets of the Shadow
World,'' a two-hour ``miniseries'' about UFO conspiracy theories
and a whole lot of other things, which will be presented on Sunday
and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a long episode of ``The X-Files'' shot with the cheesy,
prefab special effects of a prepackaged wedding video and
accompanied by generic movie-score bombast. Now add a cast of
garrulous oddballs in costume-shop robes and makeup, arts
administrators, avant-garde filmmakers and a very indulgent cat.
</P>
<P>
   But really you can't imagine what ``Secrets of the Shadow
World'' is like, any more than you can imagine a day in the life of
a tirelessly inventive, endlessly curious artist with a video
camera, or a day in your own life.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar's artistry is not immediately apparent. Watching his
jerky, spontaneous recordings of life's pleasant inanity, you may
say, ``Hey, I could do that.'' Which is part of the point. What's
stopping you?
</P>
<P>
   If the video camera seems uniquely adept at registering living
human presences, in all their uncomfortable specificity, it also
offers a special access to the human interior, a vehicle for
fantasy, speculation and dreaming, exemplified in a program called
``Electronic Unconscious,'' which will be shown on Monday and
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Harris' and Kuchar's works, the films in this
program seem somewhat arch and self-conscious. The most interesting
of them is Chris Petit's ``Asylum,'' an hourlong ``sci-fi narrative
collage'' which is a bit like a condensed, British version of
``Secrets of the Shadow World'' without Kuchar's genially anarchic
presence.
</P>
<P>
   And though video art has at times in its short history been
dominated by abstraction, by an aesthetic of the image, this year's
festival, like the reality programming that is both its cultural
context and its cultural antithesis, is dominated by images of
people. If video is a way of exploring often uncomfortable personal
connections _ between videomakers and their subjects, parents and
their children, young men and their alter egos _ it can also
explore loneliness, disconnection and loss.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday a half-dozen brief studies in alienation will be
screened in a program called ``Only Disconnect,'' the best of which
is a collage of disjointed, abstract narratives called ``Nest of
Tens,'' by Miranda July.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most moving evocations of the irreplaceable quiddity
of a person is Elisabeth Subrin's ``Fancy,'' which will be shown in
the program ``Brought to Light'' on Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The video is devoted to the life and work of a photographer,
Francesca Woodman, who committed suicide in 1981 at the age of 22.
Her work, which consisted almost entirely of nude self-portraits,
never appears on screen. Instead we see her possessions, laid out
like auction lots, and hear descriptions of her pictures as fully
clothed stand-ins re-enact her poses.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Subrin confers immortality on her subject while at the
same time making vivid her irrevocable absence.
</P>
<P>
   The commemorative power of video is related to its alchemical
capacity to confer renown. The confessional impulse and the urge to
perform are not entirely separable, as the examples of Larry Huff
and George Kuchar suggest. Huff dreamed of making the big time in
his blond wig and leather boots just before the advent of MTV,
which has, in the decades since, come to dominate and to transform
the culture of videomaking.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the New York Press film critic Armond White, a
mainstay of the festival since 1993, will present a selection of
music videos, including work by the directors Mark Romanek and Hype
Williams, and musicians like Bjork, Mos Def, and Macy Gray. Like
the more rarefied (and rarely seen) work that dominates the
festival, music video, according to White, ``gives a chance for
filmmakers not connected with the Hollywood mainstream to express
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though music videos are commercial,'' White said in a
telephone interview, ``they are also experimental. They set the
tone for visual language, and they do what no other videomakers can
do: They reach a public.''
</P>
<P>
   White's cherished pop-music videos, with their fast editing and
smoothly polished surfaces, stand in obvious contrast to the rough,
knotty work of artists like Kuchar and Harris. The abundant and
varied material on display at this year's festival is evidence of
the medium's almost infinite variety and elasticity, its ability to
comprehend, in small increments and at great length, in real time
and on landscapes of fantasy, the breadth and scope of contemporary
life.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The New York Video Festival, part of Lincoln Center Festival
2000, runs through Thursday at the Walter Reade Theater at Lincoln
Center. Most programs include several videos and feature
appearances by videomakers. Unless noted, the videos were released
this year in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Video Festival also features several special events, like
``We Went Digital, Where Were You?,'' a panel discussion with
several digital filmmakers, on Wednesday at 8 p.m. There will also
be special presentations by George Kuchar, a videomaker (Saturday),
and Armond White, a film critic and author (Monday).
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for all programs are $9 ($5 for members of the Film
Society of Lincoln Center and the Association of Independent Video
and Filmmakers); Video Festival information: (212) 875-5600; Web
site, www.filmlinc.com. A free video installation will also be on
view daily from 12:30 to 8 p.m. in the Furman Gallery at the Walter
Reade. Here is a schedule of screenings:
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   ``BROUGHT TO LIGHT,'' with ``Haunt (NUMBER)451,'' by Susana
Donovan; ``So to Speak,'' by Jacqueline Goss; and ``The Fancy,'' by
Elisabeth Subrin, 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``ALL TOO HUMAN,'' with ``Fishtank'' (Britain, 1998), by Richard
Billingham; ``Loss Prevention,'' by Jeanne C. Finley and Doug
DuBois; and ``If Only I'' (Canada), by Donigan Cumming, 4:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``GEORGE KUCHAR: LARGE AND IN CHARGE!'' with ``Trilogy of the
