<HEADLINE>
49ERS BEEF UP THEIR OFFENSIVE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE ADAMS  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. - For years, the stereotypical 49ers offensive
lineman was a lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   Bobb McKittrick, the longtime offensive line coach who died of
cancer earlier this year, favored undersized, overachieving
players. His blocking schemes were based on quickness.
</P>
<P>
   That's beginning to change and is especially noticeable with the
arrival of two veteran free agent tackles _ 6-foot-8, 315-pound
Matt Willig, signed in the offseason, and 6-foot-8, 325-pound Scott
Gragg, signed earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   These two look the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be the first guys off the bus,'' coach Steve Mariucci
said.
</P>
<P>
   Willig was with the St. Louis Rams last year and Gragg comes
from the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have some depth,'' said Mariucci, who has
mentioned Gragg as a possible starter with Dave Fiore still
recovering from knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how his regulars felt about the team signing two proven
NFL starters, Mariucci said, ``It's a competitive world out there.
It makes us all better.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JERVEY'S MANDATE: Running back Travis Jervey was excused from
the morning practice Thursday with a left hip flexor strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to get some ice on that and get a haircut,''
Mariucci said.
</P>
<P>
   CLOSE ON PETERSON: Julian Peterson, the team's top draft pick,
may be closer to signing.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, a pass-rushing linebacker expected to take over the
starting spot vacated by Lee Woodall, was the 16th pick overall in
this year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   He was due in camp Saturday with his fellow rookies, but has
stayed out while the team and his agent negotiate a contract.
General manager Bill Walsh said Thursday the two sides are close.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci talked with Peterson by telephone Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Julian and his father,'' he said. ``He's working
out three times a day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1715EDT &QL; 
