<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ANNE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANNE OF GREEN GABLES': TIMES CHANGE, AND ANNE MUST FACE A MESSY
WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., Broadcast notes are at the end of the review. Broadcast time
and station are for New York; please check for your area) 
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Anne of Green Gables: The Continuing Story,'' Anne Shirley
makes her way to a publishing house in New York to peddle a
manuscript. It's 1915, but her meeting with the company's head
would sound familiar today. After complaining about the sorry state
of the business, he compliments her work and then rejects it.
</P>
<P>
   He does give her a job as an editor and tells her what kind of
book he wants to publish. With the war in Europe diverting the
attention of men, he says, he wants stories that will appeal to
women, but they should be adventure stories.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that the creators of this two-part mini-series, which
presents the famous red-haired orphan girl as an adult, have taken
the publisher's advice to heart. They have catapulted their heroine
into the thick of all kinds of adventures that merely include
engagement and marriage to her longtime beau, Gilbert Blythe, a
romantic triangle, publishing intrigue, espionage and war.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly Anne has gone a long way from Avonlea, the Canadian
setting of ``Anne of Green Gables,'' a book that remains on
sixth-grade reading lists almost a century after it was first
published. The book was made into a silent film in 1919. A 1934
version starred an actress named Dawn O'Day but she changed her
name to Anne Shirley for her first starring role.
</P>
<P>
   Megan Follows has resisted that temptation, though she began
playing Anne in 1985, when she was 16, in the television
mini-series that would become a popular video Cliff's Notes for
young readers, and again in a 1987 sequel. ``The Continuing Story''
completes the trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   Though also the work of Kevin Sullivan, who created this
handsomely produced Canadian series, ``The Continuing Story''
differs significantly from the first two parts. While those
productions took some liberties, particularly with time (placing
Anne in the early 1900s instead of the 1880s), they faithfully
remained connected to the books by Lucy Maud Montgomery. For this
installment the dramatists have gone off into dangerous territory,
to create what Sullivan has described as ``a completely original
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, who wrote the script with Laurie Pearson, has
developed a plausible adult version of Anne, the shrewd, plucky
orphan who had to win the hearts of the elderly couple with whom
she had gone to live. They were Matthew and Marilla, a brother and
sister who lived together on a farm called Green Gables and who
were hoping for a boy to help with the chores. Now Matthew and
Marilla are gone, though Anne remains shrewd and plucky, ready to
conquer all obstacles the way she conquered Matthew and Marilla's
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   But separated from her source material, Montgomery's books, Anne
has also lost much of her childhood poetry. She no longer says
things like ``my life is a perfect graveyard of burned hopes now''
with the same charm. Nor could she. She has grown up, and so has
Follows, but the filmmakers haven't found a comparable way for her
to express her adult longings and fears.
</P>
<P>
   They have replaced Anne's filigreed musings with action. As the
mini-series opens, she is returning to Green Gables from a
five-year stint away, working with orphans. But she arrives only to
find that the place she once described as ``a beautiful dream'' is
run down and occupied by trashy people.
</P>
<P>
   Though she says she wants to return there when she has children,
she leaves for New York with her fiance, Gil (again played by
Jonathan Crombie), who has been invited to work as a surgeon at
Bellevue Hospital. Soon enough, they both become disillusioned with
the politics and perfidy of the city's institutions, medical and
publishing, and head back home.
</P>
<P>
   But before returning to Canada, Anne becomes entangled _
professionally on her part, and also romantically on his _ with a
famous writer of adventure stories, Jack Garrison Jr. (Cameron
Daddo). Then everyone becomes engulfed in World War I, and so does
the mini-series. Anne forges through the hugger-mugger with aplomb,
relentlessly unflappable in the face of battlefront explosions,
remarkable coincidences and neck-wrenching plot twists. She even
disguises herself as a nun to cross enemy lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anne of Green Gables: The Continuing Story'' is clunky at
times. The actors are good but too restrained, unable to swell to
the scenario's melodramatic proportions (though the music has no
such problems). But it is engrossing all the same, especially for
those who feel as if they knew Anne as a girl and want to see what
happens to her when she grows up.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ANNE OF GREEN GABLES'
</P>
<P>
   The Continuing Story
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Sunday on PBS
</P>
<P>
   A Sullivan Entertainment presentation of Anne III Productions
Inc., in association with the Canadian Broadcasting Corp. Directed
by Stefan Scaini; written by Kevin Sullivan and Laurie Pearson;
Arthur Herriott, production designer; Bob Saad, director of
photography; music by Peter Breiner; edited by Mairin Wilkinson;
costumes by Ruth Secord. Sullivan and Trudy Grant, executive
producers; Ray Sager, executive in charge of production.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Megan Follows (Anne Shirley), Jonathan Crombie (Gilbert
Blythe) and Cameron Daddo (Jack Garrison Jr.).
</P>
</TEXT>
