<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, July 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another in the recent series of systems of thunderstorms over
the southern tier of the nation will roll east-southeastward from
Oklahoma into portions of Arkansas, southwest Tennessee,
Mississippi, Alabama and perhaps Georgia by day's end. Locally
heavy rain, gusty winds and hail will affect some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms will erupt over eastern parts of Colorado and New
Mexico and western parts of Kansas, Oklahoma and Texas as cold
winds from the northwest at 18,000 feet work in tandem with humid
surface winds to destabilize the atmosphere. A few storms will
approach severe levels.
</P>
<P>
   Variable clouds and sun with scattered showers and thunderstorms
will be the tenor of the day across parts of the Northeast, as a
pool of cold air 20,000 feet above the ground allows cumulus clouds
to build.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DERECHO
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, straight-line winds from a system of thunderstorms
prompted more than 200 reports of damage in Oklahoma, Arkansas,
Tennessee, Mississippi, Alabama and Georgia. Such a long-lived
windstorm is a derecho. For a system of storms to qualify as a
derecho, the length of the path of damaging winds must be at least
250 nautical miles. Moreover, the pattern of strong winds must show
a clear chronological progression, with no more than three hours
between damage reports. There must also be at least three reports
of gusts of 74 mph or more that are at least 40 nautical miles
apart.
</P>
</TEXT>
