<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-AUSTRALIA-MINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIGGEST MINING COMPANY IN BID TO TAKE OVER NORTH LTD. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia)   By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Making another move to expand its
interests outside South Africa, Anglo American PLC, the world's
biggest mining company, on Friday announced a bid worth $1.8
billion to take over Australian iron miner North Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Anglo's offer of 4.20 Australian dollars a share, or about $2.45
a share, and the assumption of $263 million in debt is 11 percent
higher than an offer for North from Anglo rival Rio Tinto PLC made
last month. There were expectations that Rio Tinto would sweeten
its offer.
</P>
<P>
   North Ltd. is the world's fourth-largest producer of iron ore
and is a major supplier to Asia, where demand has been strong and
where Anglo has been trying to position itself as prime distributor
of metals and minerals.
</P>
<P>
   With its growth prospects in Africa limited, Anglo has been
looking outside South Africa for opportunities to expand, and
Australia has been one of its favorite targets. Last month, Anglo
acquired several Australian coal mines, and last year, the company
acquired a 23 percent stake in an Australian nickel-mining house.
</P>
<P>
   Anglo's latest acquisition attempt also underscores the changing
corporate focus of the company, which had evolved into an array of
assets across many industries. Since shifting its primary listing
to London last year, the company has been focusing on mining and
shedding unrelated interests.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover bid for North is another step in that strategy.
Anglo, which purchased 6 million shares in North several weeks ago,
said Friday that it had been evaluating the Australian company as a
possible acquisition for some time and that the circumstances were
right to make a move now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expansion of our mining and natural resources operations
and the application of our mining expertise across commodities
where we can add value is a key element of Anglo-American's growth
strategy,'' the company's chief executive, Tony Trahar, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   North's board has indicated that it supports Anglo's approach,
and the Australian company's major customers in Japan are said to
support it as well. Anglo is the largest producer of gold and
platinum. Securing a bigger stake in the essential, if less exotic,
base metals sector has been an important objective for the company,
said Mannie Rahn, who tracks the mining industry for Standard
Equities in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   Even with such a large acquisition, more than half of Anglo's
assets would still be in South Africa, the company said. That makes
it certain that Anglo will make other acquisitions overseas, Rahn
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they would be loathe to make any other investments in
southern Africa,'' he said. ``If they have a choice they would much
rather go somewhere else. They still see South Africa as a very
large part of their portfolio and they want to diversify. I think
it's just good business practice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
