<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-HOUSES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REMARKABLE HOUSES DETAILED IN A NEW BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: For release Sunday.)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     BY FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Authors will often write about fond memories of the houses where
they grew up. But Richard Hampton Jenrette chronicles the history
of six remarkable houses in ``Adventures with Old Houses'' (Wyrick
&AMP; Co., $60).
</P>
<P>
   The author writes in detail about the properties that he has
preserved for generations to come.
</P>
<P>
   Jenrette, co-founder in 1959 and former chairman and CEO of the
investment-banking firm of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc., has a
lifelong passion for grand old houses. He is dedicated to historic
preservation, and not only tenderly restores each house, but enjoys
playing detective to find and restore the 19th century art and
antiques that once belonged in them.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn to classical architecture, Jenrette currently resides
among five of the six houses he has meticulously restored along the
East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   He owns Millford Plantation and Roper House, both in South
Carolina; Ayr Mount in his native North Carolina; the Baker House
in New York City; Cane Garden in St. Croix, and Edgewater in the
Dutchess County hamlet of Barrytown, N.Y. Jenrette wrote
``Adventures in Old Houses'' _ in longhand _ at the St. Croix
house.
</P>
<P>
   Jenrette, who calls himself a house-aholic, has either sold or
given away eight other houses.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, the author describes Edgewater, the property that
he first saw over 30 years ago, as the great architectural love of
his life.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1820, the classically styled villa sits on a winding
peninsula that was originally part of the rolling, bucolic lands
owned by the Livingston family, the landholding patrons of the
Hudson Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of this pristine estate changed in 1852 when New York
state severed the main house from its rolling fields by laying
railroad tracks approximately 20 yards from the back door.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II the double tracks were heavily used to ship
war supplies to the port of New York, the soot and noise rendering
Edgewater an unlivable white elephant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there are just cleaner passenger trains that go by very
quickly every hour or so,'' said Jenrette, during a recent visit to
Edgewater. To visually block the tracks and trains he has planted a
hedge wall.
</P>
<P>
   When Jenrette first saw the estate in 1969, it was owned by
author Gore Vidal, who had rescued the house at the end of World
War II. Since purchasing it, Jenrette has snapped up additional
parcels, bringing the total area from 7 acres to more than 100
acres. He continues to landscape the large parcel on the far side
of the railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan Porter, a neighbor, said that when Gore (Vidal) heard a
train coming, he would turn to the dinner guest next to him and
say, `Now tell me about your life,''' said Jenrette. ``Just as the
person began to talk, the roar of the train would drown out all
conversation. Once the train passed, Gore would resume his
dominance over the conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Casually attired in white tennis shoes, white polo shirt and
blue and white seersucker suit, Jenrette walked across the verdant
park-like setting shaded by stately locust trees and lush floral
hedges and gardens. He also has rights to Daisey Island, a short
distance out in the river.
</P>
<P>
   The whole shoreline to Edgewater features a stone wall to
prevent erosion. A stone boat slip originally featured a Chinese
boathouse, built by Robert Donaldson of Fayetteville, N.C., who
bought Edgewater in 1852.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the happiest days in a man's life is when he gets a
boat,'' Jenrette mused. ``The second happiest day is when he sells
it! I had too many mechanical problems with the first and second
boat here. So no more boats.'' Now he enjoys the river as he sits
on his joggling board, made out of cypress wood. ``Every house in
South Carolina has one,'' he said. ``You just sit and joggle up and
down on it. It's very relaxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenrette relocated the swimming pool to the south side of the
house, deliberately hiding it behind a slight rise in the lawn.
Michael Dwyer designed a pool house and Michael Pelletier built it
in a classical style with four Doric columns facing out to the
pool, and a brick wall to further muffle the sound of the passing
trains.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Jenrette also added a small Palladian-style guesthouse
on a point of land he bought to the north of the main house around
a lagoon. Viewed from the front porch of Edgewater, the small
Grecian temple guesthouse provides visual interest as an
architectural folly.
</P>
<P>
   Edgewater represents one of the earliest uses of columns on
residential buildings in America. Along the first floor facing the
columned porch are five French doors topped by louvered fanlights
and shutters. The home appears to be two stories high from outside,
but actually contains four full floors.
</P>
<P>
   To break the symmetry of the main core of the house, an
octagonal library was added to the north side in 1854 by architect
A.J. Davis. A small-screened five-sided porch, where morning coffee
is served from the service kitchen, was added off the dining room
in later years.
</P>
<P>
   The pinkish brown stucco exterior, scored to resemble stone, has
been painted to a faux marble finish. Robert Jackson of Columbia
County, a painter with an international reputation, executed all of
the custom faux finishes in the house.
</P>
<P>
   The entrance to the house is through a smaller columned portico
on the land side. The entrance hall with winding staircase features
a painted floor copied from an inlaid floor Jenrette admired in
Russia's Hermitage Palace in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Two doors in the foyer lead to two connecting 14-foot-high rooms
that face the river. The dining room to the south can be separated
from the living room by double sliding mahogany doors.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the era, dining room walls are painted to look
like delicate blocks of white marble. The oval dining table is
surrounded by a rare suite of 12 Duncan Phyfe dining chairs and
French porcelain (each piece stamped in gold with an `L'), which
belonged to the Livingstons. The eyes of an 1821 portrait of former
owner Robert Donaldson follow visitors around the room.
</P>
<P>
   The drawing room is an eye-catching composition consisting of a
pair of gilt Albany mirrors, matching pier tables, a suite of late
Federal style Duncan Phyfe furniture (circa 1815-20), white silk
window treatments and the omnipresent faux marble block walls.
</P>
<P>
   All of the original late Federal-style moldings, medallions and
fireplace mantles have been restored.
</P>
<P>
   To the north on an axis with the dining room and living room is
the octagonal library. A small low-ceilinged connecting hall off
the living room leads into the dramatic 26-foot-high library. A
skylight illuminates the creamy faux marble block walls and green
patterned carpet copied from a ceiling in the Roman Baths of
Pompeii.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore (Vidal) converted this lower section of the main house
into a one-car garage,'' said Jenrette. ``I think this may have
originally been the servants' room, because of the fireplace. Not
many garages have a fireplace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
