<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8967 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER22-COX     07-21 1771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Getting ready to pop the question
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush said today he'll make up his mind on a running
mate this weekend, one week before the GOP presidential convention
in Philadelphia. ``The days of speculation are over,'' he said. A
number of House Republicans were circulating a letter for
signatures, hoping to persuade Bush to pick former foe John McCain.
The letter said the only thing Al Gore fears ``is George W. Bush
calling John McCain.'' Asked about the senator specifically, Bush
said, ``He'll be a loyal soldier for my candidacy. He is a man of
duty and he loves his country.'' Bush only smiled when asked what
rank McCain might have in that campaign.
</P>
<P>
   BUT IT'S A GOOD ATTENTION-GETTER
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear today whether the reported conversation between
John McCain and Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge would in fact put
McCain seriously in play as an option for George W. Bush, who is
nearing a decision on his running-mate. Sources close to McCain
said, according to several news outlets, that when Ridge reported
the senator's potential interest to the Bush campaign, a senior
aide there received the news coolly. And the Bush campaign
apparently has not requested any of the financial or other
background information usually demanded of a potential vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   COLD WAR HANDS AT THE READY
</P>
<P>
   Cold War diplomatic veterans George Shultz, Henry Kissinger and
Colin Powell are George W. Bush's vision of a great foreign policy
team in a new administration. ``Some of whom, you know, may be a
part of the administration, but all of them are my supporters and
friends,'' Bush teased during an interview with CNN's Larry King.
Also on Bush's list is his campaign's foreign policy chief,
Condoleeza Rice, a Russian and Eastern European affairs specialist
at the National Security Council during Bush's father's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   PLANES, TRAINS AND BUSES
</P>
<P>
   Seeking a stronger commitment from labor, Al Gore tried to rouse
the union faithful in Washington today by accusing George W. Bush
of proposing a Social Security plan that would drain the retirement
trust fund. ``I'm on the side of the men and women who work hard
physical jobs all their lives, who drive those buses and lay down
train track and carry bags at airports for others, and they need
something more than an IOU when they retire,'' Gore told a
convention of the AFL-CIO. The meeting brought together the
federation's transportation trades workers, who include the
Teamsters, machinists and bus drivers who make up about a quarter
of the AFL-CIO's membership.
</P>
<P>
   LABORING HARDER FOR DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor is preparing for the fall campaigns like never
before, boosting campaign contributions and stepping up its efforts
to pull union members to the polls. The goal is to keep the White
House Democratic and return Congress to Democratic control. The
importance of turnout was described by House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt, who noted that union members accounted for 13 percent of
the vote in 1994, when the Democrats lost control of Congress, and
23 percent of the vote in 1996 and 1998, when the party added seats
to its House minority.
</P>
<P>
   MAKING THEIR MARKS MONEYWISE
</P>
<P>
   In a year of record-breaking fund-raising, Al Gore has received
$14.6 million in taxpayer funds for his campaign, more than any
other presidential candidate ever. Gore, who agreed to limit his
spending to $40.5 million in exchange for the subsidies, broke the
old mark of $13.5 million by Republican Bob Dole in 1996. George W.
Bush declined to accept federal funds and the spending limits that
accompany them _ but went on to smash all fund-raising records by
taking in $96 million and spending $88 million.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY LEFT OVER FOR SOME EXTRAS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has so much money left over in his campaign bank account
that he is increasing his travel, opening campaign offices around
the country and tripling his campaign staff from 100 to 300 people.
With $7.6 million in the bank as of June 30, Gore also is setting
aside some funds to pay the travel expenses of his vice
presidential choice, should he name the person before the
convention. ``We really tightened the belt and focused on winning
the primaries early,'' said campaign spokesman Douglas Hattaway.
``That has put us on a very sound financial footing now when it
really matters.''
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA TRIAGE
</P>
<P>
   Concentrating on four states that political strategists say
could tip the electoral balance this fall, George W. Bush's
campaign began running its first major TV ads of the general
election. The spots went on the air in Ohio, Pennsylvania, Florida
and Washington state. But the choice of locales was an instant
subject for dissection by Al Gore aides, who pointed to the
inclusion of Florida as a sign that some crucial states that might
normally be safely in the Republican column were viewed by the Bush
side as in need of some maintenence.
</P>
<P>
   SLIPPAGE IN OHIO
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has lost some ground to Al Gore in Ohio,
considered a swing state in the fall election, a new poll shows.
The University of Cincinnati Institute for Policy Research poll (4
percentage point margin of error) has Bush leading Gore 49-45
percent in a two-candidate field and 47-41 percent when Pat
Buchanan of the Reform Party and Ralph Nader of the Green Party are
included. In April, the poll gave Bush a 9-point lead over Gore in
a two-candidate race and an 8-point lead in a four-man race.
</P>
<P>
   TWO WOMEN WITH THE GAVELS
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic convention will shine a spotlight on the fact
that California _ the largest state in the country with 34 million
people _ has elected two women senators. Sens. Dianne Feinstein and
Barbara Boxer will wield gavels in Los Angeles next month as the
first two women co-chairs of a national political convention. Two
women previously chaired Democratic conventions as single chairs:
Texas Gov. Ann Richards in 1992 and Kentucky Gov. Martha Layne
Collins of Kentucky in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   BATTLE ON THE HOME (LOAN) FRONT
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting that her New York Senate opponent cared more about
wealthy campaign donors than about constituents, Hillary Clinton
attacked Rick Lazio for trying to kill legislation in 1998 to
expand a federal program that helps first-time home buyers obtain
mortgages. The program, run by the Federal Housing Administration,
assists first-time home buyers or those with shaky credit. Lazio
had vigorously fought it, saying at the time that it was an
unacceptable intrusion by government into private industry. The
program provides competition for mortgage insurance companies,
which charge fees to guarantee mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   KEATING'S HOPES NOT UP
</P>
<P>
   Whoever George W. Bush chooses for a running mate, Oklahoma Gov.
Frank Keating guesses it won't be him. ``I'm not holding my
breath,'' said Keating. ``It's my own intuitive sense. ... I just
don't think it's going to happen.'' Keating, a Catholic with
anti-abortion views similar to Bush's, is mentioned near the top of
almost all guess-lists of possible candidates Bush may be
considering.
</P>
<P>
   IF IT ISN'T ONE THING, IT'S ANOTHER
</P>
<P>
   Her race and Mississippi's once whites-only political machine
kept Mamie Cunningham out of the 1964 Democratic National
Convention. This time she's being sidelined because of gender.
Cunningham was pulled as a delegate to next month's convention in
Los Angeles because Mississippi's racially diverse delegation would
have had two more women than men. She was replaced with state Sen.
David Jordan after another delegate, Balwant Singh, filed a
challenge with the Democratic National Committee. So Cunningham, a
schoolteacher will be making the trip as an alternate instead.
</P>
<P>
   STUPID CANDIDATE TRICKS
</P>
<P>
   ``Late show'' host David Letterman is asking Al Gore and George
W. Bush to debate on his show. Gore quickly accepted the
invitation. Bush didn't immediately respond, but Letterman has been
known to publicly badger politicians into appearances. ``Do you
want a guy that doesn't return calls?'' a smiling Letterman asked,
feigning anger. ``We don't care who wins; we just want to know what
the deal is.'' Both candidates have been on the show. But in an
appearance via satellite earlier this year, Bush's jokes fell
rather flat.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM PARTY IN A FRAZZLE
</P>
<P>
   Factional fighting within the Reform Party has escalated, with
Pat Buchanan forces warning they may try to throw out the party's
primary ballot and seek their candidate's presidential nomination
on the convention floor. Maryland State chairman Robert Bowles, a
Buchanan ally, said the effort to rescind the primary is one way to
retaliate against ``rogue'' forces from the Ross Perot wing of the
party who seek to thwart Buchanan's nomination. John Hagelin, who
one was a Natural Law Party nominee, is the only opposition
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   HOME AGAIN TO CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley will campaign in his
hometown of Crystal City, Mo., Saturday with Gov. Mel Carnahan, a
Democrat trying to unseat Sen. John Ashcroft, a one-term
Republican, in one of the year's hardest-fought congressional
races. Bradley will be campaigning for just the second time since
he dropped out of the Democratic presidential primaries in March.
Last week, he endorsed Al Gore in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   YOU CAN'T GO HOME AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   He has never given any real indication that he might try it, but
President Clinton would face a hard fight if he ran for the Senate
in his native Arkansas, a new poll shows. The Mason-Dixon poll (4
percentage point margin of error), commissioned by the Arkansas
Democrat-Gazette, shows Clinton trailing Sen. Tim Hutchinson, a
Republican whose first term ends in 2002, by 49-41 percent, with 10
percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   SON OF THE PREACHERMAN
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Graham, eldest son of the Rev. Billy Graham and also an
evangelist, will deliver the benediction that closes the first day
of the Republican convention on July 31. Graham, who lives in North
Carolina and is president of Samaritan's Purse, a Christian relief
organization, offered a prayer at the 1996 GOP convention in San
Diego. Graham will fly in from an international evangelists'
conference in Amsterdam, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
