<SLUG> BC-POWER-SHIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S.F. RESIDENTS TAKE AIM AT BARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JANE KAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As a PG&AMP;E barge slated for a floating San
Francisco Bay power plant sails through the Panama Canal, residents
stood on the steps of city hall here and vowed to stop it ``on land
and on sea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gravely concerned about plans to moor an antiquated
power plant in our bay,'' said Robert James, a spokesman for the
BayKeeper, a private environmental watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as paving the way for using the bay as an
industrial parking lot,'' James said at a Thursday press conference
held to oppose PG&AMP;E's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, four five-story jet-fueled turbines set atop
the 300 foot by 90 foot barge would send electricity through wires
wrapped in cable, lying on the bay floor, to a newly built
temporary substation on land.
</P>
<P>
   The turbines would generate the same amount of pollution as a
747 flying 55 feet above ground for every hour of every day that it
operated, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over the floating power plant surfaced after a
June 14 brownout. Weeks later, PG&AMP;E asked the California Energy
Commission for emergency approval to generate 95 megawatts from its
barge, for up to 15 months, during high-peak use, possibly starting
next month.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E announced Thursday that it wanted to locate the barge in
the bay near San Francisco International Airport. PG&AMP;E said it had
dropped any plans to put the barge, which it bought in the spring,
offshore of San Francisco's Bayview-Hunters Point and Potrero Hill
neighborhoods. Both neighborhoods had strongly opposed the project.
</P>
<P>
   Bayview-Hunters Point residents raised racial and economic
issues, saying the community with the city's largest African
American population already bears the greatest amount of industry.
</P>
<P>
   Potrero residents said they already have a power plant, and
don't know the health effects from those emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Inside city hall later Thursday, after a public hearing, the
commissioners of the Bay Conservation and Development Commission
voted to send a strong letter to the state Energy Commission,
deeming the power plant environmentally unsuitable for the bay.
</P>
<P>
   Many commissioners cited concerns over air and water quality,
wildlife, recreation and scenic beauty. They chided PG&AMP;E for not
anticipating power needs but trying to place BCDC and other
agencies in the position of having accept a poor project.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Betsey Cutler said it was unfortunate that the only
example of offshore power plants that PG&AMP;E could give were the 40
barges that ring Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Cutler called them ``a blight on the landscape'' that reminded
her of the garbage scows that were supposed to be temporary but are
still there.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, BCDC can't stop the project if PG&AMP;E is successful in
getting approval from the state Energy Commission for a so-called
energy emergency.
</P>
<P>
   If Gov. Gray Davis grants this emergency status, and he would
have to do so to bring the floating power plant to the bay, the
state Energy Commission can proceed without adhering to the
California Environmental Quality Act. If Davis doesn't grant the
status, then BCDC probably would deem the project unsuitable under
state environmental law.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the PG&AMP;E National Energy Group, a PG&AMP;E
business that develops power plants, told the BCDC commissioners
the utility needed a short-term solution to meet high-energy use
until a permanent plant is ready in 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
