</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Saturday, July 22, 2000, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   GAPACIFIC-future _ What's in store for the new and improved
Georgia-Pacific? The king of plywood and boxes wants to turn away
from its commodity roots and duke it out against consumer marketing
giants such as Procter &AMP; Gamble and Kimberly-Clark. With its
proposed deal to buy rival Fort James and become the world's
largest maker of tissue products, Georgia-Pacific sent a strong
signal this week that it's heading in a new direction. Analysts
expect Georgia Pacific to sell a significant number of paper mills
and operations that don't fit its new consumer-oriented focus.
(Bond, Atrlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   BASS-NAME _ Bass PLC may soon be changing its name. The
London-based hotel/pub company agreed to do so as part of its deal
with Interbrew, which purchased its brewing operations. The company
has two years to do so and it will, of course, affect Bass Hotels &AMP;
Resorts here. (Poole, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HITECH-DIVERSITY _ With all the high-tech workers coming in from
other countries, it's changing the real estate market. Real estate
agents need to be sensitive to cultural differences. One Realtor
had to stop at a mosque while showing houses so her client could
pray at noon. (Breyer, Auystin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ETHNIC _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Dawna Cekuta has seen all kinds of deal
breakers during her 17 years as a real estate broker. But last
week, she admits, was a first.
</P>
<P>
   One of her home listings was under contract to an Asian couple.
But the deal fell through when their feng shui consultant informed
them the house did not have good energy. ``This is the first time
in my experience that a deal has fallen through because of feng
shui,'' said Cekuta of Amelia Bullock Realtors. (Breyer, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   COKE-SUIT _ Following developments in the lawsuit against
Coca-Cola Co. The company is expected to issue its official
response to a $1.5 billion lawsuit filed by for African American
women employees, who claim they were discriminated against. (Unger,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COKE-COFFEE _ Coca-Cola is planning to introduce a coffee drink
to the North America market. The soft drink company also sells
coffee in Japan. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-BMW3231 _ A review of the BMW 323i station wagon.
(DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 9:30 p.m., an ETA will be given.
