   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-EARNINGS _ Packed planes offset higher fuel costs to lift
Delta Air Lines profits by 3 percent in the quarter ended June 30.
(Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 13
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT-SPINOFF _ Lucent Technologies Inc. confirms that it will
spin out its Microelectronics business, including Austin-based
Agere Inc. in the first qurater of next year. Agere, which was
acquired by Lucent this spring, is happy about the change. It will
be the second major spinoff in a year for Lucent, which itself was
spin off from AT&AMP;T in 1996. Lucent this year spun off its
enterprise systems and service business into a company called
Avaya. (Ladendorf, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-HOTEL _ Business travelers now demand the high-tech
conveniences of their offices _ high-speed Internet access, video
conferencing, dual phone lines, and other neat stuff _ when they
check into big-city hotels. Several Austin hotels, including three
of the city's historic and recently renovated downtown hotels, now
offer many of these amenities. Some of the features: wireless
Internet access; video check-out service; Internet-enabled kiosks;
conference centers with Web-casting, even minibar drinks with bar
codes that automatically bill the guest. We'll look at how business
traveling has changed. (Gee, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   GP-WEB _ Georgia-Pacific's new business-to-business venture with
its biggest rivals will be based in Atlanta, the companies said
Thursday. ForestExpress.com, an electronic trading post for paper
and building supplies, will debut in the fourth quarter. The
company expects to hire 150 people and is looking for office space
north of the Perimeter. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-AVIATION _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Commerce Committee
holds a hearing on aviation and the Internet. (Geewax, Cox News
Service) 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   UPS _ Helped by heavy demand for international deliveries,
United Parcel Service Inc.'s second-quarter net income rose 18
percent to $695 million or 60 cents per share. The results matched
analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In the year-ago period, UPS earned $588 million, or 52 cents a
share. (Hirschman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH _ BellSouth Corporation (NYSE: BLS) reported second
quarter earnings per share of 56 cents, an increase of 9.8 percent
compared to 51 cents before a special item in the second quarter of
1999. Consolidated revenues were a quarterly record $6.8 billion
and up 9.8 percent over the same period in 1999. Growth continued
to be driven by BellSouth's rapidly evolving mix of data, wireless
and international revenues. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAMS-DRINKS _Richard Williams, dad of the pro tennis players
Venus and Serena Williams apparently sighned a deal with an Atlanta
bottler to market an energy drink under their label. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT _Deutsche Telekom gets closer to buying wireless provider
VoiceStream, which makes it less likely that the German giant will
bid for Sprint. That would leave the field open for BellSouth -- if
it's interested. Also, Sprint earnings are out, sketching the
picture of what is up for grabs. And meanwhile, no word from
Bernie, the wizard of Clinton, Miss., but everyone expects _
something _ from WorldCom. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DELL _ Photo assigned. Dell Computer Corp. is holdletz, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   DOW _ The U.S. economy appears headed for a soft landing, but
it's not there yet and still higher interest rates may be needed to
contain inflation, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
Thursday. Stocks rose on the news; Dow up 161 and Nasdaq up 116.
(Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ING-AETNA _ING buys Aetna's financial services group for $5
billion. What does this mean for ING's financial services group,
based in Marietta? (Grantham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
