<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8976 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-THE-PILL-HNS &LR;      07-21 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-PILL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BIRTH CONTROL PILL SIGNALED THE DAWN OF FEMINISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before ``the pill'' came to mean birth control, young women
who had premarital sex faced a set of potential social consequences
beyond the pregnancy itself.
</P>
<P>
   Unwed, pregnant women sometimes disappeared, to return and
resume life after delivering their babies in charitable homes.
Infants were represented as premature, born once couples were
safely married. Contraceptives and abortions were covertly sought.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine P. Henrikson recalled just what was at stake in the
1960s, while she was a graduate student and sought the pill, which
carried greater health risks than today's version.
</P>
<P>
   ``The remote possibility of a blood clot would have paled by
comparison of being pregnant and not married,'' said Henrikson, now
a 60-year-old research scientist and the new board president of
Upper Hudson, N.Y., Planned Parenthood. ``The social and family
consequences would have been a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The pill in its 40th year has been praised as a revolutionary
breakthrough that freed women and couples to decide the size and
timing of their families. Religious opposition aside, the pill,
too, was criticized, particularly when early forms were linked to
health risks, including possible stroke and blood clots.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was perceived differently by different people in
1960, this pharmaceutical form of birth control would become an
undeniable social force, entering the marketplace with a push from
the feminist movement, the sexual revolution and the fight for
civil, including reproductive, rights. A Smithsonian researcher has
called the pill one of the most socially significant medical
advancements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was utterly revolutionary. It really revolutionized birth
control,'' said Janet Farrell Brodie, associate professor of
history at Claremont Graduate University, near Los Angeles. ``It
was relatively cheap, it was relatively safe and accessible, and it
was very, very effective. It gave women the control of fertility
that women wanted for 160 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodie wrote about the history of birth control in ``The
Reader's Companion to U.S. Women's History'' (1998 Houghton Mifflin
Co.). Recalling the desperation of poor immigrant women, who in the
early 1900s beseiged birth-control advocate Margaret Sanger for
contraceptive secrets, ``the pill was that thing that women
wanted,'' the historian said.
</P>
<P>
   History shows that the pill had several fathers: scientist Carl
Djerassi in 1951 led the team that developed an early synthetic
progesterone, which, with estrogen, mimics the hormones' natural
function to inhibit ovulation as the body prepares for pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The pill also was the dream of feminists Sanger and Katherine
McCormick, who backed the successful scientific partnership that
created the first one.
</P>
<P>
   Several pharmaceutical companies held a skittish race in the
conservative 1950s to harness the synthetic compounds'
contraceptive power before scientists Gregory Goodwin Pincus and
John Rock successfully developed Enovid for G.D. Searle &AMP; Co. The
U.S. Food &AMP; Drug Administration approved Searle's first
birth-control pill in 1960. Other major companies followed suit,
and within five years, the pill became the most popular
contraceptive in the United States. A woman would take 21 active
pills, stopping to allow menstruation. Some products included seven
placebos, as reminders to continue taking it during the average
28-day cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Henrikson was among the young women for whom the pill meant the
difference between sexual freedom and social disgrace in the
conservative climate of Boston in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   She attended graduate school at Harvard Medical School
throughout most of the 1960s. In Massachussetts, the sale of
contraceptives to unmarried people was illegal until 1972, when the
U.S. Supreme Court struck down the law.
</P>
<P>
   Henrikson had to summon the nerve to seek the pill, once she
began a relationship in college.
</P>
<P>
   She recalls the prevailing view of sex, and the pill's power
over it, this way: ``The great advantage to the pill was it
separated contraception from sex. If you relied on some mechanical
method, that meant you were taking it with you on a date and that
meant you were a bad girl. When people worked up the nerve to ask
for the pill, you still had to get over the idea that this was
premeditated. It meant you were planning to have sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Those young women who got caught by becoming pregnant often
faced circumscribed paths. ``They would simply disappear'' to
deliver the baby into the hands of adoptive parents.
</P>
<P>
   Obtaining the pill, too, was often done on the sly.
</P>
<P>
   Retrospectives of life in the 1960s are full of stories about
women who were on the pill without admitting it, said Patricia
Gossel, chair of the Division of Science, Medicine and Society at
the Smithsonian's National Museum of American History. While it
certainly freed couples from worry about pregnancy, the pill also
occurred in concert with the changing role of women and more
liberal attitudes of the 1960s generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time was right for the pill to come and participate in so
many of the social changes of the 1960s,'' said Elizabeth Siegel
Watkins, author of ``On the Pill: A Social History of
Contraceptives'' (1998 Johns Hopkins University Press).
</P>
<P>
   While the media made the pill an icon of the sexual revolution,
the symbolism oversimplifies a complex era, Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a relaxing of a moral code ... There's got to be
a social shift to make premarital sex more accepted before birth
control is going to be handed out,'' Siegel Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   The press speculated greatly about the pill's role in
promiscuity, giving it greater or lesser weight depending on the
medium's editorial slant. But even as news swirled about sexual
revolution, liberal attitudes were slow to reach America's
doorstep. Some conservative middle- and upper-class Americans
considered the pill as part of the problem of wanton premarital
sex, Siegel Watkins found.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, when people had better access, the pill indeed
allowed single men and women to more freely have sex.
</P>
<P>
   Henrikson in 1965 had to work up considerable nerve to ask her
physician. ``I was very nervous about it, but I was trying to
control my own life.'' Like millions of American women, Henrikson,
once married in 1966 and free of side effects, also would use the
pill to time the birth of her two children.
</P>
<P>
   Henrikson is slightly older than the feminists who came behind
her who would question the safety of the pill.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Jaffe attended college in Boston in the early 1960s, but
it wasn't until she had graduated and was working in Syracuse that
she sought the pill. Jaffe traveled alone to a New York clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very scary. It was still very new. It was something to
make a special trip to New York and you didn't tell anyone,'' said
Jaffe, 57, now executive director of a women's philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   The pill's early use coincided with the early stirrings of
feminism. ``At first people felt that one of the results of our
struggle around women's liberation was freer access to birth
control. We felt that the pill and other forms of birth control,
that the availability of birth control was in part a success of our
women's movement,'' Jaffe said of the reaction of women she knew at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   That perception shifted, for Jaffe and some feminist
contemporaries, as awareness of reports of incidents of stroke and
blood clots accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   The pill's possible health complications prompted some women to
look askance at the varying opinions of the mostly male medical
profession, author Watkins writes in ``On the Pill.'' She argues
that this growing skepticism stressed the importance of informed
consent, and the detailed inserts that now accompany many
prescription drugs are the result of those health controversies.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffe watched the tide of optimism surrounding the pill change,
once she joined the feminist movement in New York City in the late
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think anymore that the medical establishment was
doing what was best for us,'' said Jaffe, who went off the pill
after a female gynecologist warned her of the possible health
risks. ``The first stage was great, it was something to pop in your
mouth to keep you from having babies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
