<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-EXEC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RETURN OF FORMER BANK OF AMERICA CHIEF COULTER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ David A. Coulter, who emerged this week with a
top job at Chase Manhattan Bank nearly two years after being ousted
as chairman and chief executive of San Francisco-based Bank of
America, isn't interested in looking back.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter, 52, made that clear Thursday in his first interview
with The Examiner since BofA was purchased by Charlotte, N.C.-based
NationsBank in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview one day after he was named the new head
of Chase's consumer and international banking divisions, Coulter
declined to say much about the circumstances of his departure from
BofA in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   What had been billed as a merger of equals turned into a power
grab by then-NationsBank CEO Hugh L. McColl Jr., who now runs the
combined institution with his top lieutenants from North Carolina,
where BofA became headquartered after the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to look forward as opposed to looking backward,''
Coulter said when asked how he views the NationsBank-BankAmerica
combination, and whether, in hindsight, he still would have pursued
the $64 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always tried to make the right decision from the
shareholder standpoint. You never have perfect information when you
make those decisions. It's hard to look back with better
information and say, `How would you change things?'''
</P>
<P>
   The merger has not been a boon for shareholders, with the bank's
stock now trading at $48.38, from a high of $61 in early June.
Shares of the former Bank of America traded at a high of $86.33
after the merger was announced in April 1998, but before the merger
was completed on Sept 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Merging the two banks resulted in 19,000 job cuts through the
end of 1999, including an estimated 3,300 positions in California,
1,800 of them in the San Francisco area. Coulter received a
severance compensation package valued at $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt his new senior position at Chase was a
vindication after being forced out of BofA, Coulter said that he
doesn't look at it that way, and that he is pleased that Chase
values his experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always nice to have someone say, `We want you.'''
</P>
<P>
   McColl initially said Coulter would succeed him as CEO of the
merged bank after McColl retired. But Coulter was ousted within two
weeks of the merger, after a quarterly report showed $372 million
in trading losses racked up by a New York investment company that,
using a $1.4 billion loan from Bank of America and other money, had
used a computer-based trading system to buy high-risk securities.
</P>
<P>
   The old NationsBank has since established its dominance over
BofA, holding 13 of 20 board seats as of the end of last year, and
four of five executive committee seats.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter is expected to be settled in New York by September after
shuttling between jobs as a board member of Chase H&AMP;Q and a partner
in the Los Angeles office of Beacon Group, where he manages private
equity investment and advises companies on mergers and
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Thursday that Coulter was a good choice for Chase,
given his experience and reputation for keeping an eye on
shareholder returns.
</P>
<P>
   As for Coulter himself, he said he is in a listening mode to see
how he can best make his presence felt at Chase. The bank's
consumer banking division, which he will oversee, reported a 1
percent increase in operating revenue this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
