<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAY-BED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JOY OF DAY BEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS   
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the forerunner to the sofa and the chaise lounge, the day bed
served as a place for quiet relaxation and contemplative
meditation.
</P>
<P>
   The day bed is a long seat with a stationary or adjustable end
that can be lowered to form a bed. Also called a reading seat, the
day bed became popular during the Restoration period (1660-1685),
and those with double ends were rare.
</P>
<P>
   They were quite fashionable in court circles, where they were
elaborately carved and covered in rich imported silks, damasks and
velvets.
</P>
<P>
   Day beds continued to be popular in large houses of the wealthy,
through the 1900s, where they were often accompanied with a
matching set of chairs and stools.
</P>
<P>
   Being relatively lightweight, the day bed was well suited for
impromptu gatherings and was often arranged with other furnishings
on a terrace or in the garden. Tented day beds also provided a
comfortable place to sleep during the hot summer nights.
</P>
<P>
   Open-frame day beds were popularized in China during the Ming
dynasty (1368-1644). Traditional styles included cabriole legs or
horsefeet.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, day beds were made from walnut or beech wood that
was painted black, with caned seats and backrests and spiral-shaped
stretchers and legs. Day beds made from oak, which was plainer,
were occasionally upholstered with a lightly padded leather.
</P>
<P>
   A long squab cushion or mattress and various cushions made the
day bed a most comfortable resting-place.
</P>
<P>
   New day beds in wood or metal can be found in furniture stores
for approximately $99 to $1,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is either closed on one or both ends and open on both
sides, the day bed is often placed lengthwise along a wall, topped
with an attractive coverlet and lots of fancy and comfy pillows.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the 19th century day beds, there are often tiny
wheels on the feet or legs, providing greater mobility.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heins writes about items in, on and around the home. Write to
her c/o Details, Features Department, Times Union, P.O. Box 15000,
Albany, NY 12212.
</P>
</TEXT>
