<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Saturday, July 22. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   WACO-REPORT (St. Louis, Mo.) _ Special Counsel John Danforth
concluded ``with 100 percent certainty'' that the federal
government was innocent of wrongdoing in the siege and fire that
killed 80 members of the Branch Davidian sect in 1993. By Jim
Yardley. (Early summary from wires.)
</P>
<P>
   EPA-GRACE-ASBESTOS (Undated) _ The U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency is investigating why for 18 years it ignored evidence that a
major U.S. company produced ore for its consumer products that was
laden with asbestos. An agency study in 1982 found alarming levels
in material that W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. has said was virtually free of
asbestos. But the agency shelved the report, scuttled its planned
followup studies and continued to accept the company's lower
figures, EPA officials say.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO-IV (Houston) _ George W. Bush left Yale University in
the spring of 1968 with a diploma in hand, but no plans on what to
do with it. So for five years, not unlike many young men his age,
he drifted. He lived in three states, had at least seven apartments
and at least that many girlfriends and held three full-time jobs _
one in business, one in politics and one in public service. By Jo
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Special Report, 3,600 words; an abridged version will also move.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT19.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ The Israeli peace delegation's
mood shifted toward the hopeful Friday as officials outside the
secluded Camp David revealed that Prime Minister Ehud Barak, two
days after summoning his plane to leave and then sending it back to
the hangar, believed the chances for the peace summit meeting's
success had improved considerably. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-WOMEN (Tehran, Iran) _ In a quiet revolution with
wide-ranging implications, single Iranian women are leaving home in
historically high numbers to seek higher education wherever they
can get it. Their self-assured mobility _ an independence of action
that their mothers and grandmothers could not even imagine _
represents a grand social experiment whose impact is already making
itself felt on campus and off. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   NY-AIRPORT-DENTIST (New York) _ Dr. Robert M. Trager is the man
with the unusual title of airport dentist and the unusual
responsibility of using dental and bone X-rays to determine an
immigrant's age, which can be critical to his or her effort to gain
entry to the United States. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT1, 2.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   G8-CLINTON (Naha, Japan) _ Russian President Vladimir Putin
continued to make the case against a national missile shield being
proposed by the United States in a meeting with President Clinton
Friday night, but Clinton, despite a failed test earlier this
month, refused to back down from the controversial defense program.
By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   FTC-INTERNET-PRIVACY (Washington) _ The Federal Trade Commission
settled its lawsuit against Toysmart.com, forbidding the bankrupt
Internet toy retailer from selling its database of personal
customers information, except under very limited circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MOSQUITO-SPRAYING (New York) _ Arguing that humans are more
important than a few fish, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani sharply
criticized state and federal environmental officials Friday for
blocking the city from spraying pesticides in wetlands and other
marsh areas in its battle against the West Nile virus. By Thomas
Leuck.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-BRITISH-OPEN (St. Andrews, Scotland) _ Tiger Woods set the
stage Friday for another major championship runaway, shooting a
near flawless 6-under 66 to seize control midway through the
British Open. By Clifton Brown. (Summary from wires.)
</P>
<P>
   CAVIAR-SMUGGLING-PLEA (Undated) _ Capping a case that exposed a
large-scale caviar smuggling ring, a Maryland company and three
people pleaded guilty Friday to a host of federal fraud, smuggling,
and wildlife charges and the company agreed to pay a $10.4 million
fine, which prosecutors said is the largest fine ever won in a
wildlife smuggling case. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
