<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8989 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-ENVY22-COX     07-21 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ENVY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hard to resist envy or resent new rich
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's not that Larry Cordle has anything against
people in high-tech; his own wife works for Advanced Micro Devices.
</P>
<P>
   But he's bothered by the adulation of the young high-tech
millionaires, whose sudden fortune has become the talk of the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're drawing a lot of attention, sucking up a lot of
resources and building a lot of ugly buildings,'' said Cordle, 45.
``Why does being rich make you interesting or meaningful?''
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Serpico, who worked in the insurance industry for nearly
25 years, said she doesn't begrudge these young millionaires their
good luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that we worked for a long time to get what little we
got, and we still don't have what they have, and we never will have
what they have,'' said Serpico, who quit her underwriting job 12
years ago. ``It gets to be a little much sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Society has always had its haves and have nots, its high-living
tycoons and its struggling working class.
</P>
<P>
   But the Internet economy has changed the rules and created an
unsually young generation of very wealthy people, seemingly
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The number of millionaires in Central Texas has doubled over the
last five years to 31,000, many of them thanks to the tech boom.
It's a national phenomenon: A Fortune magazine package on what it
called ``the young and the loaded'' included a listing of the 40
richest people under 40. The youngest was 26; the poorest was worth
$243 million.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have missed out on the new economy, it can be hard
to resist some envy or resentment. It's a theme of lunchtime
conversations and letters to the editor, morning talk shows and
beauty parlor prattle. No one wants to appear petty or
materialistic; few of the people interviewed for this story wanted
to share their views publicly. But the sentiments are there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both adulate and attack'' the new rich, said Paul
Schervish, director of the Boston College Welfare Research
Institute, which studies how affluence is changing the culture.
``They're our saints and our sinners.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The American dream is supposed to have the right combination
of effort, intelligence and luck,'' he said. ``When it appears to
be too much, too young, we are bothered by it. It makes us feel
diminished.''
</P>
<P>
   And the in-your-face displays of this wealth can be hard to take
_ the massive mansions, with media rooms and auto barns and master
bedrooms larger than most houses, rising all around Austin; the
shiny midnight blue Corvette with its ``IPO-Vet'' license plate
whizzing by on Mopac; the $36 T-bone steaks and $1,000 bottles of
wine at Austin's growing number of posh restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these new millionaires got there by grueling 80-hour
weeks and sacrificing their personal lives. But then there are the
people who bought Dell at $4 a share or went to work at a startup
weeks before its successful IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Borowitz, New York author of the satirical ``The
Trillionaire Next Door: The Greedy Investor's Guide to Day
Trading,'' a said he never felt envious of the Yankees
centerfielder or the glamorous movie star who pulled in millions of
dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could say to myself, I can't catch a fly ball, I can't do
the things they can do,''' Borowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   But this is different, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have always been envious of those who have made tons of
money,'' Borowitz said. ``In the current climate, that envy is
coupled with the stinging sense that but for that one good tip or
trade, we could be right where they are. The more unspectacular the
wealthy are, the more it bothers us. We think, 'It could be us. It
should be us.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, wealth was predicated on one's ability to turn
natural resources _ land, cattle, oil _ into riches, said Lodis
Rhodes, a professor at the LBJ School of Public Affairs who
specializes in technology and community development.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the 19th Century _the Gilded Age _ was a tremendous
period of innovation, with the advent of the telephone, the
automobile and electricity. These were the days of the Morgans and
Rockefellers and Carnegies, who made their fortunes off steel,
coal, oil and the railroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were the entrepreneurs who helped build industries and
became wealthy in the process _ wealth like society had never
seen,'' said Marcia Cantarella, an assistant dean at Princeton
University who teaches a course called ``The Big Money: America's
Ambivalence Toward Wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been other periods of explosive wealth -- the 1920s,
with its stock market boom and land speculation, and the ``greed is
good'' '80s, Cantarella said.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledge has been a traditional path to wealth. People spent
years in law school or medical school, going on to build successful
practices. They paid their dues.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in this new information economy, people are turning ideas
into gold with astonishing speed. Neither age nor experience seem
to matter, and the concept of dues paying has all but disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can come up with an idea that seems to be new, and you
can market it as a new idea, you can quickly turn that into paper
wealth,'' Rhodes said. ``That accounts for why you can have
twenty-somethings with a great deal of paper wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony, said Borowitz, is that even those with money feel
envious in this new economy. Doctors and lawyers look longingly at
the large fortunes of young techies. Those with millions, he said,
long for billions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Wall Street types who are infuriated that their huge
bonuses are dwarfed by the incredible paper millions of the
dot-comers,'' Borowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If life is defined by how much money you make, then there was
a whole generation that was sold a bill of goods,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In some new economy capitals, the backlash has been hostile.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Francisco Bay area, where an estimated 64 new
millionaires are created every day, and real estate prices have
become insanely high, these sentiments have become increasingly
visible.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, a group called the Yuppie Eradication
Project has emerged in response to the gentrification of the city's
Mission District.
</P>
<P>
   One flier urged that ``Cigar bar clowns be chased back to the
suburbs'' and that ``Lexus, Porsches and Jaguars be vandalized.''
The project has encouraged the bombing of yuppie bars and
restaurants . Some have awakened to find their homes or cars
spray-painted with such phrases like ``Get Out Yuppie Scum.''
</P>
<P>
   The movement's leader, Kevin Keating, was arrested last summer
for making terrorist threats after police picked him up with a
knapsack stuffed with anti-yuppie fliers. The charges were later
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some street guerilla reaction building,'' said Gary
Chapman, an expert on the new economy at the LBJ School of Public
Affairs at the University of Texas, although he says it's a hard
thing to quantify.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, the signs have been milder. In Hyde Park, one of
several Central Austin neighborhoods where charming old bungalows
are being snatched up by young families with money, fliers have
been taped up with the warning: ``This neighborhood is being
gentrified.''
</P>
<P>
   A billboard on West Fifth Street for Buffalo Billiards says:
``Pretend this ball is your friend who can't stop talking about how
much he made on his IPO. It's your shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest people feel too envious of this new generation of
millionaires, there is a downside, according to some experts. It's
not all champagne and caviar.
</P>
<P>
   In a culture where almost anybody can be turned into a victim,
psychologists have coined a names include a deep identity crisis,
anxiety, guilt and dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, two psychologists in the Bay Area recently established
a clinic for depressed millionaires called The Money, Meaning and
Choices Institute. Although headquartered in the San Francisco Bay
Area, the institute deals has clients from coast to coast, said
psychologist Stephen Goldbart, one of the founders of the
institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a society that says that if you have money, you
should be happy,'' Goldbart said. ``What we discovered is that a
lot of people who come into money are shocked at how it affects
their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course those with ``No Wealth Syndrome'' _ most everybody
else _ may find it hard to sympathize with their problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the big bank account is the panacea, then everyone else
will feel left out,'' Goldbart said.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact R. Michelle Breyer at mbreyer(at)statesman.com
or 445-3856.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
