<HEADER>
A8991 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TESTDRIVE-BMW3231     07-21 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-BMW3231 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BMW 323i wagon fast, versatile
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although available in other parts of the world for some time,
it's only now that BMW's compact 323i sport wagon, read station
wagon, is available in the United States. It can only enhance sales
of the 3-Series line, which includes the Z3 and ``M''
high-performance roadsters and coupes built at Greer, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, here's a wagon that enables consumers and critics to
say, ``Hey, this drives and rides like a sedan.''
</P>
<P>
   Pricing begins at $29,200 with the 323i debuting as a vehicle
strong on safety that offers seating for five with enough engine _
a 170-horsepower inline six-cylinder _ to move briskly. It's
difficult to believe traditional wagon drivers are going to really
be swayed by the 323i's 155 mph speedometer and BMW's claim that
it's computer-limited to 128 mph and has a zero-to-60 mph time of
8.8 seconds. Those are not real-world numbers, but come from
professional drivers on test tracks.
</P>
<P>
   No, what's best about the 323i is its sheer utility. So it won't
take the 4-by-8 sheet of plywood that's the traditional test of
van, wagon and pickup cargo capacity. What it will do is take five
passengers, two really comfortable and three a bit crowded in the
second seat, and 25.7 cubic feet of cargo.
</P>
<P>
   It does this while, well, driving like a sedan and
parking/maneuvering like a compact. An unloaded weight of 3,351
pounds gives a solid feel, and the 323i has an overall length of
14-plus feet, about the same as a Ford Escort or Mitsubishi
Eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   The interior is typical BMW, meaning it provides good
white-on-black instrumentation with orange lighting at night,
comfortable six-way adjustable front seats and simple controls. The
test 323i, which totaled $34,620, added optional steering-wheel
controls for the upscale stereo and traction/stability control
systems that enhance drivability and safety. Power anti-lock disc
brakes are a standard feature on all 3-Series vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its test-track figures and 170-hp engine, the five-speed
automatic can be draggy in coming up to speed and isn't really
eager to downshift. Fortunately, there's a manual-shift feature
and, for purists, a five-speed manual transmission is standard.
</P>
<P>
   Limit the number of passengers to four, and all will ride in
style. The outboard rear seats are about as cushy as those up
front. The 323i has a sizable rear center console that folds and
pops out drink holders every bit as functional as the two up front.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of three rear head restraints hampers rear
visibility a bit; otherwise, it's good all around. The cargo area
comes with a restraining net and a window-blind type cover to hide
whatever's being hauled.
</P>
<P>
   But the 323i is best viewed as a people mover, one that should
fare well in the metro area in view of the popularity of upscale
vehicles. It's also a good alternative to gas-guzzling
sport-utilities and vans that don't drive like sedans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
