u s BC-GLF-BROPEN-BISHER22-C     07-21 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-BISHER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golden Bear, southpawsget their due
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   St. Andrews, Scotland _ This was a day that could grab and jerk
you about in a dozen different directions. You know how the Scots
are about tradition. Their halls hang heavy with it. They say grace
over their battlefields. There's a marker or some symbol for
anything of any consequence that ever took place here, from
Bannockburn to Leuchers. So it fell to reason that Jack Nicklaus'
last British Open would not be allowed to pass without due
ceremony, especially being here at St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   That is, should it be his last, which I doubt. But the Scots
made the most of it, posing him and having him wave from the stone
bridge at 18, doing the traditional ``farewell'' news conference,
during which he let it slip that chairman Hugh Campbell, of the
Championship Committee, already had invited him back to St. Andrews
when the Open returns in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be 65 then, and I'll have to see how it goes. I don't say
that this is my very last. I don't ever, ever say never,'' Nicklaus
said, speaking to an interview room packed with a panting press
herd.
</P>
<P>
   So choke back the tears. Spare the grief. Save yourself until
the Golden Bear etches it in stone.
</P>
<P>
   On another sentimental side, the most refreshing event of the
day centered on the tragicomic figure of the Open at Carnoustie
last year. Jean Van de Velde, the Frenchman, came off more popular
in defeat than he would have been in victory. Far more widely known
and acclaimed than Paul Lawrie, who won, and who joined a brigade
of former champions who were missing the cut here.
</P>
<P>
   Transferring his ambitions to America, Van de Velde has done
more in the name of sportsmanship than even the Boy Scouts. He has
played well, earned well and borne up under burden of his
bunglesome finish at Carnoustie in good spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it get tiring? Not really,'' he said to answer a
question. ``I said last year that I would probably have to talk
about it for 10 years. I played 71 holes pretty well. That's what
I'm looking at. No one beat me even in 72 holes.''
</P>
<P>
   He lost the four-hole playoff to Lawrie, and not to be forgotten
is Justin Leonard, third party to the extended championship.
</P>
<P>
   So while Lawrie, the Scot, was checking in with rounds of 78-75,
and out of town, Van de Velde finished with a birdie at 18 and a
round of 68, 36 holes in 139. The bunker at the Road Hole cost him
a stroke. The lead is not unachievable. And the audiences of the
Old Course are cheering along with him. ``My reception has been
fantastic,'' he said, ``but it has been like that everywhere I go
all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The first 36-hole leader who made an appearance on the board
brought into focus another side of the game, the left side. Steve
Flesch, the Kentuckian who dodged basketball _ ``I went to
Kentucky, where basketball is life, but fortunately I found golf''
_ checked in at 137 and played an encore visit to the media center.
It was then established that with four left-handed players in the
field, this a record for the sinister side at a British Open:
</P>
<P>
   Flesch, Phil Mickelson, Mike Weir and the curtain-call champion
of 1963, Bob Charles.
</P>
<P>
   This championship has a peculiar attachment to the southpaw
side. It is the only major ever won by a left-hander. Now it
appears that three of the four would make the cut, Flesch leading
the parade. He is not the first left-hander out of the University
of Kentucky. Russ Cochran, who is not here, preceded him, and at
times they have found themselves sort of lone rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny thing, `` Flesch said, ``Kentucky is a school with two
professionals on the tour and both are left-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the limestone in the water, which, they say, lends to
the breeding of great thoroughbreds. Flesch comes from Union, Ky.,
a burg just south of Cincinnati. He started playing golf
right-handed, ``because my father was right-handed. Then I hit some
balls with one of my uncle's clubs. He's left-handed. It felt so
good I changed. I'm naturally left-handed, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   There would be scoring changes, and Flesch would be passed by
David Toms, another Southeastern Conference alum, from LSU. But
hovering above the field, like the Goodyear blimp, a shadowing
menace, was Tiger Woods, and it appeared the 2000 Open was sitting
there for his taking.
</P>
<P>
   But for the day, here's to the guys who swing from the other
side.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
