<HEADER>
A8997 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV23-NY     07-21 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC VIEW: DEATH, TAXES AND LETTING THE HEIRS FOOT THE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By TOM REDBURN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Americans should not be taxed when they die,'' declared Rep.
Bill Archer, R-Texas, the chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, just before the House voted last month to end what
opponents of the estate tax call the ``death tax.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ancient Egyptians built elaborate fortresses and tunnels
and even posted guards at tombs to stop grave robbers,'' he added.
``In today's America, we call that estate planning.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad line, but what about the living? Should someone be
able to inherit, say, $10 million without paying any tax on it? If
you cash in $10 million in stock options from starting a new
company, you face a federal tax bill of as much as $2 million on
the capital gains. And someone who gets a $10 million paycheck for
starring in a movie or pitching for the Yankees probably pays a tax
of nearly $4 million. Where's the logic in treating these people
differently?
</P>
<P>
   There isn't any, argues William Gale, a senior fellow at the
Brookings Institution in Washington, who recommends that the United
States replace the estate tax with a true inheritance tax, or what
he calls a ``transfer'' tax. This distinction is not just
semantics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The estate tax raises all kinds of emotional arguments about
the tax collector reaching into the grave,'' Gale said. ``But if
you think broadly about the tax system, it makes sense to tax all
sources of income consistently. Ideally, a transfer of wealth,
whenever it occurs, should be treated the same as any other source
of income,'' with taxes on it payable by the recipient.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the way the estate tax works. Today, when a wealthy
person dies, his estate pays a tax on the value in excess of
$675,000, an amount that is scheduled to rise gradually to $1
million by 2006. Family-owned businesses and farms are exempt up to
$1.3 million. Above those limits, estates are subject to a
graduated tax, with a top rate of 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a politically popular move, both houses of Congress have
voted to eliminate the estate tax within 10 years. Lawmakers
rejected a White House proposal simply to raise the exemption for
family businesses and farms. For the moment, nothing is likely to
change, since President Clinton has said he will veto the repeal
bill.
</P>
<P>
   But many economists contend that a true inheritance tax _
introduced as part of a broader overhaul aimed at simplifying the
whole income tax system, closing loopholes and reducing rates as
much as possible _ looks like a better approach than either of the
alternatives currently on the table. Large transfers of wealth
would be treated like other sources of income, with all the
recipients paying taxes on their bequests at rates similar to those
imposed on wages, interest and dividends. By broadening the tax
base, rates could be lower, too. In the case of ongoing businesses,
Gale recommends a method to make the payments more manageable.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the United States is one of only three major countries
_ Britain and New Zealand are the others _ that rely solely on the
estate tax to tax transfers of wealth. Most others use inheritance
taxes or some combination of the two.
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting as well that some of the most thoughtful
supply-siders _ those who worry that high marginal tax rates
discourage work and savings _ are not necessarily opposed to
inheritance taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The estate tax is a very inefficient tax,'' says Alan
Reynolds, director of economic research at the Hudson Institute in
Washington. ``It's a major source of complexity, and the truth is
that it is fairly easy to avoid. An inheritance tax, at a low rate
and allowing for income averaging, avoids many of its problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the existing estate tax argue that repeal would
simply be a gift to those who deserve it least. And in a political
system where there are many competing claims by far needier people,
it would be.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, keeping the estate tax provides a powerful extra
incentive for wealthy people to give to charity or set up
foundations, helping to soften the harsher edges of a capitalist
system that has rewarded them so handsomely.
</P>
<P>
   But its critics have a point, too. At the top rates, a dollar of
earned income left in a taxable estate yields only about 27 cents
for heirs. That may encourage some high-income professionals and
executives, argues Martin Feldstein, a conservative economist at
Harvard, ``to retire early or simply to work less, save less and
take less investment risk,'' creating less wealth for society as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
   So why not impose a more reasonable tax _ on the heirs? Then
they might decide to go out and pull their weight, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
