<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9000 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-PTCRUISER-     07-21 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-PTCRUISER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2001 CHRYSLER PT CRUISER: THE SEXIEST VAN ALIVE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
(editors: optional sidebar at end of article) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT7 has been sent sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAN NEIL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good and proper fenders, those curvaceous swells of metal
flanking the bodies of vintage cars, began to fade away with
Chrysler's Airflow of 1934. By the mid-1950s, fenders were pretty
thoroughly smoothed into cars' overall shape. Now, with the
Chrysler PT Cruiser, fenders are back. Can't the company make up
its mind? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fenders are but one of many nostalgic notes played by the
2001 PT Cruiser, DaimlerChrysler's category-defying
minivan-cum-sedan. Its overall shape owes much to the 1937 Plymouth
PT50 commercial sedan as well as to the Ford Fordor sedan of the
late 1930s _ with a 1950 Chevy Panel Van and a little Willys
Overland in there somewhere _ though with the PT Cruiser these
contours are drawn with a mighty small pen. Visually, the
diminutive car comes close to being silly _ you rather expect
clowns to tumble out, or Shriners _ but the aggressively posed
front end, reminiscent of the hangdog look of classic street rods,
saves the car from terminal cuteness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the Cruiser is no longer hot news _ they've been in
rental fleets for months _ it is indisputably the hot ride of the
summer. Curious car lovers are still swarming around the car like
pesky mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   But novelty wears off and nostalgia is a shallow sentiment. The
glow went off the New Beetle when, in the sober light of the
showroom, shoppers began to see that it was limited by its
flower-powered design, that the roofline offered wasted headroom up
front but a neck-bending lack of it in back. In contrast, the PT
Cruiser's charismatic retro design merely camouflages what is
actually a supremely efficient box on wheels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lift the yawning rear hatch lid and you see that the floor is
flat, thanks to a low-profile beam-axle rear suspension. No
shock-absorber towers intrude into the space.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Government can't decide what to make of the PT Cruiser.
With its cargo-carrying versatility, it is a truck in the eyes of
the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, which enforces
fuel-economy standards and safety rules; the Environmental
Protection Agency sees a car in there, and holds it to automobile
pollution standards. The Cruiser _ PT stands for personal
transportation _ demonstrates how out of date the government's
taxonomies are in a market where some of the most popular new
vehicles are neither car nor truck.
</P>
<P>
   The split rear bench seat, with three sets of belts, folds flat
or can be pivoted upright and secured with straps to the middle
window pillar. The seats can be unlatched from the floor and
removed. (Since these units are heavy and awkward, a back brace
should be among the options.) With the rear seats out and the front
passenger seat folded down, the interior is cavernous, big enough
to hold two or three mountain bikes, an eight-foot ladder or a
downtown DJs rave-ready turntable and loudspeakers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even with the seats in place, but folded down, this van-in-drag
offers loads of usable cargo space. The package shelf in back _ it
can be used in several positions, and also doubles as a fold-out
table for tailgate parties _ can be positioned to form a level
surface from rear hatch to dashboard. If you run a catering service
or flower shop, your next delivery van has arrived. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the driver, gaining access to the PT Cruiser is as easy as
pulling up a chair at the dining-room table; the low step-in height
(about mid-shin on me) and high lintels mean one doesn't lean or
duck to get in _ as one must with, say, a Dodge Neon. The driver's
seat is mounted high, rather like a lifeguard's chair, affording
excellent legroom as well as the commanding seating position that
would-be SUV owners crave.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rear seat is some 8 inches higher than the one in front, so
passengers back there can see ahead (a car-sickness-prevention
measure that parents will appreciate along the Taconic Parkway).
Still, the rear headroom is more than ample for the most ambitious
beehive hairdos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The PT is only 168.8 inches long, nearly a foot shorter than the
Ford Focus wagon, but offers 64 cubic feet of cargo space, beating
the Ford by 8 cubic feet. The secret to this space efficiency _ and
the headroom, the great visibility, the easy access _ is the
elevated roof. At 63 inches high, the PT is a half-foot taller than
the Focus, which is itself fairly upright.
</P>
<P>
   In another company's hands, such a tall, stubby package would
look _ well, the word ``dorky'' comes to mind, along with the image
of the Toyota Echo. But DaimlerChrysler has wisely concealed the
PT's proportions with heart-grabbing retro touches.
</P>
<P>
   The fat fenders, the low and prominent bumpers, the lower-body
contours that suggest running boards, all give the Cruiser a firm
visual foundation that keeps it from looking tipsy, although the
center of gravity is quite high by car standards. The government
has conducted crash tests, but has not yet released the results. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That foundation is more than skin deep. The PT Cruiser feels
overbuilt, really sturdy for what could be considered, by some
measures, a subcompact. The middle roof pillars are thick and the
doors are wide and hefty.
</P>
<P>
   Under power, the PT's big-boned structure provides rattle-free
composure and excellent isolation from even the shabbiest secondary
roads. Contrary to popular belief, the Cruiser shares few
mechanical parts with the Neon. Indeed, the Cruiser, which is built
in Toluca, Mexico, has a surprising number of exclusive parts,
along with a smattering of minivan bits.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of substance is underscored in the heavy steel door
handles on the outside _ how many women will lose a nail on these
old-fashioned push-button mechanisms? _ as well as the polished
chrome door levers on the inside. The door gussets in the Limited
Edition test car were rich suede over dense, sound-deadening
panels. The sturdy rubber door pulls were textured to match the
wrap on the four-spoke steering wheel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All this comfort and convenience comes with considerable mass.
Tipping the scales at more than 3,200 pounds, the test car worked
up a lather accelerating to interstate speeds. Under hard throttle,
all the hard-won interior quiet melted in the face of engine howl.
Powered by an in-line four cylinder of 2.4 liters (with 150
horsepower and peak torque of 162 foot-pounds at 4,000 rpm), the PT
won't tempt hot-rodders to feats of derring-don't. The test car was
equipped with an automatic transmission, however, and the
performance equation improves with the standard five-speed manual.
Besides, the manual has a cue-ball shift knob; will that be enough
to tempt Americans back to the pleasures of shifting gears? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The car's handling suffers in the name of excellent ride
quality. On the optional 16-inch Goodyear Eagle radials, the test
car practically glided over the road, absorbing hits that would
send other small cars skittering. But the handling, even with the
``touring'' suspension, seemed a little shifty. In the
back-and-forth of spirited driving I found myself correcting the
steering more than I'd like, to keep the PT in line. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The driver's environment is functional and understated. The
gauges are set in a shiny body-colored panel that mirrors the
passenger's air bag cover. The audio and climate switches are off
the DaimlerChrysler shelf. But why are front-window toggles high on
the dash while the rear-window switches are toe-high in the back? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On balance, complaints are few and compliments abound. This is a
superb automobile at a terrific price ($16,000 before options). The
glossy black test car had luxury features like leather seat trim
and side air bags, power driver's seat, 16-inch polished chrome
wheels, smoked rear glass and heated outside mirrors _ plus the
expected air-conditioning, power windows, remote locking, traction
control and anti-lock disc brakes _ in short, everything you can
reasonably squeeze into a small car. It weighed in at $20,835.
</P>
<P>
   The charmed life of the PT Cruiser is coming to an end. There is
wide discontent across the land over long delivery delays _ a
neighbor ordered hers in May and won't receive it until September _
and dealers who demand thousands of dollars over sticker price.
That will end when the supply moves closer to the demand.
</P>
<P>
   But the essential goodness of the PT is likely to survive all
assaults. Above all, it is efficient. There is no wasted sheet
metal, no four-wheel-drive systems whirring away unnecessarily
underneath. The retro look is a stopper, but the useful design is a
keeper. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OTHER VIEWS
</P>
<P>
   Not since the 1998 New Beetle, or possibly the '65 Mustang, has
a car captivated the public like the PT Cruiser. Here are three
other views of the car and the phenomenon:
</P>
<P>
   HOT RIDE AT HIGH SCHOOl  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By AUSTIN LAVIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ Will the PT Cruiser, like the Mustang and
Corvette before it, become the car of a generation? If my friends
and I have our say, it will. Lance Kramer, one of my junior-class
mates here at Whitman High School, has made his parents take three
test drives. I persuaded my dad to rent one for a week when our
minivan was in the shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``This car is amazing,'' Lance said. ``I just love the way it
looks.'' The PT Cruiser is different; it stands out. When I drive
it, people stare, and whenever I park they come up and tell me how
cool it is. Porsches and Ferraris are so expensive I can only dream
about them. But with a base price of $16,500, the PT Cruiser is
agonizingly close. It is definitely the best car for that money. If
I could only convince my parents, I'd be so happy.
</P>
<P>
   GANGSTER CHIC, AND MORE
</P>
<P>
   By PETER PASSELL
</P>
<P>
   OJAI, Calif. _ Like many people, I fell in love with the PT
Cruiser's gangster-retro sheet metal. This, after all, is the car
Eliot Ness would want to be seen in, if he were still chasing
bootleggers through the mean streets of Chicago. But the PT Cruiser
is not just another marketing ploy from the folks who brought you
the sensuous (utterly impractical) Prowler and the fierce (utterly
impractical) Viper. It is a new category of people mover that
sacrifices nothing in style while delivering the versatility of a
minivan and the economy of a compact car.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it would be nice if the Cruiser had more pep, took rough
roads with a bit more composure and breezed through curves as
nimbly as, say, the Neon R/T. But where else are you going to find
a quiet, comfortable, roomy, inexpensive car that's so much fun to
drive?
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER BLAST FROM THE PAST
</P>
<P>
   By JAMES G. COBB &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK, N.Y. _ Bad times produce good design. After
Chrysler's near-death experience in the 1980s, its collective brain
turned out the useful minivan, the cab-forward sedan, the
mucho-macho Ram truck. The creative juices of a design team headed
by Tom Gale and John Herlitz jelled into jaw-dropping shapes like
the Atlantic show car, the Viper supercar, the Prowler street rod
and the PT Cruiser (attributed to Bryan Nesbitt, 31).
</P>
<P>
   But fine design cannot exist in a vacuum, and one secret of
Chrysler's success was a management that encouraged risk-taking. In
particular, Robert A. Lutz, who rose to vice chairman, went to bat
for proposals he liked, staving off the committee-think that often
dulls sharp ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed. Lutz retired. Daimler-Benz acquired Chrysler.
Many talented people defected. A new top designer, Freeman Thomas,
hasn't yet made his mark, but one wonders if corporate conservatism
has set in; DaimlerChrysler's other '01 models _ new midsize cars,
redone minivans _ don't set off the same sparks. Will the PT
Cruiser be the last testament to a remarkable confluence of the
right people in the right company at the right time? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
