<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVTOUR-HOLLOWAY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kramer no more _ but still a kook
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Michael Richards, a guaranteed belly laugh for
almost a decade as wild-haired Kramer on ``Seinfeld,'' returns to
TV this fall as a bumbling, Inspector Clouseau-style detective.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the plan. The project has had some trouble
getting off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Richards now has calmer hair but will never
exactly blend in with a crowd. For one thing, he's tall _ about 6
feet, 5 inches. And he has high-octane fashion taste. He loped into
an interview in an ivy-green suit, purple and white polka-dot shirt
and multicolored striped socks.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot for NBC's ``The Michael Richards Show'' was scrapped,
leading to speculation that the sitcom is doomed. But Richards is
confident his show will be on track well before its October debut,
and he's eager to convince people he's not the captain of a sinking
ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first pilot hinged on my character, and we recognized the
necessity of pulling together an ensemble of supporting
characters,'' he said in a conversation that was more earnest than
anyone expected. ``I have a driving style, so some of the
characters will circle around me, but it's going to be an ensemble
show.''
</P>
<P>
   Too much of a good thing, in other words. Within the past week,
Richards added William Devane and Tim Meadows to the cast. Devane
will play the owner of the detective agency, and Meadows, who has
quit ``Saturday Night Live,'' will play a fellow detective
struggling to overcome a voyeurism fetish.
</P>
<P>
   Richards counts among his comedic heroes Ernie Kovacs and Peter
Sellers, and his new character, Los Angeles sleuth Vic Nardozza,
will reflect those influences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course he's going to be deeply eccentric,'' Richards said
with a crooked half-smile. ``That's my interest when I'm building
characters. He'll do undercover work, so there'll be disguises.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there will be physical shtick. Kramer's
door-crashing, barely controlled sliding into Seinfeld's apartment
is legendary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most comedy on TV today is talking-head comedy,'' Richards
said. ``I like to do comedy, so there'll be a lot of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Kavet, one of three former ``Seinfeld'' producers working
on Richards' show, is well aware that it will be hard for the actor
to shake Kramer. As far as we can tell, Vic Nardozza hasn't fallen
too far from the Kramer family tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough balancing act,'' Kavet said. ``Everyone's
expecting to see the Kramer character but reluctant to see it
again. We'll exploit Michael's strength, which is quirky physical
comedy, but Vic will be much more human than Kramer.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards says he was never approached to do a Kramer spinoff
when ``Seinfeld'' ended but wouldn't have done one anyway. He
always felt Kramer needed to be in a mix. After ``Seinfeld'' went
off the air, Richards dropped out for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the classics, traveled, did a little interior
decorating,'' he said. ``I really had no incentive to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he does, it will be up to Kramer fans to decide if Vic
will stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``WEST WING''_ Aaron Sorkin, who writes all of the
dialogue-heavy scripts for ``The West Wing,'' is notoriously
troubled by deadlines, which often leaves the cast wondering what
they'll be doing in the next day's scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Fridays, before we have run-throughs on Mondays, we see him
staggering around the set in his pajamas, asking if anybody has any
ideas,'' laughed Brad Whitfordwho plays Josh Lyman on the show.
``He looks like a plasma donor. But then by Monday, it's all done,
and we have this brilliant stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield would not say who, if anyone, is killed in the
cliffhanger assassination attempt on the president. But it has been
reported in Variety that Moira Kelly will not return, so maybe
that's a clue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
