<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9011 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-WHITCOMB-ART-$     07-21 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WHITCOMB-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
  
 INVESTING WITH: Roland P. Whitcomb, First American Technology
Fund  
 (For release Sunday, July 23)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT4 has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plenty of mutual fund managers call themselves growth or value
investors, but Roland P. Whitcomb rejects those labels in favor of
another: technology investor, pure and simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology is an independent style of investing,'' said
Whitcomb, 42, the lead manager of the $799.1 million First American
Technology fund. ``You get one-time innovations that sweep through
the economy like automobiles in the '20s, television in the '50s or
personal computers in the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   The movements of these technological waves work against
proponents of the two investing schools, Whitcomb contends.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you enter a technology cycle, value investors get
confused by the apparent high valuation of the stocks, because they
underestimate the wave of innovation that's coming,'' he said.
``Growth investors often have trouble exiting the technology cycle,
because they take the growth rate that has occurred and extrapolate
it forward in a linear way.'' He added that ``the endgame of a
technology stock is that it becomes a capital goods or a consumer
durables stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitcomb gives each new technology cycle time to run. Investing
too early, he said, is akin to reckless speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Insights like that have helped the fund catch the technology
tide. The fund returned 66.6 percent a year, on average, for the
three years ended July 14, compared with 53.8 percent for its
technology peers, according to Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Whitcomb gets started by identifying new technologies in growing
markets, and then works with his six industry analysts to pick the
80 to 110 stocks in the fun. The key issue, he said, is valuation.
</P>
<P>
   One way that Whitcomb avoids overpaying for a stock is by
gauging the maturity of a technology company's market; a company in
a growing market, of course, is likely to warrant a higher
valuation than one in a mature market. He estimates a market's
potential size, looking at the volume of products or services sold
and forecasting the percentage of current customers who will need
to upgrade their products or services. In particular, he looks for
the ``inflection point'' _ where a market becomes more than 50
percent saturated and is due for slower growth.
</P>
<P>
   To value profitable companies that make actual products, he uses
a conventional dividend discount model, projecting the company's
future earnings and then discounting them back by using long-term
bond rates. He then adjusts that discount to reflect a company's
risk level.
</P>
<P>
   For unprofitable companies that nonetheless generate product
revenue, he forecasts when they will turn profitable and then
discounts the profit figure, taking into account net operating
margins and any interim capital deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   Most difficult to value are companies with recurring revenues,
typically service companies. Here, he forecasts the revenue
generated per customer, adjusting the figure for marketing and
other start-up expenses, capital costs and ``churn'' created by
customer turnover, and then discounts that figure back, too.
</P>
<P>
   Whitcomb sells shares if a company's market turns out to be
smaller than he had anticipated or if a company's fundamentals
deteriorate. He also trims shares as a company approaches full
valuation. The fund's annual turnover rate of 184 percent is high,
he said, because the market has been volatile.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks that technology shares in general are pricey these
days, after their rebound of the past two months, though he is
still is optimistic about their long-term prospects. ``Everything
is pretty expensive right now because we had a nice bounce,'' he
said. ``But we're on the verge of a new personal computer cycle
with Windows 2000, along with accelerating growth in
telecommunications, capacity constraints among semiconductor and
other component vendors and strong demand in the Asian markets.''
</P>
<P>
   One favorite profitable ``product'' company is Compaq Computer.
``It's a valuation play, because people have been ignoring the
sector lately,'' he said. ``But we expect companies to buy a lot of
Windows 2000-based servers.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's recent management changes and its cheap stock price, he
said, make it a bargain. He expects revenue to grow 11 percent a
year, on average, over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   He bought shares this month at $25; they now trade at $28.0625,
or 18.7 times consensus earnings estimate of $1.49 a share for
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite is Broadvision, which makes software to help
e-tailers track Internet customers. The stock hit a high of $90.67
on March 6 and now trades at $41.25, or 375 times Wall Street's
earnings estimate of 11 cents a share for this year. The fund
bought shares this month at $37.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think putting mainstream companies on the Web is a really
big market.'' he said. ``Broadvision is the biggest company in the
group and may lose some market share, but the stock price is down a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitcomb also likes America Online, which the fund bought this
month at $57, even as investors have begun to fret about the
prospects for online advertising. ``No one's sure what will happen
short term, and they're worried that ad revenues on the Internet
will slow down,'' he said. ``They might, but winners like AOL will
take enough market share that it won't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger deal with Time Warner will make AOL more powerful,
but there are risks in integrating two big companies, Whitcomb
said.
</P>
<P>
   AOL now trades at $57.625, just over 100 times analysts'
pre-merger earnings forecast of 56 cents a share for the year
ending in June 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
