<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IVORY-COAST-REFERENDU     07-21 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVORY-COAST-REFERENDUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFERENDUM MAY BRING MORE POLITICAL TUMULT TO IVORY COAST 
</HEADLINE>
   By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast _ This onetime redoubt of political
stability and steady growth in West Africa has been through a lot
in the last year: the fall of an unpopular president, the first
coup in its history and military misrule that twice in the last
month raised the possibility of another army uprising.
</P>
<P>
   During all this tumult the spotlight has stayed on one man, a
former prime minister and mild-mannered international banker,
Alassane Ouattara.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ouattara returned here a year ago from Washington, where
he served as the International Monetary Fund's deputy managing
director, his political fortunes have been on a roller coaster. He
is down again _ and, along with him, maybe the chances of Ivory
Coast's smooth transition back to civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Ivoirians are to vote on a constitutional referendum
whose key parts were intended specifically to exclude Ouattara from
running in the presidential election scheduled for September.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with a bitterness and a weariness that people say are
new to him, Ouattara, 58, vowed in an interview last week to win in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's this group of mediocre people,'' Ouattara said of his
main political opponents and the military government. ``They know
that they could not stand competition. They have their toys they
want to keep to themselves. They know that if we open up, they are
so mediocre they would lose everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The country's military ruler, Gen. Robert Guei, declared a
four-day state of emergency Friday , which members of his junta
said was intended to ensure that the referendum take place
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the former president, Henri Konan Bedie, who was
ousted in the coup, had tried to eliminate Ouattara as a rival by
arguing he was less of an Ivoirian than others because his father
was from neighboring Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
   Bedie's strategy was part of an overall concept of Ivoirite,
which he argued were values shared by pure Ivoirians, but which was
essentially tribalism that sought to draw a line between Christian
southerners and Muslim northerners like Ouattara.
</P>
<P>
   The cleavage was strange in a country that had long been known
for its ethnic tolerance. But even though Ouattara always
maintained that both of his parents were Ivoirian and he himself
was as Ivoirian as anyone else, ethnic divisions have widened in
the Ivory Coast in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   For a few months after the fall of Bedie, Guei, preached ethnic
reconciliation, and the two men appeared to be on friendly terms.
</P>
<P>
   But as Guei's intentions to hold on to power have become
clearer, the two men have stopped cooperating. The general, a
member of a minority ethnic group from the southwest, has adopted
the same ethnic strategy against Ouattara. A commission set up to
prepare the referendum recommended that a presidential candidate
must be Ivoirian-born of a father or mother born in the Ivory
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday evening, just six days before the referendum, Guei
issued a decree saying that a presidential candidate must be
Ivoirian-born of a father and mother born in the Ivory Coast. In a
news conference, the general claimed that 15 of the country's 18
administrative regions had pressed him to change the ``or'' to
``and.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people have expressed their wish,'' said the general, who
came to power after young soldiers mutinied throughout the Ivory
Coast in late December. ``We are here to respond to their wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   But the change was widely interpreted as another effort to
dislodge Ouattara. Another clause _ that a candidate should never
have availed himself of another nationality _ also seemed targeted
at Ouattara, who represented Burkina Faso for a regional financial
institution earlier in his career, a relatively common practice at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the December coup, Ouattara described it as a
``popular revolution.'' He said he had hoped that the new military
ruler would not try to cling to power, the way others have
typically done in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general was in retirement,'' Ouattara said. ``So we
thought he was really coming to help the process of restoring
democracy as he said he would. But obviously once in power he
wanted to confiscate and grab power. And this is quite a
disappointment for all of us who consider ourselves democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Arguing that none of these clauses affected his eligibility,
Ouattara has told his followers to endorse the referendum, as have
the country's two other major parties. So while the outcome may not
be in doubt, it will yield hints as to how September's election
might unfold.
</P>
<P>
   A constitutional court that will rule on the eligibility of
presidential candidates recently got a new head: one of Guei's
legal advisers. If Ouattara is prevented legally from running, it
is likely that the battle will spill onto the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I'll get popular support,'' Ouattara said. ``But I
hope it will not get to that point. I hope that the international
community, the regional partners and domestic pressure will put
sense into the head of the general.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, in a news conference a day after meeting
Guei, the U.S. ambassador, George Mu, said Washington was worried
about Ivory Coast's stability. The ambassador restated the State
Department's position that Guei, having seized power by force,
should not stand as a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mu's comments came after two days of rioting by soldiers in
downtown Abidjan. Displeased that they had not received money they
claimed had been promised them, the soldiers shut down businesses
and the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Guei took refuge in the police headquarters and was able to
defuse the situation only after agreeing to give soldiers about
$1,500 each.
</P>
<P>
   Guei accused Ouattara's party of fomenting the riots, a charge
he denied. The U.S. ambassador said they appeared to be strictly
over money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mutiny reduced the popularity of the general, who now
looks weakened,'' said a Western diplomat here.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was a reminder that even the general has never had
full control over the country's 14,000-member military since the
December coup. A military emboldened even further and ensuing
instability would make it harder to reverse the Ivory Coast's slide
and would turn it into a source of problems for the region, many
Ivoirians and foreigners here believe.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Second to Nigeria, the Ivory Coast is the economic leader in
West Africa. It stands as the world's largest cocoa-producer and at
the top of French-speaking Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But Abidjan, an African bright spot famous for its smooth roads
and solid infrastructure, is beginning to show the signs of being
led by a government that has little money left. Gaping potholes and
collapsed highway ramps have been left unrepaired for months.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he will run and win in September, Ouattara promised an
IMF-style cleanup of the Ivory Coast's economy that would include a
sweeping anti-corruption campaign and an overhaul of an inefficient
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Having left the IMF only a year ago, Ouattara said he was
pessimistic about Africa. He has seen too many African countries
ground down by men whose only concern was to capture or keep power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, if you have a system where the people can vote you
out, the situation will be different,'' Ouattara said. ``But many
people that get in are rigging elections or doing it by coup
d'etat, because they are mediocre. They know they cannot stand
competition. They confiscate power and continue to rule the
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
