<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SEX-ABSTINANCE-ART-2T     07-21 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-ABSTINANCE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ONCE AND FUTURE VIRGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RUTH LA FERLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If you don't like the way I am, just keep on steppin'.'' Those
are fighting words, she knows, and Donna Marie Williams, 41, levels
them equally at men who grouse about her weight (she's a plus-size
and proud) and those who try to rush her into bed.
</P>
<P>
   Celibate by choice for the last half-dozen years, Williams
hopped off the sex-and-relationship hamster wheel after her second
child born outside  &UR; of  &LR; marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I came to my senses,'' said Williams, a single
mother and author of self-help books, recalling how she put the
brakes on sex to regain a sense of independence and self-reliance.
``Before, I kind of depended on men to sustain me. Now I can do
that for myself.'' The greatest benefit of living single and
sex-free, she added, is ``knowing who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Another sexual teetotaler, identified in a Web chat room only as
204.240.2.73, took to celibacy after a series of bad love affairs,
the last of which left her picking dourly at her wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took stock then and realized that at 36 years old, I had
nothing to show for my life,'' she wrote. ``I saw other couples and
wondered what was wrong with me.'' Her discovery, after 10 months
of sexual abstinence, she said, is ``a self-esteem that I have
never experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   In a culture saturated with sexual messages, where consenting
adults seem to hop into bed at the bat of a feathery eyelash, a
small minority are willfully dropping out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Calling themselves ``born-again virgins,'' they embrace
abstinence not so much on moral or religious grounds, but to
cleanse themselves and reassert self-control.
</P>
<P>
   As old as ``Lysistrata,'' the notion of celibacy has taken on
new and particular urgency for these converts, many of whom, though
not all, have been singed by affairs gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a recent outpouring of books, manuals and screeds
advocating celibacy, including Williams' ``Sensual Celibacy''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1999), in which she argues that saying no to sex
recharges the spirit. She urges women to pamper themselves with
luxuries they might once have lavished on men: soft pillows,
scented candles, decadent underwear.
</P>
<P>
   The most scholarly offeing is ``A History of Celibacy''
(Scribner, 2000) by Elizabeth Abbott, the dean of women at Trinity
College at the University of Toronto. ``Thanks in part to AIDS,''
she writes, ``and much more to a stultifying surfeit of mindless
sex, celibacy has emerged from clandestineness and has crossed back
into the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   That would tickle Bridget Jones, Helen Fielding's best-selling
heroine, who is back in a sequel, ``Bridget Jones: The Edge of
Reason'' (Viking). In it she flirts briefly with abstinence after a
breakup. ``Celibacy!'' she exclaims, relieved to be able to put a
name to her condition. ``I mean, if it's happening to me, chances
are it's happening to lots of other people as well. Isn't that the
whole point about zeitgeist?''
</P>
<P>
   Miramax has commissioned an original screenplay from Wendy
Keller, author of ``The Cult of the Born-Again Virgin'' (Health
Communications, 2000), and Iris Martin, a psychotherapist, who is
one of many celibate women interviewed in the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a groundswell of women ready to curb their hormones
until and unless someone worthy comes along,'' Keller writes. She
and others predict that celibacy could become a ``movement'' with
millions of adherents, as unlikely as that sounds at a time when
sexually freewheeling women reign in television shows like ``Sex
and the City.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller, 36, a divorced mother in Malibu, Calif., is perhaps the
most vociferous cheerleader of the new celibacy. She was inspired,
she said, by the women she interviewed, as well as by ``A Return to
Modesty,'' Wendy Shalit's 1999 polemic against feminism, which
argues that the sexual freedoms of the 1960s and  &UR; ' &LR; 70s ultimately
betrayed women.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   No figures are available for how many born-again virgins there
are. The newly chaste (who include a tiny number of men) range from
purists, who refrain from all sexual activity, to those who tailor
their celibacy to suit their tastes, permitting a degree of kissing
and fondling but drawing the line at penetration.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 survey by the University of Chicago for the National
Science Foundation found that 17.4 percent of adults over 18 had
had no sex partner within 12 months. Many were elderly or had not
yet married. It is unclear how many in the most sexually active
years were celibate by choice.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Spencer, a senior editor at Glamour magazine, whose latest
cover promises ``65 Intimacy Secrets Men Need You to Know by
Tonight,'' scoffs at the notion of celibacy. ``It's not the sex
that's bad, but the emotional baggage these women have
accumulated,'' she said. ``The idea of cutting off sex is denial.
It's like taking cold medicine when you have the West Nile virus.
It stops the runny nose, but it doesn't change the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller acknowledged that many of the newly celibate have been
wounded in love. ``I think a lot of women come to celibacy from a
position of anger _ maybe 50 percent of the women I talk to,'' she
said. `` `You're damn right, men are pigs' _ they come to me from
that perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   In her book she advises them to stop blaming men and take
responsibility for their own behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, the college dean and celibacy scholar, is twice divorced
and the mother of a grown son. She had not embraced celibacy
personally when she began her research, but eventually her view
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It occurred to me that at this stage of my life I had been
celibate by happenstance,'' she said. ``I felt very tentative about
my life. I saw it as incomplete, and yet I had no control over
that. Maybe I would meet someone and maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I realized I've had children, I've been married and I've
had lots and lots of sex. I decided being celibate would focus me.
I would feel more in control of my life. I would try to become a
more complete person. Once you know that you're celibate, you
relate differently to people, you have more intensity in your
relationships with men. They are deeper and more intimate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the new celibacy takes place in the context of a
sexual revolution which went too far,'' she added. ``At its extreme
it put pressure on young people to have sex because it's cool.
Celibacy as an option for young people should always be out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison Saget, 40, an Internet executive from San Francisco,
decided to take a timeout from sex three years ago, after a
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   It helped her remain clear-eyed enough to sift potential lovers
in her life from the losers and cads, she said. Currently in a
relationship that has come to include sex, she found her
self-imposed dry spell rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer I abstained from sex the more confident I got,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Giannini, Saget's partner, found her self-assurance so
attractive that he agreed to put his own libido on hold. ``Allison
was intriguing,'' he recalled. ``Here was an outgoing, adventurous,
very contemporary woman with values that sort of buck the trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Carroll, 40, is that rarity, a man who is celibate by
choice (and not a member of a religious order). A features writer
for The Arizona Republic newspaper in Phoenix, Carroll, the
divorced father of an 11-year-old son, recounted his experiences in
a column last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to control my sexuality myself, instead of turning it
over to pop culture,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   He also came to share the wisdom of his sex-free female
counterparts. ``Just because you're close physically,'' he told his
readers, ``doesn't mean you're in the same area code emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Expecting to be labeled a hapless geek, Carroll was astonished
to receive 3,000 letters and phone calls within days of writing his
piece, most cheering him on, many from men. Today he is engaged to
marry, but said he and his fiancee do not intend to have sex before
the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll views celibacy as part of a journey to self-acceptance.
``At midlife,'' he wrote, ``I'm through apologizing for who I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
