<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9026 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-SUIT22-COX     07-21 0222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-SUIT22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke seeks lawsuit dismissal
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANAT _ Coca-Cola Friday denied the allegations in a $1.5
billion employment discrimination lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In its formal response, the company advanced 22 defenses,
including that its workplace practices have been based on
``legitimate, nondiscriminatory business reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   It asked that the suit be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in June on behalf of four black women by
attorneys Willie Gary and Johnnie Cochran, alleges that the company
created a hostile and discriminatory work environment.
</P>
<P>
   The former employees also make several other claims, including
that the company engaged in intentional infliction of emotional
harm and negligent hiring and supervision.
</P>
<P>
   This suit is a separate action from the federal class-action
lawsuit filed against Coke more than a year ago on behalf of 2,000
African-American current and former employees.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement in principle has been reached to settle the
class-action suit, which is being handled by a different group of
plaintiffs' attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   While the second suit was filed in state court, Coca-Cola
recently moved it to federal court, where it filed its response
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
