u w BC-MILITARY-GAYS-HNS &LR;      07-21 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON RELEASES ANTI-HARASSMENT PLAN TO HELP PROTECT GAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Announcing a new ``anti-harassment action plan,''
the Pentagon said Friday that military commanders will be held
responsible for failing to act against subordinates who intimidate
homosexuals or who ignore anti-gay behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military must function with honor and discipline at all
times, and that includes treatment of homosexuals,'' said Carol
DiBattiste, undersecretary of the Air Force and head of a panel of
civilian and military leaders that created the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was developed after a survey in March by the Defense
Department's inspector general found harassment of homosexuals was
commonplace in the military, especially among enlisted troops.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon leaders hope the plan will help solve the difficult
problem of enforcing the department's policy that allows gays and
lesbians to serve as long as they don't reveal their sexual
orientation. The policy, adopted in 1993, is called ``don't ask,
don't tell, don't pursue.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the measures the panel recommended to reduce the
harassment:
</P>
<P>
   _ Issuing a department-wide directive making it clear that
mistreatment and harassment of gays and inappropriate comments or
gestures toward them are not acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   _ Holding commanders and officers accountable for any failure to
enforce the directive.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewing all anti-harassment training programs to ensure that
they convey the department's attitude condemning harassment of
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   _ Making sure training programs let troops in each rank know
what their responsibility is in making the policy work.
</P>
<P>
   _ Encouraging reports of harassment by telling members of the
military the various ways they can inform their superiors.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Benecke, an executive director of the Servicemembers
Legal Defense Fund, a group that advocates gay rights in the
military, called the panel's report ``thoughtful and considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Benecke, a frequent critic of the Pentagon's policy toward gays,
said, ``Today's recommendations, if implemented, would be a very
good start.''
</P>
<P>
   DiBattiste presented the panel's recommendations at a joint news
conference with Gen. Eric Shinseki, Army chief of staff, who also
released an Army inspector general's report on the circumstances
surrounding the murder July 5, 1999, of a gay private at Fort
Campbell, Ky., by another soldier.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's report absolved the base's officers of
responsibility, saying there was no ``climate'' of homophobia on
base. Instead, the report blamed a sergeant first class for failing
to stop a four-month campaign of anti-gay harassment against Pfc.
Barry Winchell, 21, who was bludgeoned to death with a baseball bat
as he slept in his barracks.
</P>
<P>
   The Army report said that while some members of Winchell's Delta
Company held anti-gay attitudes, a pervasive homophobic atmosphere
did not exist on the base, home to the elite 101st Airborne
Division. It blamed Sgt. 1st Class Roger Seacrest, Delta's top
sergeant, for failing to stop the harassers.
</P>
<P>
   Two soldiers were court-martialed for the attack. Pvt. Calvin
Glover was sentenced to life in prison and Spec. Justin Fisher
received 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   The report exonerated Seacrest's superior, Capt. Daniel Rouse,
and all higher officers including the post commander, Maj. Gen.
Robert Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., questioned a number of the
inspector general's conclusions. ``Giving Fort Campbell a
relatively clean bill of health doesn't square with recent reports
of prevalent anti-gay harassment throughout the services,'' Meehan
said..
</P>
<P>
   During the news conference, Shinseki said that harassment
threatened the ``stability'' of the military. ``Harassment of any
kind violates individual dignity and tears at the fabric ... and
the cohesion of our Army,'' he said. ``It will not be tolerated for
any reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Outrage over the Winchell killing renewed a national debate over
the Clinton administration's policy on homosexuals, which gay
rights advocates say does not work because it has failed to protect
perceived homosexuals from harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department inspector general's survey found a
widespread belief among troops that the policy is not working. Vice
President Al Gore has said he would eliminate it if he were elected
president, but which Texas Gov. George W. Bush has supported it.
President Clinton said last year that the policy is ``out of
whack.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday Undersecretary of Defense Bernard Rostker took
issue with Clinton. ``I don't agree with that characterization. I
think the policy is working reasonably well to provide a degree of
safety'' for gays in uniform, Rostker said. ``The days of witch
hunts, the days of stakeouts, are really gone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rostker said more needs to be done to ensure that everyone
in the military understands the policy.
</P>
<P>
   Last August the Pentagon announced a new requirement that
commanders must seek approval from senior civilians at the Pentagon
before opening investigations of troops suspected of being gay.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
