<HEADER>
A9028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WANDERLUST-BOOK-REVIE     07-21 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WANDERLUST-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WANDERLUST': JOURNEYS WHERE THE MEANS IS THE END 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are as many walks as there are walkers. One explorer
trekked 1,700 miles across the Australian outback accompanied by
three camels. A woman known as Peace Pilgrim set out in 1953 on a
pilgrimage for world peace, beginning at the Rose Bowl Parade in
Pasadena, Calif., and logging perhaps 80,000 miles before, in 1981,
she was killed in a car whose driver had offered her a lift.
</P>
<P>
   In another era, Charles Dickens desperately paced London's
streets; ``If I couldn't walk fast and far,'' he said, ``I should
explode and perish.'' Walkers abound. There are climbers seeking
glory, urbanites seeking respite, believers seeking salvation,
protesters seeking change, flaneurs seeking amusements, joggers
seeking slimness.
</P>
<P>
   So what can possibly be made of all this strolling, hiking and
pacing? Writing about walking, it turns out, is almost as plentiful
as writing about writing, yet much of it, as Rebecca Solnit points
out in ``Wanderlust: A History of Walking,'' is ``episodic,'' with
``no overarching plot.''
</P>
<P>
   Solnit, who is herself an avid walker and elegant essayist,
calls one such book ``a sort of trail mix made up of bite-size
epiphanies, moral lessons, blisters, social encounters and
recounted practical details.''
</P>
<P>
   This subtle and suggestive study, though, is something else.
``Wanderlust'' is, as Solnit admits, an ``amateur history,'' but
amateur in the best sense. The trail mix is always ready at hand,
providing unexpected nuggets (Hobbes, we are told, had a walking
stick with a built-in inkwell) and piquant sensations (the desert,
Solnit writes, is ``a place where loneliness has a luxurious
flavor, like the blues'').
</P>
<P>
   Its real pleasures, however, resemble the pleasures of walking.
It doesn't systematically press on toward a goal, but savors detail
and varied perspectives, stopping to consider the nature of
mountaineering, the life of the London streetwalker, the conflict
between public right of way and private property in 19th-century
England and 20th-century Las Vegas. Solnit joyfully trespasses
across disciplines and genres, tracing a path through philosophy,
paleontology, politics, religion and literary criticism.
</P>
<P>
   But a path, as Solnit points out, ``is a prior interpretation of
the best way to traverse a landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To follow a route,'' she says, ``is to accept an
interpretation.'' And while Solnit's path may seem rambling, it
does indeed have a shape. ``Walking is usually about something
else,'' Solnit proposes, and the something else is usually an
attempt to explore ``the unpredictable and the incalculable.''
Walking dwells in a strange in-between state: half-public,
half-private; half-here, half-there; half-active, half-passive.
</P>
<P>
   For Solnit, though, walking is endangered, ``under assault'' by
the forces of the modern era: the phony colonnades of Las Vegas,
the growth of suburbia, the sterility of the treadmill. Modernity
is eclipsing nature.
</P>
<P>
   This is a familiar romance _ perhaps too familiar _ one that has
been part of the Western heritage since romanticism and is linked
to the countercultural sensibility that Solnit celebrates. But it
is also unavoidable; walking does indeed seem to have its rise and
fall. As Solnit points out, it has long been associated with the
philosophic mind: Aristotle paced while lecturing; Kierkegaard
rambled around Copenhagen while thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Some recent paleontological theories cited by Solnit argue that
the development of walking is associated with the development of
intelligence. But it was only with romanticism that walking really
came into its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only meditate when I am walking,'' Rousseau proclaimed.
``My mind only works with my legs.'' The vision of the solitary
walker that Rousseau pioneered came to define a culture. William
Wordsworth _ ``one of the first to employ his legs as an instrument
of philosophy,'' Christopher Morley wrote _ composed poems aloud as
he hiked through England's Lake District. Solnit suggests that
Coleridge stopped writing blank verse when he ceased taking walks.
</P>
<P>
   Solnit has less sympathy for 19th-century prescriptions for
health and happiness that developed around the culture of walking
and is more skeptical still about how walking's philosophic ramble
is harnessed to power and status in the cult of mountaineering.
</P>
<P>
   But she is fascinated with how urban life caused the walk to
mutate into soliciting, cruising, shopping, rioting, skulking,
loitering. Each city defines its walkers. With her casual San
Fransciscan ways, Solnit explains, she feels like an alien whenever
she is in New York, disrupting the fast pedestrian flow, ``as
though I were a butterfly strayed into the beehive, a snag in the
stream.''
</P>
<P>
   As a guide, though, Solnit knows the path well; she is tireless
and sure-footed. The only time she seems to stumble is when she
enthusiastically recalls the ``populist communion'' of the street
protests against the 1991 Gulf war; she suggests that because of
government censorship ``most Americans weren't much better off''
than Israelis in Tel Aviv who had to seal themselves in rooms,
wearing gas masks. Surely a veteran walker would have a larger
perspective on where particular paths come from and where they
might lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Solnit's greatest worry about contemporary life is what is
happening to the art of walking itself. The treadmill is the
emblematic villain. One writer noted, ``It is its monotonous
steadiness and not its severity which constitutes its terror and
frequently breaks down the obstinate spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   But this was a writer in 1823, who was talking about the
treadmill's use in English prisons. Now, Solnit proposes, the
treadmill's severity makes it ``a corollary to the suburb'': ``a
device with which to go nowhere in places where there is nowhere to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the walk uneasily comes to an end. Are perceptions of
time and space distorted now that the body is not the instrument of
motion but its recipient? Are the unpredictable and incalculable
doomed to be displaced by false certainties and familiar comforts?
Perhaps, but a mental stroll still has its compensations, and
Solnit makes thinking seem a lot like walking.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   WANDERLUST
</P>
<P>
   A History of Walking. By Rebecca Solnit. Viking. 326 pp. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
