<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET WATCH: AGAIN FEELING BULLISH, BUT NO LONGER BULLETPROOF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miami)   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Too much, too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had reason to smile last week. As expected, neither
rising energy costs nor high short-term interest rates stopped a
stream of strong second-quarter earnings news. And the Federal
Reserve chairman, Alan Greenspan, added to the cheer on Thursday,
when traders interpreted his comments as a signal that the economy
was slowing and that the Fed might be done raising rates, at least
for a while.
</P>
<P>
   That news sent the Nasdaq composite up more than 3 percent,
putting it back into positive territory for the year, and the Dow
industrials and Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 also rallied. So for at least
one weekend, Wall Street's biggest concern is likely to be nothing
more than the weather in the Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the picture is pretty, said Abby Joseph Cohen, chief
market strategist at Goldman Sachs. With the economy slowing a bit
but earnings still strong, she thinks the S&AMP;P 500 could hit 1,575
by the end of the year, a 5 percent gain. ``Second-quarter numbers
have been quite good,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Agreed. But that is not the whole story. After all, the
fundamentals were just as good three months ago, when the Nasdaq
plunged into a sickening tailspin that pushed it from 5,000 to
3,300 in a matter of weeks, leaving many investors bruised and some
broke.
</P>
<P>
   But during 1999 and early this year, the market, especially the
Nasdaq, increasingly became a kind of casino, a speculative frenzy
in which the performance of many stocks seemed almost entirely
divorced from the reality of the companies behind them. That
cognitive dissonance was most obvious in the market for initial
public offerings, as technology companies with no earnings and in
many cases no revenue found investors desperate to buy their
shares, which then rocketed higher on their first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   So when the plunge came, nearly every professional money manager
agreed that it was a necessary corrective. Necessary to remind
investors that most stocks do not double or triple in a year.
Necessary to prove that, as every investment textbook explains,
high returns do not come without high risks. Necessary, most of
all, because the capital markets are supposed to be a place where
deserving companies get the money they need to grow, not a casino.
</P>
<P>
   Yet now the froth is beginning to rise again on Nasdaq stocks,
which are up almost 30 percent from their lows of late May.
Double-digit dollar swings are again becoming common. On Thursday,
JDS Uniphase, the fast-growing fiber optics maker, soared $21, an
increase of 20 percent, on the not particularly surprising news
that the company would be added to the S&AMP;P 500 index. On Friday,
JDS gained an additional $6.875.
</P>
<P>
   The new-issue market, which slowed sharply in May and June, is
heating up, too. New companies are coming to market again, and 100
percent gains on the first day are again not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   All this worries even some longtime bulls. ``As painful as the
bear market was, it was absolutely necessary,'' said Bill Keithler,
who manages the $9.3 billion Invesco Technology fund. ``We needed
to shake out that kind of goofy speculation, and maybe it's not
done.'' Like other pros, Keithler is not anxious for a return to
the frenzy of last winter. ``I would like a more measured advance
as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not surprising. It took a drop of 30 percent to convince
speculators accustomed to a decade-long bull market that they are
not bulletproof. If the Nasdaq reaches new highs and they are able
to regain their losses in only a few months, they will have little
incentive to think of the markets as anything but a casino.
</P>
<P>
   And then the next crash will really hurt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
