<SLUG> BC-JONES-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL T. JONES: UNIONS OF THOUGHTS AND ACTIONS AND WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill T. Jones frequently talked as he danced in ``The
Breathing Show,'' his impressive solo on Thursday night at La
Guardia High School. But even when his voice fell silent, he still
spoke through the eloquence of his moving body.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized unions of thoughts and actions and words and deeds
throughout the 90-minute piece, which was staged in its New York
premiere under the auspices of his Bill T. Jones/Arnie Zane Dance
Company as part of Lincoln Center Festival 2000. The solo,
commissioned by the Hancher Auditorium of the University of Iowa
and the National Endowment for the Arts, was presented in February
at the New Jersey Performing Arts Center in Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Jones made no attempt to disguise his audible breathing in ``The
Breathing Show,'' which became a hymn to life. Much of the time he
moved to recordings by composers as various as Schubert, Mozart and
Thelonious Monk. There was also original music by Daniel Bernard
Roumain, who wandered across the stage playing plaintive phrases on
a violin. Jones' actions fit the moods of the scores.
</P>
<P>
   But occasionally he interrupted even emotionally fraught moments
to speak to the audience. He reminisced about teaching dance to
schoolchildren. He paid tribute to Isadora Duncan and confessed
that repeated listening to Schubert made him realize that ``I've
come out as a Romantic.'' He invited spectators to join him in a
meditative Zen breathing exercise. Most seemed willing to accept
that invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jones was usually serious, he also introduced
pleasantly silly jokes into the proceedings. Thus he had Bjorn G.
Amelan, who designed the production, which included an attractive
mobile, make repeated appearances in which he inflated and
punctured balloons. Come to think of it, those sight gags were not
totally frivolous: after all, inflating balloons does require
breath, and breath was a theme of ``The Breathing Show.''
</P>
<P>
   What helped bind the miscellaneous events together was a long
phrase filled with swinging movements that Jones introduced at the
start of the work. Then, like a composer devising variations on a
musical theme, he later offered different versions of it. In one he
gave a kinesiological analysis of every step as he did it. In
another he spoke aloud the random thoughts that were supposedly
running through his mind as he danced, among them reflections on
love, fear, Harlem, India, the Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival and
Hollywood movies.
</P>
<P>
   One might wonder if these were really his thoughts at the time
or if they were statements prepared in advance to create certain
theatrical effects. No matter. Art involves craft, and these
observations seemed typical of the free associations a dancer's
mind might conjure up.
</P>
<P>
   Dance sequences were separated by two films. Abraham Ravett's
``Garden'' depicted a garden dominated by large stones. And in his
commentaries, Jones echoed Voltaire in ``Candide'' by urging all to
``cultivate our gardens.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more striking was ``Ghostcatching,'' in which Paul Kaiser
and Shelley Eshkar used computer-generated images to create
illusions of apparitions floating through space and drawing chalk
lines and patterns on otherwise empty air. Whereas the dance
onstage celebrated the flesh, this film celebrated the spirit. The
production as a whole celebrated both.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you call life, it will come,'' Jones assured his audience.
``The Breathing Show'' was proof of that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
