<HEADLINE>
FURNITURE.COM FACES DELIVERY COMPLAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Furniture.com's chief executive, Andrew Brooks, wants to
revolutionize the furniture industry. But first, according to a
leading consumer watchdog group, the Internet retailer needs to
deliver those sofas, chairs and tables.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 Furniture.com shoppers have complained to the Better
Business Bureau in Worcester, Mass. about late deliveries, damaged
goods and other problems. The bulk of the complaints were dated
over the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extraordinary number of complaints,'' said Barbara
Sinnott, president of the local BBB. ``It makes me alarmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives with the Framingham, Mass. retailer acknowledged that
a surge in orders this year caused ``a few stresses in the
system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second quarter, there was dramatic growth in our
business,'' Brooks said. ``It was far greater than we expected. It
was far greater than our carriers and manufacturers were able to
handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com lost $43.7 million on sales of $10.9 million last
year, according to the company's IPO filing. So far this year,
Furniture.com's orders have ballooned to $20 million, Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the company's call center has been unable to
handle the volume of incoming customer calls. Brooks said shoppers
nervous about Furniture.com's layoffs and the ongoing dot-com
shakeout also may have called the company to check on their orders,
causing even longer hold times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message would say, `Your wait time is more than 20
minutes. Please call back at a later date,''' said Angela Woods, a
Detroit advertising executive who has not yet received an order
placed in March. ``That scared a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials say they have been addressing customer
complaints. Woods, for example, said she has been promised that her
glass table with mahogany legs will be delivered. In addition, she
said, the company has thrown in four free chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Executives say Furniture.com also has taken steps to solve the
internal problems that contributed to the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the retailer began working with a telemarketing
center handling many of its customer service calls. It also
abandoned a national carrier and has begun working with several
regional shippers with extensive experience in delivering
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   During the switch, however, the company believes several orders
were lost.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com officials downplayed the customer complaints,
saying they represented a small percentage of the company's total
orders. ``Our overall complaint rate is low _ and it's low in an
industry that typically has a high complaint rate,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sinnott said she had never seen as many complaints in such a
short time frame. Even giant retail chains like Framingham-based
Staples Inc., which had $8.9 billion sales last year compared to
Furniture.com's $10.9 million, have not racked up as many
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com is among many online retailers that are slashing
costs and laying off employees, hoping that the capital markets
will exhibit renewed interest in dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the furniture seller announced plans to raise up to
$50 million in an initial public offering. But by spring, it was
clear that Wall Street investors had developed a distaste for
unprofitable dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   The company delayed its offering, which has been formally
withdrawn, and laid off 29 employees. Last month, the company laid
off another 80 workers.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of Furniture.com's troubles, investors have stood by
the Web's largest seller of home furnishings even as they have
withdrawn support from other e-tailers. Last month, an investor
group led by (at)Ventures, the venture capital arm of Andover-based
CMGI, gave the company a $27 million lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   But industry observers have long predicted that furniture
sellers will have a tough time on the Web due to high costs
associated with shipping and returns, as well as limited experience
dealing with manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Furniture is a very difficult commodity,'' said Barry
Tatelbaum, an executive with Jordan's Furniture, one of Greater
Boston's best-known furniture sellers. ``You need to be so
systemized. You need to have your back-end (distribution system) so
well thought out _ and many stores don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
