<HEADLINE>
WOODS' 6-UNDER GIVES HIM LEAD IN BRITISH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ The wind comes in off the North Sea, the
brogues are thick, the days are longer, and the heralded golf
course of choice is devoid of plush green fairways. Yet in a
haunting way, everything about this ancient town is starting to
feel and look like Pebble Beach, thanks to the continued dominance
of Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   His record-setting performance in last month's US Open, a
15-shot triumph that worked like a shot of Novocaine to the golf
world, is threatening to play itself out again at the 129th British
Open. Woods shot 6-under 66 Friday to assume a three-shot lead
through two rounds. Brushing off an afternoon tee time that could
have spelled trouble, Woods drove to 11-under 133 and hurdled David
Toms (67-136), an earlier finisher.
</P>
<P>
   Lefthander Steve Flesch (70), Sergio Garcia (69), and Loren
Roberts (68) are tied for third at 7-under, and thanks to another
day of ideal scoring conditions, Phil Mickelson (66) and Fred
Couples (68) were among 27 who broke 70 and moved into the picture
at 6-under, tied with Erie Els (72), Thomas Bjorn (69), and Tom
Lehman (70).
</P>
<P>
   But unless they can figure out how to re-wire this machine
called Woods, those gentleman are playing for second place because
the leader has no intention of changing his game plan. It does not
take a genius to understand that plan; it simply takes one to carry
it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what you try to do in any tournament is not make
mistakes and don't make bogeys,'' said Woods, who would become just
the fifth player in golf history to complete a career grand slam if
he won here. ``Bogeys aren't good for a scorecard.''
</P>
<P>
   To underscore his point, Woods made his second straight
bogey-free trip around this historic layout. Going back to the
third round of the US Open, he has now played 62 consecutive holes
without a bogey in major championship competition.
</P>
<P>
   That streak stayed alive with a brilliant up-and-down at the
par-4 17th, though protecting his three-shot lead was his primary
motivation, said Woods. His approach to the Road Hole ran through
the green and down a short embankment, and it came to rest on a
thin stretch of grass before the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I might end up there, and there I am,'' said Woods.
He took out a club that isn't used much around this rock-hard
course _ a 60-degree sand wedge _ and played a finesse chip up over
the embankment, across the green to a slope, which he hoped would
turn the ball back toward the pin. It did, and Woods completed the
masterful sequence by draining an 8-foot par-save that had two
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been practicing that shot,'' he said, as if you
couldn't tell.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, another way to avoid bogeys is to make birdies, and
Woods is adept at that, too. He had watched the early action on
television from his hotel room and vowed to join in the fun that
the morning starters were having.
</P>
<P>
   Toms, for instance. Toms said his first goal ``was to play on
the weekend'' in this, his first British Open, and he assured
himself Saturday's last starting time thanks to five birdies in his
bogey-free effort. The three-time winner on the PGA Tour took over
the lead at 8-under by avoiding the incoming problems that roughed
up Couples, Flesch, and Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Couples, a six-time Top-10 finisher in this event, rekindled a
little of his laid-back magic by going out in 32, then adding
birdies at the 14th and 15th to get to 8-under. Alas, he violated a
golden rule on this course and slammed his approach into a
greenside bunker at the 16th, had to hit out sideways, and then
three-putted from 50 feet to give back two shots.
</P>
<P>
   Flesch, tied with Woods one shot behind first-round leader Els,
went out quietly _ one birdie, one bogey _ but birdied the par-4
12th and drilled a 3-wood from 280 yards to set up an 8-foot eagle
putt at the par-5 14th. He was at 8-under, alone in first, until a
bogey at the par-4 15th pushed him back.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia was next to get to 8-under, thanks to birdies at 10 and
12, but a sloppy three-putt from 45 feet at the Road Hole slapped
him back.
</P>
<P>
   Woods avoided such problems throughout his stroll over land once
guarded by Old Tom Morris. A few shots behind when he started,
thanks to what the morning starters had achieved, Woods promptly
knocked a sand wedge to 8 feet and made birdie at the first hole,
then added two more birdies to get to 8-under through just five
holes. Yes, the thought occurred that we had seen this before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am playing very similar to how I played at Pebble,'' said
Woods, who started 65-69 there to build a six-shot lead through 36
holes. His pursuers can gain a slice of hope, however, because the
last two days have not been as good as the first 36 at the Open, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can mis-hit a shot here and kinda get away with it,''
Woods said. ``I've done that a couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   You'd need a team of detectives to uncover those mis-hits, but
it's beside the point the way things are shaping up. Woods drove to
the front of the 314-yard 12th, chipped to 12 feet, and drained
that putt, then he made a 10-footer set up by a wedge into the
par-5 14th.
</P>
<P>
   His lead was three, but as the sun went down and the Scottish
air chilled the senses, it felt like 30. It also felt like Pebble
Beach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
