<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG WINS A STAGE, SETS RECORD IN TIME TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MULHOUSE, France _ For the past three weeks, Lance Armstrong has
had to endure the question on everyone's mind: Yes, the leader's
yellow jersey is nice, but when the heck are you going to win a
day's race?
</P>
<P>
   Neither Armstrong nor his team seemed concerned _ ``our
objective is the yellow jersey,'' was their mantra _ but only four
racers since World War II have captured the yellow jersey without
winning a stage. The last one to do so was American Greg LeMond in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong silenced the critics Friday with a resounding
victory in the individual time trial with just two days left in the
Tour. His time was half a minute faster than Germany's Jan Ullrich,
and set a record for the fastest pace in a Tour time trial or a
race against the clock.
</P>
<P>
   The race was almost a repeat of last year, as Tyler Hamilton of
Marblehead, Mass., finished fourth. The day before last year's Tour
finish, Hamilton was third behind Armstrong. Hamilton moved up to
26th in the overall standings Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the race, each rider sets out in descending order of the
rankings two minutes apart, or three for the top 25. Their only
competition is the course and the clock. Tenths of seconds, and
even 100ths of seconds, become critical, so the racers use
different bikes, often with a spokeless rear wheel, and wear
plastic helmets whose sleekness makes them aerodynamic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the race of truth, and I think it's important that the
yellow jersey takes it,'' said Armstrong, who has the overall lead
by more than five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't certain if Armstrong was bluffing Thursday when he
said he feared Ullrich would win the race. But the American's
rationale sounded logical _ Ullrich is the time-trial world
champion, and he'd be cheered by the throngs of Germans as the race
headed out from Freiburg, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jan is a big engine, and it was in his back yard, so that's
hard,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't look hard, though, as he set out from the starting
gate wearing his yellow Spandex cycling suit, hunched over the
handlebars, gritting his teeth, and pedaling furiously for the next
41 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
   Even though a time trial involves nonstop exertion, Armstrong
said he tried to pace himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, I start too fast, so today, perhaps, it was good
that there were tailwinds, but I started very conservative,'' said
Armstrong, who watched his heart monitor on his bike's computer and
listened to his time splits the team manager radioed through his
earpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard at the first time check that I was on the same
time as Ullrich, I knew I could have a good ride,'' he said,
finishing in 1:05.01.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's pace of 33.48 miles per hour set a record for long
time trials in the Tour. LeMond had a slighty faster pace in '89,
but it was over a course half the length.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not the biggest win of his career. Armstrong said
that would be the stage he won in the Tour of 1995 at Limoges. It
was three days after his teammate Fabio Casartelli had crashed in
the mountains and died.
</P>
<P>
   ``This win was not even close,'' Armstrong said. ``Limoges is
still my most memorable stage win and the most important victory of
my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he couldn't deny the satisfaction of wearing the yellow
jersey and topping it off with a stage victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was nice to win, though,'' he said. ``I had an empty
feeling up until now, and now it's complete.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton may not have the fastest time in the Tour, but he has
the lightest bike. Last week, a group of German technicians weighed
the bicycles used during the mountain climbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a special mountain one for Lance, Kevin (Livingston),
and Tyler, and Tyler's was the lightest bike in the (pack),'' said
Geoff Brown, the head mechanic for the US Postal Service team.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's bike weighed 7.3 kilos, Brown said, ``or a tad under
16 pounds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
