<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9044 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-INHERITANCE-TAX-ART-B     07-21 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INHERITANCE-TAX-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 A FEDERAL TAX WITH ONE FOOT IN THE GRAVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you believe the rhetoric coming off Capitol Hill, ending the
federal tax on inheritances would either: (a) help the rich get
richer, or (b) stamp out an unfair system that reaches into the
grave to tax the same money twice.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the gravitational pull of election-year politics, the
issue isn't so simple _ or polarized.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, quashing the estate tax would lower tax bills
for many but raise them for a few, simplify tax planning while
threatening the livelihood of tax planners, and give the wealthiest
Americans a boost, at the expense of charities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public discussion to this point has been largely driven by
politics,'' said Neil Harl, an agricultural law professor at Iowa
State University and the author of three books on the estate tax.
``The spin hasn't had much to do with reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the so-called death tax, adopted early in the 20th
century, may not survive long in the 21st.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Senate voted 59 to 39 to phase out the estate tax
between now and 2010. The House of Representatives approved the
same legislation by a 279 to 136 margin in June.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has promised to veto the measure when it
reaches his desk, which congressional leaders say should happen in
September. In its place, Clinton has proposed a partial rollback
aimed specifically at farms and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, we are on the verge of eliminating this tax, no
matter what the president does,'' said Jim Hirni, chief tax
lobbyist for the National Federation of Independent Business, which
supports the bill. ``The anti-death-tax push has gained so much
momentum that it's only a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that's true remains to be seen, but there is little
question the public would like to see the tax scrapped. A Gallup
poll taken in late June found 60 percent of those surveyed favored
its elimination.
</P>
<P>
   The strong economy, especially in regions such as New England,
is at least partially responsible. As stock prices and home values
rose in recent years, millions of middle-class families faced the
possibility of dying with a big enough estate to trigger the tax.
</P>
<P>
   One out of six questioned in the Gallup poll said they were
likely to ``personally benefit'' from repeal of the tax, which
experts say is probably too rosy, even in the strongest of
economies. In 1998, the latest year for which the Internal Revenue
Service has released estimates, only 2.1 percent _ or one out of 48
_ of those who died were hit with the levy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a pretty big disconnect between the perception and
reality of who is affected,'' said Steven Riley, a Florida
estate-planning lawyer and author of ``Generations: Planning Your
Legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, individual estates up to $675,000 pass
tax-free to heirs. Couples are allowed twice that amount, or $1.35
million, before the tax kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   By 2006, the exempt amounts rise to $1 million and $2 million,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers and owners of family businesses are allowed even more
before the tax takes effect. The basic exemption, for example, is
$1.3 million per individual or $2.6 million per couple.
</P>
<P>
   (The White House proposal would increase those amounts to $2
million and $4 million, respectively.)
</P>
<P>
   The IRS also lets farms subtract as much as $750,000 from an
estate's value to account for the fact that farmland is worth less
than land used for, say, apartments or shopping malls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is rare for a farm to be impacted at all,'' said Harl, the
Iowa State professor. ``I have been involved in this area for
almost 36 years, and I've never seen an instance where a farm had
to be sold as a result of the federal estate tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Selling the family business, though, is precisely what Cliff
Sjoberg's accountant suggested recently. Sjoberg, who owns a metals
fabrication company in Cranston, R.I., rejected that idea but is
still working with a lawyer and accountant to pass the firm to his
sons.
</P>
<P>
   When he took over the operation in the late 1960s, Sjoberg said,
his father simply gave him shares of closely held stock over a
couple of years. That way, they stayed within guidelines that limit
the size of tax-free gifts in a single year.
</P>
<P>
   But the current gift limit, $10,000 per person per year, is too
low for the 69-year-old Sjoberg to transfer the company in his
lifetime. And with the business valued at more than the estate-tax
exclusion, his family faces a whopping bill if he simply leaves it
to his sons when he dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see my kids take and work the business,'' he said.
``This idea of selling it because we can't afford to take and
handle the transfer is repugnant to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, many people with sizable estates avoid paying the
tax through complex planning, often involving trusts and charitable
donations. But when the numbers get too big, they typically have no
choice but to give up some of the assets _ or pay the piper, at
estate-tax rates that top out at 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hirni, of the NFIB, said that Sjoberg and other business owners
should not be forced into that decision, or forced to spend
thousands of dollars on lawyers, accountants, and financial
planners to deal with the tax. The NFIB prefers Congress's all-out
repeal to President Clinton's modifications, Hirni said, because it
would simplify business owners' lives.
</P>
<P>
   Killing the tax wouldn't eliminate the need for all estate
planning, of course. Individuals and business owners would still
have to decide how assets should be divvied up at their deaths, and
have legal documents drawn up to make their wishes known.
</P>
<P>
   It would, though, end much of the complex planning done
specifically to avoid the estate tax. That's especially true for
the handful of Americans with estates valued at $5 million or more,
who paid more than half of the tax in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   An unintended consequence of the change would be an estimated
decrease of $5 billion to $6 billion annually in charitable
donations from high-net-worth estates, which have traditionally
chosen philanthropy over taxation.
</P>
<P>
   Not every millionaire would save equally, though, if the death
tax is deep-sixed.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the current system allows a ``step-up in basis''
on stocks and houses when a person dies. The assets are counted for
tax purposes at their value on the day of death, rather than on the
day they were purchased. Heirs, therefore, are never taxed on the
often substantial gains in between.
</P>
<P>
   Under the system Congress has proposed, step-ups in basis are
limited to $1.3 million for individuals and $3 million for couples.
Heirs who inherit sizable investment portfolios or expensive homes
might face more in capital-gains taxes, which are hard to avoid,
than they would have in estate taxes, which can largely be
sidestepped with careful planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proponents of the (congressional) plan have sort of finessed
that issue,'' Harl said. ``For farmers in Iowa and homeowners in
Boston, who have a lot of wealth wrapped up in land values, it's a
pretty big issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepped-up basis also plays a role in countering the belief that
the estate tax amounts to double taxation _ the government tapping
money it has already nicked once. Stocks and homes, which now
account for more than half of the typical estate, according to the
IRS, almost always include tax-free gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start putting these things together, and you realize it's
not a simple case of the world being better or worse without this
tax,'' said Riley, who teaches seminars for the National Network of
Estate Planning Attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Riley said, both clients and his fellow
professionals seem to be expecting a major overhaul in the estate
tax soon, if not its outright demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are just waiting and watching,'' he said. ``It's
kind of crazy, but a lot of planning is on hold until Washington
gets done with this thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
