<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FOX-SEASON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX HOPES TO LIGHTEN UP ITS DARK, DISMAL SEASON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ If television ratings success eludes you, there's
always honesty. At least that seemed to be the theory of Fox
executives discussing the network's upcoming fall season for
assembled journalists on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Grushow, chairman of Fox Television Entertainment Group,
who was brought in to help the foundering network last November,
was frank in his assessment of the network's performance last
season: Fox ``failed to capture an audience for any of its new
series. And I don't mean they launched and failed. I mean they
never launched.''
</P>
<P>
   Grushow even offered criticism of the network's upcoming season:
``Taken as a whole, I'd prefer to see a more balanced Fox schedule,
one that relies less on dark sci-fi and more on shows that speak to
a young adult female audience.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Fox flagship ``The X-Files,`` the network has
four hourlong dramas _ ``Dark Angel,'' ``Night Visions,''
``Freakylinks'' and ``X-Files'' spinoff ``Lone Gunmen'' _ to air in
the coming season.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gail Berman, who became the network's president of
entertainment three weeks ago _ replacing Doug Herzog, the brunt of
most of the blame for last season's debacle _ mildly chided one of
the network's most successful series, David E. Kelley's ``Ally
McBeal.``
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that some of you have raised concerns that the show
took too many flights of fancy, sacrificing its emotional center. I
did agree with some of the observations that it might have taken
off into some flights of fancy _ that perhaps, it took too many of
them.'' (Winner of the Outstanding Comedy Series in 1999, the show
was virtually shut out in this year's Emmys.)
</P>
<P>
   In a startling contrast to NBC, which seemed to be champing at
the bit to wallow in the reality series trend, Fox _ notorious for
its ``shockumentary'' ratings stunts in the past, culminating in
the embarrassing ``Who Wants to Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' fiasco
_ seems to be employing uncharacteristic restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we obviously stepped back and took a look at was the fact
that there's a danger attendant to doing these things, and there's
got to be real risk assessment every time you say `yes,''' Grushow
said. ``We've even brought in an outside risk management firm
(PriceWaterhouse) to help us assess every single one of these
specials that are in development. It's a very challenging area.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Fox's only announced new venture into reality is an
upcoming summer series, ``American High,'' from R.J. Cutler, an
Oscar-nominated filmmaker of political films (``The War Room,'' ``A
Perfect Candidate''). The series examines teens and their lives in
and out of school _ the students themselves were given video
cameras to document their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think 'American High' at all deals in going over the
line,`` Grushow said. ``It's very instructive to see what's going
on in American high schools, and with American youth today.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's problems extend to a troubling trend _ in each of the past
three seasons, the network has announced a series on its fall
lineup that eventually ended up never airing. The odds-on favorite
to continue that trend this year is ``Schimmel,'' a family sitcom
starring comic Robert Schimmel that was yanked from the fall
schedule the day after its announcement received an unenthusiastic
reception.
</P>
<P>
   Grushow explained that the show was always planned as a
midseason replacement. Executive producer Mike Scully's work on
``The Simpsons'' ostensibly prohibits him from getting ``Schimmel''
into shape any earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than explain to the whole advertising community how
we're going to run four episodes of `Malcolm in the Middle' and
repeat episodes of other shows at 8 p.m. on Wednesday night, our ad
sales president basically suggested to announce (`Schimmel' in the
time slot),'' Grushow explained.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the comic has been diagnosed with cancer. ``His
prognosis is good, positive,'' Berman reported. ``He is in a good
frame of mind. And we are anxious to get going as soon as he is up
and ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in trouble is John Goodman's new sitcom, previously titled
``Don't Ask,'' in which he plays a gay father. The pilot was
scrapped and will be reshot, with very few original cast members
surviving the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Production company) Carsey-Werner and (executive producers)
Bonnie and Terry Turner had some serious concerns about the
long-term viability of the premise that was presented in the
pilot,'' Berman said. ``They decided they wanted to go back in and
take a hard look at the premise _ and came back with what we
thought was a terrific reworking of the idea. It's a much more
family-oriented show than the original pilot was.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox announced the premiere dates for its fall season, a
particularly tricky schedule this year, given that the networks
don't want to compete with NBC's Summer Olympics in September. Fox
has the baseball playoffs and World Series in October, and
presidential debates and election coverage will also figure in
there somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Angel,'' James Cameron's post-apocalyptic drama, debuts
Oct. 3. Thrillers ``Freakylinks'' and ``Night Visions'' will be
unveiled Oct. 6. ``Boston Common,'' a classroom drama from David E.
Kelley, premieres Oct. 23. The Goodman sitcom and ``The $treet,'' a
Wall Street-based soap from Darren Star, premieres Nov. 1. ``Lone
Gunman'' won't be seen until midseason. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1914EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
