<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT-CISCO SUIT HEATS UP WITH EX-WORKER ALLEGATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A heated rivalry between two communications equipment
giants, Lucent Technologies Inc. and Cisco Systems Inc., got a few
degrees hotter.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement filed in US District Court, 10 former Lucent
employees who left earlier this year to work for Cisco alleged
``abusive and oppressive management tactics'' at Lucent's
manufacturing plant in North Andover. The statement also alleges
``discriminatory treatment of female employees'' but did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The statement was filed as part of a lawsuit Lucent brought in
June against the former employees. Lucent contends the former
workers violated its employment agreement by going to work for
Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   Although the statement was filed by the workers, Lucent
considered it an attack from Cisco, which is picking up the legal
tabs for the employees' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing that Cisco would respond to Lucent's
reasonable efforts to protect its proprietary secrets by making
false allegations about Lucent's integrity,'' said Lucent
spokeswoman Mary Lou Ambrus.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Lucent's lawsuit against its former employees, Ambrus
said, ``We've simply taken steps to ensure that certain former
Lucent employees who now work for Cisco not be permitted to
disclose Lucent's trade secrets to their new employer.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's lawsuit also seeks to prevent the employees from
working on optical networking technology for a nine-month period.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the employees argued that they had never signed any such
agreement with Lucent. Further, they started seeking jobs when
Lucent managers in January said up to half the workers at the North
Andover plant could be laid off as part of a ``reconfiguration,''
according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the dispute is a fierce battle between Cisco and
Lucent for ascendancy in the burgeoning market for sophisticated
fiberoptic technology used to ferry vasts amounts of information at
high speeds. That market is expected to explode from $6 billion a
year in 1999 to $23 billion in 2003, according to estimates by RHK,
a market research firm in South San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent makes fiber optic equipment at its North Andover site,
while Cisco plans to significantly ramp up its offerings by
building an optical networking plant in Salem, N.H. Cisco's plant,
where the 10 former Lucent employees will work, is expected to be
ready by the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, meanwhile, has been unable to keep up with a voracious
demand for optical networking equipment, a fact analysts believe is
contributing to the Murray Hill, N.J., company's faltering
finances. On Thursday, Lucent reported a third-quarter loss and
downplayed its profit outlook for the remainder of the year,
triggering a 15.5 percent drop in the company's stock. Lucent's
stock fell another 5.4 percent Friday, slipping $3.0625 to $51.125
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a situation (Lucent) can turn around overnight,''
said Steve Levy, analyst with Lehman Bros.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's stock began its tumble in January, when the company
reported a 23 percent drop in first-quarter profits. That marked
the first time the company fell short of Wall Street expectations
since it was spun off from AT&AMP;T Corp. in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent has more than 9,000 employees in Massachusetts, most of
whom work in North Andover. Last year, Lucent spent $24 billion
buying Massachusetts-based telecommunications start-ups, including
Nexabit Communications in Marlborough.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco, based in San Jose, Calif., also has a substantial
presence in Massachusetts, with about 2,200 employees in the state.
Cisco has spent $10 billion buying 11 companies in New England in
the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe reporter Peter J. Howe contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9048 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-SPEARS-BRITNEY-LADN &LR;      07-21 1418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEARS-BRITNEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OOPS, SHE'S DONE IT AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teen-pop princess Britney Spears and her pals in the ultra-hot
bubblegum genre drive the record industry.
</P>
<P>
   To hear Spears tell it, however, the 18-year-old small-town girl
and ex-Mouseketeer hasn't realized just how much power she actually
wields.
</P>
<P>
   Just after returning home from taping her Fox-TV special in
Hawaii recently, Spears was thrilled ``they let me bring my friends
out'' on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Got that? They let me bring my friends on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   What Spears doesn't seem to understand is she has the sort of
clout Garth Brooks had a few years ago when he demanded a change in
his label's executive suite _ and got it.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't have to ask nicely if it's OK if some pals come
along to Hawaii. She can demand a private plane and top-flight
service for her friends.
</P>
<P>
   Britney Spears isn't merely a here today, gone tomorrow kid-pop
phenom. In the past two years, the bubbly diva has sold more than
20 million albums to become the reigning queen of all
bellybutton-baring female singers.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did she just celebrate the milestone of 10 million
worldwide sales of her debut album, ``... Baby One More Time,'' but
she's the youngest female in pop history to have a simultaneous No.
1 single and album on the charts _ in the album's first week in
stores.
</P>
<P>
   And that was before the release of her follow-up album, ``Oops!
... I Did It Again,'' which has sold more than 4 million copies in
six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Spears' popularity shows no signs of waning. All remaining seats
for her concerts at the Forum on July 30 and 31 (plus Saturday at
the Verizon Wireless Amphitheatre in Irvine and Aug. 5 at the Glen
Helen Blockbuster Pavilion in Devore) are expected to be gone by
the time you read this. Not that there were many left unsold to
begin with.
</P>
<P>
   And with a memoir (``Britney Spears' Heart to Heart'') selling
like hotcakes and a new single burning up the charts, Spears' star
power is shining brighter than ever.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent phone interview, we asked if the real Britney has
been lost amid all the fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure there are some misconceptions,'' she says. ``A lot of
people think it happened overnight (for me), and that bothers me
because I worked really hard to get where I am. But people see that
I'm a real person like everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Spears says her current tour, which was choreographed by the guy
who did the Ricky Martin extravaganza, includes pyrotechnics, set
changes and plenty of flashy costumes. In fact, the technical
aspects and size of the show forced her to change venues in Los
Angeles and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are sweet parts and strong, hard parts that are edgy,''
she says. ``There's lots more pyro and gadgets. It's just a fun
show.''
</P>
<P>
   Spears has joined the short list of one-named stars _ Madonna,
Sting, Whitney, Shania, err, Eminem.
</P>
<P>
   Oops! Did we really mention Eminem, the gleefully crude
chart-topping rapper who skewers our Britney in unprintable terms
(along with Christina Aguilera and 'N Sync) on his hit single and
video, ``The Real Slim Shady''?
</P>
<P>
   Spears takes the high road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take it as a dis at all,'' she responded. ``I think
it's cool. It's flattering when someone's gonna write about you in
their song. I think Eminem is brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   She also dismisses any rumored rivalry with Aguilera.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a friendly competition,'' she admits. ``A lot of
people compare us because we're kind of the same age, but I think
our music and personalities are very different.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in rural Kentwood, La., Spears was singing and
dancing to the Mariah Carey and Whitney Houston hits she heard on
the radio.
</P>
<P>
   After spending much of her early childhood performing in talent
shows, church choirs and gymnastics competitions, she studied at
New York's Professional Performing Arts School, acted in TV
commercials and the off-Broadway play ``Ruthless'' (inspired by the
movie ``The Bad Seed''), and competed on TV's ``Star Search.''
</P>
<P>
   At 11, Spears began a two-season stint on TV's ``New Mickey
Mouse Club,'' alongside future ``Felicity'' star Keri Russell, 'N
Sync members-to-be Justin Timberlake and J.C. Chasez, and current
teen-diva Aguilera. Spears and Timberlake are now rumored to be a
couple, though they've denied they are secretly married.
</P>
<P>
   When ``The New Mickey Mouse Club'' was canceled in 1994, Spears
started planning a recording career. Jive Records signed her at age
15, mostly on the strength of an informal demo tape of her singing
karaoke-style over a prerecorded instrumental track.
</P>
<P>
   Extensive marketing to set up the release of the single ``...
Baby One More Time'' a few months before Spears' debut album came
out in January 1999 made sure the teen queen was already a pop
star.
</P>
<P>
   But will a couple of multimillion-selling albums and
chart-topping singles lead to a long-term career?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Britney has a lengthier career ahead of her, like 'N
Sync does,'' says Anita Bond, general manager at Tower in Sherman
Oaks. ``She appeals to young adults as well as teens and the very
young, and her music has a bit more content than the usual
teenybopper stuff. I think she might stick around a little longer
than others in the genre because she probably has a few more good
albums to come. Will she be Celine Dion? I don't think so. But
she'll be around.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Spears albums have been produced by the unabashedly
commercial hit-making machine of Max Martin and his team at
Sweden's Cheiron studios. Martin and crew are also the brains
behind 'N Sync and the Backstreet Boys and are brilliant at
creating deceptively simple pop melodies that sound great on radio.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Spears' current tour is doing a blockbuster business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a preteen, there's a lot of excitement,'' says Gary
Bongiovanni, editor of the concert industry weekly Pollstar. ``The
tour is doing very well _ the grosses are huge and attendance is
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Bongiovanni says Spears' numbers for the first six months of the
year place her ``Oops! ... I Did It Again'' tour in the No. 12 spot
with grosses of $14.7 million based on 29 shows in 28 cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will she be around for a long while?'' he adds. ``That's the
$64,000 question on just about every teen act.''
</P>
<P>
   Radio, too, has joined the Spears bandwagon. For example, Radio
Disney, which broadcasts to preteens in 46 cities, recently saw its
number of calls rise to 90,000 daily with kids trying to register
for a Spears contest that offers a front-row concert seat and a
chance to meet the teen queen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really think Britney's come into her own with this new
album,'' says Robin Jones, Radio Disney's senior director of
operations. ``We don't know if she's a Barbra Streisand, but we
don't think she's anywhere near ready to go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her music success, Spears wants to branch out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to do a movie next year,'' Spears says. ``But
nothing's set in stone.''
</P>
<P>
   She admits both her image and sound have grown up a bit. She's
cranked up the vixen appeal slightly, trading her polite skirts for
tight leather pants, and altered her message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did change things up,'' she says. ``The first album was
talking about heartbreak and how lonely I was, and the message in
the new one is, 'You're stronger' and 'What you see is what you
get.' It's a similar sound, but that is my sound. I'm marking my
territory, and this is the kind of music I sing. I definitely think
this album (represents) major growth from the first one.''
</P>
<P>
   Spears is ready for a backlash.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are gonna have opinions, and I can't worry about what
everybody thinks,'' she says. ``I can just try and be me. I think
you're the sexiest when you're being yourself. And if they think
that's sexy, that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Spears says she doesn't view herself as a role model, she
has been called the ``voice of a generation,'' the same tag given
to Nirvana's late frontman Kurt Cobain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about it as a weight on my shoulders, to be
honest with you,'' Spears says. ``It's flattering they say that.''
</P>
<P>
   ---Who: Britney Spears with ATeens. &QL; 
Where: Forum, 3900 W. Manchester Ave., Inglewood. &QL; 
When: 7:30 p.m. July 30 and 31 (plus Saturday at the Verizon
Wireless Amphitheatre in Irvine and Aug. 5 at the Glen Helen
Blockbuster Pavilion in Devore). &QL; 
Tickets: $30 and $49. &QL; 
Information: (213) 480-3232. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
