u t BC-ORIENTALISM-EXHIBIT-H     07-21 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORIENTALISM-EXHIBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASCINATING EXHIBIT TAKES A LOOK AT ORIENTALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIMOTHY CAHILL  
 c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. _ The key to the exhibit ``Noble Dreams,
Wicked Pleasures'' here at the Sterling and Francine Clark Art
Institute is the small John Sloan painting ``Movies.''
</P>
<P>
   On a dark Manhattan sidewalk, the bright light of a cinema
marquee advertises ``A Romance of the Harem,'' and a crowd of men,
women and children gathers in the glow. Exotic and erotic, the
artificial light of the Orient has been attracting Americans this
way for more than a century.
</P>
<P>
   The Clark's big summer show is an ambitious history of
Orientalism in America, from 1870, when it gained popular currency,
to just before World War II. Orientalism, the notion of an
``Orient'' replete with sultans and dancing girls, camel drivers
and bazaars, is a concoction of myth and cliche that has served a
range of nationalist, capitalist and chauvinist purposes through
the years. The term describes something in ourselves that remains
largely unexamined to this day.
</P>
<P>
   This exhibit is a masterful bit of art history _ no museum has
ever attempted what the Clark, led by Williams College Islamic art
scholar Holly Edwards, has accomplished here _ but it's more. The
exhibit is a mirror of attitudes and assumptions we've inherited
from the past.
</P>
<P>
   The work on view is splendid, from paintings by 19th-century
stars like Frederic Church, Jean-Leon Gerome and John Singer
Sargent to 20th-century goodies by Maxfield Parrish, Irving Berlin
and Douglas Fairbanks.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit calls on the viewer to do what Sloan did in his
painting, see through the surface reality to what it represents.
The Clark has mapped a legacy of prejudice and willful foolishness
with its show, and found as well a strain of longing for some
missing ingredient in American culture.
</P>
<P>
   American attitudes toward the Orient were forged in France,
which in the mid-19th century was this country's paragon of
culture. Beaux-arts painters like Gerome, with their extreme
technical skills and vivid imaginations, invented the ``Orient,'' a
place extending roughly from Moorish Spain to Palestine to Turkey,
Iran and Iraq. It was, to be sure, predominantly a region of the
mind, populated by turbaned kings, bare-chested henchmen and veiled
women, and erotically charged. Gerome's 1870 ``The Snake Charmer,''
which depicts a naked slave boy presenting a coiled python to his
master, makes the none-too-subtle point that the Orient was a land
of depravity and sexual adventure.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, one of the exhibit's handful of masterpieces, also
features drop-dead technique. Gerome's draftmanship was impeccable,
his illusionism superb and his mastery of paint consummate _ the
blue-tile walls, the stone floor, the carpet, the snake's basket,
all are utterly lifelike, as is the creamy smoothness of the boy's
skin. Gerome fused the exoticism of the Orient to an academic
Classicism that in the European mind was all-virtuous.
</P>
<P>
   France, busy colonizing Arab North Africa and the Middle East,
took comfort in its cultural superiority and lurid images of
peoples so unlike itself.
</P>
<P>
   America, meanwhile, was rising from the ashes of the Civil War
to a burgeoning era of growth and power. It craved international
respectability, and appropriating French attitudes was an easy
shortcut to class.
</P>
<P>
   But French Orientalism was too heady for the Protestant
sensibilities of the American Renaissance. Pleasures of the flesh
were taboo; the Orient became instead a land of religious heritage,
the cradle of American Christianity. Church painted it like this in
his grand ``Jerusalem from the Mount of Olives,'' a depiction of
the Holy Land as Arcadia not all that different in feel from his
views of the Hudson River and South America.
</P>
<P>
   If Church and Gerome represent the two poles of 19th-century
Orientalism, most of the artistic thinking in this country took
place in the middle. Painters like Sargent and Frederick Arthur
Bridgman depicted the Orient as a land of indolent splendor, a
getaway, vicarious or actual, for empire-builders worn out by
relentless capitalism and global profiteering. Here was a place
filled with magnificent stuff _ carpets, ceramics, weapons,
textiles, architecture _ and all of it just waiting to be possessed
by us of the civilized nations, who could truly appreciate its
worth.
</P>
<P>
   And chief among the Orient's fine possessions was its women,
made mysterious by their clothes and manners, and all the more
alluring for that mystery. Their languor and intrigue fired the
American male's imagination without assaulting his public
rectitude.
</P>
<P>
   Images like Bridgman's ``Siesta,'' painted in 1878 and depicting
an Arab girl napping amid fine furnishings and an opium pipe,
defined how we were to conceive of the region for much of the next
century. A place created for American delectation, where our
appetites, be they for art or romance or crude oil, could easily
and cheaply be met.
</P>
<P>
   Although the show's scope extends only to 1930, it's hard to
walk through the galleries and not reflect on the forms Orientalism
takes even today. From Disney's ``Aladdin'' to ``The English
Patient'' to the recent ``Three Kings,'' Hollywood continues to
exploit familiar motifs that have their roots in the last century.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Three Kings,'' in which Gulf War soldiers
plunder Saddam Hussein's gold, these cliches consciously undermine
themselves. But isn't that also what's happening in reality, in
this region full of rogue zealots ready to declare war on the U.S.?
It becomes a little easier to comprehend Iranian and Libyan
extremism when viewed in the context of the Western exploitation on
display at the Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Survey this shameful history on the museum's walls and something
poignant also presents itself in our ancestors' behavior. Church
and other artists, including William Merritt Chase, appropriated
Middle Eastern objects and designs into their own lives (the show
includes a number of objects and photographs borrowed from Olana,
Church's Orientalist manse just outside Hudson). Seen from the
vantage point of today, what they did has an almost desperate edge
to it, as if they were grasping for authenticity their own lives
lacked.
</P>
<P>
   America may have been the juggernaut of the world, but its
material culture paled in comparison to places like Baghdad and
Istanbul. These artists must, at least in part, have intimated in
this rich culture an underlying richness of spirit, one that was
genuine and could not be manufactured for the open market.
</P>
<P>
   Not that American ingenuity didn't try. The exhibit's energy is
divided roughly in half, the first part tracing the history of
Orientalism up to the 1890s, and the second recording how that
early history was transmuted by modern culture. If the early
chapters feature oil painters inventing a domestic image of the
Orient, the later ones give us ad men, fashion designers and movie
stars making the image into product.
</P>
<P>
   The show picks up momentum here, probably because it feels so
familiar. By the 1890s, retailers from Sears, Roebuck to Tiffany &AMP;
Co. were selling decorative vases, tea sets and other furnishings
based on Middle Eastern designs. The exhibit includes some of the
more ornate examples of the trend _ a Moorish desk by Tiffany, for
example, or a pair of enameled and gilt bottles by Crown Derby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
