<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9054 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-REVIEW-LOSER-HNS     07-21 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-LOSER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOSER' AIN'T WORTH IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Appropriating another defeatist term of endearment from the
mouths of America's young, ``Clueless'' writer-director Amy
Heckerling returns with ``Loser.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a non-event, though. The knowing bite is gone. She seems
merely bitter now, casting about for unmitigated warmth and hating
herself for it, and punishing us in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Fashioned as a teen comedy with wrinkles and a depressive
streak, ``Loser'' is an arthritic failure, genuine only when the
two outcast lovers' eyes dart toward each other, then retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Heckerling just pollutes the marketplace with a new
``in'' address in an overpopulated teenage wasteland. You don't
simply wish for Dora (Mena Suvari) to realize that she wants Paul
(Jason Biggs), you want him to scoop her under his arm and carry
her into a better Amy Heckerling movie. (Will she ever revisit the
acute raunch of ``Ridgemont High''?)
</P>
<P>
   With its limp ``complaint rock'' soundtrack, ``Loser'' feels
dated and distressingly conventional as it flickers before you.
</P>
<P>
   Paul jets from cheery Midwest locale to cruel New York City.
Back home the whole family babysat the mailbox, waiting for his
college-acceptance letter. Once there, Paul is more or less jailed
with three glam-pothead roommates so full of prankster hate that
the film loses instant credibility for not making them Jerky Boys
fans. Instead, they sit around playing the heretofore unseen
``Rhoda'' drinking game, razzing financial-aid Paul for his
boorishness.
</P>
<P>
   Paul's problem is not that he's hopelessly nice, it's that his
pop reservoir doesn't run deep enough to know that when the guys
you're living with dress as if Urban Outfitters had its way with
the Delia's catalog, you've been handed your hint to leave.
Eventually, he does move out of the dorm and into the
basement-level digs of a veterinary clinic, where the film embarks
on a PSA for PETA.
</P>
<P>
   Biggs is saddled with the somewhat unfortunate task of being the
Anthony Michael Hall in this '80s Brat Pack renaissance - the
nerdy, gangly victim, forever doomed to perform a variation on the
Web-cam dance from ``American Pie.''
</P>
<P>
   Heckerling is making a genre flick so Biggs has to play by the
rules, even suffering through the requisite makeover that turns him
from a dork in a hunter's cap into a dork wearing the clothes of a
British pop fan circa 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The change in attire comes at the behest of Suvari's Dora, a
Goth chick with a silver lining. They meet in English Lit class.
She's introduced sucking on packet of honey, and it's a tease for a
zanier movie (a barely post-pubescent ``Something Wild,'' perhaps)
that never arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven knows, ``Loser'' glides over its own dark themes _ Dora's
emotionally abusive affair with her lit prof (Greg Kinnear, as
svelte and smug as he gets), who pronounces Betty Friedan dead;
Paul's roomies' attempts to drug girls for sex. Heckerling seems to
despise the world she's built around these two but plumbs for
cuteness anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Putting Paul in that hunter's cap and Suvari in the role of
work-study misfit, it seemed like Heckerling was introducing Holden
Caulfield to a Jane Austen heroine. Even better, Dora's the cynic
and Paul's the eternally put-upon naif like Catherine in
``Northanger Abbey.''
</P>
<P>
   But Heckerling's wily, agile adaptation days seem behind her.
``Clueless'' used a love-struck Austen satire to make a soapy
satire of all things 90210. It was a Binaca blast of teen steam
that bopped like a mash note hooked up to an amplifier. ``Loser,''
by comparison, trudges around like it's taking its cues from
whatever Freddie Prinze Jr. was in last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1922EDT &QL; 
