<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9058 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISONCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-21 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    BUSH SHOWS FATHERHOOD `COMPASSION'
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ You could tell the meeting had something to do with
a presidential race. There was a Secret Service agent posted for
about every 20 square feet of floor space, and invited guests were
frisked at the door.
</P>
<P>
   The seating in the small conference room was rearranged when a
tall man in the middle of the front row blocked a camera shot. And
George W. Bush was there, preaching the virtues of fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Fatherhood?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, fatherhood. Not missile defense systems, foreign relations,
taxes or even education.
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't discussing the virtues _ or advantages _ of having
a former president as father and a politically potent family name
to help open doors.
</P>
<P>
   He was promoting the everyday, family unit-type fatherhood of
mentor and role model. The kind of father who plays checkers (or
Nintendo) with his kids, wipes their noses, helps them with their
homework, comes home at night and is otherwise there for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most important job any of us will ever have if we're
blessed to be a dad,'' Bush said during an appearance last week at
Faith Works, a faith-based social services agency in Milwaukee's
inner city.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, fatherhood is a more important job than being
president. But since Bush is running for president, not father of
the year, why is he trying to sound like a social worker or a
minister?
</P>
<P>
   Bush would argue that he is being a ``compassionate
conservative,'' focusing attention on major social problems that
government alone cannot effectively tackle. He seems to be trying
to walk a middle ground between those who believe government hasn't
done enough and those who believe government has tried to do too
much and made things worse.
</P>
<P>
   Part of his strategy is to increase the role of church-related
or faith-based organizations in the effort to make America a better
place. According to this approach, it is compassionate to be
charitable and conservative to save tax dollars and government red
tape.
</P>
<P>
   Faith Works is a long-term, nondenominational, residential
program aimed at getting fathers who are addicted to alcohol or
other drugs back with their families and back on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sat around a table with the agency's director, a counselor,
a minister, a father who had participated in the program and the
head of a charitable foundation that contributes money to it. The
small audience included several other ministers and several men
(accompanied by their children) who were in the program.
</P>
<P>
   The event was obviously staged. Bush wasn't asked any questions,
and he got to deliver his ``compassionate conservative'' spiel. But
it was, nevertheless, informative.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Fatherhood Initiative, whose director,
Wade F. Horn, also joined in the discussion, almost 40 percent of
American children (about 25 million) don't live with their dads.
And their fathers' absence has produced some sobering statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 75 percent of children in single-family homes will
experience poverty before they are 11. And most violent criminals
are males who grew up without fathers, including as many as 60
percent of men who committed rape, 75 percent of teens charged with
murder and 70 percent of long-term prison inmates.
</P>
<P>
   One presidential candidate is not going to solve those problems
with a pitch for responsible fatherhood or any other positive
quality. Neither is all the compassionate conservatism _ or
compassionate liberalism, for that matter _ in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush is correct to focus attention on some of the causes of
society's problems and to support the work that churches and other
faith-based organizations play in trying to improve lives and
prevent some of those problems, provided the line separating church
and state isn't crossed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also recognizes that government has a role. In Milwaukee,
for example, he proposed that the federal government provide $185
million over five years for grants to community- and faith-based
organizations that provide job training and other services to
low-income fathers and their families.
</P>
<P>
   That amount would seem to be only a drop in the bucket compared
to the need. But Bush is conservative, as well as compassionate.
</P>
<P>
   No amount of faith-based efforts will relieve the government of
its responsibility to fund crucial services for which all taxpayers
should share the tab, including services made necessary by absent
fathers. That part of the debate, as always, will revolve around
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Robison is chief of the Chronicle's Austin Bureau.
(clay.robisonchron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
