<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9059 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-METALLICA-MUSIC-REVIE     07-21 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METALLICA-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TATTOO THE EARTH TOUR: OUTSIDERS VENTING THEIR INNER DARKNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANN POWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Tattoo the Earth Tour, which arrived at Giants
Stadium on Thursday, was organized to illustrate a longstanding
concept in rock: the steadfast commitment of serious devotees to
life beyond the norm. Heavy rock is an outsider's pleasure, and
tattoos are permanent emblems of the soul's insurrection. Seriously
tattooed people, with ink on the neck or down both arms, can
alienate employers, family and people in line at the supermarket.
They incorporate confrontationalism into their very membranes.
</P>
<P>
   Tattoo the Earth is intended to honor this ultimate commitment
to strangeness alongside the music that, to many ears, shares its
stance. Elsewhere on the national tour's 18 stops, this idea is
being realized by having famous tattoo artists practice their art
on willing customers. But New Jersey officials decided to ban the
tattoo artists, fearing they would not be properly regulated. So
the bands had to promulgate outsiderness on their own.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't a stretch, since estrangement is the wellspring for
heavy rock. Its intense amplification, frantic speed and brutal
repetition is purgative. It strips away politeness to reveal darker
emotions: fear, craving, rage. Heavy rockers locate these feelings
within disquieting scenarios: Countless songs played Thursday were
about death, war, crime or self-directed violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``My spirit's so cold,'' sang Rey Oropeza of Downset, a socially
conscious hardcore band that played the show's first half, which
unfolded on a temporary stage outside the stadium. Whether
expressing defiance of social authorities or focusing on inner
turmoil, heavy rock draws listeners into that chilliness, that
refusal of comfort and serenity, as a way of freeing the mind. Each
band at Tattoo the Earth worked a variation on this approach. The
artists that played the daytime outer stage, aside from the
virtuous Downset, switched off between the blend of hip-hop and
hardcore guitar bashing that has worked for Limp Bizkit and the
more glam-inflected variation on that theme practiced by Korn.
</P>
<P>
   The hardcore screamers in Hatebreed got the biggest response
from the crowd. But the melodiously gloomy Full Devil Jacket may
have shown the biggest commercial potential. On the mainstage,
heavy rock's nuanced alienation played out in more masterly hands.
Metallica's claim on the headlining spot turned the night into
friendly combat. The band that has defined monster metal since the
1980s is dealing with a serious image problem because of its battle
with Napster, the online service that allows fans to connect and
download music free. Lars Ulrich, Metallica's drummer, has
alienated many Internet-loving fans with his vehement protest
against what he (and many artists) considers Napster's abetment of
piracy.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this trauma a back injury that forced the singer James
Hetfield to sit out several dates of the group's Summer Sanitarium
tour, and the death of a fan who fell from a balcony at a July 5
concert in Baltimore, and Metallica had to be feeling some
pressure. The evening also put the band up against Slipknot, heavy
rock's newest pretender to the throne, as well as old rivals Slayer
and Sepultura and rising contenders Sevendust. Each artist raised
the event's stakes a little higher. The Brazilian band Sepultura
played old-fashioned thrash with unusually complex rhythms,
courtesy of the fine drummer, Igor Cavelera. Next came Sevendust,
an Atlanta-based outfit featuring the singer Lajon Witherspoon, who
slipped a little James Brown into his gruff and sweet delivery.
</P>
<P>
   These bands suggested how black music is turning metal on its
ear, and unlike many currently popular bands, their members were as
multicultural as their styles. These good bands still had nothing
on the mighty Slayers' purist thrash. These California-based
veterans are idolized by heavy rock specialists, having wielded
rapid-fire riffs and hellish visions for decades. ``How many people
can I kill?'' howled Tom Araya, the band's singer of legendary
manliness, in ``Holy War,'' and the band answered his question
symbolically with an unrelentingly focused set. This was a pure and
totally effective sonic attack.
</P>
<P>
   Slipknot took the exact opposite approach, with a similar
effect. The Iowa-based band is the flavor of choice among teen-age
rockers. Its highly theatrical set demonstrated why. In jump suits
and hideous masks, banging on garbage-can style drums or
manhandling their guitars, Slipknot's members were not just
unfocused. They were anti-focused, making music closer to a
Nintendo game than conventional rock. As his eight bandmates,
including a D.J., pounded away, the vocalist Corey Taylor rapped,
crooned, grunted and growled. The jumble was hard to trace, but it
obviously engaged the fans, who followed it like a round on their
Game Boys. Slipknot disregarded virtuosity, lyricism and narrative
suspense. It simply hit from all sides; the fun came in trying to
absorb the assault.
</P>
<P>
   If such disorganized multiplicity is the new paradigm, Metallica
may really be in trouble, because its artfulness is based on total
control. It shapes heavy rock's dry-ice soundscape into grand,
well-ordered tableaus. When the quartet appeared onstage to the
strains of a Western movie soundtrack, its cool was as palpable as
Clint Eastwood's. And in a two-hour set, Metallica won the
shootout. The triumph had its cost. Metallica focused on older
material, apparently heeding the fans who protested its recent
experiments with softer-edged music. Unadulterated versions of
crowd favorites like ``Fade to Black'' and ``One'' made this an
official proclamation of dominance. Kirk Hammett, the band's High
Romantic guitarist, flashed his filigree, but Metallica wanted to
present itself as a virile powerhouse, and it did, without
flinching.
</P>
<P>
   On the other leg of its tour, Metallica has been jamming with
the members of Kid Rock's band. Those loose sessions probably
aren't as satisfying as the band's herculean triumph at Tattoo the
Earth. But they might show more about Metallica's future, if it
dares mess with its invincible formula again and offer a new design
for beautiful alienation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
