<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-OIL-SPILL-ART-     07-21 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-OIL-SPILL-ART-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH VILLAGE STILL RECOVERING FROM OIL SPILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA TURBALLE, France _ Under the white tent, set high up on the
beach, six little boys held out their limbs with horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get it off! Please, quick,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it cause cancer?'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never going swimming in there again,'' said a third.
</P>
<P>
   Lucille Nicol, wearing a bright green T-shirt and equipped with
paper towels and a bottle of olive oil, did her best to calm them.
``Look, it comes right off,'' she said, rubbing, oiling and rubbing
some more to take off the black stains that dotted their arms and
legs.
</P>
<P>
   Amputation, she assured them, was not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The boys did not crack a smile.
</P>
<P>
   The teams of ``green T-shirts'' at La Turballe are new this
year, one of the measures that the town has taken to help tourists
feel better about going on the beaches. The teams have sand pails,
soccer balls and rackets to distribute. They organize games for the
children. But tucked in with the other gear are the olive oil and
paper towels used to take No. 2 crude oil off when it washes up on
the sand or when swimmers run into the strands of seaweed that it
often clings to.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, over 200 miles of the Brittany coast was drenched
with thick crude oil when the tanker Erika, registered in Malta,
broke up in stormy seas 65 miles off the coast.
</P>
<P>
   A huge effort was made to clean the beaches in time for the
tourist season. But in some of the villages like La Turballe the
tarlike fuel keeps washing up. Only last week a new slick oozed
over the shoreline that stretches north from the harbor, leaving
the rocks glistening with black streaks and the sand contaminated
with gooey globs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the town's people say it almost doesn't matter, because
there are no tourists anyway. There is plenty of room to lay down a
towel at the other beaches in La Turballe. The sun shines and the
sea glistens, but only those who have houses here or prepaid
vacations have returned this year. Some of the merchants say their
business is off by as much as 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse and Florence Gisalson say they believe they will go
bankrupt in the fall. The restaurants right on the port in La
Turballe say they are doing all right, and the fast-food
restaurants that have catered to the soldiers sent in to clean up
the beaches are having a better season than usual. But the
Gisalsons' restaurant, in an old stone house tucked behind the
port, hardly sees anyone these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually these streets are like a rock concert _ they are so
crowded,'' Gisalson said. ``Look at them now; it's noon and there
is no one here.''
</P>
<P>
   The little towns along the coast have for months been caught in
a sort of moral quandary: to speak or not to speak about their
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Some have railed at the government for not moving fast enough,
for not offering the merchants tax breaks and other aid. Promises
have been made, they say, but the cash is not in hand. Others do
not want to have their towns associated with the pollution and have
chosen to keep a lower profile.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of La Turballe, Rene Leroux, has been among the most
outspoken, willingly showing journalists the damage that the Erika
has done. ``If we lied to our friends the tourists, then they would
never come back,'' he said. ``This way at least we can hold onto
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Leroux put out a pamphlet this year, marking out beaches that
would be cleaned immediately and monitored daily. He hired 50 extra
employees to act as a quick-response team under the town's own
control, and he set up the teams of green T-shirts. But halfway
through the season, he has the air of a beaten man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so tired here,'' he said. ``The season came in and we
hardly noticed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since the breakup of the Erika, French officials have said they
want to strengthen international shipping regulations to make sure
that such an accident does not occur again. The Erika was an old
boat showing signs of rust and poor maintenance when it split
during a storm on Dec. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the spill, estimated at 10,000 to 12,000 tons, came from
the forward half of the boat. The stern half, which sank about five
miles from the front half and is almost 400 feet under the surface,
contains another 12,000 to 15,000 more tons of oil.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of experts have begun trying to pump out the rest of the
oil in the holds, but the project is several months behind
schedule. Touring the area this month, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
promised that those who were financially hit by the spill would be
compensated.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone in La Turballe believes him. Jean-Luc Fardoit,
the president of the local chamber of commerce, says many of the
merchants are ``barely sleeping these days.'' Fardoit, who owns two
shops that sell souvenirs and beach toys, cut his staff from 11 to
9 and then reduced everyone's hours by 25 percent. Still, he says,
he has plenty of time to go for coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are Bretons and we will not let go,'' Fardoit said. ``But
we are waiting to see how much help we get. It would have been nice
to get a few more specifics.''
</P>
<P>
   The oil spill has not affected all the seaside towns in the same
way. Some resorts, like La Baule, just a 20-minute drive from La
Turballe, have hardly been affected. La Baule's beaches face south
rather than west, and that has made all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   But along the rockier shore lines, the picture is bleak.
</P>
<P>
   In La Turballe this week, the closed beach was something of a
tourist attraction. Visitors drove up to see what the pollution
looked like and watched soldiers in white plastic suits, red gloves
and green boots scraping the oil from the rocks with trowels. Some
of the workers complained that their suits were hot and the trowels
were hardly efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Rene Guerin, who drives his camper here every summer from
Rennes, said he did it again this year out of loyalty. ``This is
where we come, and it wasn't a good time to abandon this town,'' he
said. ``It will be all right in a couple of years. Nature will take
over again. But it is hard to wait.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
