<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9064 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-DAVIDIANS22     07-21 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DAVIDIANS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORIAL _ Partners in disaster
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Special Counsel John Danforth believes he has answered ``four
dark questions.'' That leaves dozens that forever may beg for
light.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, even with a staggering $10 million price tag, the
Danforth probe into the 1993 events at Mount Carmel was way too
limited to put to rest so many concerns and suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth's report bolsters much of what a federal jury ruled
last week _ that the principal causes of death and destruction were
David Koresh and his well-armed, recalcitrant followers.
</P>
<P>
   They had a right and an opportunity to test the government's
charges before a jury when a warrant came to their door Feb. 28.
They chose trial by fire. They have not been exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has demonstrated that federal agents caused the inferno
that killed so many people April 19, while much evidence shows the
Davidians set one fire or several. Incendiary grenades among the
evidence made Page 1 across the country. Did they cause the fire?
No, says Danforth. They were used hours before the fire and not
where they could have caused it.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, nothing has demonstrated that FBI agents fired guns
into the compound during the April 19 tear gas siege. Danforth's
inquiry rebuts that unequivocally. U.S. District Judge Walter Smith
has yet to rule on this evidence. It appears more and more clear
that any bullets fired April 19, 1993, were vessels of suicide and
fratricide.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is a disservice to take the Danforth report and the
jury's advisory as exonerating the government. Danford shades it as
``bad acts'' vs. ``bad judgments.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that if it takes 153 pages to exonerate the
government of bad or illegal acts, it surely might have taken a
James Michener-style epic to explain all the government missteps,
not just at the federal level but at the local level.
</P>
<P>
   To the eye of the nation and world, those sorry judgments
started with a bone-headed decision by the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms to go ahead with a raid the ATF knew was
compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Those bad judgments included the FBI's forcing the issue with
tear gas and armored vehicles after a 51-day wait, as if 51 more
days, and 51 more, wouldn't have been worth every minute to end a
hostage stand-off without loss of life.
</P>
<P>
   Bad judgment: not preparing adequately for the possibility that
the compound might burn. Bad judgment: armored vehicles disturbing
the crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department helped no one, certainly not itself, with
a critique of these decisions that was pure whitewash.
</P>
<P>
   The local angle
</P>
<P>
   Before this became a national story, however, bad judgments were
manifold. At the tragedy's root were local officials who took less
than seriously the claims _ later confirmed by DNA _ of sexual
abuse, little girls who would bear children for Koresh.
</P>
<P>
   He could have been arrested on these suspicions away from his
commune when he was gallivanting around Waco. The other suspicions
about the Branch Davidians _ illegal weapons, scam marriages,
welfare fraud _ could have been dealt with separately in solemn
court. Without Koresh to pump up the volume back home, this all
might have been settled peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Koresh and his cohorts had been to court once before
over a gun incident in the 1980s, and had been treated fairly.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't give the system a chance to work this time.
Tragically, the system stumbled all over itself in trying to do its
work in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Bad acts, bad judgments _ and dark questions still unanswered
seven years and millions of dollars later.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial appeared in the Waco Tribune-Herald
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
