<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9068 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      07-21 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Saturday, July 22. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   WACO-REPORT (St. Louis, Mo.) _ John Danforth, the special
counsel investigating the 1993 tear gas assault by federal agents
on the Branch Davidian compound, issues a sweeping report that
clears Attorney General Janet Reno and the government of any
wrongdoing in the controversial episode. By Jim Yardley. (We plan
to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ The Israeli peace delegation's
mood shifts from dire to hopeful as officials outside the secluded
Camp David reveal that Prime Minister Ehud Barak believes the
chances for the peace summit's success have improved. By Deborah
Sontag. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,300
words.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead: 4-column photo reefer to NY-OFFICER-FUNERAL.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO-IV (Houston) _ George W. Bush left Yale University in
the spring of 1968 with a diploma in hand, but no plans on what to
do with it. So for five years, not unlike many young men his age,
he drifted. He lived in three states, had at least seven apartments
and at least that many girlfriends and held three full-time jobs _
one in business, one in politics and one in public service. By Jo
Thomas. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Special Report, 3,600 words; an abridged version will also move.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT19.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to inside story: TEXAS-BUDGET.
</P>
<P>
   EPA-GRACE-ASBESTOS (Undated) _ The EPA is investigating why it
ignored evidence for 18 years that W.R. Grace and Co. produced ore
for its consumer products that was laden with asbestos. An agency
study in 1982 found alarming levels in material that Grace said was
virtually free of asbestos, but the agency shelved the report,
scuttled its planned follow-up studies and continued to accept the
company's lower figures, EPA officials say. Grace officials on
Friday did not dispute the EPA report, but said their own studies
have consistently shown much smaller amounts of asbestos. At issue
now is how much asbestos _ in a form known as tremolite _ made its
way into those products as a contaminant. By Michael Moss and
Adrianne Appel. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.)
</P>
