<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont.)   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Safe Player in the Market Embraces Risk to Save a Life  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   James Stack, a leading market analyst and financial adviser
based in Whitefish, Mont., is known for taking a conservative
approach when confronted with risks. But last April 11, he threw
caution aside and risked his life to save a drowning man.
</P>
<P>
   That night, a motorboat capsized in Whitefish Lake, throwing
Randall Bruckner and Julia Cassidy into 39-degree water. Stack, who
has a home on the lake and heard their cries, jumped into his
kayak, paddled out and pulled Bruckner ashore. Others helped
Cassidy, who later died of hypothermia.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Carnegie Hero Fund Commission, established by
Andrew Carnegie in 1904 to recognize acts of bravery, selected
Stack, 47, as one of its Carnegie Heroes. He was among 22 Americans
and Canadians honored this year who risked their lives trying to
save others. The awards include bronze medals and $3,000 grants.
</P>
<P>
   Stack's company, Investech, emphasizes safety. His professional
caution, he said, stemmed from the rough markets of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Though he may seem less cautious once his workday is done, he
still calculates risks and returns. ``My market philosophy doesn't
interfere with everyday life,'' he said. ``When I heard their cries
I knew it was a life-and-death situation. I knew I could control my
own odds.''
</P>
<P>
   His family would like him to emphasize odds control a little
more in the future: if solo kayak rescues on frigid lakes in the
dark became a habit, he said, ``they'd shoot me.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By MARCIN SKOMIAL
</P>
<P>
   Switching Careers, and Continents
</P>
<P>
   So what do you do if you're 53 and have already had a
been-there-done-that academic career? If you're George
Stephanopoulos _ no, not that George Stephanopoulos; this one,
unrelated, is a professor of chemical engineering at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology _ you switch careers and
hemispheres. He is taking a stab at turning Japan's largest
petrochemical company, Mitsubishi Chemical, into a force in the
risky but profitable world of nanochemistry, microreplication and
the like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a member of the National Academy of Engineering, I have
received the top awards that the chemical engineering profession
can give, I've written 10 books, close to 200 scientific papers,
graduated 45 Ph.D.'s,'' Stephanopoulos said earlier this month,
just before Mitsubishi Chemical officially named him its chief
technology officer. ``I had to rejuvenate myself intellectually and
professionally.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife and two children will stay in Boston, and the
separation looms painfully. ``But they saw the gleam in my eye, and
they all said, `You've got to do this.''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, another task: a crash course in Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH
</P>
<P>
   So What About Mount McKinley?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Staehelin squared off against Ronald McDonald and lost.
</P>
<P>
   Staehlin says that in naming McWellness, her three-year-old
company that offers health assistance over the Web to executives on
the road, she meant no allusion to McDonald's. ``We used the name
because we had been working at McKinsey,'' she said, referring to
the consulting firm where she met her co-founder, Catharina
Maulbecker. Her own company, based in Basel, Switzerland, has won a
national prize for business innovation.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's, however, saw the name as trademark infringement and
challenged the company's effort to register it in the United
States. ``The Mc prefix is well established to be McDonald's,'' a
company spokesman said. ``We do business in 119 countries where the
trademark is known. It is directly connected with medical programs
and hospitals'' through Ronald McDonald House charities for the
families of gravely ill children.
</P>
<P>
   So, as of this month, McWellness is now GetWellness.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ELIZABETH OLSON
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Their Eyes On High-Tech Fortunes
</P>
<P>
   Americans who have grown rich in high-technology industries are
highly likely to have made plans to preserve their wealth and to
pass it along to their heirs, United States Trust Co. found in an
annual survey.
</P>
<P>
   This year's survey was limited to people who work in high-tech,
have an annual household income of at least $300,000 and a net
worth of at least $3 million _ levels that put them in the top 1
percent of all Americans in both categories.
</P>
<P>
   Just 54 of the 150 participants were 55 or older. But 89 percent
of the total said they had a will, while 75 percent had a complete
estate plan, which may include trusts; 72 percent had set aside
money for the education of their children or grandchildren; and 70
percent had a written financial and tax plan. The participants had
worked an average of 22 years in high-tech; their average age was
48.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the group was quite generous to charities, donating an
average of 6 percent of income. Americans in general give about 2
percent of their income to charity each year, with nearly half of
that going to religious organizations, according to research by the
National Center for Charitable Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Among the high-tech wealthy, the most common recipients of gifts
were human services charities; 69 percent of the respondents
reported such donations. Close behind were educational and
religious organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also showed that some people paid a fairly high price
in amassing their fortunes. All 134 respondents who had children
said that building wealth had come at some expense in their
relationship with them; 29 percent said the toll was substantial.
Of the married respondents, 27 percent said their work took a
significant toll on their relationship with their spouses. And 22
percent of all those surveyed said there was a significant adverse
effect on their health.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
