<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT &LR;      07-21 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPAIN PUTS U.S. IN DEEP HOLE IN THE RED CLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTANDER, Spain _ There was no positive spin to put on the day,
only the monotonous reality of the penetrating topspin strokes that
ground the United States' Davis Cup chances to near miracle odds,
if not red clay dust.
</P>
<P>
   John McEnroe could not help Todd Martin or Jan-Michael Gambill,
and it is quite possible that Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi would
not have saved McEnroe from the bad luck of the semifinal draw.
Playing at Spain, on clay, in the heat of summer, was never going
to be a day at the beach, even if the beach was only a long
forehand away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not playing chopped liver here,'' McEnroe said after his
team dropped both singles matches and fell into an 0-2 hole, with
Saturday's doubles looming as the Americans' last gasp. ``We're
playing the real deal, and these guys want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hot, as promised, but not oppressively humid. The
temporary stadium erected above the coastline of the Peninsula de
Magdelana was jammed with a crowd of an estimated 13,000, but one
not excessively raucous. Opportunities were abundant for Martin and
Gambill, but consistency is the name of the game on clay. In the
end, Albert Costa was the Road Runner who eluded Martin's grasp in
a 6-4, 6-4, 6-4 victory before Alex Corretja played rope-a-dope and
let the aggressive Gambill punch himself out, 1-6, 6-3, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Spaniards, who have never won the Davis Cup, need to win
only one of the three remaining matches to reach their first world
group final in 33 years. Should they finish the job they began so
impressively Friday, they will play host to Australia next December
in Barcelona, meaning they will have played an entire Cup year
without leaving home soil, red clay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is tailor-made for them,'' McEnroe said. ``If they can't
win this, they'll be winning the Davis Cup in the year 3000.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was any encouraging news for the Americans, it was that
Gambill, the 23-year-old with the two-fisted ground strokes on
either side, showed enough fire and rained enough winners to
suggest he might help them contend for their 32nd Cup title long
before the next millennium. Gambill, a quarterfinal loser to
Sampras at Wimbledon, wasn't supposed to have enough clay-court
game for a specialist of Corretja's quality. Yet after Martin lost
to Costa routinely, Gambill set upon Corretja like a cyclone,
winning the first set in 31 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was playing just unbelievable tennis, just wonderful,''
said Corretja, the world's seventh-ranked player. ``He was serving
big and his returns were every time in the corner. He didn't drop
his level until maybe the middle of the second set. I can tell you
that I don't know if Sampras or Agassi would play better than
Gambill.''
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a compliment, but Gambill strikes the ball and
speaks his mind as if he intends to be a lot higher than No. 37 in
the rankings sometime soon. He firmly believed he could have won.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ticked, at the world, at myself,'' he said after failing
to take advantage of several openings Corretja presented him, even
after the first set.
</P>
<P>
   Most frustrating for Gambill was an opportunity to perhaps
demoralize Corretja by getting back on serve after trailing by 1-5
in the second set. Gambill broke for 2-5, then saved two set points
for 3-5.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth game, Gambill had three break points to get back on
serve but missed, in the following order: a running backhand down
the line that was two inches long, a forehand into the net off a
very ordinary second serve and a backhand wide off a second serve
that kicked effectively wide of the ad court.
</P>
<P>
   As McEnroe said, ``The break points were there, but you give
these guys an out and you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambill would earn more chances in the third set, but Corretja
was controlling the play by then, running and sliding and whipping
his forehands cross-court like a maestro conducting a symphony. By
the fourth set, Gambill's backhand broke down and his unforced
errors, numbering 51 to Corretja's 27, piled up.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his performance was enough to make McEnroe, given the
dire straits his team was in, reconsider the doubles team he will
send out Saturday against Corretja and Juan Balcells. Having
originally tabbed Chris Woodruff and Vince Spadea, McEnroe said he
would most likely switch to Gambill or Martin with Woodruff, though
it seemed unlikely that Martin could play three days in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Despite fast starts in the first and second sets, Martin turned
in a wooden performance against Costa, putting in only 53 percent
of his first serves and committing 31 unforced errors to 13 for the
Spaniard. Martin, having had limited match play this year because
of a viral infection and a sprained ankle, looked 30 going on 50 as
he vainly tried to apply pressure to Costa.
</P>
<P>
   He did his best, McEnroe said. Both players did. But the draw
was what is was, and Sampras and Agassi stayed home and as Gambill
said when asked if the Americans needed more practice time on clay:
``We could have maybe been here a month and still had these results
because these guys are so tough on this surface.''
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   John McEnroe again expressed his frustration at the way the
Davis Cup year appears to be playing out, but said he had no plans
to quit. A U.S. Tennis Association official said earlier this week
that McEnroe was working on a year-to-year basis, but McEnroe said
Friday that he had a three-year contract. ``The one thing I'm not
going to do is say, `That's it, I quit if we lose,' what I would
have done when I was younger,'' he said. ``You know, I signed a
three-year deal and I'd like to think I could do something
positive. I'm not sure it's bad luck or I haven't made a
difference. It's hard to say right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
