<HEADLINE>
THE ID THAT HAD POLYPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George W. was getting into full stride and pulling
some pretty decent laughs. Bill Clinton was making some comic
headway explaining the cosmic unfairness of the whole Monica thing.
(``A little reward. Just a little reward. A piece of angel food
cake to recharge my batteries.'') Monica told all, once again, to
Linda Tripp. And Joe Eszterhas, sitting front row center at the
Douglas Fairbanks Theater on Monday night, listening to the words
of his ``American Rhapsody'' wash over him, expertly delivered by
seven actors, looked like a happy man.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not. Eszterhas' normal facial expression is clenched.
Even in repose, if that's the word, it looks furious. His attire _
baggy black pants and a short-sleeved black shirt open almost to
the navel _ seemed designed to dissipate the heat of a temperament
permanently on the boil.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Brown, the editor of Talk magazine, tried to take the
measure of her star guest in her opening remarks to the audience
she had summoned. She settled on the notion that to understand
Eszterhas _ one-time Rolling Stone reporter and the author of
screenplays like ``Flashdance,'' ``Basic Instinct'' and, always and
forever, ``Showgirls'' _ one must understand that he is an
idealist. ``He is not a jaded ex-hippie or a tired celebrity,'' she
said, as Eszterhas sat there, looking like a jaded ex-hippie and
tired celebrity. ``You can think of him as the id of American
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The id had drawn a fun crowd. Talk, the magazine famous for
still believing that something called synergy exists, excels at
putting together events at which e-commerce tycoons talk earnestly
with hip-hop producers. ``American Rhapsody,'' Eszterhas' personal
channeling of the Clinton years, a blend of reporting, transcribing
and fantasizing, seems tailor-made for Talk. It's Hollywood and
Washington, politics and celebrities, and this night, it was New
York, too.
</P>
<P>
   Drinking post-performance Champagne, the crowd milled in front
of the theater. There was Carolyne Roehm, gliding past Pete
Peterson, who bumped up against George Stephanopoulos, who did not
seem to be rushing over to chitchat with Peggy Noonan.
Stephanopoulos surely would have something fascinating to say about
``American Rhapsody,'' in which the presidential penis becomes a
character named Willard. But whatever Stephanopoulos was thinking,
he was not about to share it with a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Mehta, the editor in chief of Knopf, which published
``American Rhapsody,'' talked earnestly with Ed Victor, the agent
for the book. Victor, aglow in a tan linen suit and shocking black
and white spectator shoes, described the manuscript vividly. It
poured forth from Eszterhas like lava from Mount St. Helen's. ``It
blew me away,'' Victor said. Erica Jong, George Plimpton, James
Atlas, Joni Evans and Harry Evans were there, giving a literary
gloss to the affair. Suddenly the doors to the theater opened, and
Eszterhas emerged, puffing madly on a cigarette and hugging his
very pregnant wife, Naomi.
</P>
<P>
   After breaking free from photographers and scribbling scribes,
Eszterhas retreated to a corner of the theater lobby and reviewed
the evening. ``George Bush just exploded on stage,'' he said
admiringly. His own performance, limited to a brief reading, he
dismissed with a wave of his cigarette. ``I've done very few
readings,'' he said. ``It's a problem for me, because I have bad
polyps on my sinuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Eszterhas wrote the book, he said, during a period of seclusion
brought on by disgust at living a too-public life. Now, the book
was starting the cycle all over again. And on top of that, polyps.
``Faulkner once referred to the writer's puny and inexhaustible
voice,'' he said. ``It's getting puny already. Now we'll see how
inexhaustible it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
