<HEADLINE>
FUNDS WATCH: A GLOSSY FUND SETS ITS DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wired and Fortune magazines are used to competing for
advertisers, circulation, staff members and attention. So why not
mutual fund dollars?
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Fortune Group, a unit of Time Warner, announced a
plan to open two exchange-traded funds later this year, including
one, the Fortune e-50 Index Tracking Stock, that will mirror
Fortune's new ``e-50'' Internet index.
</P>
<P>
   The product, which trades like a stock, is similar to a mutual
fund in that it is a basket of stocks. (It is not a true tracking
stock, which reflects the performance of part of one company.)
</P>
<P>
   The fund is making a late entry into the ever-expanding universe
of technology funds, going up up against the 19-month-old, $195
million Guinness Flight Wired Index fund, which is based on a
40-stock index compiled by Wired.
</P>
<P>
   Neither publication has been what one might call modest in
describing its own stock-picking prowess. Fortune billed its e-50
as ``the ultimate Internet index'' on its cover last December and
proclaimed inside that it had ``the potential to upstage the Dow.''
That recalled the June 1998 cover of Wired, heralding the birth of
its index with ``Forget the Dow. Here comes the new economy!''
emblazoned over a picture of Godzilla on the rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Vivek Shah, director of new business ventures for Fortune Group,
said the e-50 was different, because Wired includes stocks like
DaimlerChrysler in a new-economy index that Wired says should
include technologically savvy companies in all business sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The e-50 is an Internet company index,'' Shah said. `` It's
not a new-economy index.'' The Fortune product, which will trade
like a stock, will charge investors lower fees than traditional
mutual funds like Wired's, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Which fund will prove mightiest? The warm-up round goes to
Wired. Its index rose 12.4 percent this year through Thursday,
versus 1 percent for the e-50.
</P>
<P>
   But Wired will not be Fortune's only media competitor.
Exchange-traded funds like Fortune's already track technology and
Internet indexes compiled by Dow Jones, publisher of The Wall
Street Journal. And Fortune's other new offering, based on its
45-year-old Fortune 500 annual ranking of large companies, will no
doubt be measured against the tens of billions of investment fund
dollars pegged to the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, maintained
by McGraw Hill, publisher of Business Week. The good news here for
Fortune is that its 500 have outperformed S&AMP;P's, not to mention the
Dow industrials, by a fair margin so far this year.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
