   &UR; PAGE ONE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVESTING-GREENBERG-BUFFETT (Undated) _ One plays the hayseed,
the other the New York tough guy, but Warren E. Buffett of Omaha
and Maurice R. Greenberg of Manhattan _ have a lot in common. Each
has built an empire that has delivered tremendous value to
shareholders. Greenberg, 75, and Buffett, nearly 70, are giants in
the same game. Though both Buffet's Berkshire Hathaway and
Greenberg's American International Group have other operations,
each is mainly in the insurance business. ``We think alike,''
Buffett said recently. ``If you showed us 10 deals, we would
probably come to pretty similar conclusions on most of them.'' That
makes all the more extraordinary this fact: For 10 years,
Greenberg's company has been the better bet for investors. By
Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   PESYSTEMS-HUNKAPILLER-GENOME (Foster City, Calif.) _ PE
Biosystems has emerged as the leading supplier of equipment to the
exploding genomics industry. The company controls at least 70
percent of the market for gene sequencers. It is the leading
supplier of equipment used for one of the fundamental processes in
biotechnology, the amplification and detection of DNA by polymerase
chain reaction. It is in the early lead for machines used to
analyze proteins. Competitors often refer to PE as the Microsoft of
genomics equipment, for its commanding position and its aggressive
tactics. If PE is the Microsoft, then Dr. Michael J. Hunkapiller is
the Bill Gates, a nerd at heart, who has transformed himself into a
respected, shrewd and tough businessman. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INVESTING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-CHARTING (Undated) _ For years finance professors have
held chartists in contempt. The problem has been one of translating
chartists' visual pattern recognition into the mathematics on which
academics rely, according to a new study, in which the authors, all
academics, gauge which charting techniques work. After defining the
chart patterns mathematically, the researchers back-tested the
patterns' predictive prowess for 750 stocks over 35 years ending in
1996. One of their findings is that the patterns predict the future
direction of Nasdaq stocks better than they do exchange-listed
issues. By Mark Hurlbert.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-REITS (Undated) _ It might not be realistic to expect a
Real Estate Investment Trust to be the next Cisco Systems, but a
significant new law is leading some money managers to suggest that
investors look to REITs as technology plays. They point to REITs
that are either actively investing in technology to improve
businesses, or that cater to the real estate needs of e-commerce
companies. These companies are poised to benefit from the federal
REIT Modernization Act of 1999, which, in January, will allow
REIT's to offer services like landscaping, parcel delivery, and
telecommunications _ to tenants and other parties. The new law is
``probably the biggest development in the REIT industry since 1986,
when REITs were permitted to both own and manage real estate,''
says Anthony R. Davis, an analyst at UBS Warburg Dillon Read. By
Sana Siwolop.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-WHITCOMB (Undated) _ Roland P. Whitcomb, the lead manager
of the $799.1 million First American Technology &UR;  &LR; fund, says that in
a technology cycle, value investors get confused by the high
valuation of the stocks, because they underestimate the coming
innovation. Growth investors often have trouble selling, because
they take the growth rate and project it forward, he says. Whitcomb
gives each new technology cycle time to run, an inisght that has
helped the fund return 66.6 percent a year for the three years that
ended July 14, compared with 53.8 percent for its technology peers.
By Carole Gould.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-Q&AMP;A-BRONSON (Undated) _ Gail Bronson, a senior analyst
for IPO Monitor, and a Silicon Valley venture capitalist, is
interviewed about the new issue market. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS-MUTUAL-FUNDS (Undated) _ Last year the mutual fund
industry discovered the Internet; this year the buzz word is
``wireless.'' Four funds focused on wireless investing have opened
this year, and regulatory paperwork has been filed for a fifth
offering from Fidelity Investments. Further, the telecommunications
fund sector _ previously the best way to play wireless stocks _ has
seen its offerings swell from 10 at the end of 1998 to about 25
funds that are either open or in the pipeline. By Danny Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS-WATCH (Undated) _ Wired and Fortune magazines are used to
competing for advertisers, circulation, staff members and
attention. So why not mutual fund dollars? Last week, Fortune Group
announced a plan to open two exchange-traded funds later this year,
including one, the Fortune e-50 Index Tracking Stock, that will
mirror Fortune's new ``e-50'' Internet index. By Danny Hakim.
