<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGANSTANLEY-ANALYST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE ANALYST LEAVES PAINEWEBBER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH B. TREASTER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alice D. Schroeder, an insurance analyst who managed
to charm Warren Buffett and Maurice Greenberg, has left PaineWebber
to join Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, who has done perhaps the most detailed and exhaustive
research of any analyst on Buffett's company, Berkshire Hathaway,
and Greenberg's, American International Group, left PaineWebber on
June 28. She began work at Morgan Stanley the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Schroeder nor PaineWebber would discuss her reasons for
leaving. There was no indication that it was related to the
purchase of PaineWebber by UBS, which was announced on July 12.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, no large Wall Street firm had covered Berkshire
Hathaway, which eschews the advice of investment bankers and in
whose stock there is little trading.
</P>
<P>
   But, seeking a better public understanding of Berkshire after it
had become an insurance giant with the purchase of General Re, one
of the biggest reinsurers, Buffett called Schroeder to invite her
to delve into his company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear to me that she was a superior analyst, both in
her knowledge of the insurance business and in her willingness to
do the legwork to garner facts,'' Buffett said then.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, who has an M.B.A. from the University of Texas, met
Buffett in New York, then flew with him to Berkshire's headquarters
in Omaha, Neb., and visited several of the company's businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, she issued a report on AIG that ran to nearly
300 pages and was based on research in New York, China and several
other countries and ranged over five months.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Schroeder was named the No. 2 analyst on the
Institutional Investor magazine's All-America Research Team in
property casualty insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Before working at PaineWebber, she had been an analyst at CIBC
Oppenheimer and Dowling Partners. Schroeder, who is qualified as a
certified public accountant, also had worked at the Financial
Accounting Standards Board and at Ernst &AMP; Young, the consulting
firm. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
