<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE BEAR ASSESSES TIGER
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Like ships that pass in the night, Jack
Nicklaus was coming up the 18th fairway on the Old Course in the
sunshine of applause from thousands of Scots Friday as Tiger Woods
strolled out of the Royal and Ancient clubhouse shortly before
shooting 66 for a three-stroke lead halfway through the British
Open.
</P>
<P>
   More golden than bearish now at 60, Nicklaus missed his birdie
putt, tapped in and waved to the applause. With a 1-over 73 after
Thursday's 77 for 150, he missed the 36-hole cut in what will
probably be his last ``favorite event,'' golf's oldest tournament
that he had won three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking over the Swilken Bridge is very nice,'' he was saying
now, referring to when he stood and waved with his son Steve, his
caddie. ``But not on Friday afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Not for the golfer who won a record 18 major titles. Not with
the championship still to be decided Saturday and Sunday when
Woods, at 24, will have the opportunity to dethrone Nicklaus as the
youngest to complete the career Grand Slam. Nicklaus was 26 when he
won the 1966 British Open to go with his U.S. Open, Masters and PGA
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the fact that Tiger is coming along doesn't bother me in
the least,'' Nicklaus said. ``I'm kind of rooting for somebody to
come along and if it's Tiger, that's fine. Or if it's somebody else
to challenge that record of 18 majors or break it, or whatever. I
think it would be good for the game of golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game of golf needs a shot in the arm constantly. It always
needs a shot in the arm. Some of the golf I've seen from this young
man has been pretty phenomenal and I think that he should get even
better. And if he does, I'm going to be the first one there to tell
him, `Well done.'''
</P>
<P>
   For all his power in his prime, Nicklaus seldom played golf as
aggressively as Woods does now. Nicklaus believed in ``playing the
way I thought it should be played _ for me.'' Meaning in keeping
with his conservative and managed manner, waiting for somebody else
to lose a tournament rather than gambling to win it on what could
be a disastrous shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not really watched Tiger play that much,'' he said,
``but every time I turn on the television set, he holes a putt. I
turned on the television set seven or eight times in the U.S. Open
and all I saw him doing was walking after a 30-footer and picking
it out of the hole. When you putt like that, the game becomes awful
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think mentally he is a very good player. But it's easy to
have a good head on your shoulders when you don't worry about
making anything from 15 feet in. You know you're going to make it,
why worry about the problems? It's like I never worried about
chipping because I never missed anything inside 10 feet anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus knows how Woods feels because at his best, he had the
same confidence, especially on pressure putts, that Woods has now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were periods of time when I was doing exactly what he
was doing,'' he said. ``Nothing matters because I'm going to knock
it in anyway. When you get that, the game becomes easy. When you're
struggling with the putter, it just goes right through the bag and
it makes every other shot difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Woods posses golf attributes that Nicklaus did not?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't played enough golf with him to know what he has,''
Nicklaus said. ``I know he has a good mind. I know he drives a
ball. I think we're fairly comparable off the tee. He's longer than
I was because of equipment. He definitely has a better short game
than I had. But I think we grew up differently. I was a big kid and
he was not a big kid. A lot of kids who are slight in stature have
a very good short game because they need a very good short game,
and now he has a big game but he's not going to forget the short
game. I never had that opportunity. I'm the same size now I was at
13.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he think that some pros have mentally surrendered to Woods'
dominance?
</P>
<P>
   ``I liken that to when Arnold Palmer came along,'' he said.
``Arnold came along after Snead, Hogan and Nelson, all past their
prime, and there was a five, six, seven-year gap when not much
happened. Nobody dominated, then Arnold came along when the public
needed somebody to dominate it. Then Gary came along, then I came
along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I don't think there's anybody contending. There are
a lot of very good players, don't get me wrong. I don't mean the
players today can't play golf. Vijay Singh has won two majors,
Ernie Els has won two. That would be the closest. I was playing
Arnold, who won seven; Gary nine, Lee Trevino six, Tom Watson
eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys had all learned to win major championships,'' he
continued. ``I always had somebody who knew how to win, like I knew
how to win, competing against me. Right now Tiger doesn't have
that, but he will. He's certainly not going to get off the next 15
years with a free run. There are just too many good players coming
along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger is good for the game, but he has to have challengers for
the whole thing to be right. He has done some great things. He's
the new kid on the block and he's a great player and he's going to
get better. But he will have competition, too. You're finding that
a lot of good athletes gravitate to golf now, which is only going
to make it better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9120 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-R-CIR-MP3-PLAYERS-ART     07-21 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CIR-MP3-PLAYERS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: mass appeal.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first stumbling block _ storage _ is being tackled on
several fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Practically all portable players store music on solid state
memory chips, including Compact Flash, Smart Media cards and Sony's
Memory Sticks.
</P>
<P>
   While solid state memory chips are small, run noiselessly and
are reliable, they are also expensive and appear to be growing more
so as demand begins to outstrip supply, manufacturers say.
</P>
<P>
   One frustrated executive at an American consumer electronics
manufacturer said he had traveled to Asia in an unsuccessful search
for a company that could make and then sell the hardware components
for a digital audio player to his company for $1. The reason? Much
of the cost of a player, which is passed to consumers, is consumed
by the cost of memory.
</P>
<P>
   A digital player with adequate memory _ for at least a half-hour
of playback _ that costs less than $100 has eluded the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Most players are sold with 32 megabytes of embedded, often
called ``onboard,'' memory. A 32-megabyte memory card costs about
$100. And the rule of thumb is that a player, like Samsung's Yepp
player, requires about a megabyte of memory for every minute of
recorded MP3 music (at near-CD-quality sound).
</P>
<P>
   Adding more music requires more memory for storage, and the cost
starts to climb steeply, said Craig Rathbun, the worldwide director
of Clik technology for Iomega, maker of disk-based removable
storage devices like the popular Zip and Jaz cartridges.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-megabyte memory cards used in audio players are
``essentially $100 half-hour albums,'' Rathbun said. Iomega is
taking a different approach by adapting its Clik drives to digital
audio players so that they may use the 40-megabyte Clik disks to
store and play music.
</P>
<P>
   Clik disks are not solid state and introduce moving parts into
the players. But they are cheaper than solid state memory, Rathbun
said.
</P>
<P>
   A 40-megabyte Clik disk can cost as little as $10. They are also
rugged, Rathbun said, as he held a handful of the half-dollar-size
Clik disks, each containing a different genre of music.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the first digital player using Clik technology, the
Rave MP 2300 by Sensory Science, reached the market. Iomega
officials said seven players with built-in Clik drives by other
manufacturers _ including one by Iomega itself _ are expected to be
available before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Rio is exploring alternatives to expensive, solid-state flash
memory for storing music in its players.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Rio 600, which is the first player to seamlessly
play music encoded in the MP3 or Windows Media format, comes with
32 megabytes of memory. A more feature-laden Rio 800 is expected
later this summer, with 64 megabytes of included memory.
</P>
<P>
   Rio has also taken a novel approach to the question of expanding
the storage capabilities of its audio players. Earlier models like
the Rio 300 and Rio 500 use, as most players do, a slot in which an
expansion memory card can be inserted, boosting the player's
overall capacity to play more music. But such designs are limited,
making it difficult to add more than a 64-megabyte card to the 32
megabytes already built into the player.
</P>
<P>
   The new Rio players are designed with what its engineers call a
backpack. It is a slip-off and slip-on back that contains the
player's memory and power supply. The Rio 600, which costs $169,
comes with a backpack with 32 megabytes built in and a single AA
battery to power the unit.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 64-megabyte backpack comes with a rechargeable
battery. And Rio, in partnership with IBM, will soon release a
backpack that will house a 340-megabyte IBM Microdrive. Also in
development is a Rio backpack equipped with a new 500-megabyte
drive by DataPlay.
</P>
<P>
   While executives at S3's Rio division said they were not ready
to discuss the cost of the backpacks with the minidrives, they said
the emerging memory technology helps to make their new Rio players
``future-proof.''
</P>
<P>
   And because the disk-based storage devices spin only to retrieve
a song before playing it from small embedded memory, they do not
greatly tax battery life or make players more susceptible to
skipping when moved or bumped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are turning the corner with the release of the Rio
600 and other products in the family,'' Reed said, and added that
Rio is looking beyond the youth market.
</P>
<P>
   S3's Rio division, as well as a number of other consumer
electronics companies, is also preparing to release a line of
home-based digital audio players that resemble conventional stereo
components. The newly released SongBank SL CD Memory System by
Lydstrom not only plays and records CDs, but can also convert their
content into a digital format and save iton the $800 machine's hard
drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the ways that people listen to CD's today,''
Reed at Rio said, you can pretty much count on us to replace that
CD technology in the future with our technology.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
