<HEADER>
A9149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KINA-PROFILE-$$ADV23-     07-21 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINA-PROFILE-$$ADV23-1125(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE FOOT IN MOTOWN ANOTHER IN LED ZEPPELIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 was sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(For release on Sunday, July 23) 
 By DOUGLAS CENTURY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a hot July night, the Bowery Ballroom on the Lower
East Side was packed with lager-sipping hipsters waiting for the
arrival of rock's next big thing. She was an hour late, but when
she bounded onto the stage in a floor-length red suede skirt, a
white tank top and gold hoop earrings, the crowd chanted her name:
``Ki-na! Ki-na!''
</P>
<P>
   It was still a full week before the release of Kina's debut
album, but many already had learned the words to her songs. They
waved hands overhead and mouthed along as she belted the lyrics to
``Girl From the Gutter,'' an ``I told you I was gonna be a star''
anthem that sounds like Alanis Morisette as sung by Tina Turner.
``I hope your hell is filled with magazines,'' Kina sings to
doubting former friends. ``And on every page you see a big picture
of me.''
</P>
<P>
   She has the boundless, often angry energy of a young Turner, and
the same never-ending legs, planted wide in a prizefighter's
stance. All right, she doesn't do the wigs. She wears her hair in a
blond-dyed Afro. But Kina does like skintight red leather pants and
stiletto heels.
</P>
<P>
   A gut-bucket soul singer with the attitude and style of a rock
star, she is the latest of a recent wave of African-American women
to break from the rigid formula of contemporary R&AMP;B. They're losing
the glitzy hair and the nail extensions, the minks and the diamond
baguettes, the silky smooth vocals and the often vapid lyrics that
have been the hallmarks of R&AMP;B acts like Toni Braxton and Destiny's
Child, and branching into rough-edged terrain traditionally
associated with white rock divas like Morisette and Sheryl Crow.
</P>
<P>
   Often dubbed alternative soul, this eclectic group includes Macy
Gray, Kelis, Angie Stone and Dionne Farris, singers whose style and
musical sensibility vary widely, but all have defied
categorization. From Gray's space woman coveralls to the David
Bowie T-shirt worn by Dawn Robinson of the band Lucy Pearl, their
crossover appeal comes from the raw looks and sounds and an
antifabulous style.
</P>
<P>
   With the promotional muscle of Dreamworks Records and a
high-powered manager, Benny Medina, Kina is poised to break out.
MTV has deemed her ``buzzworthy,'' a new artist to watch for.
``Girl From the Gutter'' is being played heavily on Top 40 radio,
though it is largely ignored by black stations. And next week, she
begins a 30-city tour with the Australian pop-rock band Savage
Garden. She has developed a network of celebrity fans, including
the designer John Bartlett and the actor Matthew McConaughey, who
has memorized her lyrics and calls her to gush over her record.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard that one of her major influences was Led
Zeppelin, I thought it was killer,'' McConaughey said from his home
in Los Angeles. ``I mean, just on straight appearance, you wouldn't
expect someone who looks like her to be influenced by Led Zeppelin,
but after you meet her, you get it, because Kina's really a rocking
chick.''
</P>
<P>
   She's also captured the respect of veteran black singers like
Darlene Love and Nona Hendryx. After the Bowery Ballroom show,
Love, the '60s soul powerhouse, came backstage to hug and
congratulate her. ``I told her that she reminds me of myself,''
said Love, known for her no-holds-barred belting. ``She sings from
the, heart, she sings without tricks, without doing all those
flashy runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Kina and her crew went by limo to an after-party at Lotus on
West 14th Street, where the singer accepted congratulations from
Serena Altschul and David Lee Roth. She danced with Medina, the
diminutive, powerfully built music manager best known for
shepherding the careers of Will Smith, Puff Daddy and Jennifer
Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   But Medina's latest star was fading. Kina smiled at her road
manager, Brett Goetsch, a rock-and-roll veteran with the immense
layered blond hair of a heavy metal star of the '80s. Goetsch, who
has done stints on the road with people like Joan Jett and Guns 'n'
Roses, nodded back. Time to go.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, over coffee at Asia de Cuba in midtown, she
acknowledged that the rhythm-and-blues scene needed shaking up.
``R&AMP;B is very stale, unfortunately,'' she said. ``I appreciate R&AMP;B,
but I appreciate the old R&AMP;B. It had more substance, even in terms
of the lyrical content. Today it's about hits, and it's very
producer-driven, very copycat. It's not even real R&AMP;B. It has the
rhythm, but where's the blues?''
</P>
<P>
   With her sweaty T-shirts and Stratocaster power chords, it comes
as a surprise to hear that she got her start in the soft-core R&AMP;B
tradition. Born Kina Cosper in Detroit, the home of Motown, she
began her career in an En Vogue-knockoff group, a forgotten
foursome called Brownstone, which had a few hits in the mid-'90s.
Her look in Brownstone was all flash and flowing tresses. (``That
hair wasn't mine _ it was a weave, child.'') Now, she sports plain
white undershirts and close-cropped hair, and at her concert last
week she kicked off her stiletto heels and pranced barefoot,
leading her guitar-driven band through a tight set that included
Sly Stone's ``I Want to Take You Higher.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Brownstone, I replaced a member who had left,'' she said.
``The thing is, Brownstone had established a sound before I got
there. I was in the group for about two and half years, but it
wasn't really what I'm about musically.''
</P>
<P>
   Kina is a case study in the traps of today's narrowly segmented
music business. She felt that the way to break into the industry
was with a highly pasteurized ``urban'' sound, even though her real
roots were in more free-spirited rock.
</P>
<P>
   With a roll of her eyes she recalled how an uncle used to blast
his eclectic record collection in Detroit. ``I didn't love Jean-Luc
Ponty or Hiroshima or the Rolling Stones back then,'' she said. ``I
do now, but as a kid I was embarrassed by it. Everybody else's mom
was listening to Barry White, but in my house Hiroshima and Led
Zeppelin were always playing.''
</P>
<P>
   After Brownstone broke up, Kina tried a solo career. She began
writing her own songs while honing a style of dress and grooming
that, like her music, cuts against the grain. The look of current
R&AMP;B, like that of its cousin hip-hop, is high-priced designer
labels and garishly chunky diamond jewelry. ``I like more of the
thrift-store look,'' Kina said. ``I'm not into the whole designer
thing _ you see everybody doing it. I'd rather take a cheap
second-hand skirt, a cheap shirt and accessorize it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Her striking looks help her make such antistyle statements
glamorous and have also earned her a modeling contract. ``Yeah, I'm
a Wilhelmina model _ that sounds so weird,'' she said, laughing.
``I can't see myself doing runway, but it would be cool to do some
ads.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Kina's brand of genre-hopping is not without risk. For every
Macy Gray, whose quirky voice and work-boots-and-overcoat look
managed to cross over to a mainstream audience, there is a Dionne
Farris, formerly of Arrested Development, who released a critically
acclaimed solo album only to be dropped by her record label when
sales were slow. Black rockers like Living Color and Lenny Kravitz
had to fight hard to find a niche within the racially pigeonholed
music industry. Vernon Reid, the lead guitarist of Living Color,
often bemoaned how rock, created by black artists in the '50s, has
come to be seen as music that's odd for African-Americans to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few companies heard my demo and loved it,'' Kina said. ``But
they were from the urban department and didn't know what to do with
it. They couldn't hear it being played on black radio. I got signed
by the pop department at Dreamworks.''
</P>
<P>
   At most of her concerts, the crowds are racially mixed,
mirroring the makeup of her band: black drummer and bass player and
two white guitarists. ``It's really interesting, because I go to
places like Atlanta, where most of my audience is black, but I get
no love from black radio,'' Kina said. ``I've been picked up mostly
by Top 40. I would like to be played on black radio.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, most radio formats are tightly segregated,
and there is often a tacit color line behind the programming
decisions. A rock station like WXRK in New York will play hip-hop
records by white artists like Eminem and the Beastie Boys, but
never by black rappers like Busta Rhymes or Jay-Z. And
black-oriented stations like WBLS rarely play the rock songs of
African-American artists like Kravitz.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of artists like Kina and Macy Gray is evidence
that musical divisions can be broken down, but not without
prodding, and a few awkward moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``At our show in Philly the other night,'' Kina said, ``the
crowd was split about 50-50, black and white, and it was quite
interesting to see how separate it was. The black people all rushed
to the front of the stage; the white people stayed more to the back
dancing. If I could've found a way to bring everybody in, I would
have, but I couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she added, smiling, ``But I honestly think the more people
start getting exposed to different sounds, the more those barriers
are going to break down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
