</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BENEATH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHAT LIES BENEATH' IS CANNED BUT GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   True confessions from a hardened critic: I screamed AHHHHH! 14
times at ``What Lies Beneath.''
</P>
<P>
   A few of them might have been OOOOOH's. And OH, NOOOOOO's. Not
to mention ACK's, ARRRRH's, OY's, EERRRGH's and YIIIEEEEAHHHH's. I
think I might have even yelled EEEEEEK at some point, although I'd
be most grateful if word of this didn't get out. I have a
reputation to protect.
</P>
<P>
   See, movie critics are supposed to be skeptical creatures. Which
I am. I was skeptical enough to know going in that ``What Lies
Beneath'' would be hell-bent on eliciting screams from anyone who
watched. I knew this from the preview, which I had seen eight or
nine times (I do not exaggerate) and which promised a film about an
unreasonably gorgeous yuppie couple haunted by the ghost of a
green-eyed babe who had had an affair with the husband and then
died (suicide? murder? bad hair day?), only to possess the guy's
wife and rip off his shirt in the throes of foreplay.
</P>
<P>
   I knew all this. I knew what I was in for. I knew that ``What
Lies Beneath'' would be a shameless and manipulative horror film.
And still, I shrieked. I might add in my defense that the unwitting
stranger who sat to my left also shrieked, as did the unwitting
stranger directly behind me, although the unwitting stranger to my
right didn't shriek once and in fact turned to glare at me every
time I let one rip.
</P>
<P>
   To her and everyone else with the self-control (OK, poise; OK,
OK, intelligence) not to caterwaul at ``What Lies Beneath'': I
apologize. There is no excuse for my behavior. No excuse, that is,
beyond the unavoidable fact that this hackneyed, ridiculous, tautly
schlocky ghost story, sprung from the forehead of director Robert
Zemeckis (``Forrest Gump,'' ``Contact''), packs one mean scare
after another. They're preprogrammed scares, of course. You've seen
them before, you know they're coming, and please, could there not
put another ghostly face in the bathtub? But all the same, they
work.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a film that plays on two levels: the first is
horror; the second, camp. Though there's nothing inherently jokey
about it (knockoffs of ``The Shining'' are serious business), the
film takes its gothic chain-rattling to such goofy extremes that
every shock-point feels like a punchline. The joke's on us: We fall
for it, every time. We know we're being had. We convulse in terror,
then laugh at ourselves for being such a bunch of gullible wusses.
</P>
<P>
   Ha-ha! What a dumb cluck I am! I can't believe I screamed at
that cliched eye-in-the-fence-hole bit, but I'll be smarter next
time! I'll be such a cool customer, I won't yell or get suckered in
or behave like a ninny or AHHHHHHH!!!
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes, and so it goes, for two straight hours of
effective, pre-canned chills. There isn't much to say about the
plot that wasn't covered in the previews (see above), though the
last half an hour does wind down some new and twisty paths.
Harrison Ford plays the yuppie husband (a geneticist), Michelle
Pfeiffer plays the yuppie wife (an ex-cellist), and both of them
play-act quite believably at being (A.) rich, (B.) beautiful and
(C.) the rich, beautiful owners of a sprawling lakeside home in
mountainous Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   This sprawling home turns out to be ground zero for the
green-eyed spook, who makes her presence known by mucking around
with electrical appliances and knocking framed pictures onto the
floor. The yuppie wife responds by freaking out, gradually at
first, and by inviting her plucky best friend (Diana Scarwid) to
join her for a seance in the bathroom. She also sees a shrink (Joe
Morton), who plies her with candy and fails to burst out laughing
when informed that his newest client has a paranormal home life.
</P>
<P>
   As the tale unfolds, two things become ever more limpidly clear.
One is that Michelle Pfeiffer can lend depth, class and sympathy to
any role, no matter ho patently absurd. The other is that Robert
Zemeckis, discounting his fondness (here avoided) for squishy
sentimentality, is among the most skillful storytellers in
mainstream filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   While nothing in his bag of tricks will strike anyone as
anything new, there's a narrative competence to the whole thing.
The pacing, the atmosphere, the rhythmic regularity of the scares
that punches up several exhausted cliches and ensnares the viewer
in a well-mounted, suspenseful climax. I would call it nail-biting,
except I didn't actually bite my nails. I'm above such things; I
had notes to take, flaws to discern, a stern, cynical brow to
furrow. I'm a critic, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I was too busy screaming.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
