<HEADER>
A9154 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CYC-TOUR22-COX     07-21 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armstrong starting to sense victory
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MULHOUSE, France _ The question gnawed at Lance Armstrong, so
much so that he thought about it all throughout his 34.7-mile time
trial Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The day before, a French journalist had asked the defending Tour
de France champion if he thought his lead of 5 minutes, 37 seconds
was safe coming into Friday's time trial. The question hinted that
Jan Ullrich, the 1997 Tour champion and ace time trialist, would be
able to make up that much ground in one stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won all three time trials last year,'' Armstrong snapped.
``Next question.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong believed that question showed a collective lack of
respect for his achievements. He let it bother him throughout
Thursday evening and all Friday, as he and the other riders left
Freiburg, Germany, and crossed the border into the Alsace region of
France.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday afternoon, after Armstrong not only won the time
trial, but posted the second fastest average speed ever in such a
Tour event, the Austinite went looking for the reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is the guy?'' he asked, a broad smile on his sunburned
face.
</P>
<P>
   After giving away stage 12 on the summit of Mont Ventoux to
Marco Pantani, Armstrong finally was able to celebrate his first
stage win of this Tour. And he also allowed himself to think about
his imminent victory stroll along the Champs Elysees on Sunday
afternoon in Paris. Barring some catastrophic event, Armstrong will
be wearing yellow on Sunday's final podium. With 231.88 miles to go
until Paris, the next two stages are flat and will be dominated by
sprinters far back in the overall standings.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, dressed from his shoulders to knees in bright yellow
for the first time this Tour, traveled the course at an average
speed of 33.47 miles an hour. The only rider to ride faster in a
Tour time trial was American Greg LeMond, who posted an average
speed of 33.82 on the final day of the 1989 Tour to clinch the
yellow jersey by a meager eight seconds over France's Laurent
Fignon.
</P>
<P>
   However, Armstrong's accomplishment seemed more monumental,
given that LeMond maintained that speed over a course of only 15.1
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich, like he was in the overall standings, was second Friday
to Armstrong, finishing 25 seconds back. Armstrong's overall
cushion over Ullrich was 6:02, with Spain's Joseba Beloki in third,
10:04 back and France's Christophe Moreau in fourth, 10:34 behind.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich was the next-to-last rider on the course. A malfunction
in his two-way radio prevented him from communicating with his
coach, which made it impossible to keep up with Armstrong's
whereabouts on the course. Ullrich told the German media contingent
that he was not using his communication problem as an excuse for
finishing second.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Johan Bruyneel, Armstrong's coach with U.S. Postal,
was able to listen to Tour radio and tell the cyclist where he
stood in relation to Ullrich and the rest of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Armstrong had no idea that he had neared a Tour record
until he appeared at his press conference. Tyler Hamilton,
Armstrong's teammate, was fourth Friday, 3:01 out of first place.
Hamilton was the course leader until the final four riders took the
course.
</P>
<P>
   The 129 cyclists still in the Tour started three minutes apart
on Friday, riding the short distance from Germany back into France.
Ullrich had a huge crowd advantage. His hometown of Merdingen,
Germany, was about 10 miles from the course, and most of the large
throng that crowded the route was sporting pink and white Deutsch
Telekom hats or jerseys in support of Ullrich.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, it was Armstrong whom they applauded. Friday was his
final realistic chance at claiming a stage victory. If he failed to
do so, he likely would have become the first Tour champion not to
have won a stage since LeMond did so in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an empty feeling until now,'' Armstrong said. ``I really
wanted to win a stage. There's been a lot of stress on me here. I
did not want to finish in yellow and not win a stage. I achieved
today what I wanted. This has been very positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
