<SLUG> BC-MARKET-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS FALL AS INVESTORS CONSIDER QUARTERLY REPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after pleasant surprises from the chairman of
the Federal Reserve Board, investors turned their focus back to
corporate earnings Friday and stocks sagged, with the Nasdaq
composite index falling 2.2 percent and the Dow Jones industrial
average down 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But bond prices rallied a little as hopes persisted that new
signs of slowing consumer spending and economic growth would
persuade Fed policy-makers to leave interest rates alone when they
next meet, on Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   In the oil market, the price of crude oil plunged 4.1 percent,
to less than $30 a barrel, as it appeared more likely that the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would go along with
Saudi Arabia's call to increase daily production by 500,000
barrels.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, both stocks and bonds rallied sharply after Alan
Greenspan, the Fed chairman, was more positive than expected about
the economic outlook. Although he clearly did not rule out future
interest-rate increases, he seemed to surprise investors with his
detailed presentation of reasons for believing that the economy
could be slowing to a manageable, noninflationary pace.
</P>
<P>
   But there were some disappointments on the earnings front
Friday. Eastman Kodak reported a 4.5 percent rise in second-quarter
earnings but said that its market share in the United States had
slipped this year. Its stock was down 1 7/8, to 58. BorgWarner,
which makes engine turbochargers, fell 15/16, to 36, after its
second-quarter earnings per share of $1.51 missed Wall Street
estimates by 5 cents. Lexmark International, a maker of computer
printers, said that its third-quarter profit would come in below
expectations. Its shares plunged 14\, or 22.3 percent, to 49}.
</P>
<P>
   Semiconductor stocks also declined on concerns about chip sales
for the rest of the year, with Intel falling 4{, to 138 3/16, and
Motorola sliding 1\, to 36 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq index fell 90.11 points, or 2.2 percent, to 4,094.45,
while the Dow dropped 110.31, or 1 percent, to 10,733.56. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index slumped 15.38, or 1 percent, to
1,480.19.
</P>
<P>
   For the week, the Nasdaq was down 3.6 percent, the Dow 0.7
percent and the S&AMP;P 500 2 percent. For the year, the S&AMP;P 500 and
the Nasdaq are up less than a percentage point while the Dow is
still off 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, prices were higher as yields, which move in
the opposite direction, fell. The yield on the 10-year Treasury
note fell to 5.98 percent from 6.00 percent on Thursday, while the
price rose 4/32, to 103 23/32. The yield on the 10-year note has
been fighting to get back below 6 percent for the last five weeks.
The yield on the 30-year bond fell to 5.79 percent from 5.81
percent as its price rose 11/32, to 106 19/32.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The seesaw battle in the oil market over where the price is
heading has been going on since July 3, when Saudi Arabia
unexpectedly announced that it was ready to pump 500,000 more
barrels a day if the price did not drop.
</P>
<P>
   But other members of OPEC immediately opposed the Saudi plan,
and reports about negotiations were inconsistent, indicating more
oil to come one day and no more oil the next. Then after an OPEC
official said earlier this week that there was no need to pump more
oil, Saudi Arabia quietly made clear that it was shipping more oil
by contacting oil brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market finally believes Saudi Arabia,'' said Irene King,
senior oil-markets analyst at J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. ``Why it took so
long, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday in New York, the price of oil for September delivery
fell $1.21, or 4.1 percent, to $28.56 a barrel, the lowest price
since mid-May.
</P>
</TEXT>
