<SLUG> BC-JUPITER-MOON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MOONLET OF JUPITER SEEN, ASTRONOMERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astronomers reported Friday that they have discovered another
tiny moon of the giant planet Jupiter. The new moonlet, if
confirmed, would be the smallest in the solar system and the first
new moon of Jupiter discovered in more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The new moon, which does not yet have a name but is designated
S/1999 J 1, is about 3 miles across, roughly the size of Block
Island, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery involved a collaboration between astronomers in
Arizona, who made the observations last fall, and in Cambridge,
Mass., where the object was initially classified as an asteroid and
just this week was unmasked as an unusual moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a beautiful collaboration,'' said Brian Marsden,
director of the Minor Planet Center at the Smithsonian
Astrophysical Observatory in Cambridge, who made the initial
calculations this week that showed the object was really in orbit
around Jupiter, not around the sun. ``They take the images, and we
interpret them,'' he said, referring to a team of astronomers in
Arizona who search the skies in a project called Spacewatch,
designed to detect asteroids that might be on a collision course
with Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Spacewatch astronomer James Scotti and other Spacewatch
observers took the pictures as part of an effort to search for
possible unknown Jovian moons, taking advantage of the closest
approach to Earth in Jupiter's 12-year orbit around the sun. But
initially, it appeared that all they had found was several new,
rather ordinary asteroids.
</P>
<P>
   Then, earlier this week, Tim Spahr of the Minor Planet Center
was reanalyzing some data in the Center's files, and noticed that
several observations of this object, which had been designated as
asteroid 1999 UX18, did not quite fit on an expected asteroidal
orbit. He showed the data to Marsden, who quickly calculated a new
orbit showing that the object was probably a moon of Jupiter.
Gareth Williams of the planet center then made a more detailed
observation that seemed to clinch it.
</P>
<P>
   Which, among other things, illustrates just how difficult it is
to pin down the orbits of celestial objects, even with the power of
modern computers. ``It's still an art,'' Marsden said.
</P>
<P>
   Absolute confirmation will require follow-up observations, which
should be possible in coming weeks now that the view of Jupiter is
no longer blocked by the sun.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a moon of Jupiter was discovered from a telescope
on Earth was in 1974, when a moon called Leda, believed to be about
5 to 10 miles across, was found. Until now, it was the smallest
confirmed moon of any of the solar system's planets. Three other
Jovian moons were discovered by the Voyager spacecraft in 1979.
Along with the new find, that brings Jupiter's family to a total of
17 moons. The object, which orbits the planet in the opposite
direction from most of the others, is probably an asteroid or a
burned-out comet that was captured by Jupiter's gravitational
field, Marsden said.
</P>
<P>
   If this moon is confirmed, it would then be up to a panel of the
International Astronomical Union, chaired by Marsden, to decide on
a name. The accepted convention is that moons of Jupiter are all
given names of lovers associated with the Roman god Jupiter.
Fortunately for the astronomers, Jupiter was a rather promiscuous
god, so there are still plenty of names to choose from.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
