<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-POKMON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`POKMON' IS GOOD, COMMERICIAL FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Will children abandon their dog-eared copies of
``Harry Potter and The Goblet of Fire'' for ``Pokmon the Movie
2000?''
</P>
<P>
   Wait until kids get a load of ``P2K,'' with its jacked-up
self-consciousness and attempt to give kids the summer-movie fix
they may have missed with ``Chicken Run'' (though I don't see how).
</P>
<P>
   Aping the same exasperating format of the first film (20-minute
short as prelude to 90-minute feature), the second Pokmon movie in
less than a year is aglow with shameless commercialism. But it
knows that you know it's simply after your last dollar, and has
trumped cynics by opening a can of player-hate on itself.
</P>
<P>
   Our villain this time is none other than a crazed Pokmaniac,
scouring the earth for the most obscure creatures to add to his
collection. And at some point he's chastised for giving people the
impression that all collectors are crazed materialist fanatics.
It's a moment of freakish self-awareness aimed at aligning the
Japan-born series with the other WB cartoon staples ``Tiny Toons,''
``Pinky and the Brain'' and ``Animaniacs,'' each marked by
muscle-bound, adult-targeted savvy.
</P>
<P>
   ``P2K's'' own pleas for pop props don't go unnoticed. But the
film is littered with such snide indictments of the entire
consumer-merchant Pokmon relationship that you'll never ``catch 'em
all'' with your youngster in quite the same way again.
</P>
<P>
   The crazed fan is called Lawrence III; he speaks in the haughty
mumbles and sighs of Frasier Crane and gets around in a massive
airborne contraption that looks like Alexander Calder's Hindenburg.
And if he gets his hands on Zapdos, Moltres and Articuno, the
powerful Pokmon birds of lightning, fire and ice, respectively,
Lawrence III would become the most powerful Pokmon trainer on
earth.
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of these three creatures with their different
elemental functions will also unleash the sea monster Lugia _
better known to you and me as the Perfect Storm. (All this is laid
out for us in a pageant of helixes and a board of color codes that
suggest a Pokmon equivalent of the human genome project.)
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Takeshi Shudo's Japanese script, ``P2K'' has a far
more involving story than the first film's cloning parable. This is
a Warner Bros. joint, looking to give the tykes in attendance a
taste of what their folks are getting in that studio's other
seafaring epic, ``The Perfect Storm.'' Only ``P2K'' has less
schmaltz, more brine and a pronounced affection for the antics of
``Gilligan's Island.'' Ash Ketchum, Misty and the gang are out at
sea when a gale whips up and threatens to shipwreck them. We get a
shot of Ash's prize Pokmon, Pikachu, clinging to a rail, staring
off into the oncoming chaos with a look of pure Clooney etched on
his face. He knows, in the same way ``Storm's'' Mary Elizabeth
Mastrantonio knew: They're headed right for the (pocket) monster!
</P>
<P>
   They are shipwrecked on the tropical island of Shimouti (didn't
I go to school with her?) just in time for the annual legend
festival - or the second season of ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   This little celebration happens to reenact the story of Zapdos,
Moltres and Articuno, who lord over their own islands while
maintaining earth's natural balance, which is disrupted by Lawrence
III, No. 1 fan. The legend foretells of such an event and says that
only the Chosen One can restore the balance, and because Harry
Potter is signed on for a seven-book series, the job of using the
supernatural to save the world falls to Ash Ketchum.
</P>
<P>
   Nice try, but all the action-movie tension ``P2K'' generates is
in the bizarre _ like the triangle between Ash, Misty and jaded
islander Melody, who can work wonders with her homemade woodwind.
Ash and Misty spend their time on the show locked in Mulder-Scully
flirtations (bland, bland, bland). The tension rises with the
innocuous pluck of a toddler blowing bubbles in his milk.
</P>
<P>
   Randy and armed with a crush, Melody is essentially on hand to
make things rough for poor, jealous Misty, whose tomboyishness
prohibits her from admitting she loves Ash. ``If you want someone
to do whatever you want, whenever you want, get yourself a
girlfriend,'' she warns. And here ``P2K'' offers its most novel
service: kiddie dating tool.
</P>
<P>
   The regular adversarial coed duo Team Rocket has discovered the
power of good, which here means offering tips on not getting
involved with the opposite sex. And the film's recurring themes of
fire, ice and lightning _ not to mention Pokmon-trading, with a
cockfighting subtext and that suggestive ``catch 'em all'' tag line
_ suddenly come full-circle as sandbox-love metaphors.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's little else of interest about Pokmon beyond
the consumption factor. And the franchise keeps things between its
trainers platonic, refocusing millions of collectors on the task at
hand: Buy more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
