<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9163 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-MCCAIN-BOS &LR;      07-21 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-MCCAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN RISES TO THREATEN BUSH AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN JOHNSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George W. Bush thought he had defeated John McCain
with a pair of primary victories in early March, but the Arizona
senator is popping back into the presidential spotlight just as the
Texas governor plans take center stage at the Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush poised to announce his running mate as early as
Monday, he finds himself confronted with fresh reports his
vanquished primary rival is willing to join him on the ticket. At
the same time, 60 House Republicans _ more than a quarter of the
GOP members _ signed a petition this week asking Bush to consider
McCain as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The letter said the only thing Bush's current rival, Democrat Al
Gore, has to fear ``is George W. Bush calling John McCain,''
according to a Republican official who had the wording read to him.
</P>
<P>
   McCain already has plans to resurrect his ``Straight Talk
Express'' campaign bus and drive it from Washington to the
convention hall, arriving next Saturday. He will be trailed by
three media buses.
</P>
<P>
   Once in Philadelphia, the senator will deliver the kickoff
address July 30 at a ``shadow'' convention organized by columnist
Arianna Huffington and others who feel the major-party events are
too scripted.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 1, McCain will deliver a prime-time speech during the
GOP gathering.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the Bush team is taking the latest bout of
McCain mania in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand there are all kinds of speculation,'' Bush
spokesman Ari Fleischer said Friday. ``This is one of five vice
presidential boomlets I have counted.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night there were new reports that former Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney, who is heading Bush's search for a running
mate, had positioned himself for the job. He reportedly switched
his voter registration from Texas, where he has been living, to
Wyoming, where he once served as a congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Switching registration would avoid conflict with the 12th
Amendment of the Constitution, which prohibits the Electoral
College from voting for a president and vice president who are
``inhabitants'' of the same state.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Cheney and McCain, current speculation centers on
Oklahoma Governor Frank Keating, Nebraska Senator Chuck Hagel,
Senators Fred Thompson and Bill Frist of Tennessee, Representative
John Kasich of Ohio, Governors George Pataki of New York and Tom
Ridge of Pennsylvania, as well as former Cabinet secretary
Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   The renewed talk about McCain is somewhat troublesome for Bush,
though, because he thought he had long ago doused the speculation.
He also is about to embark on a carefully choreographed run-up to
his party convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the Bush point of view, this is a real kick in the
butt,'' said Washington political analyst Stuart Rothenberg. ``He's
trying to make a decision that would be greeted on its own, that
people would reflect on positively, and instead this elevates
McCain and might force people to say, `Why not, all things being
equal, select McCain?' It's bound to create comparisons.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush worked carefully in the spring to get McCain, who won seven
primaries, to publicly rule out an interest in the vice presidency.
The governor has said repeatedly that he wants a running mate who
is loyal to his cause. Bush feared that openly rejecting McCain,
with whom he clashed over campaign finance and Social Security
reform during the primary campaign, would leave the senator's
legion of reform-minded supporters angry.
</P>
<P>
   Following a May summit meeting with Bush in Pittsburgh, McCain
said he had asked not to be considered. Bush declared he would
respect his wishes.
</P>
<P>
   But during a conversation earlier this week with Ridge, the
Pennsylvania governor, McCain reportedly said he didn't want to be
vice president, yet if asked, ``I would serve.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Arizona senator never ruled out such a possibility in
May, leaks about the conversation reignited speculation about
McCain and Bush teaming up.
</P>
<P>
   The talk about McCain comes as Bush is about to execute a plan
aimed at maximizing his ability to keep attention off Gore.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend has been blocked out for the final decision-making
about a running mate. Bush spokesman Ray Sullivan said Friday,
``The process is still working. The governor has not made up his
mind but may be prepared to make an announcement next week as early
as Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Before heading off to a huddle with advisers at his Texas ranch,
Bush was asked specifically about McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be a loyal soldier for my campaign,'' the governor said.
``He is a man of duty and he loves his country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush only smiled when asked what rank McCain might hold.
</P>
<P>
   When the announcement comes, it will trigger a run of
high-profile campaigning by the Republican presidential ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is planning to take his running mate on a five-day trip
from Texas to Arkansas, Missouri, Kentucky, Ohio, West Virginia
and, finally, Pennsylvania _ arriving in Philadelphia on Aug. 2
amid the convention frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the renewed attention on McCain, his spokesman says the
Bush team has nothing to fear from the senator's presence at the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator McCain is going to Philadelphia to reiterate his
strong support of Governor Bush, and any time the spotlight is
shining on Senator McCain, it will only serve to heighten the
public's awareness of the senator's strong support for Governor
Bush,'' said McCain spokesman Todd Harris.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush team does have precedent for concern about McCain
sticking the the script.
</P>
<P>
   During a working vacation in Kennebunkport, Maine, in early
June, Bush and his staff met to flesh out a convention plan and a
tentative list of speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Card, the former Massachusetts state representative and
onetime US Transportation secretary who is heading up Bush's
convention planning, returned to Washington the next morning, where
he received a call from McCain's staff asking for an immediate
meeting. Card had been planning to meet with the senator the
following week.
</P>
<P>
   Card cleared the impromptu visit with Bush headquarters, yet no
sooner had he walked out of McCain's Capitol Hill office than the
news wires began reporting McCain was slotted for a prime-time
speaking role, along with former Joint Chiefs Chairman Colin
Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, Bush's communications chief, was befuddled when
reporters traveling with the governor in Maine confronted her with
the McCain news.
</P>
<P>
   An array of speakers, including Powell and Bush's wife, Laura,
had yet to be told, Hughes said with exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wire service material was used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
