<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYSMART-LIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC SAYS TOYSMART DATABASE ON CHILDREN CREATED ILLEGALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toysmart.com gained international notoriety by trying to auction
off customer data after promising shoppers it would never do so.
</P>
<P>
   Now the bankrupt retailer from Waltham, Mass. will also be
remembered as the first company accused of breaking a new law
protecting children's privacy online.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest twist to Toysmart.com's woes, the Federal Trade
Commission said Friday the toy seller collected names, e-mail
addresses and ages of children in violation of the Children's
Online Privacy Protection Act.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC plans to file an amended complaint in US District Court
in Boston demanding that Toysmart.com ``immediately delete or
destroy all information'' gathered in violation of the law.
</P>
<P>
   The federal agency also announced Friday that it has agreed to
settle a suit filed last week over Toysmart.com's plans to sell
customer data. That means the retailer can auction off information
about its adult customers under certain conditions and approval
from a US Bankruptcy judge.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial settlement squeaked by the federal agency's
commissioners Thursday night by a 3-2 vote. Commissioners Sheila F.
Anthony and Orson Swindle rejected the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``To accept the bankruptcy settlement would place business
concerns ahead of consumer privacy,'' Anthony said in a statement.
``In my view, consumer privacy would be better protected by
requiring that consumers themselves be given notice and choice
before their detailed personal information is shared with or used
by another corporate entity.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement also faces opposition from state officials. On
Thursday, attorneys general from 38 states filed an objection to
Toysmart.com's plans to sell customer information. New York and
Texas filed separate objections.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Attorney General John Cornyn said in a statement Friday
night that the proposed FTC settlement does not sufficiently
protect consumers' privacy. ``This settlement is the first of its
kind in the important area of Internet privacy,'' Cornyn said. ``It
is important that it is done in the right way and clear guidelines
are established.''
</P>
<P>
   The office of the Massachusetts attorney general declined to
comment on the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Toysmart.com closed its Web site in May after Walt Disney Co.,
which owns a majority stake in the online retailer, yanked its
support. A month later, the Internet store filed for bankrupcty
protection from its creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed by the attention, Disney has offered to buy and then
``retire'' the online retailer's customer database. Another
company, Digital Research Inc. of Kennebunk, Maine, said it would
bid on the customer list and agree to keep the names private.
</P>
<P>
   Digital may have a tough time winning over the court, however.
Under the FTC's restrictions, Toysmart.com can sell customer data
only to a family-oriented company that agrees to abide by the
retailer's privacy policy.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also calls for a package deal that forces the
buyer to purchase Toysmart.com's name and Web site. If a sale or
reorganization of Toysmart.com is not approved by July 31, 2001,
the online retailer must delete or destroy all customer data,
according to a copy of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful that the settlement resolves the concerns of the
various attorneys general,'' said Harry Murphy, a Boston attorney
representing Toysmart.com.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed deal immediately came under fire from customers
and consumer advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's sleazy,'' said Fred Boak, a computer programmer
from Harwich who often shops online. `'Given their promise, I find
it interesting that the FTC can work out a deal with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Shen, a policy analyst with the Electronic Privacy
Information Center, said the settlement sends a message to
consumers that online retailer's privacy policies are not to be
trusted.
</P>
<P>
   On its Web site, Toysmart.com encouraged shoppers to provide
tidbits about themselves and their children. That information, the
company said, ``is never shared with a third party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the settlement seems to be saying, `Don't take
privacy policies seriously,'' Shen said. ``If I was a consumer, I'd
be hesitant to shop online.''
</P>
<P>
   Shen also criticized TRUSTe, an online privacy program that
offers an Internet version of the Good Housekeeping seal of
approval.
</P>
<P>
   TRUSTe officials contacted the FTC after Toysmart.com, one of
its members, advertised its intention to sell customer information.
But Friday, a TRUSTe spokesman indicated Friday that the
organization was amenable to a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have kept going after this company,'' Shen said.
``I think this is going to reflect badly on the TRUSTe as well as
the FTC.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
