u k BC-EDITORIAL-WACO-BOS &LR;      07-21 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-WACO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO WACO ATROCITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Waco is a word that took on heightened meaning in the past
decade. To those at one edge of American culture it symbolizes the
unfeeling and even brutal authoritarian use of power by the federal
government. It was no accident that bombers destroyed the federal
building in Oklahoma City on April 19, 1995 _ the second
anniversary of the deadly fire at the Branch Davidian compound in
Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Horrible as that fire was, however, two credible forums have now
concluded that the Justice Department and agents of the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms were not the satanic evildoers
described by some paranoid right-wingers.
</P>
<P>
   Former Senator John Danforth, a Republican appointed by Attorney
General Janet Reno last fall to answer what he described as ``the
dark questions'' in the case, concluded in a preliminary report
Friday that government agents did not start the fatal fire or shoot
at those in the compound. There was no inappropriate use of the
military and no major coverup, Danforth said.
</P>
<P>
   His report came just a week after five jurors who heard
extensive testimony in a civil case in Waco advised a judge that
there was no federal negligence in the deaths of nearly 80
Davidians, including 20 children.
</P>
<P>
   While that judge's ruling and Danforth's final report are still
to come, it is clear that wild charges against government agents
were based in evidence that was thin to nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Although the government has been at least preliminarily
exonerated of criminal or civil liability, its actions have not
been applauded and do not deserve to be.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Danforth found that, while they had nothing to do
with the fatal fire, several pyrotechnic rounds had been fired _
and their use covered up _ by the FBI and other officials. This is
inexcusable and deserves harsh sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   More fundamentally, Reno's judgment in ordering agents to storm
the compound is likely to remain in doubt. Patience is usually the
prime strategy in such standoffs. We will never know if David
Koresh would have killed his followers anyway. We do know that the
federal assault was tragically ineffective.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9169 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ELYCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-21 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    GORE'S LACK OF APPEAL ISN'T JUST A TEXAS THING
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the best of times, it was the worst of times, it was the
age of wisdom, it was the age of foolishness, it was the epoch of
belief, it was the epoch of incredulity. &QL; 
A Tale of Two Cities &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Had Charles Dickens been writing about this new century of
American politics instead of the times of the French Revolution,
he'd have been half right.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, maybe a little more than half. Of foolishness and
incredulity, there can be no question. But, though it most surely
is incredibly difficult to find, there is some of the best mixed in
with some of the worst. And, what the hey, maybe there's even a
hint of wisdom and a trace of belief, but that probably is
stretching it.
</P>
<P>
   Moving along, from pure fiction to recalled reality, let it be
noted that the politics of 2000 are every bit as _ actually even
more _ strange as can be remembered well back into the last
century. Such hardly should come as a surprise to anyone, at least
anyone who's even remotely inclined to the ranks of political
junkies.
</P>
<P>
   For not even the most dedicated of political addicts have been
able to produce much ardor of any kind this year.
</P>
<P>
   For example, this old ragtag Texas political writer recently
rather mildly exhorted Vice President Al Gore, the soon-to-be
Democratic presidential nominee, and any and all other Democrats
not to mess with Texas in their attacks on the for-sure Republican
presidential nominee, Texas Gov. George W. Bush. As it happened,
this column ran in The Tennessean, the Nashville newspaper where
Gore once worked.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, this column inspired a fair number of Tennesseans
to e-mail their reactions to it. For some it was one thing, for
others, another and for many, all.
</P>
<P>
   But, none, not one, gave any indication the correspondent much
liked Gore. A whole bunch indicated they had little regard for me.
A lot more were especially clear they are not admirers of Bush.
And, most, by far, sure don't like Republicans. Period.
</P>
<P>
   But, none wrote of liking Gore, or of admiring him, or even of
supporting him.
</P>
<P>
   There's this, none pushed him for the No. 2 spot on his ticket.
</P>
<P>
   That makes Gore and Bush about the only politicians of note who
haven't been cited by someone as being on a list of possible
running mates for either party.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it seems the closer we get to the two candidates'
announcements of their choices of vice presidential candidates, the
longer _ certainly weirder _ these so-called lists get.
</P>
<P>
   Daily, sometimes hourly, we get speculation about who's likely
to be tapped as a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking that generates this speculation truly is wondrous.
As has been the case with Bush in every aspect of late, the
wondering about his choice is not only more publicly aired, it's
about 10 times more convoluted than the process the pundits go
through to suggest running mates Gore is likely to choose.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's pondering, of course, is pretty consistently reported as
being dominated by whether a running mate who's pro-choice or one
strongly opposed to abortion will be of more help to his own
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge, a pro-choice
Catholic, has had miles of print and hours of air time devoted to
his prospects with Bush. None of that, however, comes close to the
serious _ yes, really, honestly serious _ speculation Bush
ultimately will reject Ridge because he's physically bigger than
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   It's stuff like this that explains why already a forest's worth
of paper has been used for all the alleged ``short lists'' making
the media rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Back to Gore and Texas. As demonstrated in his late week San
Antonio visit, the veep seems to have gotten the message he will
fare far better if he can manage to beat up on Bush without totally
dissing Texas.
</P>
<P>
   That done, Texans _ especially those who live in the 18th
Congressional District _ were reminded, no matter what, some things
just never will change.
</P>
<P>
   This came in a report about the House Black Caucus joining with
President Clinton in carping about what they call the Senate's bias
in refusing to confirm some of Clinton's judicial nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saddened to make these accusations, but I will make
them,'' Democratic Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee reportedly said. ``The
United States Senate has acted racistly and with sexism.''
</P>
<P>
   Racistly?
</P>
<P>
   It may be the best of times. It, for sure, is the worst. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
