<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9170 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBO-FISK-HOMETOWN-BOS     07-21 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FISK-HOMETOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISK'S ROAD TO HALL BEGAN IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTOWN, N.H. _ There is a Fisk Field here.
</P>
<P>
   There is no neon or granite sign marking the way. In fact, there
is little around making note that this is the hometown of a
baseball Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a Fisk Field. There is a big ``F'' in the cement
walkway leading to the white house next door. But there is no
scoreboard. There are no Fisk Franks for sale. There is no
commemorative plaque noting this is the place where Carlton first
hit them out.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, it's not only Carlton Fisk's Field.
</P>
<P>
   It was just as much Calvin's and Conrad's and Cedric's and
Janet's and June's field as it ever was the field of Carlton, who
goes mostly by Pudge in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fine and attractive small field, but it's not much of a
ball field these days. The grass was scraggly and orange day lilies
brightened the backside of it on a gorgeous midsummer day a week
ago.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sign of the backstop Cecil Fisk made for his kids
and half the kids in town. There are no worn-out basepaths.
</P>
<P>
   Long gone are the days that the neighborhood kids _ the six
Fisks and the Hogancamps and the Kinsons and the rest, ``33 of
them,'' said Leona Fisk, den mother and coach and a heck of a
softball player and football thrower herself _ gathered here for
games galore to be followed by fresh milk from the Fisk's cow and
cinnamon buns.
</P>
<P>
   Long before there were memorable high school basketball nights
in tiny gyms around the state. Long before there were big pitching
and slugging performances and then catching duties in high school
and Legion ball and finally Fenway Park and Comiskey Park and
throughout the major leagues. And long before there was that most
famous home run of all, there were games, games, and more games at
Fisk Field and Gates Field and Highter's Field and other play spots
all around Charlestown, a workingman's town hard by the Connecticut
River and only several long homers from Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Carlton Fisk is to be honored with other inductees in Baseball's
Hall of Fame Class of 2000 Sunday. He will be the first player from
New Hampshire in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The road to Cooperstown started in Charlestown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he was a good athlete, but we never thought he'd be a
professional,'' said Cecil Fisk, the father, who at 87 has the same
sturdy build and rugged forearms as the son. ``It's a small town.
We never had any connection with professional sports.''
</P>
<P>
   And then one day when Cecil was in Mexico City on business _ he
put in 39 years across the river in Springfield, Vt., at Jones &AMP;
Lamson Machine Co. _ they called from home looking for his input
because the Red Sox wanted to sign Carlton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they had looked at him, but we had no idea,'' Cecil
said. ``If he had the opportunity, I said he probably should sign.
That's what he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvin before him and Conrad and Cedric after him were better
known for their baseball. What Carlton Fisk really wanted was to
play professional basketball. To line up with the Celtics and make
his fame in Boston Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball, after all, was his sport. It was the sport in a
small, New England town _ Charlestown's population is pushing 5,000
now and was about 3,000 then. Basketball drew the crowds to tiny
gyms all winter, and basketball was what stirred the fire of folks
in Charlestown and Walpole and Alstead in their heated rivalries
before they joined up in regional school districts. Baseball was a
short-season game played in front of family _ and often not even
they could make it to an afternoon game in a working town.
</P>
<P>
   Carlton Fisk had springs for legs and had the big hands and
those broad shoulders and _ no surprise here _ he really got after
the ball. He was a fierce rebounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of it is attitude,'' said Leona. ``A lot of it
is his upbringing. He had to do things around here. I think with
both of us it was play as well as you can and give 100 percent. Or
more. It all worked out for him. That's where the drive came from.
That was just him. The way he played. He played his heart out. And
he wasn't afraid to tell someone else they should be working a
little harder, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Others saw it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pudge, I don't think, knew the word stop,'' said Jim
Hogancamp, one of the neighborhood kids and a teammate in high
school. ``He had a tremendous competitive drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime basketball watchers in the state still talk about the
game Fisk played as a senior against Hopkinton in the state high
school basketball tournament in 1965. His 40 points. His
30-something rebounds against a front line that went 6-9 and 6-5 to
his 6-2 and change. Finally, Fisk fouled out. His team lost by a
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most incredible game I ever saw,'' said Ralph Silva, who
came out of Gloucester, Mass., and Springfield College just in time
to coach all the Fisk boys in soccer, basketball, and baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk went to the University of New Hampshire on a basketball
scholarship and played center on the freshmen team and played well.
He ran up against guys who also had springs in their legs and
pounded the boards. And were 6 inches taller than he was.
</P>
<P>
   He settled on baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever this kid set his mind to do, he was going to do it,''
Silva said. ``He had a tough time in the minor leagues in baseball.
He didn't hit for crap. I've still got some letters he sent. He was
pretty discouraged. `I don't know if this is the right thing for
me.' He definitely didn't think it was the right thing. He almost
walked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Red Sox and the White Sox, he did not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fisk signed with the Red Sox in 1967 and in 1969 played two
games with the big team. He came up for good late in the 1971
season and in 1972 was the first unanimous American League Rookie
of the Year after hitting .293 with 22 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   He saw his chance. And grabbed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of good ballplayers have the ability and don't get the
opportunities,'' Cecil Fisk said. ``He had the chances. And he had
the ability. He's been in the right spot at the right time, many
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 21, 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Right place. Right time.
</P>
<P>
   Game 6 of the World Series, Red Sox vs. Cincinnati Reds. Bernie
Carbo ties it in the eighth with a three-run pinch-hit home run.
Fisk comes up in the 12th inning.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you've heard what happened next.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk took a pitch from Pat Darcy and knocked it off the foul
pole in left for a game-winning homer _ but not without the help of
his body English and that of tens of thousands in Fenway Park and
countless others around New England watching on television and
listening on radio and every one of them willing the ball fair.
</P>
<P>
   Leona and Cecil Fisk and much of their family were in Fenway,
Section 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a noise,'' Leona said. ``Wow. Everyone was standing up
and screaming.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe you've seen the camera shot of Carlton Fisk jumping
and pushing the ball fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us later that picture of him probably would never
have happened,'' Cecil Fisk said. ``They said there was a big rat
in center field where the cameraman was. I guess he should have
followed the ball or had the camera going someplace else, but the
rat scared him and he left the camera and left it on. It was just
an accident that the camera stayed on him that long.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Charlestown, Dave Conant watched the home run on
television. He had to do something. He went down the street to St.
Luke's Episcopal Church and quietly slipped inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rang the bell violently for about four or five minutes,''
Conant recalled a decade ago. ``And about the time I decided I had
had enough, the bell had had enough, and the town had had enough,
there were blue flashing lights in the yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. Police told him they would have joined in the
celebration if they had realized what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   Just another landmark on the road from Charlestown to
Cooperstown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
