<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-KOREAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN'S GRAND TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin, while preparing for his debut
at this weekend's summit meeting of the wealthy nations that call
themselves the Group of 8, stopped off for state visits with
President Jiang Zemin of China and North Korea's ``Dear Leader''
Kim Jong Il. In Beijing and in Pyongyang, Putin placed public
emphasis upon the one crucial security interest that is common to
China and North Korea _ ardent opposition to America's plans for a
national missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing in particular stands to pay a high price should American
leaders plunge ahead with deployment of the contemplated missile
defense system despite its technological inadequacies.
</P>
<P>
   The mere specter of a defense against China's deterrent force of
about 20 ICBMs could oblige Chinese leaders to squander enormous
sums on increasing and modernizing their missile force.
</P>
<P>
   So Putin and Jiang indulged in elaborate rhetorical exercises to
intimate that they may be forced to form an improbable alliance
against the American hegemon in the event that US taxpayers are
bilked of $60 billion or more for a porous missile shield that will
leave Americans less secure, not more.
</P>
<P>
   In Pyongyang, Putin raised the antimissile folly to new heights.
After a two-hour chat with Kim Jong Il, the novice Russian leader
said: ``North Korea is even prepared to use exclusively the missile
technology of other countries, if it is offered rocket boosters for
peaceful space research.''
</P>
<P>
   To give Putin his due, it must be acknowledged that his
underlying brief is sound. The notion that the United States, with
its thousands of nuclear missiles, may have something to fear from
the failed state of North Korea is hardly credible.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it is ludicrous to pretend that the North Korean
communists, whose starving subjects have been eating grass, have
some rational reason to spend billions of dollars on space
research. North Korean space research is as irrational as the
deployment of an American missile defense that cannot distinguish
warheads from the decoy balloons that are sure to accompany those
missiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
