<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR22-POLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sunshine and a pole for Stewart
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long Pond, Pa. _ The rain gods smiled on Tony Stewart again
Friday and apparently helped him to his first pole position of the
Winston Cup season.
</P>
<P>
   He'll start on the pole in Sunday's Pennsylvania 500 at Pocono
Raceway after his late-afternoon qualifying run, delayed by a brief
episode of rain sprinkles, produced a track record 172.391 mph.
</P>
<P>
   He breezed around Pocono's 2.5-mile tri-oval in 52.207 seconds
to grab the pole from Rusty Wallace, who earlier had broken his own
track record with a lap of 172.157 mph.
</P>
<P>
   It began sprinkling just prior to Stewart's lap, stopping
qualifying for 10 minutes. The brief rain apparently cooled the
track and made it a tad faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get moisture in the air it creates a lot of drag,''
Stewart said. ``We learned that from the Indy car days. But the
nice thing is that the sun came back out. But with the sun, the
track temperature starts climbing again. So as soon as the
raindrops quit, I wanted to get in the car as fast as I could and
get going before the surface temperature started rising again,
which would start making the car slide around a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Stewart benefited from a New Hampshire rainstorm.
He was leading with 27 laps remaining in the 300-lap Jiffy Lube 300
when the skies opened up a second time and he was declared the
winner.
</P>
<P>
   But he's no fan of the wet stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate rain,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rain got us in the position we were in (at New Hampshire,
out of sequence on pit stops). If the first rain didn't come, we
were on the same playing field as everybody else. But with that
first rain, a bunch of guys gambled and didn't have anything to
lose by pitting. We had everything to lose by pitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't stand to see it rain. It drives me nuts. I'm usually
losing years off my life every time it rains somewhere now.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the rain played with Stewart's mindset.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard when you prepare mentally to go out and make your
lap, and then to have the rain start just about the time that
you're getting ready to go out, and have to go through that cycle
again, it created a little more anxiety than I wanted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a ride with driver Buster Auton in the pace car calmed
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said `When you're comfortable with the race track, we'll
go,''' Stewart said. ``He gave me the confidence that I knew what
the track conditions were like when I went out there, and having
the confidence to go out and do what I needed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
