<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ROTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROTH ADVANCES THE BALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 23, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A stalemate over drug benefits for Medicare recipients has been
loosened by Senator William V. Roth Jr. of Delaware with his
embrace of direct payments rather than the cumbersome and probably
unworkable House-passed measure for channeling funds through
private insurers. The principle Roth has adopted deserves support
from the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Roth, as head of the Senate Finance Committee, has broken with
many of his Republican colleagues in both houses of Congress. They
favor a plan that would subsidize private insurers to encourage
them to offer drug insurance to Medicare beneficiaries. It makes
little sense to dissociate drugs from the administration of other
forms of medical care, and it introduces an element of uncertainty
for private insurers, who would be required to absorb the risks of
such insurance rather than having that risk carried by the federal
program, as it is for other forms of care.
</P>
<P>
   The Roth proposal has a downside. Medicare recipients would have
to choose between drug coverage and a reduction in support for home
care _ a proposal that could be modified in the course of Senate
debate on the matter. That debate assumes that Senate Republican
leadership would allow it to take place, an uncertain proposition.
</P>
<P>
   The coverage would also be only partial, covering only half of
the first $4,000 in drug costs and 80 percent above that figure.
The effects of that structure would weigh more heavily on
lower-income elderly, but those figures, too, could be adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans will do well, before and after this fall's election,
to consider the political implications of Roth's move. He is
running for his sixth term in the Senate against a strong challenge
from Delaware Governor Thomas R. Carper. Medicare, and especially
coverage for medications, is a major national issue on which
Democrats, a minority in both House and Senate, have more
aggressively supported expanded coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the political considerations for Roth, he has
changed the atmosphere in which the issue of drug coverage will be
fought out in Congress. That is a significant contribution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
