<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9179 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-BACTERIA-BO     07-21 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BACTERIA-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (For release Monday, July 24, 2000) 
TOO CLEAN? &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   To warn us about the dangers of disease-causing bacteria that
don't succumb to antibiotics, scientists have started referring to
a future ``post-antibiotic'' era that will have some of the horrors
of the pre-antibiotic era. This may sound like scaremongering, but
the problem is serious enough that the World Health Organization
earlier this year sounded an international alarm, and in Atlanta
July 17 a Tufts microbiologist criticized the increasing use of
antibacterial cleaning agents that could foster
antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   This is the paradox behind all the antibacterial hand soaps,
dish detergents, cutting boards, and toothbrush handles being sold:
While buyers assume they are protecting themselves and their
children from infections, they may just be encouraging development
of super-germs that brush off the most dependable antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   The antibacterial cleansers have that effect, at least, in
laboratory studies by Stuart Levy of Tufts. The American Medical
Association is so concerned that it has asked the US Food and Drug
Administration to speed up its rule-making process for the
antibacterial soaps. The FDA has yet to determine either whether
they have a real health benefit or whether they encourage resistant
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Levy sees another downside to the antibacterials. Studies in
Europe have shown that children growing up in overly antiseptic
environments are more likely to suffer from allergies and asthma _
their immune systems fail to develop properly.
</P>
<P>
   Levy advises using such traditional cleansers as alcohol,
bleach, and hydrogen peroxide, which leave no antibacterial
residue, the great selling point of the new soaps. Except for those
with compromised immune systems, antibacterials are not needed.
</P>
<P>
   No one claims that antibacterials are the major factor in the
growing phenomenon of resistant bacteria. Scientists place more
blame on doctors' overuse of antibiotics and, to a lesser extent,
the use of antibiotics in livestock feed. But consumers are being
sweet-talked into buying antibacterial products that may do more
harm than good. Levy's message of restraint _ ``Go back to Coke
Classic'' _ is sound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
