<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Savannah lifters make presence felt
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Orleans _ Here, today, are the U.S. Olympic weightlifting
trials. They could have saved some travel expenses by hijacking the
event to another funky southern tourist hangout.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 37 muscled men and women (following three injury
withdrawals), nine do their grunt work for Team Savannah. Six years
after the city pledged tax dollars to a gym devoted to lifting and
hired Michael Cohen to ride herd over it, Savannah has become the
sport's blazing hot-spot.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the nine are home-grown. Top female seed? From
Savannah. Top male seed? Ditto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think one city has had that many going to the
trials,'' said Cohen, the U.S. women's Olympic coach.
</P>
<P>
   Put an asterisk by his claim, because all previous trials have
been testosterone festivals. The women have their coming-out party
in Sydney as the latest sport to eliminate its gender-specific tag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finally going to the Olympics,'' said Cheryl Haworth.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Haworth has been waiting forever. The 17-year-old
heavyweight barely had hoisted her first barbell at Cohen's gym
when the last Games rolled around. Haworth so dominated in lead-up
competition this year that the qualifying-points total she carries
into today's meet makes her place on the U.S. roster as guaranteed
as a wild time on Bourbon Street. Yet Haworth does not plan toease
off. She wants an American record.
</P>
<P>
   That's okay with Cohen. At the same time, he will watch her
closely _ and nervously. ``If she shows the littlest twinge,''
Cohen said, she's done. The U.S. women secured the maximum four
slots in Sydney by taking sixth at last year's World Championships.
(One place lower, and they would have sent only three.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet another Georgian, Robin Goad of Newnan, begins today's heavy
lifting in third, just above a Savannah move-in, Cara Heads-Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Only two U.S. men are headed Down Under, a consequence of their
dreadful 29th place at the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Chaplin III of Savannah sits atop the men's standings.
</P>
<P>
   No contestant is more dogged than Wes Barnett, an Olympian twice
over. A cancerous tumor two years ago damaged the optic nerve of
his right eye, leaving him with 20-800 vision. But, entering today
in third place, he is close enough to envision another Olympic
experience for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
