<HEADER>
A9186 &Cx1f; tth-z
u i BC-PEARLJAM-ROSKILDE-SPI     07-21 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEARLJAM-ROSKILDE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ONE CAUSE CITED IN PEARL JAM CONCERT DEATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By D. PARVAZ  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Danish police recommend that no criminal charges be pressed
against Pearl Jam for the nine deaths during the Seattle band's
June 30 performance at the Roskilde Festival.
</P>
<P>
   In a 10-page report filed Wednesday, Roskilde Deputy Chief
Constable Bent Rungstrom said he cannot judge who is to blame for
the tragic incident.
</P>
<P>
   However, stories circulating online quote the report as saying
that Pearl Jam is ``morally responsible'' and that the band incited
``violent behavior'' among audience members.
</P>
<P>
   British music magazine NME posted a story saying Pearl Jam is
being ``slammed'' for ``whipping the crowd into a frenzy.'' Similar
reports have been posted on the www.dotmusic.com and Netscape
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Drachmann, a reporter for Politiken, a daily national
newspaper in Denmark, says that the report makes no such
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the report only refers to Pearl Jam twice, once to
place the band at the Orange stage at the time of the incident and
again to state that Pearl Jam typically gets its audience highly
excited. Drachmann says the term ``morally responsible'' does not
appear anywhere in the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general conclusion is that you cannot find one single
explanation for what happened,'' says Drachmann. He further
translates Rungstrom as saying that ``It's my opinion that the
accident was caused by several unlucky circumstances occurring at
the same time, with the behavior of the audience as the most
important factor.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``unlucky circumstances'' listed in the report are weather,
the band's ability to excite a crowd, alcohol and drug use by the
audience and sound quality _ referring to the fact that at one
point, some of the speakers cut out, causing people to rush toward
the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have some critical remarks but it wouldn't be fair to say
that they write that Pearl Jam is responsible. He says he doesn't
know if this behavior (moshing, crowd surfing, rushing the stage,
etc.) is characteristic (of these concerts) or if it is a new
development in youth culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The most critical comment directed toward Pearl Jam in the
report: ``The band Pearl Jam is according to explanation from
witnesses known for almost to be appealing the audience to behave
in a frenzy.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Drachmann says public response to the deaths as well
as the report in Denmark have been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a general discussion in Denmark that's very much like
what the police here said, that it was just bad luck. Others say
that that's too easy to say _ nine people are dead.''
</P>
<P>
   People are more concerned with preventing further incidents like
the one at the rather than finding a single party to blame, he
adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That festival has been going on for 30 years ... we've never
seen anything like this ... we have never seen anyone die at a rock
'n' roll concert in Denmark. That's why it's so shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Jam manager Kelly Curtis fired off an angry response to
stories that the band is being held ``morally responsible'' by
Danish police. His statement, which can be found at
www.sonymusic.com/artists/PearlJam/rumorpit/release7.html, reads:
</P>
<P>
   ``Pearl Jam are well known for their exciting live shows, but
they have never, in their ten-year history of performing, `appealed
for violent behavior.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Further, while `crowd surfing' is an audience `phenomenon'
closely connected with many rock bands who are currently
performing, it is not one that is encouraged by Pearl Jam.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the band's manager, I find it hard to believe that after
all that has transpired, the band's devastation over the tragedies
that occurred at the Roskilde Festival during their performance,
and their long history of attention to safety, that anyone would
assign `moral responsibility' to them. That, I find `appalling' and
ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Jam has always, and will continue to do everything
possible to ensure that their shows, and shows that they are part
of, are safe and enjoyable for those who attend.''
</P>
<P>
   The band is gearing up for the U.S leg of its tour, which kicks
off in the first week of August. Both band and management were
unavailable for further comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
