<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SURPLUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURPLUS PERILS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, July 24, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rising surpluses have prompted calls for increased programs and
tax cuts based on hope that optimistic forecasts will continue to
underestimate future windfalls. Political leaders should remain
wary of these forecasts, as Alan Greenspan, Federal Reserve
chairman, again urged them on Thursday. They will do even more if
they broaden their perspectives to include persistent trade and
payments deficits that are tolerable now but could presage a
serious problem.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's announcement of the largest one-month trade deficit
ever, $31 billion, was particularly disappointing because it
included a drop in exports, probably reflecting the high value of
the dollar that makes American goods and services more expensive
for foreign customers. In the short run US consumers benefit from
lower prices. But the longer-term issue is complicated by the
return of those dollars spent on exports in the form of investment
in or loans to the US economy, generating interest and dividend
payments to foreign investors at the same time they provide
employment opportunities for Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Economists Martin and Kathleen Feldstein have pointed out that
the net costs of these payments is now about $1 billion per day,
with no indication of any reversal.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the budget surpluses _ and the federal debt. About $3.7
trillion is owed to the public, which includes foreign holdings of
US Treasury bonds, notes, and bills. Using significant portions of
surpluses to pay down some of those obligations, as Greenspan
pressed for in his congressional testimony, would ease the effects
of any reversal in foreigners' willingness to invest in this
country. It would also reduce Treasury demand for credit in
competition with private sector needs. And it would provide more
leeway for Congress and future administrations to counter any
downturn through deficit financing of programs to restimulate the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Debt reduction is like putting money in the bank. It is worth
the commitment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
