<HEADER>
A9190 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-BROPEN-RND222-COX     07-21 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-RND222-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Challengers blink; Tiger plays through
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   St. Andrews, Scotland _ After the first day of the 129th British
Open at the Old Course, understudies Ernie Els and Steve Flesch
were allowed to step on the stage and deliver a few lines.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's play, the star was back in the spotlight.
Different major championship, different ocean, but same story. The
Tiger Woods Show is back.
</P>
<P>
   Leading a major championship for the sixth round in a row, the
24-year-old Woods on Friday moved halfway to achieving the final
leg of a career Grand Slam. With a 6-under-par 66, Woods assumed
the 36-hole lead in the 129th British Open by three strokes at
11-under 133.
</P>
<P>
   After Woods' 15-shot win in the U.S. Open last month, the
situation at the home of golf is starting to feel familiar. Woods,
who trailed South African Els by one stroke at the start of play
Friday, gradually pulled away from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Told that he's ``making it look easy,'' Woods said, ``That's a
nice compliment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When anybody is playing well, the game seems easier,'' he
said, ``but when you're playing out there under these conditions, I
guarantee you, it's not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   If others might term the tournament over, Woods said, ``I don't
have the trophy sitting next to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the wind continues to be a nonfactor, another Open might
be nothing but a race for second. American David Toms, with a 67,
is Woods' closest challenger at 8-under 136.
</P>
<P>
   Els, after a 66 Thursday, slipped to a 72 and is at 6-under 138
along with Phil Mickelson (66), Fred Couples (68), Denmark's Thomas
Bjorn (69) and Tom Lehman (70).
</P>
<P>
   The cut came at even-par 144. A year ago at Carnoustie it was
12-over 154.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is on pace to both rout the field again and break the
British Open record of 18-under-par 270, set in 1990 by Nick Faldo.
He has not made a bogey since the 10th hole of his third round at
Pebble Beach, a stretch of 62 consecutive holes. Nor has he been in
one of the Old Course's 112 bunkers over two days.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately, Jack Nicklaus finished what might have been his
last British Open round just as Woods was walking behind the first
hole after a few practice putts. The winner of 18 pro majors and
Woods' prime career target missed the cut with 77-73_150. While
Nicklaus roots for Woods to break his records, even he is starting
to wish for more suspense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's good for the game, but he has to have challengers for the
whole thing to be right,'' Nicklaus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad story if there isn't any. . . . Right now he's the
dominant player. Everybody has thrown up a white flag and
surrendered.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
