<HEADER>
A9191 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-(TRIMS)     07-21 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK AND CLINTON HOPEFUL ABOUT SUCCESS OF TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG with WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ The Israeli peace delegation's mood shifted from
dire to hopeful Friday as officials outside the secluded Camp David
said that Prime Minister Ehud Barak believes the chances for the
peace summit meeting's success have improved.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, Dalia Itzik, the environment minister, said that
Barak told her in a phone call Friday that the odds for securing a
peace agreement were now 60-40.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton also sounded upbeat Friday as he told
reporters in Okinawa, where he is attending a meeting of leading
industrial nations, that he was ``hopeful,'' and aides said he
might scale back his schedule in Japan to return to Camp David
earlier on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior Palestinian official, Abu Mazen, who left Camp
David earlier in the week to attend his son's wedding in the West
Bank, reported no lifted spirits among the Palestinians. Speaking
on Voice of Palestine radio, he offered a somewhat depressed
account of the large gaps that remain between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Given the complete news blackout on the negotiations, it is
impossible to know what altered the Israeli and U.S. leaders'
outlooks, or indeed how much they may have improved after the
summit meeting nearly crashed and burned on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials disclosed Friday that the two sides were
entertaining a U.S. proposal that involved a limited sharing of
sovereignty in East Jerusalem, and that Jerusalem had been the main
stumbling block that nearly derailed the talks for good.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. proposal was reportedly placed on the table before
Clinton left for Japan early Thursday morning. And even if the
details were reported accurately, it was not clear whether further
discussion on the proposal shifted the tenor of the summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It remains very hard going,'' said Richard Boucher, the State
Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the talk about Jerusalem caused a flurry of heated
commentary in Israel and the Palestinian territories. If Israel
accepted sharing sovereignty, even in a limited fashion, that would
represent a considerable concession from the previous Israeli
position _ that the Palestinians could control but not own some
Arab neighborhoods in the contested city.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials, while cautioning against debating shards
of leaked information, said the concession as represented did not
appear to be considerable enough. They have contended from the
start that they are demanding full sovereignty of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   According to officials, the Israeli and Palestinian delegations
were engaged Friday in more substantial conversations than they had
expected to undertake in Clinton's absence. They stopped talking
about catching up on their sleep or hovering in a holding pattern
until his return.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat met for the first
time in five days on Thursday night. It was informal, but, given
the acrimony that had accompanied the near collapse of the talks,
it was a sign of progress that they took their places on either
side of Secretary of State Madeleine Albright for a dinner. They
made ``dinner conversation,'' according to Boucher, and the mood
was neither jovial nor acrimonious.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare sign of attempted conviviality Friday night, U.S.,
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators played a pick-up basketball
game on mixed teams. The leaders were invited but did not join the
game.
</P>
<P>
   As part of what appeared to be a campaign to prepare the public,
Itzik, the minister who spoke with Barak, communicated his
sentiment that Israel would now have to choose between painful
concessions and a future of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The painful concession debated in Israel Friday involved a
reported plan for granting limited sovereignty in Jerusalem to the
Palestinians. Israeli newspapers, radio and television reported
Friday that Barak, who previously said he would never consider
dividing Jerusalem, was now contemplating joint sovereignty in some
areas of the holy city.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One newspaper, Yedioth Ahronoth, said Barak had agreed to a full
transfer of some Palestinian neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Michael Melchior, a Cabinet minister who has been serving
as an Israeli spokesman in the United States during the talks, said
that Barak was considering ``administration-plus'' of Palestinian
neighborhoods in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about administration-plus, perhaps also with some symbols
of sovereignty, of joint sovereignty'' in Palestinian neighborhoods
outside the Old City, ``at the edge of Jerusalem,'' like Shuafat,
the refugee camp, Melchior said. ``This is something that I think
we can accept.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's Cabinet secretary, Yitzhak Herzog, said later that
Melchior was not speaking officially and not fully apprised of all
the details of the U.S. proposal.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Israeli journalists, based on background briefings from
officials here, reported two variations on a plan for Jerusalem.
Both involve shrinking and expanding Jerusalem in a kind of land
swap with the Palestinians, whereby Jewish settlements in the West
Bank that abut the city would be added to a reconfigured Jewish
Jerusalem while Palestinian neighborhoods would be given to the
Palestinians _ fully or partially, depending on the version.
</P>
<P>
   The Old City, home to Christians, Muslims and Jews, would be
frozen as is and the question of its status deferred.
</P>
<P>
   These could be trial balloons, meant to sensitize the Israeli
public to less far-reaching concessions. But they also could
reflect accurately a U.S. compromise proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Yossi Beilin, the leftist justice minister, hinted Friday that
Jerusalem might indeed be divided and said that Israelis would be
better off with a reconfigured, more Jewish capital city. The world
and the Palestinians would recognize an expanded West Jerusalem as
the capital of the Jewish homeland, ``an achievement we have not
reached to date,'' he said in a newspaper interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many people truly believed that we would get more than
West Jerusalem?'' Beilin said. ``The warped myth that has been
built in regard to Jerusalem's borders, which the right wing also
knows is incorrect, must not bind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Beilin was referring to what many Jerusalemites acknowledge to
be the divided-ground reality of Jerusalem, which in some ways
defies the legal reality of Israel's annexation of eastern, Arab
neighborhoods after the 1967 war. But despite this reality, the
city is very segregated; 70 percent of Israelis surveyed said in a
poll released Friday said that they oppose any concessions on
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by the polls, opposition leaders stepped up attacks
on Barak for even considering the handover of large Arab
neighborhoods as part of a comprehensive peace pact.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``With what Beilin and others are saying, Barak appears to be
preparing public opinion for this,'' Ehud Olmert, the mayor of
Jerusalem and a leader of the rightist Likud party, said in an
interview. ``You have to give him credit: He is the prime minister,
and when he is finished making his case the opposition will no
longer be 70 percent. But I don't see how he can win a referendum,
or an election.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanan Ashrawi, a Palestinian spokeswoman, suggested that the
Israelis were getting ahead of themselves and conducting an
internal debate. She said that Melchior was talking about conceding
outlying parts of Jerusalem, ``which are ours anyway,'' to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be something new on the face of it, but when you
look at the substance there is nothing new,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9192 &Cx1f; tdt-z
