<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV23-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKAWAY IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 23, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news last week that the Greenland ice sheet is melting into
the ocean at the rate of 50 billion tons of water a year was a
sobering reminder that Alan Greenspan's ability to contrive yet
another soft landing is not the only thing we have to worry about
heading into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   There is global warming, too _ in this case nine inches added to
the water level over the last hundred years, according to an
article in Science magazine. And who knows at what rate in the
future?
</P>
<P>
   Happily, recent experience in the matter of controlling
atmospheric pollution is as reassuring as has been the long boom of
the past 20 years, nearly.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons to think that we possess the know-how
necessary to keep in check greenhouse gas emissions, or to
accommodate ourselves to those aspects of climate change that it
would be prohibitively expensive to prevent.
</P>
<P>
   This know-how consists, of course, of the technology of markets.
More than 30 years ago economist J. H. Dales wrote in ``Pollution,
Property and Prices'': ``If it is feasible to establish a market to
implement a policy, no policy-maker can afford to be without one.''
Today the consensus that government-maintained markets offer the
best hope of regulating many forms of pollution is becoming global
_ at least among the experts.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A here is Title IV of the Clean Air Act Amendments of
1990, a ``cap and trade'' program that has made a good start at
reducing the sulfur dioxide emissions that are key contributors to
acid rain _ a prototype for a system to control the emission of
greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to fix an aggregate amount of pollution, assign and
distribute rights to firms, and let them trade permits among
themselves, thereby creating maximum flexibility in choosing how
and where to control emissions within industry as a whole. The
alternative is old-fashioned _ and far more expensive _
command-and-control regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The law came about in response to pressure from environmental
groups, Northeast states, and a Canadian government worried about
the effect of acid rain from coal-fired Midwest power plants on
down-wind forests and marine life.
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush, who had campaigned on a promise to
be an ``environmental president,'' and his chief of staff, former
New Hampshire Governor John Sununu, teamed up with Democratic
Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine to overcome the
opposition of Representative John Dingell (D-Mich.) and pass into
law a system of tradable sulfur dioxide emissions permits within a
stringent cap.
</P>
<P>
   It is working. Five years after going into effect, the statute
has cut acid rain in the Adirondacks by 26 percent from levels of
the previous decade. Sulfur dioxide levels per unit of output have
fallen 57 percent. (Nitrogen oxides, a big part of the acid rain
problem, were not addressed by the law.)
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the state of New York recently has engaged in a
silly and spiteful act that undermines the efficacy of the
cap-and-trade approach. Worried that progress against acid rain is
progressing too slowly in certain areas, environmental groups have
badgered the legislature into restricting participation in the
emissions market by New York firms.
</P>
<P>
   A new law levies fines on firms equal to their profits from the
sale of emission permits to power companies in 14 states: New
Jersey, Maryland, Pennsylvania, Delaware, Ohio, Michigan, Indiana,
Illinois, Wisconsin, Kentucky, Tennessee, West Virginia, Virginia,
and North Carolina. The effect is indeed to cut sulfur dioxide
emissions somewhat overall, but at the cost of disproportionately
raising the price of power in New York.
</P>
<P>
   What is unsettling is the politics of the breakaway. Republican
New York Governor George E. Pataki signed the measure into law.
Meanwhile, a bill in the US Senate sponsored by Daniel Patrick
Moynihan and Charles Schumer would mandate a nationwide 70 percent
cut in sulfur dioxide emmissions, as opposed to the 50 percent
reduction required by the 1990 law. Such a sudden change would
effectively confiscate half the permits already issued for 2005 and
after.
</P>
<P>
   At the base of the New York law is a misapprehension: that
companies buy the permits instead of spending money on new plants
and equipment that would emit less pollutants. In fact they do
both. Upwind states invest $3.3 billion in scrubbers, lower-sulfer
fuel, and other changes, producing 5.1 million tons less of
atmospheric sulfur dioxide than the law allowed, according to a
critique of the New Yort statute by Paul Joskow and Danny Ellerman
of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. The two are
co-authors, with Richard Schmallensee, Juan-Pablo Montero, and
Elizabeth Bailey, of ``Markets for Clean Air: The US Acid Rain
Program,'' an authoritative account of developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to keep your eye on the ball in addressing
environmental problems,'' says Joskow. Maybe, he says, New York is
more worried about meeting National Ambient Air Quality Standards
than about acid rain. In that case more cost-effective,
region-specific measures should be considered.
</P>
<P>
   Experts may understand cap-and-trade programs well enough, but
politicians have been slow to grasp the fact that, like any other
market, they won't work if the government constantly tampers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally found a program that works,'' says Joskow, who was
one of the architects of the 1990 law, ``and now we're gonna screw
it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Better not. Remember, the water is rising.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
