<HEADLINE>
WAXING ELOQUENT ON CD BURNERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: I bought a CD writer to make CDs from our 600
LPs. I am able to get the records to play through the computer
speakers.MDNM/ but still haven't been able to figure out how to get
LP tracks onto the CD. _ Stacks o' Wax
</P>
<P>
   Dear Stacks: When you hear how incredibly easy this is, you're
going to wonder why you just spent $18 for that new Backstreet Boys
CD, which cost maybe a quarter to manufacture. OK, make it 26 cents
if you feel obligated to pay the band what it's worth.
</P>
<P>
   And before all the editors and lawyers in the building have a
fit, let me remind you that making unauthorized copies of
copyrighted material is illegal, so whatever you do, don't
photocopy this column.
</P>
<P>
   Walk on any college campus, and you'll find hundreds of kids
churning out bootleg CDs on the computers their folks got them to
help them pass English 101. There's a whole network of Internet
sites devoted to storing tracks off popular albums.
</P>
<P>
   The band Metallica got so cheesed off by all of this that it
actually sued Napster, a music-lovers' Web site where _ entirely
coincidentally _ naughty boys and girls can find ways to download
music tracks from each others' computers. Metallica claimed
copyright infringement, but I still think it was the only way they
could make it back into ``Rolling Stone.''
</P>
<P>
   Copying an entire CD is a no-brainer. Your CD-burner software
makes a disc image from the music CD, then it writes the image to a
blank CD-R, which costs a buck or less. If you want only certain
tracks, you have to do a little more work.
</P>
<P>
   Your burner software probably has the capability to take a
single CD track, remember what disc it came from, then prompt you
for it during the recording phase. If you don't want to shuffle all
those CDs, use CD ripper software, which takes individual tracks
and turns them into either uncompressed (.Wav) or compressed (MP3)
audio files on your hard drive. You then drag and drop them into
your burner software in the order you want. As your CD is being
recorded, the .Wavs or MP3s are converted into the standard CD
audio format.
</P>
<P>
   LPs are a little more work. You've already figured out that you
need to connect your stereo system's tape-out to the line-in jack
on the sound card. Tweak your sound-card software so that it
records with the highest quality, then use .Wav-recorder software
to capture the song as a file.
</P>
<P>
   You can use something as simple as the Windows Sound Recorder,
but there are shareware products that do a better job. I like CFB
Software's LPRecorder and LPRipper, both $20. The recorder makes a
single .Wav file from a side of the LP, and the ripper separates
the tracks into individual files. Check out the demos at
www.cfbsoftware.com.au. Just don't be surprised if you hear from
Metallica's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: I have tried unsuccessfully to change and/or
delete the Windows Critical Update Notification from my Scheduled
Tasks program. It just keeps reappearing every day. If flattery
gets me a quicker response, I enjoy your column immensely. _
Fawning Fan
</P>
<P>
   Dear Fan: I can't imagine why anybody would want to disable
anything as mind-bogglingly useful as the update notification, but
open up the Scheduled Tasks window, right-click on the update task,
select Properties from the menu, then uncheck the ``Enable''
checkbox. Now you'll never know when Microsoft has fixed the bug
that lets anybody on the Internet use your credit card. Happy? &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Dr. Emilio Bombay spends all of his time these days looking for
Go-Go's MP3s. Everyone except Metallica fans can write to him at
drbombay\Nstar-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth Star-Telegram,
Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: 390-7257. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com1.)nn
</P>
</TEXT>
