<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9198 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GAPACIFIC-FUTURE-COX     07-21 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAPACIFIC-FUTURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia-Pacific puts down new roots
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Can the prince of plywood go toe-to-toe with the likes
of Mr. Whipple?
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific thinks so. In a surprise move earlier this week,
Chairman and Chief Executive Pete Correll unleashed a major change
in direction for the Atlanta-based forest products giant. After 73
years of churning out lumber, pulp and other commodities,
Georgia-Pacific wants to flex its muscle in supermarkets and
Wal-Mart stores across the globe.
</P>
<P>
   In an $11 billion deal that would make it the world's largest
maker of paper towels and bathroom tissue, Georgia-Pacific plans to
buy rival Fort James. The merger would blow consumer products giant
Kimberly-Clark out of the top spot and team Brawny and Quilted
Northern brands with Georgia-Pacific's Sparkle and Angel Soft.
</P>
<P>
   Some tissue operations would be sold to help alleviate antitrust
concerns, but if the merger goes through as planned,
Georgia-Pacific would have nearly half the tissue market in North
America. And that would take the company right where Correll has
been steering it for several years _ in the faces of retail
shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we're going is down the value chain. We've built
Georgia-Pacific as a raw-material-based commodity seller, and over
the past several years we've been moving toward a marketing-based
organization with brands,'' Correll said.
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit of the acquisition is that Georgia-Pacific would
be less prone to the ups and downs of prices in the pulp and lumber
businesses, Correll said. With Fort James' business, one-third of
Georgia-Pacific's profit would come from the steady market of
tissue and paper towels. (As one analyst pointed out, toilet
paper's not going out of style.)
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts didn't immediately warm to the
new-and-improved Georgia-Pacific. Some said the consumer focus is a
bit of a stretch for a company that built an empire on pine and
paneling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, the thing we appreciated most about G-P was its
steadfast focus _ big, commodity businesses...,'' said analyst Mark
Connelly of Credit Suisse First Boston. ``...That made G-P stock
less risky than some of the big players, who diversified into all
sorts o square off in a marketing arena that has made a household
icon of grocer George Whipple and his ``Please, don't squeeze the
Charmin'' ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been somewhat embarrassed ...that people don't understand
how well we run our tissue business,'' Correll told analysts in New
York. The company has focused so much on outlining its financial
strategies of paying down debt, repurchasing stock and issuing
dividends that it has neglected to talk much about business
strategies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, the company has bragging rights. Georgia-Pacific
has steadily taken market share from the top players since it got
into the branded tissue business in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is price. Angel Soft bathroom tissue and Sparkle
paper towels typically cost less than the top-selling brands.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's consistent growth couldn't have happened
without some marketing smarts, Correll noted. Georgia-Pacific hired
grocery store specialist Mike Burandt to launch its consumer tissue
sales. And marketing manager Rob Lorys has boosted the Sparkle
brand with the ``Healthsmart'' campaign, which gave it an
antibacterial spin. Beyond that, Georgia-Pacific's strength is its
relationship with retailers such as Wal-Mart, its biggest tissue
customer. About half its tissue business is driven by the
``big-box'' retailers, which like mass quantities of goods in
multiunit packages.
</P>
<P>
   Years of feeding Home Depot and Lowe's with big displays of
building materials has taught Georgia-Pacific how to catch the eye
of the consumer, Correll said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If tissue products were still being bought four rolls to a
bundle in your local grocery store, I would be scared to death to
compete with Procter &AMP; Gamble and Kimberly-Clark,'' Correll said.
``But you put them in a Target or a Wal-Mart or a Sam's (Club), you
bet we can compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't become the largest supplier to Home Depot...without
understanding retailing,'' Correll said.
</P>
<P>
   He'll continue taking that message on the road next week,
speaking to analysts and institutional investors, which make up
three-fourths of the company's shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The other part of the new strategy is getting rid of businesses
that don't fit the consumer focus.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific, founded in 1927 in a lumberyard in Augusta,
plans to sell 5 million acres of timberlands to Seattle-based Plum
Creek Timber Co.
</P>
<P>
   The company hasn't identified other operations it will sell, but
some analysts suspect the company's massive office paper business
will take a cut on the manufacturing end.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to have to let go of businesses that have been
their babies...if this is really going to work,'' said analyst
Linda Lieberman of Bear Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific will certainly hang onto the distribution end of
the business, which it picked up through its acquisition of
Unisource Worldwide last year.
</P>
<P>
   Unisource's fleet of red trucks, branded with the
Georgia-Pacific name, has given the company an invaluable education
on consumer demand in delivering goods to Office Depot, Staples and
other big retailers, Correll said.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how these moves will affect the company's large
building products business. Georgia-Pacific is the country's
largest maker of plywood and the second-largest lumber producer.
It's also a leading maker of gypsum products.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the company is going to keep its dominant place in
the aisles of Home Depot and Lowe's, where towering stacks of wood
products are emblazoned with the Georgia-Pacific logo.
</P>
<P>
   Correll said he will pursue products that can be branded with
the company's name on store shelves and likely weed out the no-name
raw materials that end up in other manufacturers' goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The middle American customer _ the guy who drives a pickup
truck and stays at Days Inn and shops at Wal-Mart and Home Depot...
is developing a unique relationship with (Georgia-Pacific),''
Correll said. ``And we're going to follow that customer through the
mass retail chain with a lot of value-added products.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
