<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-FRIDGE-CHINA-$ADV23-2     07-21 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIDGE-CHINA-$ADV23-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CHINA, A MANAGEMENT MAVERICK BUILDS A BRAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   QINGDAO, China _ At first, you notice the balloons. Thousands of
them, lining the sides of the road from the airport. Tethered at
the end of long strings, they bob and weave, the name Haier
emblazoned on each side. Then you notice the road signs, which say
Haier Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   You pass the Haier Industrial Park, with its sprawling factories
and a skyscraper with a sign on the roof that also says Haier. Once
in Qingdao, there are still more balloons and billboards. A giant
lighted Haier sign twinkles from the far side of the city's
crescent-shaped bay.
</P>
<P>
   To pay a call on the local Communist Party boss, you go to the
modern city hall, where the lobby has been transformed into a
showroom for Haier's refrigerators, dishwashers, personal
computers, mobile phones and flat-screen television sets.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Qingdao is a company town understates the degree to
which a single corporation, the Haier Group, has imprinted itself
on the landscape. Qingdao may be most famous as the home of
Tsingtao beer. But when you spy the brewery's red, green and blue
logo on a sign or storefront, it is a bit like finding an image of
Deng Xiaoping in a sea of Mao posters.
</P>
<P>
   Haier's exuberant self-promotion _ even more showy than usual
during a recent trade show here _ reflects the ambitions of its
chief executive, Zhang Ruimin. In an interview, Zhang said his
determination to put the Haier name everywhere was inspired less by
heroic images of Chinese leaders than by the brand marketing
practiced by Western corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinese companies have a problem because the label `Made in
China' means low quality and low price,'' Zhang said. ``In 1996, we
started exporting products under our own brand name. We were told
it wouldn't work, but we insisted. Now we're successful with the
Haier name all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Haier Group, a sprawling enterprise ultimately
controlled by the city government here, has become China's largest
appliance maker, with sales of $3.2 billion last year. It is also
one of China's largest exporters, selling $1.4 billion of products
in 160 countries. This year, it opened a $30 million refrigerator
factory in Camden, S.C. _ becoming one of the few Chinese companies
to have an American beachhead.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang's overseas focus might make sense, given the cutthroat
price war raging in China. On July 14, one of Haier's main rivals,
Guangdong Kelon Electrical Holdings, warned that its first-half
profit would be lower than expected because of the price pressure.
With deflation still ravaging the Chinese economy, stores are full
of unsold appliances.
</P>
<P>
   But why make fridges in South Carolina when China is much
cheaper? Zhang said he wants Americans to think of Haier as an
American company. Designing and making products in the United
States, he said, will allow Haier to be more responsive to American
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an era of globalization, you can't separate domestic and
international markets,'' Zhang explained. ``We've got to learn how
to compete with General Electric and Whirlpool on their home turf.
Otherwise, we'll lose the Chinese market.''
</P>
<P>
   Such confidence _ not to mention worldliness _ is rare in a
Chinese executive. It is even more remarkable from one who spent
his career in the parochial confines of the Qingdao municipal
government. At 51, Zhang has become a symbol of how Chinese
businessmen can remake themselves to meet the global economy's
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rank him as the Jack Welch of China,'' said Fred Hu,
chief Asian economist for Goldman, Sachs. ``In a country that has
been dominated by central planning and state control, he really
stands out.''
</P>
<P>
   T.L. Tsim, a consultant who studies Chinese state enterprises,
says marketing like Haier's is crucial to the country's
development. ``What China needs today are brand-name products,'' he
said. ``It takes years of work and millions of dollars of
investment.''
</P>
<P>
   By creating one of China's first genuine brands, Zhang himself
has become a marquee attraction. He is invited to speak at
conferences here and abroad. His views are sought by government
officials and journalists. And the story of how he built Haier from
the ruins of a state-owned factory has become a legend _ a
businessman's equivalent of the Long March.
</P>
<P>
   The short version: In 1984, Zhang was asked to run the Qingdao
General Refrigerator Factory, a lethargic, nearly bankrupt plant
where erratically paid, demoralized workers turned out shoddy
products.
</P>
<P>
   The Haier name, adopted in 1991, is a Chinese approximation of
Liebherr, a German appliance maker that supplied technology to the
factory in its early days.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang was not a likely candidate to produce a turnaround. A
bureaucrat who missed out on college because of the Cultural
Revolution, he worked his way up the Qingdao hierarchy in
anonymity. But he also devoured Western management books, which
taught him heretical ideas like the unfairness of paying every
worker the same wage, no matter his ability.
</P>
<P>
   Early in Zhang's tenure at the company, a customer complained
about a broken refrigerator, prompting the boss to stalk through
the factory pulling out 76 defective ones. He piled them up and
handed sledgehammers to the workers who had assembled them. At his
signal, they all set upon the fridges, reducing them to shards.
</P>
<P>
   That singular act of destruction impressed on employees that
poor quality would no longer be acceptable. Zhang has reinforced
the message with an aggressive Western-style quality-control
program. ``We cannot expect to smash refrigerators every day,'' he
said. ``But actually, I think about doing it every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Zhang had improved the quality of Haier's products, he set
about exporting them to every corner of the world. Starting in
developing countries and then to developed markets, Haier now has
62 distributors and 30,000 sales outlets. Its small refrigerators
are especially popular in hotel minibars; it has a 25 percent share
of the small refrigerator market in the United States.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Haier says its exports and a diversified line that runs to 9,000
goods in 42 categories have allowed it to avoid the downdraft in
domestic prices that has afflicted its rivals. Because Haier's
shares are listed in Shanghai _ where financial disclosure is not
as rigorous as in Hong Kong _ analysts say it is difficult for
outsiders to assess the impact falling prices have had on Haier's
performance. ``It's hard to imagine Haier has escaped it,'' said
Charles Cheung, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Haier would like to list its shares outside China. But it has
put off its plans because of volatile Asian markets and the need to
streamline its baffling amalgam of dozens of holding companies and
joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
   When Haier does make its pitch, analysts say, it will have to
answer some hard questions. First, why is it building factories
overseas? For all of Zhang's explanations, analysts say that it is
squandering its advantage as a low-cost producer.
</P>
<P>
   Second, why does Haier need a soup-to-nuts product line?
Guangdong Kelon makes refrigerators, air-conditioners and washing
machines. Zhang wants to supply every electrical appliance in the
household. Doing that while maintaining quality is tricky.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Haier branched into pharmaceuticals. Zhang did
so because he is convinced that biotechnology will be one of the
great industries of the 21st century. But he acknowledged that
Haier had struggled so far. ``We may fail in that field,'' he said
without a hint of defensiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Risking failure, after all, is the mark of a modern company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
