<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9210 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-G8-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      07-21 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G8-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN GIVES CLINTON AN EARFUL SEEKING TO KILL MISSILE SHIELD
</HEADLINE>
  By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAHA, Japan _ At the summit meeting here of eight world leaders,
where the focus was unremittingly on harmony, President Vladimir
Putin of Russia met with President Clinton Friday night to argue
against U.S. deployment of a national missile shield.
</P>
<P>
   The two met during a break in the meeting of seven leading
industrial nations and Russia that is under way here in Okinawa.
National missile defense was the most attention-getting issue,
because it exposed a rift in a well-scripted gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton joined Putin in a casual setting, a private dining room
overlooking a hotel pool. Clinton wore a tan suit and an exhausted
look. Putin, in a dark blue suit, shook Clinton's hand vigorously
for the photographers but offered no Boris Yeltsin-style bear hug.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by aides, the two men spent 75 minutes discussing and
disagreeing on security issues.
</P>
<P>
   Of the national missile defense system, a senior administration
official said, ``President Clinton made clear, as he has publicly,
that he has not made a decision, but he intends to make a decision
during the course of this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who met recently with the leaders of China and North
Korea to solidify opposition to the building of such a system,
briefed Clinton on an offer by the North Korean leader, Kim Jong
Il, to scrap his missile program if other countries provide him
with rockets to explore space. U.S. officials have reacted with
skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not entirely clear what is in Kim Jong Il's mind with
regard to this possible trade-off,'' one official said. ``A very
dangerous idea would be that the international community would
provide actual launch capability to North Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin was not the only leader making the case against a U.S.
missile shield. President Jacques Chirac of France, speaking to
reporters, said the system might never work but nonetheless would
prompt an arms race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's of a nature to re-trigger a proliferation of weapons,
notably nuclear missiles,'' Chirac said. ``Everything that goes in
the direction of proliferation is a bad direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany sided with the critics
of the system, saying simply, ``I'm skeptical.''
</P>
<P>
   But such disagreement was rare. Common ground was what this
annual meeting was all about. For instance, Clinton and Putin
issued a statement saying they would set up a center for the
exchange of data between systems that provide early warning in case
of a missile launching.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the eight nations discussed other topics ranging from
debt relief for developing nations and AIDS, to oil prices and
financial crime. ``We are deeply concerned about the growth of
armed conflict in the continent of Africa,'' said one unanimous
decree.
</P>
<P>
   Official events took place in a majestic seaside resort, the
Cape Busena. Journalists, protesters and even top aides were
stopped in their tracks at the front door. Few people with last
names other than Clinton or Blair or Amato or Chirac or Chretien or
Mori or Putin or Schroeder could stroll easily through the metal
detectors.
</P>
<P>
   All of the leaders seemed to be sweating, and plainly not
because of the intensity of the meeting. Chirac was wiping his
forehead as he stopped in the hotel lobby to admire Okinawan
schoolchildren in traditional dress who were beating drums and
singing.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning Clinton and Japan's Prime Minister, Yoshiro
Mori, sat down to discuss economic and foreign policy issues.
Later, they planted a tree together.
</P>
<P>
   In the giant media centers set up in hotel ballrooms across the
island to accommodate the thousands of reporters covering the
meeting, ``officials,'' ``senior administration officials'' and
some people actually willing to use their real names briefed them
on everything from the volatility of oil prices to the trade in
illicit diamonds in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the area of debt reduction, there was a very lengthy and
very good exchange,'' said Lael Brainard, Clinton's adviser on
international economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Middle East also came up repeatedly Friday, as leaders
congratulated Clinton on his peacemaking efforts. Clinton planned
to remain here on Saturday, but his spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said
the president might scale back his schedule on Sunday to hurry back
to Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Okinawa clearly was full of action, but Thomas Foley, the U.S.
ambassador to Japan, staged a summit-related event on a tinier
island off the coast. Reporters boarded a ferry to photograph Foley
unveiling a plaque honoring the memory of Ernie Pyle, the
celebrated war correspondent who died on Ie Shima during the Battle
of Okinawa in 1945.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
