<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9213 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DAVIDIANS22-COX     07-21 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIDIANS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report clears government in 1993 siege
 &HT;    By Mark England
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The government was resolved of wrongdoing at Mount
Carmel in 1993 for the second week in a row Friday with the release
of Special Counsel John Danforth's interim report.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth was appointed by U.S. attorney general Janet Reno last
September to investigate the ``dark questions'' regarding the FBI's
actions on April 19, 1993, which saw a fire after a tear-gas
assault that led to the deaths of David Koresh and 75 followers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind about the conclusions of this
report,'' Danforth stated in the report's preface. ``Government
agents did not start or spread the tragic fire... did not direct
gunfire at the Branch Davidians and did not unlawfully employ the
armed forces of the United States,'' he stated.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth's report also concluded that the government did not
engage in a massive cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   However, it accused several people within the government of
trying to hide the fact that military tear gas canisters, which are
pyrotechnic, were shot at the covering over an underground tunnel
at Mount Carmel. Danforth called their actions ``puzzling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``... because the use of these pyrotechnics had nothing to do
with the fire,'' the report said. ``They were used four hours
before the fire began, 75 feet from the Branch Davidian residence,
and in a manner that would cause no harm. Yet the failure to
disclose this information, more than anything else, is responsible
for the loss of the public faith in the government's actions at
Waco, and it led directly to this investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction was mixed to Danforth's report, split along which side
of the Waco's federal courthouse one sat on during the Davidians'
wrongful-death lawsuit. An advisory jury on July 14, like Danforth,
found the government was not guilty of wrongdoing at Mount Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Director Louis Freeh issued a statement praising Danforth's
report for being ``vigorous and thorough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of public recitation of the complete facts can only
serve to support the long-term best interests of the FBI and our
desire to be fully accountable to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   However, former U.S. attorney general Ramsey Clark, who
represented most of the longtime Davidians at the civil trial, said
that Danforth's focus on whether the FBI was guilty of atrocities
at Mount Carmel skewed his perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like judging a diver's performance off the high dive and
failing to mention there wasn't any water in the pool,'' Clark
said.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth should have examined the appropriateness of the entire
government operation, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does it by looking at the dark side, but you have to look
at everything that happened,'' Clark said. ``We can't really want
law enforcement to do that again. I never in my life expected to
see ATF go out there like that. It was an invitation to disaster.
The same thing with the tanks. We shouldn't praise or glorify those
who did it just because they didn't go in there and slit throats.
The people are just as dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bradford, the government co-counsel at the civil trial,
disagreed with Clark's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it answers the important questions,'' said Bradford,
the U.S. attorney for the Eastern District of Texas. ``It gets to
the heart of whether the agencies acted in good faith and who was
responsible for the tragedy. Those were the questions most
troubling to people, and both were thoroughly addressed by Danforth
and by the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Danforth investigation was done by 17 private
lawyers and 38 postal investigators to ensure it was independent of
the Justice Department. About 900 witnesses were interviewed, and
2.3 million pages of documents were examined. Danforth said he
expects to spend $11 million to $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   At the St. Louis press conference where he released the report,
Danforth blamed Koresh for the tragedy at Mount Carmel,
</P>
<P>
   ``The blame rests squarely on the shoulders of David Koresh,''
Danforth said. He added, ``This is not a close call.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth wrote in his report that most of the Davidians did not
want to escape the fire. He noted that a Davidian who did escape
told FBI agents that he witnessed others in the group make no
effort to leave. Also, Ruth Ottman tried to go back into a burning
Mount Carmel and had to be pulled out by an FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Danforth blamed the Davidians for starting the fire.
</P>
<P>
   His report relates fire-related comments by Davidians picked up
by surveillance bugs planted inside Mount Carmel, such as ``I want
a fire on the front... you two can go.'' ``Keep that fire going.''
``Do you think I could light this fire soon?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only plausible explanation for these comments is that some
of the Davidians were executing their plan to start a fire,''
Danforth wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
