u p BC-REFORM-PARTY-SPLIT-NY     07-21 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-SPLIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOES SEEK TO DISQUALIFY BUCHANAN IN STUDY OF PETITION NAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what both sides consider an all-out war for control of the
Reform Party, opponents of Pat Buchanan's efforts to win the party
presidential nomination say they have evidence of irregularities by
his campaign in the primary that could disqualify him from the
balloting.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of party officials has been appointed to audit the
400,000 petition signatures collected by Buchanan and by his
opponent, John Hagelin, a physicist who has twice run for president
under the Natural Law Party banner.
</P>
<P>
   Petition signers would otherwise be sent primary ballots for
voting, which began this month and concludes when the party
convention begins in three weeks. If the signatures cannot be
verified as party members or as people who have requested a ballot,
they would be invalidated, and the candidate who submitted the
names could be removed from the primary.
</P>
<P>
   The audit is expected to be completed next week. Several party
leaders who oppose Buchanan said they were certain that the results
would show that his campaign violated the rules by submitting the
names of people who were not qualified to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectation is that the Buchanan campaign committed
widespread fraud in attempting to corrupt the process and steal the
nomination,'' said Jim Mangia, the national party secretary who is
leading the campaign against Buchanan along with Russell J. Verney,
an associate of Ross Perot, the party founder.
</P>
<P>
   The Buchanan campaign denied the accusations, saying the audit
would prove that they were unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   `` Mangia is trying to invent any way he can to subvert the
process because he can't defeat us legitimately,'' said Brian
Doherty, a spokesman for the Buchanan campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the signatures submitted by Buchanan were first
raised by Hagelin and his supporters, who are waging a long-shot
campaign to win the nomination. But the cause was rapidly embraced
by Reform leaders who are concerned that Buchanan would change the
ideological direction of the party, infusing it with a social
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they became suspicious when the petitions
included thousands of names from states like New York, California
and South Carolina, where Reform candidates were not required to
gather signatures because the party was already on the November
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Mangia and the campaign managers for Hagelin, Kingsley Brooks
and Nadine Padower, said many of the names were those of Buchanan
supporters and contributors from his days in the Republican Party
who had no connection to the Reform Party, which Buchanan joined
late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The audit panel, which has four members and includes a
representative from each campaign, will try to sort through the
names and determine if there are irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Kresky, an official with the Reform Party in New York and
a panel member, said the audit would probably start on Monday,
assuming the two campaigns had provided the material needed to
validate each signature.
</P>
<P>
   If improprieties are found, the panel would make a
recommendation to the presidential nominating committee for a final
disposition that could be appealed to the executive committee.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he were disqualified from the primary, Buchanan could
still become the nominee if two-thirds of the delegates attending
the convention next month in Long Beach, Calif., vote to invalidate
the primary and install Buchanan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
