u a BC-CAVIAR-SMUGGLERS-PLEA     07-21 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAVIAR-SMUGGLERS-PLEA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUILTY PLEAS IN CAVIAR-SMUGGLING OPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)   By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Capping a case that exposed a large-scale caviar smuggling ring,
a Maryland company, two of its officials and a third person pleaded
guilty Friday to federal fraud, smuggling and wildlife endangerment
charges. The company agreed to pay a $10.4 million fine, which
prosecutors described as the largest ever in a wildlife smuggling
case.
</P>
<P>
   The guilty pleas, entered in U.S. District Court in Greenbelt,
Md., followed a prolonged investigation of a sophisticated
black-market operation. The inquiry ranged from the shores of the
Caspian Sea and the Mississippi River to the first-class cabins of
American Airlines jets and the shelves of gourmet stores in
Manhattan, Greenwich, Conn., and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The illicit operation was part of a continuing illegal trade in
the eggs of sturgeon, huge bottom-feeders that live a century or
more and reproduce slowly, whose high-priced roe have made them a
target of poachers.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the scheme, Justice Department officials said, was the
illegal importing of roe from several Caspian Sea sturgeon species
protected by an international conservation treaty. Another part,
they said, entailed falsely representing roe from two American
species _ the shovelnose sturgeon and the paddlefish _ as legally
imported Sevruga caviar.
</P>
<P>
   The company that admitted guilt Friday was U.S. Caviar &AMP; Caviar,
one of the largest caviar importers in the country. From 1995 to
1999, according to court records, the company channeled tons of
illegally harvested fish eggs from the Caspian and other waters to
its offices in Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the roe was smuggled into the country in large
containers and was repackaged in Rockville, where workers placed it
in caviar tins that bore counterfeit labels, some with fake Russian
health agency certification seals. In other cases, the labels,
printed in Rockville, were shipped to the Middle East, where
Kenfood Trading, another company involved in the operation,
packaged some of the roe in caviar tins and sent them on to
Rockville.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 alone, the operation funneled more than 18 tons of
sturgeon caviar from the Caspian. The quantity of roe smuggled from
Russia by U.S. Caviar &AMP; Caviar was so great that it exceeded the
total amount that could be legally exported from the country under
international treaties.
</P>
<P>
   The operation was aimed in part at meeting the high demand for
caviar in the months leading up to millennium celebrations around
the world, Justice Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The first hint of it came in December 1998, when an inspector
for the Fish and Wildlife Service at Baltimore-Washington
International Airport noticed something odd about the labels in a
shipment of caviar tins: The labels were of the peel-off variety,
said Thomas Healy, the senior inspector in the agency's Baltimore
office, whereas genuine labels on Russian caviar are glued on.
</P>
<P>
   The three men who entered guilty pleas Friday are Hossein
Lolavar, 46, president of U.S. Caviar &AMP; Caviar; Faye Briggs, 53,
the company's sales manager; and Ken Noroozi, 42, president of
Kenfood Trading, which handled some of the illegal trade through
the United Arab Emirates. All three men face at least a year's
imprisonment when they are sentenced in December, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Healy, the fish and wildlife inspector, said the prosecutions
had probably made a significant dent in the larger illicit trade in
the roe of protected fish, but added that no one really had a good
idea of the trade's size.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in the last two years, couriers carrying suitcases
jammed with caviar tins had been caught at airports in Boston, New
York, Miami, Los Angeles and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a national problem,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
