u s BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT     07-21 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN SOLIDIFIES LEAD IN BICYCLE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MULHOUSE, France _ Lance Armstrong, who says he draws his
motivation from both positive and negative sources, had both of
them at his disposal Friday and blended them expertly to win a long
individual time trial in the Tour de France by 25 seconds and
solidify his overall lead.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a yellow suit that was furnished to him hours earlier by
the race's organizers as a symbol of his leadership, the star of
the U.S. Postal Service team rode with power and smooth authority
over the 58.5-kilometer course (about 36 miles) from Germany to
France in hot weather to finish first in 1 hour 5 minutes 1 second.
He averaged 53.9 kilometers an hour (33.5 mph), the fastest pace at
that distance in the Tour's 87 years.
</P>
<P>
   Second was Jan Ullrich, the German leader of the Telekom team,
the winner of the 1997 Tour and the favorite of many fans in this
individual race against the clock. Christophe Moreau, a Frenchman
with Festina, was third, 2:12 behind, with Tyler Hamilton, another
American with Postal Service and Armstrong's lieutenant in the
mountains, fourth, 3:01 behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big fight,'' Armstrong said. ``Jan is a big engine. I
went all out, as the yellow jersey is supposed to do. This was nice
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring illness or accident, the victory guaranteed Armstrong's
second successive victory in the Tour when it ends Sunday in Paris.
Ullrich remained in second place over all, going from 5:37 behind
at the start to 6:02 now, with Joseba Beloki, a Spaniard with
Festina, still in third place but now 10:04 behind.
</P>
<P>
   Enormous crowds lined the road in the 38 kilometers (23.6 miles)
the race traversed in Germany before passing into France for the
final 20.5. The German police estimated the crowd at 1.5 million
for the stage Thursday from Lausanne, Switzerland, to Freiburg, and
it seemed comparable Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Texan said earlier that he feared the size of the crowd,
both because it might make the few tight turns difficult by
overflowing the sidewalk and because there might be some fan of
Ullrich's who would try to prevent the American from beating the
Telekom leader.
</P>
<P>
   If, at the 20-kilometer (12.4-mile) time check, he had no chance
of victory, Armstrong continued, he would probably slow down to
prevent any possible aggression. But the American led Ullrich by
five seconds and the rest of the 129-man field by a minimum of 1:40
at that point and kept on pushing.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he had plenty of motivation, both positive and
negative.
</P>
<P>
   The positive influence was his desire not to become the fifth
Tour winner since World War II and the first since 1990 not to have
won a daily stage when the three-week race is done. It ends in
Paris on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Although he said 10 days ago that he did not care how many times
he finished second _ three in this 87th Tour _ as long as he was
first in Paris, he has changed his tune lately. ``I would be
disappointed not to win a stage,'' he admitted this week. Last
year, in his first Tour victory, he won four stages to go with two
in previous races.
</P>
<P>
   The negative influence was this question asked at a news
conference Thursday by an Italian journalist: ``Do you think
Ullrich can make up the 5:37 and win the Tour tomorrow?''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong called it one of the dumbest questions he had been
asked, and he refused to answer.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise relaxed and friendly, bantering at 40 kilometers an
hour (24.8 mph) as he moved along on his bicycle with a team car
escorting him, he reported that he was feeling good and promised,
with a confident smile, to give his answer in the Tour's press room
after the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the guy who asked that question yesterday?'' Armstrong
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ullrich was heavily favored to win the stage because, as
Armstrong put it a few days ago, ``It's in his adopted hometown,
and that gives you a big push.''
</P>
<P>
   The German, a native of Rostock in the east, has lived for years
in the village of Merdigen, a sprint away from the start in
Freiburg. Many of the flat roads used in the time trial were the
same ones Ullrich used in training and he undoubtedly passed many
of the suppliers of the cream pies that the habitually overweight
rider puts away in quantity every winter.
</P>
<P>
   After riding himself into top condition in the first two weeks
of the Tour, Ullrich looked svelte Friday in the jersey of the
world time trial champion. He rode splendidly, but 26 seconds too
slowly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
