<SLUG> BC-OLY-JOHNSON22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maurice vs. Michael: track's marquee matchup
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Michael Johnson vs. Maurice Greene. It's a
matchup bombastic boxing promoter Don King would love.
</P>
<P>
   As the United States Olympic Track and Field Trials heads into
its second weekend here, there's no doubt what the main attraction
of the meet will be. It's the heavyweight championship of sprinting
between Johnson, the world record holder in the 200 and 400 meters,
and Greene, the world record holder in the 100 meters. The
much-anticipated matchup on Sunday will be over quicker than one of
Mike Tyson's recent fights, and it comes complete with all the
smack talking that's used to hype fights.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week Johnson said, ``Rivalries are good for the
sport. I tune in when there are two guys boxing that don't like
each other. The people you don't like, you certainly don't want to
lose to. It intensifies the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the ultimate `put up or shut up' in this sport,
especially the sprints,'' Greene said. ``You've got to believe
you're the best, and talking about it makes it a little more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Even sprinters who aren't running here have gotten into the act.
Ato Boldon, who'll be racing for Trinidad and Tobago, said,
``Sprinters talk, boxers talk. Michael Johnson says the rest of the
field is `company.' Well, I hope he's preparing for company.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprinters, like many boxers before the Muhammad Ali era, once
were a quiet lot. Jesse Owens didn't talk trash, he let his times
do his talking. The professionalization of track certainly helped
change the atmosphere. No longer are sprinters one and done in the
Olympics before moving on to real-world careers. Now, they're
around for two or three Olympics, and they're not only competing
for the fastest times, but also for the appearance and endorsement
money that they once could be banned for accepting.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Lewis wasn't merely a sprinter/long jumper, he became a
track celebrity. Lewis said what was on his mind, and Ben Johnson
was on his mind a lot. Lewis believed, and was eventually proved
correct, that Johnson's speed wasn't all natural, that it was
enhanced by a banned substance. Lewis vs. Johnson turned sprinting
into a bad-blood grudge match.
</P>
<P>
   Then, along came loquacious Donovan Bailey, a Canadian who
trains in Austin and doesn't mind ruffling anyone's feathers. He
likes it when he can make other sprinters edgy. With Bailey, the
100-meter gold medalist in Atlanta, the Canada-U.S. sprint team
duel often turned into a war of words.
</P>
<P>
   If that wasn't enough, some sprinters started striking poses,
something Lewis didn't do. Some sprinters are now built like
bodybuilders and actually flex after winning.
</P>
<P>
   Greene is right at home in that kind of atmosphere. He points
and gestures and struts and jabbers after he wins a race. The
9.79-second 100 meters he clocked in Athens on June 16 last year
made him the world's fastest human. His vanity license plate reads
``Mo Gold.'' The Mo could stand for the 200 meters. Greene won
that, as well as the 100 meters, at the World Championships last
year, becoming the first man to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The 200, however, has been owned by Johnson. The Baylor graduate
blistered a 19.32 in that event at the Atlanta Olympics, setting a
world record that some experts believe could stand for decades. His
400-meter record of 43.18 seconds isn't shabby either. Most believe
Johnson to be the best ever at running the curves. When Lewis was
ending his reign, Johnson carefully positioned himself to be ``The
Man'' in track, going for and completing the much-publicized 200
and 400 meter double in Atlanta in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while taking over Lewis' Superman role, Johnson hasn't
become the celebrity Lewis was. Although his charm is lost on some,
Lewis is an engaging athlete, bright and interested in more than
just his own career. Johnson is one of today's modern breed of
athletes who can throw up a wall when he's around people. He's
rarely funny, sometimes almost surly.
</P>
<P>
   Other athletes are jealous of his status. Some predictions he
made in USA Today weren't laughed off by other athletes. Some,
especially the female sprinters, were chagrined by what they
perceived as slights. Johnson didn't apologize; he told them to
grow up, the way he has Greene, labeling him ``immature.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson huffed, ``I don't like a lot of things Maurice has said.
What Maurice is trying to be, which is to become a great sprinter
and supplant me as the premier track athlete, can be done without
personal attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Greene have met only twice in the 200, with each
winning a race. Greene, seemingly taking a page from boxing
promotion, has claimed that Johnson has lately been ducking him.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson is at his best, it's a knockout. As Johnson put it,
``What motivation do I need to beat up on a 19.9 guy?'' But, in a
1997 made-for-TV sprint match it was Johnson who suffered a TKO
loss to Bailey, pulling up lame with Bailey winning in Toronto.
Greene plans to jump out ahead of Johnson and make him run faster
than he wants to go, so anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   After all it's boxing ... uh, track.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
