<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AIKMAN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aikman, Cowboys revamping offense
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS _ On the first day of training camp, dozens of
photographers crowded around Troy Aikman as he carried his clothes
and other personal belongings from his car to his room at the
dorms.
</P>
<P>
   It has been the same routine for a dozen years. The quarterback
of the Dallas Cowboys shakes his head, wondering what the fuss is
all about. He resembles a Hollywood star on his way to the Oscars.
If photographers want to waste their time taking pictures of a man
carrying a stack of jeans and T-shirts, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   This is the worst day of the year for Aikman, an old codger at
33.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the routine of training camp is nearing an end. Aikman is
not the fresh-faced phenom who was the No. 1 pick of the 1989
draft. The aches and pains that accompany each NFL season have
taken their toll on No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many years I have left,'' Aikman said after
completing his first camp workout in 106-degree sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   He pauses to reflect on his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going into my 12th year,'' he resumes. ``As I've said
before, I'm not going to play 12 more.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, players often speak about their ``window of
opportunity.'' The Cowboys have squeezed out three Super Bowl
championships under Aikman, but a five-year absence from Super
Sunday suggests Aikman's opportunities are about to shut.
</P>
<P>
   The window of opportunity is closing fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``How close is it to being shut? That's year to year.''
</P>
<P>
   Like bluebonnets in the spring, there is a freshness to every
season. The Cowboys haven't lost a game yet, and if you listen
closely, they see no reason they can't win every game. An influx of
new blood, from wide receiver Joey Galloway to cornerback Ryan
McNeil, gives them reason to be optimistic in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, who knows what will happen?
</P>
<P>
   ``It will all come out in the wash,'' Aikman said. ``We'll get a
chance to line up and play. I'd hate to just give you a sound bite
because you could go back to last year's (media) coverage and get
the same one.''
</P>
<P>
   Optimism has spread like hay fever in Wichita Falls because
Aikman's offense has a new look. Or is it an old look? When Dave
Campo succeeded Chan Gailey as head coach of the Cowboys this
spring, he hired some familiar faces to revamp the team. The
new/old offense is designed to take advantage of Aikman's ability
to read pass coverages and throw to a certain spot.
</P>
<P>
   When the quarterback and his receivers are on the same page, the
system is hard to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Jerry Jones has overseen the offensive overhaul. It
was his decision to hire a coach ``from the family.'' He admits
that hiring Gailey, a former Pittsburgh Steelers offensive
coordinator, was one of his worst moves in the 12 years he has
owned the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious change during the first week of camp has been
the addition of speed. Receivers Rocket Ismail, James McKnight and
Galloway are as fast as any group of receivers in the league. If
nothing else, the Cowboys should add excitement in games by
throwing deep passes with reckless abandon.
</P>
<P>
   The early results have been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman has had trouble connecting with Galloway, perhaps the
fastest Cowboys receiver since Bullet Bob Hayes. Aikman's passes
have been underthrown, overthrown or missed their mark completely.
It isn't easy throwing to a blur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joey and I will get better even after we break camp,'' Aikman
said. ``I don't want to be naive and say we're going to be where we
want to be when we break camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Reilly knows it will take time. Campo's choice for
offensive coordinator worked with Aikman in 1997 and they have a
good relationship. The Cowboys needed to change an offense that
ranked 24th in the league in passing last year. They were boring
and predictable. And less exciting than a Michael Bolton concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously have a real deep threat now,'' he said. ``People
have to respect that. It opens everything up. If they don't, we'll
have to throw it down the field.''
</P>
<P>
   With all this talk about passing deep, one major element of the
offense has been nearly forgotten: Emmitt Smith. One of the best
running backs in NFL history likely will get fewer carries because
the Cowboys plan to throw more than usual. But Campo stresses that
``offensive balance wins games'' and Smith accepted the change of
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I think we were a little high in the run end,''
Campo said. ``Every game is going to be different, though. It
depends on how the defense plays you. I think Emmitt's going to
have a chance to do what he does all the time, and that's to make
plays when the ball is in his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, Smith and Aikman have more help.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway promises to be an extraordinary weapon, given his speed
and ability to make plays on punt returns. McKnight would be the
fastest player on many teams, but not with Galloway and Ismail
around. The addition of former Tennessee tight end Jackie Harris,
who has dropped from 260 to 247 pounds, is another passing target.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys stress that the majority of camp will be used to
implement the offense and get all the moving parts working
together. Aikman is eager to give it a try. After 12 years, he'll
try anything that isn't routine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
