<HEADER>
A9243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-BRITISH22-COX     07-21 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiger still on top
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ The commotion started as soon as Tiger
Woods was walking off the 18th green. To his right, a topless
streaker came running across the fairway and onto the green before
a security guard stopped her and led her away.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, it seems, gets close to Woods these days.
</P>
<P>
   Not the world's greatest golfers. Not a streaker wearing only
panties and a smile. Not the exhaustive list of adjectives that no
longer do justice to his domination.
</P>
<P>
   So let's be brief: Woods shot a six-under-par 66 Friday on the
Old Course to take command of the 129th British Open at St.
Andrews. Woods is at 11-under 133 with a three-shot lead over David
Toms. He stands two rounds away from becoming the youngest player
(24 years) to complete the career grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the rest of the world thinks that development is
just a formality, Woods has this response: ``The trophy's not
sitting next to me yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Give it time, Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of streaks, Woods extended his own of not having a
bogey in a major to a remarkable 62 holes, dating back to the 10th
hole in the third round of last month's U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might go another 36, too,'' said Nick Price, who spent the
last two days playing with Woods. Price says Woods' pursuers better
hope for outside intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the wind doesn't blow hard, everyone's going to be playing
for second place,'' Price said. ``I honestly think that's the only
chance they're going to have. He's on cruise, man. He hasn't even
tried any shots yet.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt that Woods is longer than a Scottish summer day,
which helps him reduce both of the Old Course's par-5s to par-4s,
and at least two of the par-4s to par-3s. Add a velvet-smooth short
game and it's no wonder he may soon own each of golf's four majors.
</P>
<P>
   This seems like a sequel to last month's blockbuster showing at
Pebble Beach, where he set U.S. Open records for margin of victory
(15 shots) and score in relation to par (-12). Friday's 66 tied
Phil Mickelson, Jose Coceres and Davis Love III for low score of
the day, and his 67 Thursday was bettered only by Ernie Els' 66.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing very similar to how I played at Pebble,'' Woods
said. ``I'm driving the ball well and hitting my irons pretty
solidly _ not great, but good enough. I'm putting well and that's
what you have to do on this golf course (because of the large
greens).''
</P>
<P>
   The only complaint Woods could make Friday didn't involve his
game, but the streaker who made her run at him. Last year, another
scantily clad woman got a brief hug from Woods when he was on the
final hole in the second round
</P>
<P>
   at Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not right to do that, especially here at the home of
golf,'' Woods said. ``This is where you should show the utmost
respect for the game of golf. I don't think running down the
fairway without your clothes on showed the proper respect. Luckily,
we had finished the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods' shadow has grown so large over his peers that the player
who will be in the final pairing with him today (Toms) was actually
asked by a British writer if he belongs in that spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, obviously I do,'' Toms said. ``I finished top 10 on the
money list last year (No. 10) and I won twice. The only reason a
lot of people haven't heard of me is you guys (media). You make or
break people _ which is fine. If I continue to play well, everybody
will know who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Just in case anyone's interested, tied for third at 137 are
Sergio Garcia (69), Steve Flesch (70) and Loren Roberts (68), who
won last week's Greater Milwaukee Open.
</P>
<P>
   It would be ironic for Garcia, who finished second to Woods in
last year's PGA Championship, to have a chance to win on Sunday. A
year ago, he left the British Open in tears after finishing last
with rounds of 89 and 83.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the big difference between this year's Open and last
year's, Garcia grinned. ``Thirty-five shots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The five players tied for sixth, five shots back, constitute a
formidable group: Els (72), Fred Couples (68), Mickelson (66), Tom
Lehman (70) and Thomas Bjorn (69). Among the four players at 139 is
Jean Van de Velde (68), who kicked away last year's Open with a
triple-bogey on the final hole.
</P>
<P>
   They all have a formidable challenge: To make a run at Woods.
With their clothes on, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
