<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, JULY 22 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday July 22. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-EUROPE-AUSTRIA-NYT (moved on Friday, July 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article that was sent on Friday,
July 14, about moves by the European Union to lift sanctions on
Austria referred incorrectly to the body's decision-making process.
While decisions on key issues including sovereignty, taxation,
foreign policy and financing for regional development require
unanimous votes, most others do not.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SIERRA-LEONE-NYT (moved on Thursday, July 20)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article that was sent on Thursday,
July 20, about criticism from Ambassador Richard C. Holbrooke that
Washington was not providing adequate financial support for United
Nations peacekeeping missions misstated the amount Congress is
being asked to approve. The administration has proposed spending
$1.7 billion, not $7.1 billion, for emergency relief for
peacekeeping.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-CANADA-DIVERSITY-NYT (moved on Monday, July 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article that was sent on Monday,
July 10, about the growing prominence of Sikhs in British Columbia
and Canada's acceptance of diversity referred incorrectly to
Adrienne Clarkson, an immigrant from Hong Kong who is the governor
general. She is not Canada's head of state; Queen Elizabeth II is.
</P>
<P>
   The article also referred incorrectly to a trade mission to
India by Ujjal Dosanjh, an Indian-born Sikh who is British
Columbia's premier. While such a mission has been discussed, there
are no plans for one in September.
</P>
<P>
   The article also misspelled the surname of a reporter for The
Vancouver Sun who commented on the growing links between Indians in
Vancouver and in the state of Punjab. She is Kim Bolan, not Boland.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BC-TEXAS-PRIDE-NYT (moved on Thursday, July 20)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article that was sent on Thursday,
July 20, about Vice President Al Gore's campaign trip to Texas
referred incorrectly to remarks made by Gov. George W. Bush in
response. He read a statement to reporters; it was not merely
distributed.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
