<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9249 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-SYDNEY-DO23-COX     07-21 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYDNEY-DO23-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Sydney tour: Opera, outdoors, Olympics
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Take a harbor cruise. The two-tone green and cream ferries of
the state transit system are as beloved in Sydney as cable cars are
in San Francisco. Morning, afternoon and evening excursions provide
an inexpensive introduction to the harbor.
www.sydneybuses.nsw.gov.au
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tour the Opera House. The roof gets all the raves, but the
interior _ housing a small city of theaters, concert halls and
restaurants _ isn't too shabby, either. Be sure to check the
performance schedules. www.soh.nsw.gov.au
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Climb the Harbour Bridge. If the Opera House represents modern
Sydney, this grand old arch built in 1932 evokes the past. For the
best views of the city and harbor, walk across the bridge or visit
the lookout in the south pylon. Or, if you have the guts and cash
($117 and up), take a guided hike to the top of the superstructure.
www.bridgeclimb.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  See the Olympic Park. Homebush Bay, home of the athletes
village and most of the venues, is a triumph of recycling. A few
years ago, it was a waste dump and the site of a huge
slaughterhouse. Come September, it will be the focus of global
attention as the Olympics begin at Stadium Australia. There are
tours daily. www.oca.nsw.gov.au
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hit the Rocks. The narrow streets between the bridge and the
Opera House were once crowded with brothels and sailor taverns. Now
the Rocks is lined with shops, restaurants and pubs, including two
of the city's most venerable: the Lord Nelson and the Hero of
Waterloo.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Be artful. The Art Gallery of New South Wales holds one of the
country's best collections of Australian painting. Starting Aug.
18, as part of the Olympic Arts Festival, the gallery will feature
a major show of Aboriginal dot paintings. www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Explore Australian history. Two places to start: the Hyde Park
Barracks and the National Maritime Museum. The barracks, a prison
dormitory converted into a museum, documents convict life in the
penal colony. The maritime museum tells the story of Australian
seafaring, from the arrival of the First Fleet to the coming of
Vietnamese boat people. www.anmm.gov.au
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Watch the waves. The South Pacific is less than 10 miles from
downtown Sydney. Bondi, the closest beach, is famous for its
beefcake surfers. For a more relaxed scene, ferry across the harbor
to Manly, a longer strand lined with Norfolk pines. The most
beautiful oceanside vistas come along the walking trails from South
Head to Bondi, where waves slamming into cliffs will remind you of
the northern California coast.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pet a kangaroo. Australia has some of the world's strangest
wildlife. You can find most of it _ from koalas to platypuses _ at
the Taronga Zoo, scenically situated on the hilly north shore of
the harbor. www.zoo.nsw.gov.au
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Take a last look. For a sea gull's view, visit the observation
deck atop the AMP Tower _ at 1,000 feet, the tallest building in
the Southern Hemisphere. www.centrepoint.com.au
</P>
<P>
   _Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
