<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9250 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-SYDNEY1STTAKE23-COX     07-21 1570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYDNEY1STTAKE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sydney, more than a pretty place
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 23.
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ As you watch the Olympics this September and
admire the stunning views of Sydney Harbour, remember this: In a
roundabout way, we're responsible. Americans, that is. If we hadn't
rebelled in 1776, the British might never have spun the globe
looking for another place to dump their undesirables. The Crown had
shipped 40,000 of them to its American colonies, mostly petty
offenders like the debtors who settled Savannah with Oglethorpe.
Forced to find another place to relieve its overcrowded jails,
Britain discovered a continent so far away and so isolated that no
convict would be able to breech the endless arc of ocean that
formed its prison walls.
</P>
<P>
   In going from Georgia to Australia, then, the Olympics have gone
from one British penal experiment to another.
</P>
<P>
   This odd kinship of outcasts dawned on me as I was sitting at a
cafe beside Sydney Cove, the aquamarine inlet that sets off the
heart of the city like a jade pendant. Ferry boats were churning
through the whitecaps of crisscrossing wakes. On one side of the
cove, the Opera House roof loomed like the upturned prows of a
dozen giant rowboats. On the other side, blue Australian flags
streamed in the breeze atop the long steel arch of the Harbour
Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine now, but this postcard spot was where the
First Fleet landed in 1788 with a thousand convicts and sailors.
Eight months and 10,000 miles from home, they might as well have
been on the dark side of the moon. They struggled and almost
starved yet somehow managed to transform their exile into a city
and nation that will soon command the world's attention.
</P>
<P>
   This melding of happy scenery and harsh history captures Sydney
for me. The next Olympic city has become many things: a pan-Asian
cultural center, a Pacific Rim boomtown, a sublime place to dine
and drink and shop and play. But before any of it, there was the
sea and the banished souls who found safe harbor halfway around the
globe. Everywhere I turned, Sydney kept reminding me of them.
</P>
<P>
   A harbor runs through it
</P>
<P>
   The waterfront was the first thing my wife and I wanted to see
when we arrived shortly before Easter. The trip had been
discombobulating. We left the dogwood blossoms of an Atlanta spring
and emerged 22 hours later to find paperbark trees shedding their
skin in an Australian autumn. This being our first time in the
Southern Hemisphere, we gathered over the lavatory in our room to
see for ourselves whether the water actually drains
counterclockwise. Who knew that the revolving doors run backward,
too? The damn thing blindsided me when we left the hotel to begin
our explorations.
</P>
<P>
   We were headed where all visitors seem to gravitate: to the
ferry terminal on Sydney Cove. The cool, salt air of a harbor
cruise seemed just the thing to chase our jet lag.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Harbour is actually a flooded river valley that reaches
its long fingers 16 miles inland from the South Pacific. What makes
it so picturesque is its irregular shape; for 155 miles, the
shoreline juts and rises in rocky bluffs, then curves and falls
into sandy coves. Much of it is parkland. At no point is the water
so wide that you can't make out the houses on the other side. If
San Francisco Bay feels like a small sea, Sydney Harbour feels as
intimate as a Georgia lake.
</P>
<P>
   We spent two hours gliding past mansions half-veiled in leafy
hills. These are the most exclusive addresses in Australia, their
very names sounding like money _ Point Piper, Rose Bay, Vaucluse.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where Nicole stays when she's in town,'' our guide
said, not bothering with the actress' last name as he pointed
toward another waterside enclave.
</P>
<P>
   Refreshed by the harbor, we boarded a Sydney Explorer bus that
afternoon and got a different perspective on the city. We started
in Kings Cross, a rambunctious red-light district where generations
of American servicemen have taken comfort, and meandered a dozen
miles toward the ocean, to Bondi, the crescent beach where surfing
got its start in Australia during the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Bondi (rhymes with ``sigh'') is nice if you like sugary sand,
booming waves and skimpy bathing suits. But our favorite place in
eastern Sydney was the Gap, a wind-swept park atop sandstone cliffs
near the mouth of the harbor. As we approached the edge to see the
surf crashing into rocks a hundred feet below, we noticed a warning
sign beyond the railing. It was for a suicide hotline. Like the
Golden Gate Bridge, the gateway to Sydney is one of those
timelessly beautiful vistas that attract hopeless souls bent on
hurling themselves into eternity.
</P>
<P>
   The soap opera house
</P>
<P>
   It would seem impossible to improve something as lovely as
Sydney Harbour, but the Aussies did it by erecting one of the most
distinctive buildings of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   People didn't know what to make of the Sydney Opera House when
it opened in 1973. Some thought the sharply angled roofline was a
nautical allusion to sails or waves. Others said the thing looked
like a spiky lizard crawling out of the muck to sun itself. As we
walked the curved promenade to the building, I thought the peaks
resembled the pointy helmets of Spanish conquistadors.
</P>
<P>
   The architect would probably disagree with all of us. Joern
Utzon saw the design as an exercise in deconstruction: a sphere
peeled into segments like an orange to form a living sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   The Opera House is a wondrous thing to behold. Up close, that
famous flying roof, clad in a million white ceramic tiles, has the
scaly texture of a fish. But the real wonder is that any of it ever
got built. The process took 16 years and became such a drama that
the resident opera company once produced an opera about it.
</P>
<P>
   Utzon was an obscure Danish architect when he won an
international competition for the commission in 1957. It was a
radical choice that grew more controversial as he spent six years
figuring out how to engineer his fantastic imaginings. In the
meantime, the price rose fourteenfold and the state of New South
Wales had to sell millions of dollars in lottery tickets to pay for
it. Irritated by money troubles and political meddling, Utzon
resigned from the job in 1966, and the cavernous interior had to be
completed by a consortium of Australian architects. Now in his 80s,
he has never returned to see his masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Utzon's estrangement isn't the only melancholy note in the Opera
House aria. The edifice occupies a tip of land called Bennelong
Point. It was named for an Aborigine who once lived there in a
brick hut, built for him by the British authorities who had adopted
him as a sort of mascot.
</P>
<P>
   In the generation after Europeans appeared, almost all the
indigenous people who had lived beside the harbor fled or succumbed
to disease. Bennelong was no exception. He died in 1813, his
obituary in the Sydney Gazette cruelly noting that he had
contracted one of the white man's sicknesses: The friendly native
had become a drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Placing that accent
</P>
<P>
   When he lived in Sydney during the 1920s, D.H. Lawrence
dismissed it as a pale imitation of London, ``as margarine is a
substitute for butter.''
</P>
<P>
   There's still a strong British flavor about the city. Motorists
drive on the left side of the road, pubs serve bangers and mash,
and the newspapers, God love 'em, can be as rowdy as Fleet Street
tabloids. I almost spewed my coffee one morning when I saw one of
the local wrappers refer to our vice president as ``that rat
bastard Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the cultural similarities, Sydney today is no more
British than Hong Kong. Decades of immigration from the
Mediterranean and more recently Asia have created a cosmopolitan
society that would have been unthinkable in Lawrence's day. In
fact, the multicultural population and mild, sunny climate remind
many Americans of California.
</P>
<P>
   Like any American city, there's a good side of town and a
not-so-good side of town. The harbor and waterfront get the oohs
and ahs. But most of Sydney's 4 million residents (slightly more
than Atlanta) live in the Westies, the flat suburbs that sprawl
unglamorously inland toward the Blue Mountains and the Outback.
</P>
<P>
   Geraldine Brooks, an Australian journalist, described what it
was like to grow up in the other Sydney in her memoir ``Foreign
Correspondence.'' She was born during the '50s on a ``bland street
of liver-brick bungalows, identically designed, marching in
lockstep away from the grand homes that lined the harbour.... The
farther west, the hotter the summers, the fewer the trees and the
longer the journey back to the harbour and wide scalloped
beaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Most visitors don't see that Sydney. But many of them will this
year, at least part of it. The Games will begin and end at Sydney
Olympic Park, a reclaimed waste dump on a far finger of the harbor
called Homebush Bay. Fifteen sports will be contested there, nine
miles west of the Opera House. As I toured the facilities,
marveling at the spotless sidewalks and immaculate new arenas, it
all seemed a bit sterile, as if I were walking through some theme
park that had just been scraped out of the Florida scrublands _
definitely more American than British.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
