<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0305 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9253 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-SYDNEY2NDTAKE23-COX     07-21 1929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYDNEY2NDTAKE23-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia :American than British.
</P>
<P>
   Fancy a rubber rat?
</P>
<P>
   From the first convicts to the latest Asian newcomers, Sydney
has been a city of immigrants. We looked for an Ellis Island, but
the closest thing we found was a prison dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   The Hyde Park Barracks were built in 1819 to house male
convicts, one of whom, a talented forger named Francis Greenway,
designed the three-story Georgian brick structure. It was turned
into a museum a few years ago, the best displays coming from an
unlikely source. Archaeologists discovered that rats had infested
the space between floors, making their nests with scraps of convict
clothing, shards of pottery and anything else they could get their
grubby claws into.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150,000 prisoners were transported to Australia before
the British stopped the practice during the 1860s. Their
descendants come to the barracks to imagine what it was like in the
long, gloomy rooms where convicts slept in closely packed hammocks.
</P>
<P>
   You can type their names into computers and read their rap
sheets: William Farrell, a Scottish plowman sentenced to life for
stealing bacon; William Moffatt, a bookbinder given seven years for
pilfering tea; John Johnson, a pickpocket punished with 50 lashes
for making too much noise in the isolation box, where he had been
sent for using obscene language.
</P>
<P>
   Australians used to have a difficult time talking about their
nation's convict roots. Their euphemism for it _ ``the stain'' _
sounded as if it were something that could be sent to the dry
cleaner instead of a fact. Fortunately, historians have begun to
write about the penal days, and the shame is lifting as people
become more comfortable with what is, after all, a remarkable story
of underdog triumph.
</P>
<P>
   They actually have a sense of humor about it at the barracks. On
the way out, we noticed a couple of unusual souvenirs in the gift
shop: a rubber rat and a plastic ball and chain.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosts of Gallipoli
</P>
<P>
   Southerners aren't the only people who have revered a lost
cause. When we arrived in Sydney, the papers were full of stories
about Anzac Day, a national holiday of war remembrance focused on a
catastrophic defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Anzac Day commemorates the Australian-New Zealand Army Corps,
the lads in the turned-up hats who rushed to Mother England's
defense during World War I. More than 60,000 Australians perished,
many of them in a disastrous 1915 landing on the Gallipoli
Peninsula in Turkey. The slaughter served as a traumatic coming of
age for a nation that had been independent only 14 years. April
marked the 85th anniversary, and with a new generation discovering
the tragic tale, a record crowd was expected for the Anzac parade
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   It was a gray, misty morning, yet more than a quarter of a
million spectators turned out. I noticed a khaki-uniformed Boy
Scout moving through the crowd handing out something green.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rosemary for remembrance,'' he explained, and planted a
sprig in the buttonhole of my breast pocket. I looked up and saw a
sepia-toned soldier peering out from a five-story banner, under the
words ``Lest We Forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ghostly aura, it was a surprisingly festive
procession. Men and women, wearing their Sunday best, marched down
the street grinning and waving behind standards that proclaimed
their part in the nation's battles. There were military
photographers from World War II, infantrymen from Korea, nurses
from Vietnam, peacekeepers from Bosnia. One unit strode by singing
``It's a long, long way to Tipperary.'' A pipe band skirled out
``Waltzing Matilda,'' the unofficial Australian anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, many of the old guard loosened their ties and
repaired to the taprooms along the route to lift mugs and play
two-ups, a gambling game that was popular in the trenches.
</P>
<P>
   Only 31 Australian veterans of the Great War are still living.
One of them, a farmer named Vivian Folland, served in both world
wars but wasn't seriously wounded. Then, as an old man, a kangaroo
attacked him. Reading about him in the paper after the parade, I
was relieved that he had survived; marsupial assault is no way for
a hero to go.
</P>
<P>
   Hang on to your snags
</P>
<P>
   We had sailed the harbor, strolled along it, dined beside it.
Now it was time for the ultimate harbor experience: We were going
to walk across it _ 450 feet above it _ atop the other great icon
of the waters, the Sydney Harbour Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Climbing the ``coathanger,'' as locals fondly call the span that
dominates their skyline, has become the hottest thing in adventure
tourism in Sydney. For days, we had looked up to see tiny figures
raising their arms at the crest of the graceful arch, the only
structure to cross the main body of the harbor. I wasn't sure I
could do it. I mean, 450 feet high out in the open? That's like
window-washing a 40-story building.
</P>
<P>
   We checked into the Bridgeclimb office on an overcast morning
and surrendered everything on our persons, down to coins and lip
balm. For safety reasons, nothing is allowed on the bridge. The
orientation video advised to take a deep breath if we felt dizzy or
our breakfast disagreed with us.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, a vacationer from Melbourne, threw me a wary look. ``You
didn't have any snags for breakfast, did you, mate?''
</P>
<P>
   I assured him I was not digesting sausages.
</P>
<P>
   We changed into gray jumpsuits (gray like the bridge, so as not
to distract motorists) and strapped on harnesses with clasps that
would keep us tethered to a cable that ran the length of the climb.
After some practice with the gear, we were ready to have a go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixteen people died building this bridge,'' our guide,
Michael, said as we stepped onto a catwalk beneath the roadway.
``It could have been worse. They budgeted for 32.''
</P>
<P>
   I pondered that actuarial analysis as we reached the south
pylon, a tower of stone that looked as mighty as the Brooklyn
Bridge. We started to scale a series of ladders. Commuter trains
rolled beneath us, sounding like roller coasters as they popped the
joints of the railbed. I tried not to look down.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, breathing hard, we reached the steel superstructure
that watches over the harbor like a giant eyebrow. The view was so
exhilarating that I almost forgot how high we were as we pressed on
to the pinnacle. The skyline was a toy. The Opera House unfolded
like an origami flower. The harbor was speckled with sails and
ferryboats and kayaks that looked like pickup sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Before we began our descent, I took one last look toward the
Pacific and noticed a fortress we had passed on our cruise. They
used to call it Pinchgut Island, the guide had said, probably
because incorrigible prisoners were sent there to waste away on
bread and water. On the flight back to Atlanta, I read a story
about the place that could serve as an epitaph for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   During the early 1800s, it seems, a blackheart by the name of
Francis Morgan was taken to Pinchgut to be hanged for murder. When
he was asked whether he had any final words, legend has it that he
gazed upon the waters that surrounded him and said, ``Well, it
certainly is a fine harbor you have here.''
</P>
<P>
   That it is.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there. It takes 20-plus hours to travel from Atlanta
to Sydney, usually connecting through Los Angeles. Air New Zealand,
Qantas and United fly the Pacific leg. Round-trip fares start
around $1,375. Australia requires an entry visa, which airlines and
travel agencies can usually handle when you book.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Time-tripping. Sydney is 14 hours ahead of Atlanta and on the
other side of the international date line. That means you could
leave on a Wednesday evening and not arrive until Friday morning _
Thursday just didn't happen. Coming back, you could depart Sydney
on a Friday morning and land in L.A. on the same day before you
left. Weird.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Money. The coin of the realm is a handy metaphor for
Australia's mingled cultures: Queen Elizabeth on one side, a mob of
kangaroos on the other _ and they call it a dollar. The current
exchange rate ($1 U.S. is worth about $1.70 Australian) makes for
some great bargains. But a new national sales tax of 10 percent
takes away part of the advantage. Tipping is not expected and
needn't exceed 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Olympics. The Games will run Sept. 15-Oct. 1, followed by the
Paralympics Oct. 18-29. For information on tickets and package
deals, contact the official ticket agent in the United States,
Cartan Tours, at 1-800-818-1998 or www.cartan.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to stay. Sydney has 21,000 hotel rooms, one-fourth the
number of metro Atlanta. With such a small supply, it pays to book
ahead. We bunked at the Novotel Darling Harbour, a chain hotel with
spectacular skyline views and easy access to public transit. A
bargain at $132 a night. Our last evening in Australia was spent
downtown at the Grace Hotel, a converted art deco office building
where Gen. Douglas MacArthur had his headquarters before returning
to the Philippines during World War II. Doubles start around $150.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to shop. The Strand Arcade and the Queen Victoria
Building are two of the most elegant shopping centers you'll ever
see. Both built in the 1890s, they contain dozens of exquisite but
expensive boutiques. (Don't miss the Royal Clock at the QVB; it
dramatizes scenes from British history on the hour, including the
beheading of King Charles.) Harbourside is a useful festival
marketplace on Darling Harbour, a redeveloped area reminiscent of
Baltimore's Inner Harbor. For Olympic souvenirs, visit the Sydney
2000 store on the Pitt Street Mall downtown.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to eat. Sydney has become one of the world's most
interesting places to dine. The best restaurants combine Asian
flavors with Australian ingredients, especially seafood. We enjoyed
Salt, a chic bistro in the fashionable Darlinghurst neighborhood
that was named the best new restaurant in town by the Sydney
Morning Herald. The spicy fare at Sailor's Thai, in the Rocks
district, showed us why people here love Asian food so much. For a
taste of old Sydney, we tried the beer-battered fish and chips at
Doyle's, a seafood place on the water at Watsons Bay. Our most
entertaining meal was the barbecued duck at BBQ King, a frantic,
Formica-tabletop joint in Chinatown, where deliciously bronzed
ducks hang in the window and the old chap at the register barks the
same send-off to every departing customer: ``B'bye, mate!'' Sounds
like an Aussie parrot.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Day trips. The Blue Mountains, so named because of the blue
haze cast by eucalyptus forests, begin only 50 miles west of
Sydney. Though not particularly lofty _ the peaks of North Georgia
are taller _ the Blues have some striking gorges and rock
formations. The Hunter Valley, two hours north of Sydney, is one of
Australia's premier wine regions, with dozens of inns and wineries
welcoming visitors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Reading up. I found the Access and Eyewitness guides to be the
most concise and usable. For that long flight, consider carrying
Robert Hughes' stirring history of Australia's penal colony roots,
``The Fatal Shore'' (Vintage, $17), or Geoffrey Moorhouse's
just-published ``Sydney: The Story of a City'' (Harcourt, $25).
Bill Bryson's new Australian travelogue, ``In a Sunburned Country''
(Broadway, $25), is a jolly read that ranges far beyond Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information. Australian Tourist Commission,
</P>
<P>
   1-800-433-2877; www.australia.com.
</P>
<P>
   _Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
