<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9256 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-FILMS23-COX     07-21 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBAF films showcase hope
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Young people _ struggling against poverty, physical handicaps
and adult-made wars _ can still be filled with dignity and want to
share what little they have.
</P>
<P>
   At least two of the 30 films to be shown at the High Museum's
Rich Auditorium during the National Black Arts Festival are
delicate tales of children and testaments to the human spirit. They
are:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Comedia Infantil'' (7:15 p.m. Aug. 1; $7; unrated; in
Portuguese with subtitles) is Swedish director Solveig Nordlund's
1998 film about Nelio (Sergio Titos), a boy orphaned by civil war
in Mozambique, who becomes a street urchin, healer and, ultimately,
a symbol of hope. It's a devastating, rough-around-the-edges work,
at rare times reminiscent of Francois Truffaut's ``The 400 Blows.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Equally moving is ``La Petite Vendeuse de Soleil'' or ``The
Little Girl Who Sold the Sun'' (1 p.m. July 31; $7; unrated; in
Wolof with subtitles), from writer-director Djibril Diop Mambety.
It's about Sili (Lissa Balera), a severely handicapped Senegalese
girl who bucks convention and begins to sell newspapers on the
streets of Dakar, using her wages to care for her blind grandmother
and the poor. There are long shots of her walking on two crutches,
pushing along her dangling bad leg. While at first these shots seem
tedious, they ultimately underscore the girl's persistence, her
will to fend for herself.
</P>
<P>
   Both works are part of the Pan African Film Festival (July
30-Aug. 5), one in a series of NBAF movie presentations. Included
are a family film series at Clark Atlanta University (Aug. 3-5) and
special screenings (Aug. 1-5) at Georgia-Pacific Auditorium, Rich
Auditorium and Spelman College's Cosby Center.
</P>
<P>
   Among the special screenings: selections from ``Hopes on the
Horizon: The Rise of New Africa'' (6 p.m. Aug. 1; free;
Georgia-Pacific Auditorium). It's the latest documentary from
Blackside Productions, which produced the remarkable ``Eyes on the
Prize,'' ``The Great Depression'' and ``America's War on Poverty,''
and relates Africa's struggles over the past decade to alter
political, cultural and economic relations.
</P>
<P>
   Also showing will be ``Free to Dance'' (4 p.m. Aug. 5; Cosby
Center; free with festival admission), a provocative and revealing
documentary about the development of African-American dance. The
film chronicles the careers of Katherine Dunham, Pearl Primus,
Talley Beatty, Donald McKaye and Alvin Ailey and looks deeply into
their primal connections to African tribal movements and rhythmic
gradations developed in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever been stymied by modern dance or felt disconnected
from the nuances of body movement as a means of emotional
expression, then ``Free to Dance'' is the film to help you
understand.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the family series at Clark Atlanta includes two works
from celebrated American director Charles Burnett: ``My Brother's
Wedding'' and ``To Sleep With Anger'' (noon-4 p.m. Aug. 3; free
with festival admission; Clark Atlanta University's Science and
Research Center). The latter stars Danny Glover as a storyteller
and tells of his effect on three generations of a modern family.
</P>
<P>
   At Rich Auditorium, more than two-thirds of the Pan African Film
Festival's full-length features and shorts come from outside the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The opening-night work, ``Orefu'' (6 p.m. July 30; $25; unrated;
in Portuguese with subtitles) is director Carols Diegues' retelling
of the classic ``Black Orpheus'' from the Brazilian point of view.
It will be shown with the Mauritius short ``A Lucy,'' director
Radhaa-Rajen Jaganathen's quick take on the woman considered by
some anthropologists to be the one from whom all humankind can
trace its lineage.
</P>
<P>
   Other foreign film highlights: director Idrissa Ouedraogo's
``Kini &AMP; Adams'' (7 p.m. Aug. 2; unrated), about two pals (one
played by Vusi Kunene of ``Cry Freedom'' and ``Cry the Beloved
Country'') who dream of repairing an old car so they can leave
their Zimbabwean village and head for a big city; ``Chickin Biznis:
The Whole Story'' (5 p.m. July 31), a South African comedy about a
businessman ruffling feathers in Soweto; and ``Dancehall Queen'' (1
p.m. Aug. 1; unrated), a Jamaican movie from music video pros Don
Letts and Rick Elgood about a struggling single mother who
discovers lively music (including Third World, Black Uhuru and
Sugar Minott) and relationships in the loud world of the dance
hall.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
