<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9257 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NBAF23-COX     07-21 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBAF23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cultural celebration emphasizes community
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 23.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture 100 kids locked in the Southwest YMCA on a Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   They've come to learn about everything from personal hygiene to
AIDS awareness to resume writing. When they aren't engaged in
spoken-word routines or ``funkercise'' classes, they munch on pizza
and slurp sodas. But their main objective is to soak up 250 years
of African-American history, from slavery to emancipation, so they
can act it out in a series of vignettes at the National Black Arts
Festival's children's village.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the new interactive NBAF.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be startled if a youngster posing as an Underground
Railroad agent approaches you on the Atlanta University Center
campus, where the NBAF will be spread out during its second weekend
Aug. 3-6, and whispers, ``Psssssss. Follow me to freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   While the festival will have its usual scattering of marquee
attractions around Atlanta _ Ashford and Simpson with Maya Angelou,
Sweet Honey in the Rock, the Broadway show ``It Ain't Nothing but
the Blues'' at the Fox Theatre _ this year's program will have a
decidedly more user-friendly vibe.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in its 12-year history, the festival is
charging a gate fee ($5) and consolidating many of its activities
on the grounds of southwest Atlanta's historically black colleges:
Clark Atlanta University, Spelman College, Morehouse College, the
Morehouse School of Medicine, Morris Brown College and the
Interdenominational Theological Center. Festival Executive Producer
Stephanie S. Hughley says ``tens of thousands'' of visitors are
expected for the 10-day celebration of African-American culture.
</P>
<P>
   It's Music Midtown meets an old-fashioned dinner on the grounds:
two stages showcasing such top-notch talent as hip-hop artists
Outkast and Goodie Mob, blues belter Francine Reed and the Georgia
Sea Island Singers. ``You don't need Luther Vandross,'' Hughley
says, joking about the public's fixation on big-name artists. ``You
can get him anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   By keeping many of its signature offerings (the artists market,
book fair and spoken-word panels) contained on campus, the festival
will help rein in what has been a confusing geographical hodgepodge
in years past. Once on campus, visitors will have free access to
performances, visual arts exhibits and discussions of this year's
theme, ``Artists as Agents of Social Change.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, festival ramblers might listen to Atlanta author
Pearl Cleage read from her novel ``I Wish I Had a Red Dress'' at
Spelman's Cosby Center. Or duck into a literary salon with Haki
Madhubuti, Sonia Sanchez and Askia Toure. Or watch a screening of
the American Dance Festival documentary ``Free to Dance.'' And they
can graze on everything from spicy Caribbean fare to barbecue ribs
to healthy vegetarian offerings _ food from 15 vendors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it brings the festival taste back,'' says Collette
Hopkins, the Clark Atlanta University educator who conceived the
children's village. ``In the past, you got out to (the artists
market at) Greenbriar Mall and you worried, `Could I make it back
in time? Could I make it across town? Could I find a place to
park?'''
</P>
<P>
   That's the logistical bonus. The other benefits may be more
spiritual.
</P>
<P>
   M. Akua McDaniel, director of the Spelman College Museum of Fine
Art, says that having the NBAF on campus is ``a homecoming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been nearly 30 years since the AUC has been seen as the
cultural epicenter of Atlanta, so it is fitting that the arts
return to this place,'' says McDaniel, whose gallery is hosting an
exhibit of African-American art inspired by dance.
</P>
<P>
   Because parking on campus can be difficult, visitors are urged
to take MARTA, then hop one of the special buses that will be
running from the West End, Vine City and Ashby Street MARTA
stations to the AU Center.
</P>
<P>
   With the festival's history of managerial neglect _ a combined
deficit of more than $1 million over the past two installments _
sponsors have been somewhat skittish about giving money. But
Hughley, who returned last year to run the festival she helped
start 12 years ago, says she has raised $1.6 million of her $1.8
million operating budget and that another $3 million in donation
requests are still on the table. Major sponsors this year include
the Coca-Cola Co., the Fulton County Arts Council, DaimlerChrysler,
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution and the Arthur M. Blank Family
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Hughley's intention is to turn a biennial celebration into a
year-round community-service organization that fosters education
and arts partnerships. That means programs such as the children's
village, which is meant to live on after the festival. The project
includes some 30 Atlanta teachers who will take the curriculums
they have developed over the summer back to their schools this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   It means collaborations such as the one between Atlanta's
Ballethnic Dance Company and choreographers Salia Sanou and Seydou
Boro of Burkina Faso, whose work will be performed this year. It
means Friday's opening ceremonies and Sunday's block party at the
NBAF's Studioplex headquarters on Auburn Avenue _ free events to
which the public is invited. It means collaborations with local
arts presenters Spivey Hall (where the Geri Allen Trio will
appear), Variety Playhouse (where Mali blues singer Ali Farka Toure
will perform) and numerous others.
</P>
<P>
   While the festival's heartbeat will be at the AU Center, there
will be dozens of related events all over town, as always.
Noteworthy bookings include Los Angeles' Pan African Film Festival,
which is screening some 30 films at the Woodruff Arts Center;
spoken-word and late-night jam sessions at the Yin Yang Cafe and
the Renaissance Hotel on West Peachtree Street; and morning
literary discussions at the hotel. These events, priced at $5 to
$10 and the hidden jewels of the festival, give it intellectual
vigor and a national reputation.
</P>
<P>
   It's also possible to enjoy the festival without spending a
cent. The Atlanta Symphony Orchestra will play for free at Ebenezer
Baptist Church. Theatre Emory will do a free staged reading of
Nobel Prize-winning writer Wole Soyinka's ``The Man Died,'' with
such luminous speakers as actor Bill Nunn and former Spelman
president and Emory professor Johnnetta Cole, who will lead a
discussion with Soyinka after the performance. And the Havana-based
Grupo Vocal Baobab, which blends Yoruba chants and Afro-Cuban
percussion, will give a free concert at Georgia State University.
</P>
<P>
   As Hughley says, it's all about returning the festival to its
rightful owners, the people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can convince all your neighbors that this is important,
then you have a reason to be,'' she says. ``But if the neighbors
don't think you are important, you can't survive. So we just want
to be important to our neighbors, and then the nation and the world
will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   National Black Arts Festival 2000: ``Connect. Inspire.
Transform.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday through Aug. 6. The multidisciplinary event includes
dance, theater, music, film, literary, spoken-word and visual arts
offerings at more than 20 venues around Atlanta. $5-$45; many are
free. Information: 404-730-0177 or www.nbaf.org. Ticket events:
404-249-6400 or www.ticketmaster.com.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
