<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9258 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS23-COX     07-21 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In the afternoon of life, novelist Larry McMurtry takes a
ruminative road
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 23.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESSAYS
</P>
<P>
   ``Roads: Driving America's Great Highways'' by Larry McMurtry.
Simon &AMP; Schuster. $25. 206 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The most resonant phrase in all of ``Huckleberry Finn'' is
Huck's spunky declaration, ``I reckon I got to light out for the
territory.'' Huck was young, and so was the country. If things
weren't working out in one place, a man picked up what he owned and
hit the road.
</P>
<P>
   Now the road leads _ metaphorically or otherwise _ to the dead
ends of divorce or death or plain emptiness. A man doesn't head for
somewhere as much as from somewhere. A man hits the road when he's
run out of gas. John Updike, in ``Rabbit at Rest,'' has Harry
Angstrom driving south in the rain on I-95, away from it all: ``He
even turns off the radio, he feels so battered by pellets of
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The novel ends with a single word: ``Enough.'' Not affirmation
but ennui.
</P>
<P>
   In a very different novel, Larry McMurtry's ``Lonesome Dove,'' a
wandering Woodrow F. Call digs a narrow grave and lowers into it
the body of Augustus McCrae. ``Yesterday's gone,'' Gus had once
told Call. ``We can't get it back.'' Wherever his dead friend was
headed, Call had lost his sense of direction. ``Maybe,'' he says,
``you just go back to wherever you was happiest.''
</P>
<P>
   Different as they are, you could make a strong case that both
novels _ winners of the Pulitzer Prize for fiction _ could only
have been written by a man. In their restlessness, in their
melancholy pursuit of mirages, they are among the purest
expressions of American life that our literature has produced.
Wherever the rainbow ends, the road never quite gets there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movement,'' V.S. Pritchett wrote, ``is one of the great
consolers of human woe; movement, a process of continual migration,
is the history of America.''
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry titled one of his early novels ``Movin' On,'' and he
has needed over the years to get behind the wheel and put miles
between himself and wherever the sun rose. ``Roads'' is a
deceptively simple book _ a twilight rumination amid reports from
the interstate. Not that there's not plenty about the arteries
carrying Americans north and south, east and west. McMurtry is the
early-rising, long-haul traveler, forsaking the ``blue highways''
that beckoned William Least Heat-Moon for the roads he likens to
the great rivers of transport in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   He prefers driving from east to west, when he can, and north to
south, and along the way offers observations alternately witty and
inconsequential. Does it really matter that Arkansans are the most
passive-aggressive of drivers? Is it any revelation that Montana,
of all the lower 48, is the vestibule to heaven?
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there are passages as pithy as those McMurtry
wrote 30 years ago in his almost classic ``In a Narrow Grave:
Essays on Texas'': ``It was almost dark when
</P>
<P>
   I crossed the Monongahela River, after which the road steadily
worsened, as if, with only 30 miles of Pennsylvania left, the
highway department had simply given up on it. Perhaps, too, the
people along that stretch of highway had given up on themselves. I
passed an adult video store whose neon sign was the brightest thing
to be seen in all of western Pennsylvania.''
</P>
<P>
   In his best work, McMurtry's bittersweet humor has played
counterpoint to the elegiac. The latter note he struck often and
sublimely in ``In a Narrow Grave.'' (``The cowboy has been
diminished, but the Indian was destroyed. The great homeward march
of the Northern Cheyenne in 1878 is a subject for a Sophocles, and
was lucky to draw even a John Ford.'')
</P>
<P>
   That note is conspicuously absent in ``Roads.'' But the further
one progresses _ and it's a quick drive _ something more personal
than interstate travel takes shape: McMurtry knows his best work is
behind him. A substantial body of work it is _ more than 20 novels
as well as collections of essays and film criticism. But the infant
who rocked in his lap when he was an unknown college English
teacher in Fort Worth, typing away at ``Horseman, Pass By'' (the
movies settled for the less poetic ``Hud''), is grown and a
professional musician. McMurtry himself is in his 60s _ not old,
really _ but heart bypass surgery in 1991 left him feeling that a
part of him had ``died, been lost, vanished, slipped away.''
</P>
<P>
   You have the sense, by the end, that McMurtry is not just
retracing old routes but trying to retrieve what has been lost. The
earliest road he knew, the one near the ranch house in North Texas,
was Highway 281. It runs from Manitoba to McAllen, Texas, at the
Mexican border: ``When I asked my grandfather _ the person assigned
to deal with my questions when I was three or four _ where the road
went, he would merely allow that it went to Oklahoma. An old man
then, near the end of his own road, he could see no reason why
anyone would need to go farther north than Oklahoma.''
</P>
<P>
   All roads don't lead north, but that's where you eventually want
your compass to point. In traveling the great highways, McMurtry
has been wanting to go back _ like Woodrow Call _ to where he was
happiest.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
