<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYDNEY-LINGO223-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Even yobbos and bludgers love colorful `Strine' lingo
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 23
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the delights of visiting Australia is the language.
Strine, as Australians call their colorful brand of English,
descends primarily from the Cockney spoken by working-class Brits
200 years ago. Here's a beginner's glossary:
</P>
<P>
   Arvo. Afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Billabong. A water hole in an otherwise dry streambed. One of
many Aboriginal words in Strine.
</P>
<P>
   Bludger. A bum or deadbeat (from old criminal slang), as in this
graffito we saw in Sydney: ``Karl Scully is a bludger.''
</P>
<P>
   Bum bag. Fanny pack. The word ``fanny'' will get you slapped in
Australia; it refers to a woman's privates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush tucker. Roots, berries, insects and other wild foods that
are part of the traditional diet of Aborigines. From a now rare
English term for eating (to ``tuck away'').
</P>
<P>
   Drongo. A stupid person.
</P>
<P>
   Fair dinkum. The genuine truth.
</P>
<P>
   Good on ya. An exclamation of approval.
</P>
<P>
   Jackeroo. A ranch hand.
</P>
<P>
   Lollies. Candy.
</P>
<P>
   Mateship. The Australian ideal of male friendship and teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   Middy. A small glass of beer.
</P>
<P>
   Ocker. An uncultivated Australian male.
</P>
<P>
   Oz. Australia. Shortened from Ozzie, which is how Aussies
pronounce it.
</P>
<P>
   Poms. The British. According to conventional wisdom, it derived
from the letters POME (Prisoner of Mother England), said to have
been branded on convict clothing. The editors of the Australian
National Dictionary disagree; they say it sprang from the Aussie
penchant for nonsensical sound-alike slang. In this case, any
British immigrant became a ``pomegranate,'' shortened to pom.
</P>
<P>
   Shout. To treat everyone to another round, as in: ``I've got
this shout, mates.''
</P>
<P>
   Snappies. Photos. Australians love to turn words into slang
diminutives. On a tour of the Olympic venues, a PR person told us:
``Take all the snappies you want, and if that isn't enough, we have
plenty of piccies.''
</P>
<P>
   Tall poppy. Someone who acts selfishly or displays too much
individualism. The Tall Poppy Syndrome is the opposite of mateship.
</P>
<P>
   Whinge. To complain or whine.
</P>
<P>
   Yobbo. Yet another term for a person lacking refinement. (Do we
discern a pattern here?)
</P>
<P>
   _Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
