<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-RANCH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BUSH, HEAVEN IS A HOT, DUSTY SPREAD IN TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRAWFORD, Texas _ ``It's going to be a little dusty,'' Gov.
George W. Bush announced as he walked toward a sport utility
vehicle and set off down one of the chalky dirt roads that snake
through his 1,583-acre ranch near this blink-and-you've-missed-it
town.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't kidding. The wheels turned, the vehicle lurched
forward and a thick, grimy powder filled the air, already heavy
from the 100-degree heat. The cattle up ahead looked torpid and
ornery. Bush looked happy and utterly relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   Here it was: the Texas governor's idea of heaven. Not a cabin on
Lake Tahoe or a chalet in Vail, Colo., but a parched, remote patch
of land without a remotely decent restaurant or hotel nearby.
During the Republican primaries, Bush openly pined for it, telling
an audience or two how eager he was to return. After he cinched the
party's presidential nomination, he arranged his schedule so that
he could spend almost every weekend here, even though that meant
advisers sometimes had to make the two-hour drive northwest from
Austin to see him.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday, he settled in for a long weekend during which he
said he would finally reach perhaps the most important decision of
his presidential campaign: Who would be his running mate. But
first, he took a few hours to give a group of reporters a tour of
what would be a kind of western White House if he won the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   He did not pretend that he actually worked the land here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm what you call a windshield rancher,'' Bush said. ``I get
in my pickup and drive all over the place, ranching through the
windshield.''
</P>
<P>
   That means he looks at the pretty scenery, and there is plenty:
a river, a canyon, cliffs and oak trees so broad and gnarled that
they look like illustrations from a spooky fantasy book. Deer and
wild turkey roam the fields.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also plenty of relatively flat land with grass that
looks desperate for some liquid refreshment. It is in no sense a
conventional vacation or weekend home, and that is one of the
reasons Bush likes it so much. If fits his vision of himself as a
kind of rugged, simple man without finicky airs or fancy appetites,
and it fits into his claim of being someone whose soul is rooted
somewhere far away from Washington. That was clearly one of the
reasons he was eager to share it.
</P>
<P>
   A new house for the Bushes is under construction on the
property, and as Bush and his wife, Laura, walked reporters through
the structure, Bush said that he had made few demands about the
design of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked for a king-sized bed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And a good shower,'' Mrs. Bush chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``And a good shower,'' Bush agreed. ``That's about all that I
care about.''
</P>
<P>
   At their side was the architect whom they hired for the project,
and the house that they modestly described as a three-bedroom ranch
sprawled over perhaps 4,000 square feet, although it was impossible
to know. The architect had been forbidden by the Bushes to provide
the dimensions, just as he was not allowed to estimate how much the
construction would cost. There was a another two-bedroom guest
house being built beside the Bushes' domain, plus a separate
garage.
</P>
<P>
   And the estimated $1.3 million that real estate agents have said
Bush must have paid about a year ago to buy this property, was an
indication that no matter how ordinary Bush considered his
lifestyle, it was anything but.
</P>
<P>
   The tour that Bush gave Friday also reflected his diligent
efforts over the last several months to forge a friendly, informal
relationship with the press corps. He invited representatives of
most of the nation's largest daily newspapers and all the major
television networks.
</P>
<P>
   Although has conducted some campaign business here, the ranch is
mainly the preferred refuge of a man who has vowed not to let
himself get consumed by his political ambitions and has worn that
pledge as a badge of honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never forget you're running for president,'' he said, even
on more than a thousand acres far from the madding crowd. ``But it
gives me perspective. It gives me a lot of balance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
