<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9273 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ETHNIC22-COX     07-21 1390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHNIC22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No matter how you sell it, it's still
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dawna Cekuta has seen all kinds of deal breakers during her 17
years as a real estate broker.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, she admits, was a first.
</P>
<P>
   One of her home listings was under contract to an Asian couple.
But the deal fell through when their feng shui consultant informed
them the house did not have good energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in my experience that a deal has fallen
through because of feng shui,'' said Cekuta of Amelia Bullock
Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   It probably won't be the last.
</P>
<P>
   Cekuta and other area real estate brokers increasingly are
learning to work with clients from backgrounds different than their
own, with different cultures and ways of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that we're a global economy and we have to
be sensitive to other cultures,'' said Barbara Wallace, co-owner of
Amelia Bullock Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, the U.S. housing industry has watched its
traditional market _ typically white, middle-class couples _ slowly
dwindle. In its place is a growing multicultural market, fueled in
large part by a surge in immigration.
</P>
<P>
   And, thanks largely to the region's high-tech industry, Central
Texas has seen a large influx of people from around the world. That
includes the arrival and expansion of companies with Asian ties,
including Samsung Austin Semiconductor of South Korea and Tokyo
Electron.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, 2,000 people moved to the area from outside the United
States, according to Regional Financial Associates. In 1998, 4,600
of the 24,300 people who moved to Austin came from other countries,
including India, Vietnam, China and Mexico. From 1990 to 1998, the
Austin area's Asian population jumped 75 percent to 34,900.
</P>
<P>
   According to research from the Joint Center for Housing Studies
at Harvard University, the homeownership rate for immigrants in the
age group 25 to 34 _ considered the prime home-buying years _
jumped 17.6 percent to 39.1 percent between 1990 and 1996. At least
51 percent of the foreign-born U.S. population are homeowners,
compared with 68 percent of those born in the United States,
according to the Fannie Mae Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate agents realize they need to be sensitive to the
needs of their increasingly diverse clientele if they want a piece
of this market.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of Austin-area home builders also have adapted
their marketing and merchandising efforts. Many are hiring
bilingual employees and learning about different cultures. Some
have developed creative financing plans that, in some cases, enable
people to purchase a home with no down payment.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, foreign-born households accounted for just more than
10 percent of the U.S. population, according to the Harvard
center's 1999 State of the Nation's Housing study. The U.S.
foreign-born population is expected to continue to account for a
substantial share of household growth and home sales.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to immigrants, minority home buyers are becoming a
larger share of the market. The Joint Center for Housing Studies
also reports that African Americans and Hispanics accounted for
more than 30 percent of the increase in the number of homeowners in
recent years. And they will account for three-quarters of the
nation's population growth in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Realtors three years ago started a
diversity program, including its ``At Home with Diversity''
certification. The program helps agents learn about different
minority groups, cultures and ethnic backgrounds, and encourages
more people of diverse ethnic backgrounds to become real estate
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate broker Earline Wakefield's copy of ``Kiss, Bow or
Shake Hands'' _ a book about how to do business in 60 countries _
is well-worn. With her growing roster of international clients, she
keeps the book close at hand to brush up on the business practices
and etiquette of different countries. Many other agents around the
area also have a copy on their bookshelves.
</P>
<P>
   A person's culture ``is something that does affect how people
select a home, where they select a home, how they'll pay for it and
how they
</P>
<P>
   do business,'' Wakefield said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real estate is bought and sold much differently in other
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   For real estate agents, it may be as simple as bowing instead of
shaking hands when meeting a new client. It could mean hiring an
interpreter familiar with a foreign home buyer's language. One
Austin real estate agent made sure to schedule a visit to a mosque
during a house-hunting trip so the client could say her afternoon
prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Cultural differences also can have a major influence on the type
of house a family buys.
</P>
<P>
   Asian and Latin American immigrants, for example, are much more
likely to have a parent, adult siblings, cousins and aunts or
uncles living in their households, according to the State of the
Nation's Housing. That means they may opt for larger houses with
more bedrooms. Showing a small house can be an affront.
</P>
<P>
   In areas with large Asian and Hispanic populations, builders are
showing larger floor plans with more bedrooms, said Gopal
Ahluwalia, assistant staff vice president of economic mortgage
finances and housing policy for the National Association of Home-
builders.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's feng shui.
</P>
<P>
   When working with many Asian clients, a good knowledge of feng
shui _ which means ``wind and water''_ is a must. With the
3,000-year-old practice of feng shui (pronounced fung shway), one's
physical surroundings are thought to bring balance and success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a few agents around town have learned about feng shui,''
said Marty Halseth, vice president of Prudential Owens Realty
Tejas- Lakeway.
</P>
<P>
   It sets down principles for everything from how a house sits on
its lot to the placement of walls and windows.
</P>
<P>
   Some examples of bad feng shui include a doorway that opens onto
stairs (good energy will escape up the stairs), open floor plans
where the front and rear doors line up (good energy will go
straight out the back door without lingering in the house) and
overhead beams (thought to provide a negative down-- ard pressure).
According to -- eng -- hui, an L-shaped house can raise the divorce
rate and increase the chance of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   An address with the numbers six, eight or nine is good, while
some Chinese and Southeast Asians steer clear of houses with the
number four in the address because in Chinese it sounds like the
word for death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buyers are looking for particular directions and floor- plans
that will enhance their well being,'' said Kimla Dodds, a real
estate agent with Prudential Owens Realty Tejas-Lakeway and a
consultant and practitioner with Austin-based Design with Feng Shui
Today.
</P>
<P>
   Dodds, who charges $125 an hour, said she has gotten a growing
number of calls from home buyers relocating from California who
want feng shui consultations.
</P>
<P>
   Although Austin has only two dozen or so feng shui consultants,
Southern California has more than 300 for agents and builders to
call. An entire subdiv-- -- ion in San Jose _ an area with a large
number of Asian home buyers _ was designed according to the
principles of feng shui.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, I'd just heard the term feng shui,'' said
Cindy Goldrick, a real estate broker with Wilson &AMP; Go-- drick
Realtors. ``Now you can almost count on it being important to
almost any client from Southeast Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   When Goldrick was working with a couple from Singapore, she
learned that they were concerned with the feng shui of their new
house. So she worked hard to find a house that faced in the right
direction, sat back from the street and had certain numbers in the
address. She even made sure the sales contract price had the lucky
sixes and eights in it.
</P>
<P>
   Goldrick viewed it as she would any other request by a home
buyer, whether it be a desire for a swimming pool, a preference for
three bedrooms or four, or a distaste for two-story houses. Her
job, she said, is to make the client happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``To certain people, this is an important criteria of their home
purchase,'' she said. ``It's part of their culture and philosophy,
and we respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
