<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-21 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: BOMB FACTORY SEIZED
</P>
<P>
   Police raided an apartment in Spain's northern Basque region and
discovered an arsenal of explosives, bomb-making equipment and an
apparent hit list of politicians prepared by the armed Basque
separatist group ETA. The group has been blamed for six attacks
over the past nine days.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: SPEED TRAP
</P>
<P>
   A car carrying Home Secretary Jack Straw, a champion of ``zero
tolerance'' for speeders, was stopped by a highway patrol earlier
this month going 103 mph, police said. Under guidelines laid down
by Straw's department, a motorist exceeding 100 mph can be banned
from driving and fined up to $1,200. Police say they have not
decided whether to charge the detective driving the car. At the
time, Straw was late for a Labor party meeting with Prime Minister
Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: ONLY A FAIR ATTRACTION
</P>
<P>
   The Expo 2000 World Fair in Hanover opened a new advertising
campaign to boost disappointing attendance. The ads feature the
British actor Peter Ustinov and the German actress Verona Feldbusch
with the slogan ``This happens just once. It will never come
again.'' Four million people have visited the fair since it opened
eight weeks ago _ less than a quarter the number expected.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: FALUN GONG ARRESTS
</P>
<P>
   The police continued to arrest members of the outlawed Falun
Gong spiritual movement in Beijing's Tiananmen Square, and police
were also posted at the city's railroad and bus stations to stop
Falun Gong followers from entering the capital. State media, said
the movement has evolved from an ``anti-science, anti-humankind,
anti-society cult organization into a political organization openly
opposing the government and a tool of overseas anti-China forces.''
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: ANTI-MISSILE DEFENSE DRIVE
</P>
<P>
   Beijing is expected to take its campaign against Washington's
proposed anti-missile system to the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations next week during a regional security meeting in Bangkok.
Beijing opposes the proposed plan because it would neutralize
China's limited nuclear arsenal. President Vladimir Putin of Russia
joined China in condemning the plan while in Beijing this week and
China hopes for similar support from ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH, NORTH KOREA: MINISTERS TO MEET
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers of North and South Korea will hold their
first-ever meeting next week to discuss cooperation following last
month's summit meeting, said Choi Young Jin, the South's deputy
foreign minister. The talks will take place in Bangkok, coinciding
with the regional meeting of ASEAN nations.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: SUHARTO-LINKED PROPERTY SEIZED
</P>
<P>
   As part of their investigation of former President Suharto,
prosecutors seized an office building owned by charitable
foundations he is accused of manipulating for financial gain. On
Thursday the prosecutors impounded a mansion belonging to the
treasurer of one of the fundations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
