<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9279 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v BC-HOMEDEPOT22-COX     07-21 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEDEPOT22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Would you like a loan with that hammer?
 &HT;    By Jeff Ostrowski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Depot is catering to do-it-yourselfers who just can't wait
for their savings accounts to catch up with their desire to remodel
their kitchens and bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer this month began offering home-improvement loans of
$3,000 to $30,000 at its dozen stores in Palm Beach County and the
Treasure Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Customers can apply for the loans at Home Depot stores. For
those with good credit and sufficient income, approval comes in
less than 10 minutes, said Heather Wilson, credit marketing manager
for Atlanta-based Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowers get plastic cards _ not credit cards _ good for six
months. The cards let customers buy products against their credit
lines.
</P>
<P>
   The borrower repays the loan over a term as long as 10 years.
Interest rates range from 10.99 to 14.99 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The credit lines can be turned into home-equity loans so that
the interest is tax-deductible, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot markets the loans, but financial giant GE Capital is
the lender.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's chief rival, North Carolina-based Lowe's, tried
similar loans in 1998 in Indianapolis, but customers weren't
interested, said Lowe's spokeswoman Jule Eller.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, financial planners warn consumers not to be lured
into taking on too much debt through the Home Depot program.
</P>
<P>
   Home improvement projects typically aren't emergencies, so
consumers would be better off saving to pay for materials later
rather than borrowing the money now, said Mary Lou Nason, a North
Palm Beach financial planner and chairman of the Financial Planning
Association of the Gold Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand why (Home Depot) is doing this, because they're
in the business of getting people to spend money on home
improvements,'' Nason said. ``I would caution people to look at
other ways of finding the money instead of taking on debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
