<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9296 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CARS-COLLECTING-2TAKE     07-21 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-COLLECTING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR COLLECTING: AUTOS THAT MOVE ON SURF OR TURF 
</HEADLINE>
   by KEITH MARTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Has your car left you up the creek without a paddle? If you had
an Amphicar, you'd simply float back to shore. Or you could relax,
catch some rays and have a cool drink after you drop the anchor.
(What? Your car doesn't have an anchor?)
</P>
<P>
   Both the anchor and the paddle were options on the Amphicar,
built in 1961-68 by IWK in West Germany. Sales brochures described
it as ``the car that swims.''
</P>
<P>
   The Amphicar's origins are misty. Some think it was designed to
let commuters avoid traffic by diving into the canals of Northern
Europe. But of the 3,700 built, more than 3,000 came to the United
States, where they were promoted as dual-purpose recreational
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The car was powered by an 1,147-cubic-centimeter, 43-horsepower
engine built by Triumph of England. The engine was mounted in a
watertight compartment at the rear. There were separate
transmissions for land and water; a conventional floor shifter
worked the four-speed manual (with internal parts by Porsche) that
was used on terra firma. A nearby lever activated the two nylon
propellers at the rear.
</P>
<P>
   As one might expect, these odd ducks appeal to collectors with a
sense of humor and an adventurous streak. In 1965, two Amphicars
made news by crossing the English Channel. One stalled halfway over
after a bilge-pump failure let water into the engine compartment;
that car was towed by the other to France, where they were met on
the beach by surprised customs officials.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Gordon, 60, of La Habra, Calif., recalled driving an
Amphicar from Detroit to Mexico in his college days. He took it
into the sea to Cozumel, he said, but the engine stopped running
when his bilge pump failed. ``We drifted for two days and landed on
a deserted island,'' he said. A tugboat eventually came to the
rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has also crossed Lake Michigan. Compared with boats that
bob atop the waves, the Amphicar ``goes through the waves rather
than over them,'' he said. ``It's a little like being in a
submarine.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's experience did not sour him on Amphicars. He now owns
Gordon Imports, the primary supplier of parts worldwide. He also
makes replacement parts.
</P>
<P>
   Launching an Amphicar requires some forethought, as the
steel-bodied car would quickly sink if not properly sealed. Before
taking the plunge, the driver must lock the doors with a lever that
makes them watertight. (Oversized rubber seals, similar to those on
a refrigerator, are available to prevent what owners refer to as
``door dribble.'') The door lock also prevents distracted
passengers from opening a door while in the water, which has an
immediate, negative effect on the car's buoyancy.
</P>
<P>
   But most important is the drain plug for the bilge and engine
compartment, which must be tightly secured. Owners tell a story,
perhaps apocryphal, about a German owner who proudly drove his new
Amphicar into a river but forgot to secure the plug. The car
quickly settled to the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little scary the first time you go down the boat
ramp,'' said Jeff Sweet of Gloversville, N.Y., president of the
International Amphicar Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get that feeling like, `Is this going to work?' It seems
like the nose is going in the water a long ways before it picks up
and starts to float.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then the driver shifts the water-drive lever to the
forward-propellers position and the car swims away. The front
wheels act as twin rudders; the steering wheel is used in the usual
manner. As with most boats, there is no need to shift in the water;
the accelerator controls the speed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As in a boat, there are no brakes. Marc Schlemmer, 32, an
Amphicar owner in Hebron, Ky., said, ``The most common thing every
Amphicar owner has done, and is embarrassed to admit, is they push
the brake pedal while they're in the water.''
</P>
<P>
   When new, the Amphicar reached 75 miles an hour on land and 8 on
the water. ``But it's no fun to go boating with the engine revved
that loud,'' Sweet said. ``Five miles an hour is cruising speed.''
Performance on land is leisurely, too: 43 seconds from zero to 60
mph.
</P>
<P>
   Schlemmer described how it feels to set sail:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unnatural to be sitting in the water in a car. You
have your left arm on the window sill. You're looking in the
rearview mirror. You're driving. You feel low in the water. You're
sitting at about water level. Your feet are below water level. You
can easily drape your arm over the door and drag it in the
water.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Handling, on sea or land, was never the Amphicar's forte. In a
'60s road test, the vehicle was described as ``not a very good car,
and not a very good boat either.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like driving a helium balloon,'' said Billy Syx,
who operates East Coast Amphicar, a restoration and repair shop in
Mays Landing, N.J. ``The cars weigh 2,200 pounds, have 10 inches of
ground clearance, a short wheelbase and narrow track.''
</P>
<P>
   If only the Amphicar moved fast enough, it could be a car, a
boat and a plane. Because of its high, blunt front end, it catches
the wind at highway speeds. This trait, combined with the engine's
weight at the rear, tends to make the front lift up. The steering
can become quite vague.
</P>
<P>
   But the mere fact that the Amphicar covered both surf and turf
set it apart, and it has a cult following. Sweet's club has some
250 members in 13 countries. Besides its Web address,
www.amphicar.com, other sites include www.amphicars.com and
www.amphicar.net.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh-annual Amphicar Swim In, held by the club and
organized by Schlemmer, will be July 28-30 in Celina, Ohio, as part
of the Celina Lake Festival. About 40 cars are registered; they
will parade through town and plunge into Grand Lake St. Marys for a
group swim.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always loved cars and boats, so it made sense that I
would own an Amphicar,'' said Rick Young, of Murfreesboro, Tenn. In
1970, Young's father purchased a second-hand Amphicar for $600.
``He used to fish out of it,'' Young said. Today, he and his father
own three Amphicars, which they take for cruises on the Stones
River in Tennessee. ``It's very relaxing,'' Young said. ``I would
compare it to golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Some government agencies classify the Amphicar as both boat and
car.
</P>
<P>
   Schlemmer has two titles for his '65 model; it wears auto
license plates as well as boat registration numbers on the front
fender.
</P>
<P>
   Complying with contemporary nautical regulations, Amphicars have
red and green lights on a chromed pod on the hood, with a white
light in the rear. When new, Amphicars offered options like the
anchor ($12.95), anchor cleats ($10.85) and a marine kit consisting
of a fire extinguisher, floating cushions, flares and a paddle
($49.25). The car had a list price of $3,395 in 1961, or about
$20,000 in today's dollars. Increasingly strict safety and
emissions regulations, for cars and boats, contributed to the car's
demise.
</P>
<P>
   As one might expect of a steel-body car immersed in water _
often salt water _ the maintenance needs are high, like those of a
car and a boat combined. In water, the steering mechanism,
driveshaft and brakes are submerged. Frequent lubrication is
necessary; there are nearly 30 grease fittings on the steering and
suspension. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Amphicar is not the only wheeled beast in the water. Among a
number of amphibious military vehicles, the German-built
Schwimmwagen (of World War II vintage) is the most carlike and
coveted by collectors. Currently, Dutton Marine in Worthing,
England, produces amphibious cars that use mechanical parts from
Ford Fiestas and Suzuki Samurais.
</P>
<P>
   While prices of pristine Amphicars can top $35,000, ``a car
that's been restored, that's in nice condition, that swims good and
runs good, is worth $18,000,'' Schlemmer said. ``If it runs at all,
it's worth $10,000. Anything that swims at all is $12,000.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That is roughly equivalent to the price of a vintage MGB sports
car. Since both are convertibles, either would be at home on a
topless beach. But only the Amphicar would dare to venture into the
waves. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 2102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9302 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-WACO-REPORT-ART-560(2     07-21 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACO-REPORT-ART-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL COUNSEL CLEARS GOVERNMENT IN WACO DEATHS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)   (ART ADV: Photos NYT21 and NYT22 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ John Danforth, the special counsel investigating the
1993 tear-gas assault by federal agents on the Branch Davidian
compound, Friday issued a sweeping report that cleared Attorney
General Janet Reno and the government of any wrongdoing in the
deadly episode.
</P>
<P>
   Reminding a crowded news conference of his initial pledge to
answer the ``dark questions'' surrounding the case, Danforth, a
former Republican senator from Missouri, did not mince words. He
declared that agents did not shoot at the Branch Davidians and did
not start the fire that destroyed the compound on April 19, 1993,
claiming the lives of about 80 people.
</P>
<P>
   He said the military was not used improperly and that the
government ``did not engage in a massive conspiracy and cover-up.''
Danforth placed blame and responsibility for the deaths on members
of the religious sect, particularly the group's leader, David
Koresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are certain,'' he said, reading from a statement. ``And I
give you these conclusions with 100 percent certainty. ``The blame
rests squarely on the shoulders of David Koresh. ``This is not a
close call.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Danforth exonerated the government, he also rebuked it.
He spoke pointedly and passionately about how public confidence in
government had eroded because certain officials failed to speak
candidly about aspects of the case. His own appointment by Reno had
come in September after disclosures that agents of the FBI, despite
repeated denials, had fired pyrotechnic tear-gas canisters capable
of starting a fire into the compound on the day it burned.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Danforth said that Reno and other high-ranking
government officials had not known that agents fired such
projectiles. But he blamed ``a few government lawyers and an FBI
agent'' for concealing the use of the projectiles. They were
launched hours before the fire and did not contribute to it,
Danforth said.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that FBI agents fired three pyrotechnic
rounds at a bunker about 75 yards from the living quarters of the
Davidians. The rounds did not cause any damage, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The Danforth report comes one week after an advisory jury
hearing a federal wrongful death civil lawsuit ruled that the
government was not liable for the deaths of the Branch Davidians.
The jury's verdict is not binding and the ultimate decision will be
made by the judge hearing the case.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth said he waited to publish his report in order not to
influence the jury's deliberations. He called his investigation
``95 percent complete,'' saying another 3 1/2 months will be needed
to determine whether ``further action'' is necessary against those
involved in covering up the use of the projectiles.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in a conference room at a downtown hotel, Danforth
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us should be more skeptical of those who make
sensational accusations of evil acts by government. At the same
time, government personnel, especially government lawyers, owe the
American people an openness and candor that was lacking in response
to the tragedy at Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the government did nothing evil on April 19, 1993,
the failure of some of its employees to fully and openly disclose
to the American people the use of pyrotechnic devices undermined
public confidence in government and caused real damage to our
country.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
