<HEADER>
A9303 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v BC-BUDGET-SPI &LR;      07-21 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Saturday, July 22, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Mary Downes on the national-foreign desk at (206)
448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-SURVEY (Seattle) _ Only 39 percent of its employees
surveyed gave Boeing a positive rating when asked to compare its
environment to other firms, while 24 percent offered a negative
score, according to a company-sponsored survey. The response stands
in contrast to the response in 1998, when 66 percent of the
respondents gave Boeing positive marks.
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Nyhan. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   PEARLJAM-ROSKILDE (Undated) _ Danish police recommend that no
criminal charges be pressed against Pearl Jam for the nine deaths
during the Seattle band's June 30 performance at the Roskilde
Festival. Stories circulating online incorrectly quote the report
as saying that Pearl Jam is ``morally responsible'' and that the
band incited ``violent behavior'' among audience members.
</P>
<P>
   By D. Parvaz. (Story has moved in the ``i'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-TOUR-TEACHERS (Pasadena, Calif.) _ He has done lawyers on
``L.A. Law,'' ``The Practice'' and ``Ally McBeal.'' He's done
doctors on ``Chicago Hope.'' He's even done small-town folk on
``Picket Fences.'' But David E. Kelley says he has been wanting to
do a series about teachers for a long time, and now he's finally
getting around to it.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) _ Seattle Mariners host the Texas
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Caple. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-THIEL-COLUMN (Sacramento) _ Art Thiel column from the U.S.
Olympic track trials.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
