<HEADER>
A9306 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-TOUR22-COX     07-21 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TOUR22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush give press tour of ranch; quiet on VP selection
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRAWFORD, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush took about two-dozen
reporters on a scorching tour of his 1,600- acre ranch Friday, the
place where he said he plans to come this weekend to make a final
decision about a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush gave no hints of his thinking as he fielded a daily litany
of questions about his vice-presidential pick before jumping behind
the wheel of a Chevy Suburban and leading a procession of pick-ups
and vans packed with TV and print reporters on a ride over the
ranch's bumpy terrain in McLennan County, 90 miles south of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   But the Associated Press reported that Dick Cheney, who is
heading Bush's vice presidential selection effort, may be emerging
as the leading candidate for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting an unnamed senior Republican official, the AP said Bush
is ``very, very close'' to choosing Cheney, who served as Secretary
of Defense under President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The official also confirmed that Chaney, who has been living in
Dallas, switched his voter registration to Wyoming, which he once
represented in Congress, to avoid having two Texans on the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The switch is aimed at avoiding any conflict with language in
the 12th Amendment of the Constitution that forbids Electoral
College voters in Texas from voting for both the president and vice
president who are ``inhabitants'' of their state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush gave no hint of such intrigue as he and his wife, Laura,
hosted reporters to a buffet lunch in the airy, modest farmhouse
where they are staying until a main house, now being built, is
completed. The target date for finishing that house is Election
Day.
</P>
<P>
   Looking relaxed in a green, cotton shirt, Wranglers and boots,
Bush said he does not need to meet with Arizona Sen. John McCain or
anyone else before making a decision. McCain reportedly told
Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge in a telephone conversation this week
that he would serve as Bush's running mate if asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't need to, `` talk to McCain, Bush said in response
to a reporter's question. ``I'm going to make up my mind here over
the weekend. I'm not talking to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said there would be no visitors to the ranch this weekend.
He and his wife, Laura, travel to Atlanta today for the funeral of
U.S. Sen. Paul Coverdell, Bush's point-man in the Senate. Coverdell
died Tuesday after suffering a massive stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would be in Austin Monday afternoon for a
television interview, heating up already intense speculation that
he could make an announcement as early as Tuesday. He is scheduled
on Friday to leave for a five-day tour leading up his arrival at
the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would first tell Laura the name of the person he
chooses, then notify that person and then let the other contenders
know they didn't make it. Asked when he would tell his father, Bush
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``He fits in there somewhere between Laura and the staff,'' he
said, laughing. ``No, I don't know. He'll know ...But he's not that
anxious to find out. He wants to know the decision, but he doesn't
need to be the first person to know. He trusts his boy to make the
right decision and I will make the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he is beginning to ``fine-tune'' his convention speech,
``to make it flow better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have yet to say it out loud, let me put it to you that
way,'' Bush said. ``And I will here pretty soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Friday was devoted to showing off the ranch's cliffs and
lowlands. The ranch features seven small canyons and is darted with
cedar elm, live oak, native pecan trees, among others. Laura Bush
said she plans to plant native Texas grasses around the main house.
The ranch has 200 breeding cows which belong to the foreman.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters stepped over construction materials with architect
David Heymann, associate dean for undergraduate programs at the
University of Texas, and Laura Bush as their guides. Heymann said
the couple asked him not to reveal the size of the house.
</P>
<P>
   The group walked through the main house, a long, one-story
structure featuring a breezeway, a master bedroom and kitchen area,
an office for Bush and bedrooms for the couple's twin daughters,
Jenna and Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every room offers wide-open views and the house is
constructed to allow fluid movement from the indoors to the
outdoors. It will be finished in a type of limestone from Lampasas
and will feature a roof made of galvanized steel over aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly proud of the ranch, Bush said he'll leave the interior
design to his wife. He had a few, simple requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked for a king-sized bed, and that's about all I care
about,'' Bush said. ``And a good shower. And I want some
comfortable chairs out on the porch.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
