<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9314 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-GREENBERG-BUFF     07-21 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-GREENBERG-BUFFETT-ART-$ADV23-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE BUFFETT AND GREENBERG OPPOSITES? NOT WHERE IT COUNTS. 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 (editors: optional sidebar at end of article)  
 (also see MORGANSTANLEY-ANALYST, which moved Friday for publication
on or after Saturday)  
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One plays the part of the hayseed, the other the quintessential
New York tough guy, complete with flinty stare and a vocabulary
that might stun the crowd at a hip-hop concert. One loves bridge,
and jokes that he reluctantly drags himself around a golf course;
the other is a bundle of energy whose idea of relaxation is
rocketing down a frozen ski trail.
</P>
<P>
   Look deeper, though, and these two men _ Warren E. Buffett of
Omaha and Maurice R. Greenberg of Manhattan _ have more in common
than what sets them apart. By dint of intellect and Olympian drive,
each has built a far-reaching empire that for decades has delivered
immense value to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Each rules his company _ Buffett at Berkshire Hathaway,
Greenberg at American International Group _ with imperial
authority, in gracious defiance of the conventions of good
corporate government.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, Greenberg, who is 75 and known as Hank, and
Buffett, who will be 70 in August, are giants in the same game.
Though both Berkshire, quite famously, and AIG, less obviously,
have other operations, each is mainly in the insurance business; it
represents nearly 80 percent of Buffett's revenue, and, along with
related financial services, nearly all of Greenberg's. Glamorless?
Unexciting? Maybe _ until you understand that both see it as the
business of deploying assets to the greatest possible gain. ``We
think alike,'' Buffett said recently. ``If you showed us 10 deals,
we would probably come to pretty similar conclusions on most of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   And that makes all the more extraordinary this simple fact: For
10 years, Greenberg's company has, for investors, been the better
bet.
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire, of course, has been a spectacular long-haul
investment. A stake of $10,000 sunk into Buffett's
holding-company-cum-investment-fund in 1965 has grown to about $39
million. Built for long-term investors _ Class A shares, never
split, now sell for $53,300, a price that discourages trading _
Berkshire has minted many a millionaire and has made Buffett an
investing icon.
</P>
<P>
   Yet an investor who plopped down $10,000 in Berkshire on June
30, 1990 _ a lifetime ago, by today's market standards _ would have
had $25,600 less on June 30, 2000, than one who bought an equal
stake in AIG: $74,700 versus $100,300. Over five years, the gap is
even greater: $10,000 invested in AIG in June 1995 would have grown
to $44,100 through June 2000, while the same amount in Berkshire
would have grown to just under $23,000.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett's recent underperformance of both the stock market and
his own historical record is no secret. Last year, Berkshire's gain
in net worth was less than 1 percent _ the ``absolute worst
performance of my tenure,'' he has acknowledged. And he offers his
investors little reason for optimism. Unbending in his value
discipline, Buffett says he finds it increasingly difficult to
uncover companies or stocks worth buying. Over the coming decade,
he says, Berkshire's gains will probably only modestly surpass
those of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg makes no such concessions. He has been averaging
annual earnings growth of about 20 percent since taking AIG public
in 1969, two years after he rose to chief executive; the stock has
gone up at about the same pace. As for the future, ``I don't see
anything that's going to rock that boat,'' Greenberg said in a
conversation this month at the company's Art Deco skyscraper on
Pine Street in Manhattan's financial district.
</P>
<P>
   That may be hubris on Greenberg's part, and Buffett's modesty
may be misplaced: his protestations of fallibility have often
preceded stellar performance. Indeed, the fading of technology
stocks this spring and the revival, at least temporarily, of the
consumer and financial sectors he favors have helped Berkshire
Class A shares rebound about 30 percent from a low of $40,800 in
March.
</P>
<P>
   But the long-term numbers don't lie. AIG _ today the pre-eminent
U.S. commercial insurer, with operations in more than 130 countries
_ has earned comparison to Berkshire as a vehicle for long-term
investors. And it is high time, too, to examine Greenberg's legacy
in the same light as Buffett's.
</P>
<P>
   AIG is not as well known on Main Street as Berkshire. But on
Wall Street, said Doug MacKay, a portfolio manager at Oak
Associates, a mutual fund company that holds more than seven
million AIG shares. ``Maurice Greenberg is just legendary.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposite Styles of Investing
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg may act like the tough guy, but when it comes to
investing AIG's capital, he turns cautious. The company, which has
$268 billion in assets, making it the largest American insurance
company, has a classic insurance securities portfolio, heavy with
high-quality bonds and constructed to produce steady gains. His
acquisitions and new ventures generally amplify the successes of
the past.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Buffett invests like a riverboat gambler, limiting
his market plays to a few big bets and buying up companies with
little in common except that they are moneymakers with superb
managers and products that he personally likes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Berkshire will buy businesses with very volatile earnings if
the returns are high enough,'' said Alice Schroeder, an analyst at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter who has studied both companies. ``AIG
wants companies that produce predictable earnings over time.''
</P>
<P>
   AIG, she added, ``likes to have its capital fully allocated at
all times; Berkshire is an opportunistic investor.''
</P>
<P>
   Trained as an investor, not as a businessman, Buffett was first
drawn to the insurance business in the mid-1960s by the money _
other people's money, that is. The float on premium payments can be
put to work earning investment profits until a claim is filed.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg is an insurance man from the ground up. An Army
veteran of the Normandy invasion, he got a law degree and returned
to front-line service in the Korean War. Back in New York in 1952,
he walked into the office of Continental Casualty Co. and asked for
a job. The personnel manager showed him the door, but Greenberg
tracked down the head of the New York office, who liked his spunk
and put him to work as an underwriting trainee. In late 1960, he
joined the insurance company that would become AIG as a senior
executive. Seven years later, at the age of 42, he became chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing illustrates the differences between the two men's
investing personalities so much as their biggest single
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Buffett moved into the big time in insurance with
the purchase of General Re, one of the world's leading reinsurers _
the companies that take on other insurance companies' biggest risks
for a share of the premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Most years, reinsurers collect substantial premiums without
having to make big payouts; the float can be very attractive. But
the risks of Buffett's investment quickly rained down on Berkshire:
big earthquakes in Turkey and Taiwan contributed to an underwriting
loss of more than $1 billion at General Re last year.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, Buffett loves the company. It has everything it needs, he
says, ``to become the world's most profitable reinsurance
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg is no stranger to the wild, caroming fortunes of
reinsurance; AIG owns 60 percent of TransAtlantic Re, another
global leader in the field. But far from a walk on the wild side,
his biggest acquisition _ made shortly after Buffett bought General
Re _ was of a company built to be a safe bet.
</P>
<P>
   That company, SunAmerica, is a leader in variable annuities,
which combine mutual funds and insurance and are blazing new sales
records as baby boomers fret about retirement. The business itself
is one giant annuity for AIG, piling up money in long-term
investments from customers and throwing off management fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have bought a commercial bank,'' Greenberg said,
``but commercial banks, to us, have more volatility in earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Buffett notes, the two men follow similar disciplines
in analyzing a deal. Each carefully studies the financials himself,
rather than relying on staff summaries. Buffett is famous for
spending days reading annual reports; Greenberg seldom leaves the
office without two big satchels full of papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My weekends are playing tennis and reading,'' he said. ``And
on the telephone. That's generally my weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Reins, Loose and Tight
</P>
<P>
   As a manager, Buffett says he tries to keep his hands off
Berkshire's companies. But Greenberg is totally hands-on. As
Buffett puts it, ``He knows when the sparrow falls, and he even
knows when the sparrow is thinking of falling.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a month, Greenberg assembles his division presidents around
a rectangular table in a large, plain room on the 16th floor of
AIG's headquarters. To start ``the chairman's meeting,'' as it is
known, he swings his eyes around the room and, like a stern law
professor putting students to a test, finally lets his gaze rest on
one executive.
</P>
<P>
   That person has a minute or so to rattle off current sales,
expenses, profits and any unusual developments. Then, moving
clockwise, each of the other subordinates reports. It can be a
crisp, charged atmosphere. Greenberg tells his people that he wants
them to be entrepreneurs. And he wants performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they believe you are doing everything you possibly can,
they might accept some performance slippage,'' said Susan Rivera,
the president of an AIG division that sells workers' compensation
and other business insurance. ``But if you're not performing and
it's perceived you're not doing all you can, it is a short-lived
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg often recruits specialists from other fields and
teaches them the insurance business _ as long as they are quick
studies. He signed up Joseph L. Boren, who spent years in
government and business solving pollution problems, to develop new
coverages in his field.
</P>
<P>
   Boren, now president of AIG Environmental, has been attending
the chairman's meetings for four years. Greenberg, he said, is
``not denigrating; he's penetrating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't say, `You must be the biggest dope I've ever
seen,''' Boren added. ``But he might say: `You're alarming me. You
don't sound like you're in control.'
</P>
<P>
   ``In the scheme of things, you'd rather walk into a meeting and
have people say to you, `How are you today? Did you have a nice
weekend?' But that isn't how our business works, which is why our
business is so successful.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, when AIG acquired an 8 percent stake in Risk
Labs, a dot-com start-up in Atlanta, Greenberg sent in one of his
executives as acting chief executive. That is not the Buffett way.
Buffett says that one reason he buys a company is for its
management; when he takes newcomers into the Berkshire fold, he
leaves the managers alone. That is his plan for Justin Industries,
the maker of Tony Lama boots; Berkshire said last month that it was
acquiring the company.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said a senior executive of one of Buffett's companies,
``if you want to get him involved, you practically have to drag him
into it.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has ways of letting his managers know what he wants done.
Years ago, after he acquired 50 percent of Geico, the discount auto
insurer that Berkshire now owns entirely, AIG offered to buy the
business.
</P>
<P>
   As John J. Byrne Jr., then Geico's chief executive, tells the
story, Buffett agreed only reluctantly to join him for lunch in
Greenberg's private dining room at AIG Greenberg and Felix Rohatyn,
a friend who was then a senior partner in the Lazard Freres
investment banking firm, tried to aim their conversation at
Buffett. ``You're looking at the wrong side of the table,'' he told
them. ``You've got to speak to Mr. Byrne.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrne felt the chill. The next day he told Greenberg that Geico
was not for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, though, Buffett showed that he can lose his cool
as readily as any hands-on boss. Byrne had shifted much of Geico's
investment portfolio into long-term bonds _ at precisely the wrong
moment. Interest rates were starting to rise, which meant that he
would not only soon be locked into below-market yields, but that
the value of his bonds would be falling.
</P>
<P>
   As Byrne recalls it, Buffett invited him to play golf at the
Burning Tree Club outside Washington. Rather tentatively, Buffett
started to talk about the economy, and Byrne defended his decision.
As they played, Byrne could see Buffett becoming agitated. On the
ninth hole, he noticed Buffett gritting his teeth, the veins in his
neck pulsing. Unleashing a furious swing that clipped the top of
the ball and sent it dribbling about 14 feet, Buffett wheeled on
Byrne in a rage. ``Only a fool would lend long at this point in
time,'' Byrne recalls him shouting. ``Only a fool.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrne managed to stay on as chief executive. But he immediately
hired a specialist to run his investment portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
