<TEXT>
<P>
   Woods on top at British Open
</P>
<P>
   By EDDIE SEFKO
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ They bide their time and keep waiting
impatiently. Phil Mickelson, Ernie Els, Sergio Garcia and the rest.
</P>
<P>
   If only Tiger Woods would supply them with a shred of hope,
maybe the attitude would be different going into the weekend at the
129th British Open. If he would make just one stinking bogey, maybe
they could dream.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods refuses to let any optimism creep into his pursuers'
thoughts. He remains as relentless as a headache for which there is
no pill.
</P>
<P>
   Through 36 holes at the Old Course, Woods has yet to make a
bogey. He rattled off six birdies Friday, tied three other players
for the lowest round with a 6-under-par 66 and built himself a
three-stroke cushion midway through the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The deja vu factor is getting ridiculous. It was barely a month
ago that Woods built a six-shot lead halfway through the U.S. Open.
All he did was mow down the field by 15 strokes. This seems all too
familiar, even if his advantage is only three shots over David Toms
and four over Garcia, Loren Roberts and Steve Flesch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good spot,'' Woods said. ``What you try to do in any
tournament is not make mistakes. Bogeys aren't good for the
scorecard. Everybody knows that. If you go around for the week and
don't make any bogeys, I guarantee you'll have a good chance to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm playing very similar to the way I played at
Pebble Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so that Woods has a string of 62 consecutive holes in
major championships without a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   He teased everybody on the wicked Road Hole on Friday. His
approach rolled over the 17th green down to a patch of grass near
the blacktop road that runs behind the green. He pitched back to
eight feet, using the slope beyond the hole as a backstop. Then he
drilled the putt, giving a hearty fist-pump as the ball disappeared
into the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was big because, first of all, I didn't want to make a
bogey,'' he said. ``But also, it was a double-break putt from no
more than eight feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if I could go out and play solidly, the way the wind
was dying off in the evening, I'd probably be able to post a good
number.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods birdied three of the first five holes to jump to the top
of the leader board. He passed Toms, who finished four hours
earlier, with a birdie at the ninth hole. And he never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   It is getting to look so easy for Woods. He has avoided every
hazard at St. Andrews, including a topless female admirer who
stormed onto the 18th green after Woods' group putted out. She was
apprehended before she could get close to her target, which just
proves nobody can touch Woods this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who plays mistake-free golf is going to be tough to
beat,'' said Tom Lehman, one of five players at 6-under 138. ``He
hasn't made a bogey yet. All we can do _ all I can do _ is play my
best and not worry about what he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods is playing coy, in spite of his strong play so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the trophy sitting next to me,'' he said, no
doubt resisting the temptation to insert the word yet at the end of
the sentence. ``I'm not in their shoes, so it's hard for me to
imagine what they're thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   What they mostly are thinking is how to get a run of birdies
going to close the gap. Clearly, Woods is playing well enough not
to go very far in reverse, if at all, when the third round
commences.
</P>
<P>
   What may keep him looking over his shoulder is the strong list
of players behind him. Mickelson matched Woods' 66 Friday, and an
international cast of marquee players is bunched together at 5, 6
and 7 under par. The question is whether they have too much ground
to make up.
</P>
<P>
   One chaser, Garcia, believes the tournament remains wide-open,
particularly because he's found a new weapon that has helped his
scoring _ cross-handed putting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's working so far,'' Garcia said. ``Because I played poorly
at the U.S. Open, I tried it. I played the Champions' Challenge
with my dad the week after and made a lot of putts. I went to
Ballybunion, the Irish Open, and putted really well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's helping me make putts, and it's helping my address. I
feel a lot better over the short putts than the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia has been mostly quiet since the PGA Championship at
Medinah last August. He had middle-of-the-pack finishes at the
Masters and U.S. Open, although he did have a third place at the
Buick Classic last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I am playing a lot like Medinah,'' he said. ``And I'm
in a perfect position. If you can be 10 ahead of the field, it's
great. But if not, you want to be really close to the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Four shots might not be really close to Woods. But it is about
as good as anybody could do Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Only Toms could manage better. His 67 left him at 8-under, and
he will have the chore of being paired with Woods today when the
duo tees off last at 9 a.m. CDT.
</P>
<P>
   Toms had five birdies and no bogeys Friday, playing wonderfully
by mere mortal standards, if not quite Tigeresque. But he seems
ill-equipped for the battle to come, although with three titles, he
is a proven winner on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in contention (in a major),'' Toms said.
``This is the first time I've been exempt for all four majors.''
</P>
<P>
   His first round on a weekend at the British Open figures to be a
tough initiation.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
