<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9319 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-GREENBERG-BUFF     07-21 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-GREENBERG-BUFFETT-ART-$ADV23-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: investment portfolio.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Governance and Succession
</P>
<P>
   If Greenberg and Buffett run their companies like owners, it is
not without a certain logic. Buffett owns more than 30 percent of
Berkshire's stock; Greenberg owns 2.2 percent of AIG's, but he
estimates that top management and the board control about 30
percent of the shares. And each is accorded complete authority as
the builder of his enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, each man has aligned things in his favor. In defiance
of the norms of governance for public companies, their boards are
heavy with insiders. Neither man is interested in hearing about
mandatory retirement; both say they plan to go on leading their
companies indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg had to face a few hecklers on such issues at AIG's
annual meeting in May. But their reward for speaking up was chilly
glares from other shareholders and employees who had crowded into
the modest company cafeteria. As Greenberg was detailing yet
another stellar year and announcing yet another stock split, one
protester rose to argue that earnings often suffer at companies
with less-than-independent boards. Greenberg lobbed a soft reply:
``Are you sure you're in the right place?'' And the room, full of
loyalists, chuckled and clucked.
</P>
<P>
   Professional financial analysts tend to melt before Buffett and
Greenberg, too.
</P>
<P>
   At Berkshire's annual meetings in Omaha, reporters ask Buffett
for autographs; instead of trying to poke holes in his strategies,
many securities analysts admiringly quote Buffett aphorisms. When
Greenberg invites insurance analysts once a year to what they refer
to as a fireside chat, the questions are gentle. They have all
heard the tales of how Greenberg has called analysts and read them
_ and their bosses, who covet AIG's investment banking business _
the riot act.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't mess around with Hank,'' one analyst said on
condition of anonymity. ``He could squash me like a bug.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise that such a leader would have dynastic dreams,
and Greenberg intends to keep the future of AIG in the family. His
eldest son, Jeffrey, had been regarded by AIG watchers as the heir
apparent, but he resigned abruptly five years ago, later becoming
chief executive of Marsh &AMP; McLennan, the giant insurance broker.
Now Jeffrey's 45-year-old brother Evan, AIG's president, has been
designated as next in line to run the company, where he has worked
for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the confidence of his father, it is hard to tell, at
this point, how well Evan Greenberg might perform. Subordinates
earnestly describe his thoroughness and command of the nuances of
the business. Some say he is brilliant. But industry executives who
know him well are noncommittal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know he's a competent fellow,'' said Barber B.
Conable, a former congressman and past president of the World Bank
who is one of six directors on AIG's 18-member board who are
neither company executives nor contractors. ``This is not an issue
we've been worrying about,'' he added, ``because Hank shows every
sign of continuing as the leader.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Conable said, after the senior Greenberg dies,
there is nothing to stop the board from choosing whomever it
decides is best suited to run the company. Conable said he once
told Greenberg: ``You must understand, your son will be tested by
the board at such time as you step down.''
</P>
<P>
   At Berkshire Hathaway, Buffett has installed a seven-member
board that comprises his wife, Susan, who lives apart from him in
San Francisco; his son, Howard G. Buffett; Charles T. Munger, the
company's vice chairman, who has long been Buffett's confidant; a
law partner of Munger's and two other longtime business associates
of Buffett's.
</P>
<P>
   After Buffett dies, his wife is to receive nearly all his stock.
But she will not run the company; instead, he has designated two
Berkshire executives to take his place _ one to handle investments,
the other operations. Neither has been publicly named, but there
has been speculation that Louis A. Simpson, who is in charge of
investments at Geico, would take over the investing side. Buffett
watchers mention several candidates for the operations job, with
little conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever they are, Buffett's successors will be hard pressed to
preserve Berkshire's unique place in the investment pantheon. The
market does not value Berkshire as it would an insurance company,
even though that is what it mainly is. Rather, it is priced largely
on the performance of its chief executive's stock picks. Whether
the cult followers will remain in thrall to Buffett's successors is
anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   AIG certainly revolves around Greenberg _ ``If you don't have a
relationship with Hank Greenberg, you don't have a relationship
with AIG,'' said an insurance executive who has known Greenberg for
years. But analysts say an AIG without Greenberg is a surer bet
than Berkshire without Buffett: There are more units, more decision
makers, a broader playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the Scorecards
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, neither Buffett nor Greenberg shows any sign of
slowing down. Indeed, their business strategies put them face to
face more and more, inviting the comparisons that previously were
not so obvious. For example, will Buffett's Geico or Greenberg's
AIG Direct reap the most rewards in the competition for
bargain-minded auto insurance customers?
</P>
<P>
   Both are pouring money into advertising and expansion.
Characteristically, Buffett is going for broke; he wants Geico to
become one of the giants in the business. Greenberg wants to grow,
too, but earnings in car insurance fluctuate too much to suit him,
so he will keep the line from dominating AIG's portfolio of
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, do you bet on the Manhattan tortoise or the Omaha
hare? Schroeder, the Morgan Stanley analyst, finds it difficult to
choose. ``That's like asking whether to buy a Van Gogh or a
Monet,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FROM RIVALRY TO COOPERATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH B. TREASTER &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   After decades of rubbing shoulders around the casino tables of
finance, Warren E. Buffett and Maurice R. Greenberg have come to
admire each other warmly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vibe between us is not competitors,'' Buffett said. ``The
vibe between us is friends.'' Envious friends, but friends. ``I
wish I had done some of the deals he's done,'' Buffett said, ``and
maybe he wishes he'd done some of the deals I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Greenberg said, ``we have a great relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   But things have not always been so rosy. Fifteen years ago, they
exchanged verbal punches. Buffett criticized the way the American
International Group, of which Greenberg is chief executive, used
reinsurance, and Greenberg fired back that Buffett had ``a
peanut-sized book'' of insurance business _ which was true at the
time _ and that he was a fine one to be telling him how to run his
company, already a giant in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   But that was a long time ago. Now they are doing business
together; AIG is the biggest single customer of General Re,
Buffett's main insurance holding. And they are keen competitors:
TransAtlantic, the big reinsurer that AIG controls, goes after some
of the same business that General Re does, and the two titans are
pursuing the same customers in car insurance businesses.
</P>
<P>
   They have collaborated on some joint projects, but their biggest
idea _ the attempted rescue and takeover of Long Term Capital
Management, the hedge fund that nearly failed in 1998 _ came to
nothing. Others on Wall Street beat them to it.
</P>
<P>
   But they're still thinking. ``It's logical that we would team up
on something,'' Buffett said. ``We and they have enormous capital
resources.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
