<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FTC-PRIVACY-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE STORE REACHES DEAL TO SELL DATA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over continued objections of privacy advocates and attorneys
general of 39 states, the Federal Trade Commission announced Friday
that it had reached a settlement to permit Toysmart.com, a defunct
online toy seller, to sell its customer database as part of its
bankruptcy proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   But in a 3-2 vote late Thursday, the commission also put strict
limitations on the sale. Under the settlement, a buyer of
Toysmart's database must be in a family-related commerce market,
buy the entire Web site and agree not to sell the database without
getting permission from the individuals included in it.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement must now be approved by the court hearing
Toysmart's bankruptcy proceedings. It was reached in a civil
lawsuit filed by the FTC earlier this month in U.S. District Court
in Boston in an attempt to prevent Toysmart from selling the
database.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also amended its original complaint against
Toysmart on Friday, adding a second charge that the company had
collected personal information from children in alleged violation
of the Children's Online Privacy Act of 1998. It is the first time
the government has filed charges under the act since it went into
effect in April.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it announced the second complaint, the commission said
it reached a settlement in which Toysmart agreed to destroy about
2,000 records that might have been in violation of the law, said
Harry Murphy, a lawyer for Toysmart. The law prohibits sites from
collecting data from children younger than 13 without parental
consent.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuvering on Friday highlighted how important the case has
become to privacy advocates, legislators and Internet industry
observers. With Internet companies able to easily build massive
databases on their visitors, various political and policy groups
have expressed concern about how to balance the benefits to
companies and consumers of collecting the information, which can be
used to create targeted advertising, with privacy issues.
</P>
<P>
   While the company, which is majority owned by Walt Disney Co.,
posted an explicit policy stating that it would not sell customer
information to a third party, it later went bankrupt and sought to
sell the database along with its other assets, raising the specter
that other dot-com companies would fail and would hawk their
databases too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely sending a message that just because a company
fails, we're going to continue to pursue action,'' said Eric
London, a spokesman for the trade commission. ``If there's a
bankruptcy tidal wave, this is going to happen a lot,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time the commission has filed a complaint
pertaining to the release of database information from an online
company; in August 1998, the FTC settled with GeoCities, which the
government alleged made information available to third parties
without disclosing the activity to its users. But the Toysmart case
is the first time the FTC has brought such an action in a
bankruptcy setting.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the case of Toysmart, the database amounted to information
collected on about 250,000 individuals, Murphy said. Murphy
declined to speculate on the value of the database, but he said
that earlier this year he represented a client that liquidated a
far larger database for $210,000, suggesting that the Toysmart data
might not be so lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said that the company has received two, or possibly
three, bids for the database, including one from Disney, which held
three of the company's five board seats. Disney said after the
commission sued Toysmart that it would buy the database and
``retire'' it. Murphy said a second bid was from Digital Research
Inc. of Portland, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   However, it remains to be seen whether any sale of the database
will go through. A bankruptcy court in Boston is scheduled to hear
the case Wednesday, and it will hear objections to the sale that
have been filed by at least two groups _ an online privacy
organization and attorneys general from 39 states.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the attorney general of Massachusetts filed an
objection on behalf of his state and 38 others in the bankruptcy
court, asserting that the sale of the database constitutes an
unfair and deceptive trade practice.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Kogut, an assistant attorney general in Massachusetts
handling the case, said Toysmart should be forced to live up to its
promise to never sell the data to a third party. ``Outside the
context of this bankruptcy filing, Toysmart should be prohibited
from selling this customer list,'' she said, noting that the
bankruptcy should not free Toysmart from its promise.
</P>
<P>
   She said the attorneys general were studying the FTC settlement
but wouldn't comment on it until after the bankruptcy hearing on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the court will also hear an objection from Truste, a
nonprofit agency that certifies the privacy policy of online
retailers. Toysmart was among about 2,000 sites that have received
Truste's seal of approval, and it was the organization that brought
Toysmart's effort to sell its database to the attention of the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   David Steer, a spokesman for Truste, said that he had not
studied the FTC settlement thoroughly but that it did appear to
leave too much room for the sale of the database in a way that
would violate the promise made to Toysmart visitors. ``We're going
to go ahead with our own suit,'' he said, referring to the
objection filed by Truste on Friday in bankruptcy court. ``We
applaud the FTC for getting halfway there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
