<SLUG> BC-ERICSSON-WIRELESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERICSSON STOCKS DROP ON WARNING OF SLOW SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors hammered shares in Ericsson on Friday despite a
healthy increase in second-quarter earnings, as concern grew that
the Swedish company might be losing ground in the battle for
control of the thriving market for wireless phones.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Ericsson fell $2.75, or 12 percent, to $19.8125 on the
Nasdaq market, its deepest one-day decline in more than a year and
a half. Much of the sell-off was attributed to Ericsson's warning
that third-quarter sales of cell phones would be more sluggish than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ericsson attributed part of the expected slowdown to a
recent fire at an Albuquerque semiconductor plant operated by its
main supplier, Royal Philips Electronics, some analysts questioned
whether the company's overall mobile phone strategy in the last
several years was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ericsson is paying the price for not seizing on the general
direction of the industry,'' said Mark Roberts, a
telecommunications analyst in the San Francisco office of First
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones have emerged as one of the top-selling electronic
items in the world, with more than $70 billion in revenue expected
from the sale of 450 million units this year. And it increasingly
appears that companies betting on the specialization of the
devices, as opposed to their commoditization, are winning.
</P>
<P>
   This means that Nokia, the Finnish company that has succeeded in
increasing its market share largely by providing a wide array of
devices for consumers, is doing better than competitors. Motorola,
which is based in Schaumburg, Ill., and is the second-largest cell
phone manufacturer, has been attempting to follow Nokia's strategy
in making variety a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Ericsson, meanwhile, the No. 3 manufacturer, has been derided
for not structuring its operations to produce phones profitably.
``Their design cycles are slow, and they exposed themselves to a
fire in a single factory,'' said Brian Modoff, a telecommunications
analyst at BT Alex. Brown. ``I see no reason at all why they should
be in the business of making phones.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to make its mobile phone operations profitable by
the middle of next year, Ericsson said it was planning to focus on
fewer production lines and increase research to market more
attractive lower-end models. Kurt Hellstrom, Ericsson's chief
executive, told investors in a conference call that the company had
no plans to sell its division that manufactures mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to building networks for wireless operations,
Ericsson's other main business, the company continued to show
promise, with a 32 percent increase in sales in the second quarter.
Ericsson has won some of the most lucrative contracts in Europe to
build the next generation of networks that are expected to widen
the spread of the wireless Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Network manufacturing activities largely fueled an increase in
Ericsson's profit from operations in the second quarter, which
climbed 46 percent to 2.35 billion kronor, or about $261 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ericsson excels when it comes to the construction of networks,
which is becoming a huge market,'' said Andrew Cole, who heads the
wireless practice at Renaissance Strategy Worldwide. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
