<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-NICKLAUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOND FAREWELL FOR NICKLAUS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ They were perched on the balconies of
Rusack's Hotel and hanging out of windows at the Tom Morris Golf
Shop. They were lined 10 deep along Links Road, and thousands more
were stretched from tee to green for close to 400 yards as Jack
Nicklaus approached.
</P>
<P>
   He was ``playing up toon,'' as they say here, making the walk up
the 18th fairway at St. Andrews for what is expected to be his
final appearance in a British Open. The obligatory photo on the
Swilken Bridge was taken, Nicklaus doffing his cap to the roar of
thousands, a hero in a sport that covets its history, and as he
approached his ball on the edge of the Valley of Sin, the cheers
grew louder.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were terrific,'' he said. ``They let me know that they
appreciated the good years that I've had in Scotland (all three of
his British Open triumphs were in this country, two at St.
Andrews), and they gave me a very, very nice farewell.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is a farewell, after 37 British Opens?
</P>
<P>
   ``Never say never,'' said Nicklaus, ``but I would say the
chances are I've probably played my last hole in the British
Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Former champions are awarded exemptions through the age of 65,
which for Nicklaus would mean 2005. He was told the 2005 British
Open is tentatively penciled in for St. Andrews, but Nicklaus said
that was too far down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say no,'' he said, ``but I certainly am not going to
play unless I can be competitive. I don't want to take up a spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The game's most accomplished player feels anything but
competitive these days. He missed the cut at the Masters in April
and the US Open in June, and Thursday he shot 77 here. Friday,
after making the turn in 34 to offer a hint of life, he came home
in 39 to finish 73_150. His feet are bothering him, though not as
much as a deficiency that was quite evident on the 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   From just 6 feet after a superb approach, Nicklaus hung over the
birdie putt and saw the left-to-right break. ``It just broke like
the devil,'' said Nicklaus, who parred the hole. Nicklaus had
delighted the US Open crowd in June when he reached Pebble Beach's
par-5 18th in two, only to douse the enthusiasm by three-putting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never putted like this in my life,'' he said, shaking his
head. ``Today was a good putting round for me. I made two putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like resignation talk from a guy who has made more clutch
putts than anyone in the game's history. There isn't much more
competitive golf on his schedule this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am playing a show match Monday, and the chances are I will
probably play golf on Sunday,'' he said. ``That excites me a real
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But isn't tomorrow his 40th wedding anniversary? Yes, it is, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And Barbara would approve of a golf date? ``I played golf the
day I got married,'' Nicklaus said. ``Barbara did not mind it then,
she's certainly not going to mind it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus laughed, knowing his time has come and gone on the golf
course, but his wife and five children remain the core of his life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
