<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A CONSTITUTIONAL CHALLENGE FOR BRITAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Thousands of American lawyers, here for the annual
meeting of the American Bar Association, celebrated their ``common
bond'' with English law: the legal protections of freedom developed
since the barons forced King John to sign Magna Carta in 1215.
</P>
<P>
   The two legal systems do have much in common, but there is a
fundamental difference. The United States has a written
Constitution, and Americans rely on judges to enforce its
guarantees against official abuse. Britain has no such higher law,
and judges have been bound to carry out whatever Parliament said.
</P>
<P>
   That is about to change. In October, the European Convention on
Human Rights will become binding on British courts. Judges will
have to measure acts of Parliament and government decrees against
the convention's guarantees of free speech, fair procedure and the
like.
</P>
<P>
   What is striking to a visitor is how little understanding there
is of the difference that change is likely to make. Tony Blair's
New Labor government put through a statute that will bring the
European Convention into British courts. But it is nevertheless
coming up with one proposal after another that seems, to an
outsider, to violate basic concepts of civil liberty.
</P>
<P>
   The home secretary, Jack Straw, asked a commission last year to
consider whether the rule against double jeopardy should be
abandoned under some circumstances. The rule has been part of the
judge-made law of England for 900 years, preventing the retrial of
anyone for an offense of which he has been acquitted. It is part of
the Fifth Amendment to the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The British commission considering the issue has tentatively
recommended a partial breach of the rule, and Conservative Party
spokesmen have called for action. Straw says he will wait for the
final commission report, but the expectation is that he will move
to allow some retrials of people who have been acquitted. However
limited, that would give prosecutors enormous discretion. Americans
would surely regard the step as a drastic violation of traditional
safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   Straw also has a bill pending to deprive many criminal
defendants of the right to trial by jury. Again, that would be
impossible in the United States, where jury trial in criminal cases
is guaranteed by the Sixth Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   And right now Straw is pushing through Parliament an
extraordinary bill to deal with the hooligans who go to foreign
stadiums when British soccer teams play there. As drafted, the bill
would have allowed the police to seize the passports of _ and hence
prevent international travel by _ anyone they suspect is likely to
act violently at a match.
</P>
<P>
   Guilt by suspicion, in short. Happily, the bill came under such
strong criticism that Straw modified it to cover only those
believed to have committed what would be a criminal offense. But
even then its standards are so vague that it would raise
constitutional hackles in America.
</P>
<P>
   One more venture by Straw is a bill to let the state make anyone
who uses coded e-mail give officials the key to decode it, so they
can intercept and read it as they wish. That proposal has drawn
outraged protests from leading technology companies in Britain and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Like Straw, Blair seems to have no concern for civil liberties.
What matters, evidently, is pleasing the voters by being tough on
law and order. The respected Guardian columnist Hugo Young wrote
this week of Blair's ``indifference to, almost his contempt for,
civil liberties.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether any of the legislation I have mentioned, or other bills
in the pipeline, will actually be found to violate the European
Convention remains to be seen. What is notable is that, on the eve
of a great step for the protection of civil liberties, the
government shows no sign of caring.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Britons do not understand what a difference judicial
protection of individual rights can make. Some people, especially
on the ideological left, say that British judges are too
conservative to care about civil liberties. Such commentators have
not noticed that the judges in recent years have shown an
increasing tendency to scrutinize official action. Giving them
constitutional power will make a profound difference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
