u w BC-GAYS-MILITARY-635&AMP;ADD     07-21 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-MILITARY-635&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON ORDERS PUNISHMENT FOR HARASSMENT OF GAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon announced an ``anti-harassment action
plan'' Friday that would require military commanders to discipline
service members who engaged in, condoned or ignored anti-gay
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan was short on details, and Carol DiBattiste,
undersecretary of the Air Force and head of the panel of civilian
and military leaders that drafted the plan, acknowledged in a news
conference that it was ``going to take some work'' to get the four
military services to carry it out.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, the Army formally released its internal
investigation into circumstances surrounding the murder of a gay
private last summer, which found evidence of anti-gay remarks and
harassment on the base where the murder occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department's plan recommends training tailored to
the specific rank of troops to implement the Clinton
administration's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy, which allows gay
men and lesbians to serve in the military provided they keep their
sexual orientation a secret and do not engage in homosexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is a response to a survey of 38 military bases and 11
warships that concluded that anti-gay remarks and harassment were
commonplace in the U.S. military, and that most service members
believed their superiors and colleagues tolerated it ``to some
extent.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey, ordered after Pfc. Barry Winchell, a 21-year-old gay
soldier, was bludgeoned to death last July in his barracks at Fort
Campbell, Ky., suggested that disparaging and hostile attitudes
toward gays remained a pervasive part of military culture.
</P>
<P>
   The Army investigation into the murder provided more evidence of
those attitudes. The investigation concluded that the ``command
climate'' in Winchell's unit was ``poor,'' and admitted that
``joking and bantering'' on the base before his death could be
viewed as harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The report found isolated incidents ``where leaders had
subjected soldiers to derogatory name-calling and slurs,'' and
evidence of ``inappropriate cadence calls'' in which unit leaders
led soldiers in derogatory chants as they marched in formation.
</P>
<P>
   The report details specific incidents of harassment. For
example, 21 of 568 soldiers interviewed during group sessions said
that they had knowledge of verbal harassment of service members
perceived as homosexuals. Half of those who observed such
harassment said it was done ``on a daily basis.'' Most of the
harassment was in a work area or in formation during duty hours.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the evidence of anti-gay behavior, the report cleared
all officers of blame in the murder of Winchell and concluded that
there was no general climate of homophobia at the base, home of the
101st Airborne Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was determined that the command climate at Fort Campbell''
before the murder was ``a positive environment,'' with some
exceptions, the inspector general's report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report showed that the Army had failed to educate service
personnel about the policy. Except for first sergeants,
noncommissioned officers could not recall any training on the
policy toward gays during any officer development course, the
report said. Less than 5 percent of commanders, command sergeant
majors and leaders interviewed said that they had received training
on the policy in their units.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task force was unable to confirm a single occasion where
unit training was ever conducted on the policy at Fort Campbell''
before the murder of Winchell, the report said. Half of the
soldiers interviewed said they did not fully understand the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that is not a lack of leadership, I don't know what is,''
said Michelle M. Benecke, co-director of the Servicemembers Legal
Defense Network, an organization that provides legal aid to gays in
the military.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although the sergeant who was Winchell's immediate superior was
accused in the report of ``abusive'' behavior, stripped of his
leadership position and reassigned, no criminal charges have been
filed against him. Asked repeatedly whether the sergeant was under
criminal investigation, Army Chief of Staff Gen. Eric K. Shinseki
said only that such a decision was in the hands of the base.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on an accusation by Patricia Kutteles, Winchell's
mother, that the Army was covering up a gay-bashing atmosphere on
the base, Shinseki said, ``I will tell you this, if this were a
cover-up I wouldn't be standing here today.''
</P>
<P>
   The killing of Winchell as he slept renewed the debate over the
Clinton administration's policy on gays, and the issue has
permeated the presidential campaign. Vice President Al Gore vows to
allow gays to serve openly. His Republican opponent, Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, supports the existing policy.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has described the policy, which he instituted
in the first year of his presidency, as ``out of whack.''
</P>
<P>
   But when asked Friday if he agreed with the president's
description, Bernard D. Rostker, undersecretary of defense for
personnel and readiness, said: ``I don't agree with that
characterization. I think the policy is working reasonably well to
provide a degree of safety for those who want to serve in the
military regardless of sexual orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   DiBattiste described the process by which a service member has
to report anti-gay harassment and the commanding officer has to
respond. The service member must report the details of the
harassment, but not whether he or she is gay; his or her superior
must elicit the details without asking the alleged victim whether
he or she is gay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9357 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-U.S.-CUBA-TRAVEL-NYT &LR;      07-21 0844
