<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, Ext. 218.
WASHINGTON, July 21 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: Estate
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on July 14 approved, 59-39, a bill to end the federal
inheritance tax. The legislation would phase out taxes on an estate
after the owner dies. Supports said it would save family farms,
businesses and resources. Opponents said it would threaten spending
on benefits for senior and poor Americans. A ``yes'' vote supports
the elimination of the estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: Monuments
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday rejected, 49-50, a measure to prevent the
administration from designating federal monuments without
congressional approval. Supporters said the measure would restore
local input in the development of federal lands. Opponents said it
would reduce the president's power to protect the environment. A
``yes'' vote supports the measure.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: Interior
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday approved, 97-2, a $15.5 billion spending
bill for the Department of Interior, a Northeast oil reserve and
other federal programs. Supporters said it would provide critical
funding for national parks and energy programs. Opponents said it
would underfund conservation efforts. A ``yes'' vote supports the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: Marriage
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday approved, 61-38, a bill to eliminate the
``marriage penalty'' tax. The bill would increase the standard
deduction for married couples, cutting $246 billion in taxes over
10 years. Supporters said it would offer equitable tax commitments
to married Americans. Opponents said it would shrink the projected
federal surplus. A ``yes'' vote supports the marriage tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   5) BILL NUMBER: Medicine
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday voted, 74-21, to amend a spending bill
to allow importation of medicines approved by the Food and Drug
Administration. Supporters said it would allow pharmacists to
negotiate better prices with manufacturers. Opponents said it would
swell the FDA's responsibilities and add to the spread of dangerous
drugs. A ``yes'' vote supports the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   6) BILL NUMBER: Funding
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday passed, 79-13, a $75.3 billion spending
bill for food, drug and farm programs. The bill includes $900
million in emergency aid. Supporters said it would relieve flood
and crop damage. Opponents said it would ruin federal budget plans.
A ``yes'' vote supports the spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4 5 6
</P>
<P>
   --- --- --- --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) Y Y Y Y N Y
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) N Y Y Y Y Y
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: Gambling
</P>
<P>
   The House on Monday defeated a bill to prohibit most forms of
Internet gambling. Failing to reach the two-thirds vote needed to
pass the bill, the House rejected the legislation, 245-159.
Supporters said it would have prevented crime and addiction.
Opponents said it would have created regulatory problems and
allowed for invasion of privacy. A ``yes'' vote supports the
gambling bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: Spam
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday passed, 427-1, a bill to limit unsolicited
email messages, or spam, and allow Internet service providers to
sue spammers in federal courts. Supporters said junk emails cost
providers $1 billion every year. Rep. Ron Paul(R-Texas), the only
member to vote against the bill, contended it infringes on states'
rights and wastes federal funds. A ``yes'' vote supports spam
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: Pension
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 401-25, a bill to increase the
maximum amount Americans can invest in Individual Retirement
Accounts and 401(K) funds. The legislation would raise the annual
limit for IRAs from $2,000 to $5,000 and 401(K) plans from $10,500
to $15,000. Supporters said it would encourage savings and boost
the number of pension plans. Opponents said it would reduce
pensions for low-income workers. A ``yes'' vote supports the
pension bill.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: Defense
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 367-58, a $289.6 billion
defense spending bill. The legislation would raise military pay,
built ships and aircrafts and sustain research and development
projects. Supporters said it would ensure America's military
strength. Opponents cited inadequate funding for foreign aid. A
``yes'' vote supports the defense appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
   5) BILL NUMBER: Raise
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 250-173, a 2.7 percent increase
in members' $141,300 salaries. Supporters said it would adjust pay
with the cost of living. Opponents said it would cost taxpayers
$2.1 million. A ``yes'' vote supports the measure.
</P>
<P>
   6) BILL NUMBER: Cuba
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday passed, 232-186, a measure to remove
travel restrictions to Cuba. Supporters said it would protect the
Constitutional right to travel and grant Americans the freedom to
show their way of life to Cubans. Opponents said it would give
funds to the Castro government. A ``yes'' vote supports the
relaxation of travel restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4 5 6
</P>
