</P>
<P>
   ``Many of (the G8 leaders) referenced the meeting that had taken
place yesterday . . . and which gave greater impetus to the need to
get the Cologne debt commitments implemented,'' said Lael Brainard,
deputy national economic advisor.
</P>
<P>
   A statement released by G8 leaders Friday _ not including Russia
_ expressed concern that many of the poor nations are at war or
have military conflicts which prevent them from qualifying for debt
relief. They agreed to do more to help those countries qualify, but
Brainard said there was no discussion of relaxing the terms of debt
relief.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton landed in Okinawa Friday morning and headed straight to
a peace memorial in an effort to placate criticism from another
corner _ local Okinawans unhappy with the large U.S. military
presence.
</P>
<P>
   Okinawa hosts about 26,000 American military personnel, more
than half of the American forces in Japan, even though it comprises
less than 1 percent of Japan's land mass. An estimated 27,000
people turned out Thursday to form a human chain around Kadena
Airbase in a show of protest.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged to continue efforts to ``reduce our footprint on
this island,'' but some Okinawans were disappointed that he neither
said anything specific about base reduction nor apologized for an
incident earlier this month in which a drunken U.S. marine
allegedly entered a local house and molested a sleeping 14-year-old
girl.
</P>
<P>
   A few small, scattered groups of anti-base protesters appeared
at various summit venues and along the main road.
</P>
<P>
   The Okinawa summit is Clinton's eighth and last G8 summit. He
joined the group as the new kid on the block and leaves as the
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.g8kyushu-okinawa.go.jp
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
