<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9376 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHINA-AIRLINES-1STLD-     07-21 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-AIRLINES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA REORGANIZES ITS DOMESTIC AIRLINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Changes ``1998-99'' to ``1997-98'' in 4th graf.)  
 By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China announced a vast reorganization of domestic
airlines Friday, merging seven carriers into the three largest to
reduce the overlap of routes and half-empty planes that have
plagued the industry for years.
</P>
<P>
   Air China, China Eastern Airlines and China Southern Airlines
will absorb the other carriers, giving each of the three surviving
airlines roughly $6 billion in assets, China's state news agency,
Xinhua, reported. It did not give a timetable for the mergers or
indicate which airline would merge with which. Shares of China
Eastern and China Southern are listed in New York and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   China's airline industry has had a turbulent ride since the
country broke the Civil Aviation Administration of China's state
airline monopoly into six regional carriers in the late 1980s and
later allowed provincial governments to start their own airlines.
The idea was to better serve the enormous increase in passengers
that came with relaxed controls on air travel by Chinese citizens
and a subsequent economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion led to a series of crashes that made China the
most dangerous place to fly during the early 1990s. China rectified
that with increased pilot training and a moratorium on aircraft
purchases. But a second wave of expansion left the industry with
far more airline seats than passengers when the growth of air
travel tapered off with the 1997-98 Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   China's airline industry, which includes 34 airlines, lost over
$72 million in 1998 as companies cut ticket prices in a frantic
scramble for passengers. China fixed prices and banned discounts in
1999 to try to stop the bleeding. It delayed delivery of aircraft
that had been ordered. It cut air routes.
</P>
<P>
   It even demanded that all airlines pool 80 percent of their
ticket revenue on specific routes and divide it among the carriers
servicing that route. The industry edged back to profitability last
year, but none of that solved the problem of too many planes and
too few passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The country is loath to allow the market to solve the problem by
letting money-losing airlines go bankrupt, a solution considered
too brutal in China's planned economy.
</P>
<P>
   The seven airlines to be absorbed employ about 73,000 people and
carry heavy debts. It is not clear how much of those burdens the
three surviving airlines will be forced to assume.
</P>
<P>
   The seven airlines are China Southwest, China Northwest, China
Northern, Xinjiang, Yunnan, Great Wall and Zhejiang,
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation would in theory create economies of scale and
give the industry the potential to develop hub-and-spoke networks
similar to those of airlines in the United States. China Southern
is based in the southern city of Guangzhou, China Eastern in the
eastern commercial hub of Shanghai, and Air China in Beijing, in
the north.
</P>
<P>
   And it could prepare the industry for increased competition
after China's entry into the World Trade Organization, expected
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners are expected to be allowed up to 49 percent stakes in
China's airlines, up from the present limit of 35 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
