jobs including a jet fighter pilot for the Texas Air National Guard.
(The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- July 21, 2000 -- NY-AIRPORT-DENTIST-3 --
Along with tending to travellers with emergency tooth ailments, Dr.
Robert Trager, the dentist at John F. Kennedy airport, has an unusual
responsibility. The Immigration and Naturalization Service calls on
Trager to perform dental and bone X-rays to determine an immigrant's
age, which can be critical to his or her effort to gain entry into
the United States. Thus hundreds of Chinese, Somalis, Sri Lankans,
Albanians, Hondurans and others who claim on travel documents to be
under 18 years old have filed through Trager's office in recent
years. Trager, in his office at the airport earlier this week. (Nancy
Siesel/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- July 21, 2000 -- MCCAIN-BUSH -- Months
after John McCain adamantly closed the door to accepting his party's
vice presidential nomination, a Republican close to the Arizona
senator said Thursday that he would take the No. 2 spot on the ticket
if Gov. George W. Bush offered it. McCain walked to his office on
Capitol Hill, Friday. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) PICHER, Okla. -- July 21, 2000 -- OKLA-CLEANUP-2 --
Piles of chat, huge hills of processed rock left after the lead and
zinc mines closed in the 1950s, towers over the town of Cardin near a
field where children play soccer. When the mines played out or were
forced to close by cheaper foreign imports, 175 million tons of chat
was left behind, creating a toxic moonscape encircling the town that
federal officials have been trying to clean up since 1983. (Ruth
Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) PICHER, Okla. -- July 21, 2000 -- OKLA-CLEANUP-1 --
Piles of chat, huge hills of processed rock left after the lead and
zinc mines closed in the 1950s, tower above Picher, in northeastern
Oklahoma.  The mounds of chat have marked the skyline of Picher since
miners began pulling minerals from dozens of mine shafts here in1891.
When the mines played out or were forced to close by cheaper foreign
imports, 175 million tons of chat was left behind, creating a toxic
moonscape encircling the town that federal officials have been trying
to clean up since 1983. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) HARTFORD, Conn. -- July 21, 2000 -- AETNA-HMO -- Call
it bad luck, bad timing, bad judgment or all of the above: Aetna, an
old-line insurance company, transformed itself into a hard-charging
tightly managed health care company four years ago, just in time to
become a main target of a backlash against managed care, especially
the kind Aetna was selling.  William Donaldson, chairman and chief
executive of Aetna, reads a document handed to him by his assistant,
Joanne Donahue, outside his office before an interview earlier this
week. (George Ruhe/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- July 21, 2000 -- GORE -- Seeking a
stronger commitment from labor, Vice President Al Gore tried to rouse
the union faithful Friday by accusing Republican George W. Bush of
proposing a Social Security plan that would drain the retirement
trust fund. "I will fight for you" says Gore during the annual
meeting of the Transportation Trades Department of the AFL-CIO on
Friday as, from left, the organization's executive director, Edward
Wytkind, and Sonny Hall, listened. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MALIBU, Calif. -- July 21, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JULY 23 -- SEX-ABSTINENCE -- In a culture saturated with sexual
messages, where consenting adults seem to hop into bed at the bat of
a feathery eyelash, a small minority are willfully dropping out of
the game. Calling themselves "born-again virgins," they embrace
abstinence not so much on moral or religious grounds, but to cleanse
themselves and reassert self-control. Wendy Keller, author of "The
Cult of the Born-Again Virgin." (Marissa Roth/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- July 21, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 23
-- KINA-PROFILE -- The hot new pop star Kina has the boundless, often
angry energy of a young Tina Turner, and the same never-ending legs,
planted wide in a prizefighter's stance. A gut-bucket soul singer
with the attitude and style of a rock star, she is the latest of a
recent wave of  African-American women to break from the rigid
formula  of contemporary R&AMP;B. Kina at club Lotus earlier this week.
(Miles Ladin/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- July 21, 2000 -- COVERDELL-VIEWING-COX  --
Georgia State Troopers salute as the coffin containing the remains of
Sen. Paul Coverdell lies in state in Georgia's state capitol, Friday.
Coverdell, 61, succumbed on Tuesday to the effects of a cerebral
hemorrhage. (John Spink/Atlanta Journal-Constitution) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MONTPELIER, Vt. -- July 21, 2000 -- NOISE-BUSTER-BOS
-- As executive director of the not-for-profit Noise Pollution
Clearinghouse, Les Blomberg he has spent four years helping people
across the country and the world to defeat what he calls the
forgotten child of the environmental movement. Blomberg records
traffic noise on State St. in the Vermont capital.  (Wendy Maeda/The
Boston Globe) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CRANSTON, R.I. -- July 21, 2000 -- INHERITANCE-TAX-BOS
--  Outside the gravitational pull of election-year politics, the
issue isn't so simple -- or polarized. In the real world, quashing
the estate tax would lower tax bills for many but raise them for a
few, simplify tax planning while threatening the livelihood of tax
planners, and give the wealthiest Americans a boost, at the expense
of charities. Cliff Sjoberg, 69, opposes the estate tax, which would
make it hard to transfer his metals company to his sons, Tim, 40, and
Kyle, 33. (Bill Greene/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- July 21, 2000 -- ABOUT-CARS-PTCRUISER --
The 2001 PT Cruiser, DaimlerChrysler's category-defying
minivan-sedan, owes much to the '37 Plymouth, the late '30s Ford
sedans with a 1950 Chevy Panel van and a little Willys Overland
thrown in. But Dan Niel, reviewing the vehicle, says its charismatic
retro design camouflages a supremely efficient box-on-wheels. The PT
won't tempt hot-rodders, but on balance, he says, complaints are few
and compliments abound. (DaimlerChrysler/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- July 21, 2000 --  ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 23 --
BIKE-POST-OFFICE-2  -- Cheering on professional cyclists, Gail
Sonnenberg has one thing in mind: increasing sales at the U.S. Postal
Service. As senior vice president of sales, Sonnenberg began
overseeing the Postal Service's cycling-team sponsorship in 1997 just
as Lance Armstrong emerged from his bout with cancer to join the
squad. Last year, the team with its uniforms emblazoned with the
Postal Service logo, was the first American squad to win the Tour de
France, a morale raiser at the post office. Armstrong celebrates his
victory in the 1999 Tour de France in July, 1999. (Ralph
Barrera/Austin American-Statesman Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- July 21, 2000 --  ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 23 --
BIKE-POST-OFFICE  -- Cheering on professional cyclists, Gail
Sonnenberg has one thing in mind: increasing sales at the U.S. Postal
Service. As senior vice president of sales, Sonnenberg began
overseeing the Postal Service's cycling-team sponsorship in 1997 just
as Lance Armstrong emerged from his bout with cancer to join the
squad. Last year, the team with its uniforms emblazoned with the
Postal Service logo, was the first American squad to win the Tour de
France, a morale raiser at the post office. It also brought the post
office $10 million in revenues from other sponsors, she said, and the
association with Armstrong brings glamour to an otherwise bland
brand. By Greg Winter. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- July 21, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 23 --
INVEST-WHITCOMB -- Roland P. Whitcomb, the lead manager of the $799.1
million First American Technology fund, says that in a technology
cycle, value investors get confused by the high valuation of the
stocks, because they underestimate the coming innovation. Whitcomb at
his desk during a recent interview. (Matthew F. Witchell/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- July 21, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 23 --
INVESTING-GREENBERG-BUFFETT -- One plays the hayseed, the other the
New York tough guy. The two giants of the insurance industry, Warren
E. Buffett, left, and Hank Greenberg, take different approaches to
management, but there is no question about who is in charge. (Nicole
Bengiveno, left, Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- July 21, 2000 -- NY-AIRPORT-DENTIST-2 --
Along with tending to travellers with emergency tooth ailments, Dr.
Robert Trager, the dentist at John F. Kennedy airport, has an unusual
responsibility. The Immigration and Naturalization Service calls on
Trager to perform dental and bone X-rays to determine an immigrant's
age, which can be critical to his or her effort to gain entry into
the United States. Thus hundreds of Chinese, Somalis, Sri Lankans,
Albanians, Hondurans and others who claim on travel documents to be
under 18 years old have filed through Trager's office in recent
years. Trager, in his office at the airport earlier this week,
reviewing a patient's X-rays. (Nancy Siesel/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 21, 2000 -- NY-AIRPORT-DENTIST-1 --
