<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Air raid hits Cowboys camp
</P>
<P>
   By JODY GOLDSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS _ Unless you're a college or high school coach
looking for pointers, NFL training camps generally aren't much fun
to watch.
</P>
<P>
   They're drill after drill, repetition after repetition, with
little resembling the actual 11-on-11 contact you see in an actual
game.
</P>
<P>
   But Dallas Cowboys camp has been more interesting this year.
With Troy Aikman and Joey Galloway working to get their timing
down, fans have been treated to some spectacular air shows.
</P>
<P>
   Add Rocket Ismail, Jason Tucker, Wane McGarity, James McKnight
and Jeff Ogden, and the Cowboys' speed will be the envy of many a
staff.
</P>
<P>
   And the Cowboys are working hard to take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   It is no coincidence that new head coach Dave Campo is spending
a bit more time with his offense this summer. It's the focus of
training camp _ a new, more exciting (and hopefully less
predictable) offense to help lead the Cowboys back to glory.
</P>
<P>
   And it's no coincidence Aikman is smiling a bit more these days.
The Cowboys have thrown out Chan Gailey's playbook and brought back
offensive coordinator Jack Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The object is to score points, whatever it takes,'' Reilly
said. ``If that means running the ball, fine. But we want to be
aggressive and go after people with both the running game and the
passing game.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly is known as a passing fundamentalist who favors the
crisp, timing routes rather than the short, underneath stuff for
which Gailey was criticized. Time after time on third-and-long,
Cowboys fans were frustrated to see handoffs to Emmitt Smith or
short passes up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys struggled to convert third downs last season and
finished 16th overall in offense. Adding to the frustration, Aikman
lost four receivers _ McKnight (during preseason), Michael Irvin,
McGarity and Ernie Mills _ to injury.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't simply the talent. The game plan had gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, I thought we were conservative,'' Campo said of the
old regime. ``We got set in what we could do. Jack is more
unpredictable in his play-calling. There will be times when we're
more of an off-the-seat-of-our-pants operation, which puts pressure
on the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The up-tempo style the Cowboys hope to run during games has
already been implemented in training-camp practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the tempo we're going at right now, we're finishing
practice quite a bit early,'' Campo said. ``Normally, we go a rep a
minute, so in a 10-minute period, we hope to run 10 plays. With
this tempo change, sometimes we run 12, 14, 15 plays. And we're
getting through that and still finishing practice a bit early.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps that the Cowboys worked all offseason to begin
implementing the new offense. They worked as a team during
minicamps and quarterback schools, installing the basics before
they got to Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minicamps and quarterback schools really helped us,''
Campo said. ``We really started ahead of the game offensively
coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   The new offense, which is actually the old offense with a few
tweaks, will look similar to the one used by the Super Bowl
champion St. Louis Rams last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys won't abandon the ground game. But with the addition
of Galloway, the emphasis thus far clearly has been on the passing
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously have a real deep threat now,'' Aikman said.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of pass-catching tight end Jackie Harris, formerly
of the Tennessee Titans, also adds to the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   How well the Cowboys will do in their first season with the
``old'' offense will hinge on the success or failure of Aikman, who
called last year ``disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be naive in saying that we'll be where we
eventually want to be when training camp is over,'' Aikman said.
``But I certainly believe we'll be where we need to be to at least
be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the Cowboys won't be putting their fans to sleep on
game day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm well aware that offenses bring people into the stands,''
Campo said. ``I understand what offenses mean in this league. I'm
excited about this.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
