<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9398 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     07-21 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One last hurrah for Golden Bear
</P>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ The drive was long and straight, finding
almost dead center of the 18th fairway and landing just across the
path known as Grannie Clark's Wynd.
</P>
<P>
   His second shot was reminiscent of one of those smart bombs from
the Gulf War, falling from on high and seemingly with eyes over the
Valley of Sin, bouncing once, twice and rolling to a stop about
five feet from the hole.
</P>
<P>
   So Jack Nicklaus, the once-Golden Bear now looking more like the
warm, muted glow of a setting sun, made the final walk to the most
storied green in the game with the deserved thunder from golf's
most discriminating fans ringing in his ears one more time.
</P>
<P>
   They cheered from the grandstands and from the balconies of
Rusacks Hotel. They yelled from the rooftops of houses that line
the right side of the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a poignant scene to see playing partner Angel
Cabrera bow in deference to usher the great ex-champion over the
Swilken Bridge first and to see Nicklaus call for son Steve, his
caddie, to join him on the bridge for one last round of
photographs.
</P>
<P>
   But then Nicklaus stood over that five-footer for birdie and
missed the putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been that way all year,'' he said later with a frustrated
shake of his head.
</P>
<P>
   Which, in case we forgot, reminds us of everything that made him
Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   In this age when the precocious Tiger Woods is trying to prove
he is the greatest young golfer in history, it is wise to remember
that Nicklaus is still, quite simply, the greatest golfer in
history.
</P>
<P>
   But now, on another brilliant day along the North Sea coast,
this was likely his final turn at the British Open. A 73 placed him
at 6 over par, and just as last month at the U.S. Open at Pebble
Beach, it meant he missed the cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's a mixed emotion,'' Nicklaus said. ``The walking
over the Swilken Bridge and up the 18th hole is very nice, but not
on Friday afternoon. The reception was terrific. . . . I just
wasn't playing enough golf to make anything happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He is 60 now, with an artificial hip and two bad feet that may
require surgery. But he will never be a so-called ``walking
trophy,'' a tribute to the past like Arnold Palmer or the
88-year-old Sam Snead.
</P>
<P>
   With Nicklaus, the competition has always been the thing.
Through all those years on the storied old courses around Great
Britain, Jack was always about contending. Especially at this
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember growing up and talking with Bobby Jones,'' Nicklaus
said. ``He told me, `All great golfers have to win at St. Andrews.
The record is not complete until you do.'''
</P>
<P>
   So Nicklaus won on the grounds of the Royal &AMP; Ancient in 1970
and 1978 and also at Muirfield in 1966. But the amazing part of his
record in Britain is that he finished second seven times and third
on three occasions.
</P>
<P>
   They have already invited him back to play in the Open in 2005
at St. Andrews, and he shrugs at the possibility. But the steely
eyes tell you not to count on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, when people asked me how long I'm going to play, I
always said, `As long as I enjoy it and can be competitive,'''
Nicklaus said. ``I think the two of them go hand in hand. As I
become less competitive, a lot of the enjoyment goes out of it for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   He had given himself and us a jolt of excitement at this year's
Masters by shooting even par and showing up on the leader board at
the midway point. And he did it while resenting his placing in an
old-timers group with Palmer and Gary Player. While they joked and
chatted around Augusta National, the Golden Bear was on the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Nicklaus gave himself a chance to stay around for the
weekend with three birdies on the front side. But his putter failed
him all day, and when he drove into the Beardies bunker on No. 14,
his chances dimmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The die was cast,'' he said. ``What are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus will play the PGA Championship next month, but he isn't
sure what he'll do after that. More surgery? Or does he sit back
and watch Tiger try the assault on all of his records?
</P>
<P>
   Twelve minutes after the golfer of the 20th century waved his
cap and blew kisses to the Scottish crowd, the man who has grabbed
the new millennium by the throat teed off at No. 1 en route to 11
under par and the halfway lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may sound silly, but I'm kind of rooting for Tiger or
somebody to come along and break the records or whatever,''
Nicklaus said. ``It would be good for the game of golf. It needs a
shot in the arm constantly.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees his own competitive drive in Tiger. What he'd like to
see is more players come along to challenge Tiger, to push him.
</P>
<P>
   It is said that you can learn everything about a man on a golf
course. With Jack Nicklaus, the lesson is that even in the light of
a fading sun, the glory, the dignity is always in competing.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
