<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-LARKIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS AND REDS COMPLETE DEAL BUT AWAIT LARKIN'S APPROVAL
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The New York Mets and the Cincinnati Reds have agreed
on a deal to send Barry Larkin, an 11-time All-Star shortstop, to
New York. Larkin must now decide if he will accept a trade from the
only team he has known.
</P>
<P>
   After Larkin told Cincinnati reporters Friday that he had been
approached by Reds general manager Jim Bowden about accepting a
deal to the Mets, the Mets' general manager, Steve Phillips,
acknowledged that he had made the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips refused to say which players he had given up, but the
Mets' top prospect, the 21-year-old outfielder Alex Escobar, was in
the lineup for Double-A Binghamton Friday night. Other top
prospects, including pitcher Grant Roberts, outfielder Jason Tyner
and infielder Jorge Toca, all played Friday night for Triple-A
Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Saturday afternoon, the Mets will have 72 hours in
which to convince Larkin to join them. Phillips plans to speak with
Larkin's agent, Eric Goldschmidt, and with Larkin, and said he was
prepared to fly to Cincinnati if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Larkin said he was not a hired gun, and after
speaking with Larkin by telephone this week, Mets infielder Lenny
Harris, a close friend of Larkin's, came away believing that Larkin
would insist on a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't feel he's in that renting situation,'' Harris said
on Wednesday. ``I know he doesn't want to come here or anywhere
else to visit for two months. He'd want to stay for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be a problem for the Mets, who owe Rey Ordonez $16
million over the next three years and appear poised to make a pitch
for the free-agent shortstop Alex Rodriguez of the Seattle Mariners
during the off-season. Ordonez is out for the season with a broken
left forearm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a shortstop for the future, so it means you're
looking for somebody to get you through this year,'' Phillips said
before Friday night's game against the Atlanta Braves. After he
announced the trade during the first inning, Phillips said that
Ordonez's contract would be a ``complicating factor,'' and that
this move ``doesn't affect any long-term decisions at all, right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin, 36, who has been with the Reds since making his debut in
1986, had asked Cincinnati for a three-year contract extension
worth around $28 million. The Reds balked, and after Larkin met on
Tuesday with John Allen, the Reds' chief operating officer, he said
he felt the Reds had no intention of bringing him back.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and Reds agreed on a deal Thursday afternoon, prompting
Bowden to make an unscheduled flight to Houston, where the Reds
were playing the Astros. Bowden met with Larkin for eight minutes,
and Larkin left the meeting when Bowden would not reveal the
players the Mets would send the Reds in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meeting was cool until then,'' Larkin said. ``I won't even
tell you the response I got. That's when I left.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he has at least 10 years in the majors and the last five
with the same team, Larkin must approve any deal. There may still
be hope that he will stay in Cincinnati, where he said he wanted to
finish his career. Reds center fielder Ken Griffey Jr. _ who
himself declined a potential deal to the Mets last winter, when he
was with Seattle _ has offered to defer salary to help the Reds
sign Larkin, who can be a free agent after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junior is not trying to tell anybody what they're worth or
what they should sign for,'' said Griffey's agent, Brian Goldberg.
``All he's saying and offering is, should the two sides want to
make a deal, compromise some and there is still some gap to be
bridged, he'll help bridge the gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldschmidt did not return several calls seeking comment,
although he said on Thursday that Larkin would not necessarily
insist on a contract extension before accepting a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to evaluate any situation that's put in front of
him and make a decision on his future based on all the
circumstances,'' Goldschmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   For the Mets, Larkin would be a substantial improvement over
Melvin Mora, who has filled in adequately but began the second half
of the season with a 3-for-26 slump. Some in the organization
believe Mora, who is in his first full season, is better suited as
a role player than a starter. As starting shortstops go, Larkin is
considered the best in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melvin has done an admirable job for us at shortstop,''
Phillips said. ``But Barry Larkin was the National League's
starting All-Star shortstop and he'd fit what we are trying to add,
which is a significant improvement over what we have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
