<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH RETREATS TO RANCH 
TO MAKE V-P DECISION 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRAWFORD, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush plans to spend this
weekend on the rolling blackland prairie of his ranch, deciding who
should be his running mate on the Republican presidential ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of speculation are over,'' Bush told reporters while
standing in the shade of a pair of native pecan trees at his ranch
house Friday. ``I'm going to make up my mind over the weekend. You
don't need to stake out the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, indicating that his final decision was all but made, said
he will receive no visitors at the ranch this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Bush's best efforts to end speculation, it abounded as
the week ended, with the focus on his former GOP rival, Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, and the head of Bush's vice-presidential
selection process, former Secretary of Defense Richard B. Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney set off speculation after it was learned Friday that he
has changed his voter registration from Texas to Wyoming, where he
had been a congressman. The Associated Press quoted anonymous
Republican officials as saying Cheney had emerged as a top
contender for the Bush presidential ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's registration switch could be designed to avoid conflict
with language in the 12th Amendment to the U.S. Constitution, which
forbids Electoral College voters from voting for vice-presidential
and presidential candidates who both are ``inhabitants'' of their
state.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Cheney's health raises questions about the likelihood of his
selection, though. Cheney, 59, has suffered three heart attacks and
has had quadruple coronary bypass surgery. An unhealthy heart is a
downside for a man who would be a heartbeat away from the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has a lengthy political resume, serving as White House
chief of staff under President Ford; Wyoming congressman and
eventually House Republican whip; and secretary of defense under
President Bush. Since 1995, he has been chairman and CEO of
Dallas-based Halliburton Corp., a leading engineering and
construction company for the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   McCain earlier this year said he did not want to be considered
as Bush's running mate, and their bitter battle for the GOP
nomination made it seem unlikely that Bush would pick McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday word broke that Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge,
another of Bush's potential running mates, had called McCain to see
if he would be interested in running. McCain reportedly told Ridge
he did not want the job but would accept if asked.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain drumbeat also gained volume as House Republicans
circulated a letter urging Bush to pick McCain, saying his appeal
to independent voters could help Republicans retain control of the
House.
</P>
<P>
   McCain told CNN he does not expect to be picked. ``It's
hypothetical because I don't believe I'm in the process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain aide John Weaver told the Houston Chronicle that McCain
does not want the job.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver, a Texan who is a political consultant to McCain, said
Friday that the Arizona senator still doesn't want to be vice
president and hopes that Bush won't offer the job to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (McCain) doesn't want to be asked. His position hasn't
changed,'' Weaver said.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver said McCain hopes that Bush won't call because ``if
you're asked, you have to do it ... He (McCain) is not going to be
disloyal.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver said McCain and Bush hadn't talked. ``It's the silly
season,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Bush refused to answer direct questions about whether he still
would consider McCain as a vice-presidential pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's a good man and he's a good friend of mine,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you this about John McCain. During the course of
this campaign he'll be a loyal soldier for my candidacy. He is a
man of duty. He loves his country.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what rank McCain would have in the Bush army, the
governor just smiled.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Ridge called McCain led to speculation that Ridge
considered himself to be out of the running.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge had been a popular potential choice because he is a
moderate Republican, a longtime friend of Bush's and the governor
of a key swing state. But social conservative leaders have opposed
Ridge because he supports abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Another governor high on Bush's list is Frank Keating of
Oklahoma. Keating is a Roman Catholic who opposes abortion, and he
is a former FBI agent. Keating also got high marks for how he
handled the aftermath of the Oklahoma City bombing.
</P>
<P>
   But Keating serves as little more than a safe choice because
Bush already is virtually sure to win Oklahoma. Keating on Thursday
said he does not expect the call asking him to join the ticket:
``I'm not holding my breath.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign on Friday touted a conference call with U.S.
Rep. John Kasich of Ohio to defend Bush's state budget against
attacks from Democratic candidate Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich declined to comment on the vice-presidential speculation,
other than to point out he had provided biographical information to
the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the letter promoting McCain that some Republican
congressmen were circulating, Kasich replied: ``I haven't signed
any letter or done anything. I really didn't know there was any
letter circulating.''
</P>
<P>
   Other prominent names considered to be on Bush's short list
include Sens. Fred Thompson and Bill Frist of Tennessee, George
Voinovich of Ohio and Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, and New York Gov.
George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he and his wife will travel to Georgia on Saturday for
the funeral of U.S. Sen. Paul Coverdale, a Republican. Then he will
return to to the 1,600-acre Crawford ranch to finalize his
vice-presidential decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like big decisions,'' Bush said, noting the first person he
will tell would be his wife. He said he would notify his father _
former President Bush _ ``somewhere between Laura and the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he will first call the person he has selected and then
call those who were not chosen.
</P>
<P>
   While there was much speculation about Bush making an
announcement on Monday, Bush indicated that he already has that day
planned out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to come back to Austin on Monday afternoon,'' Bush
said. ``I've got a TV interview here on the place, I've got another
TV interview in Austin Monday afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
