<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9432 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NJ-TORRICELLI-605&AMP;ADD     07-21 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TORRICELLI-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INQUIRY ON SENATOR'S AIDES SAID TO BE RENEWED 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI and TIM GOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Sen. Robert Torricelli prepares to seek the Democratic
nomination for governor of New Jersey, federal prosecutors are
intensifying their inquiry into the role that his office may have
played in a series of illegal contributions to his 1996 Senate
campaign, lawyers and others familiar with the case say.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week, Torricelli said he believed
prosecutors had effectively wrapped up their investigation last
month, when a Korean-American businessman who was a major donor to
Torricelli and other Democrats pleaded guilty to campaign-finance
violations.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers familiar with the federal inquiry say it has gained
new momentum with the decision of the businessman, David Chang, to
cooperate with the authorities in return for the promise of a
lighter sentence.
</P>
<P>
   They say prosecutors working for the Justice Department's
campaign-finance task force are focusing more closely on the
possible role of Torricelli staff members in directing and
accounting for the improper contributions of Chang and others.
</P>
<P>
   While Torricelli suggested that his staff members had not been
singled out by the prosecutors and were cooperating fully, lawyers
and others with knowledge of the case said one of Torricelli's
longtime aides had refused to answer at least some questions,
citing her constitutional right against self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   One lawyer said that the aide, Roberta Stern, was involved in
arranging one or more fund-raising events at the Hilton hotel in
Fort Lee, N.J., that was formerly owned in part by Chang. Two
lawyers said prosecutors were scrutinizing how the campaign used
the hotel and whether it was properly reported as an in-kind
contribution to the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Officials would not characterize the strength of the evidence
provided by Chang, whose credibility has sometimes been an issue in
his business dealings as well as his legal troubles. Nor is it
clear that any laws were broken by aides to Torricelli, who, as
chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, is one of
the party's most important fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Torricelli said several aides, including James
P. Fox, his chief of staff, and Adam C. Crain, his executive
assistant, submitted to questioning by prosecutors and FBI agents
as the government was preparing to go to trial against Chang.
``Each cooperated fully, and provided valuable information, and
each was prepared to testify on behalf of the government at the
trial of David Chang,'' said Abbe D. Lowell, the lawyer who
represents both Torricelli and the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell would not discuss whether Stern had asserted her Fifth
Amendment right and declined to answer questions of the task force.
But he said, ``I do know that she was one of the people ready to
testify as a government witness at the Chang trial.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lowell has fought to limit the scope of the federal inquiry,
lawyers said. They said he had repeatedly called senior Justice
Department officials, including Eric Holder, the deputy attorney
general, to complain about the actions of the prosecutors on the
campaign-finance task force.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he believed the task force was focusing on his own
fund-raising activities, Torricelli said, ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's about three incidents where people unfortunately
reimbursed contributors,'' he said, referring to cases in which six
donors to his 1996 campaign pleaded guilty to illegally funneling
contributions through others. ``As far as I know, those three
incidents have now been discovered and fully explored. As far as I
know, that has run its course.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first episode came to light last year, when a former Bergen
County Republican leader, Berek P. Don, and a former law partner,
Carmine Alampi, pleaded guilty to illegally reimbursing employees
in his office with Chang's money for $11,000 that they gave to
Torricelli's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Another major Torricelli supporter, Lawrence Penna, a
Hackensack, N.J., stockbroker, also pleaded guilty last year to
making $20,000 in illegal contributions to the Torricelli campaign
and $12,000 in illegal contributions to President Clinton's
re-election effort. (Separately, Penna also pleaded guilty to
illegally manipulating the stock price of a pharmaceutical company,
defrauding investors of millions of dollars in a deal in which
Torricelli's blind trust made a one-day profit of $50,000.)
</P>
<P>
   Chang, a shadowy New Jersey businessman who befriended
Torricelli and later sought his help in at least two failed
business schemes, was accused of crimes including perjury,
obstruction of justice, and funneling almost $54,000 in illegal
contributions to the senator's campaign. He pleaded guilty on June
2 to five misdemeanor campaign-law violations and an unrelated
conspiracy charge.
</P>
<P>
   One of Chang's former employees, Audrey Yu, and a Korean-born
businessmen, Cha-kuek Koo, pleaded guilty to helping Chang hide his
contributions in the names of other people.
</P>
<P>
   But contrary to the assertions of Torricelli and Lowell, his
lawyer, the interest of federal prosecutors did not end with the
donors to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers said one of the areas which the prosecutors are
continuing to investigate is how Torricelli's staff accounted for
an in-kind contribution of $1,700 for the campaign's use of a plane
that was paid for by one of Chang's companies, Bright &AMP; Bright
Corp. The company was ultimately reimbursed for the flights, but
the expense appears to have been charged after the campaign ended,
two lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors are also looking closely at how the campaign
accounted for the use of the Fort Lee Hilton for one or more
fund-raising events. Chang, who was a co-owner of the hotel, has
since transferred his interest to his former wife, Angeline Cho.
</P>
<P>
   Chang has provided extensive information to the authorities
about these and other transactions, they said. Chang's Washington
lawyer, David Schertler, said he would not discuss what information
his client had provided as part of his plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, as the focus of the investigation began to
shift from Chang and his associates to the possible role of the
campaign staff in the illegal contributions, the Justice
Department's task force added a third prosecutor to the inquiry
into Torricelli's fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But far from acknowledging concerns about his political future,
Torricelli insisted that in a campaign that had some 20,000 donors,
the illegal contributions that had been uncovered were isolated
problems that could scarcely be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a problem,'' he said, ``and it's embarrassing, but you
know, it happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
