<SLUG> BC-WACO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATION CLEARS FEDS 
IN WACO TRAGEDY 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ An investigation led by special counsel John
Danforth into the 1993 Waco tragedy cleared the government of any
wrongdoing and laid full blame for the fire at the Branch Davidian
compound on cult leader David Koresh and his followers.
</P>
<P>
   In a 156-page preliminary report released Friday, the
investigation concluded that government agents, at the end of a
51-day siege on the Davidian compound on April 19, 1993, did not
shoot at Davidians or start the fire that killed about 80 people at
the Mt. Carmel compound near Waco.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-month investigation also cleared the government of
charges it improperly used the military at the scene and that it
conspired to cover up its handling of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   However, the report admonished government lawyers and an FBI
agent for concealing information about the use of pyrotechnic
tear-gas rounds.
</P>
<P>
   The concealment, the report stated, raised ``darker questions''
about the government's response after it came under scrutiny for
its handling of the incident. It also resulted in the tragedy being
shrouded by a pervasive sense of distrust among the American
public, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is it possible that, last August, 61 percent of the people
of this country believed the government started the fire when there
is no evidence to support that, really none, when the evidence is
so overwhelming on the other side. How could that be?'' Danforth
said at a news conference in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth, who left the Senate in 1995 to practice law in St.
Louis, was appointed last September by Attorney General Janet Reno,
who yielded to calls for an independent inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Led by congressional Republicans, the demands for appointment of
a special counsel escalated dramatically after the government
acknowledged, following years of denials, that it used pyrotechnic
tear-gas canisters during the final assault.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth said Friday the investigation showed that the
pyrotechnic projectiles were fired, four hours before the blaze, at
a concrete construction site filled with water &UR; . &LR;  He said the tear
gas rounds were fired in an attempt to keep Davidians from seeking
refuge in a buried school bus that was used as a bunker. It was
linked to the compound through an underground tunnel that ran to
the construction site about 75 feet way.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us should be more skeptical of those who make
sensational accusations of evil acts by government,'' Danforth
wrote in the report.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that although the government ''did nothing evil ...
the failure of some of its employees to fully and openly disclose
to the American people the use of pyrotechnic devices undermined
public confidence in government and caused real damage to our
country.``
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder, Reno's top assistant, said
Danforth's report ``sheds further light on the truth and discredits
many of the unsubstantiated allegations that have skewed the
public's perception of the events of April 19, 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI Director Louis Freeh also welcomed Danforth's report and
lauded the former senator's inquiry as ``both vigorous and
thorough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple truth, as the FBI has maintained since April 19,
1993, has been unmistakingly confirmed again today _ the FBI fired
no shots on that day and the Davidians started the fire that
ultimately engulfed the compound,'' Freeh said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Houston attorney James Brannon, who is representing the
estates of the three children Davidian leader David Koresh had with
his wife, Rachel Jones, was critical of the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see the results of a lie detector test of all the FBI
agents that testified to his (Danforth's) committee, then I will
begin to believe anything the FBI says. Until then, he is relying
on known, admitted perjurers. ... I personally will never believe
anything the FBI says for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet unresolved, Danforth said, were:
</P>
<P>
   _ What happened to the shells and pyrotechnic projectiles.
</P>
<P>
   _Why the FBI denied for six years the existence of tapes of
audio transmissions of the FBI commander authorizing the use of
pyrotechnic rounds.
</P>
<P>
   _Why Justice attorneys who prosecuted the Davidians did not
disclose the use of the rounds to defense attorneys and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   _Why the FBI provided incorrect information about the use of
pyrotechnic projectiles to the Justice Department during the 1995
congressional hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statements were made that were just plain wrong about the
non-use of pyrotechnics, and the remaining four questions of the
investigations all pertain to the question of why were those
statements made that were just plain wrong,'' Danforth said.
</P>
<P>
   He said those issues will take another 3{ months to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   On July 14, a five-member jury in a civil trial in Waco decided
that the government was not responsible. The ruling came in a $675
million wrongful-death suit brought by surviving cult members and
the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey Clark, who represented several survivors and relatives at
the trial, said the Danforth investigation ``failed to address the
obvious,'' the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``If their conduct was so right,'' Ramsey asked, ``how did it
end so very wrong, with so many deaths?''
</P>
<P>
   Though Danforth has prosecutorial powers as special counsel, he
said he will not pursue charges based on his preliminary findings.
But he did not rule out the possibility of pursuing charges after
the remaining questions are answered and the investigation is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   The siege began when about 100 Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
agents stormed the compound on Feb. 28, 1993, after learning that
the Davidians were receiving large shipments of firearms, inert
grenades and black powder. A gunfight broke out, leaving four ATF
agents and six Davidians dead.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff ended April 19, 1993, when tanks driven by FBI
agents pumped tear gas into the compound. A fire broke out and
nearly all of the Davidians, including Koresh and 18 children, died
_ some from the fire, some from gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation revealed that on the morning of April 19,
Davidians spread combustible liquids through the compound and
started fires at three locations and that many of the Davidians had
no intention of escaping the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The surviving Davidians said in interviews that they saw others
making no effort to leave the burning structure and that one member
expressed remorse because she did not die in the fire. They
recalled Koresh teaching that fire was an acceptable means of death
for Davidians and they would ascend to heaven in a great fire.
</P>
<P>
   Concealed listening devices inside the complex indicated the
Davidians started the fire and that they discussed how they could
prevent fire trucks from reaching the compound.
</P>
<P>
   Experts determined that fires were started on the second floor
of the southeast corner of the compound, the stage area at the rear
of the chapel and the kitchen-cafeteria area.
</P>
<P>
   The report also stated that autopsy reports and anthropological
work showed that Davidians who died of gunshot wounds on April 19
were killed by other Davidians, and that at least 20 members were
shot and stabbed. Five of the victims were children under 14. Also,
many of those who died of gunshot wounds had been shot in the mouth
or head.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
