<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ASKS PUTIN'S INPUT
</HEADLINE>
 SUMMIT-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  ON N. KOREAN MISSILE DEAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By DAVID IVANOVICH &QL; 
c2000 Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OKINAWA, Japan _ President Clinton on Friday sounded out Russian
President Vladimir Putin about a possible deal with North Korea
aimed at persuading the nation to abandon its missile program.
</P>
<P>
   Putin arrived in Okinawa flush from a visit to Pyongyang, where
North Korean leader Kim Jong Il proposed shutting down his
country's missile program in exchange for international help in
developing its space program.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials are wary of dealing with the often-erratic
government in North Korea. But they also are clearly intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's envisioned here would be for North Korea to give up, to
foreswear its ballistic missile program in exchange for some kind
of international assistance in putting into orbit satellites and
that kind of thing,'' noted one senior Clinton administration
official.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if it was clearly understood that the launch capability
was going to be outside the territory of North Korea and thoroughly
subject to international technology controls, that not only would
be something that we would be prepared to pursue but it's actually
something we have pursued.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials are under no illusions they fully
understand North Korea's intentions. ``It's not entirely clear
what's in Kim Jong Il's mind with regard to this possible
trade-off,'' the official noted.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin deemed the North Korean proposal ``something to be
studied and discussed,'' the official said. ``I'd say he was
cautiously optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met early today with Japanese Prime Minister Yoshiro
Mori and discussed the North Korean proposal. Clinton said the
proposal is ``something that needs to be explored. ... We need to
see exactly what the specifics are.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea caused great alarm throughout East Asia in 1998 when
it fired a missile over Japan, a launch North Korea called a
satellite launch.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of an attack by an unpredictable regime like that in
Pyongyang is one of the driving forces behind a U.S. proposal to
build a missile defense system to protect both the United States
and U.S. troops stationed abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, North Korea and China have all expressed concern at the
prospect of the United States developing a missile defense system.
Russia insists deployment of such a system would represent a
violation of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Putin reiterated those concerns again during his meeting with
Clinton. The president has not decided whether to move forward with
the project.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those differences, the United States and Russia have
agreed to continue cooperating to control the spread of missile
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Putin came here to Okinawa on Friday to meet with
their counterparts in the so-called Group of Eight, the seven
industrialized powers and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who arrived in Japan one day later than scheduled to
spend more time at the Camp David peace talks, is considering
leaving Okinawa early to hurry back to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Putin offered Russia's help in brokering an Israeli-Palestinian
peace agreement, but Clinton administration officials would not
discuss what kind of role Russia may play. ``How exactly it might
be helpful will depend on the outcome in Camp David,'' the
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Evaluating the state of the world economy, the leaders expressed
concern about the risk that increased oil prices may represent.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from reiterating the argument that stable oil prices
would help both producing and consuming nations, the world leaders
did not consider any specific proposals to push crude prices lower.
</P>
<P>
   The Group of Eight members also expressed regret that plans to
relieve the world's poorest nations from crushing debt is
proceeding more slowly than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Security at the economic summit remained extremely tight, two
days after an estimated 20,000 demonstrators blocked the entrance
to the Kadena Air Base to protest the U.S. military presence in
Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to ensure demonstrators did not disrupt the economic
summit, the Japanese government brought in more than 20,000 police
officers from other parts of Japan to augment the Okinawan police
force.
</P>
<P>
   Police lined the roads to the summit area, and businesses in the
vicinity were closed. In addition, streets were cordoned off, and
the beaches around Okinawa's resort hotels were off-limits.
</P>
<P>
   Police scuffled with protesters again Friday outside the summit
area. And a small group of about 40 protesters marched down a key
street near where world leaders had gathered.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators carried a banner which, roughly translated,
read: ``We want to shatter the Okinawa Summit into pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   The police, many in riot gear, kept that demonstration
contained.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY
</P>
