<HEADLINE>
NEWHALL LAND MALL SALE WILL BUY BACK SHARES
</HEADLINE>
 - LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA FARRELL AIDEM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALENCIA, Calif. _ Negotiations are under way for the sale of
the Valencia Town Center - the mall, office buildings and
entertainment complex that make up the busiest retail district in
Santa Clarita, an official with The Newhall Land and Farming
Company said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Escrow is expected to close by the end of summer on the mall
itself, the retail buildings along Town Center Drive and the
entertainment center with its IMAX theater, company spokeswoman
Marlee Lauffer said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Newhall Land expects to finalize the sale
later this year with a second buyer interested in the three-story
office building on Town Center Drive and Princess Cruises' three
buildings, two of which are under construction, Lauffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither buyer was identified, nor were the selling prices of the
various properties.
</P>
<P>
   Newhall Land also is accepting offers on the Bank of America
building east of the mall, and the Spectrum Club gym on Town Center
Drive, including the 7.9 acres that surround it.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from the pending sales will be reinvested into the
company as part of a stock buyback program. Newhall Land announced
plans last year to repurchase up to 6.4 million shares - about 20
percent of the outstanding shares at that time.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is that the stock is undervalued and offers a
healthy investment for the Valencia-based developer.
</P>
<P>
   The sales will provide a cash infusion but substantially reduce
the company's income from commercial properties, according to its
second-quarter report, released this week. During the last quarter,
escrow closed on two neighborhood retail centers - in Castaic and
in the Valencia Industrial Center, adding $18.8 million to revenues
and $3.7 million to income.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue and income were down for the third quarter, which ended
June 30. Revenue fell $63 million to $55.3 million over the same
period a year ago and net income dropped $12.7 million to $6.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   Lauffer said the drops were not significant and that sales
cannot be timed around quarterly earnings reports. In fact, Newhall
Land expects its third straight record year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
