<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEISTY ON THE FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Only hard-core soccer fans know much about
the Galaxy's Peter Vagenas, but don't be surprised if the Pasadena
native is spotted in Sydney for the Olympic Games in September.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Vagenas has been all over the place for the Galaxy. He
has scored three goals with five starts in nine games played
overall.
</P>
<P>
   He's as feisty as a fly at a picnic and he'll get another start
against Tampa Bay in Raymond James Stadium this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy is without six starters for the second straight match
because of World Cup qualification matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity for all of us, not just myself,'' said
Vagenas. ``We feel like we have the best team in the league, not
just the best starting 11. We didn't get the job done last week
against D.C., so now we have to get the job done on the road before
the boys get back.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid loves about Vagenas. He
talks like a seasoned team leader, not a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has one of those good soccer brains,'' said Schmid. ``His
technical skills are going to improve, but he's having success
because he loves and understands this game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was never more apparent than last week. After creating and
finishing a beautiful goal to give the Galaxy a 1-0 lead, all
Vagenas would talk about later was the easy goal he missed, which
led painful 2-1 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know Pete, he was as upset as anybody,'' said Schmid.
``And that's how I measure players: Does that sort of thing bother
him or did it worry him? It bothered Pete, and if he gets that
opportunity again he's not going to do the same thing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   During a practice Wednesday, Vagenas was still harping on his
missed opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play a game of soccer for 90 minutes hoping to get one
chance and I had two of them in a span of 20 minutes,'' he said.
``That's why I'm gearing toward this game with Tampa. I'm going to
make amends. I'm going to make this game my best one all season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
