<HEADER>
A9463 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-NYT &LR;      07-21 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER TWO ROUNDS, WOODS EYES A KNOCKOUT
</HEADLINE>
  By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Tiger Woods sensed a career Grand Slam.
His opponents sensed the door slamming shut.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Woods work Friday was like watching a top surgeon
performing a delicate operation. His most precarious moment
occurred at the Road Hole, the par-4 No. 17 at the Old Course at
St. Andrews, when his second shot rolled off the green and down a
ledge onto a thin strip of grass near the road. But Woods showed
his brilliance once again, hitting a deft chip over the ledge that
ran eight feet past the cup before making the putt coming back to
save par.
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive round at the British Open, Woods did
not have a bogey. He has now played 62 consecutive bogey-free holes
at major championships.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Saturday's third round, Woods held a three-stroke
lead and the path to history in his hands. At age 24, Woods can
become the youngest player to complete the career Grand Slam,
having already won the Masters (1997), the PGA Championship (1999)
and the U.S. Open, which he won last month.
</P>
<P>
   Will anyone beat Woods? Perhaps only if he falters, and after
Friday's performance that did not seem likely. Shooting a 6-under
66 after his opening-round 67 on Thursday, Woods was 11 under (136)
for the tournament, three strokes ahead of David Toms (8 under,
69-67) and four strokes ahead of three players who were tied at 7
under: Steve Flesch (67-70), Sergio Garcia (68-69) and Loren
Roberts (69-68).
</P>
<P>
   Whether he is magical, or simply methodical, Woods is by far the
world's No. 1 player. And with 36 holes remaining between Woods and
history, he looked determined to let nothing stand in his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am playing very similar to how I played at Pebble,'' Woods
said, referring to the U.S. Open, which he won by 15 strokes, the
largest margin in major championship history.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his bogey-free streak, Woods smiled and said:
``Bogeys aren't good for a scorecard. If you go around and not make
any bogeys for the entire week, I guarantee you're going to have a
chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Five prominent players were tied at 6 under _ Fred Couples,
Ernie Els, Tom Lehman, Thomas Bjorn and Phil Mickelson. They will
all try to catch Woods, but that can be like trying to catch a
world-class sprinter who has a 10-yard head start.
</P>
<P>
   His competitors have seen it before. They do not want to see it
again. But there may be nothing they can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't made a bogey, and anybody who plays that kind of
golf is going to be tough to beat,'' Lehman said. ``All we can do,
all I can do, is play my best.''
</P>
<P>
   But Woods has played the Old Course as if it's his home course,
taking advantage of the benign conditions that have allowed players
to attack. There are 112 bunkers on the course, and Woods has not
been in one since the tournament started.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Els faded Friday with an even-par 72, quickly
surrendering the one-stroke lead he held over Woods and Flesch
through 18 holes. Playing in near-prefect conditions in the
morning, Els missed several short putts on the front nine, lost
confidence and squandered an opportunity to put more pressure on
Woods before he teed off in the afternoon. ``I never got into a
rhythm,'' Els said. ``Today was my bad round. I know I can play
better over the weekend, and I'll do that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Els foundered, Toms, Flesch and Garcia played well in the
morning and put themselves in the hunt. But Flesch has yet to win a
professional tournament, and Toms has only one top 10 finish in a
major championship. Garcia, however, took on Woods last year in a
thrilling back-nine duel at the PGA Championship, losing by one
stroke but gaining great respect at age 19. Garcia turned 20 in
January, and he is young enough not to be intimidated by the
prospect of chasing Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be something special,'' Garcia said about the
prospect of another final-round battle with Woods. ``I feel I'm
playing very solid, very well.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one is playing better than Woods, who displayed his
versatility in front of a crowd estimated at 47,000, the largest in
tournament history. Woods opened with a birdie at the par-4 opening
hole, hitting a sand wedge approach shot to eight feet, then making
the putt. He added a 12-foot putt for birdie at No. 4, then birdied
the par-5, 568-yard No. 5, hitting his second shot just short of
the green, then chipping to four feet and making the putt.
</P>
<P>
   Woods also made 12-foot birdie putts at Nos. 9 and 12, but his
up-and-down at No. 17 to save par was the highlight of his day.
Showing his touch and imagination, Woods stood on the thin grass
bordering the famous road and hit a soft shot over a three-foot
ledge onto the green, running the ball past the cup but
intentionally using a slope behind the hole to slow down the ball.
He also saved par at No. 18 by making a testy six-foot
double-breaking putt.
</P>
<P>
   With the tournament at his midway point, the world's best player
had a three-stroke lead. The weather could turn nasty this weekend,
which would make the Old Course far more difficult. That could also
work to Woods' advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think that to put some heat on Tiger Woods, we
need to have some good weather,'' Roberts said. ``If it's bad
weather, he's such a strong player, with his length, it would be
tough to catch him.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the weather, Woods planned to stay where he was.
When asked how he would feel in his competitors' shoes, he offered
no advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to answer that one, because I am not in their
shoes,'' Woods said. ``It's hard for me to understand what their
thought process is. I know what mine is. And that's all I need to
know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
