<HEADLINE>
GORE PURSUES UNIONS 
WITH MINIMUM WAGE 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to shore up his support from labor, Vice
President Al Gore warned union members Friday that his Republican
rival for president would gut the federal minimum wage law and
drain working people's retirement safety net while giving huge tax
cuts to the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on the side of the men and women who work hard, physical
jobs all their lives, who drive those buses and lay down train
track and carry bags at airports for others,'' Gore told
transportation trades workers at an AFL-CIO convention. ``They need
something more than an IOU when they retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore secured the labor federation's endorsement months ago, and
unions have donated about $15 million to the Democratic Party this
year, compared with $9 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic candidate has met resistance from the
Teamsters and the United Auto Workers, who have so far withheld
their support and may be considering backing Green Party candidate
Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   The two unions, which constitute about 2 million of the
AFL-CIO's total membership of 13 million, were angered earlier this
year over the Clinton-Gore administration's support of free trade
legislation, especially the granting of permanent normal trade
relations to China.
</P>
<P>
   Unions, which normally provide a bedrock of support for
Democrats, also winced at Gore's recent appointment of former
Commerce Secretary Bill Daley to run his campaign. Daley led the
administration's fight for China trade.
</P>
<P>
   Still, union members gathered at Washington's Capital Hilton
gave Gore a warm reception Friday, with leaders enthusiastically
hugging him and a packed ballroom drowning out his speech with
applause.
</P>
<P>
   Gore pledged to increase the minimum wage by $1 an hour, and
noted that his opponent, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, would allow
states to opt out of minimum wage laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is that all about?'' he asked. ``You talk about a
reactionary lurch back to the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been attacking Bush all week on his budget priorities
in Texas and on his economic adviser's recent acknowledgment that
the governor's plan for beefing up Social Security would
temporarily allow the Social Security trust fund to ``run dry.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president has charged that Bush's plan, which calls for
letting workers invest as much as 2 percent of their Social
Security payroll taxes in the stock market, would drain the Social
Security trust fund and could lead to raising the retirement age or
cutting benefits or both.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was asked about Gore's comments by reporters touring his
Crawford, Texas, ranch Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome the Social Security debate,'' Bush responded. ``This
is an administration that has done nothing for Social Security. I
have laid out a plan to save the strength of Social Security. I
can't wait to debate the vice president on this subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ray Sullivan said Bush, like Gore, supports
increasing the minimum wage, ``so long as there is flexibility for
states who have work force or economic challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY
</P>
