<SLUG> BC-FBO-BOWL-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA, FLORIDA PREPS TO BATTLE IN ROSE BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; PASADENA, Calif. _ They managed to stay at the same hotel
without incident. They sat in the same restaurants and attended the
same charity benefits. Now it's time for the players to battle in
what many consider the most attractive high school all-star
football game in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Designed to end years of debate over which state boasts the most
talented players, California and Florida's best prep football
standouts will meet at 7 tonight in the inaugural CaliFlorida Bowl
at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   California has already proven its dominance over Texas, another
of the nation's prep-talent hotbeds. California beat Texas for the
sixth straight year in last month's Shrine All-Star Football
Classic in Cerritos.
</P>
<P>
   Florida coach David Wilson marveled at the history of the Rose
Bowl earlier this week. But he admits his team is here to defend
Florida football's reputation, not get caught up in tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``California has proven its dominance over Texas, so we're
another measuring stick for them,'' said Wilson. ``But this is a
measuring stick for Florida football, too. We have talked about
this game a long time. And we have talked about leaving here
victorious.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a meeting many can't wait to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the emergence of Florida as a power in football, I think
this will be far and away the marquee game in the nation,'' said
Chuck Price of Air 7 Sports, tonight's chief sponsor. ``There are
so many all-star games out there. We didn't want this to be just
another game. With this event, at least 95 percent of the kids will
be going to Division I colleges.''
</P>
<P>
   The California squad features Concord De La Salle linebacker and
University of Miami-bound standout D.J. Williams, the consensus top
player in the nation. The team also includes USC-bound Matt
Grootegoed of Mater Dei and Santa Margarita quarterback Chris Rix,
formerly of Bishop Amat, who's headed to Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's all-star team features 6-foot-5, 225-pound linebacker
Eric Moore (Florida State) as well as quarterback Dominic Dunbar,
who prepped at Manatee High in Bradenton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Wink Barnett, director of the Florida Athletics Coaches
Association, hopes this all-star event sets the standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire state of Florida is extremely excited about being
involved with this event,'' said Barnett. ``We hope to build a
long-term relationship and rivalry with California.''
</P>
<P>
   California coach Gene Vollnogle said earlier in the week that
his players would have to be dead not to get excited about
tonight's game. He was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said we couldn't beat Texas and look what we did to
them,'' said Williams. ``Now we want to find out who the real
champion is. It's a big thing. You want to be able to say when you
play football in California, you come from the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Vollnogle, the longtime coach of Los Angeles City championship
teams at Banning and Carson, said his team will run the ball only
five to 10 times. That means a lot of work for Rix, as well as
fellow quarterbacks Scott Vossmeyer (Van Nuys) and Matt Cassel
(Chatsworth).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running a four-wide receiver set,'' said Rix. ``We'll be
throwing the heck out of the ball and it will be exciting because
we're surrounded with all this talent and speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Vollnogle expects Florida to mix it up more than his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Florida will run the ball more than us,'' said
Vollnogle, who has been in semiretirement for 10 years, though
working as an assistant coach. ``They're sort of like Texas. They
run the option, the power and they will throw a little. Hopefully,
we have done enough this week to be prepared for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
