<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9602 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-BOBBY-LADN-(SLANG     07-21 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BOBBY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRASWELL GETS CSUN EXTENSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL A. ANASTASI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Bobby Braswell has done things the right way.
</P>
<P>
   And so Cal State Northridge rewarded its men's basketball coach
with a four-year contract extension on Friday that will pay the
37-year-old Valley native nearly $140,000 annually plus incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great day for me and for my family,'' said Braswell,
who graduated from CSUN and began his career as the coach at
Cleveland High in Reseda.
</P>
<P>
   Braswell has a 63-53 record in four years at CSUN and led the
Matadors to their first 20-win season at the Division I-A level
last season.
</P>
<P>
   He has built the program while remaining steadfastly loyal to an
old-school brand of coaching that at times has left some of his
best players on the bench for important games because they violated
a team rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been the most satisfying thing about it,'' Braswell
said. ``We've done this without sacrificing our principles. It's
been a fun ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Braswell will earn a base salary of $100,116 plus an additional
$38,000 from outside sources. He said he can earn more by achieving
a number of incentives that are written into the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The salary puts Braswell in line with other men's basketball
coaches in the Big West Conference, which CSUN is moving to
following a final season in the Big Sky.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Morgan at Long Beach State, for example, signed a contract
extension earlier this summer that pays him $140,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been impressed with Coach Braswell's integrity and with
his concern for student-athletes and their development on and off
the court,'' CSUN athletic director Dick Dull said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has molded this program into a highly competitve team, and
I look forward to even bigger and better accomplishments in the
years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Braswell has been interviewed several times for coaching
vacancies at other universities. He said his new contract raises
the bar for employment elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I am committed to Cal State Northridge,'' Braswell
said. ``It's going to have to be a very, very, !ital!very!off good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN twice has come one victory away from reaching the NCAA
Tournament under Braswell, most recently in April when the Matadors
lost in the Big Sky Tournament final in overtime to Northern
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors, while playing inconsistently at times this past
year, nevertheless defeated both Fresno State and Oregon _ two
eventual NCAA teams _ on the road.
</P>
<P>
   This year's team returns four starters: Brian Heinle, Markus
Carr, Jeff Parris and Carl Holmes. Together they averaged 44 points
a game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
