<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-U.S.-WOMENS-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON DAY 2, MALLON LEADS BY CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
  By BILL FIELDS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GURNEE, Ill. _ Meg Mallon abandoned her maverick strategy on one
hole but held on to her patience for the entire round. It was the
latter that allowed her to maintain the lead through two rounds of
the U.S. Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was much more of a scramble day,'' said Mallon, whose
even-par 72 at the Merit Club put her at 4-under 140, one stroke
ahead of Betsy King and Karrie Webb. ``I hung in there. Just making
a bogey in an Open is OK''
</P>
<P>
   Cristie Kerr is at 143, and six players are another stroke back
at 144: Juli Inkster, the defending champion, who shot a 74; the
19-year-old Dorothy Delasin, who had the day's best round, a 68;
Laura Davies (71); Rosie Jones (71); Kathryn Marshall (72), and
Shani Waugh (75). Annika Sorenstam, the LPGA's leading
money-winner, who has five victories this season, has ground to
make up after shooting a 75 and finishing 36 holes at 4-over 148.
</P>
<P>
   Mallon and King were in the same grouping, which gave the two
former Women's Open champions a chance to practice what they had
recently preached to one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betsy and I are very good friends,'' Mallon said, ``and we
made a pact to be patient golfers this week. Sometimes we get a
little fired up out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The pace was tedious and the wind was fickle, but Mallon, who
won this event in 1991, and King, who won consecutive titles in
1989 and '90, were up to the challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meg played very well,'' said King, who shot 70. ``I think that
helped me keep it up with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb, the 25-year-old Australian star, who has won four
tournaments this year, said she was inspired by the tough
conditions and the importance of the championship on her way to a
72.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest event we play all year,'' Webb said.
``Whether or not I win this weekend, it's a tournament I'll be
gunning to win every year. The atmosphere _ there's just a little
more electricity out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb's only blemish was a bogey on her last hole, but on a day
when the field averaged 76.8 and 31 players shot in the 80s, Webb
did not leave the course too concerned about it.
</P>
<P>
   Mallon attracted attention while taking the first-round lead
when she purposely played her tee shot on the 14th hole into the
adjacent 13th fairway. But she took the conventional route Friday,
making a par 4 as she had done in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   USGA officials did not take any action to deter players from
taking the alternate route. Pat Hurst and Beth Daniel took the
detour, but the most of the field played the 14th hole
conventionally.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when rounds stretched beyond five hours and many of the
holes were buffeted with crosswinds, golfers had to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty tired right now,'' said King, 45, who has two
victories this season. ``It took a lot to play out there. When
you're a little bit older, it's tough. It's hard to give that age
up to the competitors. But I'm happy to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb started this season on a tear with four early victories.
But she last won in the year's first major, the Nabisco
Championship, in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's just been a drought hasn't it?'' she joked when
someone noted that it had been a while since she won. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
