<SLUG> BC-COMICS-COMICS </SLUG>
  
 MARVELING AT COMIC-BOOK HEAVEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SUPERHEROES, COLLECTIBLES AND TRINKETS DRAW 45,000 TO SAN
DIEGO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BY DAVID LAZARUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Tom Twohy traveled all the way from San Jose to
the San Diego Convention Center to spend $300 for a new light
saber. He wanted a really good one to go with his Jedi Master
costume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to carouse around and get my picture taken,'' the
40-year-old Silicon Valley dot-commer explained. ``Of course, that
happens more when I wear my Klingon costume.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of crowd at the 31st Comic-Con International,
North America's largest comic-book confab and trade show. The
event, which features the latest trends in the comics industry and
attracts more than 45,000 visitors, commenced Thursday and ends
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   This year's convention received an extra spark from the recent
opening of the ``X-Men'' movie. Yet while X-Men paraphernalia was
everywhere, the mutant heroes themselves were noticeably absent.
</P>
<P>
   At the sprawling booth of Marvel Comics, publisher of the
various X-Men titles, visitors had to make do with a skinny guy in
a Spider-Man costume. Spider-Man will have his own movie out by the
end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are enough other superheroes to take care of things,''
Spider-Man said when asked who was keeping the streets of San Diego
safe while he was inside posing for pictures. The X-Men, he added
with a measure of scorn, ``are all busy with their movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the aisle, rival DC Comics trundled out its writers and
artists instead of guys in costumes. San Francisco writer Judd
Winick, 30, was on hand to discuss his new role as author of the
Green Lantern series, a move to keep the character fresh.
</P>
<P>
   Green Lantern, he said, ``is going to grow up. He's going to eat
fast food and surf the Net. He's going to be one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, another San Francisco writer, Ed Brubaker, said he was
looking forward to his debut next month as the new author of
Batman. He said alert readers might notice Gotham City seeming a
little more like his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent more time in San Francisco than Manhattan,''
Brubaker said, ``so when I think of corrupt city politicians and
city crime, I think of San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he admitted that he ``can't see Willie Brown
coming out and turning on the Bat Signal.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood at the convention was decidedly festive, with the
event's hundreds of exhibitors peddling everything from vintage
comics to original artwork to all manner of toys and collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Hanford, a San Diego third-grade teacher, kept busy by
poking through bins at various booths in search of vintage Classics
Illustrated comics. His face lit up as he plunked down $100 for a
stack that included titles such as ``The House of the Seven
Gables'' and ``Silas Marner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I now have every Classics Illustrated except one,'' he said
with pride.
</P>
<P>
   Hanford gingerly fingered the one missing piece from his
collection, a mint-edition copy of Westward Ho! selling for $650.
He said he planned to cruise the other booths before purchasing
this long-sought treasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like good literature,'' Hanford said. ``I read the
books, too. I like to see how they compare.''
</P>
<P>
   His 13-year-old daughter, Cathy, said her dad lets her read his
comics from time to time. ``I liked A Tale of Two Cities,'' she
noted. ``It was better than the book. It had better pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking around the convention hall, some might conclude that
Comic-Con was populated almost exclusively by geeky overweight guys
with ponytails and scraggly little beards. But that would be
unfair.
</P>
<P>
   There were women present as well.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriella Tejeda, 15, prowled among the booths in a black
leather Catwoman outfit. ``I'm just being myself,'' she said.
``I've always loved Catwoman. She's so brave and stands on her own
two feet.''
</P>
<P>
   She also commits crimes, it was pointed out. ``Yeah, she does
that,'' Tejeda reluctantly allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Lorraine Thomas, 35, flew up from Venezuela for the show. She
was looking to round out her collection with some missing Fantastic
Four and Little Lulu comics. Asked how many Little Lulus she now
possessed, Thomas whipped out her Palm handheld device and punched
in some commands. ``Seventy,'' she reported.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, however, women at Comic-Con fell into the
girlfriend/wife category and seemed to be struggling to share their
guys' passion for men who wear tights and capes.
</P>
<P>
   Many, like Jill Durham, 21, who sported a blue Superman shirt as
she trailed her fiance, said women didn't really see what the big
deal was. But they did have this to say: There's an awful lot of
sex at a comic-book convention.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everywhere visitors looked, they saw drawings and
photos of women with unusually robust proportions clad in skimpy
costumes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans like tough, dominant women,'' said Monte Michael
Moore, an illustrator who specializes in cheesecake depictions of
fantasy heroines. ``That will never change.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles artist Paul Dale was promoting his creation, Chopper
Chicks of Mars, which he said is ``kind of like `Baywatch' on
Mars'' and is marketed to male readers ages 16 and up. ``I'm trying
to capture kids who are just discovering sex,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than a few of those kids gathered near the booth of Stacy
Walker, a Chopper Chick of Mars come to life. Walker, wearing a
low-cut blue-sequined gown, has worked for the past decade as a
model for some of the leading illustrators in the fantasy/superhero
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Among the numerous prints for sale was one of Walker in the
guise of an icy villain beating the tar out of Superman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comics are very over the top, very over-exaggerated,'' she
said of her suitability as a comic-book model. ``I'm sort of an
unknown, but in this realm, I'm really big.''
</P>
<P>
   Falling into the same category was Esther Hwang, the curvaceous
former assistant to Mayor Brown and former spokeswoman for the San
Francisco Department of Public Works who has since refashioned
herself as an Internet pinup princess.
</P>
<P>
   Like Walker, Hwang attracted a crowd of admiring boys of all
ages as she autographed prints and calendars showing her in a
variety of too-small swimsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make appearances at a lot of conventions,'' she said.
``These guys love the Internet, and I'm really big on the Net. I
fit right in at Comic-Con.''
</P>
<P>
   Hwang said she's making a much better living now peddling her
flesh online than she ever did as a municipal worker. She intends
to use the proceeds to help pay for law school.
</P>
<P>
   ``My site isn't just about babes, boobs and bikinis,'' Hwang
insisted. ``I have something to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Her site says that ``Esther desires to be recognized for her
talents and intelligence and is determined to uphold strong morals
and values on her upward strive toward stardom.'' She charges $10 a
month for access to photos of her in lingerie.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, muscleman Lou Ferrigno, who played the
Incredible Hulk on television, was selling prints of himself in
even tinier swimsuits and flexing his still-huge biceps for fans.
He said he's looking forward to making a cameo appearance in a
coming film version of the Hulk.
</P>
<P>
   And looking more than a little startled by the goings-on around
her, Veronika Kirueshkin-Stepanoff did her best to appear
comfortable in the barely there costume of a new superhero called
Gamma Girl.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to San Jose from Moscow four years ago and was
recommended by a friend for a gig at Comic-Con. In heavily accented
English, Kirueshkin-Stepanoff said she believed Gamma Girl would do
well in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gamma Girl fights with the bad guys,'' she pointed out, ``and
Russia has a lot of bad guys right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamma Girl is the creation of Dan Marquez, an engineer at a
Silicon Valley maker of integrated circuits who has invested
$10,000 into publishing his own comic. And he's about to sink
thousands more into a second issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping it will turn into a big comic-book company,''
Marquez said. He gazed hopefully around the crowded hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a lot more fun than integrated circuits,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
