u a BC-NC-HEZBOLLAH-SMUGGLER     07-21 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-HEZBOLLAH-SMUGGLERS-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEZBOLLAH CELL REPORTED IN NORTH CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a series of raids throughout the Charlotte, N.C.,
area, federal officials on Friday arrested 18 people in what they
called a broad conspiracy to aid the militant Islamic organization
Hezbollah, listed by the government as a terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
   Those arrested, most of whom originally came from a neighborhood
south of Beirut, were part of an active Hezbollah cell in North
Carolina that trafficked in contraband cigarettes and laundered
money that was then sent to the group's leaders in Lebanon, the
government charged in an affidavit filed in U.S. District Court in
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Although the authorities did not specify the amount transferred
to Hezbollah, they did say that one suspect alone had sent it at
least $1 million. Lending support to an organization designated by
the government as terrorist is a federal crime.
</P>
<P>
   This cell meets weekly in Charlotte to plot ways to assist
Hezbollah, the affidavit said, and ``is extremely anti-United
States.'' The meetings invariably include a reading from the
Ayatollah Khomeini, it said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the suspects were charged with any terrorist activities
themselves. But the man identified as the leader of the group,
Muhammad Youssef Hammoud, was described as having received military
training from Hezbollah, and the government said he ``would not
hesitate'' to carry out a terrorist act if ordered to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Another man, Said M. Harb, was accused of helping to purchase
technical equipment for Hezbollah, including global positioning
systems, night vision goggles and computers.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the group were also charged with aiding a terrorist
organization, and with immigration and visa fraud, money laundering
and racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the information about the suspects came from five
informers who infiltrated the cell, said the affidavit, presented
in court Friday by U.S. Attorney Mark T. Calloway.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money sent overseas was raised through illegal
cigarette trafficking, the government charged. Members of the group
were said to have set up wholesale tobacco businesses as fronts and
to have then smuggled large quantities of cigarettes from North
Carolina, where the tax is 5 cents a pack, to Michigan, where it is
75 cents a pack. The difference in price, officials said, could
result in a profit of $3,000 to $4,000 for every truckload of
cigarettes sent to Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said about 250 federal, state and local agents took
part in the raids, which began before dawn Friday and struck at
homes and businesses alike.
</P>
<P>
   George Levkulich, who lives next door to one suspect, Ali Fayez
Darwich, said vehicles from the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms pulled up at Darwich's home early Friday morning and spent
the whole day there, with agents removing much of the house's
contents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took all kinds of things out of there, video cameras and
stuff,'' Levkulich said. ``We asked them what was going on, and
they said it was just a routine investigation. But I guess it
wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Levkulich said he was amazed to hear that his neighbor was
involved with Hezbollah. He knew Darwich as a painter who worked
for a local home builder and supervised a crew of other painters.
(In fact, he said another painter pulled up to the house Friday
with his truck full of ladders and was immediately searched by
federal agents.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped me with a water pipe once,'' Levkulich said. ``He
was a nice guy, a regular guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The government said Darwich was the brother of a ``well-known
Hezbollah fighter'' in Lebanon and had regularly sent large sums of
cash there via courier. He also participated in the cigarette
scheme, as did his cousin, Hammoud, the affidavit said.
</P>
<P>
   Darwich was charged with eight crimes, including marriage fraud:
He is accused of having entered into a false marriage in order to
receive American citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, backed by Syria and Iran, is Israel's fiercest enemy
in southern Lebanon, where it recently claimed victory when Israeli
troops withdrew after 18 years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In 1997, the State Department designated Hezbollah a foreign
terrorist organization, based on its participation in the bombing
that killed 241 U.S. Marines in Beirut, Lebanon, in 1983 and the
kidnapping of Western hostages in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The terrorism designation, renewed in October, makes it illegal
to provide any material or other support to the group. Israel has
long urged the United States to crack down on cells that it says
are funneling money to the organization.
</P>
<P>
   The caseagainst the suspects dates from 1997, a result of a
local investigation into cigarette smuggling, which is widespread
in North Carolina because of its low tobacco tax. The affidavit
describes numerous cigarette buying and selling trips by the
suspects, and gives a detailed record of their checking-account and
credit-card dealings with cigarette distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the proceeds from the smuggling have been invested in
semilegitimate businesses, like a tobacco shop and a Lebanese
restaurant and deli in Charlotte, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   But the most personal information in the affidavit involves the
group's ideological associations with Hezbollah, as described by
the informers. It says, for example, that Hammoud frequently
downloads songs and speeches from Hezbollah Web sites, which, it
says, he uses in the cell's Thursday night meetings. He also has a
collection of Hezbollah's videotapes, which he plays at meetings to
encourage donations, the government said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-21-00 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000721.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-NILE-VIRUS-NYT &LR;      07-21 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NILE-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORKERS DEBATE WHAT'S WORSE: WEST NILE OR PESTICIDES? 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Camille Glad and Daiva Kezys are close in age, live
in the same borough and spent part of Friday a yard from each other
on a commercial strip in northern Queens. But when it comes to
their opinions on how the city should deal with the threat of the
West Nile virus, the two could not be further apart.
</P>
<P>
   Glad, 64, bars her elderly mother from outings in the park and
keeps her grandchildren inside when they visit from Maine to
protect them from mosquitoes that carry the virus. And, though she
worries that pesticides may have some risks, she says she believes
strongly that the city should spray them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You weigh one against the other, the good against the bad,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kezys, 61, says seven people _ the number who died from the
virus last year _ are not enough to justify substantial squirts of
chemicals near her home. Last year's spraying, she says, left her
with a six-month cough, and she fears for her dog's safety when she
sees him trample the misted grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think somebody is making a buck off this spraying,'' said
Kezys, a real estate agent. ``If it is so safe, why do they tell
people to stay inside?''
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma faced by Glad and Kezys is an increasingly common
one: what to fear most, the threat of West Nile or the threat of
the chemicals being used to prevent it? And interviews conducted
around the city and suburbs on Friday indicate that how people
react depends largely on a complex array of factors, many of them
highly subjective.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that many people feel ill-informed about both
the dangers and specifics of West Nile, and the dangers posed by
pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Heilman, who lives in Scarsdale, N.Y., and is an
administrator for a pathology laboratory, falls into the group
doesn't think there is enough information. ``They haven't had any
real incidents of West Nile, so I'm reluctant about spraying,'' she
said. ``I've thought about contacting an environmental organization
to actually ask them what problems they might anticipate.''
</P>
<P>
   People who were raised in parts of the country where riding a
bicycle behind a truck puffing huge clouds of pesticide was
childhood sport, for instance, have different views from those who
never even went to summer camp. People's attitudes can be shaped by
where they get their news and how they feel about government.
</P>
<P>
   Science, in this case, is often of little help. Few people, even
top epidemiologists, can illuminate West Nile much; it was never in
North America before last year. It has no cure. The number of birds
and mosquitoes found to be infected with the illness changes every
day. And while the mayor and other officials are quick to dismiss
concerns about pesticides, they do not dole out much more
information on the chemicals than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have questions about whether strategic public
health interventions do more good than harm,'' said Gerard
Fergerson, a public health historian at the Wagner School at New
York University.
</P>
<P>
   The issue becomes more pressing each day with mounting evidence
that the disease has affected bird and mosquito populations around
the region. Friday, the State Health Department said it had
discovered nine new birds carrying the virus in Rockland,
Westchester, Richmond and Queens counties, raising the number of
birds testing positive for the virus this summer to 29.
</P>
<P>
   Further, a mosquito carrying the West Nile virus was found
farther north, in Orange County. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said that
in response, the city would extend its pesticide spraying to
northern Queens and Staten Island, where spraying began earlier
this week, in spite of protests and a lawsuit brought by
environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   Viewpoints are informed greatly by personal experience and even
jobs. Ken Pulvidente, who owns a pet store in Amityville, N.Y.,
suspects that fish in ponds in the area died last year as a result
of spraying, which led him to worry about his drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought that when they sprayed last year it was
ridiculous,'' Pulvidente said. ``The spraying is probably going to
kill us 20 years from now. You're spraying it in the middle of
residential areas. How can that make sense?''
</P>
<P>
   A scientific background can bring an added twist.
</P>
<P>
   Mary-Ann Karpel, who has studied entomology, said that she had
learned that mosquitoes and people both could build up a tolerance
to chemicals. It is not an environmental opposition she harbors,
but a fear of what happens next. She envisions a world where
supermosquitoes dwell, flying about immune to all poisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then what do we do?'' mused Karpel, munching on an ice-cream
bar in a Mount Kisco health food store. ``You should keep your
antibiotics and insecticides for desperate situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Political leanings can inform as well. Denise Walter, who lives
in Stamford, Conn., said she was ``one of those people who trust
their public officials.'' As such, she tends to believe them when
they promise that pesticides are safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're being responsible,'' she said. ``I support
what they're doing. Better than finding it out on the back side,
after someone's gotten West Nile.''
</P>
<P>
   And while opinions about pesticides do not divide along age
lines, there are some subtle distinctions. Marilyn Morello, 63,
lives on Staten Island, where dead birds infected with West Nile
have been discovered this month. She has grandchildren. But she
fears for her own health most and at the same time worries about
the efficacy of the spraying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really scared to death,'' she said. ``I have lung cancer
so I'm really worried about what the spraying might do to my lungs
when I breathe the stuff in. I don't know how effective spraying
for mosquitoes will really be. Mosquitoes are everywhere and they
can fly from place to place.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Barone, a teacher's aide who lives on Staten Island, also
worries whether spraying is effective. But she adamantly supports
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have children, everything just becomes much more
frightening,'' she said. ``You just take so many precautions. I'm
not all that concerned about what the spraying will do to humans
because I heard that it doesn't really affect us, but I'm afraid
that it might not completely get rid of the virus.''
</P>
<P>
   People with world travel experience tend to view the specter of
disease more gravely. Randy Altman, a tea trade consultant from
Pleasantville, in Westchester County, said he was reluctantly in
favor of the spraying and feared that the United States was far
behind other countries in understanding the full health risks of
outbreaks like West Nile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States middle class feels it is immune from these
insect-borne diseases,'' he said. ``They think it is a third world
problem. And it is not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
