<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX INCREASE NO LONGER JUSTIFIABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   A development that hasn't gotten nearly
the attention it deserves is the recent House Republican push to
roll back the 1993 tax levied on Social Security benefits.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tax raised the portion of Social Security benefits subject
to income tax from 50 percent to 85 percent for some relatively
high-income retirees. Although the tax affects only about one in
five beneficiaries, the rollback is the fitting thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was part of an effort to pare the federal budget
deficit, which hit a record $290 billion the year before. The
budget is now in surplus, thanks to excess revenue generated by the
Social Security payroll tax. This means there is no further
economic justification for the imposition.
</P>
<P>
   Another good reason is that a tax on any portion of benefits is
unfair and immoral. Working taxpayers not only pay Social Security
taxes from the first dollar of their wages but also are obligated
to count as income for tax purposes the wages they never see that
have been paid into Social Security. This means the money made over
a working lifetime paid to Social Security is effectively taxed
twice.
</P>
<P>
   To tax it a third time in the form of benefits made possible by
a worker's own tax money already contributed to the system has
always seemed the worst sort of tax-policy immorality. Washington,
however, got away with it because the levy affected only those
perceived as affluent. Thus, the class-warfare ploy worked when
stated in the context of a patriotic obligation to help fight the
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   This rationale no longer exists, though, and House Ways and
Means Chairman Bill Archer is hoping to marshal enough support to
return the limit of benefits subject to taxation to the pre-1993
level. A recent story in The New York Times said Archer hoped to
get floor consideration for the bill by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   The '93 tax increase was passed over considerable GOP objection
when Republicans were still a congressional minority. Archer
characterized it as ``money grubbing'' and said with the budget now
in the black, it was time ``to right this wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Excellent point. It's too bad there probably won't ever be
enough support for a total elimination of taxation of Social
Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   When most Americans are confronted with any proposal to convert
Social Security to a means-tested entitlement, the objection is
unfairness, because they paid their money into the system and
deserve their payoff.
</P>
<P>
   In the early debate over whether to tax any part of Social
Security benefits, however, this wasn't an issue because most
beneficiaries wouldn't be affected. Nevertheless, the principle
remains the same. If you paid the money into the system as taxes,
what's the justification for taxing it again on the way back into
the taxpayer's pocket?
</P>
<P>
   There was no justification, but it happened because just like
the income tax itself nearly 90 years ago, it was sold as a
class-warfare package that would affect only a relatively few
richies.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, it seems, is just trying to keep history from repeating
itself by making sure a tax designed to soak ``the rich'' doesn't
eventually become a tax on everybody.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
