<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMGEN-PATENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMGEN INC. WINS SOME ARGUMENTS, AS PATENT INFRINGEMENT SUIT
PROCEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amgen Inc. won another round Friday in its patent infringement
lawsuit against Transkaryotic Therapies when the judge overseeing
the case eliminated some of the arguments Transkaryotic was trying
to use in its defense.
</P>
<P>
   Still, lawyers and analysts said the trial, which is expected to
last at least until September, was far from decided.
</P>
<P>
   Transkaryotic wants to sell its own version of erythropoietin,
the best-selling drug in the biotechnology industry. Transkaryotic
says it can make erythropoietin, which is used to treat anemia, in
a manner that does not infringe Amgen's patents, but Amgen
disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its defense, Transkaryotic is trying to persuade
Judge William Young of the U.S. District Court in Boston to declare
Amgen's patents invalid. One set of arguments it made was that
Amgen's claims did not warrant a patent because they were obvious
and anticipated by the previous work of others.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, who is trying the case without a jury, ruled against
Transkaryotic on those points Friday. But he did not rule on
whether Transkaryotic infringed any patents.
</P>
<P>
   Elise Wang, an analyst with PaineWebber, said the ruling
weakened the position of Transkaryotic and its partner, Aventis SA,
the European drug company that is also a defendant in the suit.
Shares of Transkaryotic fell $3.875, to $31.125, while Amgen rose
$3.9375, to $78.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are other grounds on which Amgen's patents can be
declared invalid. TKT's main argument is expected to be that the
claims in Amgen's patents are broad and seek to cover things beyond
what Amgen invented. It is also arguing that Amgen defrauded the
U.S. Patent Office by withholding information.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still have half a dozen defenses left,'' said Jonas
Alsenas, portfolio manager for ING Furman Selz Asset Management.
</P>
<P>
   Erythropoietin is a protein normally produced in kidneys that
stimulates production of red blood cells. Amgen makes it by cloning
the human gene for erythropoietin and putting it in hamster ovary
cells that are grown in culture. Transkaryotic puts DNA into human
cells grown in culture to turn on the erythropoietin gene, which is
usually dormant.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high because erythropoietin accounts for roughly
$2 billion in sales for both Amgen and its licensee, Johnson &AMP;
Johnson. The industry is watching closely because if Transkaryotic
prevails, it might also make versions of other drugs. However, each
such attempt by the company is likely to face a separate patent
challenge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
