<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBC-RUMOR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBC DENIES ACQUISITION RUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once again, Interstate Bakeries Corp. has denied reports that
it's being courted by Mexico's largest bread and cake maker, Grupo
Industrial Bimbo.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate Chairman Charles Sullivan on Friday tried to quash
the rumor that seemingly refuses to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coming from a reporter in Mexico, and I have no idea in
the world where he dreams it up,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   After the report erupted, Interstate's stock price went up 18
percent. The New York Stock Exchange even suspended trading in
Interstate for a little more than an hour, until shortly after the
company released a statement denying the speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate, which makes Wonder bread, Twinkie snack cakes and a
slew of other products, is the largest wholesale baker in the
United States and one of Kansas City's few Fortune 500 companies.
</P>
<P>
   It's been widely reported that Bimbo, which has a presence in
Texas and Southern California, is eyeing other acquisitions north
of the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   In a story appearing in El Financiero//Infolatina, business
writer Dario Celis Estrada reported that Bimbo had been considering
four acquisition targets and had settled on Interstate.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate has been vulnerable to a takeover since its stock
took a huge one-day hit in late 1998 when the company missed
earnings expectations. The stock has never recovered, prompting the
company to implement a poison pill late last year.
</P>
<P>
   That poison pill, or so-called shareholder rights plan, was
later dissolved after a protest from Interstate's largest
shareholder, Ralston Purina Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston owns more than 40 percent of Interstate's stock, which
it received when it sold its Continental Baking Co. to Interstate
in 1995 in a cash-and-stock deal.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate and Ralston resolved the issues over the poison pill,
and Interstate reinstated it earlier this year. The poison pill
can't prevent a takeover of Interstate but does force a possible
suitor to deal directly with the company's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   But as of late Friday afternoon, Sullivan said, Interstate had
not heard from Bimbo or any other interested acquirer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position has always been we do what's best for the
shareholders, so if someone is interested and wants to talk to us,
we certainly have an open mind to it,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Bimbo spokesman Gustavo Solares, in response to an inquiry as to
whether the company was pursuing Interstate, e-mailed a response
that said in part that Bimbo was always looking for opportunities
to grow, including through acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nevertheless,'' Solares wrote, ``it is our policy not to
comment on rumors or speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bimbo had sales of about $2.3 billion last year, compared with
about $3.5 billion for Interstate.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said Interstate also normally did not respond to
rumors, but issued its statement after receiving a call from the
stock exchange saying it was going to halt trading unless the
company put out a release.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation sparked heavy trading and sent Interstate's
stock up from its opening price of $15.50 a share to a high of
$18.25 a share. However, after Interstate reported the rumors were
false, the stock fell back to just above its opening price to end
the day at $15.75 a share.
</P>
<P>
   There was some speculation that Bimbo might be talking to
Ralston Purina about buying its Interstate shares, but Sullivan
said that was highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our agreement with Ralston precludes them from doing anything
like that,'' Sullivan said. ``If they violated that agreement, the
penalties would be onerous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
