</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO IS ASSAILED FOR VOTE ON BILL INCLUDING PAY RAISE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBION, N.Y. _ Fending off another attack on his voting record,
Rep. Rick Lazio on Friday defended his vote to approve a bill that
gave members of Congress a raise and said Hillary Rodham Clinton's
campaign was resorting to ``cynical'' tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, the Clinton campaign and the New York State
Democratic Party lambasted Lazio for throwing his support on
Thursday behind an appropriations bill that included a $4,000 pay
raise, also called a cost-of-living increase, for members of the
House of Representatives, because Lazio, a Long Island congressman,
campaigned against pay raises when he first ran for office in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   During a sweep through western New York for his Senate campaign
that ended in this rural village 50 miles east of Buffalo, Lazio
said several times that he was opposed to pay raises. But he said
he had voted Thursday in support of a budget bill that included the
raise and several other measures after an attempt to remove the
increase from the bill failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have generally opposed the cost-of-living increases for
House members,'' Lazio said, adding, ``I don't recall that I've
ever voted for one, to the best of my recollection. And that's
consistent with my past record.''
</P>
<P>
   But Howard Wolfson, Clinton's spokesman, and Judith Hope,
chairwoman of the state Democratic Party, cited news reports that
Lazio voted for a pay raise in 1997. Lazio spokesman Dan McLagan
said the campaign was not aware of his supporting a pay increase in
1997, and said he had consistently opposed pay increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just more double talk from Rick Lazio,'' said Wolfson.
``He ran for Congress against perks, privileges and pay raises but
once he got there he voted twice for pay raises in the dead of
night.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It's the worst kind of dog-ate-my-homework excuse
I've ever heard. Why doesn't he just come clean with New Yorkers
and admit that he voted for a pay raise?''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of raises for members of Congress has been such a
traditionally hot topic in campaigns that Congress several years
ago changed the rules to mute it. Under current rules, unless
Congress votes to block a pay raise, members are automatically
given a certain percentage increase in the general Treasury budget,
which is voted on as a part of a huge appropriation bill that
includes financing for much of the government, the IRS, the Secret
Service and other divisions. There is no specific language in the
appropriations bill for the Treasury that gives Congress the pay
raise; it is drawn from those general revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In this week's votes, the first vote involved a procedural
motion that could have opened a way for opponents of the increase
to block it. But that motion was defeated, 250-173, with Lazio
among those voting to block it. That vote effectively halted
efforts to defeat the pay raise.
</P>
<P>
   The two subsequent votes pertained specifically to the Treasury
appropriations bill, and on those Lazio voted yes each time, and
the appropriation was approved.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio campaign then criticized Clinton, saying she did not
understand the legislative process if she believed that Lazio
should have voted against the Treasury bill, which included
financing for things like child care for federal employees. And it
noted that her husband, President Clinton, has signed several pay
raises for federal employees into law.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was the second day in a row that Lazio's voting record
was the subject of sharp exchanges between the two campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Clinton lashed out at Lazio for trying to kill and
then scaling back a program to help first-time home buyers secure
mortgages in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Lazio suggested several times during stops in
Buffalo, Niagara Falls and Albion that the Clinton campaign
appeared to be desperate for dirt on him.
</P>
<P>
   During a morning radio program on WLVO-AM in Buffalo, Lazio
said, ``I understand what the opposition is trying to do. They've
made a decision. They can't win this race by staying positive or
being honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at Kafana's Coffee Shop in Albion, he told a small crowd,
``This campaign will be about taking the high road. I'm not going
to sink down. We're not going there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
