u p BC-BUSH-VEEP-1STLD-WRITE     07-21 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VEEP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY EMERGES AS TOP CANDIDATE TO BE BUSH'S RUNNING MATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for inserts in 4th, 10th and 11th grafs.)   
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dick Cheney, the former defense secretary who is
heading Gov. George W. Bush's search for a vice presidential
nominee, has emerged as a leading contender for the job, changing
his voter registration Friday to make his selection possible,
Republicans close to the governor said Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is not expected to announce his final decision for several
days, and one Republican cautioned that he still planned to do some
thinking over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans close to Bush said that Cheney, whose wealth of
government experience includes a stint as White House chief of
staff under President Ford and a long career as a congressman from
Wyoming, had become a top choice of the governor's in recent days.
They said that his change of registration from Texas to Wyoming was
needed to pave the way for his likely, though still not assured,
selection.
</P>
<P>
   The registration switch, which Cheney carried out Friday, so he
could vote in Wyoming, was designed to avoid problems under the
12th Amendment to the Constitution. That provision forbids
Electoral College voters to choose candidates from their state as
both president and vice president. Property records from 1999 show
that Cheney has a home in Casper, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican close to Bush said the former defense secretary
was now the leading candidate, though he cautioned that Bush still
had not come to a final decision. Another Republican familiar with
the governor's thinking said Cheney was among the few finalists.
Yet another Republican, who is close to the former defense
secretary, said, ``Bush really, really, really likes Cheney.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign did not offer confirmation, but did nothing to
dampen the speculation about Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, told
reporters at his Texas ranch Friday that he was going to think
``long and hard'' at the ranch this weekend and review the options
that had been carefully prepared by Cheney himself. By the end of
the weekend, Bush said, ``I'll be a lot closer to the decision.''
He said, ``The days of speculation are over.''
</P>
<P>
   His aides said the announcement would come next week, possibly
as early as Monday, a week before the opening of the Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Other names that have figured prominently in the speculation
include Govs. Frank Keating of Oklahoma and George Pataki of New
York; Rep. John Kasich of Ohio; and Sens. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska,
John McCain of Arizona, and Bill Frist and Fred Thompson, both of
Tennessee. Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania was also under
consideration, but his stance in favor of abortion rights had
caused his star to dim in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush announced this spring that Cheney, who was his
father's defense secretary, would lead his search, he praised
Cheney, an executive at the Dallas-based Halliburton Co., an energy
company, and said that his role would not preclude him from being
considered for the No. 2 job himself. ``I trust Dick Cheney's
judgment; I know his character,'' Bush said. ``It's obviously an
important decision for me and I can't think of a better person to
work with on making that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Republicans said Cheney, 59, had repeatedly insisted
he did not want the job. In recent weeks, however, as Keating had
looked as if he was emerging as Bush's favorite, prominent
Republicans began lobbying Bush for Cheney. Many of them felt that
Keating was too conservative and not impressive enough to win over
independent and swing voters. And several Republican Party
officials pressed Cheney to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   He initially fretted about his health, they said _ he has
suffered three mild heart attacks and has had bypass surgery _ but
did not say no. And he slowly warmed to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a huge movement for this,'' one Republican said,
``and it started several weeks ago. This did not come out of the
blue.'' A Republican familiar with the conversations said Bush's
father has also been an active advocate for Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Though his health could become an issue, one Republican familiar
with the past few days' events said the Bush campaign had checked
on Cheney's medical records and health with the doctor who
performed the heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 House Republicans petitioned Bush Friday on McCain's
behalf, and Ridge, Republicans said, implored McCain to reconsider
in a telephone conversation Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   An associate of McCain's said the senator told Ridge that he
would prefer not to be asked but would accept the vice presidency
if offered it by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, however, said Friday, ``I don't believe anything has
changed'' since he told Bush in May that he did not want to be
considered for the ticket. And Bush gave no indication he would be
influenced by the pressure from House Republicans. He said simply
that he was sure that McCain would be a ``loyal soldier for my
candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Like McCain, Cheney would bring a wealth of experience in
national security to the ticket. He was a strategist of the Persian
Gulf war as defense secretary under Bush's father. He has good
relation with Republicans in Congress, where he was a party whip,
and he has served in the White House, as chief of staff to Ford.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike McCain, he has no further political ambitions of his
own, Republicans said, and would be devoted solely to the Bush
presidency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
