<SLUG> BC-TIBB-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH COMPANY LITTLE-KNOWN LOCALLY HAS BECOME SIZABLE AREA
EMPLOYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Days before the April layoffs of 1,300 union
workers by Associated Wholesale Grocers Inc., Teamsters leaders met
privately with executives of a British company in hopes of averting
a showdown with the Kansas City, Mo., food wholesaler.
</P>
<P>
   Although the meeting didn't prevent the layoffs in Kansas City,
Kan., and Springfield, Mo., it helped lay the groundwork for the
union's current working relationship with Elite Logistics, a
company owned by the North American arm of the British company,
Tibbett &AMP; Britten Group plc.
</P>
<P>
   Elite Logistics was one of four companies Associated had
contracted with to take over running its distribution centers April
2 _ provided Associated and the union didn't reach a new contract.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters officers came away from the late-March meetings
convinced they could reach an agreement with Tibbett &AMP; Britten if
its Elite Logistics alone took over all of Associated's operations
in Springfield and Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen in April, and a bitter two-month battle
ensued between Associated and the 1,300 employees who contended
they were locked out. But following a May ruling by the National
Labor Relations Board that was favorable to the union, Associated
in June agreed to outsource all its operations in the two cities to
one company _ Elite Logistics.
</P>
<P>
   Elite Logistics, in turn, returned Associated's union employees
to their jobs and agreed to an eight-year contract with the
Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Tibbett &AMP; Britten has become a sizable area
employer. About 680 people work for the company at Associated's
warehouse in Kansas City, Kan., under the name Elite Logistics.
</P>
<P>
   Although little-known locally, Tibbett &AMP; Britten is becoming a
prominent player in the logistics business nationwide. It provides
warehousing and transportation services in the food and retail
industries, and entered North America in 1989 in Canada with about
35 employees, said Mike Sprague, president of Tibbett &AMP; Britten
North American Group in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   After establishing a Canadian presence, Tibbett &AMP; Britten moved
into the United States in 1995, and gained contracts with companies
such as Kroger Co., Safeway Inc. and Procter &AMP; Gamble Co.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague said Tibbett &AMP; Britten has about 30 different contracts
in the United States and has its biggest operations in California
and Texas. The North American Group has about 12,000 employees and
last year posted sales of about $630 million, one-third of the
entire company's annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   While Sprague directs the overall strategy of North American
operations from Toronto, he said the various units, such as Elite
Logistics, are relatively autonomous.
</P>
<P>
   Each member-company, as Tibbett &AMP; Britten calls its units, has
its own name. In Nashville, Tenn., for example, Tibbett &AMP; Britten
operates Galaxy Logistics, which handles food distribution for
Kroger. In the Dallas area, Southstar Logistics has a contract with
Kroger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all these member-companies focus on the local
community and the local customers,'' Sprague said. ``Each
member-company has its business partner. The member-companies may
exchange ideas, but they run themselves and make the day-to-day
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping its entities locally based is a strategy that has worked
for Tibbett &AMP; Britten. Although Tibbett &AMP; Britten has lost a few
contracts that were not renewed, Sprague said that was because of
ownership changes that led the partners to move in other
directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never been thrown out due to bad performance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Tibbett &AMP; Britten apparently has a pretty fair
reputation among union workforces. After talking with union
counterparts in other parts of the country, Teamsters leaders in
Kansas City, Mo., and Springfield were agreeable to seeking a new
contract with Tibbett &AMP; Britten instead of Associated.
</P>
<P>
   While Associated had been prodding the Teamsters for ways to
reduce labor costs in a new contract, Tibbett &AMP; Britten came up
with an eight-year deal that provided wage increases and pension
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people we've dealt with at the top have been reliable,
straightforward and fair to deal with,'' said Jim Kabell, business
manager with Teamsters Local 245 in Springfield. ``Does that mean
we'll never have a fight with them? No, but there's a different
attitude from in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, problems have surfaced with Elite Logistics in the first
six weeks as sole operator of Associated's warehouses in
Springfield and Kansas City, Kan. The company laid off 19 workers
in Springfield after that division lost a big customer during
Associated's dispute with the Teamsters. A worker in the Kansas
City, Kan., warehouse died earlier this month in a forklift
accident. The company has declined to comment on details of the
accident during its investigation and an inquiry by federal
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   In union relations, Tibbett &AMP; Britten operating Kroger's
warehouse in the Dallas area has been beneficial for members of
Teamsters Local 745.
</P>
<P>
   After rejecting the company's first proposal, the 250-member
workforce ratified the second contract by a 2-1 margin in 1998,
said Randy Thorn, Local 745 business agent. The agreement
eventually eliminates a two-tier wage system that Kroger had
obtained from the union in 1987, Thorn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our overall relationship, compared to Kroger, I feel like it's
better,'' said Thorn, who worked in Kroger's warehouse for 17 years
before taking the union position. ``You may have people working in
the warehouse who feel differently. But Tibbett &AMP; Britten has done
a lot of things for our people that Kroger never would have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Tibbett &AMP; Britten's labor relations have been as
smooth. Last year, about 325 members of a Teamsters local in
Nashville struck Galaxy Logistics for six weeks before a settlement
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   However, Teamsters leaders made no allegations in the Nashville
media that Tibbett &AMP; Britten was attempting to break the union. And
both sides reportedly were satisfied with the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Clete Daniel, a professor of labor history at Cornell
University, said Tibbett &AMP; Britten's roots in Canada and the United
Kingdom probably make its management culture more accommodating to
organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canadian transportation companies are more amenable to unions
than transportation companies in the U.S.,'' Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague said about 50 percent of Tibbett &AMP; Britten's workforce
in North America is unionized. However, the company doesn't
distinguish between union and nonunion, he said, just as it tries
not to separate its Canadian and U.S. businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We treat team members like team members, whether they're union
or not,'' Sprague said. ``We work pretty well with most unions. But
if a group of workers chooses not to be union, that's fine, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
