<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-21 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9646 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-EPA-GRACE-ASBESTOS-1S     07-21 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPA-GRACE-ASBESTOS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA ADMITS SHELVING REPORT ABOUT ASBESTOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to correct administration to administrator in 10th graf.)  
 By MICHAEL MOSS and ADRIANNE APPEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency is investigating why its own
officials ignored evidence for 18 years that W.R. Grace and Co. had
used ore laden with asbestos in an array of building products.
</P>
<P>
   An agency study in 1982 found alarming levels of asbestos in ore
that Grace had said included harmless amounts of the material,
which can cause cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency shelved the report, scuttled follow-up studies
and continued to accept the company's lower figures, EPA officials
said this week.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed Grace, a maker of specialty chemicals and building
materials, largely to avoid government scrutiny and use the ore in
products, like fireproofing, that the company promoted as a safe
alternative at a time of growing anxiety about asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   The widely used fireproofing materials, as well as attic
insulation and other products, remain in thousands of homes and
offices.
</P>
<P>
   But the health risks are unclear, because it is not known how
much asbestos may be present in the products. Grace said it tried
to remove as much asbestos as possible during processing. EPA
officials are advising homeowners to call the agency for more
information if they are concerned that they may have the company's
loose-fill insulation, known as Zonolite, in their attic.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, EPA officials said this week, an agency official
misrepresented the report in 1983 and downplayed its findings in
responding to congressional inquiries about the level of asbestos
in the ore.
</P>
<P>
   The report resurfaced after the EPA began an investigation in
December into a health crisis in Libby, Mont., where Grace mined
the ore, known as vermiculite, until 1990. Workers and town
residents are dying from lung disease at rates far above the
national average. Agency officials are poring through thousands of
documents to figure out why the government failed to properly
oversee the mining operation and why EPA officials didn't follow up
their report.
</P>
<P>
   The report, letters and other records have been sent to the EPA
inspector general, who plans to begin an inquiry on Monday, agency
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't ask our inspector general to do an investigation
lightly,'' said Steve Johnson, deputy assistant administrator of
the office of prevention, pesticides and toxic substances. ``We
want to know precisely what did happen. With regard to W.R. Grace,
more and more information seems to be uncovered that raises
questions about what they knew and what they didn't know and what
they released and didn't release to us, and it's entirely possible
that information may come out through this investigation that may
show they have done something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials said this week that they had uncovered Grace
documents that show high levels of asbestos in the ore. Paul
Peronard, head of an EPA team trying to clean up the Montana mine
site, said, ``It doesn't appear to me that the data contained in
the documents were shared with anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace officials Friday did not dispute the EPA report, but said
their own studies had consistently shown much smaller amounts of
asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our results from measuring the ore do not find the same thing
that EPA's results do,'' said William Corcoran, vice president of
public and regulatory affairs for Grace, which is in Columbia, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the mining operation were touched off by
newspaper articles last fall on the health problems of Libby
workers and residents. Lawsuits that they have filed accuse Grace
of covering up the hazards posed by the mining operation.
</P>
<P>
   Corcoran said, ``We don't believe we've ever covered them up. We
know people have been hurt.'' He added that Grace's preference is
to continue trying to settle the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The ore went into insulation that Grace began selling in the
early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   At issue now is how much asbestos _ in a form known as tremolite
_ made its way into those products as a contaminant. A growing body
of medical evidence has raised concern among doctors about this
lesser known form of asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tremolite is one of the most dangerous fibers,'' said Dr.
Jacqueline Moline, an occupational and environmental health
specialist at Mt. Sinai School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   At processing plants throughout the country, Grace had sought to
remove most of the asbestos from the vermiculite in its Zonolite
line of products, which included a popular loose attic insulation
that Grace sold until 1984 and is believed to still be in as many
as 1 million homes. Some asbestos remained in the insulation, but
Grace did not warn consumers, The Boston Globe reported earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Grace has maintained that its products contain only trace
amounts of asbestos _ far below the 1 percent level at which the
EPA restricts its use.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer concern over the insulation has raised another issue
that is confounding government officials: how best to measure
asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners who are having their insulation tested for
contamination are getting widely varying results _ from ``traces''
to 2 percent asbestos, said Wayne Toland, the EPA asbestos
coordinator in Boston. One test turned up 5 percent. ``The results
are not necessarily consistent,'' Toland said. ``The method being
employed varied and so did the results.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, he said, is that testing laboratories are
unfamiliar with vermiculite and tremolite and do not know how to
properly prepare the samples. He said his office has hired an
asbestos expert, Eric J. Chatfield, of Chatfield Technical
Consulting, Mississauga, Ontario, to develop a standard procedure
for preparing the test sample.
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, Peronard said he also is working to develop new
methods of testing vermiculite for asbestos, since the common
techniques are designed to detect asbestos at quantities of 20
percent or more _ huge by today's standards, where 1 percent or
less may be cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at it at the wrong angle, you won't see the
fibers,'' Peronard said. ``We obviously have the fear that we're
under-counting and under-reporting the asbestos content of
samples.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace has written to the agency questioning the need for new
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``EPA does have methods for determining what is asbestos
content, which have been peer reviewed and scientifically accepted
for years and years,'' Corcoran said, ``so we are trying to get
some understanding of why, if those methods are good enough for
every other situation, why are they not good enough for this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Yang, who while working as a scientist for Grace designed
the company's asbestos laboratory techniques, said in a recent
interview that she had developed her own method of measuring
asbestos fibers. She said she thus avoided counting things that
looked like fibers but were not, like the edges of platelets. As a
consequence, she said she came up with results that were typically
50 percent less than the methods suggested by regulatory
authorities would have produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used a modified technique,'' Yang said.
</P>
<P>
   Because she was convinced the ore had minimal amounts of
asbestos, Yang said she rarely checked the levels in Grace's
products, maybe once or twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   The 1982 EPA study was triggered by an earlier outbreak of
health problems among workers at a Marysville, Ohio, plant where
vermiculite from Grace's Montana mine was used in making
fertilizer. A federal inquiry in 1978 found that four workers
suffered from bloody lungs. X-rays showed that one in four workers
had lung abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   In late October 1980, Thomas Dixon, an EPA analyst who then
worked in the toxicology branch, went to Montana to gather samples
of Grace's vermiculite ore. With an early winter storm threatening,
Dixon recalled that he and the agency's consultants rushed over the
next five days to collect dozens of scrapings from the mine and an
adjoining cleaning plant, which were then shipped to a laboratory
for testing.
</P>
<P>
   They found between 21 percent and 26 percent asbestos in the raw
ore, and up to 7 percent in the cleaned form that was shipped to
plants for further processing. The five grades of cleaned ore they
tested ranged for the most part between 2 percent and 7 percent,
with only one category falling below the EPA's regulatory threshold
of 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Grace has maintained over the years that far less
amounts of the cancer-causing substance contaminated its ore. For
instance, in a 1986 letter to the EPA in which Grace argued for an
exemption from proposed rules to label products that have asbestos,
the company said its Montana ore was sullied by only 4 percent to 6
percent asbestos coming out of the mine, and less than 0.5 percent
on average when cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   EPA staff became anxious for their own safety. A Grace official
described in a memorandum how he received a call on May 20, 1982,
from a Denver EPA employee who ``had just heard that vermiculite
may be contaminated with asbestos. The EPA uses vermiculite to pack
samples for shipments to laboratories for analysis. I spoke to him
for a few minutes because he was so upset and I did not want to
transfer him without calming him down. They dump half a bag of
vermiculite into a shipping carton two or three times a day. I told
him that the exposures would undoubtedly be low if good ventilation
was provided and that the respirator he indicated they were using
would provide additional protection.''
</P>
<P>
   But the EPA never carried out its plans to follow up on its mine
study by examining the Grace material at its processing plants. Nor
did it test the consumer products made with the ore as planned,
agency officials said. Agency staff say they moved on to pressing
health matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The priority dropped and we were off on other things, like
looking at dioxin for the first time,'' said Martin Halper, a
former toxicology division chief.
</P>
<P>
   The report surfaced briefly in 1983 when the late Peter Rodino
and another member of Congress forwarded to EPA a letter from a
Grace competitor in the fireproofing business who asked: ``Why did
EPA embark on such an extensive project collecting, analyzing and
characterizing vermiculite samples for asbestos contamination and
then suddenly choose both to simply drop its intended second, and
more critical, phase of the project.''
</P>
<P>
   The response came from an acting assistant administrator for
pesticides and toxic substances, who, according to Peronard,
wrongly cited a table of data in the study as indicating the
asbestos fell below 1 percent. ``He mixed it up,'' Peronard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
