<SLUG> BC-BBO-CUBAN-DEFECTOR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORALES LOOKS FOR HIS NEXT SIGN 
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Andy Morales gleefully trotted around the bases after
his three-run home run helped the Cuban national team clinch a 12-6
victory over the host Baltimore Orioles last year, and he felt on
top of the baseball world. As it turned it, he said Friday, that
moment turned into a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 40 years of having no professional baseball, to come
here and be the first Cuban player to hit a home run against a
professional team was a tremendous feeling,'' Morales said Friday
at a news conference at a Little Havana restaurant to celebrate his
defection this week. ``But instead of that being a triumph for me,
it turned into a defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Arriving back in Cuba, the third baseman-right fielder said,
Cuban authorities began suggesting that he was going to attempt to
defect.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made my life impossible,'' he told reporters. ``They
wouldn't let me travel overseas. So it turned out to be a negative
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales, 25, was removed from the national team for having been
seen talking to the California-based agent Gus Dominguez in
Baltimore. Dominguez was by his side on Friday and talking
excitedly about Morales' prospects of becoming a major leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez called Major League Baseball Friday to inquire about
the possibility of conducting a special lottery on Morales' behalf,
as it did in 1991 after the first Cuban defector, Rene Arocha,
arrived in America. All interested teams would participate in the
drawing to gain negotiating rights with him.
</P>
<P>
   But Dominguez said he was told that there was an 80 percent
chance against a lottery being approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to be seen as doing anything special for
anybody,'' he said, adding that there had been interest shown from
``at least five teams,'' including three in the minutes shortly
after it became clear Morales was going to be released in the
custody of his father-in-law, Carlos Castillo.
</P>
<P>
   If Morales, 6 feet 1 inch and 205 pounds, remains in the United
States, he will participate in an amateur draft in 2001. That means
he could negotiate with only the team that drafts him. He could
establish residency in another country, most likely Nicaragua,
Venezuela or Peru, and go to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed Morales' decision could be affected by his family
situation. His wife, Daiyana, and their 6-month-old son, Yandy,
have received U.S. approval to immigrate and are now awaiting Cuban
approval to leave.
</P>
<P>
   How good is he? Dominguez's Total Sports International issued
revised statistics from what had been available earlier in the
week. Playing for Havana, he was said to have hit .371 during the
1998-99 season, with 71 runs batted in and 17 home runs. The season
before: .349 with 68 RBI and 12 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees pitcher Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez, who called to
congratulate Morales, told his friend and the Dominguez publicist
Rene Guim that Morales was one of the premier all-around third
basemen in Cuban history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to see him in the major leagues one day soon,'' Guim
said Hernandez had told him.
</P>
<P>
   Morales tried to defect in early June, but was one of 31 Cubans
repatriated after they were intercepted at sea. The U.S. policy on
Cubans is clear. Those found at sea are usually returned to Cuba;
those who reach land are not.
</P>
<P>
   He found himself ostracized upon returning and felt he was
virtually forced out of baseball before his next defection try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like nobody wanted me because I was bearing the cross
of having been a defector,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
